<SLUG> BC-HKN-NEVIUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY C.W. NEVIUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
Some Tinkering Could Let NHL Translate to TV  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, I took my son and some other 10-year-old
boys to a San Jose Sharks game. To say they were blown away is an
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   They loved the smoke, the lasers, the action, the speed, the
crowd and the fact that pizza was served between the second and
third periods. They begged to come back. That would be tough, I
said, but did they know that the games were on TV?
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?!'' they asked. ``Awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The next Saturday afternoon my son was planted on the couch,
ready for some totally cool ice action. Thirty minutes later, I
walked by and noticed he'd changed the channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same,'' he said, sadly.
</P>
<P>
   No, it is not, and there is hockey's problem in a slapshot.
Hockey's deep philosophical question is this: If a puck drops in
Detroit, and no one watches it on TV, is hockey really happening?
</P>
<P>
   The good news out of the NHL conference finals over the weekend
was that TV ratings were up 56 percent. The bad news? At 2.5, they
still trail the French Open (2.7) and both days of the Memorial
golf tournament (2.9 Saturday and 3.5 on Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   So why don't we just let the sport of frozen water fizzle out
and disappear? Because hockey is hotter than ever _ in person.
</P>
<P>
   Through the conference semifinals, attendance at NHL playoff
games was at 99.2 percent of capacity around the league, which is
up from last year. In Buffalo, scalpers reportedly were getting
$125 for lower-bowl tickets for the Sabres, and the team sold
18,000 playoff tickets in 21/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you say, what else are they going to do in Buffalo? But
the same kind of surge is happening in Washington, where there were
concerns about empty seats. The Capitals can close out the Sabres
tonight and reach the Stanley Cup Finals, and according to a
front-page story in the _ ahem _ Washington Post, the Capitals are
``dominating conversations around town.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong with this picture? You can bet they are banging
their heads against the boards over at ESPN and Fox, which are
televising the playoffs and have seen their overnight ratings fall
as low as 1.6.
</P>
<P>
   You can give Fox credit for knowing that something has to be
done. Unfortunately, as toupee salesmen have proved for years,
acknowledging there is a problem does not mean you will take the
right action.
</P>
<P>
   Let's lay this out. There are two problems with hockey on
television: the puck and the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Fox went right after the puck problem, and ended up getting
hoots for the red-and-blue vapor trails that follow the puck on its
broadcasts. It seems no one likes it, including Red Wings coach
Scotty Bowman, who claimed the puck, which cannot be frozen because
of the computer chip inside, ``was bouncing like a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Pshaw, I say. That's the least of their problems. The puck with
a tail offends purists because it is hokey, not hockey. That's
fine, but the problem with the purists is that there aren't enough
of them. Keep the vapor trail if it means that much to you.
</P>
<P>
   The real deal with the puck is that it spends most of its time
down around the players' ankles. In virtually every other sport,
the ball/ puck is carried at least waist-high. That makes all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Because, in case you hadn't noticed, there is no other sport in
which a four-foot fence is placed around the playing surface. You
need to get up above the boards and look down on the puck to see
what is going on. Otherwise, as soon as the puck hits the boards,
the view on your television is of the tops of four helmets as four
guys look down and dig around with their sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Fox understands the problem, but not the solution. The
network is putting cameras down low on the sides and risking motion
sickness among viewers by creating a blur of action along the
boards.
</P>
<P>
   What we really need are either cameras above the ice _ not way
up there so the players resemble water bugs, but at
scoreboard-height or lower. Too difficult to set up? OK, how about
shots from what hockey veterans know is the best seat in the house,
behind the goals?
</P>
<P>
   Again, you'd have to have some elevation, but if you are behind
the goal, you can see the puck along both sides as well as watch
the plays develop. It wouldn't be televised the way any other sport
is on television, but what would be wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Any other suggestions? Sure. A shorter season, protection
against shots to the head to stop concussions, better marketing of
the most personable players in any sport, and anything to get more
people to have the experience of being at the rink.
</P>
<P>
   We know they've got a product. Last Monday night, President
Clinton was impressed. Clinton attended the Eastern Conference
finals, and when he was interviewed by ESPN between periods, what
do you think he said?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, first of all,'' Clinton offered, ``it is much more
exciting in person than on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir, we know the problem. Now we need a solution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
