<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY DAVID STEELE 
</HEADLINE>
  
Game 1 Will Reveal Whether Jazz 
 &HT;    Stayed in Tune  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The Utah Jazz wanted this to be their
breakthrough year. One distinction they did not exactly yearn for,
however, was to be one of the best-rested teams in NBA playoff
history.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what they got, thanks to their four-game sweep of the
Lakers in the Western Conference finals and the Chicago Bulls'
seven-game white-knuckler against Indiana in the East. By Wednesday
night's NBA Finals opener at the Delta Center, the Jazz will have
been off for 10 days (the 1982 Lakers sat for 12 days before their
Finals opener against Philadelphia). And no one will know until
Wednesday whether that's good or bad for the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has their theories, of course, and all are
well-supported and perfectly reasonable. They are also nothing more
than guesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win that first game, it might give us the advantage for
the future because we will be rested,'' Jazz guard Jeff Hornacek
told reporters Monday. ``But that first game will be questionable
because you can go only so hard in practice. Then to go against a
great team like the Bulls, it's going to be a different level of
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek is one of several older Jazz players who, it has been
assumed, needed the extra days to rest various aches and pains.
Backcourt mate John Stockton has been bothered by a sore back since
the first round against Houston. Karl Malone's right (shooting)
hand has been sore all season. The Bulls, like Utah among the NBA's
oldest teams, could have used the rest as well but instead got only
one day off and were scheduled to fly to Salt Lake City Tuesday.
That would give one theoretical edge to the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jerry Sloan, however, was not in favor of that kind of
edge and put the Jazz through brutal drills last week _ telling
them that he was not going to stand for any sloppiness or laziness
just because they were blessed with extra time off. ``It's been
like training camp,'' said starting center Greg Foster (an Oakland
native), ``and everybody knows training camp isn't any fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, some believe that such a layoff is no edge at all, no
matter how sadistic the workouts are. ``Utah's been laying around
for 10 days. One time I had eight days off waiting for the
championship, and there is no way you can stay in game shape by
laying around,'' said Pacers coach Larry Bird, referring to his
playing days with the Celtics. ``So Chicago has a chance to go out
there and get a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone acknowledged that potential pitfall. ``We've got to come
out and prove that we can beat anybody in our building,'' he said.
``We have to keep right on going from the Lakers series.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Bulls, it is imperative that they go to the Delta Center
and win one of the first two games. This is only the second time in
Chicago's six trips to the Finals that they have not had home-court
advantage. The 2-3-2 format has been criticized in recent years as
being more of an advantage to the team with the three middle games,
and the Bulls have a cnace to prove a point: If they win one of the
first two games in Utah, they will have a chance to take control of
the series at the United Center, where they are 28-2 in the
playoffs the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls believe they can win in Utah, not so much because the
Jazz might be sluggish from inactivity, but because they themselves
are in a rhythm. ``I think it was good for us, because we were
playing pretty much every other day,'' Scottie Pippen said after
the Bulls' series-clinching win Sunday. ``We know what it's like,
we're ready to play, our intensity level is there. Utah's been off.
We want to be able to go out there and catch them on their heels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz have been caught on their heels once in this
postseason, in the first game of the first round, when the Rockets
surprised them in the Delta Center. They were a game away from
elimination twice in that series but won Game 4 in Houston and Game
5 in Salt Lake City and have won 10 of their past 11 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the reason the series is opening in Utah rather
than Chicago: The Jazz won both meetings with the Bulls this
season, once in the Delta Center and once in Chicago, where the
Bulls lost just four times in the regular season. When the two
teams met in the Finals last year, the Jazz looked clueless in the
United Center, but it isn't likely they will be awed or overwhelmed
this time.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Bulls will not bring anything remotely
resembling fear into the Delta Center _ even though they lost all
three games of the East finals in Indianapolis. Last year's Finals
turned in Game 5, when an ill Michael Jordan turned in one of his
legendary performances and gave the Bulls a victory in Utah and a
3-2 lead going back to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big challenge to get there (to the Finals against
Utah), but you look at our record,'' Jordan said. ``We haven't lost
in the Finals, and that's a great confidence to have. . . . Sure,
it was a battle to get there. No one said it would be easy. But
we're there. So now, let's just do the job.'
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
