<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AFTER the Celtics beat the Rockets in Houston in Game 6 to win the
NBA title in 1986, the Today show sent out a crew to interview
Larry Bird. The producer popped a tape into the VCR, and maybe a
dozen people gathered around to watch the final minutes of the
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   All you could see were the players racing up the court; there
was no shot of the scoreboard to indicate where they had picked up
the action. Someone wondered how much time was left, and Bird
nodded at the screen and said, ``That's with 5 minutes and 40
seconds to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone turned and stared at Bird. ``How do you know that?''
the producer asked.
</P>
<P>
   Replied Bird, ``That's when they played that song.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone said, ``What song?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That song,'' he replied, ``Houston's fight song. I remember
checking the clock. There was 5:40 left when the band got up and
played the fight song.''
</P>
<P>
   All of his career, as a player and now a coach, Larry Bird saw
and heard things most people miss. I was at the game. M6~'z~I live
in Houston. I didn'BeZD Q~&AMP;puWo0OA_/OXt&AMP; &QL; ul]e9GEc88 B6Ce'''
</P>
