<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE HIS FANS, JOHNSON ASKS M'S: WHAT'S THE PLAN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Mariners' frustrating decision to let Randy
Johnson go without even attempting to negotiate a contract
extension has turned into just plain ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Andy Pettitte, no Jaret Wright, no Darren Dreifort
in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   There is no team willing to trade a 20-something up-and-comer
for a 34-year-old Cy Young Award-winning dominator who probably
does have three good years left, back surgery or no back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the Mariners fail to make a deal, the more the
Dodgers and Yankees can laugh and the stranger and funnier and more
stupid the entire situation grows.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not even talking about the Mariners' continued bullpen
woes. Yes, that was Lou Piniella shouting about how something has
to change after last night's 10-9 loss to the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why the Big Unit was laughing Monday. It was a
180-degree mood swing from two weeks ago, when the reeling Johnson
admitted he was rocked by all the stuff going on between his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after two great starts and a flurry of trade talks, Johnson
is seeing the light at the end of the tunnel. He will go on. His
season-ending stats will be good, no matter where he is, so he
promises.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Mariners whose future is uncertain, mostly because it
seems they flat-out had no real plan when it came to Johnson.
Exhibit A: They spoiled Ken Griffey Jr.'s MVP day last November
with their simultaneous announcement that Johnson was not in their
future.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   They did not have a plan this winter when the Yankees offered
starter David Wells and closer Mariano Rivera and the Mariners
refused, wanting lefty Pettitte or fuggetaboutit.
</P>
<P>
   And they did not seem to have a firm idea about what to do about
Johnson when the Dodgers offered starter Ismael Valdes and
outfielder Todd Hollandsworth in January, or when Cleveland offered
starter Chad Ogea and closer Jose Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   And here we are in early June and still there is no sense of
purpose, or at least reality. What the Mariners thought they could
get, they can't.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers appear to be the only team acting serious about a
trade. And word was Monday that the Dodgers have offered Valdes and
Wilton Guerrero as a counter to the Mariners' request for Deifort,
the 26-year-old right-hander the Dodgers vow to keep.
</P>
<P>
   But even the Dodgers understand they don't have to blink first,
not with a trading deadline that will whittle away at the Mariners'
pricetag on the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're stuck in a `Lost In Space' episode,'' Johnson
declared Monday afternoon, holding court in the visitors' clubhouse
under Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the feeling they don't know what they want to do right
now. ... It's like Woody Woodward and Chuck Armstrong are molecules
bouncing off each other, no idea which way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the M's scared to deal the Big Unit?
</P>
<P>
   ``From my vantage point, it looks that way,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Or the M's might deal him to the Dodgers in what could be an
embarrassing trade. That's why the situation does not make sense.
None of it adds up, except that maybe the M's are freaked out about
what to do with the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   This is a monumental turning point in the club's history. But a
week into trade speculations, it has gotten no easier to fathom
what the Mariners are hoping to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you get rid of somebody and create a headache where
there isn't one?'' fellow pitcher Jamie Moyer said. ``Can the
Mariners do the right thing in this situation? Who can they get for
Randy who is going to give you what he gives you?''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer is right. There is no deal that gives the Mariners value
for Johnson. And if Heathcliff Slocumb was worth a $3 million deal
this winter, why wasn't Johnson worthy of at least a negotiation?
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I worth? What have I been worth to this team the last
two or three years? What's my value there?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's inquiry was mostly rhetorical, an indication he
believes the Mariners do not value him as much as they now want
other teams to value him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only one player. I'm worth a couple of fungo bats and a
couple of balls, at least,'' Johnson said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   What is Johnson worth? It's the same question over and over, but
the M's appear to be discovering what they should have known from
the start: There is no trade for the Big Unit that makes any shred
of sense.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest value to the M's might have been to pitch and win
in Seattle for three more years and finish a Hall of Fame career
where it blossomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't get Andy Pettitte? Well, then, what else are you
offering? Chuck Armstrong and Woody Woodward were saying no teams
were calling. Well, that's because they're asking for Andy Pettite
and Mariano Riviera. They're asking for Jaret Wright and Bartolo
Colon. That's pretty steep,'' Johnson said. ``That's why I'm still
here. The players they want, the other teams aren't willing to give
up. The asking price is a little too steep.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to load the cannon, like the M's did, it's
always good to know what you're aiming at _ and know if there's
enough powder to reach the target.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
