<TEXT>
<P>
   Reynolds &QL; 
finds self &QL; 
in groove
</P>
<P>
   Astros pit hot hurler &QL; 
against Padres tonight
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ Throughout the course of the baseball season, a team's
starting rotation can resemble a deck of cards. And in any game
during the 162-date shuffle, a club can draw a coveted ace.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds, the Astros' opening-day starter each of the past
three years, is all too familiar with the whims of the deal. But
the 30-year-old righthander currently is trumping with the best of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the smoke generated by hot starts from teammates Mike
Hampton and Jose Lima, Reynolds was something of a forgotten man
during the first month of the season. His numbers weren't terrible,
but they clearly weren't up to his standards.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds was 1-2 with a 4.30 earned run average in Apr s~Zv1UQ
</P>
</TEXT>
