<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANDY-JOHNSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TRADE ON SIMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Mariners want to trade Randy Johnson, but they
aren't eager to face him.
</P>
<P>
   That is why that on-again, off-again deal with the Los Angeles
Dodgers probably would not be consummated before Wednesday night at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have offered right-handed pitcher Ismael Valdes and
the choice of outfielders Todd Hollandsworth or Wilton Guerrero for
Johnson, according to a source close to the National League team.
</P>
<P>
   The teams nearly pulled off this deal six months ago, but it
fell apart when the Dodgers took Valdes out of the trade. L.A.
instead inserted right-hander Ramon Martinez, and the Mariners
turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers want to complete the deal Tuesday, but the Mariners
apparently want to wait until after Johnson pitches against the
Anaheim Angels tomorrow night at the Kingdome. That would prevent
their all-time winningest pitcher from making his Dodger debut this
weekend when Los Angeles plays a three-game series at the Kingdome
in the first interleague games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one more hangup.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle wants to lure right-hander Darren Dreifort away from the
NL West team, but the Dodgers refuse to include the
reliever-turned-starter in any deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they will take Valdes, the deal is done,'' the Dodger
source said. ``If they keep insisting on Dreifort, it won't be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Los Angeles radio stations reported Monday that the teams
had reached agreement on a trade. One report said the Mariners
would receive Valdes, Hollandsworth and Guerrero, while the other
said it was a Valdes-Hollandsworth swap for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner officials wouldn't comment, as has been their policy
since trade talk heated up last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't comment on rumors,'' said M's vice president of
baseball administration Lee Pelekoudas, who is with the team in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward, the team's vice president of baseball
operations, was not available Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes would move into Seattle's starting rotation, joining
Jamie Moyer, Jeff Fassero, Bill Swift and Ken Cloude.
Hollandsworth, a product of Newport High in Bellevue and the
National League Rookie of the Year in 1996, would give Mariner
manager Lou Piniella the left-handed bat he has wanted for several
weeks. Hollandsworth is batting .267 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who had a 10-11 record last season despite a 2.65 earned
run average, is 3-5 with a 5.33 ERA. The Mexican native reportedly
is having a difficult season because his father recently was
diagnosed with cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
