<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9659 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-02 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BLOW ANOTHER LATE LEAD, FALL TO ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Something seems wrong with this picture.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are seriously thinking about trading left-hander
Randy Johnson, but little is being said about another lefty who is
much less dependable.
</P>
<P>
   What do they do with Tony Fossas?
</P>
<P>
   The veteran reliever with the long history of dominating
left-handed batters continued his journey to who-knows-where Monday
night at Camden Yards, serving up a game-losing home run to
left-handed hitter Rafael Palmeiro in an explosive eighth inning as
the Mariners' bullpen blew another gasket in a 10-9 loss to the
Baltimore Orioles before 42,622 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Shoddy defense by third baseman Russ Davis, leading to three
unearned runs off starter Jeff Fassero, and a Mariner-like,
three-homer barrage in the eighth by the Orioles sent the M's to
yet another gut-punching defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rather obvious this isn't working,'' manager Lou Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   That might be construed as a plea that it is going to take more
than trading Johnson to solve the Mariners' woes. Too many errors.
Too many runs allowed by the bullpen. Too many losses.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez hit two home runs, and David Segui and Russ Davis
hit one apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you score nine runs, you expect to win,'' Segui said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orioles scored more.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wells, who relieved Fassero in the fifth inning, pitched
brilliantly until the eighth inning, striking out the side in the
fifth to keep the Mariners in front by two runs. Davis' homer in
the eighth made it 9-6. Wells had retired nine of the 10 batters he
faced until Chris Hoiles singled.
</P>
<P>
   After Jeff Reboulet struck out, Brady Anderson homered, slicing
the lead to one. The first pitch to Eric Davis was called a strike,
and it made the hitter so mad that he nearly got ejected by plate
umpire Al Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles manager Ray Miller and third-base coach Sam Perlozzo
interceded and kept Davis in the game. Davis rocketed the next
pitch he saw into the left field bleachers for a game-tying home
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wells was throwing the ball so well, and then all of a sudden,
I don't know what happened,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander got his pitches up and the Orioles hit them
out.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Fossas got another opportunity and failed
miserably. A quality slider missed inside. Another slider became a
souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a flat slider down the middle of the plate,'' Fossas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella, ``He has thrown flat pitches all (bleeping) year.
Excuse my language, but there is just too much duplication. I've
got whiplash.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossas, 40, has allowed 11 hits to the 29 lefties he has faced
this season _ a .379 batting average. This was the first home run
he has allowed to a lefty in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were the pitching coach or manager, I'd be pulling my
hair out,'' he said. ``I was signed for the purpose of getting out
left-handers and I haven't done anything. I'm going through the
worst time of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   He entered this season with a terrific track record, holding
opposing left-handers to a .204 (78-for-382) average over the past
five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to give up,'' Fossas said. ``I will leave this
game fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the same approach Fassero took into his 10th start of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Segui's 10th homer of the season capped a four-run first inning,
but the first of two errors by Davis led to two unearned Oriole
runs. Seattle added another run in the third on Martinez's first
homer of the game, and tacked on three more in the fifth, two of
them coming on Martinez's second homer.
</P>
<P>
   But forced to throw extra pitches because of Davis' miscues at
third base, Fassero weakened in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciated his effort,'' Piniella said of Fassero, who
missed Sunday's scheduled start in Tampa Bay because of the flu and
sore throat. ``He wasn't strong. He was still sick, but he went out
there and did the best he could, which is appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro and Robby Alomar did most of the damage against
Fassero. The Orioles' 4-5 hitters were a combined 5-for-6 against
Seattle's five-game winner, and Alomar slugged a two-run homer in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Their bats and Davis' glove were instrumental in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving up too many unearned runs,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis now has 14 errors this season, and the M's have allowed 25
unearned runs, fourth-highest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Seattle is losing too many games in the late
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the M's bullpen didn't get a blown save (the starter
must be the pitcher of record before a blown save is possible), it
got a blown game.
</P>
<P>
   The M's now have lost five games when leading after seven
innings and the latest came against a team that had won only once
when trailing after seven innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
