<HEADER>
A9671 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-JOHNSON-ANALYSIS-     06-02 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-JOHNSON-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ORDER DRAGS DODGERS OFFICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Less than 24 hours after Hideo Nomo told the Los
Angeles Dodgers he was going public with his demand to be traded,
he was gone. Nomo tried to force the hand of club executive vice
president Fred Claire and the wrath was quick and permanent.
</P>
<P>
   That has been Claire's style since he took over the Dodgers
baseball operation in 1987. And that's why the dragging nature of
the pending Randy Johnson trade with Seattle is so surprising.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, Claire called an agent or another team and said
this was the offer and the guy on the other line had 24 hours to
respond. He did it with Kirk Gibson, Darryl Strawberry, Orel
Hershiser and Todd Worrell. Most of those stories had happy
endings.
</P>
<P>
   But once again it is clear that Claire no longer acts alone.
</P>
<P>
   Claire says the Johnson trade talks ``have dragged on far too
long and will be resolved soon.'' It could happen before tonight's
game against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But.
</P>
<P>
   The differing management styles of the new Dodgers hierarchy has
helped create the impasse in the Johnson deal and ruined all the
momentum the club took out of its first winning road trip. That's
why former owner Peter O'Malley, now chairman of the board, has to
get the troops in one room and get them all on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have Fox man Chase Carey, new team president Bob
Graziano and Claire, who was passed over for Graziano's job.
</P>
<P>
   Carey, the point man on the Piazza deal after Claire dragged his
feet, spends money to make money. He was ripped when overspending
to get the new NFL TV contract for Fox. But football became a
bargain when all the CBS local affiliates jumped to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Carey wants Johnson and doesn't mind the time and money it will
take. He doesn't appear to understand that a protracted negotiation
can destroy a team, even one he thought he had overhauled by
getting rid of Piazza. His new team is better, but lingering trade
talks disrupt the delicate balance of a clubhouse no matter what
Bobby Bonilla says.
</P>
<P>
   This impasse is not all the Dodgers' fault. The Seattle Mariners
have a lot of issues on their end. General manager Woody Woodward
was vilified when the team did not make do well last year after an
inspiring run in 1996 that landed the Mariners within two games of
the World Series. He has two of the top players in baseball in Ken
Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez and still hasn't won a pennant. He
also traded promising Jose Cruz Jr. last year for relief help that
never came.
</P>
<P>
   After Woodward failed to offer Johnson a contract extension, the
pitcher became disruptive. Griffey and manager Lou Piniella want
him out even if it costs Seattle the playoffs. It is a far bigger
mess than anything the Dodgers have seen, Nomo or not.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, a former GM with the Yankees and Cincinnati Reds, is a
plodding sort, which makes his dilemma worse.
</P>
<P>
   He is asking for tonight's starter Darren Dreifort, who has won
three straight and is looking very much like the pitcher they took
with the second pick in the 1992 draft (behind Rodriguez).
</P>
<P>
   Woodward wanted Ismael Valdes for Johnson during the winter.
Claire said no, remember former Dodger Pedro Martinez and the Cy
Young Award he won with Montreal?
</P>
<P>
   Claire was looking at trouble if he let Nomo stick around. At
one time, he was hopeful the Mariners might take Nomo off his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   In the next six days, Claire will talk to a lot of clubs about a
suspect right-hander who can give them 200 innings even if many of
them are bad. Baltimore and Boston already are interested. Nomo
could even wind up in Seattle, although the Mariners watched him
pitch on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If Dreifort does wind up in the Johnson deal, know that it will
not be a Claire deal. Graziano is a quick thinker, but Claire's
baseball experience made him the man for the job during the Fox
transition.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Dodgers have a three-headed dog. And lots of
confusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
