</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SKIES NOT TRUE BLUE FOR RUSSELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It is two hours before game time, and the manager
of the Los Angeles Dodgers is alone in his office filling out his
lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   There is an eerie silence, and an air of gloominess pervades the
room.
</P>
<P>
   It is late Sunday morning, and the Dodgers have lost two
straight home games to the Cincinnati Reds to drop below .500
again.
</P>
<P>
   And Bill Russell is feeling the pain of their plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we get back from our first winning road trip, and all we
hear about is this Randy Johnson trade,'' says Russell softly.
``It's been a terrible distraction. A few players on the team
wonder if they're going to be here or not. We come back here on a
high, and all our players are asked about is Randy Johnson. All
that stuff makes it tough for our players to concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell shakes his head slowly in exasperation because he
knows his team is performing below expectations for a new corporate
ownership that won't have as much patience with him as Peter
O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby Dodger clubhouse, Eric Karros is saying, ``We have
the potential to turn it around and start winning. But potential is
a funny word. It means you haven't achieved what you're expected to
achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gary Sheffield is saying, ``When I first heard I was traded
to L.A., I thought, `Wow, I'll be playing with Mike Piazza. I'm
gonna see some pitches.' I didn't realize I was being traded for
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bobby Bonilla is smiling and laughing and acting in his
free-spirited manner.
</P>
<P>
   The room where the Dodger players dress doesn't have the
funereal atmosphere of their manager's quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell knows the cruel rites of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He knows his job is on the line because the Dodgers are
struggling and because new people are running the team who have no
allegiance to him because they didn't hire him.
</P>
<P>
   He knows fingers are being pointed at him by those who would
like to see him fail, and he knows there is only one way he will
survive this dark season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to start winning,'' says Russell. ``Winning cures
a lot of ills. This is a long season. Things change. Things turn.
Our turn will come. I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the brightest of Dodger years.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the season when the team would ascend to
the next level with Mike Piazza and Raul Mondesi and Eric Karros
and Todd Zeile supplying the power and with Eric Young getting on
base and with a heralded pitching staff shutting down the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows?
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers still might go on a frenzied tear, but the season
has not unfolded the way it was scripted in the optimism of the
early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza and his thundering bat now are now dispensing
heroics for the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile is doing hard time with the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Hideo Nomo has lost seven of nine decisions, lost speed on his
fast ball, and has lost the confidence of the Dodger hierarchy that
on Monday all but waived him.
</P>
<P>
   The earned run averages of Ismael Valdes and Chan Ho Park look
like T-bill percentage rates.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin refugees named Gary Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Charles
Johnson and Jim Eisenreich now are part of the Dodgers roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitching just hasn't performed like we expected it to,''
admits Russell, and it will unravel again later in the day when
Antonio Osuna and Scott Radinsky fail to protect a Dodger lead in
the late innings against the Reds. ``No one expected us to struggle
as much as we have in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expected Mike Piazza to depart the Dodgers, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surprising,'' says Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if someone told you a year ago that Mike Piazza would be
traded by the Dodgers?'' Russell is asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have believed it,'' he replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are Sheffield and Bonilla behaving?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great. No problems. And I don't expect any. They want to win
just like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Feel pressure?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Pressure's part of this job. I knew it would be there when
I took it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Bill Russell took it, Peter O'Malley was signing his
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   And Peter O'Malley and his father, the late Walter O'Malley,
never fired a manager during the team's 40 previous seasons in Los
Angeles, remaining faithful to Walter Alston and Tom Lasorda and
Russell through the successes and failures.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter O'Malley is now gone, and the Rupert Murdoch Fox
forces now operate the team.
</P>
<P>
   And Bill Russell is quite aware that Murdoch has a ruthless
history of making major changes when he takes over a new business.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell won't say it because it would violate the codes of
his sport.
</P>
<P>
   But he's feeling the pressure these days.
</P>
<P>
   That sorrowful look that remains fixed to his face as he sits
solemnly behind his office desk betrays his feelings about what has
been a numbing season for him and his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
