r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-VALENT-LADN     06-02 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-VALENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S VALENT AWAITS BASEBALL-DRAFT JUDGMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK HIPES  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So here is Eric Valent sitting in the UCLA
baseball locker room, a place he's called home for three
power-packed years, trying to explain that he's neither too small
nor too slow to play pro baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have really good power for my size, but yeah, I'm only 200
pounds,'' he explained. ``But that's not all it is. It's the swing,
the bat speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, almost exasperated, as though he had to prove something to
someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can play, you can play,'' he said. ``And that's the
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   No, here's the thing: Eric Valent, only a junior but already a
two-time All-American, a Team USA veteran, the Pacific-10
Conference's career home-run leader and UCLA's career RBI leader,
is one of the best outfield prospects in college baseball and
easily will be taken within the first two rounds of today's Major
League amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   You see, he doesn't have to state his case because he already
has.
</P>
<P>
   Valent strode to the plate in mid-April against USC freshman
pitcher Rik Currier in a Six-Pac game at Dedeaux Field. Currier
threw away from the left-hander, moving the count to 2-0. Valent,
in the midst of hitting eight home runs in nine games _ he would
eventually average one home run in every three games this year _
squared his frame in the batter's box and waited.
</P>
<P>
   Currier offered a fastball inside but not inside enough. Valent
turned with lightning-quick efficiency and crushed the ball to dead
right field. It seemed to rise as it left the park, finally landing
on the roof of an adjacent parking garage some 480 feet later.
</P>
<P>
   Said USC coach Mike Gillespie after the game, arching his neck
toward Valentville: ``You don't see many go up there.''!off!
</P>
<P>
   With a home-run swing and home-run power to go with it, Valent
is hearing a lot of different things these days. He hears the
Yankees and the Dodgers love him and could make him a first-round
pick, ensuring him at least a shot at a $1 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's crazy, isn't it,'' he asks, a huge grin emerging.
</P>
<P>
   He hears the Mariners also adore his skills.
</P>
<P>
   But he also picks up other things. He's too slow, some say, so
whoever picks him up will have to move him from center field to a
corner outfield position, where he can rely less on his feet and
more on his rocket arm.
</P>
<P>
   He sees Baseball America, which named him the 34th-best prospect
in the draft and the second-best power hitter in college baseball
(behind Miami's Pat Burrell, rumored to be the top pick of the
draft). After his freshman All-American season with the Bruins,
they wrote Valent needed more power in his game to raise his stock.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after his 30 home runs (second in the nation) in 1998, the
same people are saying he's one-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear some stuff, but all it is is talk,'' he said.
``Someone is always going to knock you, but all it takes is one
person to like you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that, being a top prospect in what is considered an
unusually deep amateur draft, many more than one person likes
Valent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the greats,'' UCLA hitting coach Vince Beringhele
said. ``You don't have to worry about him ... he's worked hard on
both his defense and offense. He's complete.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA head coach Gary Adams looks around his office before he
says it, as though he wants to make sure no one is listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got him, I didn't think he would hit with that much
power,'' he said. ``I thought he'd be a doubles hitter. I didn't
take into account him getting that much stronger. He has such
strong, quick hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Adams compares Valent with former USC center fielder
Fred Lynn, only with more power. Not too bad.
</P>
<P>
   Valent hit .289 with 12 home runs and 55 RBI as a freshman, then
blossomed in 1997 with 27 homers and 91 RBI, helping the Bruins to
the College World Series for the first time since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had such a good time,'' Valent said. ``I was in
the lineup with Jon Heinrics and Troy Glaus (Glaus had 34 homers in
1997 and Heinricks 28). ``You see them hit homers...''
</P>
<P>
   Valent joined in. His 27 home runs were the best of any
returning player this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Glaus (the third pick of the '97 draft) and Heinrics (a
ninth-round selection of the Marlins) left, as did a trio of junior
pitchers (Pete Zamora, Jim Parque and Tom Jacquez). Valent and
right fielder Eric Byrnes were left holding the brunt of
responsibility for offensive production and leadership on a very
young team.
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1998, it got to him. He began the year miserably,
hitting .148 with no homers through his first seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to carry the team,'' Valent admitted. ``It was
tough after getting a taste of glory last year. We'd have it some
days, then wouldn't have it other days.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Beringhele: ``He was playing for the draft and he had to be
the leader. He tried to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Valent, with a bit of coaxing, realized as much. He relaxed at
the plate and good things started to happen.
</P>
<P>
   He batted .362 with 30 home runs and 72 RBI over the rest of the
year. In his last 20 games, he hit .400 (40-100) with 16 homers and
36 RBI. At one point, he homered in five consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, he had the Pac-10 home-run record (69), becoming the
third player in conference history _ with Glaus and some guy named
Mark McGwire _ to hit 30 or more homers in a year. His career RBI
total (219) was one shy of the Pac-10 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it was easy to put up big numbers,'' he said. ``This
year it wasn't like that. So I'm pretty happy with what I've done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could've stayed a little longer, maybe, but maybe
it's time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he will, without the cliched waffling between pro
baseball and a final year of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's drafted past the first round, I'll talk to him about
coming back,'' said Adams, a gleam in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that is not going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
