<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FEES-COLUMN-LADN     06-02 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEES-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO'S FANS GIVE CRITICISM TOO QUICKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JARRE FEES  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seinfeld's Kosmo Kramer knew how to make an entrance. A stumble,
a pratfall, a laugh. Buffalo's Kramer is about to make an exit and
it won't be funny to anyone but the Washington Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Dominik Hasek, nicknamed Kramer by his teammates, on Sunday wore
two homemade signs on the back of his practice jersey. One sign
read ``Kramer,'' the other read ``Swiss Cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kramer sign was a peace offering to his teammates; Hasek
reportedly hated the name. The second was an apology for the
70-foot goal he allowed in the Sabres' 2-0 loss to the Caps in Game
4 of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   One soft goal and the man thinks he's Swiss cheese. Worse,
Buffalo fans behaved like cheeseheads, booing their favorite son in
the last minute of play.
</P>
<P>
   These are the same fans who booed Hasek a year ago when his
public feud with Coach of the Year Ted Nolan led to Nolan's exit
from the team; the same fans who forgave Hasek's transgressions
when he won the Olympic gold medal for the Czech Republic; the same
fans who pretended until Saturday that Hasek could win the Stanley
Cup all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't score a goal, a 70-foot shot goes in and all of a
sudden he's a bum,'' said coach Lindy Ruff on Sunday. ``He carried
us all year and through the playoffs. I thought the (Swiss cheese)
sign was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff scoffed at the idea Hasek doesn't do well in big games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't score one goal last night. One shot beat us and I
don't consider that not coming up big.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 5 takes place tonight, and Washington has a 3-1 lead in the
series. The Swiss-cheese goalie will probably not lift the Stanley
Cup this year. He will have to make do with the gold medal, his own
asteroid from Czech astronomers and almost certain MVP and Vezina
(goaltending) trophies from the league.
</P>
<P>
   TV's Kramer had his series ended by the star. Buffalo's Kramer
 &UR; !ital! &LR; is &UR; !off! &LR;  the star. Considering how long he's held this
series together, Sabres fans should be clamoring for a curtain
call.
</P>
<P>
   __Rinkside: The return of injured defenseman Vladimir
Konstantinov and team masseur Sergei Mnatsakonov to Detroit's Joe
Louis Arena on Sunday left Detroit fans cheering, Dallas players
banging their sticks on the ice and the Fox announcers too choked
up to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Konstantinov and Mnatsakonov were critically injured in a
limousine accident last summer. Both are in wheelchairs and are
expected to remain there for some time; in Mnatsakonov's case,
probably the rest of his life. They watched part of the game from
owner Mike Illitch's luxury box, waving to the crowd when they were
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said Saturday he knew the men's
introduction would be an emotional moment for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the accident) didn't just happen to Detroit,'' he said.
``It happened just as much to our team. It happened to hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the accident occurred after postseason play,
Konstantinov was not covered by medical insurance. The Illitch
family has taken care of most of his expenses, and Detroit players
have raised an additional $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   __ More heroes: Kings captain Rob Blake, Detroit's Vyacheslav
Fetisov and Jamie McLennan of the St. Louis Blues are the finalists
for the NHL's William Masterson Memorial trophy.
</P>
<P>
   The award, named after the former Minnesota North Stars player,
is given annually to a player who shows a high degree of
perseverance, sportsmanship and dedication to hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who recovered from injuries that limited him to 92 games
over the previous three seasons, led the Kings to the playoffs this
year for the first time since 1993. He also played for Team Canada
in the 1998 Olympics and was named outstanding defenseman of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Fetisov survived the limousine accident that critically injured
Konstantinov and Mnatsakonov, recovering in time to take the
Stanley Cup home to Russia last summer. The 40-year-old defenseman
is expected to retire after the playoffs and plans to work with
minor hockey in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   McLennan, 26, had bacterial meningitis two years ago. He was
hospitalized for nearly a month, lost 30 pounds and had to learn to
walk again. McLennan returned to the Blues this season and had a
16-8-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   Kings general manager Dave Taylor won the Masterson trophy in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   __ Kings media relations assistant dies: Michael Jund, Los
Angeles Kings media-relations assistant, died Sunday of a heart
attack. Jund, 22, was born with a heart defect. He grew up in
Manhattan Beach and worked with the Kings during the 1997-98
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
