A9682 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     06-02 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR USC, IT'S BEEN A WHILE BETWEEN CONQUESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ USC used to spend so much time in Omaha that it
had to pay state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In a span of two decades between 1958 and 1978, USC came to the
College World Series 13 times and won the NCAA title 10 times,
including five in a row from 1970 to 1974. On three occasions, the
Trojans went unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   Omaha didn't roll out the red carpet back then as much as a
green one, envious that one team in college baseball could be so
dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to treat us like royalty,'' said former USC coach
Rod Dedeaux. ``Of course, they booed us during games. Everyone
likes the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed. People around here aren't calling USC an
underdog as much as a stranger. The Trojans' trip here in 1998
marks only the second trip to Omaha for USC since their last
title-winning team in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   They lost their first game to LSU but stayed alive Monday night
with a 12-10 extra inning win in an elimination game against
Florida. The Trojans play Mississippi State in another
loser-go-home game tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of USC coming here as something other than a heavy
favorite is different for the Trojans as much as its fans. Florida,
the team USC eliminated, was the No. 1 seed in the tourney. All
three of Florida's career appearances have come since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that somehow this has devalued the Trojans is
understandable, but also bothersome. ``You stay away for awhile
like we did, and people start to wonder where we are, or what's
gone wrong,'' said USC coach Mike Gillespie. ``It gets like those
people who wonder why Denver or Buffalo can't win a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had good teams. Seven USC teams in the last seven years
played in the regional final. We haven't been able to get here as
often as we like. But that doesn't mean we don't have a good
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Omaha is flush with opinions that the SEC and ACC are now the
best conferences, too, and that west coast baseball is losing
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams from the west coast have given a pretty good account of
themselves over the years,'' said Gillespie after the win. ``It
won't surprise me to see one or two teams in the final. But many
people are riding the wave of the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emergence of Long Beach under Dave Snow is a perfect
example of how baseball in the west has grown. Pepperdine has been
strong for a long time. So have several teams in our conference.
Now we're seeing Washington, Oregon State and Loyola step up.''
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't need carbon dating to find out when things began to
unravel at USC.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA cast the first asteroid-sized stone in the late '70s
when it reapportioned scholarship limitations during the first
major phase of cost-cutting and gender equity. Scholarships in
spring sports like track and baseball were essentially cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   There was an extra twist to that knife, too. ``It wasn't just
that they cut scholarships,'' said Dedeaux, who retired after the
1986 season. ``It was also how they interpreted the use of those
scholarships. They even put limits on how we counted academic
scholarships toward our team total.''
</P>
<P>
   Public schools, like Long Beach, Fullerton and UCLA, could split
their scholarships up since their tuition costs, relative to a
public school like USC, were modest. The impact meant USC could
sign half as many players as they were accustomed, and they felt it
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1979 and 1987, USC failed to qualify for a postseason
regional eight of nine times. The one year it did, it lost two
straight games to Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Gillespie has fielded a team which has been a
regular contender for the Pac-10 title. Troy's East Regional win
which got them here marked the eighth postseason appearance in 10
years. In 1995, the last time USC made it to Omaha, Troy made it to
the title game, losing to Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the job Mike has done,'' said Dedeaux. ``We're winning
every year and contending for the league title and a regular in the
tournament. There are a lot more programs now playing top-level
baseball. It isn't as easy for any one program to dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an understatement. Fullerton has won three NCAA titles in
the last 20 years (1979, 1984 and 1995). Pepperdine won the title
in 1992 under Andy Lopez, who now coaches Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, Fullerton and Long Beach State have been
to the CWS four times. Only three schools have made more
appearances in Omaha LSU (8) Miami (7) and Florida State (6). Among
USC's Pac-10 friends, titles have been won in the last two decades
by Arizona (1980, 1986), Arizona State (1981, plus a second and two
third-place finishes) and Stanford (1987, 1988).
</P>
<P>
   If it vexes USC fans to see Pepperdine and Stanford, private
schools from different ends of the athletic spectrum, win national
titles while USC struggles to win a regional, so be it. The field
has changed and it's probably to the benefit of baseball on the
left coast.
</P>
<P>
   USC and Long Beach are in the same state, Nebraska. They are in
the same state, too, meaning they're very much alive in the CWS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
