<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9691 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BURROUGHS-LADN     06-02 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BURROUGHS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAN BURROUGHS FAVORITE OF BIG-LEAGUE SCOUTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ When Long Beach Wilson High third baseman
Sean Burroughs boots a ball, the major league baseball scouts are
there to see it.
</P>
<P>
   A swing and miss? Yep, although a rarity, they see that, too.
</P>
<P>
   A popup? You got it, again not common, but they see that, too.
</P>
<P>
   And all of this happens during practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're here nearly every day,'' Wilson coach Mark Clabough
said while a couple of scouts watched Burroughs swing a wood bat
during a mid-season practice.
</P>
<P>
   For the typical 17-year-old kid, the attention has created deal
of
</P>
<P>
   pressure and, at times, ruined a senior season.
</P>
<P>
   For Burroughs, who won't turn 18 until September, it's greeted
with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that big of a deal,'' said Burroughs, who is expected
to be a top 10 pick this morning when the three-day Major League
amateur draft begins, and will be at third base when the Bruins
play Esperanza at 4 p.m. in the CIF Southern Section DivisionI
semifinals at Blair Field.
</P>
<P>
   But it is
</P>
<P>
   a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to forget about these days,'' Jeff Burroughs, Sean's
father, said. ``Scouts these days put (prospective draftees)
through psychological tests, eye tests, strength tests, signability
discussions and home visits.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that way in 1969 when Burroughs was completing his
final days terrorizing the Moore League as a senior at Wilson. The
scouts did their homework by strictly watching the kids play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even have a scout come to my house,'' Jeff said.
</P>
<P>
   xleg Jeff Burroughs was chosen by the Washington Senators with
the first pick of the 1969 draft. His son probably won't be the
first pick today. The owners of the top pick, the Philadelphia
Phillies, list Sean among their four candidates, but are expected
to choose University of Miami power hitter Pat Burrell.
</P>
<P>
   Sean will almost certainly be selected early in the opening
round, though. If that happens, the Burroughs will join Tom and Ben
Grieve as the only father and son to be selected in the first round
and the first father-son combo from the same high school to be
chosen in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Jeff was given an $80,000 signing bonus by the
Senators, which was enough to sway him away from a USC scholarship
to begin a professional career that included 16 major-league
seasons, 240 home runs and National League MVP honors in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Sean, whom Baseball America projects as the ninth overall pick
by the San Diego Padres, will be offered considerably more. Three
players from last year's draft signed for more than $2 million as a
bonus, including a record $2.5million given to pitcher Matt
Anderson by Detroit, and 15 others collected more than $1million.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, will the bonus be enough to keep Sean from
honoring the USC scholarship he signed in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too hard to say right now,'' said Sean, rated by Baseball
America as the high school player most ready to play in the big
leagues, and the best pure prep hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Sean ends up, he'll be ``going on to the next
chapter,'' according to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The book began about the time Sean, who was born in 1980, left
the crib.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good arm and a good swing when he was 3 or 4 years
old,'' said Jeff, who retired from baseball in 1985. ``I guess you
could say he was born with a bat in his crib.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Jeff Burroughs and his wife, Debbie, didn't steer Sean
toward the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played soccer first,'' said Jeff, who was a quarterback in
his days at Wilson. ``He was a normal Southern California kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Normal, that is, if a normal Southern California childhood
included the ability to throw a baseball 75 mph and hit home runs
traveling 350 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Sean introduced himself to the world as a 5-foot-5, 175-pound
11-year-old when he led the Long Beach Little League All-Stars to
the first of two consecutive World Series championships. The second
season ended with a guest appearance on the David Letterman Show
and a parade down Pine Avenue in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' said Sean, ``seems like a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sean grew older, he transformed from the pudgy youngster into
a well-proportioned 6-foot-2, 195-pounder with a calm disposition
on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're pretty darn similar,'' Jeff Burroughs said.
``It's really kind of scary how similar we are. The poor guy even
looks like me a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years of varsity soccer helped Sean slim down, as did a
stringent workout program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all these pictures around the house,'' Sean said,
``where I'm a short kid with a couple of chins and a big belly.
It's kind of funny to look at now.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what his body looked like, however, he could always
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was the best third baseman in the league as a
freshman,'' Lakewood coach Spud O'Neil said. ``And that hasn't
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Millikan's Dan Peters, who played against Jeff in high school,
remembers his first encounter with the younger Burroughs. It was
during a Moore League game in Sean's freshman year and Millikan had
senior Eric Ireland, who owned a fastball that reached the low 90s
and a scholarship to the University of Texas, on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ireland made him look silly the first time up,'' Peters said.
``I go out to coach third and I hear Sean getting kind of verbal
with his teammates. He was saying things like `This guy has
nothing,' (and) `I'll (get a hit) next time.' I'm thinking, OK,
we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time up, Burroughs lined a single off Ireland's foot
and he followed that up with another line-drive single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `OK, this guy's legit,''' Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs hit better than .300 as a freshman, bested .400 as a
sophomore, and earned All-CIF honors last season after hitting .456
and compiling a 7-1 record with a 1.75 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   This year he's been even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so much better than anyone else around here, it's not
even funny,'' Poly coach Bill Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs is hitting .511, with seven doubles, three triples,
seven home runs, 35 RBIs, 22 walks and three strikeouts in 88
at-bats. He also committed only three errors at third base and
routinely makes the tough plays.
</P>
<P>
   Hard work over the summer helped build those numbers. In
addition to playing locally in the Connie Mack League, Sean
traveled to North Carolina, Florida and San Diego for competition.
The highlight of the summer was an invitation to the Team 1
Showcase, featuring the country's best prep players, in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging out at the beach took a back seat to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a different guy ever since (the Team 1 Showcase),''
Clabough said. ``He went there with a real good group of guys and
stood out. He always knew he was a good ballplayer, but I think he
saw he could play against the best in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, he would be named as the CIF Player of the Year,
which his father won following his senior season in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Sean doesn't really care to talk about any player of the year
awards. That's not his style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the attention,'' Sean said. ``I never really
have. The team recognition is more important. I just want to do my
thing and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning a CIF championship would be included in his definition
of fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working our (butts) off for four years,'' Burroughs
said. ``We had big plans for this year. It's the last year that a
lot of us will play with each other. Obviously, a CIF championship
would be a great way to go out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
