<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9701 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-LONGBEACH-LADN     06-02 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-LONGBEACH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY ENJOYING CWS PROVING GROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Paul Day knew the situation perfectly well. He'd
been practicing it since he was a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be playing Whiffle Ball,'' Day was saying on Monday,
still relishing Long Beach State's stunning come-from-behind
College World Series victory over the Florida State the night
before, ``and we'd be saying stuff like `Seventh game of the World
Series, bottom of the ninth, two out, two on, and here's the pitch
...'''
</P>
<P>
   And it was a home run. It was always
</P>
<P>
   a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Now, older all of 22 and considerably wiser, Day has learned
that, by gosh, sometimes they aren't homers after all, that
sometimes ... well, go back to the fifth inning Sunday evening:
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were trailing FSU, 4-1, but they'd loaded the bases
with nobody out. And Day was the hitter ... Paul Day, the
All-American third baseman, the Big West Conference Player of the
Year, a guy who'd practically rewritten the Long Beach State record
book in what he'd earlier called his ``dream season.''
</P>
<P>
   And he struck out on three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're disappointed, sure, but you can't take that at-bat out
on the field with you, or to your next at-bat,'' he said. ``Hey,
major-leaguers strike out, too. And, anyway, this whole season has
been one of picking one another up if one guy doesn't get the job
done, the next guy will. That's Dirtbag baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that seldom-used Mike Hota drilled a two-run
single, and lightly regarded Scott Redfox poked a three-run homer,
and the 49ers managed to win and stave off elimination, and Paul
Day will have another day.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon the 49ers take on Miami again; the winner moves
on, the loser goes home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the great thing about baseball,'' Day said, smiling.
``There's always the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Day, who carried the 49ers through a good part of the regular
season, has had only brief flurries of success so far in the
post-season. In 11 post-season games, in the Big West tournament,
the West Regional and in two games so far in the College World
Series, Day is hitting just .229 (11 for 48), his average falling
from .438 at the end of the regular season to today's .401.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it, Day says, is the caliber of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here,'' he said, ``you're facing the best teams in the nation,
the best pitchers, and on an everyday basis.''
</P>
<P>
   And part of it, too, he acknowledged, is pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly,'' he said, ``it is pressure you put on your self. You
want to be aggressive but not overly aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each level you get to is different pressure. Like when we were
2-8 (to start the season). There was pressure to prove that we were
a better club than that. Then there was the pressure of the
Fullerton-Long Beach rivalry. And then, when we lost seven of eight
(in late April and early May), there was pressure not to let our
season get away because we'd worked so hard. And then there's the
pressure of the post-season, and now the College World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a different type of pressure today for Day, and
for just about every other amateur ballplayer, when the major
leagues conduct their draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying not to think about it,'' Day said. ``I'm not
worrying about where I go, or what round. It doesn't matter. It's
already been determined (by the big scouts) anyway. I wasn't
drafted out of high school, so I haven't been through it. But, like
I said, it doesn't matter. I play baseball because I love to play,
period.''
</P>
<P>
   And playing in the College World Series, Day said, ``is the
absolute ultimate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone playing college baseball, their dream is the College
World Series,'' he said. ``And, for us, this is like a proving
ground. The other teams here, they didn't expect us to come of the
West (Regional), so we're the underdogs. The people in Omaha have
picked up on it; we've got a lot of fans at our games, it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   So, is Paul Day looking forward to getting another chance in the
clutch today?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' he said, eagerly. All he's got to do now is get
the whiff out of Whiffle Ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
