<SLUG> BC-BBC-NEWUSC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC STAYS ALIVE IN OMAHA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ The USC Trojans will play another day in Omaha,
and all they can do is hope their College World Series game tonight
against Mississippi State isn't as exhausting as their last two.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of watching LSU hit eight home runs against them in
their opener Saturday, the Trojans saw an 8-5 lead blow up on them
Monday night before 20,738 at Rosenblatt Stadium against top-seeded
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   They eventually outlasted the Gators by the same score as
Saturday, 12-10, scoring four runs on five hits in the 11th,
including doubles by Eric Munson and Jason Lane. But they could not
have strayed any closer to a series-ending loss.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Florida scored three runs with two out to tie,
the tying runs coming on Mark Ellis' two-run homer off the first
pitch by Trojans ace reliever Jack Krawcyzk. Before the inning was
over, the Gators would put runners on second and third before the
Trojans closer struck out Casey Smith.
</P>
<P>
   In the tenth, the Gators put runners on first and second with
two out, with Florida All-American Brad Wilkerson coming to the
plate. USC coach Mike Gillespie chose to walk Wilkerson
intentionally, putting the winning run on third base.
</P>
<P>
   The gamble worked. Smith worked Krawcyzk to a full count before
the closer got him on a little dribbler in front of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a great move, especially when you win,'' said
Florida coach Andy Lopez, who took Pepperdine to the 1992 title.
``I wouldn't have pitched to Wilkerson in the same spot. I did the
same thing in 1992 (he walked Fullerton's Phil Nevin without an
open base in the title game).''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a difficult decision,'' USC coach Mike Gillespie
said. ``He's a very special hitter, a future major-leaguer. We
could not let him be the guy to beat us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack stayed with it in an incredibly tough situation,''
Gillespie added. ``He's shown he's the kind of guy who won't crack.
That's about as gutsy as it can get for a college kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole stadium was standing on its feet and cheering that
situation,'' said USC outfielder Jeremy Freitas. ``But it was just
one moment in a game that had a million.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after USC scored four in the 11th, the Gators rallied.
Jason Dill hit a line drive off the top of the left field fence,
less than a foot away from a home run, that cashed in the second
run of the inning. But the carom off the wall came on a line right
to Freitas, who threw to second to get a stunned Dill by a good 15
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Florida jumped on top in the first on Casey Smith's three-run
home run off Trojans starter Jason Lane. But the Trojans scored two
runs in the second, third and fourth. Munson hit a two-run homer in
the second, Robb Gorr doubled in two runs in the third, and Brad
Ticehurst and Freitas each hit long solo home runs in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   While the Trojans bats were booming, Mike Penney was silencing
those of Florida. Penney replaced Lane with two out in the third.
After allowing a double and walk, Penney retired ten straight
Florida batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans scored solo runs in the sixth and seventh to take an
8-4 lead, but they also left five men on base in those innings,
failing to convert anything out of a bases loaded, one out
situation in the sixth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
