</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLEEFUL GIANTS ROLL OVER REDS
</HEADLINE>
  By HENRY SCHULMAN 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Giants' hitters have done a lot of good
things this season, but they had not orchestrated one of those
gut-busting laughers that let a starting pitcher sit on the bench
and dream about his November golf vacation on Maui instead of
worrying about the next half-inning.
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants finally pulled one off Monday night, burying
Cincinnati 16-3, they accomplished it against a hot team. The Reds
rolled into town off three straight wins at Los Angeles, but the
Giants simply rolled over them for their fourth straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   The rout got so bad, by the eighth inning, the Reds had
utilityman Lenny Harris pitch. Sure enough, he retired the Giants
1-2-3 and even struck out his first batter, Brent Mayne, on three
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those games that no matter who we threw out
there, we got the hell knocked out of us,'' Reds manager Jack
McKeon said. ``At least we found a relief pitcher in Harris.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kent and Charlie Hayes each tied career highs with five
RBIs, Hayes notching four of his in the fifth inning, when the
Giants scored a season-best eight runs.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds scored four runs and Rich Aurilia three. In fact,
every Giants starter scored at least once. Chris Jones was the last
to join the party, homering in the seventh inning for the Giants'
season-high 16th run and their 16th hit.
</P>
<P>
   This game fell under the heading of Hitting Is Contagious, a
controversial school of thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe in it,'' Giants center fielder Darryl
Hamilton said. ``In the first inning, after we were down a couple
of runs, we scored a few back to set the tone. Everyone just jumped
in and swung the bats well. You hope to have nights like this every
night, but they don't happen so often, so you've got to try to take
advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hamilton said, the Giants actually trailed 2-0 after a half
inning behind starting pitcher Mark Gardner, who has now allowed 15
first-inning runs in 12 starts. Reggie Sanders, the first batter of
the game, homered.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants fought back against rookie Eddie Priest in the
bottom of the first. Hamilton, Aurilia and Bonds all singled to
center, and all eventually scored. McKeon lifted Priest after five
batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hitting him hard,'' McKeon said, ``and I didn't want
to get the kid crucified.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the bullpen's job.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants went ahead 6-2 on Kent's three-run homer in the third
off Scott Sullivan, Kent's sixth of the season. The Reds got a run
back in the fourth on doubles by Dmitri Young and Bret Boone, but
the Giants blew the game open 14-3 when 13 hitters batted in the
fifth off David Weathers and Gabe White, and eight of them scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everything we hit fell in,'' said Hayes, who has
24 RBIs in just 113 at-bats. ``It's good to have that a couple of
times a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes drove in the first two runs of the big inning with a
scorching double to the wall in center, then drove in the last two
with a soft single to right.
</P>
<P>
   Kent, the second-leading RBI man on the team, raised his total
to 41 with a sacrifice fly in the first, the three-run homer in the
third and a bases-loaded walk in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Kent is achieving one preseason goal, to raise his batting
average. This time last year he was hitting .257 en route to a .250
finish. This season he's hitting .288. But his home run production
has fallen from 11 at this time last season to six.
</P>
<P>
   Kent was asked if there was any correlation between the rise in
average and the drop in home runs. He didn't like the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't appreciate any comparisons of stats this time of
year,'' he said. ``You can't judge 162 games against 30, 60, 80 or
100. You don't know what might happen. I could get hurt tomorrow,
or I could turn into Mark McGwire. I could find the right mix.''
</P>
<P>
   For one night, the Giants had nine McGwire's out there,
producing so much offense the Reds felt compelled to send a
position player to the mound for an inning. The three guys he
retired, Mayne, Stan Javier and Bill Mueller, may have been the
only dudes crying after a laugher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
