<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A'S GET ALL SENSITIVE, THEN SLUG OUT A WIN 
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ It sounded crazy at first. A's manager Art Howe
was upset with his bullpen and its 7.80 ERA over the previous eight
days.
</P>
<P>
   So what did he do? He made nice. That's right. He called all
seven relievers into his office before Monday night's game, and for
a good 40 minutes he encouraged them to share their feelings with
Howe and pitching coach Rick Peterson about how they can be more
confident.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it sounds a little like a whole staff of Stuart Smalleys
out on the mound saying to themselves, ``I'm good enough, I'm smart
enough and, doggone it, people like me.'' But who wants to argue
with results?
</P>
<P>
   The encounter-group-assisted A's bullpen was a roaring success
Monday night. It held the Twins to one run over the final 31/3
innings of the game, taking over from Mike Oquist (2-3). The A's
bombed their way to an 8-5 win, sparked by homers from Ben Grieve,
Matt Stairs, Mike Macfarlane and Scott Spiezio. Billy Taylor picked
up his ninth save, the first by an A's pitcher since May 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen did a good job,'' Howe said. ``We got focused in
there. We decided what we had to do and went out and did it. We
went after people for the most part. I didn't talk to the starters,
so Okie's out of that. ... More than anything, the meeting was
about getting ahead in the count and going after hitters low in the
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern over the first third of the season was for the A's
offense to go limp when the pitchers let a game start to slip away.
The A's (23-31) had lost six of eight games before Monday and in
the losses, A's hitters were batting just .133 after the fifth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the A's did not pick up their first hit off starter
Eric Milton (3-5) until the fourth. Once they started hitting, they
had trouble stopping and scored in every subsequent inning but the
seventh. Stairs' two-run homer in the sixth put them ahead to stay,
but late insurance runs helped a lot, too.
</P>
<P>
   The offense looked like something to be taken seriously. Rickey
Henderson stole two bases to give him 21 and tie him with Tom
Goodwin for the American League lead. Henderson, 39, is on pace to
steal 63 bases this year and surpass 50 for the first time since
1991. He's still playing like a man who wants to make a point, so
don't expect the stolen-base productivity to taper off any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve just keeps hitting, and still ranks second on the team in
RBIs with 35. One-third of the way through the season, he's on pace
to hit .310 with 24 homers and 105 RBIs. Spiezio went 3-for-4 to
extend his hitting streak to 10 games and lift his average to .286.
He's on pace for 90 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking a lot of early hitting,'' Spiezio said. ``Let's
hope we're talking like this at the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen can't think that far down the road. Safe to say,
they'll be taking it one day at a time. Monday night they needed a
little luck to look so good. Left-hander Buddy Groom's first
batter, Otis Nixon, drilled a double to left-center, but dynamo
center fielder Ryan Christenson made a good play to get to the ball
quickly, and Spiezio's relay nailed Minnesota catcher Terry
Steinbach at the plate to end the Twins' sixth with no runs
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters came in with two out in the seventh and got Ron
Coomer to snuff a small threat, then Taylor came out with two gone
in the eighth and needed just one pitch to get Nixon on a groundout
to second. That stranded two runners and kept the A's in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have confidence, you're not going to win,''
Fetters said. ``We've been on a roller-coaster ride all season
long. You can't hope for outs. You have to know you're going to get
outs. That meeting was basically to say: We have to pick each other
up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
