<SLUG> BC-GENIUS-GRANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE IN NORTHERN CALIFORNIA WIN MACARTHUR AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LORI OLSZEWSKI and DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Five Northern California talents are among the
winners of the MacArthur ``genius'' awards announced Monday _
Oakland writer Ishmael Reed, a Stanford economist, two scientists
and an attorney who works with female prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who arrived home Monday after a visit with his mother in
New York and a stop at a book convention in Chicago, said he
learned of the honor through a phone call Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't believe it,'' said Reed, the groundbreaking
poet, playwright and novelist. ``I had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Author Terry McMillan said, ``It's about time he got one. He's
brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed is among 29 people selected as this year's John D. and
Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation fellows. The other four Northern
Californians to receive the honor are: attorney Ellen Barry,
founder of Legal Services for Prisoners with Children in San
Francisco; Avner Greif, the Stanford University economist;
neuroscientist Leah Krubitzer of the University of California at
Davis; and Benjamin Santer, a senior atmospheric scientist at the
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has been handing out the awards since 1981 to
honor outstanding creativity _ with no strings attached. There is
no application process. A secret panel of talent scouts makes
nominations to the foundation board, which makes the final choice.
</P>
<P>
   Reed is recognized for his literary work, including novels such
as ``Mumbo Jumbo,'' ``Reckless Eyeballing'' and ``The Terrible
Twos,'' but he is also a popular teacher in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan said Reed, who has been an instructor at the University
of California at Berkeley for the last 30 years, was her first
fiction professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very supportive of young writers, and they don't forget
him,'' McMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very deserving and I am just thrilled for him,'' said
Blanche Richardson, the manager of Marcus Book Stores in Oakland
and San Francisco, a national center for black literature for more
than 35 years where Reed is a regular.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's politically charged art has often illuminated the serious
issues of urban poverty and America's racial divide with biting
satiric humor that takes on everybody from hypocritical whites to
cultural icons such as Oprah Winfrey. He has been criticized by
feminists and praised as an important force behind the publication
of writers with multiethnic perspectives through his Before
Columbus Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, 60, said he wants to use some of the $355,000 he will
receive as a MacArthur fellow over the next five years to stage a
San Francisco production of his opera, `Gethsemane Park,' which he
and composer Carman Moore premiered in Berkeley earlier this year
at the Black Repertory Group.
</P>
<P>
   The other four Northern Californians to receive the 1998 awards
are:
</P>
<P>
   -- Attorney Barry of Oakland, 44, founder of Legal Services for
Prisoners with Children, a San Francisco-based organization that is
nationally recognized as a leading advocate for women in prison.
She receives $275,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned. This is the first time in my life I won't have
to raise my own salary,'' said Barry with a laugh, who founded her
organization fresh out of New York University Law School in 1978.
It has gone on to be an important national force in developing
sentencing alternatives for mothers who are in prison and in
supporting grandparents left to care for their incarcerated
daughters' children.
</P>
<P>
   It also has filed lawsuits that helped improve health care for
women in California state prisons, including Chowchilla and
Frontera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these women are in on nonviolent charges, with a
history of drug abuse and petty theft,'' Barry said. ``Most have
been victims of physical or sexual abuse at an early age. That is
not an excuse, but it clearly is an explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Stanford University economist Greif, 42, who has applied
modern techniques of game theory to explain the development of
social institutions in the medieval Mediterranean region. He
receives $265,000, which he hopes to use to complete more archival
work overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-born Greif has applied game theory to explain the
growth of social institutions, such as legal systems and insurance
contracts, among Genoese traders in the 12th century and contrasted
why they did not develop among Jewish traders, known as the
Maghribi, in the Arab world a century earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The broader import of his work is to show the interactions of
individual behavior and social institutions, and how together they
affect the course of history. Many other scholars take a region's
culture or institutions as a given in explaining the history of a
period.
</P>
<P>
   -- Neuroscientist Krubitzer, 37, an assistant professor at the
University of California at Davis, whose research on the brain has
provided insights into the development of the cerebral cortex and
the evolutionary forces driving brain adaptation. She receives
$240,000.
</P>
<P>
   Krubitzer describes her work as ``the exciting business of
building a brain.''
</P>
<P>
   The award will help her crucial research into how the brains of
all living mammals have developed many common features of
organization through evolution, at the same time they acquire
special features unique to each species. It also will give her a
chance to visit Africa for the first time, to observe the
continent's widely varying animal life.
</P>
<P>
   -- Santer, 43, a climatologist at the Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory, whose research supports the hypothesis that
human activity contributes to global warming. He receives $270,000.
</P>
<P>
   When Santer led a distinguished panel of experts who concluded
two years ago that global warming is real and that ``greenhouse
gases'' are a significant factor in the dangerous problem, a
dwindling but powerful minority of scientists opposed him. Some
even charged him with unprofessional conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But the MacArthur Foundation has provided some vindication with
its award for Santer's leadership in providing ``important
scientific foundations'' for last year's international negotiations
in Kyoto, Japan, on greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Jonathan Marshall contributed to this
story.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
