<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, June 2, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SEX (San Francisco) _ State health officials are hoping
the fear of missing out on sex will curb sales of cigarettes, which
medical researchers have linked to impotence. ``We're not certain
men will stop smoking to save their lungs or their hearts,'' said
Carla Agar, spokeswoman for the Department of Health Services.
``Maybe they'll stop to save their sex lives.'' By TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   COPYCATS (Houston) _ Many vendors selling cheap imitations or
knock-offs of Nike T-shirts, Rolex watches and Dooney &AMP; Bourke
handbags used to glide through the courts with a small fine and
slap on the wrist. But with a change in Texas law and aggressive
undercover police efforts, authorities here say brokers of
illegitimate merchandise are now facing the real thing _ a felony
charge. By STEVE BREWER.
</P>
<P>
   MacARTHUR-WINNERS (San Francisco) _ The message in scientist
Benjamin Santer's fortune cookie read: ``You will hear good news
from far away.'' The next day, Santer got a phone message from far
away that he had won one of the so-called ``genius awards'' from
the MacArthur Foundation. The prize was $270,000. By MARIANNE
COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   VALEDICTORIAN (Kerrville, Texas) _ Tivy High School
valedictorian Josh Walther saw humor in calling on the two
lowest-ranking members of his class to replace him at the podium at
commencement exercises. ``Why should I have to do more work and
give a speech?'' he planned on saying. ``I wasn't the one slacking
the last four years.'' School officials stopped him from giving the
speech. By ZEKE MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   ~
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSHROOM-HUNTER (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ ``Americans have a fear of
mushrooms because we haven't studied them and we don't have a
tradition of looking for them,'' said mushroom hunter Marjorie
Lutz, who has been gathering and eating wild fungi for more than
two decades. ``But they really can be wonderful.'' By ELIZABETH
BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   BIG-TOOLS (Albany, N.Y.) _ This year, Americans will purchase
upwards of 22 million gas-powered lawn and garden tools _ a record
number, according to the Environmental Protection Agency. And as
sales of these tools grow, so too have the size of the engines
powering them _ producing harmful noise and air pollution. By PAUL
ZIELBAUER.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-COLLEGE (Kendleton, Texas) _ When the Rev. J. Horace
Germany launched a college for black preachers in Mississippi, he
was nearly killed. He made his way to East Texas to revive his
dreams. Nearly 40 years later, Germany feared his dream was dying
along with his financially strapped Bay Ridge Christian College
campus. But Bay Ridge is poised to become a leader in the
surrounding communities. By PATTI MUCK. (Art available on the New
York Times photo service)
</P>
<P>
   PARTNERS-BENEFITS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco officialdom
celebrated the first anniversary of a landmark law that, despite
ongoing legal challenges, has resulted in more than 1,700 companies
extending equal benefits to their workers' domestic partners. By
RACHEL GORDON and ANASTASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you've gotten an offer in the mail
saying you've been pre-approved for credit, don't assume you're a
shoo-in for a loan. You can still be turned down. By PAMEL YIP
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SKI-LAKE-TAHOE (Truckee, Calif.) _ In the battle of the seasons
being waged at Lake Tahoe, skis and snowmobiles definitely have the
edge on canoes and fishing poles. El Nino has crashed the summer
party that should have kicked off on Memorial Day weekend, when
hiking and mountain-biking trails heat up. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PETS (San Pedro, Calif.) _ I always wanted a pet. Once I even
brought home a dog I found in a Beirut alley. But that was years
ago, back in Lebanon, and that stray dog wasn't allowed to enter
the threshold of my childhood home. I am now an American citizen
who has become the owner of a pet. By GLADYS ALAM SAROYAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
