<P>
   This year, many travel companies are featuring trips that focus
on adventures of the mind and exploration of cultures throughout
the world.
</P>
<P>
   For example, TraveLearn, a Lakeville, Pa.-based company, seasons
its travel programs with on-site lectures; field experiences
conducted by local experts; and opportunities to meet and mingle
with the locals _ say, a meal with a Moroccan family.
</P>
<P>
   Tour groups vary in size from eight to 20 people with college
faculty escorts. Some of the 18 tours offered this year include
stops in Antarctica, China, the Galapagos, Ireland and Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are from $2,000 to $5,000 and include airfare from
departure cities.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write TraveLearn, P.O. Box 315, Lakeville,
Pa. 18438; call (800) 235-9114; or visit their Web site at
www.travelearn.com.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Senior Summer School provides a choice of college-level travel
programs that cater to the mature set at five U.S. universities in
the cities of Los Angeles, San Diego and Santa Barbara, Calif.; New
Brunswick, Canada; and Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The programs vary in duration from two weeks ($500) to eight
weeks ($2,900) and include accommodations, meals, courses and
related trips, social events and some weekend activities.
Accommodations will be at university dormitories or residence
halls.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write to Senior Summer School, P.O. Box
4424, Deerfield Beach, Fla. 33442; call (800) 847-2466; or visit
their Web site at www.seniorsummerschool.com.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   The Maui Writers Conference is the place to be for mature
travelers who have a writerly flair.
</P>
<P>
   Slated for Sept. 4 to 7 and preceded by a retreat Aug. 29 to
Sept. 3, the conference promises aspiring writers the opportunity
to mingle with publishing experts, ``rent'' an agent for 15
minutes, have a manuscript evaluated and listen to some great
speakers, from Pulitzer Prize-winner Dave Barry to Robert Loomis,
vice president of Random House.
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations will be at the Grand Wailea Resort or Aston
Wailea.
</P>
<P>
   The conference registration is $500 if postmarked by July 1;
$600 thereafter. Consultations and evaluations are extra, as are
airfare and hotel.
</P>
<P>
   For registration forms, write P.O. Box 1118, Kihei, Hawaii
96753; call (808) 879-0061; or e-mail writers(AT)maui.net.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Familyhostel, a program sponsored by the University of New
Hampshire Continuing Education, offers kids ages 8 to 15 and their
grandparents the chance to learn more about the world in which they
live.
</P>
<P>
   Familyhostel's summer '98 programs, which last 10 days, will
include trips to Vienna, Austria; Prague and the Czech Castles;
Normandy, Paris and Provence, France; Cuernavaca and Mexico City,
Mexico; and Abergavenny and Emyln, Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Familyhostel grew out of Interhostel, a travel and study abroad
program for people ages 50 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Familyhostel programs cost from $2,200 to $3,000 for adults and
$2,100 to $2,600 for grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Participants are assigned a pre-trip reading list and are asked
to create a scrapbook during the trip.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write Familyhostel, UNH Continuing
Education, 6 Garrison Ave., Durham, N.H. 03824; call (800)
733-9753; or visit their Web site at www.learn.unh.edu.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   For September, Elderhostel is offering a new two-week cultural
exploration of Ghana, West Africa, called African Music and Dance.
</P>
<P>
   This educational program, which is designed specifically for
those ages 55 and older, costs $3,000 from New York or $3,300 from
Los Angeles and includes airfare.
</P>
<P>
   This program is an intensive introduction to Ghana, its history
and people and uses music and dance as the vehicle for discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Participants will dance, sing and learn about the Ghanaian way
of life, according to Kwame Agyapong, the program coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write to Elderhostel, Dept. J3, P.O. Box
1959, Wakefield, Mass. 01880-5959; or call (617) 426-7788
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Educational travel experiences that enable travelers to meet
famous authors are what make Saga Holidays' Roads Scholar program
so special.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new 1998 offerings is a 16-night program called
British Landscapes and Literature, with accommodations at the
campus of the Oatridge Agriculture College in Oatridge, Scotland,
and in the Lake District of England.
</P>
<P>
   In Scotland, there will be lectures about Robert the Bruce and
William Wallace. In England, the topic will be the Lake poets,
William Wordsworth and Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
</P>
<P>
   Rates, based on single occupancy, start at $2,400 per person,
including airfare. For details, call (800) 621-2151.
</P>
