<SLUG> BC-MED-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 c.1998 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Medical Tribune News Service stories for Tuesday,
June 2, 1998. If you have questions about the availability of this
service, contact Bob Farnell at the New York Times Syndicate
(800)-535-4425.
</P>
<P>
   MALE-IMPOTENCE-MED _ EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE TUESDAY AT 3 P.M.
EASTERN _ SAN DIEGO _ As the hype continues over Viagra, two new
reports offer possible alternatives to the widely acclaimed
anti-impotency drug.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings are expected to be reported here Tuesday at the
annual meeting of the American Urological Association. (500 WORDS)
(DEVELOPING)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-SURVIVAL-MED _ EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE TUESDAY AT 4 P.M.
EASTERN _ Recent research has shown that people with late-stage
cancer often overestimate their odds of survival. Now, a new study
shows that such unrealistic expectations may impact on the type of
medical care a terminally ill patient chooses.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to less optimistic cancer patients, those who believed
that they had a better than 90 percent chance of living six months
or longer were more than two-and-a-half times as likely to choose
aggressive treatment rather than more conservative therapy that
emphasized relief of pain and discomfort, researchers reported in
Wednesday's issue of the Journal of the American Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But choosing more aggressive care did not result in longer
survival, according to the study of 917 adults hospitalized with
late-stage cancer of the lung or colon that had spread to the
liver.
</P>
<P>
   When factors such as age, race, sex and education were taken
into account, there was no significant difference in survival at
six months between patients who chose aggressive treatment and
those who sought so-called comfort care, reported researchers led
by Dr. Jane C. Weeks of the Dana Farber Cancer Institute in Boston.
(500 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE-HEARING-MED _ EMBARGOED UNTIL 4 P.M. EASTERN _ New
research suggests that smoking may lead to hearing loss, Wisconsin
researchers report.
</P>
<P>
   Current smokers were about 70 percent more likely to have
hearing loss than nonsmokers in the study of 3,753 adults ages 48
to 92 years old. In addition, nonsmokers who lived with a smoker
were more likely to have a hearing problem than those not exposed
to secondhand smoke at home, researchers reported in Wednesday's
issue of the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The more a person smoked, the more likely he or she was to
report hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 30 percent to 35 percent of adults ages 65 to 75
years old have some hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, just under 15 percent of the participants were
smokers. Of the entire group, 45 percent reported some hearing
loss.
</P>
<P>
   One mechanism by which smoking might affect hearing is by
constricting the blood supply to the ear, causing cells involved in
processing noises to die, said Karen J. Cruickshanks, an associate
professor of ophthalmology at the University of Wisconsin Medical
School in Madison. (500 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-ADVICE-MED _ Dr. Eric Anderson answers health questions.
This week:
</P>
<P>
   _ What treatments are available for neuropathy? I developed the
condition after undergoing a series of chemotherapy treatments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can the anti-impotency drug Viagra be safely taken with all
other medications? (500 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   DENTAL-HEALTH-MED
</P>
<P>
   David A. Whiston, president, American Dental Association,
discusses selecting oral health-care products. (500 WORDS)
</P>
