<HEADER>
A9985 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKREVIEW-IRVING03-C     06-02 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKREVIEW-IRVING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOOKREVIEW: ``Widow'' not without beauty
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A WIDOW FOR ONE YEAR, by John Irving. Random House; 537 pages;
$27.95.
</P>
<P>
   Too much is never enough for John Irving, which is both his most
admirable quality and his most reliable failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Widow for One Year'' begins with a prologue that sets up the
rest of the book, a prologue that limps along for 180 pages and
should have been cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, it is 1958, and we are introduced to the characters
that we meet again in 1990 and follow through until the book's
ending in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There is Marion, beautiful, blond, the mother of three, two of
whom are dead in a car accident before the book opens but who hover
over every waking and sleeping moment of their mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   There is Ted, her husband, a serial adulterer and author of
famous children's books. There is Ruth, Marion and Ted's
replacement child.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Eddie, a young Exeter student hired as Ted's
assistant for the summer, who grudgingly manages the logistics of
Ted's affairs when he's not vigorously pleasuring Marion, who ruins
him for any woman who isn't two decades his elder.
</P>
<P>
   When we pick up the characters 32 years later, we find Irving up
to his old tricks of compulsive character cheating, the better to
keep the plot pot boiling and indulge in his waggish sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie who, at 16, was an inventive, industrious, resourceful
young man, has in middle age unaccountably mutated into a
creatively impotent, feckless joke.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth has grown up to be her mother's flip side _ extremely
inhibited, not very sexual at all, driven mostly by the quest for
excellence in her novels _ which, in the excerpts Irving provides,
are uninteresting, prototypically P.C. feminist fiction in the Anna
Quindlen mode.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. Ruth goes to Amsterdam, where she develops a deeply
unlikely interest in the sex trade and ends up embroiled in a
murder that conveniently propels her to the next stage of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Ted, in his late 70s, is still in pursuit of every female he can
find, which is at least consistent, although it beggars the
imagination that he could beat people _ athletic people _ half his
age at squash.
</P>
<P>
   Irving seems to have some sort of literary bipolar disorder; if
his people were flesh and blood, they'd all have whiplash from the
way they're yanked around for the sake of narrative amusement.
</P>
<P>
   For me, Irving falls between two schools: He has little interest
in pure naturalism, but he lacks the capacious imagination to go
all the way into extravagance a la Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   And, as nearly as I can tell, he's completely without the lyric
gift. Irving's idea of setting a scene is a cursory, ``The sky was
a crisp and cloudless blue.''
</P>
<P>
   This prosaic flatness sometimes earns a laugh; a dreary woman
who assails Ted Cole for an autograph is described as having ``hips
like a mule.'' Not elegant, but blunt and funny. Other equally
abrupt lines _ ``as deceitful as a damaged condom'' _ are less
fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   So Irving presses on, both of him. There's the Irving who's a
devout absurdist, with his nose pressed firmly against the glass as
he objectively catalogs the ridiculousness of other people's
Christmas celebrations, and there's the Irving who is inside,
happily decorating the tree.
</P>
<P>
   At his best, he has it both ways and dissolves the glass,
portraying the celebration and the exhaustion, the endless
irritation bred by the forced march of extended family obligations,
which can be all that keep people sane.
</P>
<P>
   At these times, he's a literary Robert Altman, but ``A Widow for
One Year'' is more like a middling four-hour miniseries than it is
even a mediocre Altman movie.
</P>
<P>
   Why then, is he so popular? Why are even Irving novels that are
truly unreadable _ I know many people who began ``A Son of the
Circus;'' I know nobody who finished it _ accorded such good
reviews?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there is the continuing goodwill engendered by ``The World
According to Garp,'' one of those rare modern novels that people
truly loved. And there is the fact that, if you take away the
(often inventive) sex, Irving writes very old-fashioned fiction,
but with a modern twist.
</P>
<P>
   Irving indulges in all sorts of tics borrowed from the
Victorians, the early Victorians _ little pin-pricks foretelling
the narrative: ``If she'd known then that it would be their last
conversation, she might have tried to patch things up with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most commercial novels are all plot; most literary novels are
all character. Irving's primary gift is for character, sweet
characters, whose lives shift and twist with changing times and
circumstances. If you buy into Irving's people, you buy the often
arbitrary, occasionally ludicrous vicissitudes visited upon them by
their creator.
</P>
<P>
   Besides problems of character consistency, ``A Widow for One
Year'' is hampered by the unpleasant fact that its most interesting
character is more or less disposed of after the prologue. Marion is
driven, haunted, intensely sexual, extremely strong-minded. By
comparison, everyone else in the book is near-beer. Irving's idea
seems to be that if the other characters mention her enough, she'll
be there, but that's wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, ``A Widow for One Year'' is not without its incidental
beauties. Irving is very good with time, the way something that
happens 30 or 40 years earlier, something as tiny as a cut finger,
can suddenly resonate like a sharply struck tuning fork.
</P>
<P>
   And I like his extended homage in which Ruth spends years
working her way through Norman Sherry's biography of Graham Greene,
one of her _ and my _ favorite writers.
</P>
<P>
   Irving always has a large supply of good humor, and a good eye
for the domestic detail: ``In every marriage there are designated
chores; there is always someone who is largely responsible for
putting out the trash, and someone who is principally in charge of
not running out of coffee or milk or toothpaste or toilet paper.
Allen was in charge of temperature. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   And, for all of his too-cute self-indulgence, Irving's emphasis
on humanity seems to me ultimately admirable. The middle-aged Eddie
is asked how he can possibly press himself against the withered
flesh of the older women he takes as simulations of Marion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to see the whole woman,'' he replies. ``Of course I
recognize that she's old . . . (but) I can picture her when she was
much younger than I am _ because there are always gestures and
expressions that are ingrained, ageless. An old woman doesn't
always see herself as an old woman, and neither do I. I try to see
her whole life in her. There's something so moving about someone's
whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   What starts out as a coarse running joke is redeemed by a
poignant sympathy. In moments like these, John Irving justifies his
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
