A9987 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYEMAN-ON-BOOKS03-COX     06-02 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYEMAN-ON-BOOKS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sandberg poem charming, but is he still read?
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Sandburg won two Pulitzer prizes, one for his poetry and
one for writing the most popular Lincoln biography of the first
half of this century. He also wrote a best-selling novel
(``Remembrance Rock''), but all this was a long time ago and I get
the distinct sense he's not widely read anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Knopf has issued ``Not Everyday an Aurora Borealis
for Your Birthday'' ($13), a previously unpublished, but charming,
poem with lovely illustrations by Anita Lobel.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth your attention are two new volumes from New
Directions. The first is Balzac's ``Colonel Chabert'' ($9.95), a
new translation of one of the best sequences from ``The Human
Comedy,'' the great cycle that eventually encompassed more than 90
novels and novellas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colonel Chabert'' concerns a war hero believed to have been
killed, but who returns to Paris a disfigured man who finds his
wife remarried and his soldier's pension long gone. He hires a
lawyer and begins the arduous process of proving he is who he says
he is, in order to force his ex-wife to give up some of her money.
</P>
<P>
   There are some similarities to Dickens' ``Bleak House,'' and one
can easily imagine Twain using the same idea for a savage attack on
human cupidity, but Balzac wasn't writing out of satirical or
mordant impulses, but in a deeply realistic vein of pity and power.
Balzac wrote ``Colonel Chabert'' in 1832, and it remains completely
involving.
</P>
<P>
   The second volume, ``The Notebook of Trigorin'' ($19.95) is a
real curio, Tennessee Williams' free adaptation of Chekhov's ``The
Sea Gull.'' It was written in the early '80s, when Williams' best
work was far behind him, and not performed until a year ago in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   A ROOM FOR TWO, OVERLOOKING THE POOL: One of Miami's landmarks
is the lovely Biltmore Hotel in Coral Gables, and Helen Muir's book
about it, originally published in 1987, has gone into its third
edition. It's full of great photos that bring back the salad days
of the great Florida land boom of the mid-'20s, when the hotel was
built.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Biltmore: Beacon for Miami,'' costs $19.95 and is
available at Books and Books, gift shops around South Florida, and,
of course, The Biltmore itself.
</P>
<P>
   Also noteworthy is ``The BFI Companion to Crime,'' from the
University of California Press ($29.95). It's a reliable,
accessible, one-size-fits-all _ more or less _ guide to the world
of crime movies and film noir.
</P>
<P>
   The book is organized encyclopedia-style _ ``Gaslight'' is
followed by ``Get Carter,'' which is followed by ``The Getaway,''
etc. The entries are concise, well-written, often provocative and
feature a good selection of Japanese Yakuza films although the
emphasis is on English and American films.
</P>
<P>
   Ten or so years ago, the British Film Institute published ``The
BFI Guide to the Western,'' and this might even be better than that
worthy volume.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE: ``Women deprived of the company of men pine, men
deprived of the company of women become stupid.'' _ Anton Chekhov
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
