<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9989 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REALLIFE03-COX     06-02 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALLIFE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I just couldn't give it up
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On the stage, she will dance without
fear. The four tendus a la seconde to the right, the four to the
left. She will land in a near-perfect fifth position, her soft,
classy navy blue outfit falling around her and then she will close
her eyes and listen to that spectacular applause. She will run
backstage with the other girls, her comrades with the aching
muscles and the smelly Icy Hot ointment stuffed into their scuffed
Danskin bags, her comrades with the school-girl giggles, and they
will hug and laugh and hug some more.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Morgan, the strictest of the strict at the Academy of
Ballet Florida in West Palm Beach, Fla., will come forward and
enthuse, as only Miss Morgan can, `Girls, that was beautiful.' And
then Shannon Pasley, a girl who just 15 months ago had something so
wrong with her brain that her family didn't know if she'd be able
to feed herself again, let alone do a plie, will go home and wake
up in the morning and be just a normal teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel lucky,'' she scoffs. ``Very.''
</P>
<P>
   There she was, all legs and smiles, in the fourth grade and
barely reading chapter books, when she started getting The Feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon went to her mother, Jane, and complained about it. It
felt as though she was having a spasm in her arm, a tightness that
wouldn't go away. Something wasn't right, she told her mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm would become dead weight and I would just lean toward
it because I couldn't keep it up and then I would just lean all the
way down,'' Shannon says now. ``I knew before it would happen and
that would give me time to get down, or something. I'd get that
feeling and go, Oh, God.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Jane Pasley treated Shannon's complaints casually. But
after a while, it became clear that something, something big, was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were finding her everywhere,'' says her mother. ``On the
floor in the bathroom, on the floor in the bedroom. And she didn't
know what had happened.''
</P>
<P>
   They went to a doctor, of course, who sent them to another
doctor who did some tests on the brain of the smiling 9-year-old
and then delivered the very bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon had a noncancerous tumor that was causing her seizures,
three or more a day. At one point during the diagnosis they hooked
Shannon up to a machine as she slept. Her brain was seizing,
practically nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor put Shannon on medicine and, for about a year, the
episodes were controlled, although ``controlled'' is a misleading
word when you are discussing seizures. Everywhere the Pasleys went
_ school, church, the mall, the movies _ there was the fear that
Shannon would collapse in a puddle on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were constantly on pins and needles,'' says her mother.
``Oh, it was horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   But all the while, Miss Shannon Pasley, the girl who put on her
first dance leotard at the ripe old age of 3, reported to Ballet
Florida, to practice her biggest love.
</P>
<P>
   She practiced her shuffle off to Buffalos.
</P>
<P>
   She practiced her ronde de jambe en l'airs.
</P>
<P>
   She practiced her dance over and over and over again, even
though she was still getting The Feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Morgan, dance teacher extraordinaire, remembers the time
Shannon collapsed during class.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, the important instructor with all the right moves,
freaked out. But Shannon's friends who had been with her for a
while knew ``just what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so scared,'' says Morgan. ``But one of her friends just
took her by the hand. And by the time I had opened the door to the
tap studio and turned around, Shannon was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Except that she was having two, three, four, even five and six,
seizures a day. ``We just never knew,'' said her mother.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, doctors at Miami (Fla.) Children's Hospital learned
near the very beginning, was a small lesion on Shannon's brain. In
February 1994, surgeons cut through the fifth-grader's skull to get
to the tumor, about the size of a small eraser head. But because of
its location _ on the motor strip of the left side of her brain _
they couldn't get it all.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, the seizures continued. At the beginning, right
after the surgery, they weren't nearly as frequent. But by the
winter of 1997, when Shannon was an eighth-grader, they were
happening eight, nine, 10 times a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was getting to the point where she was actually hurting
herself,'' said Jane Pasley, remembering the time Shannon fell in
dance class and scraped her face. The doctors and the family
decided this could not go on. They'd go in again, only this time
they would do something a little fancier, something called a
Multiple Subpial Transection.
</P>
<P>
   This is how doctors explained it: Epileptic seizures travel
vertically in the brain, so the surgical team would go in and cut
the connectors that were carrying the seizures. When they were
done, the seizures wouldn't be able to travel from spot to spot.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one other thing, Mrs. Pasley. There's no telling the
outcome with this operation. Your daughter might never dance again.
</P>
<P>
   The six-hour surgery went well, but when 13-year-old Shannon
woke up, she couldn't move her right side. She couldn't wiggle her
fingers. She couldn't wiggle her toes. Her hand would not move. Her
leg would not move. Her father, Sam, a downright emotional wreck by
this point, had to carry her to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were freaking out,'' says Jane Pasley.
</P>
<P>
   But Jane Pasley had something else to say to Shannon and the
doctors and anyone else who would listen:
</P>
<P>
   She is not leaving this hospital in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   The physical therapy started the very next day. Shannon bounced
a ball against a trampoline and tried to hit it back. She struggled
to support herself on a flat treadmill and to balance herself on a
big, rubber ball.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, most of the feeling back in her right side,
Shannon Pasley walked out of Miami Children's.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks that followed, the real therapy began. The weights.
The leg lifts. The hours and hours of muscle-strengthening
exercises. And within a couple of months, just after spring break,
in fact, Shannon went back to school. And back to dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of guts,'' said her mother. ``We were so proud
of her because she just went in there almost like nothing had ever
happened. It took so much strength, because a lot of the kids
didn't understand what had been happening to her. And, then, she
started to get her confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been 15 months since the operation. That first year, she
stayed on seizure medicine, but then, this last March, they even
started weaning her off that. And now, glory be! No more medicine.
No more seizures! Not in the bathroom. Not in the bedroom. Not on
the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   She used to tire easily and her mother had to watch her like a
hawk. But just this past week Shannon and her mother were in
Washington, D.C., so Shannon could represent Florida in the
Children's Miracle Network, an international, nonprofit group that
raises money for children's hospitals, including Miami Children's.
While there, she met Hillary Rodham Clinton and saw an Orioles game
and raced around shopping and sightseeing with her mother. And she
could have stayed longer, honest, she had the strength, but she
needed to get home.
</P>
<P>
   So now, the stage awaits. Finally. Shannon prepares for her
first show since her big surgery in Miami a year ago February. And
she is strong enough and confident enough and good enough to do the
four tendus a la seconde to the right and then to the left and land
in her perfect fifth position. Miss Morgan will be so proud!
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I would have done if they'd told me I could
never dance again,'' says the ballerina, the one who used to be 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never give it up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
