<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9990 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EASY-BAKE-OVEN03-COX     06-02 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASY-BAKE-OVEN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Still hot after 35 years
 &HT;    (Has two sidebars: EASY-BAKE-SIDE0NE-03, EASY-BAKE-SIDE2-03)
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Watts cookin'? A cake the size of a
hockey puck. More than 100 million since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The Easy-Bake Oven _ that plastic Kenner gizmo fueled by a light
bulb _ is 35 years old. Not only did the toy teach tots about
baking, it also launched careers. Powder, water and whammo! A chef.
</P>
<P>
   ``It catapulted me into cooking,'' says chef John Carlino, 35,
an instructor at the Florida Culinary Institute in West Palm Beach,
Fla. ``That's where it all started _ with a light bulb. I had a
60-watt bulb, and I remember replacing it with a 100 watt so I
could increase production.''
</P>
<P>
   (A 100-watt bulb is standard on today's model.)
</P>
<P>
   Susan Dodge, 47, owner of Susan's Bistro in West Palm Beach,
also started with an Easy-Bake.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I remember most are the little tiny cake pans,'' she
says. ``And the teeny-weeny cookie cutters _ I had the rabbit and
the chicken. I couldn't wait to get home from school.''
</P>
<P>
   For those of you not in the Easy-Bake loop, here's how it works:
You mix a packet of cake powder with water, pour it into a pan 4
inches in diameter, push the pan through a slot so it sits under a
bulb for 12 minutes, then push the pan (with another pan or a
plastic stick, depending on the oven model) into a cooling chamber.
The wee treat cools for 10 minutes, then voila! Slather on icing.
</P>
<P>
   FYI: One Easy-Bake chocolate devil's food cake has 228 calories
and 0 vitamins. But there is a smidgen of calcium and iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really not a great story about some crazy inventor
with a light bulb who came up with the oven,'' says Easy-Bake
spokeswoman Sonia Fuller. ``They say a warm pretzel bought from a
street vendor inspired the idea, but the product was created by
Kenner in 1963 so kids could imitate adults. It remains a
top-selling toy.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Hasbro, which bought Kenner in 1991, created a
separate Easy-Bake division. Knockoffs have sprung up _ such as the
Mrs. Fields Baking Factory for $24.99 _ but the $19.99 Easy-Bake
remains No. 1. The original price 35 years ago was $15.99.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 11 models since 1963, each reflecting the colors
and oven styles of their day.
</P>
<P>
   The first was turquoise and had a carrying handle and fake stove
top. In 1969, the avocado green Premier Easy-Bake Oven came out
with more dials, a fake clock and an oven hood. A year later, the
harvest gold Super Easy-Bake Oven _ with no fake stove top _ hit
the market.
</P>
<P>
   The ovens were orange and brown throughout the '70s, including
the ``high-tech'' Easy-Bake Mini-Wave Oven introduced in 1978. Next
came several white models before this year's pink and purple
microwave-shaped Easy-Bake Oven &AMP; Snack Center with a mock digital
clock that always says 12:30. (Not unlike many real digital
clocks.)
</P>
<P>
   Cake mixes aren't just chocolate and vanilla anymore, either.
You can buy a Creme Pups Bake Set to make little cake sandwiches;
an All My Love Chocolates kit to make candy; and a Tiny Turnovers
Bake Set to make pastries. Plus, Easy-Bake has teamed up with
M&AMP;M's, Dunkin' Donuts and Oreo for mix ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our house once you ran out of mix that was it,'' says Betty
Baird, 43, owner of Sweet Tiers Bakery in Hobe Sound, Fla. ``So I
used to get my own red clay, mix it with water and salt, and make
little figures. I knew you weren't supposed to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, who needs rules? When the Easy-Bake first came out, guys
weren't supposed to play with what was billed as ``the hottest
girl's toy since dolls.'' But they did. (``There was always a girl
on the box,'' Carlino recalls, jokingly miffed. Nowadays, there's
just a picture of the oven).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about 8, and I kept it inside the house, of course,''
says David McBride, 26, a chef with Total Food Service Direction, a
Miami-based corporate dining company. ``I asked for one because I
saw it on TV. A couple of my friends got into it, too. My biggest
problem was that everything was undercooked.''
</P>
<P>
   (Guess he didn't ``illegally'' boost wattage like Chef Carlino.)
</P>
<P>
   Chef David Pantone, 37, director of the Florida Culinary
Institute, had an Easy-Bake knockoff that made monster-shaped
cakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a Rambo oven,'' he says, laughing. ``It was a guy oven.
I'd decorate my cakes with candy bugs and worms so people would
think I was cool.''
</P>
<P>
   A passing observation: Many boys who played with Easy-Bakes grew
up to be kitchen professionals, while a lot of women say their
Easy-Bake was the last time they cooked _ or close to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine was orange, and I thought the neatest thing about it was
the little pans,'' says Christy Drolet, 24, at Max's Bakery in Boca
Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A bakery?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no, I work the register. I didn't stick with the baking
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Precilla Burleson, 39, who works _ but doesn't bake
_ at The Upper Crust in Lake Worth, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite was chocolate,'' she says. ``But I used to cheat
and use my grandmother's mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Storandt, 26, a teacher who lives in Boynton Beach,
Fla., used to break rank from standard mix and make pineapple
upside down cake. (``It was a challenge because you had to place
things.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was in the Navy, and we got mine at a thrift store in
Japan,'' she says. ``I was about 7, and it was avocado green.''
</P>
<P>
   (If you're savvy, you can guesstimate someone's age by the color
of their oven. Next time you're at a party, slyly ask, ``So . . .
what color was your Easy-Bake?'')
</P>
<P>
   More than 16 million Easy-Bake Ovens have sold since 1963, plus
more than 100 million packets of mix. And Hasbro _ which launched a
Web site this year: http://www.easybake.com _ plans to keep
updating the toy that has become a pop-culture icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the next thing is a voice-activated model,'' Fuller
predicts with a laugh. ``Or maybe one that's solar-powered.''
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, how about one that comes with a cook?
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
