<SLUG> BC-EASY-BAKE-SIDEONE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The light came on in '63
 &HT;    (1st sidebar for EASY-BAKE-OVEN03-COX)
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1963: Kenner (now a division of Hasbro) develops the turquoise
Easy-Bake Oven and sells 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   1970: The new harvest gold Super Easy-Bake Oven bakes cakes up
to twice as big as the original model and includes a working
20-minute timer.
</P>
<P>
   1978: Easy-Bake goes high tech with an orange, white and brown
Mini-Wave Oven that resembles a microwave (no fake stove top here).
</P>
<P>
   1983: The orange Easy-Bake Dual-Temp Oven lets you bake treats
on ``high'' or ``low.''
</P>
<P>
   1987: Easy-Bake swaps long-standing orange for a more ``modern''
color like mom's oven: white.
</P>
<P>
   1993: The Easy-Bake Oven &AMP; Snack Center (with a warming tray to
melt toppings) is introduced in pink.
</P>
<P>
   1998: More than 16 million Easy-Bake Ovens have been sold, and
the product line is expanded with mix sets from M&AMP;M's, Dunkin'
Donuts and Oreo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
