<HEADER>
A9992 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH03-COX     06-02 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Netw(at)tch: Internet access, Microsoft top Harvard agenda
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cambridge, Mass. _ The Microsoft antitrust litigation cast a
long shadow over the Harvard International Conference on Internet
and Society held in Cambridge, Mass. May 25 - 29.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle's Larry Ellison and Sun Microsystems' Scott McNealy, who
have never been fans of the software giant, did not hide their glee
over Microsoft's current troubles.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the gathering of Internet professionals who came
from as near as Harvard's graduate school and as far away as
Australia had more on their minds than Microsoft. That's good news
for anybody who ever has or ever plans to log on to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There were discussions of copyright, community and the need to
push harder to wire more people in more countries as the millennium
approaches. Americans tend to think the Net is something uniquely
American -- a toy used to read magazines and browse movie Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Dyson -- known in technology circles as one of the
philosophers of the digital age -- and others made it clear the
Internet isn't just a cool hobby for rich Americans. Their message
was simple: Internet access is as vital as telephone access. Wiring
the poorest citizens in the United States and around the world will
empower them and enable them to tap into wisdom and news from half
a world away.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in Boston will be able to diagnose an exotic illness of
a patient in an African village. Eastern European companies will be
able to develop, helped by information and advice from Western
businessmen. Students in remote areas will be able to get an
education from some of the best and the brightest teachers in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   None of these scenarios is fantasy. They are possible now if the
world community could find some way to get computers and technical
know-how into the hands of people who can't afford them.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, no one at the four-day conference seemed to know
how to do this, who would pay for it or how long it would take to
close the gap between Internet haves and have-nots. Some academics
pointed to Microsoft's efforts to wire schools and libraries,
although others were just as quick to say Microsoft's interest in
wiring schools is more of an effort to build brand loyalty than to
bring technology to the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what?'' said one panelist. ``I don't care why they are
doing it. If they are going to give us the computers and the
training, I'm just gonna take the money and run.''
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks were met with applause from a packed auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   But every discussion, whether about regulation, content or
society, was colored by the specter of Microsoft. Every speaker
seemed to feel duty-bound to make a witty comment about Microsoft.
Most people tired of the Microsoft jokes and predictable lectures
on monopolies from its competitors. So when Steve Ballmer,
Microsoft executive vice president, began his talk via cybercast
from Redmond, Wash., people were waiting to hear something --
anything, really -- that would make Bill Gates seem more like
Florence Nightingale and less like Darth Vader.
</P>
<P>
   But Ballmer stuck to his script and gave a talk he's given many
times before. He described Microsoft products, hyped the Microsoft
Network and talked about the company's numerous content
partnerships. A speech like that at a conference like this gave the
appearance Microsoft was out of touch with the global community and
more focused on its stock price and market share than anything.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a go-round with the Justice Department might give
Microsoft some of the perspective and vision the people at the
Harvard conference had. But don't place any bets just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz covers the Internet and the World Wide Web. She has
been attending the Harvard Conference on Internet and Society. Her
coverage of specific Web sites will resume next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
