r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN03-COX     06-02 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Viagra even cures unemployment!
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ When future generations speak of 1998, and I
feel sure they will at great length, and when perspectives have had
a chance to shift and re-focus, I am certain that yet another truth
will have become self-evident to this great nation: Viagra cures
unemployment. Such a simple solution to such a pernicious problem.
Like it or not, the little blue pill has begun a revolution. In
Ohio and Michigan, welfare recipients have been told that if they
want to play, they're going to have to pay. The Ohio Department of
Human Services has declared that Medicaid will not foot the happy
pill bill because no lives are hanging in the balance due to a lack
of it (Viagra, that is).
</P>
<P>
   The potency pill debuted in late March to rave reviews and even
testimonials. Everybody's talking about it and that's
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   For millions of folks, it's a miracle. Only a possible cure for
cancer has been able to push Viagra out of the headlines. The pill
hits millions of folks where they live (or used to live) and what's
wrong with that? Not a thing the way I see it, but according to
what I read, some folks are seeing it quite differently.
</P>
<P>
   A lady in Garden City, N.Y., is suing her 70-year-old ex-live-in
for $2 million in palimony. Seems he got a little heavy-handed with
the Viagra and has begun to stray from their 10-year relationship.
Her lawyer says the drug should carry a warning label. Excuse me
while I snicker. How should such a warning read? CAUTION: Might be
habit forming and user may experience periodic symptoms of
well-being, happiness, and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   A man in Long Beach, Calif., hopes common sense will prevail.
``If sexual performance is fading,'' he writes, ``so be it! It may
be wiser to exchange machismo for maturity. That is the true
measure of manliness.'' No comment.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in San Francisco writes: ``...9 out of 10 of us who are
over 60 would tell you that we do not want bad-tempered, horny old
men on our hands.'' Tsk, tsk. Nice talk for a lady! (And where did
you get your statistics, dearie?)
</P>
<P>
   Viagra provides a temporary cure for impotence just like aspirin
provides temporary pain relief. And where do we get off waxing all
righteous about a little blue pill?
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, folks, we're a pill-popping society.We have
pills to relieve stress and overcome anxiety. We have hormone
replacement therapy. We have pills to put us to sleep and pills to
wake us up. We even have pills to make us look like we've been
lying on the beach in Bermuda. So why not a potency pill? Who
knows? It could turn out to be the cure for ``road rage.''
</P>
<P>
   An old friend (15 years my senior which makes her slightly older
than Moses) called a while back for a giggle and a chat. ``I've got
a new boyfriend,'' she confided, ``and he's the most romantic man
I've ever known. I feel sixteen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with that, I'm thinking. Seniors' sex lives are
their own business and now that there's Viagra, business should be
better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, on a visit to my parents' home, I overheard a
conversation between my then 72-year-old father and my 67-year-old
mother. He was offering her a deal. He'd repair the washing machine
in exchange for certain favors. She, of course, was playing hard to
get and telling him he should be ashamed of himself, a man of his
age. I remember her saying, ``...and even with our daughter in the
house.'' My father's sage comment was, ``We must assume she's
worldly enough to have figured out where we got her.'' Mother
choked. Daddy chuckled. And I can only assume the washer was
repaired and the bill subsequently paid.
</P>
<P>
   My father, a gentleman of the old school who called all ladies
``Ma'am'' and never came to the table without his coat, would have
been mortified if he'd known I was listening, but I'm also sure
that if he were alive today he'd have a prescription (if he even
needed it) for Pfizer's little blue pill. Of course, we would be
too polite to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra, even if it turns out to be useless as a cure for road
rage, is a miracle for millions. It solves two problems at once -
impotency and, in Ohio and Michigan, unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
