<SLUG> BC-JUSTFORFUN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just for Fun: Whatever your gizmo, there's a case
 &HT;    By Yusuf Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No matter what portable electronic device you use,
from the smallest personal digital assistant to the bulkiest
laptops, Targus has a carrying case to fit and protect it.
</P>
<P>
   Constructed for strength, durability and user comfort, the
Targus line of computer luggage combines a protective carrying case
and convenient briefcase into a single system.
</P>
<P>
   Most allow electronic devices to be operated easily, without
removal from their carrying cases, and most cases are equipped with
pouches, dividers and pockets, making them a virtual portable
office. Some are even designed to hold a variety of portables and
their accessories.
</P>
<P>
   The top-of-the-line notebook cases are designed with the Air
Protection System, a layer of sealed pressurized air to protect
sensitive portables from bumps and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Fabricated from nylon or leather, Targus carrying cases are
widely available from $30 to $300. For more information, visit the
Web site at http://www.targus.com.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid camera named for the Spice Girls
</P>
<P>
   Whether you love them or hate them, there's no denying the Spice
Girls have gained worldwide notoriety. Capitalizing on that
popularity and targeting Generation X and Y-ers, Polaroid has just
released SpiceCam, which it says is the first instant camera in
history to be named after a pop group.
</P>
<P>
   However, like the fun-loving quintet, SpiceCam has more style
than substance. Modeled after Polaroid's newly restyled OneStep,
SpiceCam is highlighted in the Spice Girls' ``Girl Power'' colors
of pop purple, hot pink, neon orange and touch-of-class silver.
It's packaged with Spice Girls portrait stickers to allow users to
customize and personalize it.
</P>
<P>
   The multihued SpiceCam accepts Polaroid 600 instant film,
including Platinum and the new AlterImage, a matte-surface film
that invites after-exposure artistic expression with pens, paint
and markers.
</P>
<P>
   The suggested retail price is $39.99.
</P>
<P>
   System 270 caters
</P>
<P>
   to home theater crowd
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Technology says its speaker systems are designed for
home theater only. As a result, its speaker systems are built from
the ground up to meet the demands of multichannel movie sound
tracks, such as Dolby Digital, Dolby Pro-Logic and DTS.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently introduced System 270, a midpriced,
six-piece home theater speaker system, designed to deliver the
sonic excitement of the latest Hollywood blockbusters to serious
home movie viewers.
</P>
<P>
   System 270 consists of an adjustable center-channel speaker with
boundary compensation, two left and right front speakers, two
dipolar surround speakers and a 225-watt, powered subwoofer, which
promise optimum music performance without sacrificing home theater
sound effects.
</P>
<P>
   The system has a $2,396 suggested retail price. To learn more,
visit the Web site at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .atlantictechnology.com.
</P>
<P>
   Digital assistant fits in your palm
</P>
<P>
   PalmPilot by U.S. Robotics is a pocket-size personal digital
assistant that will help users keep track of contacts, appointments
and personal notes.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra-compact, the PalmPilot stores and retrieves tons of
information at the touch of a button. It will also exchange
information with a PC and display it on a backlit screen for easy
viewing, even in low light conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Applications include a date book, address book, to-do list, memo
pad, expense report, calculator and games.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmPilot has a suggested retail price of about $290. The
PalmPilot Pro, with more features and expanded memory, has a
suggested price of $380.
</P>
<P>
   Yusuf Davis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
