<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ ATLANTA _ The Hollywood publicity machine is running
full speed for Jim Carrey. The rubber-faced comedian, who was on
the cover of Time last week, graces the covers of New York ($2.95)
and Entertainment Weekly ($2.50) this week. (And other news.
Rundown of this week's magazine features.) (Patureau, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/1.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDSHOPPING _ ATLANTA _ Not surprisingly, there's a group of
re-released Frank Sinatra albums now in stores, with a second wave
set for Sept. 8 by Reprise and Capitol Records. Other areas of pop
music are fully covered this week with new releases from country,
rock, alternative and rap stars expected to roll in high on the
Billboard charts. (Reviews of recently released CDs.) (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/1.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKREVIEW-IRVING _ Too much is never enough for John Irving,
which is both his most admirable quality and his most reliable
failing. ``A Widow for One Year'' begins with a prologue that sets
up the rest of the book, a prologue that limps along for 180 pages
and should have been cut in half. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ Carl Sandburg won two Pulitzer prizes, one for
his poetry and one for writing the most popular Lincoln biography
of the first half of this century. He also wrote a best-selling
novel (``Remembrance Rock''), but all this was a long time ago and
I get the distinct sense he's not widely read anymore. Undaunted,
Knopf has issued ``Not Everyday an Aurora Borealis for Your
Birthday'' ($13), a previously unpublished, but charming, poem with
lovely illustrations by Anita Lobel. (And more news on recently
released books.) (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (d category)
</P>
<P>
   EASY-BAKE-OVEN _ The Easy-Bake Oven _ that plastic Kenner gizmo
fueled by a light bulb _ is 35 years old. Not only did the toy
teach tots about baking, it also launched careers. For those of you
not in the Easy-Bake loop, here's how it works: You mix a packet of
cake powder with water, pour it into a pan 4 inches in diameter,
push the pan through a slot so it sits under a bulb for 12 minutes,
then push the pan (with another pan or a plastic stick, depending
on the oven model) into a cooling chamber. The wee treat cools for
10 minutes, then voila! Slather on icing. (Grantham, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EASY-BAKE-SIDE1 _ Easy-Bake timeline. (Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EASY-BAKE-SIDE2 _ Easy-Bake invites kids 8 to 11 to submit their
favorite recipe using one or more Easy-Bake brand mixes. Five
finalists will be chosen and sent to New York for the finals in
October. Professional chefs will help the finalists make their
creations, which will be judged by a panel of culinary and toy
experts. Here's how to enter: (address follows). (Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-LANIER _ GAINESVILLE, Ga. _ Lake Lanier Islands after
$12 million upgrade by new owner, KSL Corp., including 30
rustic-posh rental lake houses, an excursion boat for evening
cruises and a new family water attraction, the FunDunker.
(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 5 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-CALENDAR _ Regional calendar of events. ETA 5 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ In the end, the gathering of Internet
professionals who came from as near as Harvard's graduate school
and as far away as Australia had more on their minds than
Microsoft. That's good news for anybody who ever has or ever plans
to log on to the Internet. There were discussions of copyright,
community and the need to push harder to wire more people in more
countries as the millennium approaches. Americans tend to think the
Net is something uniquely American -- a toy used to read magazines
and browse movie Web sites. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   JUST-FOR-FUN _ ATLANTA _ No matter what portable electronic
device you use, from the smallest personal digital assistant to the
bulkiest laptops, Targus has a carrying case to fit and protect it.
Whether you love them or hate them, there's no denying the Spice
Girls have gained worldwide notoriety. Capitalizing on that
popularity and targeting Generation X and Y-ers, Polaroid has just
released SpiceCam, which it says is the first instant camera in
history to be named after a pop group. (And more news on
technology.) (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT _ ATLANTA _ It's not so much trouble to reach for the
stack of compact discs, pick the one you suddenly have a hankering
for, pop it into the CD player and hit play. But wouldn't it be
nice to just tap the CD player and have that tune start playing?
You can, if you have every single CD you own sitting in the CD
player. And you can have that if you have the cash to buy one of
the new Kenwood 200-disc CD mega-changers. (And other news on new
technology.) (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   BOTOX _ ATLANTA _ Lisa Randolph was tired of hearing people tell
her to stop frowning. The 36-year-old Alpharetta resident had deep
lines above her brow, and was considering having laser resurfacing
to erase them. But instead, she decided to correct the problem one
afternoon with a quick-and-easy injection of one of the world's
most deadly toxins. Call it botulism for beauty. Originally
harnessed for serious medical conditions such as swallowing
disorders and crossed eyes, Botox _ a diluted purified form of the
toxin _ is now one of the hottest new weapons against wrinkles.
(Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 5 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
