r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENTARY-BJT03-COX     06-02 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, June 3, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ It is not clear that any survey of the
population would reveal a deep yearning for another professional
football league, but it looks as though we may be getting one
anyway. (Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED 6/1.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Political carnivorousness remains unabated,
partisan appetites never satiated. Hypocrisy _ a technical-sounding
term for the droppings of a male cow _ is the main ingredient of
much of it. Two great recent examples are the incongruous rantings
of House Speaker Newt Gingrich as he spews his double-speak bile
about the Middle East _ a breach of U.S. political ethics _ and
last weekend's so-called response to President Clinton's Saturday
radio address. Howard Kleinberg is a former editor of the Miami
News. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED 6/1.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The potency pill debuted in
late March to rave reviews and even testimonials. Everybody's
talking about it and that's understandable. For millions of folks,
it's a miracle. Only a possible cure for cancer has been able to
push Viagra out of the headlines. The pill hits millions of folks
where they live (or used to live) and what's wrong with that? Not a
thing the way I see it, but according to what I read, some folks
are seeing it quite differently.(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REAL-LIFE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There she was, all legs and
smiles, in the fourth grade and barely reading chapter books, when
she started getting The Feeling. Shannon went to her mother, Jane,
and complained about it. It felt as though she was having a spasm
in her arm, a tightness that wouldn't go away. Something wasn't
right, she told her mom. But now, it's been 15 months since the
operation. And glory be! No more medicine. No more seizures! Not in
the bathroom. Not in the bedroom. Not on the dance floor. (Minor,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
