<SLUG> BC-SKI-LAKE-TAHOE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL NINO GIVES LAKE TAHOE CHRISTMAS IN JUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRUCKEE, Calif. _ In the battle of the seasons being waged at
Lake Tahoe, skis and snowmobiles definitely have the edge on canoes
and fishing poles.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino has crashed the summer party that should have kicked off
on Memorial Day weekend, when the lake normally heats up and the
hiking and mountain-biking trails and campsites begin to defrost.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in storm after storm, the mountains that frame the
picturesque lake have been dusted with fresh snowfall that has
prolonged stellar late-season skiing.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino is the name given to the unusual warming of waters in
the Pacific Ocean that affects global wind and temperature
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   On Memorial Day weekend, more than 10,000 skiers and
snowboarders hit the slopes while traditional summer activities
like water skiing, camping and sunbathing were avoided because of
chilly temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just ready for a change of scenery,'' said 43-year-old
Lisa Fielding, an avid skier who traded in her skis for in-line
skates Friday, even though the latest storm to roll through the
region made the paths dangerously slick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great winter, but it's summertime now. I'm really
anxious to get it started already.''
</P>
<P>
   Tahoe isn't used to prolonged winter seasons. Little League
games have been postponed because the fields are too soggy. Popular
hiking and mountain-biking trails are closed because they are still
covered with snow. A local newspaper dubbed last month ``Mayuary.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiing would normally be winding down right about now as the
snowpack melts away, but a few savvy resorts have stayed open and
are still enjoying good crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum from having a strong winter has definitely pushed
into the spring and now summer,'' said Jody Churich, sales manager
at Alpine Meadows Ski Resort. ``We're still seeing great turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   The resort has logged its fourth snowiest season in 28 years,
thanks to the record February snowfall of 186 inches. Alpine had
planned to close its doors May 5. But with a snowpack of between
seven and 17 feet, it extended daily skiing through June 7, and
plans to offer weekend skiing through the Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the endless winter,'' said Jeannette Lewis, a member
of the resort's ski patrol. ``It just won't quit snowing. We're
hardly ever open through June.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1218EDT &QL; 
