<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENLEY-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERICAL ERROR PUTS TEXAS MASS MURDERER IN PRISON TRUSTY JOB 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN MAKEIG 
and MATT SCHWARTZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A clerk's error left longtime inmate Elmer Wayne
Henley, serving a life sentence in the killings of 27 youths in the
Houston area, as a trusty in charge of youths at a prison boot
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Prison system spokesman David Nunnelee said that Henley, 42, was
a trusty at the Coffield Unit boot camp near Palestine from April
15 until May 1.
</P>
<P>
   He was assigned there based only on his prison identification
number by someone unfamiliar with his history, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Henley's career as trusty ended hurriedly once Coffield Unit
Warden Kevin Moore learned the convicted multiple murderer had the
assignment. Henley now is back inside the maximum-security prison
unit, adjacent to the boot camp, working as a ``unit artist,''
meaning he paints signs.
</P>
<P>
   Moore declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Polunsky, chairman of the Texas Board of Criminal Justice,
called it an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime a mistake is made by our personnel, I become
concerned,'' Polunsky said. ``I wouldn't describe it as systematic
of the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding that, there has been, from what I can see, a
slight breach in the policies and procedures in the division. And
that calls for a review,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky said he asked Texas Department of Criminal Justice
officials to investigate the incident and make necessary changes to
procedures to prevent a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   Though Henley qualified for trusty status, he said, TDCJ
policies prohibit inmates convicted of dangerous crimes from being
placed in positions with less security from which they could
escape.
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky said Henley was transferred to a facility adjacent to
the Coffield Unit that housed adult inmates, adding there were no
youthful offenders there.
</P>
<P>
   Nunnelee said prison files suggest that Henley has been an ideal
inmate during his 24 years and nine months in custody, with only
two infractions on his record. In 1986, he got in trouble for
fighting with another inmate and in 1973 he was written up for
failing to obey a posted order.
</P>
<P>
   Henley is serving six concurrent life sentences for his role in
the torture-slayings of 27 youths in the Houston area in 1973 when
he was a teen-ager. His co-defendant, David Owen Brooks, also is
serving a life sentence in four of the murders.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Corll, 33, was the primary culprit in the killings. Henley
shot Corll six times _ in self-defense, he told authorities _
before calling police and confessing.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, despite his record as a good inmate, Henley has been
passed over for parole numerous times. Nunnelee said Henley has
accumulated 73 years of good-time credit toward parole, but it
remains doubtful he will ever be freed. Henley's next review for
parole will be in October 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henley's name is pretty much synonymous with mass murder,''
said Andy Kahan, the mayor's advocate for crime victims. ``Even if
it was a clerical error, the minute you yell out `Elmer Wayne
Henley,' that should raise some eyebrows. Anything that involves
Elmer Wayne Henley draws notice and attention, even the name. Even
when the transfer comes across your desk, you take notice of the
name.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wondered why it took two weeks for officials to
realize the error but _ like Polunsky _ Kahan stopped well short of
criticizing TDCJ procedures. ``I don't know if you can say there is
a problem,'' Kahan said. ``You're dealing with 140,000 inmates on a
daily basis. Clerical errors do happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, an inmate named Steven Jay Russell won a
special needs parole to a South Texas nursing home after duping
prison doctors and parole officials into believing he was
terminally ill with AIDS. Once there, Russell had someone call the
facility posing as a doctor authorizing special treatment at a
Houston hospital, from which the inmate escaped. He was later
captured in Dallas, but slipped free after feigning a heart attack
and being taken to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Polunsky drew a distinction between Russell and Henley's cases,
noting that Henley ``was never outside the fence at all. He was
under supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Russell escaped from TDCJ's Estelle Unit near
Huntsville, posing as a doctor after he used a green marker to
color his white prison uniform.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
