<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRE-APPROVAL MAY NOT MEAN APPROVAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've gotten an offer in the mail saying you've been
pre-approved for credit, don't assume you're a shoo-in for a loan.
</P>
<P>
   You can still be turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Under changes in the federal Fair Credit Reporting Act, banks
may reject your pre-approved credit card application if they find
that changes in your financial condition make you a bad credit
risk. For example, they can take back that offer if you've lost
your job or have taken on too much debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes to the Fair Credit Reporting Act, (which sets
rules for credit reports), give creditors more leeway after making
a prescreened offer to get information about the applicant,'' said
Sandra Wilmore, an attorney in the credit practices division of the
Federal Trade Commission, which enforces the credit reporting act.
``If they found out you were unemployed or any circumstance that
was different than what their prescreened information suggested,
then they could turn you down.''
</P>
<P>
   So what about that letter saying you are ``pre-approved?''
</P>
<P>
   The commission has ruled that if a creditor tells you you've
been pre-approved for credit, they should ``have the intention'' of
extending you credit, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's not true, that would violate the FTC Act, which
prohibits unfair and deceptive practices,'' Wilmore said.
```Pre-approved' means they've already made a decision to give you
credit. Our view is that if they say that, they should mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid getting themselves in legal hot water, many creditors
have revised their offers to say you've been ``preselected'' to
apply for credit. In other words, you've been invited to apply.
</P>
<P>
   If creditors deny you credit, don't hold a grudge. They may be
doing you a favor. If your financial circumstances have taken a
turn for the worse, it's not a good time to add to your debt load.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if you have too much credit _ even if you're not
tapping it _ it could affect your chances of getting a loan in the
future because creditors may view excess borrowing as too much of a
temptation for you.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect an end to such tempting come-ons. Banks dangle
credit lines of as much as $100,000, offer an initial ``teaser''
rate of as low as 5.9 percent or promise a gold or platinum card.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders are fighting for your business. Last year, they sent out
a record 3 billion credit solicitations, said Bob Litwin, director
of creditor/community relations at Consumer Credit Counseling
Service in Houston, a community organization that helps consumers
with credit problems.
</P>
<P>
   Don't choose your credit card by opening your mail each day.
It's just too easy to get yourself in financial trouble by adding
more and more credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly true if you've gotten way behind on your
bills. The law says if you charge more than $1,000 on a single
credit card 60 days before filing for bankruptcy, it's highly
unlikely that a bankruptcy court will allow you to walk on that
debt &UR; , &LR;  said J. Thomas Black, a consumer bankruptcy attorney in
Houston and vice president of the Houston Association of Debtor
Attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presumption is you knew you were going to file for
bankruptcy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy reform proposals before Congress are seeking to make
the law even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   So before accepting a pre-approved credit offer, consider why
they are so eager to lend money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at primarily what interest rate are the credit card
companies offering,'' Litwin said. ``Is it a better interest rate
than what they already have on their current card?''
</P>
<P>
   If it is a super-low rate such as 5.9 percent, many times, it's
just for six months. After that period, it soars to a double-digit
rate.
</P>
<P>
   It's not worth it to apply for the credit if the rate eventually
will be higher than the rate you're paying now. Also, pre-approved
credit cards may well come with fees.
</P>
<P>
   If you do decide to apply for credit based on the initial lower
rate, have a plan to pay off the balance before the lower rate
expires. The only way to get out of debt is to bear down and really
be determined to whittle down the bills and pay them off.
</P>
<P>
   Black offers a simpler plan: Consumers should just toss all
pre-approved credit offers in the trash can.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're lending money to increasingly shaky people, far more
than they could ever afford to repay,'' said Black, adding that he
``routinely'' gets pre-approved credit card offers at his office,
addressed to his clients. ``It's too expensive. It gives them a
feeling that they're richer than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
