<SLUG> BC-COPYCATS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALERS SELLING FAKE GOODS FACE REAL TIME IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Most vendors selling cheap imitations or knockoffs of
Nike T-shirts, Rolex watches and Dooney &AMP; Bourke handbags used to
glide through Texas courts with a small fine and slap on the wrist.
</P>
<P>
   But with a change in Texas law and aggressive undercover police
efforts in Harris County, authorities say brokers of illegitimate
merchandise are now facing the real thing _ a felony charge and the
possibility of being fitted with an authentic wardrobe of jail
attire.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six weeks, Houston police have made 21 arrests using
the state's new trademark counterfeiting statute. Five of those
arrested have been indicted by Harris County grand jurors, who are
expected to hear a dozen more of the cases in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, less than 10 cases were filed elsewhere in the
state. But since Sept. 1, Houston has taken the lead in being the
most assertive and aggressive city in the state,'' said Mike
McKenna, a security consultant and private investigator who
specializes in intellectual property rights and trademark theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is going to end up being a model city for the rest of
the country on this type of enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Guidry Group, the firm McKenna works for, has offices in
Houston and Dallas and represents companies such as Disney, Warner
Brothers, Oakley, Rolex, Louis Vuitton, Dooney &AMP; Bourke and Nike.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are active in catching trademark thieves in
Houston because counterfeits of their products _ T-shirts,
handbags, sunglasses, jewelry, luggage and other items _ are so
popular here, McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   His firm helps police and prosecutors in identifying bogus
merchandise and provides the expensive expert testimony and
trademark documents needed to make the cases in court.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna said trademark theft is especially acute in Houston, New
York and Los Angeles _ big cities with ports, international
connections and a base of customers who want to pay cheap prices
for the status they think comes with a brand like Nike or Rolex.
</P>
<P>
   The companies and police were frustrated for years because Texas
law only allowed them to charge offenders with a misdemeanor, no
matter how much of the counterfeit merchandise the vendors moved.
That meant mostly small fines and probation if the cases even made
it to court.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Jennings, a prosecutor in the district attorney's major
fraud division, said that many times, the misdemeanor cases weren't
feasible because taxpayers weren't getting ``a lot of bang for
their buck.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said the companies were wary of providing the experts
and documents needed to make the cases with little or nothing on
the line for the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   So the International Anti-Counterfeiting Coalition, based in
Washington, D.C., went to Texas lawmakers and pointed out that more
than $200 billion a year is lost to U.S. companies because of
trademark theft, McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas lawmakers, following their counterparts in New York and
California, responded by revamping the law during the last
legislative session. As of Sept. 1, vendors and their employees
selling the fakes can now face felony charges and more substantial
jail time.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the old law, the seriousness of the charge can be
enhanced depending on how much merchandise the vendors and their
employees are caught trying to sell. That opens the door to more
severe punishments.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said there's also a caveat for those who buy the fakes.
The law may be tailored to hit the merchants, but it's conceivable
customers could also face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the new law) makes it more worthwhile to pursue these
cases because the old statute just wasn't effective,'' Jennings
said. ``Now, there's commitment all around. The law is more
equitable and efficient. The ball is rolling. (The companies being
victimized) are taking it seriously and we're taking it
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where Houston police Sgt. Doug Osterberg and a team of
undercover officers come into the picture. They recently targeted a
number of shops in southwest Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The merchants in some of the small shops in the area had no
problem telling undercover officers that their products, like $16
fake Rolex watches, were fake. The officers bought some merchandise
and returned with search warrants.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of dollars' worth of the products were seized at the
shops and at other locations, Osterberg said. After that, many
vendors moved their lucrative businesses to flea markets. But the
authorities were right behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran 10 search warrants (May 16) in several places, like
small flea markets, and seized over $20,000 in merchandise,''
Osterberg said. ``And all these cases are being made in a short
time. We're not even working on them every day.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the merchants in southwest Houston who ended up facing
charges reacted to a sting in his shop by trying to pay Osterberg
and another officer, Jennings said. Now, he's also facing bribery
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Osterberg said the vendors might be a little less brazen in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enforcement used to be next to nothing and they were pretty
open about it all,'' Osterberg said. ``I don't think they'll be
quite as open anymore.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
