<HEADLINE>
MINISTER HOPES TO KEEP DREAM ALIVE AT TEXAS SCHOOL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT photo service) 
 
(Attn: Miss., Ind., and Chicago area) 
 
By PATTI MUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENDLETON, Texas _ When the Rev. J. Horace Germany launched a
college for black preachers in Union, Miss., in 1960, he was nearly
killed for his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   After a brutal beating by thugs who wanted him and his black
students to leave, Germany, who is white, hid out in a hospital
attic with the help of sympathetic nuns and made his way to this
East Texas community in Fort Bend County revive his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Here he started Bay Ridge Christian College. Students _ mainly
young, black men _ came from around the nation and other countries.
Many went on to become pastors, Germany said.
</P>
<P>
   After almost 40 years, however, Germany _ now 84 and retired in
Covington, Ind. _ feared in recent times that his dream of
brotherhood and equality among races was dying along with Bay Ridge
Christian College, which was losing money and land nearly as
quickly as it was losing students.
</P>
<P>
   But like the recently planted roses and fresh landscaping around
campus, Bay Ridge is showing new signs of life and is poised to
become a resource and a leader in the surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrived here three years ago, Bay Ridge was on the
respirator and hemorrhaging,'' said Dr. James L. Phillips, senior
associate dean and professor of pediatrics at Baylor College of
Medicine in Houston. ``There were questions about whether we could
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was elected board chairman this year at the college,
which is one of eight higher education institutions nationwide with
ministry programs for the Church of God.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the late 1800s, the Church of God is a Bible-based
religious movement headquartered in Anderson, Ind. Its membership
is reported at more than 220,000.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said the first and most important step in getting Bay
Ridge back on its feet was putting the right leader in place _ a
step he said the board accomplished when it hired longtime educator
Verda Beach of Chicago about a year ago to become the school's new
president.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly an administrator with the City Colleges of Chicago
system, Beach grew up in the Church of God, where Germany was a
legend of sorts. Phillips also grew up in that church and remembers
as a youth hearing Germany speak.
</P>
<P>
   Beach and Phillips vowed that Bay Ridge will meet its
longstanding commitment to fulfill its founder's dream, and to
provide some sort of retirement benefits for him.
</P>
<P>
   Since he stepped down several years ago, his family says, he has
lived on a tiny income from Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to enhance the great work he started,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   From his home in Indiana, Germany said he has special hopes for
the campus where he and his deceased wife, Janetta, reared four
children and where scores of young, poor black men were trained to
become leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did they receive a basic education, but they also were
taught a living through training in agriculture, mechanics,
construction, welding, carpentry _ a host of practical occupations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a wonderful thing going,'' Germany said. ``We've got
pastors pastoring churches all over the country from that little
school. I put 44 years into it (including four years trying to get
started in Mississippi).
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows I want that school to go on so bad. It would make me
sick enough to die if it closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the school has fought its way back after
hurricanes, tornadoes and economic busts. When Germany wasn't
laboring on campus, he was flying around the country seeking
donations.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't like to mix doubt with anything related to the
college, but his family's concern about his lack of retirement
benefits after years of near-volunteer work prompted him last
November to write to the then-chairman of the college board.
</P>
<P>
   His letter lamented the decisions by that board, some of whose
members are no longer in office, to sell real estate to pay for
operating expenses, to use property to secure loans and to raise
administrators' salaries. He also criticized the lack of
fund-raising and what he considered mismanagement of monies left to
the college.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, who has since remarried, asked that his family's campus
home, which he deeded to Bay Ridge in 1977, be returned to him. A
1981 resolution by the board guaranteed him and his deceased wife
lifetime use of the property and also set up a life annuity note of
$60,000 in appreciation for his years of sacrifice and service to
Bay Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   The 7 percent interest was payable on a monthly basis beginning
at Germany's retirement, according to the note, but Germany said it
never was paid regularly. His Social Security payments are minimal
because he never made more than $3,500 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's letter said he feared the school was ``no longer being
used as an instrument of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Holifield, a stepgrandson of Germany's and general counsel
to the family, said negotiations are continuing about setting up
some more substantial retirement benefits for Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just not getting any income,'' said Holifield, a law
clerk for a federal judge in Tyler, Texas. ``I think the last thing
he would ever want is for this to detract from the wonderful
accomplishments of Bay Ridge.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
