<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0098 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-COLLEGE-ART     06-02 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-COLLEGE-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
KENDLETON, Texas: Bay Ridge.``
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indeed, the rich history of Bay Ridge and its founder is making
its way into a nearly completed autobiography with Nashville
publisher Larry Arnett and Light of Day Publishing. ``Brotherhood
at Any Cost'' traces the roots of Bay Ridge in Mississippi, where
Germany faced death at the hands of Ku Klux Klansmen who had warned
him to get the black students out of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   New interest in the 1960 attack on Germany has been sparked by
the opening of the long-sealed Mississippi Sovereignty Commission
files in March. The commission is said to have been a state-run spy
agency designed to protect segregation, and its files may hold
clues to criminal acts during the turbulent 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett said there is interest from a Hollywood filmmaker in
making a movie about Germany's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horace Germany is a true believer,'' Arnett said. ``He's
real.''
</P>
<P>
   His on-campus home at Bay Ridge outside Kendleton, where he
raised bird dogs out back and held meetings in his spacious front
room, has remained unused since he left several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips acknowledged many of the concerns Germany's letter
cited.
</P>
<P>
   For example, more than $300,000 willed to Bay Ridge by Germany's
friends and supporters _ including several nuns he had developed
friendships with over the years _ was exhausted and the college has
nothing to show for it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Previous administrations basically didn't know how to
manage,'' Phillips said. ``Perhaps there were too many clergy on
the board. You have to have a wealth of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The board has been reduced from more than 30 members to 16,
Phillips said, and Beach has cut operating expenses significantly.
</P>
<P>
   She has spent her first year assessing the campus, improving the
facilities and working toward a fall enrollment of 25 _ a major
increase, considering that only one or two students were on campus
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Beach said Bay Ridge should no longer be considered a school
just for black students. It is multicultural, she said, and has a
much broader role than just educating preachers.
</P>
<P>
   Society needs good Christians in all phases of life, she said,
and Bay Ridge will be a model for starting students down that path.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Ridge also is starting to take an active role in the
community, including becoming the library for Kendleton's nearly
600 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Beach is loaded with ideas on how to turn the campus into an
areawide resource. One idea is to turn Germany's former home into a
bed-and-breakfast inn for visitors to the college and to Kendleton,
where she serves on the economic development committee.
</P>
<P>
   She and Phillips are intent on finishing the campus gymnasium,
which has been under construction about 15 years. Just a decade
ago, Bay Ridge had a decent basketball team _ the Eagles _ and a
trophy case filled with honors still sits in the library. Beach
said Bay Ridge has a potential donor ready to finish the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Beach has overseen a host of physical improvements at Bay Ridge,
not the least of which was a repair job to the library roof and an
effort to dedicate hallways around campus to history, past
presidents and other topics. The hallways are packed with
portraits, stories and documents to trace the college's history.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said Beach has accomplished more in one year than had
been accomplished in the previous 10. Both are excited about
another deal in the works to house up to 60 Houston-area youth in
campus dormitories. Designed for low-performing students or those
who have not adjusted to their schools, the program would involve
Bay Ridge students training in counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still master-planning the college,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   But he and Beach pledge that Germany has nothing to fear about
the future of Bay Ridge Christian College. It will survive, they
say, and without compromise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
