<SLUG> BC-MUSHROOM-HUNTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNGI LOVERS PICK THEIR MUSHROOM FEASTS, CAREFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ Armed with a sharp knife and a wooden
basket, Marjorie Lutz stalks her quarry in the undergrowth on
Monument Hill in this city's Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Birds twitter in the treetops overhead. The ground is a tangle
of roots and dappled shadows. Except for the broken glass and
crumpled potato chip bags underfoot, civilization could be miles
rather than blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   With sharp eyes trained downward, the 65-year-old resident of
nearby Voorheesville looks for the convoluted, brain-like head of
her prey: Morels, a mushroom that grows from mid-April to early May
around the base of elm, apple and ash trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have a fear of mushrooms because we haven't studied
them and we don't have a tradition of looking for them,'' said
Lutz, who has been gathering and eating wild fungi for more than
two decades. ``But they really can be wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding edible mushrooms does not necessarily require a daylong
trek into the depths of the woods. Delectable specimens of fungi
can be found in a patch of suburban lawn, under a bush in an urban
park or even in a planter on the street. Morels, in particular,
Lutz said, grow well in ``trashy or burned-over places,'' more
frequently found amid development not in the wilderness. Foraging
for a few hours in public spaces, particularly parks, can turn up a
wide variety of mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fungi inhabit the whole Earth, not just the pristine forest,''
said John Haines, senior scientist and mycology expert with the
state Biological Survey and New York State Museum. ``Mushrooms grow
on city trees and in lawns and flower beds. There are certain
mushrooms that thrive in those conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that wild mushrooms can be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy can be avoided by being sure not to eat anything you
gather unless you're completely certain about what it is, Haines
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are a variety of toxins in poisonous mushrooms. Only one
has an antidote, Haines said, although others respond to early
treatment. There are more edible mushrooms than poisonous ones,
however.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years of avid mushrooming, Lutz is an experienced
amateur mycologist. She first became interested when she was out
walking in Vermont with a European friend who picked a Puffball
mushroom and said she would take it home for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Lutz recalled. ``I asked her if she
was really going to eat that and she said, `Oh, yes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she would die, but when I called her a few days
later, she was fine. Then I thought: `If she can do it, so can
I!'''
</P>
<P>
   Lutz started out very slowly, collecting every mushroom she
could find, taking it home to study, draw and identify. She thinks
Americans are afraid to eat wild mushrooms, in part, because of
``those stories'' about someone eating just a piece of one and
dropping dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always the same stories told over and over and blown out
of proportion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lutz realizes even an experienced mushroomer must
be careful. She takes great pains to identify whatever she finds,
using a miniature magnifying glass to search for characteristics
that set one mushroom apart from another. She looks for a
fringe-like ``veil'' hanging off the edge of the cap, for example,
which not all fungi have, or ``gills'' on their undersides that are
either attached to the stem or not.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent sunny weekday at Schenectady's Central Park, Lutz
spots her first mushroom growing in the grass several feet off a
paved path. Carefully, she pries the lone, buff-colored fungus from
the earth with her knife.
</P>
<P>
   And then, the all-important, yet difficult, task that must
precede eating the booty _ identification.
</P>
<P>
   Lutz notes the mushroom's traits on a small note card:
``Glaberous (which means the cap is almost sticky to the touch).
Thick, brownish, attached gills. Striated stem about one inch long.
A slight veil.'' After consulting the ``Audubon Society Field Guide
to North American Mushrooms'' (Alfred Knopf), which lists
characteristics of several thousand mushrooms and includes color
photographs of many of those, Lutz reaches a verdict: She's not
entirely sure what her find is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a Lawn Mowers Mushroom (Psathyrella
foenisecii). But there are so many similar to this type, that I'm
not sure. So, we won't eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lutz wraps the mushroom in wax paper and places it
in her basket to take home for closer inspection. She then cleans
the knife by inserting it into the soil several times, and wipes
her hands on her jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Resuming her search several hundred yards into the woods atop
Monument Hill, Lutz discovers a trove of what she identifies as the
Coprinus atramentarius, more commonly known as one of the ``Ink
cap'' family. The small, reddish-brown mushrooms are growing on and
around the base of a cottonwood tree.
</P>
<P>
   The Coprinus atramentarius are parasites that live on rotting
wood, and their presence can mean impending doom for the tree host.
However, these particular fungi are good to eat as long as they are
not consumed with alcohol, which can give some people a
stomachache. She harvests several bunches.
</P>
<P>
   Lutz also finds some ``LBMs,'' or little brown mushrooms, in the
grass at Central Park, which she studiously avoids, saying that
they are almost always poisonous and not worthwhile for all but the
most amateur of fungi-hunters who are working on honing their
identification skills.
</P>
<P>
   There are no morels to be found in Central Park. Lutz is
disappointed because morels, with their delicate ``woodsy'' flavor,
are among her favorite of the edible wild fungi. But the
hollow-stemmed mushroom is elusive, Lutz said.
</P>
<P>
   Lutz does not despair. She knows local supermarkets and
specialty stores stock varieties of wild mushrooms that have become
fashionable and mainstream _ morels, chanterelles and oyster
mushrooms _ for the less adventurous of fungi lovers who may not
have time or the courage to forage for themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
