<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MARKS ANNIVERSARY OF DISPUTED PARTNERS' LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON and ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ City officials have marked the first anniversary
of a contested law that has resulted in more than 1,700 companies
extending equal benefits to their employees' domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one-year anniversary shows the rest of the country that
not only do we have a symbolic victory in assuring equality in the
workplace, but there has been a tremendous practical effect,''
Supervisor Leslie Katz, co-author of the city ordinance, said
during a City Hall celebration Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was on hand to celebrate, however. With some 50
uniformed police officers standing guard, a small band of
protesters demonstrated against the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, led by the Rev. Fred Phelps of the Westboro
Baptist Church in Topeka, Kan., carried signs saying gays will burn
in hell and that AIDS, the acquired immune deficiency syndrome,
will cure homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the demonstration, Shirley Phelps-Roper, one of Fred
Phelps' 13 children, said: ``Righteousness exalts a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Homosexuals have taken this city hostage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The law also is the target of legal challenges. The nation's
major airlines seek to overturn the ordinance. And an Ohio company
that lost out on a contract because of its failure to provide
domestic-partners benefits is suing the city in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic-partners ordinance, which took effect June 1, 1997,
requires companies that do business with the city of San Francisco
to provide the same benefits to their workers with domestic
partners _ both gay and heterosexual _ as they do to married
couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very proud day for San Francisco. It was a significant
day internationally when the legislation was signed,'' Mayor Willie
Brown said. ``Now that we proved it is working, my guess is that it
will be replicated in jurisdictions all over this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's Human Rights Commission has had inquiries about the
law from New York, Seattle, Madison, Wis., and West Hollywood,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   According to the San Francisco Human Rights Commission, which
oversees the law, 6,331 companies have requested compliance review
by the city. Of those, 1,738 companies, with more than 700,000
employees, offer domestic partners benefits; 351 do not comply
outright; 1,366 offer no benefits to anyone and are exempt from the
law; and 755 have no employees in the United States and also are
exempt. Another 2,121 compliance reviews are pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
