<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-FILM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUO FINDS VERMONT A CHOICE SOURCE FOR FILM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A.   DAVIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARNET, Vt. _ Filmmaker Jay Craven and novelist Howard Mosher
seem at first to be unlikely collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; With his long hair and beard, intense air and commanding
manner, Craven comes across as the activist, organizer, and
entrepreneur that he is. This is a man who excels at the
deal-making, cajoling, improvising, innovating, stroking,
hard-selling, and creative financing necessary to make a big movie
on a small budget in an unlikely location.
</P>
<P>
   Graying, soft-spoken, and serious, Mosher looks and talks like
the high school English teacher he once was. Not so obvious is the
outdoorsman, a guy who when he's not writing is happiest walking a
forest trail or wading with rod in hand into a fast-moving trout
stream.
</P>
<P>
   What the two share is a deep love and concern for the place
where they live and work: the beautiful but remote corner of their
state that Vermonters call the Northeast Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Craven has made three films based on Mosher's work, all set in
the kingdom. The most recent is ``Stranger in the Kingdom'' _ a
story of xenophobia and racial intolerance in a small town, which
will be released in August. A fourth, ``Disappearances,' a
picaresque tale of rum-running along the Vermont-Quebec border in
the 1920s, goes into production later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others in Vermont these days, both men were born
elsewhere, the 47-year-old Craven in Pennsylvania and Mosher, 55,
in upstate New York. No longer viewed as outsiders by most natives,
``transplanted'' Vermonters like Craven and Mosher are in the
forefront of the struggle to preserve the character of a state now
going through the painful process of becoming a post-agricultural
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is affirm Vermont but not romanticize it,''
says Craven, who calls his style of filmmaking ``Vermont verismo.''
Although filmed in autumn and a delight to see, ``Stranger in the
Kingdom'' definitely doesn't sentimentalize rural life: Most of the
bad guys are dyed-in-the-wool Vermonters. Mosher's novel was
inspired by an incident that occurred in 1968 in Irasburg, Vt.
(pop. 900), where he lives. After drunken youths fired shotguns at
a black man's house, authorities trumped up an adultery charge to
drive him from town. ``It was the kind of thing that was supposed
to happen in Mississippi but not Vermont,'' says &UR;  &LR; Mosher.
</P>
<P>
   Mosher, has written five novels set in a fictional ``Kingdom
County.'' His description of the county, ``an out of the way and
little known fragment of a much earlier rural America,'' also
describes the kingdom. ``After living here more than 30 years, I'm
not a stranger in the kingdom any more,'' Mosher says, ``but it
took a long time to be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   He writes in long hand on yellow legal pads while sitting at a
table in the kitchen of his weathered white frame house. On the
wall is a framed, hand-stitched sampler that reads:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufpoetry &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Travel East
</P>
<P>
   Travel West
</P>
<P>
   After All
</P>
<P>
   Home Is Best
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,19 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Telling Vermont's story
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Craven operates out of a paper- and props-cluttered office on
the second floor of a former school house in the village of Barnet
(pop. 300), 40 miles south of Irasburg. Tacked to his wall is a
large map of Vermont covered with 100 round yellow stickers; each
represents a Vermont town without a movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and Christmas, Craven plans to win these towns to
the cause of independent regional filmmaking by showing ``Stranger
in the Kingdom'' in town halls and church basements to audiences
that probably will have driven over miles of washboard dirt roads
to see it. ``We send a postcard to everyone in town,'' says Craven,
who is usually the projectionist, ``and it becomes a community
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they knew of each other by reputation, the two didn't
meet until 1986 when Craven wrote and asked if he could option the
screen rights to some of Mosher's work. The resulting screenplays
have been cowritten by Craven and another Vermont novelist, Don
Bredes, an arrangement that suits Mosher. ``I have input on the
final script and it's been a good collaboration,'' he says. ``I'm
one of the few authors I know of who has had his books made into
movies and liked the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Craven and Mosher say they feel an urgent need to portray
the people and capture the images of rural Vermont now, before they
change drastically or disappear. ``When I first came there were a
lot of small family farms and the French-Canadians were a distinct
group but now the farms are mostly gone and the French-Canadians
largely assimiliated,'' Mosher says. ``And the old horse loggers
and hill farmers and moonshiners and whiskey runners have vanished
like the elms on a thousand New England village greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven says he became interested in film in the early 1970s
while a student at Boston University, where he was active in the
antiwar movement. After graduation, he moved to New York to study
visual arts. ``I was very excited about film but New York was so
competitive, I didn't see how I could get anywhere,'' he says.
``And I wanted to live in a place with a sense of community and
connectedness and where everybody I knew wasn't just like me.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in 1974 he settled in St. Johnsbury, Vt. ``My first year in
Vermont was the most isolating time in my life,'' Craven remembers,
``but that was good for me.'' The following year he began teaching
at an alternative school in Peacham and founded Catamount Arts, an
arts organization that ran a theater and coffeehouse and sponsored
concerts and appearances by performers such as Johnny Cash and
Peter, Paul and Mary. He founded his filmmaking company, Kingdom
County Productions, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,19 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At home in the kingdom
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mosher discovered the Northeast Kingdom in 1964 when he and his
wife, Phillis, both fresh out of the University of Vermont's
graduate school of education, were looking for teaching jobs and
chose a school in a small town in the kingdom because the fishing
was so good. He describes the kingdom he came to then as: ``a
remote enclave of narrow glacial lakes and north running rivers,
thickly forested mountains, half forgotten hamlets, and high hill
farms home to some of the most fiercely independent individualists
left on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosher is a pretty fierce individualist himself. Instead of
suffering in silence, like most writers, when he gets a rejection
letter from an editor, or a newspaper or magazine runs a review
critical of one of his books, he nails them to the front of his
garage and blasts away with a shotgun. ``The wall of my garage has
a lot of holes in it,'' he concedes, ``but I haven't had to shoot
at it much lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get a teaching job because of his vocal opposition to
the war, in 1969 Mosher went to work in the woods for $8 a day
hauling logs for a larger-than-life local character named Jake
Blodgett, the model for Noel Lord, the protagonist of Mosher's
novel ``Where the Rivers Flow North.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake was an old rumrunner and wildcat logger but he had a
heart of gold,'' Mosher recalls, ``and I named my son after him.''
In the film ``Where the Rivers Flow North'' that Craven made in
1994, Lord was played with great gusto by veteran actor Rip Torn.
</P>
<P>
   During the filming, Craven says, it was Mosher who saved the day
by persuading a reluctant Torn _ a method actor who is also an
ardent fly fisherman _ to appear in a key scene. ``Rip is from
Texas and a thorny character and he didn't want to be shown in a
bathtub, half-naked and looking vulnerable,'' recalls Craven, ``but
he admired Howard as a writer and outdoorsman in the Hemingway mode
and he was able to get him to do the scene when I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the well-known Hollywood actors appearing in ``Stranger in
the Kingdom'' _ which had a budget of $1.8 million, minuscule by
Hollywood standards _ are Martin Sheen, Ernie Hudson, and Henry
Gibson. Most of the actors worked for scale, Craven says, attracted
by the opportunity to play larger roles than they can get in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The 600 extras, residents of Chelsea, Vt., where most scenes
were filmed, worked for free. Sheen, who portrays an oily
prosecuting attorney, also donated his time. ``It requires
generosity and community involvement like that for a film like this
to get made,'' Craven says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
