A0212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EPISCOPAL-GAY-BOS &LR;      06-02 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPAL-GAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY PRIEST A FINALIST TO BECOME BISHOP OF NEWARK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Rev. Gene Robinson of New Hampshire, an openly gay
priest, became a finalist to become the next bishop of Newark,
Barbara Harris, a friend and the Episcopal Church's first woman
bishop, made a point of showing him her hate mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``She talked to me about how much it costs to be the first,''
Robinson, 50, canon to the bishop of New Hampshire, told an
Episcopal forum two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Harris's warnings could come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   If elected by the Newark diocese Saturday, Robinson would become
the first openly homosexual bishop of the 2.5 million-member
Episcopal Church in America. He is considered by church officials
and other observers to be the top contender among six finalists to
succeed the Rt. Rev. John S. Spong.
</P>
<P>
   His candidacy is already causing an uproar in a denomination
embroiled over the issue of homosexuality. While the national
church has not forbidden the ordination of openly gay priests, and
several dioceses have been doing so for several years,
conservatives have heatedly opposed it. The issue will be debated
this summer at an international Anglican conference.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson declined to be interviewed, saying the finalists for
the Newark position had agreed not to speak with the media until
after a new bishop is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its relative small size compared to other Protestant
denominations, the influence of the Episcopal Church in America,
known for its many affluent and socially prominent parishioners,
far exceeds its numbers, and the church's positions on social
issues are closely followed.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Robinson becoming bishop is anathema to
Episcopal conservatives, who could still block his election after
Saturday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is very clear: Is the Epsicopal Church prepared to
elevate a practicing homosexual to the rank of bishop?'' said the
Rev. Todd Wetzel, executive director of Episcopalians United, a
traditionalist evangelical group that claims 34,000 members
nationwide. ``The issue isn't whether he's likable or capable. The
issue is that the Scriptures clearly condemn homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Robinson was married with two daughters before he acknowledged
his homosexuality, according to documents he gave to the Newark
diocese.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Asked by the nominating committee in Newark to describe what
risks he had taken for his faith, Robinson wrote: ``I answered
God's call to acknowledge myself as a gay man. Risking the loss of
my children and the exercise of my ordained ministry in the church
was the biggest risk I've ever taken, but it left me with two
unshakable things: my integrity and my God.''
</P>
<P>
   Divorced from his wife, &UR;  &LR; Robinson lives in Weare, N.H., with
Mark Andrew, a program manager for the New Hampshire Department of
Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   While those who know Robinson say he is not a crusader for gay
rights, he is well aware that his desire to be a bishop makes him a
public target. His supporters say he is courageously testing the
church's tolerance; Robinson brought Andrew along during a visit to
the Newark diocese two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene is one of the most prepared people in the country to
become a bishop,'' said Kim Byham, a member of the Newark
nominating committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under church rules, even if Robinson wins approval from the
diocese of Newark he must receive a majority of votes from the
house of bishops and the standing committees of the nation's
dioceses.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, approval from the bishops and the standing committees
is a rubber stamp. A diocese's choice for bishop has never been
rejected by the national church. But Robinson's case promises to be
anything but usual. Still bitter over Harris's election as bishop
in the diocese of Massachusetts, many conservatives have vowed a
national lobbying effort against him.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in Newark comes at an awkward time for the church; in
July, Anglican bishops from around the world will gather in England
for meetings they hold every 10 years. Many of the bishops have
chastised the Episcopal Church, the American branch of Anglicanism,
for straying too far from Christian tenets by permitting the
ordination of women and homosexuals. There are currently eight
women among the 200 &UR;  &LR; bishops, and more than 100 openly gay
Episcopal priests nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's election would further antagonize conservative
Anglican bishops, some of whom have suggested the American church
should no longer be considered part of the worldwide communion.
</P>
<P>
   ``His consecration would be a further indication that the
Episcopal Church has abandoned traditional standards of Christine
doctrine,'' said the Rev. Sam Edwards, executive director of the
Episcopal Synod of America, another traditionalist organization
with a national membership list of about 20,000. ``If he is openly
professing his homosexuality and advocating the goodness of that
lifestyle, it would be absolutely unacceptable to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some national church officials acknowledged that the timing of
the international Anglican bishops' meeting will make it difficult
for Robinson to receive approval from the national house of bishops
and the standing committees.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a priest for 25 years, is widely praised both in New
Hampshire and across the country as a talented administrator,
gifted pastor, and skilled mediator. His homosexuality was not a
factor in his being named a finalist, Byham stressed, adding that
all the finalists are committed to gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never known Gene to overexploit his sexual
orientation,'' said Bishop Walter Righter, who lives in New
Hampshire and was cleared two years ago of heresy charges for
ordaining a gay man when Righter served under Spong. The diocese of
Newark is among the most liberal; Spong has been an outspoken
advocate for the ordination of women and gays, and the blessing of
same-sex relationships.
</P>
<P>
   At a May 15 news conference in Newark after the announcement of
the finalists, Robinson told reporters: ``I think the best thing I
could do for gay and lesbian Christians would not be to be a gay
bishop, but to be a good bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad part,'' said the Rev. Edward Rodman, canon to the
bishop of Massachusetts, ``is that he is such a good guy and so
competent that it would be shame if it just came down to the issue
of his homosexuality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
