<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN FUN WITH FILM TITLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When American and English movies are shown overseas, the first
thing to go is often the title. Here, from the Sunday Times of
London, are titles that in China became the following:
</P>
<P>
   _In Mandarin, ``The Full Monty'' is ``Six Naked Pigs.'' In
Cantonese, it is ``Six Stripped Warriors.''
</P>
<P>
   _The Cantonese version of ``The English Patient'' is titled ``Do
Not Ask Me Who I Am, Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Fargo'' is called ``Mysterious Murder in Snowy Cream.''
</P>
<P>
   _Oliver Stone's ``Nixon'' is ``The Big Liar.''
</P>
<P>
   _``As Good As It Gets'' is ``Mr. Cat Poop.''
</P>
<P>
   _And ``Boogie Nights'' is ``Instant Fame,'' which in Hong Kong
is slang for ... well, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And speaking of titles: &LR;  ``Titanic'' means ``Let's have sex'' in
Arabic slang, according to Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
