<HEADLINE>
NEW HEALTH ADS LINK SMOKING TO SEXUAL FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ State health officials have unveiled a vivid new
advertising campaign advising young people to quit smoking to
improve their sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the public health effort is an ad featuring a
handsome man who lights up a cigarette that goes limp in his mouth,
prompting ridicule from the woman with whom he has been flirting.
</P>
<P>
   The tagline reads, ``Cigarettes. Still think they're sexy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not certain men will stop smoking to save their lungs or
their hearts,'' said Carla Agar, spokeswoman for the Department of
Health Services. ``Maybe they'll stop to save their sex lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Another television commercial focuses on the dangers of
secondhand smoke. Agar said she hoped it would ``set off warning
bells'' in the minds of young parents.
</P>
<P>
   The camera flashes on a young boy on a baseball field, three
little girls whispering, an infant being bathed. ``Some of the
heaviest smokers are children,'' the narrator says. ``Of course the
smoke they inhale is from someone else's cigarette. Smoke a pack a
day at home ... your kid inhales 50 packs a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are part of this year's $22 million anti-smoking
education effort, funded by the Tobacco Tax Initiative that was
approved by voters in 1988. The advertisements target people ages
18 to 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at that against what the tobacco industry
spends, its a drop in the bucket,'' Agar said. ``They spend $5.1
billion marketing their deadly products nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertising had drawn criticism from some anti-tobacco
interests who contend the state has toned down its message so as
not to offend tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stanton Glantz, a member of the committee established by the
state legislature to oversee the public health campaign, said he
was unhappy with the ad review process set up by Gov. Pete Wilson
in 1994. Since then, according to Glantz, the input of his
committee has been ignored and all ads must be approved by Health
and Welfare Secretary Sandra Smoley.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they ran the old campaign, smoking was going down. With
the new ads, since '94, smoking has been going up,'' he said. ``I
think they're committed to running a weak campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Agar defends the state's efforts, saying California is at the
forefront of anti-smoking education and has the second lowest rate
of adult smoking in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``To suggest we've been anything other than hard-hitting, and
controversial, flies in the face of reality,'' she said. ``We
depict a woman who smokes a cigarette through her throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Another frequent critic of the state's campaign said he was
encouraged by the latest messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these are some of the most effective ads out in a
while,'' said David Shields of the American Nonsmokers' Rights
Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
