<HEADLINE>
DIANA TOUR SET TO LEAVE NEW YORK IN AUGUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A ``Diana Tour'' will visit the sites associated with her in
London and England, including her family home and gravesite. The
$1,999 nine-day tour leaves from New York on Aug. 14, and will
include a gathering with one of her friends. The tour includes
tickets to Althorp, where she is buried, and the newly opened
visitors' center. The tour is organized by Insight International
Tours of Boston; call 800-582-8380.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you have a stopover at Singapore's Changi Airport, consider
staying over a night or two. The first hotel night is just $1;
additional hotel nights are $30. The deal is good for long-haul
passengers flying either Singapore or Silk airlines, and is valid
through Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Air France, which again is flying out of Boston, is featuring a
six-day/five-night stay in Paris including hotel accommodations and
round-trip air fare from $909 from Boston. Tickets must be
purchased by June 15 for travel between July 13 and Aug. 31. For
information, call 800-2-FRANCE.
</P>
<P>
   Alitalia is offering Tuscany, beginning at $1,399 ($1,199 after
Sept. 15 through Oct. 31) a person from Boston. The six-night
package includes hotel, car rental, and breakfasts. For
information, call 800-252-ITALY.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Prohibition remembered
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the 65th anniversary of the signing of the 21st
Amendment and the repeal of Prohibition. America's grand social
experiment with the prohibition of alcohol failed, and instead we
remember the period as one of bootleggers, speakeasies, flappers,
and gangsters. America's hotels were affected in many ways by this
period. Historic Hotels of America, an association of 127 hotels
that are at least 50 years old and have maintained their historic
integrity, architecture, and ambience, have many stories from this
period. At the Lafayette Hotel in Marietta, Ohio, many staff were
suspicious of Skinny, a young bellhop who seemed to be living above
his means. How successful he was became clear after a flood (the
hotel is right on the Ohio River, and to this day has markers
indicating the height of the flood waters, including one that is
well above the lobby) that sent pint bottles of moonshine floating
up the main staircase of the hotel. Skinny, who operated the
elevator, apparently was also selling the bottles during his ups
and downs. When discovered, Skinny was fired, but reportedly
rehired moths later. Things were different at the Red Lion Inn in
Stockbridge. The inn, which was dry for more than 100 years, began
selling liquor with the passing of Prohibition. Many guests were
not happy with this. One wrote, ``As you have gone into the rum
business, I shall not come to your hotel anymore.'' Another noted
that the change was revolting to old regulars and that she had seen
a lot of ``cheap'' people at the inn. Staying at a Historic Hotel,
you can share in these stories. For a copy of a member listing
booklet, send $3 to Historic Hotels of America, National Trust for
Historic Preservation, 1785 Massachusetts Ave. NW, Washington, DC
20036; or call 800-678-8946 for reservations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vacation cash
</P>
