<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NORMANDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEA, SAND AND HISTORY MEET ON NORMANDY'S CALVADOS COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONFLEUR, France _ On a sunny summer day, this snug little port
on Normandy's Calvados Coast is a swirl of movement and activity,
filled with cheerful sounds and sensual aromas.
</P>
<P>
   Yachts bob in the boat basin, and flocks of cawing seagulls
circle fishing boats unloading their catches. Crowds of casually
dressed people promenade alonq the quays and meander through the
narrow streets. A buzz of animated conversation rises and falls
from sidewalk cafes along the waterfront. The air is filled with a
strong, salty smell of the sea flavored by cooking scents emanating
from Honfleur's many seafood restaurants, the Sole Normande of one
blending deliciously with the Coquille St. Jacques of another.
</P>
<P>
   Strategically situated at the mouth of the Seine River, Honfleur
in the Middle Ages was a base for the Vikings, or ``Northmen,'' who
colonized Normandy and for whom it is named. But the town's glory
days were in the 17th century, when a hardy breed of Norman
mariners, many from Honfleur, explored almost every corner of the
world and gave France an overseas empire in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In 1608, for instance, Samuel de Champlain set sail from
Honfleur to found Quebec in the wilds of Canada. Today, a visitor
sitting at a cafe table _ a glass of wine in hand, perhaps _ and
contemplating the delightful place Champlain left behind might well
ask: ``Why on earth would Sam want to leave?''
</P>
<P>
   About 60 miles long as the seagull flies the Calvados Coast _
the curving coastline between the mouths of the Seine and Vire
rivers _ is a necklace of beach resorts and yachting ports. Only
about a two-hour drive from Paris via the A13, a high-speed toll
road that resembles an American interstate highway, this is the
most convenient place for Parisians to savor summer at the seaside.
They do, and in droves.
</P>
<P>
   The Calvados Coast is noted for broad, sandy beaches, often with
high cliffs behind them, that have been attracting vacationers
since the mid-19th century. It was on these same wide beaches that
the allied forces landed on June 6, 1944 _ D-Day _ to begin the
liberation of Europe from Nazi Germany. Many traces of the D-Day
invasion remain, from massive bunkers, gun emplacements, and
wrecked landing craft to poignant military cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   Artists long have been drawn to the area and found Honfleur
particularly appealing because of its antiquity and distinctive
architecture. Reflecting the Norse ancestry of the Normans, some
Honfleur buildings look like stone and slate versions of the
steep-roofed, wooden-stave churches of Norway.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most unusual buildings is 15th-century St.
Catherine's Church, which is made entirely of wood, a very rare
thing in France. During the reconstruction of Honfleur after the
devastating Hundred Years War, the story goes, highly skilled local
shipyard workers built it as a temporary church in the only way
they knew how: like a ship. St. Catherine's has two naves, the roof
of each shaped like an inverted ship's hull.
</P>
<P>
   Honfleur became an important artists colony in the late 19th
century, and many of the Impressionist painters, including Claude
Monet, lived and worked in the town. But the artist most closely
associated with Honfleur is Eugene Boudin. Son of a local harbor
pilot and a master of the seascape, Boudin encouraged fellow
painters to come to his beloved Normandy. The Eugene Boudin Museum
in town is devoted largely to the so-called Honfleur School of art;
Boudin and his friends, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its proximity to Paris, the eastern part of the
Calvados Coast _ the so-called ``Flowery Coast,'' from Honfleur to
Cabourg _ is the most fashionable. Trouville, an old fishing port
with a fine beach, became a tony resort in 1852, when a casino was
built. Its posher neighbor Deauville, which has an equally splendid
beach, was founded a few years later and modeled after England's
then ultra fashionable Brighton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Besides beaches that in summer are forests of bright red and
yellow beach umbrellas, both Deauville and Trouville have wide
boardwalks and many old hotels and villas. But Deauville is
definitely the fancier and more resorty of the two _ ``The Monte
Carlo of the North,'' it likes to be called _ with a large and
elegant casino, a health spa specializing in sea water therapy, and
a race track.
</P>
<P>
   West of Deauville are several smaller resorts _ Bionville,
Villers-sur-Mer, Houlgate _ quiet, family-oriented places with good
beaches. Cabourg, beyond Houlgate, is a well-preserved, high
Victorian resort that looks attractive but has a reputation for
stuffiness. The invasion beaches are all to the west of the Orne
River. Because of the width of the Orne at its mouth, the coastal
road goes inland and crosses the river, and the Caen Canal that
parallels it, at Benouville, where some of the fiercest D-day
fighting occurred.
</P>
<P>
   To secure the east flank of the landing area, British
paratroopers were dropped onto Benouville the night before the
landings and captured the bridges. They held them, despite repeated
German counterattacks, until relief arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Now known as the Pegasus Bridge (the mythological winged horse
was the emblem of the British airborne forces), the canal bridge is
the scene of a seasonal sound and light show, ``The Night it All
Began.'' There is a small museum nearby and also Cafe Pegasus,
where the paratroopers set up their headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe boasts that it was ``the first building in France to be
liberated.'' Still grateful, the management serves free drinks to
any British veterans of the battle who stop by.
</P>
<P>
   Ouistreham, at the mouth of the Orne on the west bank, is where
the car ferry from Portsmouth, England, disembarks. You can tell
because there are signs, in English, warning arriving
Brits:``FRANCE _ Keep Right!''
</P>
<P>
   Ouistreham was a key position in the system of coastal defenses
the Germans called ``The Atlantic Wall.'' Near the terminal is a
massive five-story-high concrete bunker, formerly a German
artillery observation post and now a museum, the bunker tells the
little-known story of the Atlantic Wall: an enormous construction
project on which more than two million people, many of them slave
laborers, worked for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Ouistreham are the British Commonwealth forces landing
beaches: Sword, Juno (where the Canadians came ashore), and Gold.
There are a lot of memorials to individual units along the coast
road here, often incorporating old tanks or artillery pieces. Also
sadly numerous are signs pointing to the allied forces military
cemeteries in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Normandy landings caught the Germans completely by surprise
because they took place on open beaches where there were no ports
with facilities for unloading supplies and reinforcements, an
essential requirement for a successeful invasion. The allies'
secret weapon was ``the mulberry harbor'': steel breakwaters towed
across from England in prefabricated sections, bolted together, and
sunk off the landing beaches to create temporary ports.
</P>
<P>
   Arromanches, a typical Calvados Coast beach resort, was right in
the middle of the landing area. And, it still has a D-Day view:
Vestiges of its mulberry harbor, ``Port Winston,'' have survived
war and weather. In the two weeks after D-Day, 2.5 million men and
half a million vehicles were landed at Arromanches. An Embarkation
Museum, with a glass wall looking directly out at the rusty but
sturdy remains of the breakwater, uses a large diorama, a mockup of
a mulberry harbor, a film of the actual landings, and multilingual
lecturers to explain how it was done.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``Calvados,'' by the way, is a corruption of
``Salvador,'' the name of a Spanish galleon wrecked in a storm and
beached _ like a section of mulberry harbor _ off Arromanches
centuries ago. A landmark for mariners, in time the name of the
wreck came to be applied to all the coast here. Also, by extension,
to the famous _ and famously potent _ local apple brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Omaha Beach, where American forces suffered their heaviest
casualties, shows surprisingly few traces of the fighting, other
than scattered monuments to units that fought there. Shortly after
it was completed, the mulberry harbor serving Omaha Beach was
demolished by a violent storm, cutting off support to the troops on
shore. Faced with fierce defensive resistance as they tried to push
inland, many GIs were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The American military cemetery at Colleville-sur-Mer is on a
bluff overlooking Omaha Beach. It's a beautiful, terribly moving
place that no American traveling in Normandy should fail to visit
if at all possible. There are 9,386 graves (four of them of women),
each in a long row and marked with an identical white stone cross
or Star of David. In a memorial, beside a reflecting pool, is a
22-foot-high bronze statue depicting ``The Spirit of American Youth
Rising from the Waves.''
</P>
<P>
   A path leads down from the cemetery to the landing beach.
Because of the abundance of shellfish, this stretch of coastline is
known as ``The Mother of Pearl Coast.'' And today on Omaha Beach,
once littered with artillery shells, there are almost always people
walking barefoot along the water's edge looking for seashells.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For detailed and up-to-date information specific to individual
interests and needs about Normandy and other regions of France,
call the French Government Tourist Office public information hot
line: 202-659-7779. Calls are answered Monday through Friday from 9
a.m. to 9 p.m.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLINS-TRAVEL-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     06-02 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-TRAVEL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW TOWN SQUARE, Pa.: ... good meal.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk was of the ship's remarkable speed, and a report of
icebergs on its course. Strangely, Dick's father had experienced an
iceberg-steamship head-to-head joust in 1879 aboard the Arizona. He
wasn't too concerned. Then passengers and crew worked together to
stanch the leaking hull with the cargo of cotton. But it was
``inconceivable'' the Titanic could be damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses were awakened in their portside cabin at 11:45 by
``merely a jar. The ship seemed to tremble slightly. The engines
were no longer throbbing. We were not excited, but felt something
had happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning of the clash, they saw the only immediate evidence _ a
sailor exhibiting a bucket of ice as a souvenir. ``There was no
panic, some confusion. The band was playing lively tunes. Even if
the improbable happened and she did sink, she would float for 12 or
15 hours,'' they assumed, and ``any number of ships would stand by
to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Eureka. The steamer California came so close ``our worries were
over. But ... she serenely sailed by into the darkness.'' Distress
rockets were interpreted as celebrational fireworks for the maiden
voyage. No one was in the wireless room to hear the Titanic's
``CQD!'' signal (the predecessor to SOS).
</P>
<P>
   Father and son, with lifebelts beneath heavy fur coats, explored
the brightly lighted decks, ``although the listing made the going a
little hard.'' Harder were the ``harrowing scenes enacted when
wives were forced to leave husbands, for the order had been women
and children first.''
</P>
<P>
   The last of the insufficient number of lifeboats gone at 1:45
a.m., Dick and his father were gripped by ``a peculiar feeling,
wandering, knowing that all means of escape seemed cut off.
Everything was very still but cheerful under the circumstances. The
band was out on the deck now, still playing. It was a beautiful
night, the water full of phosphorus sparkling. A man who may have
cracked under the strain wore a high hat, wanted to save it. We
smiled, it was funny.''
</P>
<P>
   But the situation turned ominous. In their wandering ``I heard
the crack of a revolver'' (possibly the suicide of first officer
Murdock, who, by some later, and disputed, accounts, had ignored
the lookout's sighting of the fatal iceberg).
</P>
<P>
   Only two decks of the gargantuan liner remained above water.
Suddenly the deck beneath them was awash. Dick knew it was time to
get away, to swim for it. He yelled to his father: ``Quick! Jump!
He started toward me just as I saw one of the four great funnels
come crashing down on top of him. For a moment I stood transfixed.
Then I jumped to the rail, about 15 feet above the rising water,
climbed over and jumped clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed I would never come up. The shock of the cold water
was quite bad. As soon as I came to the surface, with `suction' in
the back of my mind, I started swimming with all my might.'' His
life, almost snuffed by the collapsing funnel, now hung on this, a
100-or-so-yard freestyle away from the disintegrating, plunging
Titanic. Perhaps more of a flailstyle because Dick was rather
sartorially encumbered _ though maybe no more so than Worth, the
Kentucky Derby winner that year, would have been if carrying a
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   It was like swimming inside a refrigerator, and Dick, hardly
dressed for speed, may have set the the world record for a sprint
through 29-degree water in a bathing costume of trousers, shirt,
sweater, raccoon coat, shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kicked off the shoes but could not get out of my coat. In my
struggle I turned toward the ship as she was about to sink. An
extraordinary sight. As the bow went under, the stern lifted higher
and higher, then pivoted slowly over my head. Had it come down then
I would have been crushed. Looking straight up I saw the three
propellers and rudder outlined against the clear sky. She slid into
the ocean. No suction. No noise. Two or three big waves.
Stillness.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. ``Then came the horror _ the cries of 1,600 people
struggling in ice cold water. At times it grew into a roar, then
dying down. You seemed to hear groups, even individuals. Here and
there from some unfortunate came some oath, groans, a supplication
_ and there was nothing to do. Their cries grew weaker and weaker.
Presently everything was quiet, the ocean calm _ a deathly
stillness.''
</P>
<P>
   Spotting a small group holding to something, he swam there,
``fortunate enough to get a little place to hang onto, and threw
off my coat at last.'' His haven materialized as a ``collapsible
boat'' that had washed off the ship. Its canvas sides had indeed
collapsed, but the wooden bottom floated just below the surface, a
platform of salvation. As many as 30 in a changing cast had clung
with him. But after six hours and the arrival of the rescuing
Carpathia, ``only 13 of us were picked up.''
</P>
<P>
   They prayed, sang for a bit, tried to cheer each other up,
wondered if a ship would come in time, considered attempting to
bail out the boat with a hat. But the man wearing it refused its
use, saying, ``I'd catch cold in the night air.'' As a mother and
daughter drifted off, dead, ``We watched with prayers on our
lips.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-awaited dawn and deliverance came at last, ``a beautiful,
sparkling morning looking down on a group of heartbroken,
bedraggled humanity _ all that was left of the greatest ocean
steamer ever built. As my eyes swept the horizon I had my first
sight of icebergs. Five or six. The irony was that with the morning
sun on their gleaming and sparkling whiteness, they made a
beautiful, never-to-be-forgotten picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow _ youth, athletic fitness, guts, providence, luck? _
Dick endured. The warmth of the coming summer must have seemed
impossibly beyond reach as he hung almost paralyzed from a panel of
wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always most satisfying playing for my country,'' he
told me in a phone conversation in 1966, two years before his
death, and long before I learned of his Titanic adventure. ``The
gold medal, of course, was great fun.'' That was his 1924 Olympic
triumph alongside Bostonian Hazel Wightman in the mixed, two
old-ies-but-goodies, she 37, he 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had sprained an ankle badly in the semis, and told Hazel I
probably should default, and we'd settle for the silver. Nonsense,
she replied. She told me to stay at the net and she'd cover
everything else. I didn't move much, but,'' Williams recalled
gallantly, ``Hazel ran everywhere and won the match and the medals
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   You might be surprised to learn that his Olympic gold was not in
swimming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
