<P>
   HEART-YOUNG-ATHLETES (Undated) For many students, sports
physicals are a necessary nuisance to participate in sanctioned
school athletics. But too often the exams are cursory. They lack
the scope to detect a leading killer of young athletes: sudden
cardiac death, which takes 15 to 20 lives a year, according to the
American Heart Association. Could more thorough physical exams save
some young lives? That question has sparked a national debate in
the medical community over whether sports physicals should have
mandatory guidelines for cardiovascular screening. GRAPHIC
</P>
<P>
   with HEART-RYAN (Seattle) As a 24-year-old sophomore guard for
the Seattle Pacific University basketball team, Ryan Sowards is
fortunate: His heart condition was detected and he now take
medicationto keep it in check.
</P>
<P>
   with: HEART-MORRELL (Undated) Former Washington State University
Cougar Chuck Morrell is on a mission to educate people about sudden
death of athletes because of heart failure.
</P>
