<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0238 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      06-02 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRUE TITANIC SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW TOWN SQUARE, Pa. _ No, she hasn't seen ``Titanic,'' and Sue
Williams has no intention of doing so. She knows the story, and
knows that her man's story _ miraculously true _ is far better than
the ones made up for a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo DiCaprio (as Jack Dawson) couldn't hang on in the
refrigerated North Atlantic that ghastly April night 86 years ago,
depicted in the award-winning flick, but her man, Dick Williams,
did. DiCaprio, the movie's hero, went under, and was last seen
wearing an iron mask.
</P>
<P>
   Almost too late in getting off at the Titanic's last stop,
Williams wasn't identified as one of those frightened, freezing,
and floundering in the North Atlantic in the film. They were all
extras, anyway. But 21-year-old Richard Norris Williams II _ Sue,
his widow, says he preferred just plain Dick _ was actually there,
his life ebbing away in the terribly big chill. Unmentioned in
Hollywood and literary accounts of the compelling sunken subject of
1912, his dreadful night's tale was amazingly improbable: of nearly
losing his life, then his legs _ yet five months later racing to
the quarter-finals of his US Tennis Championships debut at Newport,
R.I., earning a number two national ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been a horrible experience,'' Sue Williams is
saying, sitting in the living room of her attractively decorated
and furnished home in New Town Square, a leafy Philadelphia suburb.
``But Dick never talked about it. His father died right in front of
him, crushed by the collapsing funnel, and Dick _ an only child _
was very close to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   A memento remains, a watercol-or of the Titanic painted by a
young boy, grandson Quincy Williams, hanging in a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how Dick felt about that, but he loved Quincy,
and so we put it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she did read the memoir of the tragedy that Williams
wrote for his family, and graciously has permitted me to quote from
it. She is charming and witty, handling her 90 years very well. Her
lively blue eyes express much amusement as she tells about the only
tennis tournament she ever won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the mixed doubles title of a small club we belonged to,
and I played with Dick. The woman of the team we beat was furious.
She told me I was one of the worst players ever.'' Sue laughs and
says, ``And she was probably right.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dick Williams, who died 30 years ago, was one of the best, a
resident saint since 1957 in the International Tennis Hall of Fame
at Newport, R.I. Credentials: A world top-10 luminary seven times
between 1914 and 1925, he took time out for World War I in which,
as a US artilleryman at the front, he was decorated by both his own
and the French government. He was number five the last year, at age
34, won the US singles title in 1914 and 1916, doubles at Boston's
Longwood Cricket Club (with Vinnie Richards) in 1925-'26 and helped
the US win six Davis Cups as player or captain.
</P>
<P>
   However, personal accomplishments weren't things he dwelled on.
``Not long after we were married,'' Sue says, ``Dick remarked that
he was tired of all the trophies around the house. He packed up 162
of them, had them melted down, and ordered one tray made, right
here.''
</P>
<P>
   She exhibits the extraordinary bauble, engraved with signatures
(from correspondence) of all the great players of his time,
including the greatest, Bill Tilden, and first US champ Dick Sears.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did keep the US singles and doubles trophies, and, over
there, his prize for winning the Wimbledon doubles'' in 1920, with
Chuck Garland. ``But,'' she says, chuckling, ``look at it.'' The
fine sterling tray is as scarred and scratched-up as an aging
hubcap. He casually used it for a carving platter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He truly played for the fun of it, not tangible rewards,''
says another visitor, grandson Quincy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The mercurial score of his 1916 US title win over Bill Johnston
(4-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2, 6-4, at Forest Hills) tells much about his
all-or-nothing approach, a daring style that made the likable
6-footer immensely popular. A dashing presentation and shotmaking
artistry meant more than merely winning a match as he nervelessly
shot for winners whatever the situation. After the Titanic and the
slaughterhouse of war, tennis must have seemed a lark.
</P>
<P>
   But, oh how close Williams came to never striking another ball.
While others clinging with him to a submerged liferaft slipped away
in death _ ``they didn't drown, they froze,'' he recalled _ Dick
hung in. For six hours, until rescued by the steamer Carpathia as
one of the slim, lucky minority, the alumni of the Big T. Of the
1,677 in the water, only 42 lived.
</P>
<P>
   By then, his legs were frozen stiffer than Republican resistance
to campaign finance reform, and a physician on board ``cheerfully
advised'' immediate amputation, to fight hypothermia and defend
against the expected onset of gangrene.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Williams vetoed that medical judgment and delivered
the gutsiest performance of a long sporting career. Somehow getting
to his feet _ ``As I tried to stand it was like thousands of
needles going through my legs'' _ he began to lurch and trudge.
Half-dead man walking, he forced himself to step out and away from
the surgeon's crippling blades. ``I tramped the decks constantly
even through the nights, getting up every two hours to walk some
more.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Dick Williams was in circulation again. In three
months, he hit the US tennis scene running on those recently
petrified pins. Virtually springing from ice water to boiling
shotmaking and electrifying achievements, Dick won his American
bow, the Pennsylvania Grass tourney at Philadelphia's Merion
Cricket Club, beating Tilden along the way.
</P>
<P>
   He was brilliant, pure, and uninhibited, a college boy with
close-cropped chestnut hair succeeding spectacularly also in a
higher league. Immediately after capturing the national
intercollegiate title for Harvard in 1913, he was instrumental in
the US seizure of the Davis Cup from Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   A voyage that started out at Cherbourg as fun for young Dick on
the brand-new, supposedly invulnerable Titanic became anything but.
He had grown up and become an exceptional player in Switzerland, a
climate recommended as beneficial to the delicate health of his
father, Philadelphia attorney Duane Williams. Father and son were
traveling to the United States to enroll Dick in the class of 1916
at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Fateful luck, measles for Dick, delayed their journey. Thus, the
Titanic's unveiling became an option they selected ``because of its
reputation for safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so big, so queenly, four city blocks long,'' Williams
wrote. ``She felt very safe and sound.'' Seated at the captain's
table for the ship's ``elaborate'' last supper, Sunday night, April
14, ``all of us had the human weakness to overindulge.'' Later, in
the water during his blackest night, he would think, ``I'm darned
lucky I had such a good meal.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
