<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``BILL OF RIGHTS'' FOR PATIENTS BADLY NEEDED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The health insurance industry has declared war on legislative
efforts in Congress aimed at restoring consumer confidence in,
ironically, the health insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans enrolled in managed health care plans
such as HMOs has grown from 13 percent in 1987 to 75 percent today
_ or 138 million out of 185 million with private health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the percentage of consumers who believe that
insurance plans often compromise the quality of health care to save
money has risen to 80 percent, according to some polls.
</P>
<P>
   This obvious lack of consumer confidence in managed care is
directly related to the restrictions the plans place on both
doctors and patients, often at the expense of the sacred
doctor-patient relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Some managed care plans, for example, have gag rules that
prevent doctors from telling patients about services that are not
covered, or from ``making referrals to the specialists they
consider most appropriate to treat a patient's condition,'' surveys
show.
</P>
<P>
   Some plans also place physicians at financial risk for
recommending costly, but necessary, health care.
</P>
<P>
   Plans have become so restrictive that more than 2,000 physicians
from across the nation signed a manifesto that said: ``Physicians
and nurses are being prodded by threats and bribes to abdicate
allegiance to patients, and to shun the sickest, who may be
unprofitable. Some of us risk being fired or `delisted' for giving,
or even discussing, expensive services, and many are offered
bonuses for minimizing care.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation called The Patients' Bill of Rights, sponsored by US
Senator Edward M. Kennedy, would provide doctors and nurses with
protection against such retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the bill provides more rights to patients in
need of costly but vital referrals to physicians who are not in
managed care plans. This consumer ``bill of rights'' has been under
increasing attack from conservative Republican senators as well as
from lobbyists for corporate interests and the health insurance
industry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For example, the deceptively named Health Benefits Coalition,
which consists of about two dozen chief executives from the
Washington-based Business Roundtable, recently began a major
lobbying effort aimed at scuttling the Kennedy bill.
</P>
<P>
   The group ostensibly argues that providing such protections and
rights to doctors and patients would raise the cost of managed
health care and place an unfair burden on businesses providing
their employees with such insurance. They argue that the
free-market system, with no federal regulations, is the way to
improve quality in health care.
</P>
<P>
   Some GOP senators realize these arguments do not match the
strength of the Kennedy bill, which is reflected in polls saying
that 90 percent of US consumers see a need for regulation of health
insurance plans.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Senator Alfonse D'Amato is pushing his own
legislation designed to replace, rather than destroy, the Kennedy
bill. The New York Republican's bill replicates only a section of
Kennedy's measure, specifically a provision for 48-hour hospital
stays for women with mastectomies and coverage of reconstructive
breast surgey after a mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato recently attacked supporters of Kennedy's bill for
delaying D'Amato's. Kennedy, in turn, is demanding a vote on his
more comprehensive legislation.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has been suggesting that Kennedy, by not supporting
D'Amato's bill, is basically anti-woman, a charge that is as
ludicrous as D'Amato's attempt to portray himself as a women's
rights advocate.
</P>
<P>
   One thing consumers have that gives them a chance against this
health industry Goliath is Kennedy himself, who &UR;  &LR; proved to be more
than a match for corporate giants who unsuccessfully fought his
minimum wage bill.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry knows that the next rock in Kennedy's
political slingshot, his Patients' Bill of Rights, is pointed right
at them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1424EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
