<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NETSCAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE _ THE LITTLE COMPANY THAT ENRAGED THE GIANT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPEEDING THE NET &QC; 
The Inside Story of Netscape and How It Challenged Microsoft &QC; 
By Joshua Quittner and Michelle Slatalla &QC; 
Atlantic Monthly Press, 323 pp., $25 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Netscape Communications Corp. should be dead by now. Well,
comatose, at least.
</P>
<P>
   This brash little start-up made its mark with Navigator, the
most popular software for cruising the Internet. It introduced
millions of people to on-line life. And when Netscape stock went
public, the company's value soared to $4.4 billion in a single day
_ a record that stunned Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Netscape, its performance also stunned the
titans at Microsoft Corp. Bill Gates and his notoriously
competitive lieutenants had no intention of allowing this upstart
company to undermine the Microsoft empire. They responded with a
relentless counterattack that seemed likely to drive Netscape to
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't happened. Netscape may be bleeding cash and losing
market share, but the Netscape story is far from over. Which
explains the unfinished tone of ``Speeding the Net,'' a breezy and
fast-paced history of the company. The book, by veteran computer
writers Joshua Quittner and Michelle Slatalla (he's familiar from
his work at Time, she from hers for The New York Times), is short
on deep analysis of the company and the industry, and it presents
little new information. But it does serve up a lucid, readable
overview of the computer industry's fiercest competitive rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   It begins, in classic computer-industry style, with a couple of
kids. One of them, Marc Andreessen, has since become a living
legend, obscuring the role of his equally important colleague, Eric
Bina. In 1992, Andreessen and Bina, then students at the University
of Illinois, began hacking up an Internet browser that would
display pictures as well as text. The result was Mosaic, the first
popular Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   After Andreessen graduated, in 1993, his work came to the
attention of Jim Clark, physicist and cofounder of Silicon Graphics
Inc. Clark, in search of new worlds to conquer, met with Andreessen
and began dreaming up ways to make money in the fledgling Internet
business. As with the founding of Hewlett-Packard Co. in the 1930s,
the two men knew they wanted to start a business, but not what the
business would actually do. They batted around a host of ideas
before settling on building a better browser.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the original Mosaic team, that's what they did.
Netscape released Navigator in 1994. For the first time since
Microsoft's Windows 3.0 hit the market, in 1990, somebody had
produced a computer program that set the world on fire. Within
weeks of its release, millions of people around the world had
become loyal Netscape users.
</P>
<P>
   By August 1995, when Netscape stock went public, Microsoft was
gearing up to strike back. The company would license the original
Mosaic software made by Andreessen and Bina, and use it as the
basis for a much better browser built right into the Windows
operating system at no extra charge. It was a strategy well suited
to devastate Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   But was it illegal, as federal and state antitrust regulators
are now contending in their suit against Microsoft? Some
information in the book tends to vindicate Microsoft. Quittner and
Slatalla show that Microsoft executives launched a plan to add
Internet browsing to Windows 95 back in the spring of 1994, before
Netscape's founding. This jibes nicely with Microsoft's assertion
that the built-in browser was simply a logical product improvement,
not an illegal effort to crush a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   But the book is also likely to be popular at the Justice
Department. It features some of those notorious Microsoft internal
documents that frankly discuss using the linkage between operating
system and browser as a way to destroy Netscape's core business.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Microsoft had grown accustomed to competing against firms
like IBM, Lotus Development Corp., and Apple Computer Inc. _
companies whose repeated blunders paved the way for Microsoft's
dominance. Not this time. While Microsoft's onslaught devastated
Netscape's market share in browsers, Netscape has fought back with
courage and cunning.
</P>
<P>
   The company has taken its share of flak for urging the Justice
Department to investigate Microsoft: Cynical folks like me have
accused them of being crybabies. But there's no denying that the
gambit has worked, with a big assist from the arrogant moguls of
Microsoft. Netscape has bought itself some breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's trying to transform itself into an Internet media
company. Its Netcenter Web site is already one of the Internet's
most popular. Now Netscape is adding a host of news, information,
and Internet search features to attract millions of regular
visitors, as well as millions in advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Netscape matched Microsoft's browser giveaway
strategy, it's even giving away the underlying ``source code'' used
to write its browsing software. This has made Netscape the darling
of hard-core techies, and the leader of a fledgling movement to
expand the use of ``open source'' software as an alternative to the
Microsoft empire.
</P>
<P>
   But will the new strategy work? Quittner and Slatalla, for all
their skills in telling the story thus far, are as much in the dark
as the rest of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
