<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-RYAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE FOUND A WAY TO PLAY ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (WITH HEART-YOUNG-ATHELETES and HEART-MORRELL)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As a 24-year-old sophomore guard for the Seattle
Pacific University basketball team, Ryan Sowards is fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Not because he was able to pursue a professional baseball career
in the minor leagues and still return to his game of passion,
collegiate basketball. And not because he averaged 12.7 points a
game and started 24 of 30 games last season after not playing
basketball for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Sowards is fortunate he's still healthy and able to play sports
at all. He lives with a condition, supraventricular tachycardia,
that causes rapid heartbeats. The condition is similar to the
irregular heart beat experienced by former Seattle SuperSonics
forward Terry Cummings, who has had a long and successful NBA
career despite his ailment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a little circus going on inside my heart,''
Sowards said. ``It's like my heart skips a beat and the next beat
is really hard. I've had it for so long that it's very easy to tell
when it starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Supraventricular tachycardia can cause palpitations, dizziness,
light-headedness or unconsciousness. In some cases, it can lead to
death unless medical help is provided immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Sowards remembers the day he knew something was wrong. He was
pitching a Little League baseball game when he started to feel
faint and noticed his heart racing. A doctor at the game
recommended that he be checked thoroughly. Doctors at University
Hospital in Seattle discovered his condition and ultimately treated
it with medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid, you pretty much think you're invincible and
nothing is going to happen to you,'' Sowards said.
</P>
<P>
   Now he knows his heart inside and out. He said his condition is
caused by his A-V node, which sends electrical current to the
heart, causing it to beat. He had a leak on one side of the node,
so the heart would beat with a faster rhythm to compensate for the
irregular flow of current.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm having an episode and my heart is racing, I'm not
supposed to play. I should sit out until I can get it under control
or stop it,'' Sowards said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a sophomore at Bothell High School, Sowards had
heart surgery to correct the problem by cauterizing the leak.
Within a week after leaving the hospital, he scored 28 points in a
basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   But despite surgery, the condition remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the operating table for six to eight hours, and (the
heart defect) was in too difficult of a spot for them to fix it,''
Sowards said. ``But the doctors were able to figure out what kind
of medications stimulated and reduced it ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Few people know what Sowards has gone through to continue his
athletic career. For almost four years, he pursued baseball at
Walla Walla Community College and for the Los Angeles Dodgers farm
system as a pitcher and catcher before he decided to return to SPU
and reclaim his basketball eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough road, and it's taken a while to get back
into the swing of things,'' Sowards said.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, he leaves his heart condition in the
past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
