<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0258 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-MORRELL-SPI &LR;      06-02 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-MORRELL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER COLLGE FOOTBALL PLAYRE PUTTING OWN HEART-DISEASE STORY ON
FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (WITH HEART-YOUNG-ATHLETES and HEART-MORRELL)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Chuck Morrell watched his beloved Washington State Cougars
prepare for their first Rose Bowl in 67 years, he was grateful he
had lived long enough to see one of his dreams come true.
</P>
<P>
   But the 60-year-old Morrell, who set the record for WSU's
longest run from scrimmage (87 yards in 1958), wasn't at the Los
Angeles Coliseum just to relive old glories.
</P>
<P>
   After a career as a screenwriter and Hollywood producer, Morrell
was on a mission to bring attention to one of the most frightening
foes some young athletes face: sudden death caused by heart
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being lucky to be alive doesn't mean much to me any more.
I want to do something about it,'' Morrell said of a malady that
takes about one life in every 200,000 young athletes each year.
</P>
<P>
   Morrell is more than familiar with heart disease. In 1991, he
lost his twin brother, Gary, a longtime Seattle broadcaster and
sports announcer, because of a condition known as Hypertrophic
Cardiomyopathy (HCM). Gary's two sons died of sudden heart failure
at ages 12 and 14. Morrell's mother, Virginia, died of heart
failure at 54, and his half-sister died in her sleep at age 3.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Morrell is still around to tell his story is
because of a heart transplant in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   As he looked out onto the football field in California on New
Year's Day, Morrell wondered how many other young athletes could be
hiding the same ticking time bomb he had _ HCM _ without knowing
it.
</P>
<P>
   With him was his brother's grandson, Tyler, who was diagnosed
with HCM last year at age 11, and has an automatic cardiac
defibrilator surgically implanted into the chest muscle to
stimulate his heart when an irregular heartbeat occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my day and age, we had no idea what was going on,'' Morrell
said. `` ... But we haven't advanced much farther and that's why
I'm trying to do what needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrell, who has appeared in films such as ``The Sting,'' and TV
shows such as ``Ironside,'' ``Banacek'' and ``McCloud,'' is
producing a documentary film to spread the word to young athletes
and their parents. He hopes to complete the film by the end of the
year with an eye toward broadcast on a cable network, such as the
Learning Channel. He still is seeking funding.
</P>
<P>
   He considers sudden death from heart failure to be a public
health problem that has gone virtually unrecognized since the days
he played college sports.
</P>
<P>
   The script of his documentary, ``Without Warning,'' begins with
Morrell recalling his 87-yard run, which he figures would have been
a touchdown if not for his hidden heart problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had started on our own 3-yard line and fell to the ground on
their 10-yard line,'' Morrell recalled. ``No one tackled me. I just
ran out of gas. I tripped over the line marker. I fell on my ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Morrell feels lucky that his actual heart failure didn't
occur until later in life and that he lived to see the Cougars
return to glory. So, now he's more determined than ever to
publicize sudden death in young athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't know anything about it,'' Morrell said.
``People always used to laugh at me when we were doing dummy
scrimmages, because you were supposed to run eight yards or so and
then turn around to come back to the huddle. Well, I used to always
run another 50 yards just because I wanted to do it. With my
condition, I could have died in a moment's notice, but we didn't
know it then.''
</P>
<P>
   His own personal struggle with heart disease now gives Morrell's
life a renewed purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky,'' he said. ``But there has to be some reason for
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
