<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0268 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BRIDES-BOS &LR;      06-02 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BRIDES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITIONAL BRIDAL WHITE GIVES WAY TO COLOR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here come the brides, all dressed in ... yellow? Blue? Green?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. This spring, many brides are shunning the almost
sacred white wedding gown in favor of radical colors like ice blue,
mint green, soft pink, lavender, and even sherbet orange.
</P>
<P>
   No, these aren't just second-time brides. They're modern brides,
women who consider fashion and personal style more important than
old-fashioned societal rules and symbolism. They think white gowns
all look the same, don't flatter their complexion, or aren't flashy
and memorable enough to justify the average $500 to $2,500 price
tag. Their role models aren't society matrons but celebrities like
Elizabeth Taylor (who wore a yellow gown in her most recent
marriage, to Larry Fortensky in 1991).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nontraditional,'' says Christine Perkins of Back Bay, who
chose for her wedding a yellow gown she saw on a movie star in
InStyle magazine. Says Perkins, a brown-eyed blonde of 32, ``When I
put white on, it makes me look washed out. Yellow brings out my
skin tone.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, colorful wedding gowns aren't for everyone (white
and ivory remain the clear favorites, retailers report). Some
traditionalists maintain that the new color concept is almost
sacrilegious, since custom links white symbolically with virginity.
``This trend is a total reflection on the family and how we view
family,'' says LeRoy Attles, pastor of St. Paul AME Church in
Cambridge. ``The whole notion of marriage is invaded now. People
live together before they're married or they don't get married.
It's almost a mockery to put on a white dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Shari Thurer, a psychology professor and authority on cultural
studies at Boston University, says many women are more motivated by
magazines and TV shows than social conventions. ``The whole social
construction of marriage, weddings, and romance is very
disconnected from religious sources. People would rather be
copycats of models and celebrities. They like to mimic their
lifestyles,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Other women might use a colorful gown ``as a mechanism for
rebellion or to be exhibitionist or to take the hinge off a
controlling mother,'' Thurer says. ``Outrageousness is in. But
there are very individual reasons for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some brides concede that the decision to break protocol isn't
easy. Rather than face clucking tongues before the wedding, they'd
prefer to surprise everybody. ``I didn't tell my mom. I told her I
don't want to show her,'' says Perkins. ``And I didn't tell the
priest either. I didn't want to shock him. My family is very
traditional,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Harrison, 31, of Johnston, R.I., also hasn't told her
fiance about her gown, for their upcoming wedding Sept. 27: a gold
lace dress (with ivory satin showing underneath). ``He's very
conservative,'' she says. ``Once in a while, I get a little
nervous. `Oh my God. Is this too much? Everyone else is going with
white.' It's definitely not a traditional wedding gown. But you
know, you only live once.''
</P>
<P>
   The white gown is certainly the most identifiable aspect of
American weddings. Many young women grow up dreaming about the day
they'll wear all white. But some women today report that when the
time came to actually try on white-dress samples, the uniformity of
it all gave them the blahs. They wanted something more exciting and
memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want an ordinary gown,'' says Harrison. ``When you
look at people's photo albums, all the gowns look the same. They
have puffy sleeves, beads, and, of course, white fabric.'' Harrison
believes that with her gold gown, ``at least people will notice it.
It has a lot of style to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Litchfield of Hamilton chose a pink gown for her big day
last month. ``White is too stark. It's too much of a contrast
against my skin,'' says Litchfield, 26. ``The pink gives the dress
a lot of character, a lot of life.''
</P>
<P>
   To increase the impact of their colored dresses, some brides are
asking their bridesmaids for the unheard of _ to wear white.
``Bridesmaids' dresses are looking more bridal,'' says Yolanda
Cellucci, owner of Yolanda's boutique in Waltham, which is
showcasing only ice-blue wedding gowns in its windows. ``They have
to wear white or ivory so the bride stands out,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, in some countries, like India and China, many brides
wouldn't even consider white. The color of choice there is red.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over color isn't so new in the United States either.
American brides in the 1800s wore the best dress they owned, and it
was typically black or blue, says Sandra Newman, a professor of
pattern design at Lasell College in Newton and a wedding-gown
designer herself. ``It was usually a dark color because you
couldn't get light colors clean,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``White (a tradition popularized in England by Queen Victoria in
the early 1800s) was for the rich, who didn't care if they only
wore the dress once,'' Newman says. By the early 1900s, more
American women were wearing white ``to show off how rich they
were,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, colors like pink and mint green have appeared
occasionally in bridal stores (particularly in the 1950s, early
1960s, and even in the late 1980s). But never with such variety,
retailers say. And they often weren't selected by first-time
brides.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the design house Christian Dior plans to introduce
something not for the fainthearted: a chocolate-brown wedding
dress. New York designer Angel Sanchez plans to introduce in his
bridal collection this fall dresses in light brown, silver, and
gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for something different,'' Sanchez says.
``This is one of the most important moments in a woman's life.
White is so plain. I find young people are open to different
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, mothers seem supportive of the trend, at least in some
families. Some of these moms wore pink themselves, some 30 years
ago. Marie D'Eramo of Melrose actually pushed her daughter Kristen
D'Eramo Gerety to choose a colored gown for her wedding in October
1996. ``Twenty-eight years ago, I had a white gown with gold
beading all over it,'' says D'Eramo. ``And when the church lights
hit the beads, it was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristen, 26, took her mother's advice and bought a similar gown.
``Everyone loved it,'' she says. ``They made such a big deal over
it.'' Says D'Eramo, ``If you're going to spend that much on a
dress, it might as well be remembered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
