<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-YOUNG-ATHLETES-     06-02 2328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-YOUNG-ATHLETES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDEN DEATH BECAUSE OF RARE HEART PROBLEMS HAS STOLEN YOUNG
ATHLETES LIVES) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (WITH HEART-RYAN and HEART-MORRELL)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jason Pennington desperately wanted to play football and no one,
not even his doctor, thought the 13-year-old's asthma would get in
the way. But the condition masked a congenital heart problem that
killed the teenager on his first day of fall practice in Caldwell,
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Western Washington University's Duke Wallenborn lived to play
basketball, and did so, despite being diagnosed as a child with a
heart problem known as Wolff-Parkinson-White Syndrome. But his
heart condition caught up with him, and took his life in his junior
year of college at the age of 23.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State University's Hayward ``Spud'' Harris, 21, was
an imposing presence on the football field, an All-State lineman
from Lakewood's Lakes High School. But his life suddenly was cut
short on his first day of fall drills. Horrified teammates watched
him slump over on the field of an apparent heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   All three succumbed to sudden cardiac death, which takes the
life of one young athlete in every 200,000 _ 15 to 20 a year _
according to the American Heart Association. Only violent head and
spinal injuries cause more deaths among young athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But the trio shared something more: Each had passed a standard
physical exam and was cleared to play a strenuous sport.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are statistics in an ongoing debate about whether a
sports physical should include the most effective tools to spot a
potentially fatal heart problem: an electrocardiogram (ECG), the
most common test of a person's cardiac system, or an
echocardiogram, which uses sound waves to evaluate a heart's
condition.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict centers on three issues:
</P>
<P>
   _Whether testing could prevent athletes from placing themselves
in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether it would cost too much and who would pay.
</P>
<P>
   _Whether it actually would save lives.
</P>
<P>
   One recent study suggests tests could be performed in a
large-scale program for as little as $10 per athlete through
competitive bidding, while other estimates place the cost at much
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a way to detect it ... what is a life worth?''
asked Tom Wallenborn, Duke's father. He said his son sometimes had
spells in which his heart would race, but was told by doctors he
was in no danger playing sports. He died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he went to college, I took him in to a cardiologist
just to make sure, because I figured playing ball at the college
level would be more vigorous and I just wanted to make sure
everything was all right,'' said Wallenborn, of Vancouver, Wash.
``That's when it was labeled Wolff-Parkinson-White and the doctor
told me and Duke that it was a non-life-threatening situation. So
with that clean bill of health, we sent him on his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Rice, who tracks sports injuries involving young
athletes, will never forget hearing about Harris' death in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many years it has been, but why do I remember
Spud Harris? Because he dropped dead on the campus just a couple
days after he had his physical,'' said Rice, a national expert on
sports injuries and young athletes. ``When that happens, you stand
up straight and say, `What can we do to prevent it? This is really
unbelievable.'''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent deaths of Washington state high school students
participating in sports both occurred in 1992:
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 21, 14-year-old Clarissa Erickson, a freshman at R.A.
Long High School in Longview died after a three-mile, cross-country
race. A coroner's report showed she had a rare heart defect that
wasn't detected in a physical.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 13, Stacey Olson, 17, died of heart failure at Liberty
High School near Spokane after collapsing during a gym class _ 50
feet from where his twin brother, Tracey, had died of a heart
problem in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Washington and many other states advise parents that
sports physicals should include a detailed family medical history,
one of the most valuable resources a physician has to determine the
risk of heart problems. Doctors also are supposed to perform a
blood-pressure test and listen to the heart for signs of murmurs or
other problems. A stress test is optional, but most states advise
that it be done.
</P>
<P>
   Juli Edwards, Pennington's mother, said her son's physical in
the summer of 1993 lasted only minutes. He did that August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even had to ask that they do a blood test, or it wouldn't
have been done,'' Edwards said. ``The doctor looked at him with a
stethoscope, he looked at his tonsils ... and then he pretty much
released him.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Pennington been tested with an echocardiogram, Edwards
believes, her son's congenital heart problem would have been
detected. Instead, it wasn't found until his autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had done an `echo' on Jason, he would still be alive
today,'' Edwards contends.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such cases, a 1996 panel put together by the American
Heart Association determined that running every young athlete
through advanced heart testing during a sports physical would be
impractical.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which included one of the nation's leading experts in
sudden deaths, Dr. Barry J. Maron of the Minneapolis Heart
Institute, estimated that the tests would cost an average of $600
per athlete, and that they wouldn't save many lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at $500 per (test), it would theoretically cost $250,000
to detect even one previously undiagnosed case,'' the panel wrote,
because of the odds of an athlete having a potentially fatal heart
defect.
</P>
<P>
   At Children's Hospital and Medical Center in Seattle, the cost
of an ECG, an echocardiogram and related tests can cost up to
$2,000, said cardiologist Dr. James French.
</P>
<P>
   The key, he said, is to do the groundwork before such tests are
performed _ a full physical involving a stress test and treadmill
test, combined with an extensive family history.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any history of problems such as fainting spells,
abnormal heart beats, shortness of breath or a family history of
heart disease, French advised parents not to wait to get their
child's sports physical done.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the signs of (heart) diseases don't happen when
you're sitting quietly waiting for the physical to begin,'' he
said. ``A lot of the things that cause the problems have to be
provoked.''
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that the most comprehensive way to detect
potential problems is to use an ECG or an echocardiogram. But the
main issue is the cost of the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this cardiac screening with an ECG can be accomplished for
$10 per athlete and has to be done only once during a four-year
high school career, the task becomes manageable,'' wrote Rice,
former director of the Athletic Health Care System at the
University of Washington, who for years has studied and tracked
sports injuries among young athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, currently at the Jersey Shore Medical Center in New
Jersey, was responding to a study published in the September 1997
issue of Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise. The study
screened 5,615 athletes in Nevada schools to determine the
effectiveness of an ECG as part of a full physical exam.
</P>
<P>
   While the study found no specific cases of the most common fatal
heart disease, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM), 582 students were
discovered with other heart abnormalities after answering a family
history questionnaire, taking a blood-pressure test and having an
ECG screening. Of those, the ECG detected 146 students with
abnormal heart beats, heart wave abnormalities and other
irregularities. Sixteen students were not approved to play sports
and were referred for further testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the objective is to reduce the number of nontraumatic
sudden deaths on the high school playing fields, then we suggest
performing an ECG once in the athletic career of a high school
athlete,'' concluded the Nevada study headed by Dr. Colin M.
Fuller, the Sierra Nevada Cardiology Associates and the Sierra
Heart Institute, all of Reno, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ECG tests can be performed by a cardiac technician without
a physician being present at the time,'' the study said. ``The ECGs
can be computer interpreted and over-read by a qualified physician
off-site ... and the authors estimate that a cost of $10 per ECG,
including technical and professional fees, is a reasonable
estimation.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with that information, Rice suggests doing a study
involving 120,000 young athletes to put them through full heart
examinations to determine the true cost and effectiveness of such
examinations on a larger scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to work it with many thousands of people
to have big enough numbers to let things show up statistically,''
Rice said. ``Plus, it's the issue of finite health-care resources.
In other words, you have to think of how much money is spent doing
all these false tests, and all these people inconvenienced, to find
what maybe is 10 people a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he noted, ``When a kid drops dead playing sports, that's
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Maron said he realizes that the death of a young athlete
``strikes to the core of our sensibilities.'' But he stands by
recommendations made by the Heart Association panel and believes
there is no practical way to do extensive, cost-effective testing
on a large-scale basis.
</P>
<P>
   In its recommendations to the Heart Association, Maron's panel
looked at 158 sudden deaths nationwide among young athletes between
the years 1985 and 1995. Of those, 134 were linked to heart
problems, and nearly all had passed routine physicals.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found one common factor: almost all the deaths
occurred during or after intense exercise. But more than 20
different heart disorders were found in the deaths. Maron said he
doubts that performing specific heart tests during physicals would
have caught many more cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are rare diseases, so they are going to be uncommon and
you have a lot of athletes,'' Maron said. ``So the numerator is
small, the denominator is large, the tests are expensive, at least
at retail value ... and it's not going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the cost could be reduced from the Heart Association
panel's estimate of $600 per athlete to $10, Maron asks who would
pay for the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you made it $1, I think there would be some situations
where that would be too much,'' he said. ``If you're talking about
broad-based screening, you're talking about everybody.'' That
includes the estimated 4 million high school-age athletes, the
500,000 college-age athletes and about 5,000 professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Maron said, ``we are stuck'' with the standard
physical and family medical history as the best way to detect early
warning signs of heart disease and sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, Maron said he hopes the screening guidelines
developed by his panel have helped physicians around the country
become more aware of the dangers of heart disease in young
athletes. But he warns: ``Don't assume that clearance by history
and physical screening excludes all forms of heart disease that
might be important.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Smaha, director of athletic medicine at WSU, was on the
field in 1979 when Harris suddenly died. Smaha performed
cardiopulmonary resuscitation, but could not revive the 270-pound
lineman. Harris was the second person he had to try to revive in
his first two years at WSU.
</P>
<P>
   The other one, a former Cougar basketball player, had a heart
attack but was rushed to the hospital after manual CPR and placed
on a defibrilator, which restored the rhythm of his heart by
applying a brief, high-energy electric shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked out of there with no brain damage and sends me a
Christmas card every year,'' Smaha said. ``That was the good one.
The other one was Spud. And quite frankly, I was on top of him
within 30 seconds. ... But he was basically gone at that time and
we didn't realize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Rice, Smaha is haunted by Harris' death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when you've had this kind of thing happen at
Washington State and it's right in front of you there, it makes you
take a second look and second-guess how you do things,'' Smaha
said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Athletic Trainers Association, like the American
Heart Association, has studied the issue of whether an ECG should
be performed on college athletes. To Smaha, finding heart disease
that can cause sudden death is nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many times people have conditions that you are not going to
find doing all these tests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, he said, the first warning sign comes with a heart
attack. Or someone just suddenly dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's sheer luck that people are caught, said
cardiologist Dr. Dan Doornik, a former Seahawk and Washington State
running back.
</P>
<P>
   The unlucky ones are athletes like Duke Wallenborn, who suffered
a heart attack in his sleep the day after a game and only days
before he was scheduled to see a specialist about the possibility
of heart surgery to correct his problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew something was wrong since he was probably 3 years old
when he came in one day and his heart was beating fast,'' father
Tom Wallenborn said. ``At that time, which was the early 1970s, no
one really knew what the problem was and said that he would
probably outgrow it. It never seemed to slow him down. When it
would happen, he'd just sit down and in two or three minutes it
would go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallenborn said his son's heart began racing more frequently
during his last basketball season at Western, but the condition was
not limited to the basketball court. He still questions whether his
son should have been cleared by doctors to continue playing sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what is so frustrating and questionable,'' Wallenborn
said. ``That he had this his whole life and then we find a way to
take care of the problem, but it's too late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
