<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALEDICTORIAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SCHOOL DISTRICT BARS VALEDICTORIAN FROM SPEAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Photo of Walther available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KERRVILLE, Texas _ Tivy High School valedictorian Josh Walther
saw humor in calling on the two lowest-ranking members of his class
to replace him at the podium during commencement exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I have to do more work and give a speech?'' he
planned on telling the Class of '98. ``I wasn't the one slacking
the last four years.''
</P>
<P>
   But school officials weren't amused and vowed to have the police
remove the straight-A student from the stage if he insisted on
delivering the farewell address as written.
</P>
<P>
   ``It infringed on the rights of those lower-level kids not to be
humiliated in public,'' said Tivy Principal James Chase. ``We
weren't trying to tell him what to say, just `Please leave that
part out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Neither side budged during a week of negotiations, so Walther
sat silently as diplomas were handed out Friday to 247 classmates,
some of whom chanted, ``Let Josh speak!''
</P>
<P>
   The class salutatorian, Sally Graham, did deliver her speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair at all,'' Walther said Monday. ``They didn't
have the right to tell me I couldn't speak.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode not only tarnished Walther's final days of high
school, but also has raised questions about the authority school
officials wield over student expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly violates the spirit of free speech,'' said Jay
Jacobson, director of the American Civil Liberties Union of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever the government creates a public forum, such as always
offering the valedictorian an opportunity to speak, they ought not
be allowed to censor that speech because they do not like the
content,'' Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   Chase and Rolinda Schmidt, president of the school board in this
South Texas city, said the district could censor student speech
under its policy concerning ``school-sponsored publications.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy says district employees may exercise control over
style and content of student speech ``so long as their actions are
reasonably related to legitimate pedagogical (teaching) concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase cited the section of the policy on speech that ``does not
meet the standards of the professional employees who supervise the
production of the publication.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he didn't recognize Walther's opening remarks as humor,
Chase said: ``You've got to hunt for it.''
</P>
<P>
   After referring to the low-ranking students, Walther's speech
went on to point out that even the lowest-ranking medical students
still are called ``doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson questioned both Chase's sense of humor and the
applicability of the district policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do I disagree with the interpretation of their
policy, but if their interpretation is correct, it may very well
run afoul of constitutional principles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walther's father lobbied Chase, Schmidt and Superintendent Mark
Jackson to let his son's speech be made, uncut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really a disgrace that students aren't given the
right to freedom of speech,'' said Bob Walther, 48.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt supported Chase's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel there were parts of it that were appropriate for
the audience,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Walther, who plans to study zoology at Texas A&AMP;M
University, finally got to deliver the 10-minute speech Saturday at
his home, before his family and a few friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' his father said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
