<P>
   ELN-OTHER-STATES (Undated) _ Roundup of results in other states
holding primaries, including Iowa, Montana, New Mexico and South
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering other late stories, including the California
initiative aimed at requiring unions to secure members' permission
for political spending.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Response from Kenneth Starr to the
president's decision on executive privilege; other developments in
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-WASTE (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to vote late
today on whether to force the Energy Department to live up to its
agreement to accept nuclear waste from utilities, even though it
will be years before a permanent repository is ready. Clinton has
promised a veto but the bill may have enough support to override.
By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-COST (Washington) _ A bipartisan federal advisory panel
concludes that the Clinton administration has probably
underestimated long-term costs of Medicare, the insurance program
for the elderly. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-OIL-DUMPING (Washington) _ Royal Caribbean, one of the
nation's largest cruise lines, is expected to plead guilty to
deliberately dumping oil from its ships in Miami and San Juan, and
lying to the Coast Guard. The company threw in the legal towel
after a judge in Miami rejected its arguments, made by two former
U.S. attorneys general, that the Law of the Sea treaty requires
that the case be tried in Liberia, where it is incorporated. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   DRUDGE (Washington) _ Matt Drudge returns to Washington to
address the National Press Club, angering some members. By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MISS-WOODHAM-TRIAL (Philadelphia, Miss.) _ Opening arguments
today in the trial of Luke Woodham, 17, accused of stabbing his
mother to death and fatally shooting two classmates at his high
school. Defense lawyers are likely to argue that Luke was under the
influence of an older boy who was into devil worship. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CENSUS (Houston) _ President engages local leaders in a
roundtable on the census, and the need for statistical sampling to
get a more accurate count. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHILD-WELFARE (New York) _ In a major shift in child welfare
policy, the city announces it is putting its entire
$600-million-a-year foster care system up for competitive bidding.
Agencies will be required to place foster children in their own
neighborhoods and establish a decentralized system of services. By
Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FOOD-VENDORS (Undated) _ On the eve of a planned protest by
New York's food cart operators, a sampling of the views of these
street vendors, whom Mayor Rudolph Giuliani wants to ban in key
portions of Manhattan. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   NY-REPUBS-CONVENE (New York) _ Curtain-raiser on the New York
State Republican convention. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Developments in Russia's financial
crisis. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-AUCTION (Washington) _ Russia's last three auctions of
treasury securities have failed to meet the target as investors
have shied away from risk. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-ECON (Washington) _ Six weeks ago Treasury Secretary Rubin
told Congress that the chances another major country would need a
bailout was ``a low probability event.'' He wouldn't say that
today. The question in Washington is where will economic contagion
stop. Rubin speaks today at 2 p.m. EDT. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   BAHRAIN-U.S. (Washington) _ On a rare visit to the United
States, the Emir of Bahrain came not to buy more American military
hardware or ask for more protection against Saddam Hussein, but to
woo American investors. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we are considering stories on Indonesia and the
India, Pakistan nuclear issue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-ARTHRITIS (Undated) _ After two decades, the
biotechnology industry is about to introduce its first drug aimed
at rheumatoid arthritis. That drug is just the first of what could
be a series of promising new medications developed to treat the
disease, for which there have been almost no new therapies for
years. These drugs could represent the biotechnology industry's
first blockbuster product. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ Chrysler and some of the foreign auto
makers report May sales data.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly travel column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was up down 13 points at 1:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments: The long bond
was down 11/32 at midday. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rich's ``Journal'' and Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties'';
details to come.
</P>
