A0283 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY LOIS PINES IS GETTING A PASS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems some people take an instant dislike to Lois Pines, the
state senator running for attorney general. However, that's
understandable because in our fast-paced world it simply saves
time.
</P>
<P>
   Pines reeks of ambition the way your pants smell of dry-cleaning
fluid after one-hour martinizing. That's not necessarily a bad
thing, either, because in politics people don't move forward unless
they can look in the mirror each morning and say to themselves,
``You are the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, though, Pines apparently got furious after finding
out that a few people in the business community had contributed to
her primary opponent, Tom Reilly, the district attorney for
Middlesex County. According to news reports, she got on the phone
and threatened to drop the hammer if she was elected.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are two views of this behavior: (1) It's no big deal;
all politicians regularly do this in an attempt to raise money
quickly with the aim of shutting an opponent off from potential
revenue sources in order to win a huge victory. (2) It's extortion.
</P>
<P>
   Pines is in the Legislature. She wants to be attorney general.
And it appears she gives bad-phone to some who choose to contribute
to Reilly, leaving them with an implied threat of retribution
ringing in their ears.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the old double standard arrives. No, not the
tired, lame, and obvious difference in sex, but, rather, the zip
code and ideological double standard.
</P>
<P>
   Pines is a huge liberal. She lives in Newton, socialist
sister-city to the world. Her voting record makes Karl Marx look
like Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   And everybody knows that liberals do good works. Liberals are
cool. Conservatives are morons. So it doesn't matter when a Lois
Pines comes off sounding like Jackie Presser of the Teamsters
during a phone conversation because she's a liberal darling and
liberals mean well.
</P>
<P>
   But if you substitute a name like Flaherty, Murphy, Kelly, or
Flynn, exchange her trim figure for a 44-inch waist, complete with
beet-red face, attribute the character with pro-life views and a
house in South Boston, Malden, or Billerica, why you can almost
hear the sound of sirens and handcuffs being attached. At a
minimum, such rude behavior would be sure to attract the interest
of the current attorney general, who has a foolish history of
hauling politicians to court on evidence a whole lot flimsier than
the words out of Pines's own mouth.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lois Pines gave us the bottle bill. She loves busing
and whales and low-income housing _ as long as it's located 57
nautical miles from her neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   She is a charter member of the ``We're better than you crew''
that figures government is a tool to make the rest of us conform to
codes of behavior that liberals can often ignore because of escape
hatches like affluence or geography. She's the kind of process
liberal so beloved by editorial writers, the kind who would haul a
Kip Kinkel into court in order to charge him with failure to
display a license rather than indict him for the murder of his
parents along with a couple of classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff like that _ multiple homicides _ is actually viewed by
many well-meaning liberals as inappropriate behavior. But not
following regulations? Not having a license? Not recycling? That's
big stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So when Pines threatens others with revenge because they toss
money to Reilly rather than to her, it's OK. The same way it was OK
when Hillary Clinton decided to ignore the law as she conducted her
very own hearings into health-care policy. If the cause is liberal
enough, or correct enough, bad behavior is excused, condoned, and,
sometimes, ignored.
</P>
<P>
   But let some poor stooge just to the right of center make a
threatening phone call to a businessman and the howls would be loud
enough to wake up Helen Keller. I mean, there have been more than a
couple of saps hauled in front of a grand jury for doing less than
Pines supposedly did out of a simple fit of pique.
</P>
<P>
   However, she gets a base on balls because she's a liberal, lives
in Newton, presents an attractive picture, and certainly couldn't
be guilty of being no better than one of the boys. After all, she
means well, and in our goofy, liberal state, any end justifies the
means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1434EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
