<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCEPTING THE NEW DEAL DID CONSERVATIVES A LOT OF GOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Barry Goldwater died, it was automatic for the
TV people to reach for the famous ad from the 1964 presidential
campaign, showing the little girl counting daisy petals before the
announcer counted down to a nuclear explosion.
</P>
<P>
   But I was surprised that no one showed another ad from Lyndon
Johnson's successful creative destroyers that year, featuring a
pair of hands ripping up a Social Security card.
</P>
<P>
   The first ad is part of our Cold War historical memories. The
other one, though, played with concepts and emotions that are hot
to this day.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad about the Bomb, foreshadowing the disgusting trends of
the next 30-plus years, the technique was to imply what not even
LBJ's hardball players dared directly allege _ that Goldwater would
produce a nuclear war. In the ad about Social Security,
foreshadowing another disgusting trend of outright distortion, the
explicit claim was made that Goldwater would ruin Social Security
and produce ``the end of widows' pensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Each ad, however, was made at least plausible _ and certainly
devastating because of its continual repetition in news coverage _
by Goldwater's own deserved reputation as a fundamentally
impulsive, even lazy, conservative with an equally deserved
reputation for shooting from the hip.
</P>
<P>
   He had said to reporters that the commander of NATO should have
authority to use tactical nuclear weapons, had opposed the treaty
banning nuclear tests in the atmosphere, and was himself the origin
of the interesting strategic doctrine of ``lobbing one'' into the
men's room of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Of more relevance to today's politics, he had also said to
reporters in Concord during the New Hampshire primary campaign in
'64 (which he lost to write-in Henry Cabot Lodge) that
contributions to Social Security should be voluntary and that if an
individual could make out better on his own, he should be free to
do so, but that if he prefers to have ``the government do it,''
fine.
</P>
<P>
   As his meticulous biographer and former aide Lee Edwards has
written, there was context for that answer _ Goldwater statements
going back several years. He had called Social Security
inadequately if not fraudulently funded, likely to become the major
tax ahead of the levy on income for most workers, and had called
for ``voluntary'' contributions on a phased-in basis so as not to
hurt anyone in the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater, however, never fully explained what he meant by
``voluntary,'' which left him open to doubts about his intentions.
Indeed, he validated those doubts a decade after his presidential
campaign, as Edwards also discloses. Following his reelection as
senator despite the Watergate landslide for the Democrats in 1974,
Goldwater wrote to his longtime adviser, the eminent conservative
economist Milton Friedman, that he thought the moment had come to
``advocate an end to Social Security,'' an idea Friedman quickly
got him to deep-six.
</P>
<P>
   The point here is that deep down, Goldwater's gut conservatism
did not accept, politically or substantively, the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Today's conservatives, having moved beyond that point
intellectually as well as politically, are in a much stronger
position. That is because they are seeking change by focusing on
the dangers to the system unless change occurs and by focusing on
the rate of return a worker can expect today from Social Security
compared with the return from the system they envision.
</P>
<P>
   What was called ``voluntary'' in Goldwater's day is now called
``privatization,'' only it really isn't. The typical proposal would
retain the tax on payroll that finances survivors' and disability
benefits; it would then give new workers the option of directing
the remaining eight percent of payroll (split with the employer) to
a ``personal'' retirement account that could be invested instead of
just placed in US Treasury debt.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to criticize this idea on a variety of fronts,
beginning with risk, but it is not possible to argue fairly that it
is a plan to ruin Social Security or threaten vulnerable retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The reason conservatism is strong today is not that Goldwater
paved the way so much as that conservatives learned from his huge
mistakes and made peace with FDR _ none more dramatically than an
old Democrat and Roosevelt-lover named Ronald Reagan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
