</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL FIGHTS ON IN LEBANON, EVEN AS IT TRIES TO EXIT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAQOURA, Lebanon _ The sound of missiles pounding a nearby
village rumbled like distant thunder last week inside the
Israeli-occupied security zone.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli helicopters retaliated against the hit-and-run Hezbollah
guerrillas as part of an intense week of fighting that was part of
a gradual, two-month escalation of attacks by the Iranian-backed
Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations observers in this city just north of the Israeli
border say Hezbollah carried out more attacks in April and May than
in any comparable period in 12 years. The attacks maintained
pressure on Israel as it searches for a way to pull its troops back
from what has become known here as Israel's Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years after Israel carved out a nine-mile swath inside
southern Lebanon to protects its citizens in northern Israel from
cross-border attacks, fighters and civilians on all sides inside
the ``security zone'' hear a lot these days about proposals for
peace. But the battle rages on.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday night, two Israeli soldiers were killed and two
were wounded when a roadside bomb exploded. The day before, two
members of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army were killed and five
wounded. Two Lebanese civilians were also seriously wounded later
the same day in artillery exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a Lebanese civilian was killed and another wounded
from Israeli fire, raising to 11 the number of civilians killed and
to 36 the number wounded in south Lebanon this year.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting intensified after Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's government last month ``officially adopted'' UN
Security Council Resolution 425, the 1978 resolution that called
for Israel to ``withdraw forthwith'' from Lebanon. But Netanyahu
attached a set of conditions to any withdrawal, and 1,500 Israeli
troops are still there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are coming into a routine of keeping the pot boiling, but
not tipping it over,'' said Timur Goksel, chief political adviser
of the United Nations Interim Forces in Lebanon, or UNIFIL. He
added that while Hezbollah has intensified attacks dramatically,
the number of casualties in the past two months has been relatively
low.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine Israeli soldiers were killed last year, the highest
in any year since the zone was established. So far this year, eight
Israeli soldiers have been killed. But the number of mortar
attacks, which are closely monitored by the UN, exceeded 100 in
April and 90 in May. The totals are higher than any month since
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Goksel says the increase in attacks and relative decline in
casualties indicates a need by Hezbollah to maintain pressure on
Israeli forces without crossing a line that will galvanize Israel
to rescind its offer to pull out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Goksel adds that Hezbollah's attacks may also have a broader
political motive. With the guerrilla operation trying to transform
itself into a more mainstream political force, it used its military
wing against Israel while campaigning for the first local elections
in 35 years on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   If that was indeed the plan, it worked. Hezbollah won wide
support in its strongholds south of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the reasons, the point is there's too much lead
flying right now, and it can very quickly get out of control. All
of these diplomatic scenarios can be overtaken by events very
rapidly,'' warned Goksel. ``There's a real opportunity to end the
conflict here, but if both sides don't focus it will be lost just
like all the other opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its offer to live up to the 1978 UN resolution, Israeli
units continue fighting to hold the swath of land in southern
Lebanon to protect citizens from cross-border attacks. The Israelis
say they will abide by the UN resolution if security guarantees,
including a disarming of Hezbollah, are carried out.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on Israel increased over the weekend. On Saturday,
President Jacques Chirac of France, while visiting Beirut for a
Francophone mayors' conference, said Israel ``must withdraw from
Lebanon in accordance with Resolution 425 and without any
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government and Hezbollah leaders say that if Israel
really wants to live up to Resolution 425, which requires that
Israel ``withdraw forthwith,'' then it should simply withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Nabil Kaouk, Hezbollah's military commander for the
south, said in an interview with The Boston Globe, ``If Netanyahu
had the true intention of withdrawing, I don't think anyone would
stop him. The Israelis knew the way in, so certainly they know the
way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah leaders have been noted for conducting interviews
while members clutching Katyusha rockets stand in the background.
But last week, Kaouk, wrapped in the black robe and turban of the
Shiite clerical hierarchy, offered a reporter fruit drinks as a
small army of stylishly dressed advisers scurried in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah seems to have gone slick. It is highly organized and
increasingly sophisticated. It closely monitors the US and Israeli
media to gauge what it sees as a tide of public sentiment pulling
against Israeli involvement in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not stop while they try to come up with a solution for
their own exit,'' Kaouk said of Israel. ``We will be the winners
here ultimately because we are fighting for our land and we have
the approval of our people that what we are doing is right. The
Israelis are not even able to convince their own people that what
they are doing is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Nizar Hamzi, a professor of political science at American
University in Beirut, said, ``I think the Israeli offer has to be
viewed as a dramatic development. I think it will work in the long
run.''
</P>
<P>
   His confidence may emerge from signs in Iran, however subtle,
that the key financial and political backers of Hezbollah are
willing to explore all possibilites.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he cited a letter from the Iranian government to
the US Secretary of State, Madeleine K. Albright, promising that
Iran would not interfere if Hezbollah wants to negotiate with
Israel over a withdrawal. Hamzi also characterized as ``important
and encouraging'' recent promises by Hezbollah leaders not to take
control of southern Lebanon if Israel pulls back.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Israeli intitiative has been rejected by the Lebanese
government and, more importantly, by its neighbor, Syria, which
stations 35,000 troops in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in the Arab world and in Israel have viewed the
Netanyahu government's offer as a ploy to defuse criticism of his
perceived intransigence in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
It is also viewed as a way to isolate Syria by stripping it of its
only bargaining chip with Israel in talks over the return of the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's deputy general in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Yoav
Biran, insisted that the Israeli offer is genuine. ``It is not an
exercise in public relations and it's not aimed at scoring
points,'' he maintained last week. ``We want 425, but as a package,
and if you want 425 to be implemented you have to accept it as a
package'' that includes guarantees of security for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We don't want to leave Lebanon in order to come back
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Israel's concerns is the fate of the 2,500 members of the
South Lebanon Army and their families, who are regarded by militant
factions of Hezbollah as collaborators with a sworn enemy of
Lebanon. The South Lebanon Army fights with the Israelis against
Hezbollah. Although Hezbollah leaders have introduced a law that
would offer amnesty to South Lebanon Army members who turn
themselves in, the Israelis fear a blood bath.
</P>
<P>
   South Lebanon Army Sergeant Ali Sebleini, 34, says he joined the
pro-Israeli forces out of economic necessity. The $450 a month
salary he earns as a soldier in Israeli uniform provides for his
six children, ages 7 to 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have no choice,'' he said. ``You just have to keep
good relations and keep your own family safe. That is my priority.
My heart is clean. I didn't kill anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Sebleini explained that his job consists largely of walking the
roads looking for Hezbollah-planted road bombs typically hidden in
fiberglass painted to look like rocks and aimed at Israeli
transports. ``I'm just trying to get by,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 200,000 people who live in the zone and each
day dodge the shelling and mortar exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon in a sleepy farming village, Israeli
forces were shelling a nearby hillside. The bombs exploding two
miles away shook the ground. Birds in the trees scattered. A cow
tensed and looked out of the corner of its eye toward the six
echoing thuds in the hills. A minute passed, and there was quiet
again. The birds' chirping returned. The cow went back to its hay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, there's shelling along here,'' farmer Naim Hamzieh
said in the village of Kfar Rouman, a few hundred yards from the
forward positions of the Israeli army that overlook his fields.
``And then you reporters come in and out and nothing changes. I've
lost family and friends. I've lost a dozen cows. How long can we go
on like this?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
