<HEADER>
A0383 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-VIETNAM-BOS &LR;      06-02 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-VIETNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL LEBANON PROVE TO BE ISRAEL'S VIETNAM?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZARIT, Israel _ An army of flies buzzed around a sticky bottle
of soda inside a bunker as Captain Hanan Iserovich, only 24 years
old, talked about the mission he would be sending 20 men out on.
</P>
<P>
   At this army post on the edge of the ``security zone,'' the
conversation quickly turned to comparisons with Vietnam, as it
often does about Israel's involvement in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comparisons don't work,'' Iserovich said. ``Vietnam was
far from home for Americans. This is so close we can see what we're
guarding. You can hear the chickens at the farms on this side. You
can see the lights of Haifa at night.''
</P>
<P>
   But one way in which the comparison with Vietnam appears valid
is the sense that Israelis tire of their young men dying in a war
in Lebanon. Public pressure mounts for an Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Iserovich insisted that he does not allow himself or his men to
be distracted by such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hezbollah doesn't give us a rest, so there is no time to think
or to debate,'' he said. ``It's a war over here, so of course you
don't like to hear the hysterical voices out there. But OK. It's
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Just outside his bunker office, 20 young men from a company in
the Nahal brigade prepared for a three-day mission inside the
9-mile-wide swath of land in south Lebanon occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   With the hammering, industrial beat of ``trance'' music blaring
in the background, the soldiers got ready by their own rituals.
</P>
<P>
   They slapped together kosher salami sadwiches and stuffed drab
green backpacks with junk food, like Kit Kat bars, Frosted Flakes,
chocolate syrup, peanuts, butterscotch candies, and tiny tinned
rations of pudding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need the sugar buzz to stay awake in there,'' said a
20-year-old infantryman named Avna.
</P>
<P>
   They cleaned machine guns, polished scopes, and tested
night-vision equipment. They carefully placed black tape over watch
faces and whistles. Anything that shines can make them targets.
</P>
<P>
   When they were ready, faces in black-and-green camouflage, the
music was turned off. The troops had been transformed from
teenagers to trained fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just after sunset and in complete silence, they walked
down a hillside to a barbed-wire fence stretching into the darkness
marking the border with Lebanon and the beginning of the security
zone. They entered through a huge white electronic gate into what
the soldiers simply call ``inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, just 70 yards inside the zone and only a few
hills away from where they entered, two fellow soldiers from a
different unit were killed by a Hezbollah-planted roadside bomb
hidden inside a fiberglass fake rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go inside, you have to forget about outside,'' said a
19-year-old sharpshooter with a rifle accurate up to 800 yards.
``You can't get distracted, not by anything. You stay focused. If
you don't, that's how you die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
