<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCEPTING THE NEW DEAL DID CONSERVATIVES A LOT OF GOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Barry Goldwater died, it was automatic for the
TV people to reach for the famous ad from the 1964 presidential
campaign, showing the little girl counting daisy petals before the
announcer counted down to a nuclear explosion.
</P>
<P>
   But I was surprised that no one showed another ad from Lyndon
Johnson's successful creative destroyers that year, featuring a
pair of hands ripping up a Social Security card.
</P>
<P>
   The first ad is part of our Cold War historical memories. The
other one, though, played with concepts and emotions that are hot
to this day.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad about the Bomb, foreshadowing the disgusting trends of
the next 30-plus years, the technique was to imply what not even
LBJ's hardball players dared directly allege _ that Goldwater would
produce a nuclear war. In the ad about Social Security,
foreshadowing another disgusting trend of outright distortion, the
explicit claim was made that Goldwater would ruin Social Security
and produce ``the end of widows' pensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Each ad, however, was made at least plausible _ and certainly
devastating because of its continual repetition in news coverage _
by Goldwater's own deserved reputation as a fundamentally
impulsive, even lazy, conservative with an equally deserved
reputation for shooting from the hip.
</P>
<P>
   He had said to reporters that the commander of NATO should have
authority to use tactical nuclear weapons, had opposed the treaty
banning nuclear tests in the atmosphere, and was himself the origin
of the interesting strategic doctrine of ``lobbing one'' into the
men's room of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Of more relevance to today's politics, he had also said to
reporters in Concord during the New Hampshire primary campaign in
'64 (which he lost to write-in Henry Cabot Lodge) that
contributions to Social Security should be voluntary and that if an
individual could make out better on his own, he should be free to
do so, but that if he prefers to have ``the government do it,''
fine.
</P>
<P>
   As his meticulous biographer and former aide Lee Edwards has
written, there was context for that answer _ Goldwater statements
going back several years. He had called Social Security
inadequately if not fraudulently funded, likely to become the major
tax ahead of the levy on income for most workers, and had called
for ``voluntary'' contributions on a phased-in basis so as not to
hurt anyone in the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater, however, never fully explained what he meant by
``voluntary,'' which left him open to doubts about his intentions.
Indeed, he validated those doubts a decade after his presidential
campaign, as Edwards also discloses. Following his reelection as
senator despite the Watergate landslide for the Democrats in 1974,
Goldwater wrote to his longtime adviser, the eminent conservative
economist Milton Friedman, that he thought the moment had come to
``advocate an end to Social Security,'' an idea Friedman quickly
got him to deep-six.
</P>
<P>
   The point here is that deep down, Goldwater's gut conservatism
did not accept, politically or substantively, the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Today's conservatives, having moved beyond that point
intellectually as well as politically, are in a much stronger
position. That is because they are seeking change by focusing on
the dangers to the system unless change occurs and by focusing on
the rate of return a worker can expect today from Social Security
compared with the return from the system they envision.
</P>
<P>
   What was called ``voluntary'' in Goldwater's day is now called
``privatization,'' only it really isn't. The typical proposal would
retain the tax on payroll that finances survivors' and disability
benefits; it would then give new workers the option of directing
the remaining eight percent of payroll (split with the employer) to
a ``personal'' retirement account that could be invested instead of
just placed in US Treasury debt.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to criticize this idea on a variety of fronts,
beginning with risk, but it is not possible to argue fairly that it
is a plan to ruin Social Security or threaten vulnerable retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The reason conservatism is strong today is not that Goldwater
paved the way so much as that conservatives learned from his huge
mistakes and made peace with FDR _ none more dramatically than an
old Democrat and Roosevelt-lover named Ronald Reagan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1521EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0388 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBERIA-COLA-COX- &UR; -$A     06-02 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBERIA-COLA-COX- </SLUG>
   -$ADV07 
 &HT;     REMOTE RUSSIA HOSTS A `CRAZY' COLA WAR
 &HT;     With photo to be placed in the International and Financial
folders on the Cox Server and are available from the New York Times
News Service.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 7 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRASNOYARSK, Russia _ A local beverage company in the heart of
Siberia may have lost its senses, but not its sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Challenging the production and marketing might of Atlanta-based
Coca-Cola Co. in this remote part Russia, the firm named its brand
Crazy Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows it is a joke to go against Coca-Cola. So we
called ours `Crazy Cola' in order to laugh at ourselves,'' said
Yevgenia Kuznetsova, president of Pikra, a Siberian beer and
soft-drinks manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Even crazier, she added, Crazy Cola is showing a slight profit
18 months after it was introduced, finding a small niche in a
domestic market increasingly keen to buy Russian-made goods.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's thirst for domination of the international
soft-drink market extends even to this desolate part of the world.
A new, $40 million Coca-Cola bottling plant, one of four opened in
Russia last year, stands at the edge of Krasnoyarsk, a regional
capital in Siberia, more than 2,000 miles east of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   According to company figures, Pikra soft drinks _ including
Crazy Cola, lemonade, mineral water and other products _ held a 58
percent share of the market in Siberia in 1997 compared with 23
percent for Pepsi and 18 percent for Coca-Cola. The company did not
disclose how the colas compare in head-to-head sales.
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to cite specific market data, Coca-Cola officials
acknowledge that they sold little of their product in Krasnoyarsk
before opening their local bottling facility, one of two in vast,
sparsely populated Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   In just a year, all that has changed, they said. ``In Siberia,
we are now Number One,'' claimed Coca-Cola spokesman Alexander
Chernov in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was long dominated by Pepsi-Cola, which cut a rare deal
with Soviet officials during the Cold War and gained a lock on the
massive market in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola entered Russia a decade later and, after the collapse
of the Soviet Union, became the most popular soft-drink throughout
Russia. It now has 12 bottling plants across Russia and claims a
more than 2-1 lead over nearest rival, Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pikra, a state-run beer producer in Soviet times and
now a private company, slipped into a corner of this battlefield
with the launch of Crazy Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, Pepsi and Crazy Cola all face some discouraging facts
about doing business in deepest Russia, however.
</P>
<P>
   At least six months of the year in Siberia, one of the chief
distribution problems is getting the cola to market before it
freezes solid.
</P>
<P>
   And, added Kuznetsova: ``Remember in this territory there are
more trees than people. And trees don't drink cola.''
</P>
<P>
   Pikra was until 1995 the local bottler for Pepsi. The
partnership was mutually terminated in the face of Coca-Cola's
growing share of the Russian market and Pikra's desire to branch
out into soft-drink production.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the need to give Coke a distinctly Russian
signature, Coca-Cola earlier this year introduced its first
television advertisements specifically for Russians, breaking with
the tradition of importing American TV ads to its international
markets. The series of 60-second commercials adapted a traditional
Russian fairy tale into a modern-day love story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has past when Russians would seek out and buy
anything with foreign labels. Now, Russians tend to buy Russian
products and things with a Russian flavor,'' said Kuznetsova.
</P>
<P>
   There is yet another local entry in the cola wars. A widely
popular soccer club in Moscow, Spartak, announced last week that it
would begin marketing its own cola.
</P>
<P>
   American and other Western producers are increasingly sensitive
to a potential backlash in the Russian market. American candy giant
Mars Inc. found itself the target of communist and nationalist
politicians who denounced the ``invasion'' by Western popular
culture following a TV ad blitz for their popular Snickers candy
bars.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Coca-Cola plans a public-relations blitz of its own to
publicize a newly signed deal with the city of Moscow: Coke will be
the exclusive cola of Moscow's famous Gorky Park.
</P>
<P>
   In Siberia, Kuznetsova suggests that Coca-Cola is gaining in the
market, but at a cost. The soft-drink giant is also losing money,
she says, as a result of aggressive promotions, product giveaways
and distribution of refrigeration display cases free to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never tried to fight them and we never will. We respect
them as a huge international company,'' Kuznetsova said of
Coca-Cola. ``We just follow our own path and try to find our piece
of the market.''
</P>
<P>
