<HEADER>
A0465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      06-02 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ESSENCE OF SHRIMP  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The juices that foods exude as they're cooking are often lost in
the shuffle, especially when that shuffle takes place on the grill.
For years I never realized that one of the greatest assets of my
spicy grilled shrimp was just sputtering away on those hot coals.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I planned to produce this dish, however, it rained
so hard I was forced to resort to the broiler. It was then that I
remembered why broiled shrimp are so desirable: you get to savor
the juices, the essences, produced by the shrimp itself. This is
also true of shrimp that are sauteed, roasted or, for that matter,
steamed in aluminum foil or poached in a stew.
</P>
<P>
   Normally I serve spicy grilled shrimp on the skewers I cook them
on. But given the presence of the liquid and the time of year, the
dish cried for a bed of greens. Not wanting to overwhelm delicately
flavored greens with the spiced shrimp, I used a mixture of arugula
and lettuce, with a generous amount of mint, and dressed it with
olive oil and lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   You can take this dish in many directions. The shrimp can be
grilled instead of broiled, and the salad can be eliminated. With
its lively flavor and lovely color _ contributed by paprika _ the
shrimp also make a great starter or finger food. The salad can be
seasoned with cilantro, parsley, basil, chervil or dill, in roughly
the same amount as the mint. Vinegar can replace the lemon juice,
or peanut oil can be substituted for olive oil. Finally, a
tablespoon or two of soy or fish sauce can be added to the salad
before tossing it, and lime juice can sit in for lemon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPICY SHRIMP SALAD WITH MINT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Time: 20 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds shrimp in the 15-to-30-a-pound range, peeled (deveined,
if you like)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon cayenne, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plus 2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   30 to 40 mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   6 cups arugula and other greens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat broiler; adjust the rack, moving it as close to the
heat source as possible. Place a large ovenproof skillet or
thick-bottomed roasting pan on the stove over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine the shrimp with garlic, salt, cayenne, paprika, half
the olive oil and the 2 teaspoons of lemon juice; stir to blend.
Turn heat under the skillet to high.
</P>
<P>
   3. When skillet smokes, toss in shrimp. Shake the pan once or
twice to distribute them evenly, then immediately place skillet in
the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   4. Mince about one-third of the mint, and set aside. Tear
remaining leaves, and toss them with the arugula. Stir remaining
olive oil and lemon juice together in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   5. The shrimp are done when opaque, usually 3 to 4 minutes. Use
a slotted spoon to transfer them to a plate; it is fine if they
cool for a moment. Add shrimp juices to olive oil-lemon juice
mixture, and stir. Dress the greens with this mixture, and toss; if
the greens seem dry, add a little more olive oil or lemon juice, or
both. Place greens on a platter, and arrange shrimp on top or
around them; garnish shrimp with the remaining minced mint.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
