<HEADLINE>
TURN THE PAGE ON SUMMER DAYS WITH COOL NEW BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Here come the months of summer, when in theory you
dig your toes into the sand and pay attention to all those books
you've ignored for too long. This is a partial list of titles that
are in stores now, or will be before the pavement starts to
sizzle. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Novels good for you: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cities of the Plain'' by Cormac McCarthy (Knopf, $24). The
third novel in McCarthy's ``Border Trilogy'' brings together John
Grady Cole, the young protagonist of ``All the Pretty Horses,'' and
Billy Parham, hero of ``The Crossing,'' in a fina l story of the
West as it once was and never will be again. John Grady again falls
in love with a Mexican girl, but unlike the aristocratic young
woman of ``All the Pretty Horses,'' this one is a prostitute with
an evil pimp, and nothing good can co me of it. Like the previous
books, this has adventure, romance, stoicism, the sadness of one
era giving way to another and, ultimately, violence as only Cormac
McCarthy can portray it.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Widow for One Year'' by John Irving (Random House, $2
7.95). This book is full of writers, and although it's sometimes
bizarre and self-indulgent (in 537 pages, there's room for that),
it's Irving's best since ``The World According to Garp.'' Told in
three parts is the story of Ruth Cole, who was con ceived by her
wounded parents as a replacement for two brothers killed in a
ghastly automobile accident. The tragedy of a lost child _ indeed,
of lost boys _ is something Irving has grappled with before, but in
building upon its ramifications for Ru th he creates a sympathetic
tale. Someone once said that we tell stories to exorcise our
terrifying lives. Perhaps because he believes that, Irving tells
his stories fiercely and with considerable bravado. As Barbara
Kingsolver wrote for the Washing ton Post, ``His characters can
beguile us onto thin ice and persuade us to dance there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Freedomland'' by Richard Price (Broadway, $25). Screenwriter
Price (``Sea of Love,'' ``The Color of Money'') places this novel
in the same New Jersey setting as his last, ``Clockers,'' but
borrows its premise from the terrible South Carolina case of Susan
Smith and her murdered little boys. A White woman appears, bloodied
and stunned, in a hospital emergency room and announces that a
Black man ha s stolen her car with her young son in the back seat.
Her claim launches a search, both for the boy and for the truth, by
two characters with very different motivations: a reporter in
pursuit of the story, and the decent police detective who must co
ntend with festering racial tensions and threatened violence in the
projects near where the carjacking occurred. This novel is big,
cinematic and provocative, both a mystery and a reflection of the
great racial divide in this country, and the hope lessness that it
breeds. &QL; 
 &QL; 
These will endure: &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ ``The Time of Our Time'' by Norman Mailer (Random House, $39.50).
Fifty years and 1,300 pages of Norman Mailer, edited by Norman
Mailer. Includes excerpts from novels and major nonfiction works s
uch as ``The Executioner's Song,'' as well as poems, interviews and
odd writings that seem to be dropped here out of nowhere. There's
no accounting for the mix (except to say that the editor's ego is
no small thing), but it's worth wading throughthe silly stuff to
get to Mailer at his best.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I Know This Much Is True'' by Wally Lamb
(ReganHarperCollins, $27.50). Lamb's first novel, ``She's Come
Undone,'' got the nod from Oprah Winfrey's book club. We wonder if
Oprah will read this one . It is 897 pages long, enough to send
many readers staggering off in search of more manageable books. But
while this could have been shorter, it has much to recommend it. It
is a sad but also darkly funny family saga told through the eyes of
a be leaguered soul named Dominick Birdsey, identical twin of
Thomas, a paranoid schizophrenic. Dominick looks back on how their
family's past made him and his brother what they are. His love for
Thomas and his sense of responsibility toward him are at o dds with
his resentment over his brother's hold on his life. It's an
affecting story, proof that good things come in big packages, too. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trashy novels: &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ ``Belladonna'' by Karen Moline (Warner, $25). Harold Robbins
meets ``The Story of O.''
</P>
<P>
   An innocent young woman goes to London in 1935 and is kidnapped
by a secret sex club, auctioned to the highest bidder and subjected
to years of raunchy treatment before she escapes and seeks revenge.
This is deeply trashy, and it's selling like ice
</P>
<P>
   cream in July.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Student Body'' by Jane Harvard (Villard, $23). Harold
Robbins meets higher education. A Harvard University student,
covering a story for the Harvard Crimson, stumbles upon a student
prostitution ring and embarks on an in vestigation that involves
sex, sex and much more sex. This was co-written, badly, by four
Harvard graduates who wanted to make money to pay off their student
loans. Their intentions were good, but their book is . . . (begin
ital) trashy. (end ital) We suspect that Harvard is more crimson
than usual. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nonfiction &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ ``Here But Not Here'' by Lillian Ross (Random House, $25). Ross,
longtime writer for the ``New Yorker,'' offers a worshipful account
of her affair with the magazine's editor, W illiam Shawn. The two
took an apartment together in 1958 with the full knowledge of
Shawn's wife, Cecille (with whom he continued to live a half-mile
away), and shared it until Shawn's death in 1992. There are some
behind-the-scenes stories about th e magazine, with mention of
friends like Joseph Mitchell and A.J. Liebling, and some of the
celebrities Ross interviewed in the old days (John Huston, Ernest
Hemingway). But mostly she writes about Shawn, her relationship
with him, her early attem pts to separate from him, and her
devotion to him when she realized she could not leave. She loved
him very much, and still does.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Monk Swimming'' by Malachy McCourt (Hyperion, $23.95).
Frank McCourt (``Angela's Ashes'') sent for his younger
</P>
<P>
   brother, Malachy, three years after he himself came to the
United States. In Ireland, Malachy had left school at 13 and was
considered, he writes, ``a dunce, doomed, (begin itals) doomed (end
itals) to mendicancy, criminality, or worse, manual labo r to the
end of my natural days.'' In America, he drank a lot, played hard
and became an actor. This memoir of the first decade in his new
life is true Irish storytelling _ ribald, raucous and funny.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Tender at the Bone'' by Ruth Reichl (Ran dom House, $23).
Reichl has a flair for storytelling and admits to making ``minor
adjustments of fact'' because she finds it preferable to boring her
audience. That makes for a pretty engaging memoir. Since Reichl is
the restaurant critic for the Ne w York Times, you'll be surprised
to know that she comes from a family of non-cooking women,
including her mother, who was a manic-depressive. We hear about
them early in the book, and about how food became young Ruth's way
of making herself feel important, but the real pleasure comes
later, when she begins her education (with several mentors) in the
world of international food and the restaurants that serve it. She
reaches only young adulthood here _ her adventures on behalf of the
Times wi ll have to wait for future installments. But she includes
many recipes, and, in the tradition of restaurant critics, remains
incognito: There is no author photo anywhere. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Other fiction &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ ``My Heart Laid Bare'' by Joyce Carol Oates (Dutton, $ 26.95). A
historical novel that follows a family of con artists from Colonial
times to the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Murder on Deck!'' edited by Rosemary Herbert (Oxford, $25).
Shipboard and shoreline mystery stories by Agatha Christie, Arthur
Conan Doyle, Wi lliam Faulkner, Ellery Queen, Gabriel Garcia
Marquez and others.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``L.A. Noir'' by James Ellroy (Mysterious, $25). Three early
novels by the author of ``American Tabloid'' and ``My Dark
Places.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mothers &AMP; Daughters'' (Signet, $14.95). A
</P>
<P>
   collection of original stories written by famous mothers in
collaboration with their daughters, including one by Diana Gabaldon
and her daughter, 15-year-old Laura J. Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Sunset Limited'' by James Lee Burke (Doubleday, $24.95).
Detecti ve Dave Robicheaux in a story of racial violence and class
warfare.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Five Fortunes'' by Beth Gutcheon (HarperCollins, $24). Five
women from different backgrounds become friends when they meet at
an Arizona health spa.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Now It's Tim e to Say Goodbye'' by Dale Peck (FSG, $25).
Harrowing thriller built around racial tensions, a series of
murders and the abduction of a teenage girl in a small, Kansas
town.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Almost Home'' by T.M. McNally (Scribner, $22). Set in
Paradise Valle y, Ariz., and its surroundings, the story of the
relationship between a teenage boy and girl during a troubled year
in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Overseer'' by Jonathan Rabb (Crown, $24). The murder of
a young girl in Montana resurrects suspicions o f a master plan for
world domination created by a 16th-century monk. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Other nonfiction &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ ``My Secret Mother Lorna Moon'' by Richard de Mille (FSG, $25).
DeMille's memoir of his true parents and his upbringing by his
adoptive parents, CecilB. de Mille and his wife, Constance, amid
the glamour and luxury of early Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Greatest Benefit to Mankind'' by Ray Porter (Norton,
$35). An exploration of medicine's evolution against the backdrop
of wider religious, scientific, philosophical and political
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Granite and Rainbow: The Hidden Life of Virginia Woolf'' by
Mitchell Leaska (FSG, $35). An examination of the life and
controversies of the author.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Titan'' by Ron Chernow (Random House, $30). A bi ography of
John D. Rockefeller Sr. by the author of ``The House of Morgan''
and ``The Warburgs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Muhammad Ali Reader,'' edited by Gerald Early (Ecco,
$26). Writings on Ali by Tom Wolfe, LeRoi Jones, Pete Hamill, Roger
Kahn, Garry Wills , Hunter S. Thompson, Joyce Carol Oates, Gay
Talese and others.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``God Is My Broker'' by Christopher Buckley and John Tierney
(Random House, $20). A very funny parody of investment tactics,
self-help books and the hierarchy of the Catholic chu rch.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Online Seductions'' by Esther Gwinnell (Kodansha, $23). A
psychiatrist examines the growing phenomenon of romance over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Country Life: A Handbook for Realists and Dreamers'' by Paul
Heiney (DK, $24.95). A well-illu strated primer for becoming a
country farmer even if you're tied to the city.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Kenneth Tynan: Letters,'' edited by Kathleen Tynan (Random
House, $30). Letters by the drama critic to the likes of Marlene
Dietrich, Tennessee Williams, Mary McC arthy and John Lennon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
