<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAT THE HEAT WITH THIS COOL READING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An adorable little pig with a penchant for pancakes, and an emu
that longs to be someone else are among this month's new offerings
for preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   Light summer novels and an inspirational book for girls in early
adolescence are on tap for older children. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; EDWARD THE EMU &QL; 
 &UR; Sheena Knowles; illust rated by Rod Clement (HarperTrophy, $6.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``Edward the emu was sick of the zoo, / There was nowhere to go,
there was nothing to do, / And compared to the seals that lived
right next door, / Well being an emu was frankly a bore.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward
</P>
<P>
   tries out life as a seal, a lion and a snake before discovering
that being an emu isn't so bad, especially when there's a new girl
emu waiting back at the pen. Clement's drawings of the goofy,
red-eyed birds make the book. For ages 3-6. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; IT'S GOING TO BE PERFECT! &QL; 
 &UR; Nancy Carlson (Viking, $15.99)
</P>
<P>
   Ahhhh, motherhood . . . cooing babies who sleep through the
night, toddlers who love potty training, relaxing restaurant meals
in the company of admiring strangers, preschoolers who can't wa it
to leave home for their classrooms. Think again. With a shift in
perspective, reality can be wonderful, too. It's tranquil at 3
a.m., the word ``no'' isn't so bad if Junior's second favorite word
is ``mama,'' picnics are better than restaurants , and parting is
sweetened by reunion. This is an ideal gift for new mothers.
Preschoolers also will enjoy the jokes. For ages 3-6. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; IF YOU GIVE A PIG A PANCAKE &QL; 
 &UR; Laura Numeroff; illustrated by Felicia Bond (HarperCollins, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you g ive a pig a pancake, she'll want some syrup to go
with it. You'll give her some of your favorite maple syrup. She'll
probably get all sticky, so she'll want to take a bath. She'll ask
you for some bubbles. When you give her the bubbles, she'll proba
bly ask you for a toy. . .''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning of it all. A mischievous pig with
all the whims of a toddler keeps a little girl very, very busy.
Children will howl with delight at their escapades. For ages 3-6. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; YOU'RE NOT MY BEST FRIEND ANYMORE &QL; 
 &UR; Charlotte Pomerantz; illustrated by David Soman (Dial, $15.99)
</P>
<P>
   Every child goes through the first-time pain of strained
friendship. In this story, Molly and Ben are buddies until they
have a disagreement about which tent t o get for a backyard
camp-out. Then the relationship is off. They write in their diaries
about how much they hate each other, refuse to speak to one
another, and go miles out of their way to avoid one another. A dual
birthday party for the two draws
</P>
<P>
   them back together, with each surprising the other with the
ideal present. For ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MY SECRET GARDEN &QL; 
 &UR; Frances Hodgson Burnett; illustrated by Mary Collier ($12.95)
</P>
<P>
   The 1912 novel has been adapted for young readers, who will be
enchan ted by the mystery of the secret garden. Mary Lennox,
orphaned and lonely, comes to live at her uncle's empty mansion.
She ventures into a locked, abandoned garden and is rewarded by the
joy of good friends and making things grow. Collier's realis tic
paintings artfully depict the scenes. For ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ANIMAL SENSES &QL; 
 &UR; Pamela Hickman; illustrated by Pat Stephens (Kids Can Press,
$14.95)
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that a cricket's ears are on its legs? That an
octopus smells and tastes with its tent acles? That nocturnal
animals are colorblind? Amazing facts about how animals perceive
the world around them are collected in this book, which also
contains experiments that teach kids firsthand about animal senses.
For ages 7-10. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AGAINST THE ODDS &QL; 
 &UR; Joe Layden (Scholastic, $3.99)
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller wore braces on his legs when he was young. Alonzo
Mourning grew up in a series of foster homes. Chris Mullin is a
recovering alcoholic. Nick Anderson grew up in the ghetto. The
inspiring stori es of eight National Basketball Association
champions are told in this quick-read by Layden, author of more
than a dozen sports books for children. Game photographs and career
statistics are included. For ages 7-10. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; POPPY AND RYE: A Tale from Dimwood Forest &QL; 
 &UR; Avi; illustrated by Brian Floca (Avon, $14)
</P>
<P>
   Mourning the death of her fiance, a little deer mouse named
Poppy treks across the Dimwood Forest with her irascible porcupine
friend, Ereth, to break the bad news to her fiance's fam ily. Along
the way she meets a mysterious stranger who turns out to be her
boyfriend's younger brother, Rye. Together, Poppy and Rye face
danger and adventure.
</P>
<P>
   When they come across a company of eager beavers that plans to
build an underwater condominium project that will force smaller
animals out of their homes, Poppy champions the little guys' cause.
Poppy and Rye are drawn together during the showdown. With tongue
in cheek, the prolific author known simply as Avi penned this
sequel to
</P>
<P>
   the nationally acclaimed ``Poppy.'' For ages 8-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TROUT SUMMER &QL; 
 &UR; Jane Leslie Conly ($4.50, Scholastic)
</P>
<P>
   Their parents' separation brings 13-year-old Shana and her
younger brother, Cody, to a summer cabin on the Leanna River, where
their mom hopes to restore a sense of stability. The tranquillity
is threatened by an ornery old man named Henry, a self-appointed
steward of the river, who forces Shana and Cody to face some
difficult issues. The conflict culminates with a dangerous ri de on
the Leanna's wild rapids. This is a good summer book for middle
readers, particularly those grappling with their parents' divorce.
For ages 9-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FOR GIRLS ONLY: Wise Words, Good Advice &QL; 
 &UR; Carol Weston (Avon, $5.99)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your pretee n daughter won't listen to you, but how about
listening to Oprah, Maya Angelou, Seinfeld, Dr. Seuss, Martin
Luther King Jr. _ or Tom Cruise, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Weston, who writes a teen advice column and is the author of
four other books, addresses the topics of self, friendship, family,
love, school and work. She begins each page with a quote, writes a
one-page essay on the topic and closes with her own one-sentence
summary. Excellent guidance is dispensed in an easily digestible
format. For ages
</P>
<P>
   10-13. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; DETECTIVE STORIES &QL; 
 &UR; Chosen by Philip Pullman (Kingfisher, $6.95)
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like a good detective story to while away summer
days. The best of the genre is represented in this collection by
Agatha Christie, Isaac Asimov, Elle ry Queen, Sir Arthur Conan
Doyle and others. The crimes range from coldblooded murder to a
dog-kidnapping in settings that include an ancient Egyptian tomb, a
sinister English country house and the streets of New York. Curl up
and get scared! For ag es 12 and up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Beverly Medlyn receives e-mail at bevmedlyn(at)aol.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
