<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; L.A. NOIR &QL; 
 &UR; James Ellroy (Mysterious, $25)
</P>
<P>
   This is what comes with success _ your old books get new
attention. Ellroy has had much success in recent years with his
novel ``American Tabloid''; his memoir, ``My Dark Places''; and
with the film version of
</P>
<P>
   his earlier book, ``L.A. Confidential.'' The three novels
published here were written in the early 1980s. They feature Los
Angeles homicide Detective Lloyd Hopkins, who is prone to violence,
cheats on his wife, and has what his partner calls ``th e supreme
police intellect.'' In other words, Hopkins solves crimes. In
``Blood on the Moon,'' he goes after a serial sex killer. In
``Because the Night,'' he uncovers a link between a multiple murder
and the disappearance of a heroic cop. In ``Suic ide Hill,'' he
finds corruption in the Los Angeles Police Department in the
aftermath of a kidnapping. Ellroy wrote the first book in 1980,
then read Thomas Harris' ``Red Dragon'' and decided that it was
``the greatest suspense novel ever written.''
</P>
<P>
   He was inspired to write two more books because, he says, he
``wanted another shot at making Lloyd Hopkins as great a character
as Thomas Harris' Will Graham.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ROLLING STONE: The Complete Covers 1967-1997 &QL; 
 &UR; (Abrams, $39.95)
</P>
<P>
   There ar e some things we would like to forget. One of them is
that Tiny Tim appeared on the cover of ``Rolling Stone.'' So did
David Cassidy, Karen and Richard Carpenter, the women of ``Melrose
Place,'' O.J. Simpson (with a story called ``The Juice: A Man f or
All Seasons'') and, in 1971, Tricia Nixon, all blond and beatific,
three years before her father appeared on the cover under the words
``The Quitter.'' But there ends the bad news. Every other cover in
this book _ and there are 30 years' worth _ is just great;
irresistible, in fact. Collectively, they are a record of the most
memorable personalities of three decades, many of whom were shrewd
enough to collaborate with ``Rolling Stone'' photographers
(including Annie Leibovitz, Richard Ave don and Herb Ritts) in
manipulating their own public images. Of those who turn up more
than once, Mick Jagger is the record-holder with 19 covers. It's
great fun, introduced by the magazine's founder, Jann S. Wenner. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SPOILED &QL; 
 &UR; Nicols Fox (Pen guin, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   Do you want to know any of this? Can you afford not to?
Journalist Fox became curious about food-borne diseases in 1993,
when several children on the West Coast died after eating fast-food
hamburgers. She began with a mental sc enario right out of a
science-fiction novel: Could genetic researchers be creating new
strains of bacteria that will contaminate our food supply, harming
thousands of people? Her research taught her something more
disturbing _ that pathogens indeed could infiltrate our foods, but,
Fox says, ``not by intentional manipulation on the part of a few
malevolent or careless scientists, but by unintentional and
uncoordinated shifts in our relationship to what we eat.'' This is
the sobering story of a system out of balance, ``of change,'' Fox
says, ``and the doors it opens to disease.'' She ends with a few
suggestions for cooking and eating safely in your home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TREASURES OF THE BASEBALL HALL OF FAME &QL; 
 &UR; John Thorn (Villard, $39.95)
</P>
<P>
   Her e are Christy Mathewson's Bible and his checkers. Shoeless
Joe's shoes. The ball that Cy Young pitched for his 500th win on
July 1, 1910 (on his way to his immortal record, 511). A ticket
stub from the Lou Gehrig memorial on July 4, 1941, and the sh
ooting script for ``Pride of the Yankees.'' A letter written by
John F. Kennedy asking for Jackie Robinson's support in the 1960
presidential campaign (Robinson backed Richard Nixon). The bat with
which Willie Mays got his 3,000th hit, the glove he used to make
``The Catch.'' There are lots of elegant photographs here, lots of
wonderful stuff, but no captions. What were they thinking? You must
look for everything in Thorn's text, which is a nuisance, and later
you must squint as you try to r ead a minuscule reproduction of the
letter from the Mayo Clinic that ended Gehrig's career, or the
polite note written by Babe Ruth to Yankee general manager George
Weiss thanking him for the ceremony that marked his farewell to the
game. It's a han dsome book, but more frustrating than it should
be. With a sweet foreword by Ted Williams. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ROME: Oxford Archaeological Guides &QL; 
 &UR; Amanda Claridge (Oxford, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   This handsome (if decidedly formal in tone) guide begins with a
historical overview of ancient Rome and a glossary of building
materials and techniques, architectural orders and major public
works. Claridge proceeds through the city's major archaeological
sites, offering maps, diagrams, historical background, travel
advice
</P>
<P>
   and museum information. Included are the Roman Forum; the Upper
Via Sacra; the Palatine; the Imperial Forums; the Campus Martius;
the Capitoline hill; Circus Flaminius to Circus Maximus; the
Colosseum valley and Esquiline hill; the Caelian hill and
</P>
<P>
   the Via Appia. This is one of four new books in a series.
Available are archaeological guides to Scotland, Spain and the Holy
Land. Future books will cover Egypt, western Turkey, southern
France, England, Crete, Greece, Ireland and North Africa. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
