<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN A RASPBERRY REALLY HURT A COW?  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Wash., Ohio)   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To date, no vegetables have filed any of the so-called veggie
libel lawsuits. The only cases so far have been brought on behalf
of cattle, eggs, lawns and emus.
</P>
<P>
   Food disparagement laws, as they are more formally known, are
intended to protect perishable agricultural products from false and
disparaging statements and to make it easier for growers and
distributors to sue anyone who says anything bad about their
products.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous of the veggie libel suits is the one brought by
Texas cattlemen in federal court against Oprah Winfrey, who swore
off hamburgers on the air after a segment about mad cow disease.
They blamed the comment for a drop in cattle prices. The cattlemen
lost, but are appealing the decision.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, such suits sound silly. The lawn suit, for
example, involved a Texas agricultural agent who issued a report
critical of the sod made by a particular company. The case was
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that emu ranchers would sue Honda for casting
aspersions on emus in a commercial may make most people smile. But
this is no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to repeal the food disparagement laws that exist in
13 states and to discourage other states from enacting them, 26
organizations have formed the Foodspeak Coalition, with
headquarters in Washington. They include not only groups associated
with First Amendment advocacy, like the American Civil Liberties
Union and the Society of Professional Journalists, but also the
Humane Society, the United Farm Workers, Public Citizen and the
Center for Science in the Public Interest.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Collins, director of the coalition, said no other
industry benefits from such laws, which grew out of a lawsuit
brought by Washington State apple growers in 1989 against CBS over
a ``60 Minutes'' segment. The apple growers charged that the
program had defamed their product when it said the apples were
unsafe to eat because they had been sprayed with Alar, a chemical
used in fruit ripening. The apple market dropped sharply, and the
growers sued.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was dismissed by a federal judge, who said it violated
no existing law. The response of agribusiness was to present state
legislatures with the draft of a model act and to lobby hard for
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``These laws did not spring up spontaneously,'' said David
Bederman, a professor of law at Emory University in Atlanta and an
expert in food libel issues. ``It's a classic instance of big
business seeking to insulate itself from criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dave Kelly, assistant director of news services for the
American Farm Bureau, a lobbying group, said that even though he
supports free speech, such laws are needed because ``reckless
comments'' have hurt producers and shouldn't be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Glasser, executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union, countered that the First Amendment protects even those who
say things that are not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``If false statements were prohibited by law, there would not be
a politician who would escape a lawsuit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oprah Winfrey case, the judge ruled that live cattle were
not a perishable agricultural product and so did not fit the Texas
law. The judge added that even if beef on the hoof were covered,
she did not believe that the statements made on the show were
disparaging or knowingly false.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas court decision is of no comfort to the Public
Interest Research Group chapter in Ohio, which sued Buckeye Egg
Farm of Cronton, Ohio, for consumer fraud for rewashing and
repackaging eggs after the expiration date and redating them. In
announcing the suit, Amy Simpson, the state director, said, ``We
have no idea how many, if any, have been made ill from these
eggs.'' Buckeye sued the group, claiming that statement hurt its
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Simpson said she considered Buckeye's suit ``a form of
intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger King, the lawyer for Buckeye Farm, maintained, ``You have
to balance the harm that media sound bites can have on agricultural
producers.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, technicalities have prevented a true test case of these
state laws from going to a jury. ``Frankly, I don't think this is a
good test case,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   To the consumer advocate Ralph Nader, the object of such suits
is not money. ``It is to send a chilling message to millions of
people,'' he said, ``that they better keep their opinions to
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
