<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0478 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BALLAD-AZR &LR;      06-02 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BALLAD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPALACHIAN TALE WEAVES FACT, FICTION  
 
THE BALLAD OF FRANKIE SILVER
</HEADLINE>
  Sharyn McCrumb (Dutton, $23.95) 
 
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUE DOERFLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1833 in Mitchell County, N.C., Frankie Silver was hanged for
killing her husband, who by all accounts, was not the best husband.
She went to the grave with a secret, a mystery that people have
tried to figure out for years hence.
</P>
<P>
   Was she really guilty? Was she shielding someone else who
committed the crime? What did her father not want her to tell when
he shouted at her, ``Die with it in you, Frankie,'' when she
attempted to talk at the gallows?
</P>
<P>
   The mountain girl became a legend, one that Sharyn McCrumb has
taken and woven into a colorful intrigue of fact, fiction, history
and the present in ``The Ballad of Frankie Silver.''
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian lore is a specialty of McCrumb, who lives in a small
town in the
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Blue Ridge Mountains but grew up in North Carolina,
where her ancestors had lived since 1790. Her great-grandfathers
were circuit preachers in North Carolina's Smoky Mountains, riding
over the mountains to preach in a different church each
</P>
<P>
   Sunday. McCrumb grew up hearing stories, legends and folklore of
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on her expertise, the author, known for her mysteries
featuring forensic anthropologist Elizabeth MacPherson and
science-fiction satires featuring Jay Omega, b egan an Appalachian
series with the publication of ``If Ever I Return, Pretty Peggy-O''
in 1990. ``Frankie Silver'' is the fifth in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``My books are like Appalachian quilts,'' McCrumb says. ``I take
brightly colored scraps of legends , ballads and fragments of rural
life and local tragedy and I piece them together into a complex
whole that tells not only a story but also a deeper truth about the
culture of the mountain South.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankie Silver'' is told in alternating voi ces, with McCrumb
drawing a parallel between the Silver legend and a fictional,
modern-day event.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Sheriff Spencer Arrowood is invited to witness the
execution of a man named Fate Harkryder, who was convicted of
killing some hikers alon g the Appalachian Trail 20 years before.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation leaves him pensive: At the time of the
conviction, he was convinced of the man's guilt. Now, he's not so
sure, remembering a comment of the former sheriff, ``These
mountains have produced
</P>
<P>
   only two murder cases that make me wonder about justice: Frankie
Silver and Fate Harkryder.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrowood investigates both events, determined to discover the
truth. What he discovers leaves him with a sense of completion but
not justice. The en ding leaves much cause for thought on the part
of the reader.
</P>
<P>
   McCrumb became interested as a child in the legend of Frankie
Silver and decided to pursue it for a novel in 1992, when she
visited Charlie Silver's grave site in Kona, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Vag uely connected to the Silver family through ancestral
marriages, McCrumb spent a lot of time researching historical
events, old newspaper articles and collections of old letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I began researching the life and death of Frankie Silver,
I
</P>
<P>
   thought I was looking into a fascinating riddle concerning a
long-ago murder on the frontier. . .,'' McCrumb writes in the book.
But as she looked into the story, she found the situation really
was about the poor versus the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I conclude d that Frankie Silver had much to tell us about
equal justice under the law, and that not much has changed since
she went to her death on a bright July afternoon 164 years ago.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
