<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PALE-ALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LUSTY PALE ALE WITH A LONG FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The initials IPA may be the most mysterious three
letters in the world of beer. The letters, which appear on every
label of Bass, stand for India Pale Ale, and they designate a style
of beer that is neither pale nor Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it was developed for the Indian export market in the
English brewing city of Burton-on-Trent, whose copper- or
russet-colored ales were pale by comparison with brown ale or
porter.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that the beer would survive the long sea voyage
without souring, it was brewed to a high alcohol content, as much
as 9 percent by volume, and heavily hopped. Full-bodied, dry and
refreshing, India pale ale gained favor all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Heartland Brewery, which is located on Union Square West and
recently opened an outpost in midtown (1285 Avenue of the Americas,
at 51st Street), makes a particularly fine example of the style,
which it has dubbed Indiana Pale Ale.
</P>
<P>
   Most American pale ales, trying to clone the very hoppy, flowery
Sierra Nevada Pale Ale, wind up with an excessively bitter drink
lacking in body and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Heartland's brewmaster, Jim Migliorini, has brought all the
right elements into balance, creating a clean, coppery ale, with an
assertive hoppy bite; a rich, malty flavor, and a long, lingering
finish with hazelnut overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Sold at $4.75 a pint, it combines the thirst-quenching qualities
of a German or Czech lager with the mouth-filling flavor of good
British beer. Not a bad deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
