A0483 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     06-02 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE AIRLINES LEARN SAFETY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BETSY WADE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 40 trainers and teachers in the airline industry went to a
Federal Aviation Administration safety workshop in Oklahoma City
last month, their concerns ranged from whether eating too many
poppy-seed bagels would cause them to fail random drug tests (not
the new tests, said Dr. Dennis Canfield, a toxicology instructor),
to how to get passengers out of a sinking or burning plane fastest.
</P>
<P>
   These flight attendants also discussed the problem of difficult
passengers, and the participants floated in a swimming pool
designed for testing water-survival equipment and techniques for
the rare occasions when they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   American and Canadian airline employees must undergo periodic
retraining in all phases of cabin procedure, so the videotapes and
news films of planes sinking, skidding off the runway or bursting
into flames did not alarm the students. But the class, at the Civil
Aeromedical Institute in Oklahoma City, was not calm when the
instructor showed tapes of tests with electronically wired crash
dummies mounted on sleds in the laboratory downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   These tapes were run in stop-motion to demonstrate the effect of
a crash on 170-pound adults in airline seats, and on children in
various types of safety seats and harnesses that have subsequently
been disapproved for use on airlines. When the dummies flailed,
struck the airline seat in front, slid down and out of a belt or
flew right off the seat, the airline employees gasped. This was not
something they had seen unless they had experienced extreme
turbulence or been through a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Such events _ and, for that matter, evacuations _ are rarities.
Federal figures show that from Jan. 1, 1996, to June 1, 1998, there
were seven evacuations from planes of the major U.S. airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the anomaly that children under 2 are the only
passengers not required by law to be restrained in seats for
takeoff and landing, Van Gowdy, team coordinator of biodynamics
research at the institute, told the class: ``Everybody sitting on
that airplane should have an equivalent level of protection. If I
could do one thing in my career, it would be to get children off
the laps of adults during takeoff and landing.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory part of the FAA, which has so far rejected
appeals to keep children under 2 from riding in adults' laps, where
they cannot be belted in, has been gathering comments on this issue
since February. It may propose a rule on this later, Alison
Duquette, a spokeswoman for the agency in Washington, said. Agency
spokesmen say letters opposing a rule assert that buying a ticket
for a young child raises the cost of air travel for a family. When
urged to enact a rule, the agency has said it might mean parents
would decide it is cheaper to travel by car, which is less safe
than air travel.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day cabin-safety workshops are offered free a few times
a year to instructors of flight attendants, trainers, union
representatives and other people involved in aircraft cabin safety.
I went to observe and participate in the evacuation drills, joining
employees from Air Canada, America West, American, American Eagle,
Boeing, British Airways, Continental, Delta, United, US Airways,
UPS Airlines, Westjet of Canada, two flight attendants' unions and
some smaller organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Donell W. Pollard, cabin-safety-program manager of the FAA, who
designed the workshops, said the goal is free exchange of
information, and the air was thick with insider talk. For example,
instructors noted the intense training they give on how to shout
instructions in an emergency. This sort of repetition means that
automatic responses kick in.
</P>
<P>
   A vital element in these orders is the avoiding of negative
terms: attendants are taught to say, ``Release your seat belt and
come this way,'' not, ``Unfasten your seat belt,'' because of the
possibility that the ``un'' syllable will be lost. ``Leave your
baggage behind'' is preferred over ``Don't take your baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   Students said they wished they got better attention from the
passengers while giving safety instructions, but the teachers said
passengers who thought they knew everything were probably still
picking up information subconsciously. One problem often cited was
the instinct of passengers to exit the way they came in, even in an
emergency; few passengers turn to use an exit behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pollard listed 10 topics for discussion by small student
groups, ranging from evacuations and cabin fires to problems with
carry-on bags, passenger interference with crew members and
``passenger seat-belt discipline.'' Many of these problems are part
of an FAA safety drive.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there was frequent consideration of how to
eliminate excess carry-on bags and the resulting choked aisles and
heavily laden bins. The participants agreed that getting excess
bags checked before boarding worked better than trying to carry
bags out through the narrow aisles later. But the trainers said
that the gate agents pushed the problem down the line to the flight
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of several airlines mentioned new, tighter rules on
carry-ons. Ms. Pollard said that the agency was pleased at these
voluntary steps, but added that it was the many exceptions to the
limiting of passengers to one or two carry-on bags ``that get us
into trouble.'' Right now, the federal regulation says only that
airlines must create rules to get luggage ``properly stowed''
before takeoff and have these rules approved by the agency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pollard said a surprising number of passengers wrote the
agency to request industrywide carry-on rules to keep ``too many
and too large'' bags out of the cabin. ``We still may write a
regulation,'' she said, ``but it will take three to five years.''
Meantime, according to participants in the workshop, more than one
airline is asking designers for bigger luggage bins in the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Two exercises were carried out, one an evacuation down a slide
to the ground from a fuselage filled with theatrical smoke, and the
other a jump from a shortened wing into water while wearing a life
vest.
</P>
<P>
   For the first, we were told to wear lace-up shoes and
long-sleeved shirts in natural fibers. There was no speed
requirement, as there is when research on new slides or other
equipment is carried out. We walked in heavy smoke to the rear, up
and down steps built in the fuselage, then up the aisle, which
inclined upward. Vertigo gave several of us a sense that the
fuselage was unsteady.
</P>
<P>
   At the emergency exit, we were to fold our arms and jump out
onto the slide, landing on our backsides and sliding down. Having
done this nine years ago, I did not find it difficult, and slid
easily. A videotape showed uneven results. A synthetic shirt
created a sort of mat burn on one student's back. Several others
flung themselves out too far. Some followed the previous student
too closely and they clumped at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants have the authority to remove passengers from
the exit row to assure that everyone sitting there is able to open
a door and get out quickly. As guidance for this, Dr. G.A. McLean,
a researcher at the institute, summarized work on why passengers do
or do not get out the exit in a survivable crash, defined as one in
which the passengers do not all die of injuries. Shown on a grid,
age appears as the major factor in a passenger's ability to get
out, with an older passenger less likely to escape than a younger
one. This has even more impact than the width of the escape aisle,
McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   The next factor is weight, with the heavy doing less well than
the light; then gender, with men holding the advantage. Height was
also considered, but any differences were negligible in using the
overwing exit.
</P>
<P>
   The students discussed tactful ways of transferring passengers.
One suggestion: ``It is not that you are in the way; I am trying to
be sure you get out safely.''
</P>
<P>
   In the water evacuation, I stood in a small-plane fuselage
wearing clothes, running shoes and an inflatable life vest. The
student behind me said, ``Just inflate one half.'' On the wing, I
pulled one of the two devices, it inflated and I jumped.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pollard said later that an airline could give this
half-a-vest order or not, depending on several things, including
the type of life jacket. Where this is recommended, it is to keep
passengers from being too bulky as they exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go out foot, head, foot,'' the voice from behind said. I
avoided conking my head this way. In the water, I inflated the
other half of the jacket and we all struggled into a life raft,
which sustained us until a plug got knocked out and we all went
back into the water. The instructor said that was not part of the
test.
</P>
<P>
   After we flung off our vests, the seat-cushion exercise was most
valuable. We were told that swimming in ocean water while waiting
for rescue speeds the loss of body heat, bringing on hypothermia.
As we bobbed around embracing our cushions, we emulated a videotape
we had watched, joining ourselves into clusters by facing each
other and reaching around the facing person's cushion. Then we put
someone between the two cushions, and so on. Soon we had a big
cluster, and floated upright easily. Research indicates body heat
is better preserved this way. I could also see it would be a good
way to hold up a child or old person.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
