<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN03-COX     06-02 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: The kinds of people we don't like
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a group of us who get together regularly to discuss the
events of the world, the price of watermelons and whether it'll
ever rain again in our lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, we talk about the kinds of people we don't
like.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the foundation of lasting friendship, to have like
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   And there isn't a bigot among us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a thing in this world against such-and-such kind
of people,'' one fellow allowed. ``Fact is, I've only known one of
them. I didn't like him, but _''
</P>
<P>
   That's as good an example as any as to the level of our
enlightenment on the brotherhood of humankind.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Here's the story I wanted to recount, as shared by
one of the group. I'll try as best I can to tell it in much the
same words as he did:
</P>
<P>
   ``This was back in college,'' he began. ``A bunch of us roomed
in a big ol' house. The rooms were so large that most all of us had
a roommate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for this one fellow. He was one of those typical (fill
in the blank as to your own dislikes). About all he and the rest of
us ever could agree on was that he and the rest of us couldn't get
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you about his alarm clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every evening he'd wind that clock _ crrrank, crrank, crrank.
Next he'd drag the chair he kept by his bed over to the closet on
the far side of his room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd climb up on the chair, take the alarm clock and place it
on the highest shelf way back in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he'd move the chair back across the room. Finally, he was
ready for bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come the next morning, 6 a.m., that clock would start ringing
_ and it would ring and it would ring and it would ring. By the
time he got up, moved the chair to the closet, climbed up on the
chair, found the clock and turned off the alarm, everybody in the
house would be awake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him one time why he didn't keep the clock by his bed.
He said if he did he'd just reach over, turn it off and go back to
sleep. Hiding the clock in the closet was the only way he could
guarantee he'd get up on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to him that there were other people trying
to sleep. That's the kind of person he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until years later did I ever hear what became of him. It
turned out he was a professor of sociology in a big university. I
read about him in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was back in the early 1960s. Science had come out with
some kind of pill that could lighten the skin. As a result, he
predicted that there soon wouldn't be any black people left, that
all of them would want to take a pill to make themselves white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking, `He hasn't changed one bit.' ``
</P>
<P>
   So it is that late in life I've come to understand that it's not
so much racial differences as it is cultural peculiarities that
tend to divide us.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares what color another fellow is, just so long as he
thinks, acts, votes and believes the same as we do?
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on our upbringing. We like people who are like we are.
</P>
<P>
   And there isn't a bigot among us.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is
P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas 75915; e-mail is
awew18a(at)prodigy.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
