<HEADER>
A0558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-02 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE ADVENTUROUS, OBSCURE LABELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To a true wine enthusiast, the letters ABC have one meaning:
Anything But Chardonnay. It's a polite way of indicating that a
strident minority is bored with America's favorite white wine and
is looking for something new and different.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, it doesn't take much time in a liquor store to
discover that plenty of wine fans feel the same about the popular
reds _ cabernet sauvignon, zinfandel and yes, even merlot.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of substitutes, of course: pinot noir is on a
roll; the Rhone grapes _ syrah, mourvedre, grenache _ are popular;
white grapes like pinot blanc, pinot gris and that flashy newcomer
viognier are all welcome at most people's tables. Even the
much-maligned riesling has its champions.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, however, this list is tame stuff. To the true
adventurer, it offers little. Fortunately, there is another wine
world out there, a place where genuine rarities exist, where there
are wines guaranteed to vanquish enological ennui. And it's open to
anyone with a bit of imagination and some pocket change.
</P>
<P>
   Beauzeau is a wine that's not a household name (perhaps with
good reason). This red, a blend of zinfandel, petite sirah,
grenache, carignan, valdiguie and charbono, was introduced recently
by Beaulieu Vineyards, one of California's most respected wine
producers. And, yes, it's pronounced the way you think, and, yes,
the winery coyly acknowledges that the name is a joke. Sort of. The
wine isn't half bad, but what bozo thought up the name? (It brings
to mind a California wine produced some years back by a fellow
whose winery was going through hard times. He called it ``Chateau
Cache Flowe.'')
</P>
<P>
   Many other off-the-beaten-path choices are quite serious. Les
Vineux, for example, is an intensely sweet wine that an Oregon
vintner, Andrew Rich, makes from frozen gewuerztraminer grapes. The
grapes are frozen after picking so that the water in them turns to
ice and can be separated from the thick, sugary pulp. This
remaining, highly concentrated juice, is then fermented.
</P>
<P>
   Rarer still is a true ice wine. The Germans and the Alsatians
make it when conditions permit. One is produced now and then in New
York State, from the vidal grape. Vidal is a hybrid, a cross
between native American varieties and a European grape known as
trebbiano in Italy and ugni blanc in France. As in northern Europe,
the grapes for this wine hang on the vine long after the regular
harvest until they are literally frozen by winter temperatures. The
wine produced from this icy process also has a sweet taste.
</P>
<P>
   The Napa Valley wine maker Philip Togni makes another dark,
sweet wine he calls Ca' Togni, from a rare grape known as the black
muscat of Alexandria. In the 17th century, when many of the great
vineyards of Europe were still swamps or cattle pastures, the
world's most-prized wine was Constantia, from Cape Town. Constantia
is once again produced in the vineyards of the Western Cape but no
one is sure how closely it resembles its ancestor. Togni thinks his
Ca' Togni, of which he makes very little, is close to the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Some rare wines turn up unexpectedly. When Joe Heitz started
Heitz Cellars in the Napa Valley back in 1961, he found vines on
his new property, which turned out to be grignolino, an Italian
grape probably planted years before by an immigrant farmer. To this
day, the rose wine Heitz continues to produce from those vines has
a small but loyal following.
</P>
<P>
   Some lesser-known wines have been here all along. The early
settlers in California were casual about naming the vines they
brought with them from the old country. Mourvedre, an important
grape in Chateauneuf-du-Pape in France, they called mataro. Durif,
another little-known French grape, became petite sirah, and the
muscadet grape, from the western reaches of the Loire Valley,
became pinot blanc. Some growers have reverted to the original
names. A few wineries have made durif wines, and world-famous Ridge
Vineyards regularly produces a mataro. Zinfandel, a grape whose
origins were a mystery for a century, has been traced back to Italy
where it was called primitivo and to Croatia where it was _ and
still is _ known as plavac mali. There is some speculation in all
this; nevertheless, several California wineries have produced
primitivos that only a scientist could distinguish from zinfandel.
But even America's adventurous wine makers will go only so far. At
this point, there have been no California plavac malis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are some wine oddities that have remained obscure
for good reasons. Take, for example, the mission grape, the first
wine grape introduced in this country. Some months ago, in Los
Angeles, I sampled wine made from this variety for the first and, I
hope, last time. The mission grape arrived in California in the
late 17th century from Spain by way of Mexico. Its name comes, of
course, from the Franciscan and Jesuit missions where it was first
planted. For well over a century, it was the principal U.S. wine
grape. Zinfandel and other more refined varieties eventually edged
it aside, but there are still hundreds of acres of missions planted
in California and there are still people who drink the wine made
from it.
</P>
<P>
   But then plenty of people enjoy wine made from the Concord grape
whose bouquet reminded the English wine writer Jancis Robinson of
the smell of ``a wet, cheap fur coat.'' Concord is still grown in
New York State and Washington State. Where fine wines are
concerned, concord and mission grapes are obsolete. I picture their
dull, clumsy wines favored by people who still use typewriters and
drive DeSotos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
