<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0560 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     06-02 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STUDS LONIGAN' AUTHOR SCORES OTHER WORKS AS THE BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of necessity, I am preparing to unload a few hundred (thousand?)
books. I'll retain those that are lifetime friends and by various
means will discard others that have outworn their welcome or
usefulness. But what should I do with ``Judith'' and ``Olive and
Mary Ann''?
</P>
<P>
   Should I keep them because the author gave them to me? After
all, the author was James T. Farrell, not an insignificant figure
in the pageant of American literature. But both novels _ which he
didn't inscribe _ seem inconsequential; I read them dutifully soon
after their presentation, but now have only fuzzy recall of what I
read.
</P>
<P>
   The author, though, rated them among his very best work. Surely
the author was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   James Thomas Farrell (1904-1979) was a fallen star when I met
with him in his rather shabby Manhattan apartment, about a year
before he died. He had agreed somewhat grudgingly to the
appointment I requested, and he was gruffly distant at the start.
But I broke through to him through the device of baseball talk.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell was one of baseball's foremost fans, an eternal student
and scholar of the game; and he was quite surprised that I could
keep up with him. When he made reference to a completely forgotten
player who he once thought was the greatest he'd ever seen, I
blurted ``Charlie Hollocher'' before he had identified by name that
idol of his boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   So we talked some baseball, and he invited me to attend a game
at Yankee Stadium with him; he was proud of his lifetime pass. It
might have happened, but Jim Farrell died before another season
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Once he was relaxed, I pressed him to talk about his books. I
expressed admiration for the Studs Lonigan trilogy, which he
dismissed as ``apprentice work,'' contending that his mature
performances occurred much later. It is typical of authors to
disparage work they know as secure in reputation, and to defend and
champion their failures.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell wrote ``Young Lonigan'' at age 25, three years before it
saw publication. ``Gas House McGinty,'' written even earlier, was
published next, in 1933, while Farrell was at work on ``The Young
Manhood of Studs Lonigan.'' It appeared in 1934, and ``Judgment
Day'' completed the trilogy a year later. Farrell's reputation was
made when the Modern Library issued ``Studs Lonigan'' complete.
</P>
<P>
   It's still formidable, more than the sum of its parts. The
pulsating narrative of life on Chicago's South Side in the early
decades of this century reveals Farrell as the premier disciple of
Dreiserian naturalism. With its keen portraiture of
lower-middle-class Irish-American Catholics, ``Studs Lonigan'' is a
sweeping entertainment, now even more notable as a period piece;
but social tragedy is its stunning resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The character of goggle-eyed, baseball-obsessed Danny O'Neill is
in the background of the Lonigan books. Danny, representing Farrell
himself, moved to the forefront of a tetralogy issued from 1936 to
1943. The titles are ``A World I Never Made,'' ``No Star Is Lost,''
``Father and Son'' and ``My Days of Anger.'' Accorded mild praise
at the time, they were forgotten by the time Farrell added an
O'Neill postscript _ ``The Face of Time'' _ in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote and wrote and wrote some more _ novels throughout the
'60s and '70s, including a series focused on Eddie Ryan and other
tales centered on Ryan's friends. Farrell said his every character
was based on some person he had known. ``The Death of Nora Ryan''
(1978) was an honorable swan song, but we may not have read the
last of James T. Farrell _ his apartment was strewn with
unpublished manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studs'' unarguably is Farrell's monument, but ``My Baseball
Diary'' (1957) is a charmer for those of us who love the game. I
wish I could have had more time with him, and maybe I'll hold onto
his obscure books.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
