<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMB NECK IS NOT JUST FOR THE KITCHEN STAFF ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the sixth of eight columns by Daniel Boulud, the chef and
owner of Restaurant Daniel, in Manhattan. His collaborator on these
columns is Dorie Greenspan.)  
 (HLW)  
 By DANIEL BOULUD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When I was a young cook in France, it was common for
the butcher to give the kitchen staff the lamb neck. He would take
the cut, considered too humble to serve to the restaurant's guests,
and slice it so that each piece had some of the firm, chewy meat
and the flavor-giving bones. We would roast the lamb with garlic,
dried fennel, and herbs, and, to a cook, the crew would love it.
</P>
<P>
   These days, when lusty flavor is so much in demand, the neck of
the lamb is as welcome in the dining room as it was in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   At my restaurant, I serve the neck as part of ``an epigram of
lamb,'' a dish that uses many parts: the neck and shoulder are
boned, stuffed, and braised; the rack and saddle are marinated and
roasted; and the leg is studded with garlic and herbs, and given a
long, juicy roast. This time, I decided to create a special dish
for this underappreciated cut.
</P>
<P>
   In the best of all possible worlds, you would have your butcher
reserve a whole neck, which is about a foot long and looks a little
like an oxtail. He would bone and butterfly it so that you could
stuff it with savory ground pork, roll and tie it, and then braise
it.
</P>
<P>
   But necks can be hard to come by. If you can't get one, use a
boned and butterflied shoulder. (You can also skip the stuffing and
just braise lamb shanks.)
</P>
<P>
   To get the most from the neck, which is a relatively tough cut,
I brown the meat first and then braise it slowly in white wine with
a lot of carrots, Texas onions, and fresh fennel.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the lamb emerges from the oven, the vegetables,
nourished by the cooking juices, have softened and sweetened, in
the style of the classic beef dish, boeuf aux carottes.
</P>
<P>
   And like so many rustic dishes, this one proves what good cooks
have always known: The poorest cuts can produce the richest
flavors. You've just got to treat them right.
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED LAMB NECK WITH SPRING CARROTS, ONIONS, AND FENNEL
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   \ cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   3 large white mushrooms, cut into \-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons finely chopped fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 slice stale or oven-dried crustless white bread, cut into
\-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   { pound ground pork
</P>
<P>
   1 whole lamb neck, about 10 to 12 inches long, bone removed
lengthwise, meat deveined and butterflied, so that it lays flat and
is { inch thick (or 1 lamb shoulder, cut in the same manner)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   12 medium carrots (preferably California), peeled and cut
diagonally into {-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   6 Texas or Vidalia onions, trimmed and cut in half from root to
top
</P>
<P>
   1 fennel bulb, trimmed and cut into {-inch wedges
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle dry white wine, preferably chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   1. In medium saute pan over medium heat, heat 2 tablespoons of
the olive oil. Add onion, and cook, stirring, until it is
translucent, about 4 minutes. Add mushrooms, and salt and pepper to
taste. Saute until mushrooms are just tender. Finely chop 1 clove
garlic. Add it to pan with half of the chopped thyme; saute 2
minutes. Stir in bread cubes and parsley; saute 1 minute. Remove
pan from heat, and allow to cool. Add chopped basil, ground pork,
and salt and pepper to taste. Knead mixture by hand to blend well,
and set aside in a cool place.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Place lamb on work surface, and
season with salt and pepper. Spoon stuffing down center of meat,
forming cylinder. Roll meat firmly around stuffing, shaping it into
a roast. Tie roast with kitchen string at 1-inch intervals, to
secure stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place large deep roasting pan over medium-high heat, and add
remaining olive oil. Slip lamb into pan, and sear it, turning
frequently, until well browned all over. Add 2 tablespoons of the
butter, and baste lamb with combined pan fats. Roast lamb in oven
for 15 minutes, basting regularly. Give lamb a quarter turn, and
roast for 15 more minutes. Remove pan from oven, and carefully pour
off accumulated fat. Slice remaining garlic cloves, and add to pan
with remaining thyme, 2 tablespoons butter, carrots, onions,
fennel, and salt and pepper to taste. Continue roasting for 20
minutes, turning and basting the meat and stirring the vegetables
twice during this time. Add wine; if vegetables brown too quickly,
reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees. Braise meat and vegetables
for an additional 1{ hours, turning and basting every 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, transfer roast to cutting board, and remove
strings. Cut roast into 8 pieces. Arrange lamb on warm serving
platter, top with vegetables, and keep warm. Pour pan juices into
saucepan, and boil until reduced to 1 cup. Pour juices over lamb
and vegetables, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
