<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BITES-NYT &LR;      06-02 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE CYBERKITCHEN WITH MCLUHAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By S.A. BELZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marshall McLuhan, the 1960s media critic, looked at television
and saw the world turning into one electronic global village, a
sort of plugged-in melting pot. But on the Internet individualism
is still alive and well, and the myriad food sites, at least, have
a human face.
</P>
<P>
   Take Diana's Kitchen (www.ebicom.net/kitchen), operated by Diana
Rattray, who started out in Maine but now lives in Tupelo, Miss.,
and works for North Mississippi Health Services. She has collected
recipes and cookbooks most of her life, and is a fan of traditional
crockery pot slow cooking.
</P>
<P>
   She offers visitors to her site hundreds of electric-crock-pot
recipes and aid and comfort in using them.
</P>
<P>
   If you are around Winston-Salem, N.C., she advises, watch for a
rock band called Somebody Else's Problem. Her son Sean is the
vocalist.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rattray is also the Southern cooking specialist for The
Mining Co., an online magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Flora Maria Deter of Sacramento, Calif., a technical writer for
the California Highway Patrol, is an avid collector of cheesecake
recipes, of which she stocks about 300 at
www.deter.com/flora/mxp/chcake. She has stopped testing cheesecake
recipes only to write her thesis for a master's degree in English
from California State University.
</P>
<P>
   Go to Flora's Recipe Hideout for hundreds of chocolate dessert,
pie and pastry recipes and to her home page, Flora's Kitchen, for a
large well-chosen collection of links to other food sites. Ms.
Deter belongs to the Recipe Ring, a network of 494 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to Lara Fulton, a k a RecipeLu, who runs the Recipe
Ring, a labor of time, love and dedication. Ms. Fulton spends an
hour or two daily maintaining the ring, in addition to at least
four hours a night updating her own site of ``tried and true''
recipes (www.recipelu.com), with its giant recipe board of requests
and replies (click on Request a Recipe).
</P>
<P>
   A Torontonian (like McLuhan), she has a day job booking hotels
for tour groups from overseas, and she is planning her wedding,
which is set for Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   These sites are typical of many more, both in their networking
and their self-portraiture. Some show pictures of the children and
of last year's cruise. The Internet is looking less like McLuhan's
homogenized global village than a network of electronic villages,
each one crying, ``I am.'' And the only plugged-in melting pot in
sight is at Diana's Kitchen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like really good cheese?'' Ricki Carroll asks at
www.cheesemaking.com, site of the New England Cheesemaking Supply
Co. in Ashfield, Mass. ``Well, we think that you haven't tasted
really good cheese until you've tasted fresh homemade cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   But once you've tasted your own fresh-made cheese, she warns,
you can never go back to cheese from the store.
</P>
<P>
   Heed this siren song at your own peril. Ms. Carroll studied the
cheesemaker's art in Britain, France and the Netherlands and has
taught it for 20 years. Click on Cheesemaking 101 for a foretaste.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends that novices try making a soft, spreadable
fromage blanc (starter kit, $17). Soft cheeses can be made almost
immediately. Hard cheeses take longer to learn and need aging. For
hard cheeses, she sells the Wheeler cheese press _ at $211, the top
of Ms. Carroll's line _ made for her in Devon, England.
</P>
<P>
   She will put those who become really serious _ buying a herd of
sheep, for instance _ in touch with her own suppliers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are three restaurant-review sites that cater to the
undecided New York diner-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passport to New York Restaurants'' (Passport Press, $10.95) is
by Peter D. and Amy Meltzer and John F. Mariani, food and wine
critics who visit restaurants anonymously, pay for their meals and
write pithily.
</P>
<P>
   The guide is searchable at
http://newyork.digitalcity.com/passport. The site, like the current
edition of the guide, the 12th, limits itself to 500 restaurants.
Click on categories like Romance, Cheap Eats, Fun Spots for Kids
and Grand Celebration to narrow the search.
</P>
<P>
   Steven A. Shaw, a lawyer, has eaten his way through New York
restaurants for years, especially the French ones, and he gives
reviews of more than 200 and opinions about every bite at
www.shaw-review.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cuisine Net (www.cuisinenet.com) offers survey-based reviews not
only for New York, but also for Atlanta, Chicago, Miami,
Washington, Boston, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Seattle and
Portland, Ore. For New York, the site lists 1,455 restaurants,
based on 3,753 surveys filled out by online visitors, said Kian-Lam
Kho, founder and president of Cuisine Net.
</P>
<P>
   It took some searching to find one restaurant reviewed by all
three, but Chanterelle in TriBeCa met the test. Cuisine Net writes:
``Mention Chanterelle to anyone who's been there and here's what
you'll hear: `Oh, I love Chanterelle,' said in a voice laced with
longing.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw begins: ``Mention Chanterelle and a lot of people go `ooh'
and `ah!' I do not agree.'' Touche.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuisine Net review is the only one of the three with a
photograph. The review is short, calling the service at the
restaurant whip-smart and the food extraordinary, with a rating of
8.3 out of 10 (the average of 17 surveys).
</P>
<P>
   The Passport review rates the food a little higher, 4.5 out of
5, names dishes (like the signature seafood sausage) and calls the
seasonal menus ``original and enticing.'' But it warns the
prospective patron, ``The tranquillity of the dining experience may
be shattered by the astonishing prices'' _ $75 to $89 a person,
without wine.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw writes that Chanterelle was better years ago, when his
mother-in-law gave him a birthday gift certificate. He has found
that the waiters can be grouchy and thinks the room is too big and
unattractive, but he loves the grilled seafood sausage appetizer.
He recommends three other places in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Reading all three of these reviewers gives prospective diners a
more useful composite picture than any one alone can. And all three
welcome online reactions. Shaw, especially, says he loves feedback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
