<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRULY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAY IT AIN'T SO, PAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAT TRULY 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fisk Rubber Co. used to employ an advertising logo featuring
a sleepy little boy, in one-piece pajamas, yawning, holding a
candle in one hand and with an old-fashioned automobile tire over
his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The copy with the illustration asked simply, ``Time to
Re-tire?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. It is. And I am. So this is by way of a valedictory
message.
</P>
<P>
   An early photograph of me (I was about 2 1/2) shows me posed at
an upright Underwood typewriter in a cluttered newspaper office.
That long-ago snapshot was taken by my father, Tom Truly, and that
newspaper office was where he was city editor, in Wichita Falls,
Texas. His father, whom I never knew, also was a newspaperman.
Before the turn of the century he cruised Runnels County in a
buggy, jotting down news items in a little notebook. My mother was
in this business, too.
</P>
<P>
   You will notice that I called my father, who died in 1959, a
newspaperman. He would have been amused to have been called a
journalist. ``Journalist'' is a high-toned word that leads people
to attend professional journalism conferences and drink wine
instead of beer. Everything considered, I would rather be recalled
as a newspaperman. Anyway, the best ``journalists'' I have known
over a semi-pro and professional print career of 40-odd years have
been newspapermen. And, to be politically incorrect, some of those
excellent newspapermen were women.
</P>
<P>
   There have been unforgettable moments. As when Cope Routh, an
old-school police reporter, came into the office in Midland, Texas,
years ago with the verdict from a trial he was covering. ``The
jury,'' he announced, ``said it wasn't rape because when he and she
went through the hotel lobby and upstairs to their room, she was
the one carrying the case of beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Times change. Now I will be an ex-newspaperman instead of an old
newspaperman. I remember a joke about an old newspaperman who had
to get a second job, because there wasn't much money in old
newspapers. It's true, there wasn't. I suppose the big advantage
about being called journalists instead of newspapermen is that the
pay gradually improved, even if the spelling didn't.
</P>
<P>
   How do you know when it's time to retire? I could say it's when
you realize you have shoes older than most of your co-workers. But
that's not really true.
</P>
<P>
   I'm retiring because it's a good time to go. Because there are
other things I want to do, even though I have enjoyed most of what
I've been doing. Because I look forward to not waking to an alarm
clock. Because it gets discouraging interviewing aspiring
politicians. And even more discouraging interviewing established
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Because I am fascinated with what American antiques tell us
about our heritage. Because I enjoy the hunt through Pennsylvania
or Maine for the wily pewter cupboard or the elusive Windsor
settee. Because I like to explore America and there isn't enough
time if your editorial-writing job means you are spending 48 weeks
a year thinking high-minded thoughts about great issues. There are
a jillion reasons.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly it's because there are other things I want to do
before I admit that my get-up-and-go has gotten up and went. I've
already spent two lifetimes in this business _ one as a sports
writer and one over here on the editorial pages. That's plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, as I sit here in my rocker watching my co-workers, I
wish I had those younger journalists' feel for technology. I also
wish they had the experience of editing with soft-lead pencils and
glue pots and venturing into an inky composing room filled with
turtles, chases, Linotypes and hungover printers. See, when I
started working on newspapers in the 1950s the technology _ and the
printers _ had barely changed since the 1890s.
</P>
<P>
   In most ways newspapers are better now than when I started.
Certainly most papers (including this one) are now more reflective
of the entire communities they endeavor to serve. In other ways
they may be less good than they used to be. I take neither the
credit nor the blame for any of that.
</P>
<P>
   So all that's left is to say, ``Thirty,'' which is pre-computer,
``Gimme rewrite,'' cigarette-butts-mashed-on-wooden-floors
newspaper talk for that's all there is, folks. Everything
considered, it's been fun.
</P>
<P>
   (Pat Truly (817-390-7751) is a Star-Telegram columnist and
editorial writer. But only for a couple more days. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
