<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS AND NOTES ON FOOD AND DINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEW AT ZABAR'S
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, when Louis Zabar opened his little Upper West Side deli
and appetizing shop _ as smoked-fish counters were called in those
days _ New Yorkers were not eating goat cheese on crisp baguettes,
sprinkling balsamic vinegar on organic mesclun salads, or buying
barbecued Chilean sea bass for supper or packages of sushi for
picnics in the park. But as tastes in food have broadened, so has
Zabar's, which has grown to 18,000 square feet on two floors at
Broadway and 80th Street and now employs third-generation members
of the family (and occasionally some fourth-generation teen-agers
to help out during holiday seasons).
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the produce department expanded from a few items
to a new all-organic display near the bread counter, with assorted
greens, vegetables, and fruit (mesclun, $8.99 a pound; asparagus,
$3.59 a pound; and strawberries, $2.99 a pint). Sushi, $2.98 to
$8.40 a box, is made for Zabar's and delivered daily. The cheese
department, which now fills the aisles at the store's main
entrance, has become easier to navigate. A refrigerator case of
kosher foods offers fresh meats and chicken for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chef for the past 20 years, Boris Bassin, saw the need for
a lot of these changes,'' said Ann Zabar, whose father, Saul, owns
Zabar's with his brother Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bassin's goals has been to expand prepared foods. Now,
nearly 200 dishes are available at the service counter and 200 more
are packaged for self-service. Everything from excellent rotisserie
chickens and pot pies to portions of dilled salmon ready to go into
the microwave oven can be picked up without taking a number.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw more of a demand for ready-to-eat and ready-to-reheat
meals,'' Ms. Zabar said. The family also plans to redo the cafe to
add more self-service items.
</P>
<P>
   Only the smoked-fish counter, the soul of Zabar's, seems to have
remained virtually unchanged, with some of the same deft slicers
still at work behind it. Except now _ in addition to smoked,
kippered, pickled, and marinated salmon _ fresh salmon steaks, at
$5.99 a pound, are also available.
</P>
<P>
   HOT STUFF
</P>
<P>
   Spiciness that barely tantalizes one asbestos palate may make
another person gasp. When it comes to flavor, heat is relative, and
the common ``mild,'' ``medium,'' and ``hot'' designations on sauces
are often too vague. Thus, Tim and Wendy Eidson, who own a
mail-order spicy food company, Mo Hotta-Mo Betta, now have all
their sauces tested in a laboratory. In their catalog, each sauce
is accompanied by a Scoville rating, which measures capsaicins (the
compound responsible for the heat in peppers) in parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 hot sauces have ratings, from 50 for Tamrindo Bay
Pepper Sauce ($4.50 for 5 ounces) to 89,560 for Mad Dog Inferno
sauce ($6.95 for 5 ounces). A rating of more than 5,000 is
considered superhot. Then there is the Mo Hotta-Mo Betta Habanero
Powder ($6.50 for 1.6 ounces), which delivers 427,000 Scoville heat
units. Sprinkle it grain by grain.
</P>
<P>
   The company also makes personalized labels for hot sauces (your
photo, or for Father's Day, Dad's photo) that rate from 380
(cayenne garlic) to 5,470 (red savina habanero). These are $80 to
$100 for 12 bottles, depending on the label. For information or a
catalog: (800) 462-3220.
</P>
<P>
   AMISH MARKET EAST
</P>
<P>
   The Amish Market, 731 Ninth Avenue (48th Street), has opened a
spacious new store at 240 East 45th Street. Like the West Side
market, it is well stocked with cheeses, packaged foods,
condiments, olives in bulk, and produce. Notable are the olive
oils, especially commendable Greek brands like Minos from Crete for
$8.95 a liter. Browsing in this store can easily turn into grazing,
what with tasting samples of olives, nuggets of cheese, bread, and
pastry.
</P>
<P>
   The Amish, by the way, have nothing to do with these markets.
They have a stand at Columbus Circle for produce and baked goods.
You'll know them by their black hats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
