<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT FEELS ALL THE WORLD LIKE HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday June 9)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens to a lot of us on vacation. We start reading the
housing ads, just pretending, we say, only comparing real estate
prices. But there lurks a small fantasy about living in this
current place of our dreams.
</P>
<P>
   You're sitting in a cabin beside a creek in the Sierras and a
meadow loaded with wild flowers and thinking this would be a great
place to write novels and have a yellow dog.
</P>
<P>
   Or walking down a street in New York and thinking I walk fast
enough to keep up with this crowd. We'll sell the cars, learn the
subway and buy theater tickets with the savings.
</P>
<P>
   One night my husband and I completely remodeled an old garage
that sits across the street from a terrace cafe in a tiny town in
Italy. As the night and the Chianti wore on we scribbled our design
for a work/live studio. We'd bring over the family, telecommute to
California.
</P>
<P>
   In my mind I move several times a year, almost as many times as
I leave town. I wonder if the tourist who is sitting on Main Street
Sebastopol is dreaming about being a local, considering how to turn
that office supply store into a brasserie, become friends with the
guy who drives around with a rooster, sign up for a goddess
workshop.
</P>
<P>
   When I lived in Southern California and visited Northern
California I pictured how it would be to move here. We would take
our jugs to the friendly neighborhood winemaker and fill up from
his barrels. We'd drive into San Francisco every weekend. We'd jog
on the beach before work and take our visitors up in a hot air
balloon.
</P>
<P>
   After a good 20 years of living here, minus a few away, I get
into San Francisco an average of once a month and get near the
Pacific maybe twice that. I've never gone up in a balloon, although
every spring when they begin their whispered rise above the valley
I vow this will be the year. And I quickly learned there is no
dipping your jug into anyone's barrel, although there is a nearby
winery that lets you buy a jug and fill it up with a respectable
red from a hose from their tank.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly the dream, but even the amended version
undoubtedly appeals to the Wine Country visitor who wistfully
watches the Saturday regulars pop into the tasting room and be
greeted by name.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into an acquaintance at the market who'd spent the morning
at the beach with her dog. It's her favorite place to escape, she
said, and she often thinks of moving there. She fancies a little
art colony next to the dunes, but on the other hand, she wonders
where she would go for solace if the beach was outside her door.
Would she feel the need to drive into town to get away?
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco I sometimes tour open houses like a prospective
tenant. I like the tall beauties with a bay window at which I
picture having a candlelight dinner while watching the Asian
freighters glide under the bridge. I imagine waking up to cable car
clanging and walking out the door to my choice of ethnic
restaurants, but then I think of the frigid summers that demand you
wear wool socks with your sandals. A city resident who likes to
flee up my way reminds me that on Divisadero she can't go out and
water her vegetable garden in her pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   The city kicks me into another gear, but if I lived there would
I begin to consider the pace annoying and tell the cable cars to
shut up?
</P>
<P>
   When I visit my sister in New England I imagine a summer place
on a tiny no-name island off Crane's Beach where we would sit on
the grass, chase fireflies and chew on lobster claws. But then you
have to deal with the midgies who swarm in at twilight, and those
old cottages don't have any heat.
</P>
<P>
   When I visit friends up in the Gold Country I want a dollhouse
Victorian within easy walking to a bar that plays country music. I
don't even like country music, but the ambience is seductive.
</P>
<P>
   One daughter briefly worked at a coffee house in Venice Beach.
She had to go to cafe latte school and learn how to bark orders in
precision. She lasted less than a week because she said if she
continued working there, she'd end up avoiding coffee houses. And
then where would she go to find refuge and write in her journal.
</P>
<P>
   I can't think of any place I haven't visited that I didn't
consider moving to. And that includes Detroit, Kansas and Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I once drove from Georgia to Massachusetts and
did serious thinking about relocating to the Blue Ridge Mountains,
Georgetown, Mount Kisco, N.Y., and Olde Salem.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is the part about how do you make money and
which cats can tolerate the move and how will you gather the
relatives at Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   With any luck I'm going to Prague and Indianapolis this summer.
I'll let you know what it costs to rent a turret. Or a charming old
silo that might convert into an antique store.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartzpressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
