<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-PASTRY-CHEF-95     06-02 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-PASTRY-CHEF-950&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EMPEROR WHO CAN MARSHAL NAPOLEONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: recipes are at end of article.) 
(js) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Except for a few late-nighters stumbling home, the
Avenue des Champs-Elysees was eerily still. But inside Laduree, a
tea room, pastry shop and restaurant, everything was astir. It was
6 in the morning, and Pierre Herme, the premier pastry chef in
Paris, was taking the first of many rounds through the place _ a
marbled, gilded, palatial space that looks as if it came from
Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   He passed from the kitchen to the pastry kitchen to the shop,
his eyes scanning like radar. When an apprentice dropped a glass,
he raised his brow and stared him down, but said nothing. He is
quiet. Everyone in his presence is quiet. And to everyone,
including the head pastry chef, who has been with him for years, he
is Monsieur Herme.
</P>
<P>
   To the French, Monsieur Herme has achieved the stature of the
legendary pastry chef Gaston Lenotre. And since last September he
has taken charge of one of Paris' most beloved tea salons and
pastry shops, Laduree, whose newest site on the Champs-Elysees is
wedged among hulking commercial giants like Planet Hollywood, the
Disney Store and a Virgin Megastore.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big move for Herme. He had reigned over the pastry
kitchens at the fabled Paris gourmet store Fauchon for more than a
decade. But at 36, it was time to have a place of his own, where he
could point his creative arm in all directions, from dainty
pastries to elaborate cakes to plated desserts.
</P>
<P>
   A day with Herme _ a large, baby-faced man who always dresses in
black _ passed amid dizzying activity, most of it away from the
kitchens. He seems to be in motion even when sitting still. At one
point, he had a cell phone in one ear, an ordinary phone in the
other, and was speaking French in one, English in the other. When
he hung up, he scratched two lines off a list, and said with a rare
laugh: ``Ah, yes, Mondays are the calmest days.'' And then he began
dialing again.
</P>
<P>
   Herme rose to the top of his profession at a similar juggernaut
pace, adding reputable pastry kitchens to his resume as quickly as
he now goes through his list of phone messages. By 14, he was
working at Lenotre, then hailed as the top pastry shop in France.
By 19, he was a sous-chef there. But fame did not arrive until he
became the head pastry chef at Fauchon. There, with the help of a
graphic designer, Yann Pennors, he created the Cherry on the Cake.
Like the work of a pop art sculptor, it was a sleek-looking
milk-chocolate cake shaped like an oversize slice and topped with a
glazed cherry as shiny as a candied apple. It was an instant
success, and it is credited with starting a milk chocolate revival
in France.
</P>
<P>
   Herme's greater achievement is less quantifiable. In France,
pastry has a long and highly codified tradition. Pastry chefs are
taught the fundamentals and the classics, often more as formulas
than as models. But Herme approaches pastry as a creative chef
would approach any dish. Rather than following formulas, he
reworked recipes to achieve the best flavor; in his pastries,
doughs and desserts, he changed the proportions of salt, sugar or
butter and sometimes broke all the rules and used herbs, spices and
pepper for seasoning. He serves pistachio waffles with a liquid
yellow raisin jelly that is infused with saffron; his coconut loaf
cake contains what would have once been unthinkable _ ground
coriander.
</P>
<P>
   Herme is a stickler for high quality ingredients. And at
Laduree, his searches for the best ingredients have become almost
obsessive. The 1,200 pounds of butter used each week arrive
directly from a dairy in Charente, so the butter is as fresh as
possible, retaining all its original perfumes and flavors.
</P>
<P>
   He has chocolate specially manufactured in Venezuela from single
varieties of cocoa bean (lesser mortals use blends). Fleur de sel,
the finest and most expensive salt on the market, seasons most of
his doughs. Even the jelly to glaze fruit tarts is specially made
for each kind of tart.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such devotion to specialty ingredients, his pastries
cost what similar pastries do in other shops around the city. A
vanilla millefeuille or napoleon is about $5.
</P>
<P>
   But ingredients aren't everything. ``It's how they're used as
well,'' Herme said.
</P>
<P>
   For him, sensibility is just as important. Which is why, even
with the heightened flavors of his ingredients, his work is marked
by subtlety. You could easily polish off one of his croissants
without noticing how thin and crispy the outer layer is, or how
fine the butter tastes. In his kouign-amann, a traditional
brioche-like pastry from Brittany, the crust crackles with sugar
and the dough is yeasty. But there is something incredibly earthy
about it. A small addition of buckwheat flour makes the difference.
</P>
<P>
   His plated desserts have the same depth _ and minimalism. They
do not tower on the plate. Nor do they sparkle with gold leaf or
lie coated in cocoa. In his gourmandise, a scoop of pistachio
parfait rests atop a scattering of strawberries in a creamy pool of
coconut milk and tapioca pearls. But the pistachio parfait is so
intense that it is almost spicy, the strawberries are fragrant with
basil, and the combination of fruit and coconut brings immediately
to mind that orange-and-coconut picnic favorite, ambrosia. It is a
smart, carefully constructed dessert without an ounce of
pretension. Or a mint sprig.
</P>
<P>
   ``The know-how and the method are traditional,'' he said,
sitting in his sparsely decorated office, with its bare walls and
plain antiques, a world away from the gilded dining rooms. ``I just
reinterpret the traditional. But to do this, you really have to
understand a dish.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As with other artists, his work has become increasingly personal
over the years. ``I began working with the textures and the
alliance of textures,'' he said. ``It's less and less marked by
technique.''
</P>
<P>
   What has remained constant is the emphasis of taste over looks _
and the absence of anything that is pure garnish. ``There is
nothing on the plate for esthetic purposes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Herme, who makes regular trips to the United States, laments
that many American pastry chefs are caught up in the visuals.
``They make skyscrapers on the plate, with all these little things
around it that have no taste and no relation to the dish,'' he
said, flipping through a copy of Pastry Art &AMP; Design magazine,
pointing to example after example. Then he slapped his finger down
on a page and grimaced. ``Oh, and that mint leaf,'' he said. ``It's
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, he suggested, American pastry is going through the same
growing pains French pastry did a decade ago. The measure of a
pastry chef's expertise then were great pulled-sugar pieces and
carvings that were for show, not for eating. ``It's the public who
has to want subtlety,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Herme has at times liked what he saw. He distinctly recalls a
chocolate tart with raspberries and port made by Bill Yosses, the
pastry chef at Bouley Bakery, as the best dessert he ever ate in
the United States. Yosses, he said, ``works really hard on the
flavors, and there is nothing useless on the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Herme works more like a Renaissance painter. He
maintains his vision but relies on a team of alter egos to carry it
out. His method for creating new desserts, though, seems more
scientific than free flowing. He writes the recipe down, sketches
what it should look like or how to construct it, and notes how it
can be stored. Then his pastry chefs go to work.
</P>
<P>
   This system gives him time for other projects. Herme regularly
appears on French television (a team from the show ``Zone
Interdite'' on Channel M6 was at Laduree on this day) and in food
magazines, and he has published cookbooks in Spanish and French. In
the fall, his first book in English, ``Desserts by Pierre Herme,''
will be published by Little, Brown. He said it would have ``a
French spirit with American ingredients.'' A second book, on
chocolate, is in the works. Meanwhile, he and his wife, Frederick
Grasser, are putting together a pastry book for children.
</P>
<P>
   The books will surely introduce him, and his chocolate-cherry
cake, to many Americans. But his influence is already visible in
New York. His pineapple carpaccio, a signature dessert, can be
tasted in many variations at restaurants like Destinee.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't he want to publish in the United States just to lay
claim to his creations? When asked, France's master of
millefeuille, its king of croquembouche, suddenly turned shy and
said: ``Knowing that I may have inspired someone doesn't bother me
at all. I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   COCONUT LOAF CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Desserts by Pierre Herme''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups sugar, plus 2{ tablespoons sugar for syrup
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups unsweetened finely grated dried coconut, plus extra for
the pan (at health-food and specialty stores)
</P>
<P>
   9 tablespoons (4{ ounces) unsalted butter, plus extra for
buttering the pan, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon double-acting baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   \ cup powdered milk
</P>
<P>
   } cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   \ cup white rum.
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare simple syrup by combining 1/3 cup of sugar with 6
tablespoons of water in a small saucepan. Place over medium heat,
and bring to a boil. Immediately set aside to cool to room
temperature (only \ cup of syrup will be needed).
</P>
<P>
   2. In the bowl of a food processor, combine 1{ cups of coconut
with 1 tablespoon of sugar. Pulse until the coconut is pulverized,
but still powdery and dry. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Center a rack in the oven, and heat to 350 degrees. Butter an
8{-by-4{-by-2{-inch loaf pan, dust the interior with the extra
grated coconut, and tap out the excess. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Sift together the flour, coriander, and baking powder. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. In a mixer fitted with a paddle, beat the butter at
medium-high speed until creamy, then slowly add the remaining
sugar. While beating, add eggs one at a time, scraping down the
sides of the bowl as necessary. Reduce mixer speed to low. One at a
time, add the 1{ cups of coconut and sugar, powdered milk, and
whole milk, beating only until each addition is incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   6. Divide the flour mixture into two batches, and, with a rubber
spatula, gently fold in first one batch and then the other; the
batter should be smooth and thick. Immediately spoon the batter
into the prepared pan. Place the pan on two baking sheets, one on
top of the other, or on one insulated baking sheet. Bake until the
cake is golden brown and split down the center, about 70 to 80
minutes. To test whether the cake is done, insert a long thin knife
into the center; it should come out dry and crumb-free. If the cake
appears to be browning too quickly, cover loosely with a foil tent
after the first 30 minutes of baking.
</P>
<P>
   7. Place cooling rack over a sheet of wax paper. Remove the cake
from the oven, release it from the pan and position it right side
up on the rack. While it is still hot, combine \ cup simple syrup
with the rum and \ cup water. With a pastry brush, apply the
mixture over the top and sides of the cake. To serve, cut the cake
into thin slices and, if desired, toast them lightly. Yield: one
loaf cake (8 servings).
</P>
<P>
   PINEAPPLE CARPACCIO WITH LIME SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Desserts by Pierre Herme''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup fresh lime juice (from 5 or 6 limes)
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   Finely grated zest of { lime
</P>
<P>
   1 pineapple, trimmed and peeled
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   12 teaspoons large crystal sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt, preferably fleur de sel, or coarse salt crushed in a
mortar and pestle
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper, preferably Sarawak.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium saucepan, combine 2/3 cup water with the sugar to
make a syrup. Bring to a boil, then immediately remove from heat.
Cool the syrup to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium bowl, whisk together the sugar syrup, the lime
juice, the milk, and the lime zest. Transfer to an ice cream maker,
and follow manufacturer's instructions. Pack the sorbet into an
air-tight container, and store it in a freezer until serving.
</P>
<P>
   3. Halve the pineapple from blossom to stem, and remove the
core. Cut half of the pineapple into slices, as thin as you can
make them. Divide the slices among six large dinner plates,
arranged in a single layer on each plate.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cut the remaining pineapple into chunks, and place in a
blender or food processor. Add the coconut milk, and puree until
the mixture is smooth and very bubbly. Quickly pour some of the
puree over each of the pineapple slices. Sprinkle each plate with 2
teaspoons of large crystal sugar, a pinch of salt and a little
black pepper. Place a scoop of the lime sorbet in the center of the
pineapple slices on each plate, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
