</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-PRAYER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PLANS VOTE ON SCHOOL PRAYER AMENDMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Text of amendment at bottom of story) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping for a little less violence and a lot more
prayer in public schools, House Republicans have scheduled a vote
Thursday on a constitutional amendment protecting student-led
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that the proposed Religious Freedom Amendment is
little more than an election-year nod to Christian conservatives.
The House vote _ the first of its kind in 27 years _ comes less
than a month after Republican leaders publicly assured Christian
activists that conservative causes would move to the top of the
congressional agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendment, sponsored by Rep. Ernest Istook,
R-Okla., declares that ``the people's right to pray and to
recognize their religious beliefs, heritage or traditions on public
property, including schools, shall not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would also prohibit requiring any person ``to join
in prayer or other religious activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters acknowledge that they will have a hard time getting
the two-thirds majority needed for a constitutional change, but the
vote will give conservative groups new ammunition for the November
elections. A similar amendment fell 28 votes short of Housed
approval in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a key issue to religious conservatives going into this
election cycle,'' said Randy Tate, the Christian Coalition's
executive director. ``We're working it hard. We're pulling out
every stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition has budgeted more than $500,000 for radio ads
promoting the amendment and distributed more than 2 million church
bulletins on the topic last Sunday. Tate said the lobbying effort
is aimed at 50 undecided House members, but he declined to name
them.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Whip Tom DeLay of Texas characterized the vote as a
test of whether lawmakers believe in ``one nation under God'' and
religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our schools are filled with drugs and violence. It's time we
made room for a little prayer instead,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused House leaders of playing politics with the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party is trying to use this as a political
wedge issue,'' said Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Waco, who is leading the
effort to defeat the proposal. ``It is unconscionable to try to
amend the Bill of Rights for the first time in our nation's history
for the purpose of a 30-second campaign commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the amendment is needed to counter a trend that
began with the Supreme Court's landmark 1963 ruling prohibiting
school-sponsored prayers and Bible readings. The court concluded
that such prayers violate the First Amendment's prohibition against
a government-imposed religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a prayer is not establishing an official religion. It
is simply a prayer,'' said Istook, a 1967 graduate of Castleberry
High School in River Oaks. ``Those who don't want to hear something
are being permitted to censor other people. That is the standard
that we have today. It's intolerance in disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   Istook and his supporters also want to roll back court rulings
that restrict religious expression in public parks and
government-owned buildings. Conservative groups have assembled a
host of anecdotes to support their argument that Americans are
being denied the right to follow their religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   An elementary school student in St. Louis said he was ordered
not to say grace before eating lunch. In New Caney, Texas, two high
school students went to court to win the right to display rosary
beads. In Columbia, Mo., a nurse at a`ugiversity hospital said she
was fired for wearing a cross on her uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not only interference with freedom of religion, it's
interference with freedom of speech,'' Istook said. ``It is not
neutrality. It is placing religion at an artificial and
state-created disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the amendment is unnecessary and divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there are math exams, there will be prayer in
public schools,'' said Edwards, whose district includes Baylor
University in Waco, the nation's leading Baptist college. ``We
already have a religious freedom amendment. It's the First
Amendment in the Bill of Rights, and it's worked well for over 200
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also question Istook's assurances that students would
not be coerced to pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would essentially allow the tyranny of the majority to
establish a religion for a particular school,'' said Rep. Robert
Scott, D-Va. ``The people in the minority religion can just sit
over to the side and be suppressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Another provision in Istook's amendment that would make it
illegal to ``deny equal access to a (government) benefit on account
of religion.'' The proposal is intended to let religious-based
social service organizations receive federal funding, but opponents
say the change would be a major departure from the traditional
separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our founding fathers made it absolutely clear that they wanted
a wall of separation between church and state,'' Edwards said.
``The best way to protect religion is to keep the government's
tentacles away.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The text of the proposed Religious Freedom Amen2%ent
</P>
<P>
   ``To secure the people's right to acknowledge God according to
the dictates of conscience: Neither the United States nor any State
shall establish any official religion, but the people's right to
pray and to recognize their religious beliefs, heritage or
traditions on public property, including schools, shall not be
infringed. Neither the United States nor any state shall require
any person to join in prayer or other religious activity, prescribe
school prayers, discriminate against religion, or deny equal access
to a benefit on account of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
