<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, June 7,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories  &LR;  CHICAGO-THEATER (Chicago) _ Even though the
second-largest, after New York, Chicago's theater community is
probably the nation's most tightly knit, arguably its most
adventurous and almost certainly its most important incubator of
young talent. By Bruce Weber. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY-SEASON-PLAYS (New York) _ There were occasions during
the recent New York theater season, which is celebrated by the
presentation of Sunday night's Tony Awards, when the gasp sound
flew out of audiences who had achieved a rapt, respectful communion
with what was happening on the stages before them. The inspirations
for these abrupt responses, which are surely more gratifying to
actors than even standing ovations, are wildly varied and, taken
out of context, unremarkable. By Ben Brantley. (To come). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Brief reviews of films and their
suitability for children. This week: ``Godzilla''; ``Almost
Heroes''; ``The Truman Show'' and ``I Got the Hook-Up.'' (To come).
</P>
<P>
   BALZAC-FILMS (Undated) _ Suddenly, movie makers are landing on
Planet Balzac. On Friday, two films on the French writer Honore de
Balzax, representing two extremes of his oeuvre, are opening. One
is ``Passion in the Desert,'' an impressionistic allegory that has
been adapted by the American director Lavinia Currier for her first
feature from an eight-page short story of 1830. The other is a new
adaptation of ``Cousin Bette,'' the sprawling 1847 drama of manners
that is one of Balzac's best-known novels; this movie is the first
to be directed by the Tony-winning theater director Des McAnuff
(``Big River,'' ``The Who's `Tommy' ''). By Jean Nathan. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   COMDEN-GREEN-FILMS (New York) _ Eight MGM musicals with Betty
Comden and Adolp Green screenplays or lyrics _ the earliest is from
1947, the latest from 1960 _ will be shown at the Film Forum
starting Friday and running through June 25, and the series gleams
with their powers of invention. By Nora Sayre. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE  &LR;  AMERICAN-DANCE-FESTIVAL (Undated) _ One of the most
significant accomplishments of the American Dance Festival in its
65-year history has been its shedding light on the rich but often
little-known contributions of black choreographers to American
modern dance. The festival, in Durham, N.C., will continue the
programming this Thursday through Sunday with ``Masterpieces of the
Black Tradition.'' By Jennifer Dunning. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   SCHORER-DANCE (New York) _ At 5-feet-2-inches tall, Suki Schorer
perches precariously on a ballet barre, giving her the maximum
overview of her students in Studio 3 at the School of American
Ballet at Lincoln Center. She needs the extra height to conduct a
rehearsal of Balanchine's challenging ``Donizetti Variations,'' one
of three ballets presented this weekend at SAB's Workshop
Performance at the Juilliard Theater. By Hilary Ostlere. (To come).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARIANNA-OPERA (New York) _ ``Arianna,'' which will be given its
first American performance Sunday by the Opera Theater of St.
Louis, is not exactly a new work and not exactly an old one. Quite
who wrote it is also in doubt. According to the title page of the
score, it is a ``lost opera by Claudio Monteverdi ... composed
again by Alexander Goehr,'' the English composer who, now 65, has
steadily been gaining a reputation for music at once serious and
playful, beautiful and quirky, as this is. By Paul Griffiths. (To
come).
</P>
<P>
   HEADLINE-OPERA (Undated) _ The fad for headline opera, a genre
that began so promisingly in 1987 with John Adams' ``Nixon in
China'' and fizzled last year with Michael Daugherty's ``Jackie
O,'' seems to have passed. Breathe a sigh of relief, knowing that
we have been spared operas based on O.J., Tonya and Paula. Yet a
new recording of ``Harvey Milk'' (Teldec 0630-15856-2; two CDs),
with music by Stewart Wallace and libretto by Michael Korie, shows
that the attempt to link the opera house to the nightly news may
have been a missed opportunity rather than a cynical marketing
strategy. By David Schiff. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   BRAHMS-BIO (Undated) _ Some biographers see clearly. They keep
their affections in tow and tell the unpleasant facts. Jan
Swafford's ``Johannes Brahms'' (Alfred A. Knopf) does this, at
least to a point. What Swafford writes about Brahms and the people
around him rarely flinches from the fact that the great German
composer was in many ways not a nice man at all. By Bernard
Holland. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC  &LR;  KURT-COURTNEY-FILM (Undated) _ Courtney Love has a
genius for alienating people. That's one indisputable fact that
emerges in ``Kurt and Courtney,'' the documentary by Nick
Bloomfield that opened on Friday. Ex-boyfriends, ex-employees,
acquaintances and even Ms. Love's father are more than happy to say
nasty things about her. By Jon Pareles. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   MILES-DAVIS-WEBSITE (Undated) _ Computers speak in many
different voices, but the one coming out of the PC on Bret
Primack's desk is likely to startle even the most jaded of Web
surfers. Low, amused and overcareful, it sounds suspiciously like a
man who has just taken a good-sized shot of heroin, and not without
reason: the speaker is Charlie Parker, jazz's best-known junkie.
``I had the pleasure to meet Miles for the first time in St. Louis
when he was a youngster,'' says the digitized Parker, referring to
Miles Davis, the subject of www.milesdavis.com, an interactive Web
site designed by Primack that opened for public viewing two weeks
ago. By Terry Teachout. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART  &LR;  CARICATURE-ART (Washington) _ The National Portrait
Gallery's current exhibition in Washington, ``Celebrity Caricature
in America,'' with 229 drawings, paintings and artifacts on view
through Aug. 23 trace the rise of a new, formally playful approach
to caricature that flowered in the years between the two world
wars. By Art Spiegelman. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-ART (Undated) _ For Berlin's latest incarnation as
Germany's capital, the federal government plans to order more than
$33 million of freshly painted Neo-Expressionist canvases, cerebral
conceptual installations, neon sculpture and perhaps even earth
works. By Michael Z. Wise. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MORE-TALES-TV (Undated) _ As you might guess from the title,
``More Tales'' (to be shown Sunday night and Monday night at 9) is
the follow-up to ``Armistead Maupin's `Tales of the City.' ''
Although award-winning and hugely popular when broadcast on PBS in
1994, the original series included enough casual drug use, fleeting
nudity and happy same-sex relationships to provoke the
by-now-predictable bomb and assassination threats from religious
groups. ``More Tales'' is based on the second of the best-selling
series of novels that Armistead Maupin began writing in 1976 as a
daily column for The San Francisco Chronicle. By Stephen McCauley.
(To come).
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-TV (Undated) _ The Discovery Channel's three-hour
special ``Robert F. Kennedy: A Memoir'' (beginning Sunday night at
8), based on Jack Newfield's 1969 book, is about politics, of
course. It's about the Senate racket hearings, the civil rights
movement, presidential campaigns, power plays and the Vietnam War.
But the personal side of Kennedy, who was assassinated in Los
Angeles 30 years ago (June 5, 1968), comes across with just as much
impact. By Anita Gates. (To come).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SEINFELD-SCRIPTS-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ As they say on television,
stay tuned: On June 18, little more than a month after the
quintessentially self-involved quartet from ``Seinfeld'' went the
way of the barroom busybodies on ``Cheers'' and the medics on
``M-A-S-H,'' Christie's East is scheduled to auction the 68-page
script with all the ``alrights.'' Christie's East estimates that
the script from the 1992-93 season will go for $1,500 to $2,000. By
James Barron. (To come).
</P>
