<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0681 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSTON-OPERA-425&AMP;ADD     06-02 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-OPERA-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOREADOR, LOOK OUT FOR THE FLOOR (IT'S NOW HYDRAULIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATE MURPHY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ What do you get when you cross classical opera with a
contemporary rock concert? You get Carmen in a rhinestone-studded
bustier belting out the Habanera into a headset microphone.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's Houston Grand Opera's answer. In an effort to
reach a broader (read younger, hipper) audience in the kinds of
outdoor sites more likely to reverberate with the sounds of Bono
than Bizet, the opera company has designed a portable, multimedia
stage like those used by touring rock bands. And it has created a
flashy production to match.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, it presented ``Carmen'' outdoors at the Cynthia Woods
Mitchell Pavilion in The Woodlands, a suburb 27 miles north of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Tossing a Tina Turner hairdo and stomping spike-heeled go-go
boots, Carmen, sung by the mezzo-soprano Suzanna Guzman (who got
her start singing in a rock band called Apricot Brandy), met her
tragic fate on the troupe's new $1.3 million Multimedia Modular
Stage. A 50,000-pound steel-and-plexiglass Erector Set, the stage
takes two days to assemble into a 5,559-square-foot multitiered
space with platforms that rise and fall on four hydraulic lifts. It
also has five enormous video screens and hundreds of rotating,
colored lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've seen a Rolling Stones concert, you know the
concept,'' said Ken Billington, a Broadway lighting designer who
worked with the set and costume designer Kenneth Foy to come up
with the layout.
</P>
<P>
   More than 7,000 people attended the performance, which received
mixed reviews. Critics praised the daring new production concept
but found the orchestra sound anemic, because the stage
accommodated just half the usual number of strings. Another
complaint was that the singers were not practiced in the nuances of
performing with live video. (They often had their backs to the
camera.)
</P>
<P>
   Like so many American opera companies, Houston's has been
confronted with declining government grants, almost stagnant
attendance and a graying audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to find a medium to introduce youth to opera in a
high-impact way,'' said the company's general director, David
Gockley. The high-tech stage was created to make opera more
accessible by taking it, both physically and ideologically, to
members of the MTV generation.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the stage enable productions in the suburbs, far
from the expensive seating and perceived snootiness of the
company's downtown concert hall, but ``it gives us the opportunity
to present opera in a way that appeals to what has become a very
visually engaged society,'' Gockley said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Saturday's performance of ``Carmen,'' lights and smoke
whirled from all directions. Instead of using traditional sets and
backdrops, the technical staff created mood and scene through the
rapid-fire projection of more than 350 images (a bullfight, for
example, or a rising moon) onto three upstage video screens. Two
screens flanking the stage showed live video of the performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rich production, with lots of quick cuts, brash color
and hard angles,'' said Foy. The orchestra was at center stage, as
if it were a rock-and-roll band. The singers pranced around the
musicians, wearing skin-tight leather.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Assaf, whose experience lies in directing and
choreographing music videos and Mick Jagger's 1989-90 solo tours of
Japan and Australia, staged this ``Carmen.'' ``I've never done
opera,'' she said. ``But this isn't your typical opera.''
</P>
<P>
   The amplified voices, while true to the original libretto, sang
in English rather than French.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will definitely offend purists,'' said Patrick J. Smith,
editor of Opera News. Traditionalists may have become inured to
translations of Carmen, because the popular opera has been
subjected to a lot of ``manhandling'' over the years, he said, but
``the whole point of opera is the unamplified voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Billington argues, however, that the point of opera depends on
the place where it is performed. ``When you're playing to thousands
of people on a green, it's not about the natural voice,'' he said.
``It's about huge visual and sound effect.''
</P>
<P>
   During opera's long history, the primacy of the voice has often
given way to other elements of production. In 17th-century Venice,
for instance, audiences packed opera houses not so much to hear
arias but to see spectacles accomplished by intricate stage
machinery.
</P>
<P>
   John Dizikes, author of ``Opera in America: A Cultural History''
(Yale University Press, 1995), said the Houston Grand Opera's
``Carmen'' completed the cycle. ``We've gone back to the
extravaganza,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gockley said he saw the production as a way to attract
people to traditional opera rather than as a revolution in its
presentation. Unlike other Houston opera productions, which have 8
to 10 performances, ``Carmen'' on the traveling stage will have
only 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to plant a seed, so that young people might want to see
more opera indoors under ideal acoustic circumstances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Endowment for the Arts, which along
with private organizations provided financial support for the new
stage, said they hoped there was room for both traditional and
rock-concert-style opera productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be an either-or proposition when the goal here is
a net gain in arts participation,'' said Wayne S. Brown, director
of music and opera at the endowment. ``It's a way to reach new
audiences and remain competitive in this visually oriented
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Following ``Carmen,'' the opera company plans pop-inspired
productions of ``La Boheme,'' ``Rigoletto,'' ``La Traviata'' and
``Madame Butterfly.'' Once this repertory is complete, the company
may pack its stage onto 4 tractor-trailers (the stage for the
Rolling Stones' current ``Bridges to Babylon'' tour requires 15)
and travel around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Stadiums and amphitheaters are likely destinations, but ``the
idea behind this new stage is that we can just set up in a
cornfield somewhere,'' Gockley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
