<SLUG> BC-TV-SIMPLE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SIMPLE LIFE': YOU CAN TAKE THE GIRL OUT OF THE CITY ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILL JOYNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How difficult is it to find the simple life these
days? About as difficult as it is to come up with a situation
comedy that's fresh, smoothly paced and cleverly written.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find abundant proof of this in ``The Simple Life,'' a
forgettable new show that CBS is mercilessly sending into the
early-summer void Wednesday night at 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this clunker is a reasonable premise that is
made to feel tired from the start. Sara Campbell (Judith Light of
``Who's the Boss?'') plays a Martha Stewart-like figure,
``America's authority on achieving a relaxed, homespun life
style,'' who realizes the many ironies of her situation and decides
to move herself and her television show from Manhattan to a farm in
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing her are an assortment of frenetic studio types as well
as her mother, Muriel (Florence Stanley), who is reluctant to leave
Queens, and Sara's daughter (Ashlee Levitch), who vies for
attention by flunking out of college after college.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the not-so-simple virtues of rural ambition and
industry is Luke Barton (Brett Cullen), the foreman of the farm
Sara has purchased. He owns a prize bull, and the tenor of the
humor in ``The Simple Life'' is quickly defined when his first
encounter with Sara turns into a misunderstanding over the term
``stud service.'' (Reinforcing this tone is a desperately contrived
guest appearance by Fran Drescher of ``The Nanny.'')
</P>
<P>
   Cultures proceed to clash predictably as Sara tries to
rediscover herself and her loved ones amid the kitschy empire she
has created.
</P>
<P>
   Running throughout the first episode are echoes of estimable
sitcoms of the past, from ``The Andy Griffith Show'' to ``The
Beverly Hillbillies'' to ``Green Acres' to various ``Lucy''
incarnations. What's especially sad here is how faint those echoes
are and how ill-equipped, despite a perfectly capable cast, ``The
Simple Life'' is to improvise upon them.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE SIMPLE LIFE
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Wednesday night at 8:30 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York area)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sternin, Prudence Fraser and Pam Norris, executive
producers and writers; directed by Pam Fryman. A production of
Montrose Productions in association with Tri-Star Television.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Judith Light (Sara Campbell), Brett Cullen (Luke),
Florence Stanley (Muriel), Ashlee Levitch (Freddie), James Patrick
Stuart (Greg), Ross Malinger (Will), Eliza Dean (Charlotte).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROCESS-BOOK-REVIEW-N     06-02 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROCESS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE PROCESS': GIVING IN FOR PEACE, AND STANDING UP TO YOUR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: publication notes at end of review) 
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the age of diplomacy, when negotiations in Bosnia,
Northern Ireland and the Middle East have eased or ended violence
and changed the world. So it is natural that this also be an age of
instant history books, the records of the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Richard C. Holbrooke has recently published an informative and
readable account of his efforts to end the Bosnian war. Now comes
Uri Savir, Israel's chief negotiator, with this record of the talks
starting in Oslo in 1993 and ending in Taba on the Sinai Peninsula
in 1995 with an agreement for Israel to turn most of the occupied
West Bank over to the Palestine Liberation Organization. Can George
Mitchell, the mediator in Northern Ireland, be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   While we wait for Mitchell, Savir has given us plenty to mull
over in ``The Process,'' his detailed, balanced, intelligent and in
places intensely moving chronicle of the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations. Savir, who wrote his book in English, has produced a
fine piece of diplomatic history. Embedded in his account is also a
powerful defense of the Israeli-Palestinian agreement, attacked as
an act of treason by the Israeli far right and as humiliation and
submission by the Palestinian and other Middle East radicals intent
on destroying it.
</P>
<P>
   Savir's book is also the record of a friendship with a man who
was first introduced to him in Oslo as ``your Enemy No. 1.'' This
enemy-turned-friend is Ahmed Qurei, known as Abu Ala, Savir's
Palestinian counterpart (and now speaker of the Palestinian
Legislative Council). In Savir's portrait of the talks, he and Abu
Ala formed a microcosm of the Palestinian-Israeli relationship, or
at least a microcosm of that part of it that was able to overcome
decades of murderous hostility and produce extraordinary and
unexpected scenes of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of his book, for example, Savir describes a meeting
led by Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres (having taken over for
the assassinated Yitzhak Rabin) and PLO chairman Yasser Arafat.
Present were other former enemies: senior Israeli army and security
officials and leaders of Palestinian security and intelligence,
including several men who had served long terms in Israeli prisons.
The meeting was held so that the Palestinian commander, Mohammed
Dahlan, speaking in Arabic, could brief the Israelis on ``how his
people were systematically fighting terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were developing a new routine that signaled a profound
change in the nature of our relationships,'' Savir remarks. Not
long after that, while the senior Israelis were celebrating their
Independence Day, the Palestinian National Council voted 504 to 54
to nullify the articles in its covenant that called for the
destruction of Israel. `` `Who would ever have thought that we'd be
celebrating a PNC decision on Independence Day!' a young colonel
standing near me remarked,'' Savir writes. ``The Palestinian
Council's decision that day was, at last, recognition of our
independence by the most bitter of former enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   Savir, of course, is well aware of the precariousness of the
Israeli-Palestinian agreement and the possibility, especially since
Rabin's assassination in November 1995, that it might not hold. He
does not wax sentimental or mawkish in his account, but he does
certainly hold to a vision of the Palestinians, and especially of
Arafat, that is sharply different from that of conservative critics
of the agreement, both in Israel and among American Jews. Whereas
the latter hold to the view that Arafat has not relinquished the
Palestinian dream of destroying Israel, Savir portrays the
Palestinian leaders as sincere in their desire for a workable
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The descriptions of Arafat are in this sense among the most
gripping in Savir's account. He depicts Arafat as volatile, crafty
and often touchy but also as a skilled and adaptable negotiator
caught between his demands for Palestinian dignity and Israeli
demands for guaranteed security. Arafat could fly into a rage and
threaten to terminate the talks, and then, without explanation,
make the concession that allowed some halted element in the peace
effort to continue.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, for example, the Palestinians had brought the
talks to a stop by demanding that Jewish settlers be removed from
the center of Hebron, a move that the Israeli side found
politically impossible. This was shortly after an Israeli settler,
Baruch Goldstein, had gunned down 31 Arab worshipers inside the
Cave of the Patriarchs, an act of barbarism that, among other
things, forced the Palestinians to stiffen their resolve on the
Hebron issue. When Savir rather lamely suggested that the Red Cross
could serve as an ``international presence'' to help insure
Palestinian security, Arafat exploded. ``Unbelievable!'' he
shouted. ``You want to humiliate me, HUMILIATE me!'' But in the
end, Savir says, Arafat made ``a hard and unpopular decision,''
namely to resume the talks without the removal of the settlers.
</P>
<P>
   On the Israeli side, Savir gives Peres great credit for staying
the course, especially in the face of what he saw as unreasonable
Israeli hesitation to move forward. On the issue of Hebron for
example, Peres wanted to accede to a Palestinian demand for a
police station in the city center. When an Israeli general objected
on the ground that the settlers would be angry, Peres shouted:
``You want 150,000 Hebronites to remain under our control because
of 400 Jews? There's a limit to arrogance and a limit to
timidity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Process'' is often a complicated book, reflecting the
complexity and occasionally the dry, technical nature of the
negotiations. It ends, necessarily, in uncertainty, with Savir out
of government after the election of Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in 1996 and the peace effort mired in distrust and
obstructionism. But it would be hard to imagine a better or clearer
account of how matters got to the present point than the one Savir
provides in this book.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE PROCESS
</P>
<P>
   1,100 Days that Changed the Middle East
</P>
<P>
   By Uri Savir
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 336 pages. Random House. $27.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
