<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPTATION-TUILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TUILE: FRAGILE, BUTTERY, AND QUICK TO DISAPPEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Traditionally, the tuile, the French almond cookie,
is a curved concoction of butter, sugar, flour and almonds that is
named after the rounded roof tiles found throughout France. The
cookie bakes flat, and as it comes out of the oven, warm and
pliable, it's wrapped around a rolling pin to give it the shape.
But the tuile from Ceci-Cela is different. ``I make them flat,''
said Laurent Dupal, the chef and co-owner of the patisserie at 55
Spring St., ``because they are very, very fragile'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the world of pastry making, fragility is often a sign of
excellence.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ceci-Cela tuile is so buttery, and so delicate, that the
moment you put it into your mouth, and touch it with your tongue,
it begins to crumble into crisp buttery, almond-flavored morsels. A
near-perfect cookie, it can stand alone and be eaten by itself, one
after another until a half-pound box is suddenly empty, or used as
an accompaniment to a simple summer dessert of fresh strawberries,
mangoes or Asian pears.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of its evanescence is to use ``as little flour as
possible,'' Dupal said. ``The way we make them is to whip the
butter and the sugar and make them very light. After that we
incorporate the egg whites, one by one, and then a little bit of
flour, and finally the minced almonds,'' he said. Using a pastry
bag, he squeezes a little ball of cookie dough onto the sheet pan,
and bakes them at 340 to 350 degrees in a regular oven for 8 to 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They melt very slowly and will go flat, flat, flat,'' Dupal
said. Four cookies sell for $1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0722 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-GORE-COX &UR;  &UR; M     06-02 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-GORE-COX </SLUG>
     MILLENIUM BUG BUGS GORE
 &HT;     Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;     By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Technology buffs call it the ``millennium bug.''
But for Vice President Al Gore, known for his expertise on
technology, the bug has become a political hornet with a nasty
partisan sting.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problems came to the fore Tuesday when Republicans
accused the White House of failing to do enough to avert a
government-wide digital meltdown as the clock strikes midnight on
Dec. 31, 1999 _ just as Gore is expected to be gearing up his
campaign to succeed President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The troubling question is: Why are President Clinton and Vice
President Gore moving so slow, and being so quiet, on an issue that
could have such a serious impact on so many people?'' said Steve
Forbes, an undeclared Republican rival for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is too important an issue for the administration to play
politics with. People need to be aware of the risks that lie
ahead.'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Forbes issued a memo to ``members of Congress and
conservative leaders'' on the Year 2000 problem that asked, ``What
has the administration's technology point man, Vice President Al
Gore, been doing for the past five years?''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes cited a report released earlier Tuesday by Rep. Steve
Horn, R-Calif., that ranked federal agencies on how well they were
doing to squash the multibillion-dollar millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   Horn's grades ranged from F's for the Energy, Transportation,
State, and Health and Human Services Departments to an A-plus for
the Social Security Administration, which, he said, was already 92
percent compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Horn lowered the government's overall grade to an F from a
D-minus in February, citing ``a disturbing slowdown in the
government's rate of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem arose because many older computer systems use of a
two-digit dating system that assumes 1 and 9 are the first two
digits of the year. Without a fix, these systems will read ``00''
not as 2000 but 1900, which could cause them either to fail or spew
out bad data.
</P>
<P>
   Horn, the chief House watchdog on the Year 2000 problem,
demanded that Clinton make fixing it a top priority. He noted that
Prime Minister Tony Blair had spoken to his own countrymen on the
problem and added, ``We've got to see the same thing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Horn declined, however, to take a swipe at Gore, a fully
computer literate politician who prides himself at having taught
Clinton how to send E-mail from a laptop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress only deals with presidents,'' Horn said, ``The vice
president, under the Constitution, has one role, and that is to
preside over the Senate, and that's historic. And everything else
over the last 40 years, the president gives him the assignment. We
don't tell the vice president what to do. We respectfully request
that the president do something.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Horn demanded that Clinton name a millennium czar.
Shortly afterward, Clinton created a special White House council to
spearhead the governmental efforts to avert widespread computer
problems in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gore who recruited John Koskinen, a retired top budget
official who had specialized in crisis management, to lead the
council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having lots of meetings on this problem,'' a Gore
spokesman said. Other officials said Clinton was in fact consulting
with Gore as he prepared to deliver a major statement on the Year
2000 issue. That is expected after the Office of Management and
Budget issues its own quarterly report on the topic, probably
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-GORE-COX &UR;  &UR; M     06-02 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-GORE-COX </SLUG>
