r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN03-COX     06-02 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins throw tough questions toward Green
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ It's a scary place Yatil Green finds himself these
days, and he can't quite get past the fear.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway, which he admits. And maybe not ever, which he
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Has the surgical scar running along his right knee left a
psychological scar? It happens all the time in sports, you know,
and Green knows it, too, now.
</P>
<P>
   He's the kid wide receiver who came out of the University of
Miami all big and strong and fast, but maybe not so tough. That
maybe-not-so-tough part was a enough of a factor to drop Green so
far down the 1997 NFL draft list that he was still available when
the Dolphins' turn came up with the 15th selection.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Jimmy Johnson, trying to decide whether huge
potential was worth significant risk, told Green on the phone
before making the official announcement of his pick: ``Yatil, I
don't want any groin pulls or hamstring pulls.''
</P>
<P>
   Green promised.
</P>
<P>
   And then on July 17 of his first training camp last summer, he
tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee. What would
have been Green's rookie season was lost.
</P>
<P>
   So there he sat at his cubicle in the Dolphins' training
facility ready for the light-contact drills run as part of a
quarterback school mini-camp.
</P>
<P>
   Green doesn't know what to think. He only knows what he knows.
And what he knows is he's ``not as fast as I used to be.'' He
expects that speed to return, but mentions how his knee doesn't
flex the way it used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're fast and you're comfortable, you feel your heel
hit you in the butt when you run,'' Green said. ``I don't have
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped speaking and looked at the floor, perhaps dreaming of
the time when he can once again give himself a good and literal
butt-kicking. But when might that be? Questions about Green's
fragility have resurfaced, despite in-house reports that he was
dedicated to the rehabilitation process.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, Green was considered one of the possible
answers to the Dolphins' offensive problems. Now, he's a question.
A big one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like he was 100 percent to me,'' Johnson said after
the practice session. ``He didn't pull back from anything. We'll
have to wait and see. We've got to see him do something first. He's
doing it in shorts. Let's see him do it in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who says he always gets his message across, was sending
an obvious one. There'll be no parades for Green.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Dolphins and their head coach understand how much they
need a receiver with Green's speed and size. But they're preaching
toughness (yes, again) as an underpinning for what they hope will
produce an effective running game, and toughness is something Green
must demonstrate to them now more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Green ran all the patterns in Monday's heat. He made some clean
cuts, and slipped on some others. He made some catches, and missed
some others. He just missed running under a long ball down the
right sideline against defensive pressure, but caught one deep on
the opposite side a full stride ahead of his pursuer.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if he had re-discovered the old confidence and
swagger, Green was disarmingly honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``See,'' he said, and stopped for a full snapcount. ``Not
exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   He's stuck in that scary place.
</P>
<P>
   And if he doesn't escape, the Dolphins might be stuck in one of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
