s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAHMS-BIO-$ADV07-NYT     06-02 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAHMS-BIO-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BRAHMS BIOGRAPHY LENDS AID AND COMFORT TO A BULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 7)  
 (bl)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Biographers end up as advocates. They can't help it.
The years spent reconstructing the lives of others, seeing through
their eyes, thinking their thoughts, turn the writer into a sibling
by adoption, a loyal part of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Some biographers see clearly. They keep their affections in tow
and tell the unpleasant facts. Jan Swafford's ``Johannes Brahms''
(Alfred A. Knopf) does this, at least to a point. What Swafford
writes about Brahms and the people around him rarely flinches from
the fact that the great German composer was in many ways not a nice
man at all.
</P>
<P>
   Brahms, it seems, enjoyed denigrating his equals and humiliating
his inferiors. He reveled in Germany's renascent militarism; and
though he denounced anti-Semitism, one speculates uneasily about
what his politics might have been had he lived 50 or 60 years
later. (He was born in 1833 and died in 1897). Brahms' attitude
toward women exceeded even the misogynies of his times. The several
loves of his life sooner or later found themselves brusquely
dumped; even his lifelong object of affection, the humorless,
fanatic, and devoted Clara Schumann, felt the effects of his bad
manners and tactlessness, mingled as they were with sincere
demonstrations of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Brahms had his assets. He was basically modest and immune to
wealth and luxury, though both were his for the asking. He was
loyal to his family and endlessly generous to them. He had his
convivial side and happily ate and drank his way through life. He
liked children, but never married.
</P>
<P>
   It is on the subject of what Brahms didn't like that Swafford
gives me trouble. Liszt, Wagner, and Bruckner lead the list, and
our biographer misses no opportunity to tell us what Brahms and
company thought about the Music of the Future.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Brahms on Liszt's ``Christus'': ``incredibly boring,
stupid and absurd.'' A Brahms friend, Theodor Billroth, on Liszt's
symphonic poems: ``toilet paper music.'' Clara Schumann on Wagner's
``Tristan und Isolde'': ``the most repulsive thing I ever saw or
heard in my life.'' Brahms on Bruckner: ``As to his piety _ that's
his business, it's nothing to me. But this thrashing around is
disgusting to me, completely repugnant. He has no conception of a
musical logic, no idea of an orderly musical structure.''
</P>
<P>
   On it goes, one insult following another: ``Judas Iscariot,''
``old mountebank,'' ``garish and overripe,'' ``too Lisztian for
comfort.'' Strong stuff, though ``strong'' might not be enough of a
word. There is a touch of hysteria in these criticisms; they smell
ever so slightly of fear.
</P>
<P>
   Brahms was a continuer. His music begins in the past and draws
its virtues into the present. The Music of the Future cut old ties
and looked ahead. It also threatened to engulf Brahms' sober,
craft-oriented style of composition. He knew it and fought back.
Granted, the Wagnerian side was just as vicious. (See Cosima
Wagner's diaries.)
</P>
<P>
   Why such sectarian virulence in so expansive an age? Music seems
to breed in its creators the worst kinds of insecurity, and I don't
think that Swafford, himself a composer, quite takes into account
the venom and envy by which classical musicians _ big and small,
ancient and modern _ seem universally infected.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, he is a professional recorder of other
people's thoughts, and scrupulously so. Occasionally, however, he
speaks for himself: ``In sheer ambition, tenacity of purpose, and
power of expression, what Brahms achieved in the 44 minutes of the
C minor Symphony rivals Wagner's achievement in the 12 hours of the
`Ring.' '' Swafford adopts the bellicose partisanship of his
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Such cheerleading is fine, but one looks in vain for a few words
from the defense. If you are to cite Joseph Joachim describing
Liszt's performing style (``shameless grandstanding in performance
_ the grimacing and fainting, the suffering-Christ act''), might
you not also mention the utter stillness at the keyboard that so
many remembered of Liszt, as if, they said, he were not playing at
all?
</P>
<P>
   If you are going to report on how repulsive Clara Schumann found
``Tristan und Isolde,'' could we not also know that in the view of
more than a few, ``Tristan'' dwarfs in power and imagination
anything Brahms ever wrote? Is Bruckner to be described only in
terms of his garish behavior and not for the opening pages of the
Seventh Symphony, which represent Romantic art at its apogee?
</P>
<P>
   Swafford's silence in the face of these appalling attacks can
only signal complicitous assent. Such silence weakens his book.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Liszt wrote bad music: show-business bad. So did Brahms,
although his failures took the form of aridity (born naturally of
his faultless musical logic). Could not Swafford at least mention
Liszt's heavenly minor-major shift halfway into ``La Vallee
d'Obermann,'' the extraordinary generosity of the ``Transcendental
Etudes,'' the bleak, near-atonal explorations of the last pieces,
and ``The Fountains at the Villa d'Este,'' which is Impressionism's
ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   In allowing his cast of characters to poke fun at Liszt's
grandness without fear of contradiction, Swafford robs of us of
Liszt's magnanimity, his unselfishness, his astonishing grasp of
music and the dignity with which he lived a difficult life. Liszt
accepted the insults of Brahms, Clara Schumann and Joachim with
genuine forbearance, making all three of them look small in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Brahms planned his posterity, not only by destroying his
failures but also by belittling his contemporaries. As
concertgoers, we are all marked by him. For like Brahms, we take
comfort in the past and fear the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
