<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0736 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN03-COX     06-02 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gailey is exactly what Cowboys need
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Chan Gailey once was turned down by Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has never been a head coach in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey ran the wishbone as coach of Division II Troy State.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, they don't make offensive geniuses like they used to.
However, this 46-year-old relatively obscure quarterback guru could
make the offensively puny Dallas Cowboys a Super Bowl contender
again faster than you say ``field goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever package these offensive magicians come in _ and
this one comes in a thoughtful, red-haired package with no ego
attached _ Gailey seems to be exactly what the Cowboys need.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Pittsburgh Steelers offensive coordinator
wasn't Jerry Jones' first choice in mid-February, almost two months
after a 6-10 season ended and Terry Donahue was seriously courted.
It appears clear he was the right one.
</P>
<P>
   What's most curious after 10 successful years in the NFL but
only two as a coordinator is that this Georgia native wasn't
scooped up before now. His name had appeared on several short
lists, including that of the St. Louis Rams before they lulled Dick
Vermeil out of retirement. Pittsburgh's Bill Cowher pushed aside
offensive coordinator Ron Erhardt after the 1996 Super Bowl for
fear of losing Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was that astute. Six years ago, when Baylor's Grant
Teaff retired after the 1992 season, the Waco school brought in
this serious man with the innovative mind for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``They turned me down,'' Gailey said Monday during the Cowboys'
publicity stop in Austin, Texas. ``I knew I wasn't going to get the
job when I was there for a day and a half and interviewed with
everybody but the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was one of about 50 coaches Jones checked out to be Barry
Switzer's successor. Jerry's son, Stephen, the Cowboys' salary
capologist, said his father called him before the Steelers'
first-round playoff game and told him to pay particular attention
to Pittsburgh because he was considering Gailey and defensive
coordinator Jim Haslett.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just amazing what he accomplished with Kordell Stewart
in his first year as a quarterback,'' Stephen Jones said. ``My
respect for Chan just grows day by day. He's so focused and
intense.''
</P>
<P>
   That intensity is obvious. As Jerry Jones addressed the media,
Gailey listened hard. He measured his boss' every word, an obvious
student of everything.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones has been positively gushing about Gailey's
contagious enthusiasm. He and a recharged Michael Irvin talked X's
and O's for 2 1/2 hours during a trip to Mexico City, where Dallas
will play an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's infusion of energy and fresh ideas reminded Jones of
his initial season with the Cowboys in 1989 when he spied defensive
end Ed ``Too Tall'' Jones intently taking notes during a chalk-talk
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turns out Too Tall said he was taking notes for the first
time,'' Jones related. ``Before, the Cowboys never changed things,
and Too Tall said they used to have a problem staying awake.''
</P>
<P>
   Note-taking is definitely in this off-season. Gailey's exotic
formations with four and five wideouts at a time have served as a
dramatic wake-up call to a franchise that had gone stale. No longer
will the 20th-ranked offense consist of Emmitt Smith's dives
between the tackles, Troy Aikman incompletions because Irvin is
double-covered and a Richie Cunningham field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks transplant Chris Warren should light a fire under Smith
and prove to be a valuable pass receiver and third-down rusher.
Ernie Mills could return to the form he showed in Pittsburgh before
catching just 11 passes with Carolina last year.
</P>
<P>
   And Deion Sanders figures to be more than a big decoy, once he
recovers from ankle surgery, if Gailey has anything to say about
it. The Steelers ran more than they passed, but Gailey likes to
throw, and he has a future Hall of Fame quarterback to do so.
</P>
<P>
   So will Aikman line up at receiver like Stewart used to?
</P>
<P>
   ``Never say never,'' Gailey said. ``And never say always.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has put in the shotgun formation for almost exclusive use
on third down and in the two-minute offense, but this is no shotgun
arrangement between him and Jones. Jones is sold on Gailey, and so
are the players. Of the team's 51 players under contract, 49 have
not missed a workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were embarrassed by 6-10,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   In every sense of the word, Gailey is the anti-Switzer. He has
changed everything from meeting times to coaching staff. He won't
hire an offensive coordinator and will call all the plays. He
hasn't kept one offensive play from the previous regime's playbook,
not that that took much thought.
</P>
<P>
   He's labeled as a disciplinarian, but not a single Cowboy has
tested that trait. In fact, Gailey raved about the responsibility
and maturity level of his new team and calls the work ethic of the
veterans ``the biggest surprise'' since he came on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Chan has ever had to raise his voice,'' Stephen
said. ``The players are confident what he's saying is right.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach has not mandated a bunch of rules designed to gauge
the players' commitment. He has brought much-needed and, to this
point, universally accepted change.
</P>
<P>
   Why, even Jones has been so entranced at staff meetings, he
hasn't even offered any play suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' Gailey said, smiling. ``I don't have a Jerry
section (in the playbook), but we can have one if he wants one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
