<SLUG> BC-CUBS-DEMPSTER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Cavalcade of rookies' bestows 10-2 win on Cubs
 &HT;    By Cheryl Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was tough not to feel bad for Ryan Dempster. He
made his first major-league start under the lights on a beautiful
late-spring evening at Wrigley Field, and he wasn't around long
enough to enjoy the ambiance.
</P>
<P>
   Dempster, whose last start was a Class AA victory against the
New Haven Ravens on May 13, couldn't quite make the adjustment to
big-league hitting and the Chicago Cubs. He gave up two homers,
three walks and hit a batter before he could record his second out
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   He lasted three batters into the second before Marlins manager
Jim Leyland pulled him, and the Cubs went on to a 10-2 victory
before 25,538. Dempster was the sixth Marlin to make his
major-league debut and seventh rookie to start a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to set the `Wows' from playing at Wrigley apart from
what I have to do,'' Dempster said. ``It's frustrating. I told
myself to get ahead of the hitters. I didn't and it cost me. I'm
not too happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the worst part was Dempster entered the game with a
gaudy 31.50 ERA _ and it actually went up. He got the original
inflated number from his only two relief appearances, in which he
gave up seven runs in two innings. He threw 41 pitches against
Chicago, of which 20 were strikes.
</P>
<P>
   It started off well, as Dempster struck out Brant Brown to begin
the game. He then walked Mickey Morandini. Sammy Sosa, playing in
his first game after missing the last three games with a swollen
thumb, homered over left center. Dempster then walked Mark Grace,
and Henry Rodriguez homered to right to give the Cubs a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Blauser then walked, and Dempster hit Jose Hernandez with a
pitch. But Sandy Martinez struck out and starter Jeremi Gonzalez
grounded to short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate walking a guy after a home run because people might
think you pitch scared,'' Dempster said. ``My confidence isn't
wavering.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Brown led off with a double to left. Cliff Floyd
leaped to catch the ball, but it got lost in the vines that cover
the wall and Floyd came down empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Morandini then singled to right, scoring Brown. Sosa was
Dempster's final batter, and this time, he struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I pitched him a little better than the first time,
obviously,'' Dempster said.
</P>
<P>
   Vic Darensbourg came in for the Marlins and got Grace to ground
into a double play to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan fell behind, he made some mistakes in bad spots to guys
that can hurt you,'' Marlins pitching coach Rich Dubee said. ``In
the second, it didn't look like he was going to get himself
righted.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida could do little against Gonzalez. He faced the minimum
through four. The only base runner was Craig Counsell, who walked
in the third. But he was erased when Darensbourg grounded into a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins finally got to Gonzalez in the fifth. Todd Zeile hit
his first homer as a Marlin, to left field. He did it wearing his
old uniform number, 27. He asked first baseman Derrek Lee Sunday if
he could have the number he'd worn since high school, and Lee
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd followed Zeile with a double, and scored on Ryan Jackson's
single. The hit increased Jackson's hitting streak to seven games
and made it 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cubs ahead 7-2 in the eighth, Sosa hit his second homer
of the game off Oscar Henriquez, a three-run shot to left. The
crowd chanted, Sam-mee, Sam-mee, until he came out of the dugout
for a curtain call. It was the third time Sosa homered twice in a
game in his last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Dempster was still watching the game from the dugout. As soon as
the game ended, he had to think of his next start Sunday _ against
the New York Yankees, the best team in baseball, at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-02-98 0147E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
