<SLUG> BC-OHIO-AIRPORT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airport adds flights to Cancan and N.Y.
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Passenger traffic at the Dayton International
Airport got another boost Monday, June 1, when two airlines added
routes to New York City and Cancun, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Comair, a commuter airline serving Delta Air Lines Inc., started
a nonstop flight from Dayton to LaGuardia Airport in New York.
Sunworld International Airlines, new to the Dayton airport, started
its inaugural jet service from Dayton to Cancun on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials said passenger traffic in April increased
nearly 12 percent to more than 92,000, compared to April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The April passenger traffic increase represents our largest
monthly increase in more than four years,'' airport director Eugene
Conrad Jr. said. ``The first four months of 1998 have already
surpassed the same period of 1997 by 5.6 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comair flight to LaGuardia, offered once per day, is
Dayton's only nonstop to New York and is designed to accommodate
business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had several discussions with the Dayton airport and Dayton
Chamber of Commerce, and they really wanted to do something for the
businesses and business travelers in Dayton,'' said Merry Meyer,
spokeswoman for Cincinnati-based Comair.
</P>
<P>
   Comair, which flew about 5.4 million people in 1997, already
offers 10 daily flights from Dayton to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Airline passenger traffic and the choices in flights and fares
have sagged at the airport since it lost a USAir hub in 1992. But
Dayton airport officials said five airlines reported at least a 20
percent increase in April compared to last year. US Airways has
been the busiest carrier this year, with 68,064 passengers. Delta
is second, with 64,206.
</P>
<P>
   Cargo volume at the Dayton airport has also been on the rise.
During the first four months of the year, more than 307,000 tons of
freight has been handled, an 8.5 percent increase over the same
period last year. The biggest reason for the cargo increase is the
continued expansion of Emery Worldwide's hub.
</P>
<P>
   Emery's $56 million hub expansion is expected to create about
500 jobs. The project is slated for completion in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
