<P>
   PRINT _ Sprint Corp. introduces a new phone network that will
allow users to make multiple calls, receive faxes and use the
internet at high speeds, all at the same time through a single
connection. Sprint said the new network can deliver a voice call at
more than 70 per cent less than existing networks. It can also
provide full-motion video calls and conference calls at a cost less
than that of a long-distance call, Sprint said. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   3MOTO _ Motorola and another company announce their alliance to
develop digital signal processors. DSPs are being used in more and
more applications from wireless phones to HDTVs to cable modems to
digital cameras and auto collision warning systems. The market is
expected to grow 35 percent a year through 2002. Moto and its
partner want to grab a part of that market, rather than cede it to
Texas Instruments, which has a 48 percent share. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman). ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   3DSP _ What is a DSP? and what is it used in? (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman). ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   3TI _ Texas Instruments has bet the company on DSPs, a
technology is invented and developed. It has sold off just about
every other part of its business to concentrate on DSPs. So far,
it's a good bet. (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman). ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-JAPAN _ ATLANTA _ The number of airline seats flying
nonstop between Atlanta and Tokyo is about to take off. Delta today
starts daily nonstop service between Hartsfield and Narita
airports, joining Japan Airlines on the route. Where will all the
passengers come from? Delta, which has previously flown the route
with a stop in Portland Ore., expects to fill most of its seats
with connecting passengers from around the East who'll appreciate a
more streamlined route. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   with
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-FLIGHT _ ATLANTA _ Delta's Atlanta-Tokyo nonstop flights
will be in the air between 13 and 14 hours and travel 6,850 miles _
nearly 1,600 miles more than Delta's next-longest route. The flight
will consume 32,000 gallons of fuel and require four pilots, two of
whom sleep while the others fly. These and other factoids.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING _ A new report issued by Experian, a nationwide
real-estate data collector, suggests that home values are
increasing at their highest rate this decade. Even though
California, which leads the nation in appreciation, is bouncing
back from a time of depressed values, the nationwide average gain
is more than nine percent. Atlanta's rate is just over two percent.
(Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-AIRPORT _ Passenger traffic at the Dayton International
Airport got another boost Monday, June 1, when two airlines added
routes to New York City and Cancun, Mexico. Comair, a commuter
airline serving Delta Air Lines Inc., started a nonstop flight from
Dayton to LaGuardia Airport in New York. Sunworld International
Airlines, new to the Dayton airport, started its inaugural jet
service from Dayton to Cancun on Monday. (Wagner, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ In the end, the gathering of Internet
professionals who came from as near as Harvard's graduate school
and as far away as Australia had more on their minds than
Microsoft. That's good news for anybody who ever has or ever plans
to log on to the Internet. There were discussions of copyright,
community and the need to push harder to wire more people in more
countries as the millennium approaches. Americans tend to think the
Net is something uniquely American -- a toy used to read magazines
and browse movie Web sites. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   JUST-FOR-FUN _ ATLANTA _ No matter what portable electronic
device you use, from the smallest personal digital assistant to the
bulkiest laptops, Targus has a carrying case to fit and protect it.
Whether you love them or hate them, there's no denying the Spice
Girls have gained worldwide notoriety. Capitalizing on that
popularity and targeting Generation X and Y-ers, Polaroid has just
released SpiceCam, which it says is the first instant camera in
history to be named after a pop group. (And more news on
technology.) (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT _ ATLANTA _ It's not so much trouble to reach for the
stack of compact discs, pick the one you suddenly have a hankering
for, pop it into the CD player and hit play. But wouldn't it be
nice to just tap the CD player and have that tune start playing?
You can, if you have every single CD you own sitting in the CD
player. And you can have that if you have the cash to buy one of
the new Kenwood 200-disc CD mega-changers. (And other news on new
technology.) (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDSHOPPING _ ATLANTA _ Not surprisingly, there's a group of
re-released Frank Sinatra albums now in stores, with a second wave
set for Sept. 8 by Reprise and Capitol Records. Other areas of pop
music are fully covered this week with new releases from country,
rock, alternative and rap stars expected to roll in high on the
Billboard charts. (Reviews of recently released CDs.) (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/1.
</P>
