ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NCAATRACK-CHAMPIONSHIP _ Previewing the NCAA men's and women's
outdoor championship. It'll be Texas, LSU and newcomer UCLA
battling for the women's title. Riggs, Austin American-Statesman)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DRAFT _ Matt Belisle of McCallum and Mamon Tucker of Austin High
are likely first- or second-round draft picks in today's amatuer
baseball draft. (Davis/Halliburton, Austin American-Statesman) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   STODA-COLUMN _ DAVIE, Fla. _ It's a scary place Yatil Green
finds himself these days, and he can't quite get past the fear. On
July 17 of his first training camp last summer, he tore the
anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee. What would have been
Green's rookie season was lost. Green doesn't know what to think.
He only knows what he knows. And what he knows is he's ``not as
fast as I used to be.'' He expects that speed to return, but
mentions how his knee doesn't flex the way it used to. (Stoda, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GILKEY-DUI _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ On Monday, June 1, the New
York Mets outfielder who denied to police he was too drunk to drive
in March pleaded no contest to a misdemeanor charge of driving
under the influence. St. Lucie County Judge Dan Vaughn sentenced
Bernard Gilkey, 31, to a year of probation and 50 hours of
community service. His license was suspended for six months and he
must attend DUI classes and pay $250 plus court costs. Gilkey was
not in court when his attorney, Richard Kibbey, entered the plea.
(Cech, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CUBS-DEMPSTER _ CHICAGO _ It was tough not to feel bad for Ryan
Dempster. He made his first major-league start under the lights on
a beautiful late-spring evening at Wrigley Field, and he wasn't
around long enough to enjoy the ambiance. He lasted three batters
into the second before Marlins manager Jim Leyland pulled him, and
the Cubs went on to a 10-2 victory before 25,538. Dempster was the
sixth Marlin to make his major-league debut and seventh rookie to
start a game. (Rosenberg, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOHLS-COLUMN _ This 46-year-old relatively obscure quarterback
guru could make the offensively puny Dallas Cowboys a Super Bowl
contender again faster than you say ``field goal.'' But whatever
package these offensive magicians come in _ and this one comes in a
thoughtful, red-haired package with no ego attached _ Gailey seems
to be exactly what the Cowboys need. (Bohls, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
