<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: LAREDO TAKES POST IN VERMONT; MOMA ON FILM DRIVE;
BURIED TREASURES IN ROME; REMEMBERING EDWARD BURNE-JONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO TAKES POST IN VERMONT
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Laredo, the violinist and conductor, has been appointed
the artistic adviser of the Vermont Symphony Orchestra, based in
Burlington. Laredo, who lives with his wife, the cellist Sharon
Robinson, in Guilford, Vt., is to assume his new post almost
immediately. He will plan the orchestra's summer and winter
programs, starting with the 1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   His duties will include selecting music, soloists and guest
conductors, and offering guidance for artistic policy. He succeeds
Kate Tamarkin, music director of the orchestra, who is stepping
down at the end of the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   EXPANDED FOCUS
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aiming to add at least 200 films to its celebrated
archive (now 14,000 titles) by 2000, the Museum of Modern Art is in
the midst of a five-year campaign to reach its goal.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the harvest of the previously unannounced drive, called
``200 for 2000,'' will be showcased beginning this month, when
major works by Martin Scorsese, Woody Allen, Oliver Stone, Hal
Hartley, Joel and Ethan Coen, and John Sayles will be presented in
a summer series, ``A View From the Vaults: Recent Acquisitions and
Restorations,'' from June 19 through Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Still on the museum's wish list are films like Preston Sturges'
``Palm Beach Story'' (1942), Nicholas Ray's ``In a Lonely Place''
(1950), John Schlesinger's ``Midnight Cowboy'' (1969), Billy
Wilder's ``Some Like It Hot'' (1959) and Mel Brooks' ``Producers''
(1968).
</P>
<P>
   TRAJAN TROVE
</P>
<P>
   Italian archeologists drilling near an ancient fresco that was
recently unearthed in Rome have stumbled upon two new treasures: a
striking mosaic and another detailed fresco thought to be 2,000
years old. The discoveries were made at the Trajan Baths in the
city's historic center, near the fresco depicting a bird's-eye view
of the city that was discovered in March.
</P>
<P>
   TIME HONORED
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Metropolitan Museum of Art is commemorating the
centenary of the death of Edward Burne-Jones. On Thursday, the
museum opens the first American retrospective devoted to the work
of this pre-Raphaelite artist and designer. The exhibition,
``Edward Burne-Jones, Victorian Artist-Dreamer,'' which continues
through Sept. 6, offers what is described as the most comprehensive
assessment of his work.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the show, assembled from museums and private collections
around the world, consists of some 170 paintings, watercolors,
drawings, tapestries, embroideries, stained glass, ceramic tiles,
painted furniture, illustrated books and jewelry. Burne-Jones, who
was born in 1833 in Birmingham, England, was a pupil of Dante
Gabriel Rossetti and a protege of John Ruskin.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly self-taught, Burne-Jones had an abiding interest in
romantic and medieval subjects, particularly the Arthurian legend,
which provided much of the substance and style of his art. He died
on the night of June 16-17, 1898.
</P>
</TEXT>
