<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES SLIP FOLLOWING STRONG HOUSING REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury prices slipped on Tuesday for the first time
in four sessions amid signs that the economy was still growing at a
brisk clip. Prices were also held down by the prospects of more
corporate and government agency debt coming to market.
</P>
<P>
   A softer dollar and stabilizing stock markets in Asia added to
the downward pressure in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond fell 7/32, to 104 23/32. The
bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
rose to 5.79 percent, from 5.77 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Prices were hurt by a report that sales of new single-family
homes jumped 5.2 percent in April, to an annual rate of 888,000
units.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market was disappointed but not devastated by the
stronger-than-expected home sales data, primarily because the gains
were lopsided, with all areas except the South registering
declines,'' said Anthony Chan, managing director and chief
economist at Banc One Investment Advisors Corp., in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some of the flight-to-safety effects of the Asian
financial crisis quickly dissipated after investors heard the
comments of Robert Parry, the president of the San Francisco
Federal Reserve, who seemed to be playing down the long-term
effects of the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Chan said the comments that Parry made at a conference in Idaho
raised suspicion among investors that Parry did not think the Asian
crisis would prevent the Fed from raising rates if inflationary
pressures became apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are looking cautiously ahead of this Friday's release
of the government report on employment in May. Although some
bullish investors say the jobs report will show only moderate
growth, they are still somewhat nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Competing supply is also a worry for the Treasury market, as
traders brace for up to $15 billion of corporate and agency debt.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the Treasury sold $15 billion of 12-day cash-management
bills at an average rate of 5.30 percent. Cash-management bills are
used to meet the Treasury's short-term cash needs, in addition to
its regular schedule of debt sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
