<SLUG> BC-HANS-MARK-COX </SLUG>
     DEFENSE NOMINEE READY TO TACKLE PROLIFERATION
PROBLEM
 &HT;     By CHRISTI HARLAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Between congenial greetings Tuesday at his Senate
confirmation hearing, Pentagon nominee Hans Mark received solemn
reminders that recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan have
added new urgency to his pending job as director of defense
research and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will be at the vortex of that problem,'' Sen. John Warner,
R-Va., told Mark during the engineering professor's confirmation
hearing before the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mark, who teaches at the University of Texas in Austin, is
expected to win Senate approval for the job as chief technical
adviser to Defense Secretary William Cohen. The job will include
creation of the Defense Threat Reduction Agency, which will deal
with weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The agency ``will have the charter to go from basic research ...
to actually having groups in the field to deal with things like
nuclear accidents or inspection,'' Mark told the committee. ``I
think that the establishment of this agency will be the most
important thing that I will have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the job was underscored by the nuclear testing
that started in India less than a week after President Clinton
nominated Mark to the Pentagon post May 5. Pakistan responded with
its own weapons tests last week.
</P>
<P>
   Mark, who began his professional career in the 1950s working on
nuclear weapons, said he agreed to take the Pentagon job because he
wants to help curb the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years ago, I was very young when I started to work on
nuclear weapons,'' he said. ``I did so because I thought it was
very, very important for the United States to have the technical
leadership'' in that area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed,'' he said. ``What I'd like to do as I wind
up my career is to bring that same technical expertise that this
country has to bear ... on the control of these weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark's career has included previous presidential appointments as
secretary of the Air Force and as deputy administrator of the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration. He commemorated the
latter post Tuesday by wearing a NASA tie to his confirmation
hearing, where he was introduced by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
R-Texas, and greeted as a well-known and well-liked technical
expert by senators on the committee, which could explain his lack
of nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fourth time I've gone through this,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
