<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0773 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAR2000-GORE-HNS &LR;      06-02 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR2000-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS URGE CLINTON, GORE TO EXERT LEADERSHIP ON COMPUTER THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional experts on the Year 2000 computer
problem urged President Clinton on Tuesday to make it ``a national
priority'' to prevent the potential glitch from shutting down the
U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steven Horn, R-Calif., chairman of the House Government
Reform and Oversight subcommittee on technology, cautioned against
panic but urged Clinton to give it more attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and his administration must set priorities if
the conversion is to be successful. ... Now is the time for the
president to designate the Year 2000 problem as a national
priority,'' he said at a press conference on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate
Special Committee on the Year 2000 Problem, warned that it is
already too late to completely fix the nation's computers before
Jan. 1, 2000, and urged the Clinton administration to prepare for
the Year 2000 problem ``like a war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that on Jan. 1, 2000, power comes on,
that water continues to run, that the most vital functions of daily
life are completely safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett added: ``The only way that's going to get done is
through national leadership, which we haven't seen yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said Vice President Al Gore, who often leads
administration efforts on high-tech issues, should be the person to
address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But Bennett accused Gore of dodging the issue because of
concerns that his chances of becoming president would be damaged by
giving voters the pessimistic news associated with the Year 2000
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is both the obvious choice to lead the administration
and a dangerous choice because of his desire to be president,''
Bennett told a conference on the Year 2000 problem at the Center
for Strategic and International Studies, a non-partisan think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Peter de Jager, a Canadian who has been appointed to both the
British and Russian Year 2000 task forces, also urged Gore to
become more involved in the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Gore) should stop spending his time trying to put the
Internet in every high school and starting working on a problem
that threatens the entire global economy,'' de Jager told the CSIS
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's press secretary, Lawrence Hass, said both the president
and the vice president were ``fully on top of this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've spoken to the Cabinet heads ... and are regularly
briefed by their staff,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts warn that many computers originally programmed
to recognize only the last two digits of a year will fail or
malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines will assume it is
1900.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the glitch will be felt when one computer system
that thinks the year is 1900 interacts with another computer system
that thinks the year is 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Because computers can't think, neither system can understand why
it is 99 years ahead or behind. Unable to sort out the problem, the
two systems go into the equivalent of shock: The computers and
devices they drive either stop or give out wrong information.
</P>
<P>
   Some computers can be reprogrammed through tedious review of
their software code, but many devices have embedded microchips that
must be physically replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Horn's panel gave the federal government an ``F'' grade for its
efforts to resolve the Year 2000 problem with its most important
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The panel flunked the U.S. Department of Transportation, the
State Department, the Environmental Protection Agency, Department
of Energy, Department of Health and Human Services and the Agency
for International Development.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security Administration was the government's top
performer, earning an ``A plus'' from the Republican-controlled
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Horn noted that the Social Security Administration's top grade
is no guarantee that benefit checks won't be interrupted, for
example, because checks actually are issued by the Treasury
Department, which was given a ``C.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a potential bottleneck of dramatic proportions,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De Jager warned that the computer bug could wreak havoc on the
world economy. Even businesses that have fixed their own computers
could face a complete shutdown because of other companies' computer
failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when a businessman picks up the phone and there
is no dial tone? Tries to perform a financial transaction with a
bank and can't? Discovers that no supplies will be coming from
South Korea for the next two months? And that many of the companies
that used to buy his products can't anymore because their factories
are shut down?'' de Jager asked.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said that officials at General Motors Corp. told him
that if Jan. 1, 2000 were to occur this weekend, the company would
not be able to produce a single car on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist of Deutsche Morgan Grenfell's
North American division, predicted that the Year 2000 problem will
most likely cause a recession as severe as the economic downturn of
1974-1975. That recession was triggered by the Middle East's oil
embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's is no doubt that this will be cause some serious
disturbances in the United States,'' he said. ``The question is how
big will they be? And that will depend on what we do from this
point on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
