r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOUTIQUE-CROSSDRESS-L     06-02 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOUTIQUE-CROSSDRESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENDER BENDING IN THE VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Jim Bridges tries his darndest, really he does,
to make his clients pretty. But even red lipstick, padded bras,
industrial-strength girdles and false eyelashes can't always
transform an average Joe into a foxy lady.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bridges Boutique in Studio City is one of two shops on
Ventura Boulevard that cater to a cross-dressing clientele, men
whose alter-egos wear skirts and go by names like Lacie, Ginger and
Sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a truck driver,'' Bridges said, pointing to a photo of
a burly fellow in a boa. ``He never drives anywhere without a pair
of heels and a wig under the seat.''
</P>
<P>
   The redhead in the floor-length beaded gown? ``That's Big Mary.
He's a sheriff.''
</P>
<P>
   They may have the calves of Clydesdales and the shoulders of
Soviet shot-putters, but the tilt of their head and the come-hither
grin make it obvious they feel more like flirtatious females.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cross-dresser looks in the mirror and sees something
different than the rest of the world,'' Bridges said. ``I have
customers who are 6 feet tall, 200 pounds. They will put on a
slinky little dress and a wig without any makeup and they just get
this gleam in their eyes. They see not a man ... but an attractive
female who is 25- to 30-ish and a size 10 or 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Gender-bending has been a part of show biz as far back as
Shakespeare. From vaudeville to KISS, from ``Psycho'' to ``The
Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert,'' entertainers don
the accouterments of the other sex to shock or make us laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But real-life cross-dressers lament that they are misunderstood,
forced to keep a harmless proclivity in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not a bunch of freaks,'' Bridges said. ``They are men
who are trying to express something that is coming directly from
their soul, from their heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridges found his niche among the hordes of beauty consultants
in Los Angeles 12 years ago when a psychologist friend who ran a
support group for transvestites asked him to give the group some
beauty tips.
</P>
<P>
   Most transvestites, Bridges says, want to ``pass'' for women, so
he steers them away from get-ups that are sure giveaways: clothing
that is too trashy, or at the opposite extreme, frumpy, high-necked
ruffled blouses, long shapeless skirts, big glasses and low-heeled
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `I don't want to hurt your feelings, but you look like
Tootsie'.''
</P>
<P>
   The best chance of creating a convincing female form is wearing
well-tailored, sophisticated dresses, cut especially for men with
wide shoulders, and long sleeves and waist.
</P>
<P>
   He stocks large-size rings and size-14 shoes. High-heeled,
sling-back sandals in clear acrylic minimize foot size better than,
say, a red leather boot. A creatively tied scarf, a mock turtleneck
or choker necklace can disguise an Adam's apple.
</P>
<P>
   The most requested look? An anchorwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Bra size? 36C.
</P>
<P>
   The most common first-timer response after looking in a mirror?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God. I look like my mother!''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday afternoon, Larry Schulz went into Bridges'
boutique in jeans and a sweat shirt. He came out a blonde in
wide-rimmed black hat, gloves and a red suit.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation took about two hours and what seemed like 2
pounds of cosmetics. ``Beard camouflage,'' a heavy foundation used
to cover scar tissue on burn patients, would prevent Schulz from
suffering ``the Homer Simpson syndrome'' as the night wore on.
</P>
<P>
   A light-colored foundation on the cheekbones, a darker
foundation along the jawbone and two-toned blush contoured and
softened his masculine features.
</P>
<P>
   Next came an ``instant face-lift,'' accomplished by pulling the
skin on his face taut with clear surgical adhesive tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks my female side is younger than my male side,''
said Schulz, a divorced, 40-something North Hollywood man in the
antique restoration business.
</P>
<P>
   The finishing touch was bright red lipstick and ... voila!
</P>
<P>
   For $60, and the tasteful outfit he brought from home, Larry
became Gina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell the gals, `No matter how pretty the eyes are,
it's the lips that make the look,''' Bridges said. ``When the lips
go on, it starts to come to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them make a whole evening of it, starting with a
bubble bath and candles and music.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many cross-dressers, Schulz hid in his mother's closet as a
child and tried on her clothes. Once he came to terms with his
predilection, he found joy in playing dress-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my brighter side,'' Schulz said. ``It's my side that's
softer and gentler. I'm at peace with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He still struggles with stilettos and stubble, but he is in the
process of having his facial hair removed permanently with the help
of his current girlfriend, an electrologist.
</P>
<P>
   You might think one cross-dresser's boutique would meet market
demand. Not so. Down the road in Sherman Oaks, Lydia's TV (that's
short for transvestite) Fashions even rents lockers so men can
discreetly store potentially embarrassing items.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia's, which does business with the studios and with thousands
of customers worldwide through its mail-order catalog, is owned by
Kathy and Paul Klink.
</P>
<P>
   The couple met several years ago through a personal ad. She was
a paralegal; he, a former Air Force master sergeant and a veteran
of the Korean and Vietnam wars.
</P>
<P>
   When Paul revealed his peculiar penchant several months into
their romance, a stunned Kathy asked: ``You're gay?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Paul, like most cross-dressers, is straight.
</P>
<P>
   Within the subculture of men who dress like women, there are
divisions. Drag queens are generally gay men who adopt a campy,
hyper-feminine style. Some drag queens are also transsexuals, who
undergo sex-change operations.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-seven percent of cross-dressers are heterosexual, said
Richard Docter, a professor of clinical psychology at California
State University, Northridge, who has studied cross-dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent are married.
</P>
<P>
   Some men make the transformation as little as a few times a
year. For others, it's several times a week.
</P>
<P>
   But for most men, cross-dressing begins in early childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I have to do,'' Paul Klink said. ``This is
something so deeply ingrained in us, we have to satisfy that part
of our being.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Klink considered breaking off her relationship with Paul.
But she was tired of being single, and she loved him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the worldliness of a man and the softness of a woman,''
Kathy Klink said. ``Around the house, he is still a man.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep her happy, Paul Klink restricts cross-dressing to
Saturday nights, when a group of cross-dressers and their wives
meet for socializing at ``gender-friendly'' establishments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to makeovers for $60 ($125 with a rental outfit,
padding included), customers can browse through book titles such as
``My Husband Wears My Clothes,'' ``Where Boys Will Become Girls''
and ``Part Time Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Information about support groups and welcoming churches,
nightclubs and hotels is posted on a bulletin board.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Larry went out in public as Gina, Bridges
escorted him arm-in-arm to the Queen Mary Show Lounge, the club
next door where female impersonators draw a raucous crowd on
weekend nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first time, it feels like a long walk, like a football
field,'' Schulz said.
</P>
<P>
   But inside, a bit of booze, the suspension of reality and dim
bar lighting that can have the same effect on a less-than-perfect
face as a sheer dark veil, ``That's when all the magic comes
together,'' Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Gina, teetering at the 6-foot mark in heels, turned
heads as she strolled down Ventura Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time I can get by as a woman if I don't talk,''
Schulz said.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers in cars idling at a red light laughed. They stared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ha, ha, ha!'' howled one man, loudly so that Schulz would
hear.
</P>
<P>
   In the sunlight, you noticed her lipstick was feathered and
smudged on her tooth. A bit of face-lift tape protruded from the
wig.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, even Bridges admits that for men with particularly
masculine features _ a large nose, square jaw, wide forehead, broad
shoulders and big hands _ ``no amount of makeup, clothes, hair or
jewelry is going to camouflage that,'' Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
   For those clients, Bridges tells them to stop worrying about
``passing'' and instead just try to look good:
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may say, `Oh. That's a dude in a dress.' But at
least it will be a great dress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
