r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONION-WEB-LADN     06-02 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONION-WEB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONION SEASONED WITH TABLOID HUMOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The humor is sophomoric. OK, make that juvenile at
times.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the articles border on tasteless _ actually, forget
the borders. They are tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   And you'd swear the stories are made up.
</P>
<P>
   But no, we're NOT talking about L.A. Life. We're talking about
the Onion (www.theonion.com), the funniest Web site and humor
magazine to come giggling and snorting down the pike in years.
</P>
<P>
   The funniest, that is, if you don't count the bazillion Gillian
Anderson faux nude sites, which, for purposes of argument, we
won't. But you can think of the Onion as an ``X-Files'' site of its
own, a yuk-filled phenomenon too funny to forget or even adequately
explain.
</P>
<P>
   Witness such recent headlines as ``Gore Reprimanded for Failure
to Look Busy'' or ``New Wonder Drug Enables Users to Get Higher
Than Hell'' or ``Astronomer Discovers Center of Universe: `It's My
Beautiful 9-Year-Old Son,' he says.''
</P>
<P>
   A biting sendup of tabloid-style newspapers, the Onion comes
complete with useless info-graphics, dopey man-on-the-street
interviews, loopily earnest editorials and screaming headlines.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing too sacred or too low for the Onion to parody.
But what makes it so good _ and so laceratingly funny _ is its
dead-on parody of news-writing style _ turgid, uninspired prose so
serious that it has no sense of how silly it is.
</P>
<P>
   Like the editorial that could be the subtext of every
hand-wringing position taken by every newspaper that ever was:
``Somebody Should Do Something About All the Problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the boosterish, if not frighteningly believable business
story reporting ``New Starbucks Opens in Rest Room of Existing
Starbucks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to aspire to something that already exists,''
said Onion president and publisher Peter Haise. ``Given the weak
state of newspapers, that seemed like an easy target. We want to be
the only paper left standing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just a bunch of old hacks trying to do something
different,'' Haise said. ``A couple of guys started the paper, we
came on to help, from there it just sort of blossomed. It's been a
sweet little evolution. It was just a cruddy little, text-heavy
kind of idea.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years along, it evolved more fully into a spoof of
the news. In about 1993, the publication added a culture section,
called the A-V Club, with movie, music and other reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd last this long with it,'' said Haise, 30.
``I'm the elder statesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Onion, which began 10 years ago as and remains a
free weekly in Madison, Wis., is getting to be a very big
vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Its Web site is so popular that it gets about 3 million hits a
month, Haise said. Last fall, the Onion was named ``best written
site'' on the Net in the Cool Site of the Year awards, and was
named to PC Magazine's 100 best sites on the Internet for the
second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also is beginning to attract big-time national
advertisers such as Barnes &AMP; Noble, Sony Music and CD-NOW.
</P>
<P>
   The Onion's hard-copy version is also distributed in three other
markets: Milwaukee, Denver-Boulder and most recently, Chicago,
Haise said. And the company is trying to put together a national
distribution deal on top of the 160,000 local copies and 10,000
subscriptions that go out weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The Onion staff signed a six-figure deal with Hyperion Books to
create an offbeat take on the 20th century. The nearly complete
tome, tentatively titled ``Our Dumb Century,'' probably will be
released in the fall, Haise said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also trying to find a company that will sell its
line of goofy greeting cards, and it is using the Web site to sell
a variety of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Onion's brand of satire is going to offend some
people, such as when they ran the story ``Gulf War Syndrome Caused
by Idiots Who Join Army.''
</P>
<P>
   Or ``Nation's Stray Dogs Call for Increased Wino Vomit
Production.''
</P>
<P>
   Or ``Mother Teresa Sent to Hell In Wacky Afterlife Mix-Up.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Haise said, ``By the nature of it, it's not humor if
it's not a bit offensive. We're equal-opportunity offenders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
