<HEADER>
A0779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPSCALE-RESTAURANT-TR     06-02 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPSCALE-RESTAURANT-TRINKETS-ART-1STLD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP NEW YORK RESTAURANTS ARE OFFERING CHINA TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 (Eds: Please use this version)  
 By SUZANNE HAMLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prix fixe dinner at Lutece includes three courses
of the restaurant's specialties like smoked codfish with white
truffle oil, black bass with lobster sauce and pineapple
mille-feuille. It's $65, wine, tax and tip not included.
</P>
<P>
   The signature deep-blue and white Limoges plates aren't included
either, but they are, in fact, for sale ($180 for a five-piece
setting).
</P>
<P>
   And people are buying them. Designed for the restaurant's
executive chef, Eberhard Mueller, thechina is, Mueller said, ``the
highest quality, up to the standards of Lutece.'' And with a phone
call to Bergdorf Goodman, it can be yours.
</P>
<P>
   So can the logo-embossed silver wine coaster on the table at
Jean Georges; the restaurant has ordered a shipment to sell for $55
each. And at Aureole, there's an ash-wood box specially designed by
the architect Michael Graves _ $75 by itself, or $175 filled with
foods from the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   New York, of course, has plenty of theme-park restaurants like
the Hard Rock Cafe and Planet Hollywood, where you can order a
burger with a T-shirt on the side. But in the last couple of years,
more sophisticated establishments have been following suit, with
their own kind of refined commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, there's nothing so crass as a price tag in
sight. Often, it's a matter of asking if the pretty tableware is
for sale. Other times, one's shopping antennae must be up _ to put
2 and 2 together upon spying a display case that looks as though it
would be right at home in a hotel lobby.
</P>
<P>
   At La Caravelle, the French grande dame on West 55th Street,
diners who must wait a minute for a table can scrutinize the Chanel
watches on display in a locked glass case. Interested buyers are
directed to the Chanel boutique, two blocks north.
</P>
<P>
   In a continuing exercise in mutual image-buffing, the restaurant
is periodically represented by a little table and menu in Chanel's
window. And Thursday during lunch, models wearing Chanel's fall
line will saunter through the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties declined to be specific about exactly who pays whom
for what, but they agreed that the arrangement benefits both
equally. (In a further celebration of consumerism, the shelves in
La Caravelle's foyer which used to store men's hats is now a
decorative tableau of shopping bags from stores like Saks Fifth
Avenue and Tiffany'.)
</P>
<P>
   At Aureole, the Michael Graves box is discreetly displayed on a
pedestal next to a stack of cookbooks written by the chef and
co-owner Charlie Palmer. The dessert menu advises customers that a
maple Shaker box packed with a quarter-pound of the restaurant's
chocolates and some petits fours is available for $45. ``We don't
push it, but we sell about four a day,'' said Vincent Santoro, the
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the teddy bears at the Rainbow Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teddy bears at Rainbow are the most popular purchase at
the restaurant,'' said Robyn Massey, the director of public
relations for the Rainbow Room.
</P>
<P>
   Created by the designer of the waiters' uniforms, the costumed
bears, at $65, $75 and $85, include Rhonda the Cigarette Girl Bear,
outfitted in a black satin dress and wearing a perky pink pillbox
hat. The bear's outfit is identical with that of the real cigarette
girl (also, by the way, named Rhonda _ Rhonda Muziani), who roams
through the dining room with a tray full of bears looking for
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We substituted bears for cigarettes when the no-smoking laws
went into effect,'' Ms. Massey said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Whiteman, an wner of the Rainbow Room, sighed slightly
at the mention of the daily stuffed animal parade through the
restaurant, one of the world's most famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's an almost inevitable kind of brand marketing that is
happening all over the country now,'' said Whiteman, who as a
partner in the Joseph Baum &AMP; Michael Whiteman Co. is also an
international restaurant consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt if many restaurants make substantial amounts of money
selling merchandise, but it's great advertising,'' he said. ``A
restaurant souvenir is a permanent extension of the restaurant
experience. If you buy a plate and take it home, you'll remember
the experience every time you use it. If you give it to a friend,
so will they.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Room's silver-rimmed Art Deco-style dinner plates,
designed by Milton Glaser and made by Tiffany, are $30 a pair.
Sterling-and-enamel cuff links and stickpins are also for sale in
the display case by the cigar counter.
</P>
<P>
   Dale DeGroff, Rainbow's legendary bartender, is in the process
of designing a martini kit _ shaker, stirrer and glasses in a case
_ to add to the merchandise, which recently went on sale through
the restaurant's website (www.rainbowroom.com).
</P>
<P>
   The Monkey Bar is just getting into the act. On Monday, Hermes
china arrived at the restaurant very quietly _ for dessert. The
Hermes Africa pattern _ a subtle Noah's ark design that includes
monkeys _ has had a new desert designed especially to go on it, a
pastry, pineapple sorbet and rice pudding confection called the
Special Premie Hermes Africa Dessert fits both the design and the
mood of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who remark on the dish, which costs $98 and goes
safely into both microwave ovens and dishwashers, will be given a
brochure about the entire pattern, which can be purchased from the
Hermes shop a few blocks away, on East 57th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant, which will receive no compensation for acting as
an Hermes showcase, stands to benefit by the company it keeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great marriage with Hermes,'' said Tony Masiello, the
manager. ``It cements our classic style.''
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurateurs were on to the retail phenomenon early. The
``21'' Club, which has always sold cigarette lighters and umbrellas
imprinted with its symbol, now also sells aprons, toy trains,
baseballs _ even T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Sirio Maccioni accommodated his customers at the old Le Cirque
with Villeroy &AMP; Boche china and oversize Italian-made Burgundy
glasses for at least a decade. But restaurants do not have the room
to keep much stock on hand, he said, so small quantities have to be
ordered continually, which is frankly a headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``In six years, we did over a half million dollars' worth of
business _ but not really for a profit,'' Maccioni said.
</P>
<P>
   At the new Le Cirque 2000 on Madison Avenue, diners have already
asked to buy the crystal and the china, designed by Adam Tihanymade
and made by Bernardaud with its circus motifs. But arrangements
with the French company for retail orders are taking time, Maccioni
said, adding that ``early next year,'' the china and glassware will
be for sale, along with the small individual silver drip espresso
pots and _ most popular _ the elongated silver sorbet servers
designed by Ricciarelli, the Florentine silversmith.
</P>
<P>
   And all of it will be on display in a glass case, at the top of
the entrance stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Some items are available at restaurants and nowhere else. Take
the silver holders for mineral water bottles, which are greatly
admired, on the tables of Jean Georges. They will go right in the
glass case, next to a new cookbook written by Jean-Geoges
Vongerichten, the chef at the restaurant and one of its owners. So
will the silver wine coasters. (The shipment is expected in
August.)
</P>
<P>
   For napkin rings, there's no place like Jo Jo, another
Vongerichten restaurant. The wide, brightly colored acrylic napkin
rings, in use at the bistro since it opened in 1991, are finally
for sale, at $15 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always wanted to buy them,'' said Lois Fredman,
manager of Jo Jo. Designed by a New York artist exclusively for the
restaurant (she would not say who), this season's versions come in
four translucent pastels. Since they're already on the tables, and
the foyer at the restaurant is notoriously tiny, there will be no
display case.
</P>
<P>
   Selling them to customers makes even more sense on the balance
sheet than it seems. Ms. Fredman said the napkin rings, although
closely watched and swiftly retrieved by eagle-eyed waiters, have
shown a remarkable tendency to make their way out the door.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
