A0782 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-TV-LADN     06-02 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MELROSE' CREATOR HAS HIS WAY WITH `SEX AND THE CITY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; What do you get when you take Darren Star, the
creator of ``Melrose Place,'' and give him the content freedom of
HBO?
</P>
<P>
   Think of an R-rated ``Seinfeld'' from Elaine's perspective and
you'll have a pretty good idea.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Sex and the City,'' an intelligent, provocative
half-hour comedy that explores the mating rituals of four
30-something women who are among New York's social elite. It debuts
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes the smart, observant columnist _ a
self-described ``sexual anthropologist'' _ played by Sarah Jessica
Parker; the promiscuous one (Kim Cattrall); the prudish one
(Kristin Davis); and the jaded one (Cynthia Nixon).
</P>
<P>
   ``Melrose is a very fabricated concoction, and I think this is a
little more inside, a little more real,'' Star said. ``I wanted to
go off and do my thing. I wasn't trying to write a hit, I'm just
trying to write something funny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A little more inside'' is the operative phrase here. ``Sex in
the City'' is like watching a baseball game and being able to hear
what the players are talking about during a strategy conference on
the pitcher's mound, only this time the players are women talking
about their relationships with men, who are often being referred to
by a characteristic rather than a name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to look at four different types of women in terms
of their own relationships and sexuality and men. It's such a
fertile ground for characters and storytelling. It's sort of when
you get to the simple truth of it, everyone knows tons of
characters like these.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't let the title fool you, however. This is not the
T-and-A fest you'd expect from the network that brings you dozens
of incarnations of ``Real Sex,'' its nudity-heavy documentary
series that looks at real people having sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only use nudity when it's appropriate,'' Star said. ``When
we have it, it always services the story and the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City'' is more akin to the network's highly
acclaimed ``The Larry Sanders Show'' _ intelligent, adult
entertainment. And a pay-cable network like HBO is the only place
the show could have worked. Had its content been sanitized to the
point it would have passed through network television's standards
and practices, ``Sex and the City'' would have been a doomed
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not knocking network television,'' Star said. ``There are
some great shows on network television. But for this particular
show, HBO was the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider some of the show's steamy topics: One episode deals
with men who are obsessed with ``dating'' (that's a euphemism)
models and what that means for other women who they won't date.
Another examines what happens when experienced 30-something women
date 20-something men; it includes frank discussion of a specific
sexual variation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents didn't know quite what to make of (the show),''
said Davis, who plays Charlotte, the prudish art dealer. ``But all
my friends love it.''
</P>
<P>
   She tells a story about her 33-year-old manager, who watched the
pilot and couldn't wait to get his hands on the two subsequent
scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Like Star's other creations (``Melrose Place,'' ``Beverly Hills,
90210,'' ``Central Park West''), ``Sex in the City'' includes many
beautiful people in fabulous settings and sticky situations. But
this show, besides being a comedy, has a distinct sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great locations,'' Star said. ``This show has a very
fast pace. We were in as many locations in a half-hour as we were
in for an hour show.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong cast is led by Parker, who has starred in such movies
as ``Honeymoon in Vegas'' and ``L.A. Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who plays Carrie Bradshaw (loosely based on Candace
Bushnell, who writes the ``Sex and the City'' column in the New
York Observer), said that the show was too good to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no plans to do television for a long time,'' she said.
``I was really surprised that I said yes, and said it so quickly.
The subject matter was very provocative and very compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   The lure of appealing material, working for HBO and getting to
work in New York convinced Parker to join the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that doing HBO is like doing `television' to
these people,'' Star said. ``I think HBO is a big talent magnet in
terms of television. I think talent views it like their ad
campaign: It's not television, it's HBO.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Star and Parker both said that they didn't feel as if
they were making a dozen half-hour television shows. Rather they
approached the project as being 12 short films.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted very much to bring a different sensibility to
television,'' Parker said. ``The experience has been just
wonderful. HBO is a great champion and supporter of great
material.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the broadcast networks, HBO can afford to nurture
material. Its economics are based on the fact that quality will
entice subscribers, who in turn pay the bills. Emmy nominations and
Peabody Awards, like those the ``Sanders Show'' received, are more
important in its strategy than ratings. ``As a writer, your basic
mandate is just to do good work,'' Star said. ``That's how they
treat the creative process. It was very liberating to go from a
network to HBO.''
</P>
<P>
   And, they were also able to wait for Parker, something a network
with its rigid schedule couldn't do.
</P>
<P>
   The lead actress was interested in the role, but needed time to
1) get married (to ``Godzilla'' star Matthew Broderick) and 2) to
block some time for a movie that never went.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just perfect,'' Star said. ``She was able to be
believable smart because she is smart. She's funny and sympathetic.
She can go out on the edge and people will love her at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who won't work nude, said that she objected to some of
the language written for her character.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really important not to be gratuitous with the uses of
language,'' Parker said. ``We had to be really careful ... because
my character is a writer and would use the language, just not say
the `f-word.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And, the creator of ``Melrose Place'' with the freedom of HBO
listened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
