<P>
   SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: Of necessity, I am preparing to unload a few hundred
(thousand?) books. I'll retain those that are lifetime friends and
by various means will discard others that have outworn their
welcome or usefulness. But what should I do with ``Judith'' and
``Olive and Mary Ann?'' Should I keep them because the author gave
them to me? After all, the author was James T. Farrell, not an
insignificant figure in the pageant of American literature. But
both novels _ which he didn't inscribe _ seem inconsequential; I
read them dutifully soon after their presentation, but now have
only fuzzy recall of what I read. The author, though, rated them
among his very best work. Surely the author was wrong. By LARRY
SWINDELL. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
