<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING RFK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was 30 years ago this week that New York Sen.
Robert F. Kennedy was murdered in the pantry of a Los Angeles hotel
shortly after midnight, following a celebration of his California
Democratic presidential primary victory.
</P>
<P>
   He was carrying on in the tradition of his assassinated older
brother, President John F. Kennedy _ campaigning for the White
House as a progressive leader who could end the Vietnam War, calm
racial turmoil and bring new prosperity to the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Bobby, as we all called him, was no Jack. Despite the magic
family name, he was not quite up to the monumental expectations
generated by nostalgia and the Camelot legend. The voters were
prepared to reject the presumed inevitability of another Kennedy
presidency, as they would do a decade later when it became Sen.
Edward Kennedy's turn to try.
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy belongs now to history, and his myth has been
steadily undermined by recent accounts of his morally unacceptable
personal misbehavior. But in Bobby's time the martyred president
was such an overpowering emotional idol that not even his brother
could compete.
</P>
<P>
   With a limited public record but cleaner private life, Bobby's
reputation has survived in somewhat better shape, remembered by old
allies with undeserved reverence. But an overdue dose of reality
would be historically useful here too.
</P>
<P>
   Before that California primary, Vice President Hubert Humphrey
had already accumulated enough delegates to win the 1968 Democratic
nomination. Humphrey's advisers were so certain of victory they
were debating whether to ask Kennedy to take second spot on the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy of Bobby's untimely death conferred an exaggerated
political glow that he did not enjoy in life, just as a similar
tragedy had done on his assassinated brother. Bobby became a
central figure in the family mythology, second only to Jack.
</P>
<P>
   As his brother's attorney general and as a senator, Bobby was
seen during his lifetime as the heir apparent to a family dynasty
that owed more to his father and fate than to anything he had
achieved on his own. He even owed his Senate seat to President
Lyndon Johnson, with whom he shared a mutual loathing. Kennedy was
losing his 1964 race in New York until the then-popular Johnson
personally campaigned there for him.
</P>
<P>
   Laboring in the shadow of history and the Kennedy giants who
preceded him, Bobby was a fascinating bundle of contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   During his presidential campaign, he sought to establish a
viable political identity by championing poor farm workers, black
ghetto families, antiwar demonstrators, mine workers and all kinds
of forgotten causes. He appealed to the young, blacks,
professionals and blue-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   At his best, he could be eloquent and inspiring. His most famous
lines are probably those paraphrasing George Bernard Shaw: ``You
see things and you say, `Why?' But I dream things that never were
and I say, `Why not?'''
</P>
<P>
   He could also be the tough-minded pragmatist that, along with
his familiar large Kennedy teeth, earned him the unflattering press
bus moniker ``ruthless rabbit.'' This was, after all, a loyal son
who came to maturity managing his elder, more intellectual
brother's 1960 presidential campaign, sometimes using ugly
political tactics.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters asked another Kennedy staffer why the future
president relied so much on his younger brother, the aide replied:
``Every candidate needs a hatchet man he can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby also labored as a youth for three years on the staff of
Sen. Joseph McCarthy, R-Wis., of irresponsible communist
witch-hunting fame. His father, Joseph P. Kennedy, who was a
McCarthy friend, got him the job. Insofar as this columnist knows,
RFK never publicly disavowed McCarthy's motives.
</P>
<P>
   It is not quite clear whether the liberalism of his later years
was an acquired taste designed to get votes or a genuine
philosophical conversion. His record on behalf of civil rights
stretches back through his Justice Department years. But the extent
of his interest in social outreach to help the disadvantaged is
murky.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1966, he opposed the Vietnam War, which Johnson was
then accelerating with bombings and additional troops _ a war that
his brother had previously supported with a gradually increasing
military presence. Bobby's position may have been the result of a
revulsion against the war but also could have been influenced by
his dislike for Johnson, whom he considered an interloper in a
White House that rightfully belonged to a Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between Johnson and Robert Kennedy came to a head
after Johnson eliminated all his Cabinet members as potential 1994
running mates in order to get rid of the Kennedy-generated pressure
to pick Bobby as his vice president. That gambit stands today as
one of history's more transparent political maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Not until then did Bobby quit the Justice Department to seek the
New York Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, after Johnson declined to run again, Bobby jumped into
the presidential race even though Humphrey and Sen. Eugene
McCarthy, D-Minn., were already running. By further splintering the
party, Bobby's entry into the race increased the odds that the
likely GOP nominee, his brother's former foe Richard Nixon, would
win the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby won five presidential primaries, but in losing Oregon he
became the first Kennedy to lose a political race. He was shot when
he was 42. He would have been 72 years old today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
