<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; tad-z
a d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-MSKUBE-COX     06-02 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Asian brews excellent for quenching spicy fires
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My wife's favorite cuisine is Thai, which might explain her
sense of humor. I like spicy food just fine, sometimes even hot
food. But there are limits. So it's good that the friendly people
at Tamarind Thai Cuisine on 14th Street, a wonderful restaurant
recommended to us by dining critic John Kessler, tell you exactly
how hot is hot.
</P>
<P>
   On the menu, one pepper means mild, but with a ``a stimulating
`kick' to lips and tongue.'' Well, OK.
</P>
<P>
   Two peppers ``will set lips and tongue tingling,'' the sensation
spreading ``a hearty glow.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably where I should stop, with two peppers and the
tingling. At three peppers ``the tingly glow is transformed into a
raging fire,'' and at four peppers _ ``for addicts, masochists and
Thai nationals'' _ management advises that you should order Thai
beer and tissues as a precaution. (A further precaution: Tamarind,
which opened in January, has applied for its liquor license but is
not yet serving beer. General manager Eddie Niyomkul says he
expects to be serving Singha, the renowned Thai beer, and Bangkok
Beer by early June.)
</P>
<P>
   The Thai beer I can understand, but what are those tissues for?
Whatever it is, ``management accepts no responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Very well, let me have the Gang Phed _ for now I'm a one-pepper
man _ with an order of Thod-Mun-Pla on the side. And, oh yes, bring
me a Singha when you can.
</P>
<P>
   Gang Phed, as the menu explains, is chicken, beef or pork in
sweet curry paste, with a touch of coconut milk, and Thod-Mun-Pla
is spicy fish cakes marinated with Kaffir lime leaves, string beans
and red curry paste. Tangy but not incendiary. Singha is better
described as opulent, but there's nothing particularly ``Thai''
about it. It's a lager _ beer in a German or Czech style _ that
happens to be brewed in Bangkok by the interestingly named Boon
Rawd Brewing Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Singha, it seems, was created by a German brewmaster in Thailand
in the '30s. Among Asian beers it stands out for its body and
hoppiness _ qualities that make it ideal not only for triple-pepper
Thai dishes but also Hunan and Szechwan cuisine at Chinese
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   No less a judge than Michael Jackson calls it ``an outstanding
pale lager that would attract attention anywhere in the world ... a
wonderfully hoppy, aromatic dry lager, full of flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   I've had Singha before, but it surprised me to learn _ in
Jackson's ``New World Guide to Beer'' _ that it's brewed at 40
units of bitterness. By comparison, that's more than three times
the hoppiness of a Budweiser and on a par with the best German and
Czech pilsners. You don't notice the bitterness because the malt
gives the beer such body and balance.
</P>
<P>
   Bangkok Beer is less hoppy and lacks the overall character of a
Singha, but its clean, dry finish suits many Asian dishes _ not
just Thai _ quite well. In many an Asian country, this would be the
star.
</P>
<P>
   When you're choosing an Asian beer, you want to remember that
they aren't ``Asian.'' With a few exceptions, they're pale lagers,
no different in style from those you'd find the world over.
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't mean they're interchangeable _ many are drinkable
but ordinary, a few are excellent. Not every Asian beer can stand
up to a spicy Thai or Szechwan dish. Some don't have to. With
Cantonese cuisine, Tsingtao, less hoppy than Singha but crisp and
drinkable, works well enough.
</P>
<P>
   And with other Asian dishes your taste buds point the way almost
by instinct. Michael Jackson writes of the excellent sushi to be
found in the Japanese city of Sapporo, and it happens that nothing
complements a California roll like the pilsner character of a
bottled Sapporo Draft. Sushi, in fact, is one of those dishes that
bring out the qualities of a true pilsner _ assertive but not
overpowering, full flavored but clean on the finish. It's less
obvious why more Asian countries don't brew ales, whose generally
hoppier character suits spicy dishes. India, after all, is why the
British conceived of India Pale Ale: In the 19th century, beer kept
spoiling on the long ocean voyage to the subcontinent. Brewers
found that extra hops not only retarded spoilage but made for a
more robust ale.
</P>
<P>
   Many an American or English IPA (or even a less hoppy pale ale)
would suit curried dishes better than the Indian lager Golden
Eagle, which is hard to find fresh in the United States. There are
ale styles by the dozen, and not all of them would match Asian
cuisine. But with most Chinese dishes, I want Redhook Rye. Its
slightly tangy, slightly spicy ale character just brings more to
the palate than the unremarkable lager quality of Tsingtao.
</P>
<P>
   And a beer such as Sierra Nevada Pale Ale, which is no hoppier
than Singha, could stand up to four peppers any day. What's more,
it could complement the milder dishes without taking over the
table.
</P>
<P>
   But dining is a kind of vicarious experience. A good traveler
wants to do as the locals do, and the traveler offered a Singha is
being offered one of the world's best beers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
