<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0791 &Cx1f; tad-z
a d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP04-COX     06-02 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peanut butter fudge a dream of dishy dessert
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's hardly anything more dreamy than a creamy peanut butter
fudge. And reader Beverly Sell knew the secret ingredient for such
a fudge _ marshmallows. She just needed the rest of the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Turner of Marietta, Ga. responded with a chocolate-peanut
butter version that's simple and simply delicious. For a strictly
peanut butter candy, we turned to a classic Southern cookbook,
``Charleston Receipts,'' a collection of recipes gathered by the
Junior League of Charleston, S.C., in 1950. Sure enough, we found a
recipe for Peanut Butter Fudge Dreams.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Butter
</P>
<P>
   Fudge Dreams
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   1cup mini-marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Butter an 8-by-8-inch pan and set aside. In a heavy saucepan,
combine the granulated sugar, brown sugar and milk and cook over
low heat, stirring frequently, until the mixture reaches the
soft-ball stage, about 240 degrees. Remove from heat and quickly
add the marshmallows, peanut butter and butter and stir until
well-mixed. Allow to cool for about 2-3 minutes, then add the
vanilla and mix again.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into buttered pan. Cool in the refrigerator for at least 30
minutes. Cut into 16 squares. Keep fudge in refrigerator, as it
tends to get very soft at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 158 calories, 2 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 24), 30 grams carbohydrates, 6 milligrams
cholesterol, 43 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Butter Fudge
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4smooth peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cup semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2cups mini-marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   Butter an 8-by-8-inch pan and set aside. Combine the butter,
peanut butter, chocolate chips and vanilla in a double boiler and
cook over low heat until melted, about 5-7 minutes. Remove from
heat and stir in marshmallows until melted.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into buttered pan. Cool in the refrigerator for at least 30
minutes. Cut into 16 squares. Keep fudge in refrigerator, as it
tends to get very soft at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 217 calories, 4 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 71), 16 grams carbohydrates, 16
milligrams cholesterol, 63 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _Reagan Walker
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Carol Jones Groves of Valdosta is looking for a poundcake
recipe from the mid-'50s that uses confectioners' sugar instead of
granulated sugar.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gwendolyn Connally of Marietta is looking for a lemon
meringue pie using vanilla wafers. She thought it used to be on the
Eagle Brand milk label, but Borden didn't have it.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sonya Burnette (e-mail) is looking for a broccoli and cheese
casserole using sharp cheddar and for an oven-baked chicken that is
crispy without the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to
</P>
<P>
   Recipe Swap, Food Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689,
Atlanta, GA 30302. Include your hometown and
</P>
<P>
   daytime telephone number. E-mail: rwalker(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
