<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LAINER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $10 million in capital improvements made by KSL Recreation to
Lake Lanier Islands.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lake Lanier Islands, Ga.--Our paddleboat sank during a recent
jam-packed weekend escape to one of Atlanta's favorite playgrounds.
But not our spirits.
</P>
<P>
   As my 10-year-old daughter and I were spinning merrily along in
one of those boats you pedal like a bicycle, the darn thing took on
water and starting sinking like the Titanic. The rescue was a scene
right out of Baywatch _ except the drama unfolded on the placid
waters of Lake Sidney Lanier at the Beach and Water Park. Before I
could say glub, glub, a lifeguard zipped over in aher little chase
boat, and soon we were back on terra firma.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as we left the water park, we saw the upturned Capri
paddleboat on the shore. ``Look, there's the SS Capri,'' said my
husband, John. ``Uh, more like the SOS Capri,'' quipped Caroline.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we were able to salve our wounded egos at our
cottage _ one of the new LakeHouses on Lanier _ to relax in its hot
tub and cook burgers on the gas grill on the deck overlooking the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of $10 million in capital improvements made by
California-based KSL Recreation Corp. since it took over ownership
and operation of Lake Lanier Islands from the state last summer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to building the 30 LakeHouses _ another 10 will be
ready for occupancy this weekend and a final 10 by the end of the
month _ KSL has upgraded the 224-room Hilton Resort. The
refurbished entrance includes verdant landscaping and a splashing
fountain. Inside, the lobby has been redecorated in rich purple and
green. The 11,000 square-foot-expansion includes a new grand
ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Also new is a 65-passenger excursion boat, the Island Queen,
which offers sunset cruises Saturdays. Outfitted like a luxury
yacht, the Queen has an oak bar and trim and upholstered furniture
groupings around cocktail tables downstairs and tables and chairs
on the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   The most eagerly anticipated addition for the wet set is the
colorful FunDunker, an interactive family attraction at the Beach
and Water Park that promises ``100 ways to get wet.'' The
multilevel maze looks like Tinker Toys meets Lego, with slides,
pipes, spigots, hoses, waterfalls, faucets and valves. After
several delays, the water funhouse is expected to open by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kids will no doubt love dousing their parents with cold blasts
from jet propulsion sprays, spewing geysers and water troughs. And
what fun it should be when 1,000 gallons of water spills from a
huge bucket perched atop the contraption! Families that spray
together, stay together.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline and her friend Allison Rohan, also 10, managed to drown
their disappointment about missing the FunDunker with numerous
trips down the Chattahoochee Rapids water chutes, both solo and in
tandem tubes. They also spent hours of bobbing in the crashing
breakers of Wildwaves wave pool. I preferred to stretch out on a
towel on the grass next to the sandy beach, slurp lemon ices and
take an occasional dip in the chilly lake to cool off.
</P>
<P>
   Their energy unflagging, the girls wanted to do it all. At the
LakeHouse, they alternately lolled in the bubbling spa and watched
cartoons in their own bedroom with twin beds. They were the first
out the door for horsebacking riding _ a pleasurable hour along
trails that wind through the woods by the lakeshore and provide a
rare glimpse of the islands' wildlife (we saw at least a dozen
deer).
</P>
<P>
   My luck, I got a bull-headed steed named Mocha, who tested me
early and often, veering off the trail into the bush. Sensing my
equestrian experience was limited, he must have decided to liven
things up _ at my expense. (Perhaps he heard I was the one who
couldn't manage to keep a paddleboat afloat.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John played a round of golf at the 18-hole Emerald
Point Golf Course, which boasts 13 holes on the water. No. 2,
completely surrounded by water and accessible only by a bridge, is
the course's signature hole. John wouldn't say how many of his golf
balls now reside on Lanier's murky bottom.
</P>
<P>
   And what would a weekend at Lake Lanier be without taking a boat
out? We spent a few hours on the lake in a small ski boat _ mostly
dodging sailboats and other craft, including those ubiquitous Jet
Skis churning up wakes as they roared across the lake.
</P>
<P>
   But my favorite part was kicking back at the house in the pines
above a secluded cove _ hanging out on the large deck in a
green-painted Adirondack chair or in the spa. The steaks we seared
on the grill tasted better than any we've cooked at home. That's
probably because we opted to have Hilton deliver marinated
ready-to-grill meat along with sides and dessert ($25-$40 per
person), though you can BYOS (bring your own steak).
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long to start thinking of the spacious yet cozy
rental unit as home. Framed pictures of families posing for
vacation snapshots on the walls provide a homey touch _ the folks
could be your relatives. Turns out they are shots from the family
albums of KSL creative director Dale Moore, a former Disney
imagineer who designed and decorated the wood and rock cottages to
look like Grandma's place at the lake back in the '50s and '60s.
Call his style Faux Granny, but it works. Even if your grandmother
never went near a lake, you'll feel a twinge of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   The great room has a sleeper sofa and white wicker chairs,
stacks of Reader's Digest Condensed Books and National Geographics
(just like at Grandma's!), a river rock fireplace and hearth, and
built-in bookshelves with TV and VCR.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen is separated from the living area by a rock and oak
bar with stools. The cabinets and six dining room chairs are
painted blue, the rest of the wood furniture white. The
weathered-look dining table as well as the coffee and end tables
were custom made by local craftsmen, who also crafted the massive
carved headboards in the bedrooms, the bedside tables and folding
screens between the dressing area and the bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Star cutouts on the tables and screens complement the celestial
theme in the master bedroom, which is accented with framed prints
featuring sun, moon, stars and angels.
</P>
<P>
   The master bedroom has a king-size bed, the second bedroom has
twins, which can be connected to create a king if you prefer. And
with two bathrooms, the houses can easily accommodate two families
(give the kids the sofa bed) or two couples. All the better for
sharing the expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Both bedrooms feature braided rugs strewn on unfinished hardwood
floors _ the same throughout the house. So don't worry if you don't
wipe your feet when you come in dripping after a soak in the hot
tub.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, you could always get away with murder at Grandma's.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: Less than an hour's drive from downtown
Atlanta. Take I-85 to I-985, then Exit 2 and follow signs. $6
parking fee at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   -- Accommodations: Through June 14, the LakeHouses, which sleep
up to six, are offering an introductory rate of $250 per night,
including admission to the Beach and Water Park and one-day boat
rental. After June 14, the rate will be $350 (includes beach passes
for up to six people each day). Two-night stay required.
770-831-9400. The Hilton offers a Family Fun package for $179
(includes beach passes for two adults and two children); the golf
package is $134 (includes breakfast buffet at Sylvan's and a round
of golf with cart). 770-945-8787. At the -- ampground, an RV site
is $21; tent site, $15.50. 770-932-7270.
</P>
<P>
   -- Beach and Water Park: $18.95 daily; $11.95 (children under 42
inches); 2 and under free. Two-day and season passes available.
Opens at 10 a.m. daily through Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   -- Horseback riding and bicycles: $20 per person for 45-minute
trail ride; $6 for half-hour pony ride. Bicycles $3 per hour or $10
a day. 770-932-7233.
</P>
<P>
   -- Emerald Point Golf Course: Greens fees $42 (Monday-Thursday);
$52 (Friday-Sunday); cart rental $15. Call 770-945-8789 for tee
time.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Live at the Islands'' Summer Concert Series: Showtime is 7
p.m. at Presentation Point Amphitheater. Free admission (however,
all cars must pay $6 gate fee). The schedule: Cadillac Ranch,
Friday; Soul Purpose, June 12; Zoots &AMP; Swingin' Suits with Ms.
Manhattan, June 19; Crucial Dread, June 26; Power Play, July 3;
Kelly Richey Band, July 10; Swimming Pool Q's, July 17; Ross
Brothers, July 24; Crossover, July 31; Liz Hendley Band, Aug. 7;
Melanie Massell &AMP; All That Jazz, Aug. 14; and Rockerz, Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: 770-932-7200 or 1-800-840-5253.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
