<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let Web whisk you to World Cup in France
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you take the NBA championships, the Super Bowl, the Olympics
and possibly the World Series and lumped them all together, you
might have something that comes close to the international frenzy
surrounding World Cup soccer championships.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who know nothing about soccer, the World Cup is
the best place to learn. Every four years, almost every country in
the world, including the United States in recent years, sends its
best players to France in the round robin tournament to see which
country has the best soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   Wars have been fought over the outcome of matches. Players who
embarrassed their countries by losing a match have been
assassinated. This is serious stuff.
</P>
<P>
   One way for clueless Americans to bone up on World Cup news is
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to begin your learning adventure is at the official
World Cup Web site (http://www.france98.com). The site is artfully
designed to reflect the global nature of this year's tournament,
which is in France, and is available in French and English. You can
pick up information here about who's playing, the latest news and
team updates.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a souvenir shop where you can purchase official
merchandise direct from France in U.S. dollars. And should you be
inspired enough to go to France to attend the World Cup for
yourself, there's information about tickets and accommodations.
Tickets are mailed out in secure, nonidentifiable packets that
should give you some idea of how coveted tickets are.
</P>
<P>
   Another good place to pick up some background on the World Cup
is the FIFA (Federation Internationale de Football Association) Web
site (http://www.fifa.com). FIFA is the official organizing
committee for the World Cup. Here you can look up the history of
World Cup matches, find out the different venues where games will
be played and read up on the rules and regulations for World Cup
teams and players. Yahoo! has co-opted some FIFA content and offers
up a list of World Cup rankings at
http://soccer.yahoo.com/wc98/rankings.html.
</P>
<P>
   While we Yanks are just getting up to speed on soccer and the
World Cup, the Europeans have been mad about the sport for years.
The British Broadcasting Corporation, known for its staid
journalism and solid reporting, has a bright blue and green Web
site devoted to cup fever (http://www.bbc.co.uk). It's got news.
It's got a calendar. It's got online polls. It's got travel
information. You can also chime in on the debate over Paul
``Gazza'' Gascoigne, who was booted from the English team after
getting drunk in a Spanish hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the football star can send messages to him, listen to an
exclusive interview or read a variety of other articles, including
skyrocketing TV sales in Vietnam so fans can watch the cup or the
threats by Air France to strike during the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Here in America, we Yanks are just catching on to soccer, never
mind the World Cup. However, soccer fans in the United States and
around the world are keeping the message boards at CNN/SI
(http://www.cnnsi.com/soccer/world/events/1998/worldcup) active.
With more than 4,000 messages on everything from the Iranian team
to discussions of the sport's top players, This is the place to go
if you want to talk soccer. Meanwhile, ESPN Sportzone
(http://espn.sportzone.com/soccer/worldcup98/) does a great job of
gathering all the pertinent World Cup information into a stylish
and easy-to-navigate package. The site's minimalist design also is
accessible to many soccer fans worldwide who might not have
state-of-the-art computers. ESPN also has the American broadcast
schedule on its site and a profile of the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
