<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN will spend week on nuclear problems
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CNN will devote even more resources than usual to an
across-the-board series of specials and reports on nuclear
proliferation the week of June 15, gathered under the heading
``Ground Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, scheduled to be announced soon, calls for a one-hour
special at 10 p.m. EDT, June 16 anchored by Christiane Amanpour and
more than 50 reports throughout the week, touching nearly all CNN
programming, CNN/US President Richard Kaplan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said the overview was prompted by the recent nuclear
tests by India and Pakistan but will not be limited to the current
situation. An upcoming ``NewsStand'' magazine show with
Entertainment Weekly, for example, will look at how Hollywood has
dealt with nuclear fears. A recent taped interview with Fidel
Castro, intended for the September launch of the 24-hour miniseries
``The Cold War,'' will be excerpted for historical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where CNN shows what it can really do,'' Kaplan said.
``We have to make more of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other shows dealing with nuclear bombs will include
``Crossfire,'' ``Burden of Proof'' and ``TalkBack Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ground Zero'' is part of Kaplan's ongoing mission to improve
CNN's programming. Although much of the attention inside CNN lately
has been focused on Sunday's launch of ``NewsStand,'' there is also
the constant sound of construction from the new news set being
built for later this year. The 24-hour ``Cold War'' is finished and
the promotion effort will start this summer.
</P>
<P>
   And CNN's ``Perspective'' series of documentaries will start a
new umbrella series called ``Century of Strife'' at 8 p.m. EDT
Sunday. Hosted by James Earl Jones, the free-standing documentaries
will include ``The Kennedys in Crisis'' (Sunday), about John and
Robert Kennedy and the integration of the University of Alabama;
``Assassinated: The Last Days of Kennedy and King'' (June 14 and
June 21; it originally aired on TBS in April), an Oliver Stone
production that does not delve into conspiracy theories; and
``Somalia: Blackhawk Down,'' about the 1993 U.S. involvement in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
