   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ WASHINGTON _ With the national tobacco bill under
heavy fire and in danger of sinking, backers discussed scaling back
taxes and other measures to gain support. (Lipman, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-GORE _ WASHINGTON _ The Year 2000 Problem is becoming
Vice President Al Gore's problem. As Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif.,
downgraded the federal government's response to the ``millennium
bug'' Tuesday from D-minus to F, Republican presidential hopeful
Steve Forbes again faulted Gore's lack of leadership on the issue.
(Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HANS-MARK _ WASHINGTON _ Thanks to years of government service,
Hans Mark's confirmation hearing Tuesday was more of a reunion with
old friends in the Senate than a tough grilling by the Senate Armed
Services Committee. ``This is the fourth time I've gone through
this,'' said Mark, the University of Texas engineering professor
who is on tap to become the Pentagon's director of defense research
and engineering. (Harlan, Cox News Service 350).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL PRAYER _ WASHINGTON _ Religious and civil liberties
groups Tuesday blasted the latest Republican-led effort to add a
constitutional amendment guaranteeing the right to school prayer.
They said the effort is nothing more than a political tool to give
the Christian Coalition a chance to paint their opponents as
``voting against God.'' Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, is leading the
opposition to the amendment in the House. A vote is expected on
Thursday. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BIOTERROR _ WASHINGTON _ A Senate Appropriations subcommittee
holds a hearing on the growing threat of epidemics and
bioterrorism. Witnesses include James Hughes, director of the CDC
National Center for Infectious Diseases, and Richard Jackson,
director of CDC National Center for Environmental Health. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COX-DRUDGE _ WASHINGTON _ The color, confrontation and cuisine
as Real Journalists take on the Internet gossip-monger during lunch
at the National Press Club on Tuesday. (Dart, Cox News Service).
