<HEADLINE>
&HT;        NUCLEAR WASTE BILL DEAD: GINGRICH
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston and Dave Williams  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 2 -- A bill calling for construction of an
interim storage site for high-level nuclear waste in the Nevada
desert is dead for this year, House Speaker Newt Gingrich said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, R-Ga., released a statement late Tuesday afternoon, as
Nevada's two senators argued passionately on the Senate floor
against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I strongly support a legislative resolution to the
nuclear waste issue, it is unlikely that such a bill will make it
past the president's veto to become law this year,'' Gingrich said.
``Because of the crowded calendar and the strong opposition of some
members, I do not expect to schedule floor action this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Ensign, R-Nev., told reporters Monday that he had
received confirmation from Gingrich that the bill was dead.
However, the speaker did not comment publicly on the issue until
late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with his colleague, (Rep.) Jim Gibbons, (R-Nev.), John
Ensign has been a forceful and effective voice for the citizens of
Nevada in opposing the nuclear waste bill,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
