<HEADER>
A0810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     06-02 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE KEY TO JORDAN'S FUTURE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the eve of the Bulls-Jazz NBA finals, a series which some
speculate may be Michael Jordan's Last Finals, Last Games, Last
Dance, (would one of Jordan's last meal then be the Last Repast?)
it would be helpful to consider the circumstances surrounding the
possible grounding of His Airness.
</P>
<P>
   To many, the Bulls coach, Phil Jackson, is the key to Jordan's
basketball-playing future. And by extension, the Bulls' management
has been perceived as that which holds the hand that holds the key.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Jordan has said, and then seemingly hedged, that
he would not return to the Bulls, the only team he said he would
consider playing for, if Jackson were not the coach. Jackson was
the bench leader behind all the Bulls' five championships.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan himself has coyly left the impression that he may not go
voluntarily into that good night, and that the Bulls' management,
like the proprietor of a vaudeville stage, might just be applying a
hook, although circumspectly. That is, no Jackson, no Jordan.
Jordan isn't alone in this intimation. Phil Jackson has indirectly
also allowed the idea to metastasize.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has repeatedly stated publicly that this would be his
last season. And why would this be Jackson's last season? Because,
it is generally believed, Bulls' management wants it that way, and
is pushing Jackson out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' Jackson said recently, ``that when I signed this
last contract, Jerry Krause said that this would be my last
season.'' Krause is the vice president in charge of basketball
operations for the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Jackson indeed signed a one-year contract _ but he
had been offered a five-year contract, then a two-year contract,
and turned them down for the one-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Jerry Krause did,'' said Jerry Reinsdorf, chairman of the
Chicago Bulls, ``was only repeat what Phil Jackson had been saying.
In fact, several times in the last year I've asked Phil if he wants
to come back. And every time he has said to me, no.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Jackson and Krause _ the man who hired Jackson _
no longer have any love lost for each other. ``I'm not really sure
what the problem is,'' said Jackson, ``but I think Krause thinks
I've gotten a big head.'' Krause won't comment on the acrimonious
relationship other than to say, ``I'm going to take the high road _
there's no traffic up there.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jackson and Krause speak only when necessary, such as
when deciding and agreeing on a trade, like that of Jason Caffey.
About two years ago Jackson went to Reinsdorf and said the
situation with Krause was becoming untenable. ``Do you think you
can work well enough with Jerry to win a championship?'' asked
Reinsdorf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we'll leave things as they are,'' decided Reinsdorf.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is not wrong in believing that Krause wants him out, and
has compared the situation to the one with the Lakers in the 1980s
in which Jerry West's personality clash with Pat Riley resulted in
Riley's departure as coach. ``But Jerry Reinsdorf is not pushing me
out,'' said Jackson. And, he was asked, if Reinsdorf wants you to
stay, do you think you would be able to stay?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said Jackson, ``Reinsdorf is the bottom line, and
Krause would listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf said: ``Phil has done a great job for us, and if he
changes his mind and wants to come back, I'll be open to discussing
it with him, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be necessary to know, among other points, if Jackson
would want to be involved in rebuilding the Bulls, perhaps the
oldest team in the league. Jackson has suggested he would not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every seven years the molecular components of the body
change,'' Jackson said, in his Zen-like mode. ``And I've felt that
it's been seven years that I've been the Bulls' coach, and I'm a
changing person.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Jordan, who went from basketball to baseball to basketball
to, well, golf? ``I'm not sure even Michael knows at this time,''
said Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But like the ghost of Banquo, the notion hovers that in a matter
of a fortnight Jordan will be gone forever from the hard-court
scene, depriving a city, a nation and large pockets of the rest of
the earth, the moon and the stars the pleasure of his basketball
genius. It is a genius still wondrous though, older and achier, he
is no longer first in flight.
</P>
<P>
   But if Jordan is relying on the Jackson outcome, then it seems
safe to say that the decision is Jackson's, because it is
Reinsdorf's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
