<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0812 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-SPIRITUAL-GARD     06-02 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-SPIRITUAL-GARDENING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING IN THE GARDEN BRINGS AN UNDERSTANDING OF PARABLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    As a novice gardener, I'm often frustrated with the patches of
land I'm working. My front-yard flower beds and backyard vegetable
plots seem to grow more weeds than a rain forest -- thus turning my
Saturdays into a war on unwanted plants.
 &HT;    Weeding in the warm spring sun I wonder, why do I feel compelled
to sweat while tending little sprouts and shrubs? Only a
nongardener would call gardening fun; we gardeners (even beginning
ones) know gardening is hard work.
 &HT;    So, why garden? Oddly enough, I enjoy it. I find myself thinking
about my flowers and herbs throughout the week -- planning
projects, reading about plants, and mentally tilling the ground. By
week's end, I can't wait to don my gloves and get back to the
garden. There, in the midst of toil, as my baby looks on from her
play yard, I feel connected.
 &HT;    Allen Lacy, a philosopher of gardening, writes, ``A garden,
whether we know it or not, connects us to the world in many strange
and wonderful ways.'' Thus, the garden is not a retreat. Rather, it
is a grounded path to larger understanding.
 &HT;    For me, that includes spirituality.
 &HT;    Many experienced gardeners have written well about the
spirituality of gardening. From Thomas Jefferson to Wendell Berry,
American thinkers have expounded upon the soulfulness of
cultivation. Indeed, Americans have theologized about gardening
almost as long as we have gardened.
 &HT;    When I started this spring, I swore I wouldn't think about
gardening. Others have done it better and more eloquently. Since I
think for a living, I needed something to do with my hands -- not
my head. So, I started to dig. With every shovel, I began to learn
-- and found I couldn't helping thinking -- about dirt.
 &HT;    Dirt does not seem a likely spiritual teacher. I could imagine
waxing rapturous over flowers or herbs. But dirt?
 &HT;    Until this year, I never knew dirt was important. I thought
gardeners bought seeds or those little plants at the nursery and
popped them in the ground. Some Miracle-Gro, some water, some
patience ... picture-perfect garden.
 &HT;    But dirt is the starting place for a good garden. The soil must
be loamy, textured, balanced, rich, and, above all, alive with good
bugs and worms.
 &HT;    I'd never considered whether my dirt was alive. Much to my
dismay, I discovered that mine was hard clay. Alas, no bugs. Under
my vegetable plot, I found the remnants of an old patio -- complete
with plastic tarp and bricks. My garden wasn't loamy, it was
gloomy.
 &HT;    Undaunted, my husband and I worked that spot. We dug and hoed
and turned the earth. We added soil conditioners, compost and good
dirt. A month later, we were still digging.
 &HT;    While struggling with the clay, I recalled Jesus' agricultural
parables. One came to mind with particular force: ``A sower went
out to sow his seed; and as he sowed, some fell on the path and was
trampled on, and the birds ate it up. Some fell on the rock; and as
it grew, it withered for lack of moisture. Some fell among thorns,
and the thorns choked it. Some fell into good soil, and when it
grew, it produced a hundredfold.''
 &HT;    Growing up in the city, stories about sowing seeds never made
much sense, so I trusted my minister's interpretation of the
passage. Those who accepted God's word were like the seed sown on
good soil; those who believed in Jesus would grow and bear fruit.
If you happened to be good soil, you were lucky. If not, too bad. I
called it ``chips fall where they may'' theology.
 &HT;    This spring, much to my surprise, I learned soil can be changed.
Good soil does not usually just happen; it results from hard work.
When I reread Jesus' words, I almost heard the crowd laughing,
``Good soil? In Palestine?!'' The folks who followed Jesus -- many
of them farmers -- got it. In order for the seed to grow, the soil
must first be worked.
 &HT;    Jesus said, ``If you want to hear God's word, dig. Turn over the
dirt, till, hoe, add manure. Dig, dig, and dig. Only then, once
your soul is loamy, textured, balanced, rich, and crawling with
good bugs can you hear.''
 &HT;    Standing inches deep in mud, I understood. The seed of God's
word was not condemnation. Rather, the seed was a promise. If we do
our part working our lives into good soil, God's word will grow and
bear fruit.
 &HT;    And so does the garden. Now, three months later, we're
harvesting our first beans and lettuce. The flowers are blooming
and the herbs get bigger every day. Every fistful of dirt yields
earthworms. What was dead lives. It has been quite a rebirth.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
