<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-NOMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PLANS STRATEGY SESSION ON HORMEL NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration will host a White House
strategy session Thursday to devise ways to pressure Republican
leaders to allow a Senate vote on the ambassadorial nomination of
gay rights advocate James C. Hormel.
</P>
<P>
   Some 60 people _ including leaders of civil rights groups,
senior administration officials and a bipartisan group of senators
_ are expected to attend the session and explore ways of getting
Senate action on Hormel's nomination to be ambassador to
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an effort by the administration to communicate to a broad
cross section of America's civil rights community leadership about
what's already been done and what still needs to be done in order
to get Mr. Hormel confirmed,'' said Richard Socarides, special
assistant to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has refused to bring
Hormel's nomination to the Senate floor for a vote, saying it would
take too much time. Hormel's nomination was approved 16 to 2 in
November by the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, but it has
since been blocked from a floor vote by conservatives including
Sens. James M. Inhofe, R-Okla., Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., and Robert
C. Smith, R-N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The senators say Hormel's gay activism makes him an
inappropriate choice for the job because Luxembourg is a
predominantly Catholic nation.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Stachelberg, political director for the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay and lesbian organization which
Hormel founded, called the White House meeting ``a clear
demonstration of the administration's support of Jim Hormel and a
clear bipartisan show of that support.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, who is in Washington this week to meet with senators and
State Department officials about his stalled nomination, has
observed an unwritten rule of nominee etiquette by not speaking
publicly about the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Socarides said he believes support for Hormel is growing
among civil rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that most of these groups oppose discrimination where
ever they find it,'' Socarides said. ``People are coming to see
this more and more as an issue of basic fairness. Here's an
individual who is obviously qualified who is being discriminated
against only because he is gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, 64, is a San Francisco philanthropist, Democratic Party
donor, former dean at the University of Chicago Law School and heir
to the Hormel meat packing fortune.
</P>
<P>
   A leading Senate liberal, Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., who has
been a vocal supporter of Hormel's, has pledged to offer a
nonbinding Senate resolution in an attempt to pressure Lott to
bring the nomination up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone has said he will attach the resolution to a major bill
after the Senate finishes work on pending tobacco legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
