</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALZAC-FILMS-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKERS' NEXT LITERARY STOP: BALZAC TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 7)  
 (bl)  
 By JEAN NATHAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the French writer Honore de Balzac died of caffeine
poisoning in 1850 at the age of 51 _ he was said to have consumed
on the order of four dozen cups of coffee a day _ he had produced
more than 100 major works, predominantly novels, all in 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was not just coffee that fueled this prodigious output; it
was also genius. (In a clear case of professional envy, Robert
Louis Stevenson qualified the use of that word by pronouncing
Balzac ``an inarticulate Shakespeare.'')
</P>
<P>
   Balzac's aim was to chronicle what he famously termed ``La
Comedie Humaine,'' and to this task he brought a superlative
storytelling ability, a wicked sense of humor and a gift for
sensitive character depiction, as well as a great deal of
compassion for human beings in all their imperfection.
</P>
<P>
   Although this ``galley slave to pen and ink,'' as Balzac
described himself, was also called a ``Napoleon of letters'' and
has consistently been seen as a great writer, he has not been read
widely in recent years. And except for a ``Masterpiece Theater''
production of ``Cousin Bette'' in the late 1970s and the 1994 movie
``Colonel Chabert,'' starring Gerard Depardieu, his work hasn't
been mined much by filmmakers, a fact that Balzac scholars explain
in part by pointing to a mistaken notion that the many parts of
``La Comedie Humaine'' need to be regarded as an interrelated
whole.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, however, movie makers are landing on Planet Balzac.
Friday, two films, representing two extremes of his oeuvre, are
opening.
</P>
<P>
   One is ``Passion in the Desert,'' an impressionistic allegory
that has been adapted by American director Lavinia Currier for her
first feature from a short story of 1830. The other is a new
adaptation of ``Cousin Bette,'' the sprawling 1847 drama of manners
that is one of Balzac's best-known novels; this movie is the first
to be directed by Tony-winning theater director Des McAnuff (``Big
River,'' ``The Who's `Tommy''').
</P>
<P>
   ``Balzac is a great source of stories for the cinema,'' said
McAnuff. ``Maybe we're just arriving at him now because it required
other astronauts going ahead with other great literary works to get
us here.''
</P>
<P>
   From the scholarly camp, Graham Robb, a British writer whose
Balzac biography was published to acclaim in 1994, put it this way:
``Maybe the movie makers have just run out of Jane Austens and
Henry Jameses. In Britain, publishers are saying people are reading
19th-century novels again, and 19th-century novels are a small
pool. Balzac, sooner or later, was bound to be rediscovered. In
this matter, one evokes chaos theory.''
</P>
<P>
   In its original form, ``Passion in the Desert'' is a story
within a story within a story. In 1798, Napoleon failed to strike
further at the British when he sent his troops into Egypt. In the
aftermath of that campaign, he had wild animals sent back from
Africa to Paris. They eventually formed the core of a zoo at the
Jardin des Plantes, but first these exotic creatures were in a
circus started by one M. Martin. The acts involving lions
especially caused a stir, and it was rumored that M. Martin was
able to hypnotize the animals and that he even had sex with them.
</P>
<P>
   In the Balzac story, a couple leaves M. Martin's circus with the
woman expressing disbelief at the spectacle. The man with her
argues that it is quite possible to tame wild animals, and he
proceeds to tell her a story that he heard from a soldier recently
returned from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier had been captured by Arabs, then had escaped and
lived in bliss under a date palm tree with a female leopard as his
companion. Their idyll had ended when, in a misunderstanding, the
leopard attacked him, forcing the soldier to kill her in
self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Currier's ``Passion,'' starring British actor Ben Daniels
and a leopard named Mowgli, the year is still 1798, but Paris and
the circus have been excised. The action begins as a regiment of
French soldiers, including a young captain named Augustin Robert
(Daniels), escort the artist Jean-Michel Venture de Paradis (played
by French actor Michel Piccoli in a gripping cameo) across the
Sahara. Venture has been commissioned by Napoleon to make a visual
record of Egypt's monuments and landscapes, as well as of the
soldiers in battle. The captain and the artist are separated from
the rest of the regiment after a skirmish with Mameluke warriors,
and are thrown off course by a sandstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Augustin decides they must separate so that he, on horseback,
can seek help more quickly. But soon his horse dies, and he wanders
alone until he comes upon the ruins of an ancient city. There it
turns out that he is sharing digs with a leopard, and a sort of
romantic relationship ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, the viewer is drawn slowly, almost hypnotically into
the otherworldliness and general delirium of the desert _ and into
the world of a dangerous animal. Ms. Currier's movie, which was
filmed in Jordan and Utah, becomes a lyrical but virtually wordless
meditation on man's capacity for transformation.
</P>
<P>
   This is all the farthest cry from ``Cousin Bette,'' a ``Bonfire
of the Vanities''-like account that takes place between 1838 and
1846 in Paris. At its center is Bette Fischer, a bitter, homely
seamstress and poor relation to the aristocratic Hulot family who
is bent on vengeance for the way she has been treated. Turning on
issues of class, financial power and sex, the story feels highly
contemporary in tone.
</P>
<P>
   This new ``Cousin Bette'' stars Jessica Lange as Bette; Hugh
Laurie as the bankrupt, philandering Hulot; Bob Hoskins as Crevel,
Hulot's chief rival, and Elisabeth Shue as Jenny Cadine, a
dance-hall performer and mistress to Hulot and Crevel who helps
Bette bring about their ruination. Geraldine Chaplin makes a brief
appearance as Hulot's long-suffering wife, Adeline.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Currier needed to invent whole strains of narrative to
fill out a Balzac story, Lynn Siefert and Susan Tarr, the
scriptwriters for ``Cousin Bette,'' had to find ways to contract a
Balzac saga. Toward this end, they lopped off plot lines and
characters too numerous to mention. ``You could write five more
movies based on `Cousin Bette,' and each one would be completely
different,'' said Ms. Siefert.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
