A0824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUDGE-COX &UR;  &UR; INTERNETG     06-02 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUDGE-COX </SLUG>
     INTERNET GOSSIP TAKES ON REAL JOURNALISTS AT
NATIONAL PRESS CLUB
 &HT;     By BOB DART 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Matt Drudge, the controversial cyberspace scoop
snoop, defended his Internet dishing Tuesday against charges of
heresy from the pious practitioners of mainstream journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is a hunger for unedited information,'' the
publisher of the Drudge Report (http://www.drudgereport.com) told
members of the National Press Club at a luncheon featuring more
hostility than hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are entering an era vibrating with the din of small voices.
Every citizen can be a reporter, can take on the powers that be,''
said Drudge. He boasted that the Drudge Report was visited 6
million times by computer users last month. ``The Net gives as much
voice to a ... computer geek like me as to a CEO or speaker of the
House. We all become equal.''
</P>
<P>
   While Drudge has been credited with breaking some big stories _
most notably that Newsweek had spiked the initial blockbuster about
President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky _ he has also been attacked
for posting rumors and gossip amid the facts.
</P>
<P>
   Some Press Club members had voiced displeasure at Drudge's
invitation to speak, and that was reflected in his acidic
introduction by President Doug Harbrecht, Washington editor of
Business Week magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drudge's methods are suspect in the eyes of most
journalists,'' Harbrecht said. ``Like a channel catfish, he mucks
through the hoaxes, conspiracies and half-truths posted online in
pursuit of fodder for his Web site. That can have unpleasant
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Drudge is facing a libel suit from White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Harbrecht conceded, however, that Drudge ``is on the cutting
edge of a revolution in our business and everyone in our business
knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Drudge's own reporting makes up only a small part of his Web
site. Mostly, the Drudge Report provides hyperlinks to wire
services, columnists, newspapers and other information sources. He
reports mostly on movies, TV, the news media and political
scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge said he still works out of a $600-a-month apartment in
Hollywood _ ``and I do mean Hollywood, not Beverly Hills, not the
Palisades, no 90210 for this kid.''
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in a Maryland suburb of the nation's capital and
moved to California after high school. Drudge had no formal
training in journalism. He worked in a CBS gift shop and found that
he could pick up inside information by eavesdropping on executives'
conversations and digging through office trash cans.
</P>
<P>
   After his father bought him a computer, Drudge began to post his
gleanings on an Internet site. Over several years, visitors to his
site grew from three or four buddies to millions of online fans, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge said he has yet to make a penny from his Web site, which
is free and carries no advertising. However, he said he has sold a
column to some publications and has a TV show in the works.
</P>
<P>
   At the Press Club, questions for Drudge were mostly harsh. Asked
how much of his report he makes up, he replied none _ and
admonished the audience for not being tough on Clinton at White
House press conferences.
</P>
<P>
   The line between gossip and news is sometimes hazy, Drudge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All truths begin as hearsay, as far as I'm concerned. And some
of the best news stories start in gossip,'' he said. ``At what
point does it become news?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Real journalists pride themselves on getting it first and
right,'' Harbrecht said. Drudge responded with a list of major
newspapers, magazines and network newscasts that had settled libel
cases, admitted that reporters had made up stories or had retracted
news accounts.
</P>
<P>
   He protested that ``a lot of the stuff I do is serious stuff.
... Not everything I do is gossip or bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   In closing, Harbrecht gave Drudge a book titled ``Reliable
Sources,'' and thanked him ``for coming to the lion's den.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
