<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALZAC-FILMS-$ADV07-2     06-02 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALZAC-FILMS-$ADV07-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Ms. Siefert.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The process of bringing ``Passion in the Desert'' to the screen
began 10 years ago when Virginia Warner, one of Ms. Currier's
cousins, ``put a little-known and very atypical story by Balzac
into my hands,'' the 40-year-old filmmaker said recently.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Ms. Currier, who had majored in comparative
religion at Harvard University and then pursued an acting career in
France, had directed only one 50-minute film for television,
``Heart of the Garden.'' She conceived ``a 30-minute dreamlike film
of this encounter between a man and a leopard _ I saw it as a dance
or a completely silent film.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't work. Neither did an effort to bring the story into
contemporary times. Later, she took another stab, going back to the
text and trying to expand it in a way that would be true to Balzac.
The version that eventually became the film, produced by Fine Line,
was completed with help from a friend and poet, Martin Edmunds.
</P>
<P>
   Like her counterparts on ``Cousin Bette,'' Ms. Currier engaged
in copious research. In this she was assisted by her grandmother
Evangeline Bruce, whose husband, David, was at various times
American Ambassador to France, Britain and China, and who had spent
years writing the historical opus ``Napoleon and Josephine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I called her all the time to ask her questions,'' Ms. Currier
said. ``She had such a palpable sense of the period.'' (The film is
dedicated to Mrs. Bruce, who died two years ago. Ms. Currier's
lineage is illustrious on her father's side as well. She is
descended from the Currier of Currier &AMP; Ives.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Currier ended up taking liberties with Balzac's
story, she was a stickler for authenticity when it came to the
leopard. In preparation for the filming, animal trainers begged her
to use a tiger or a lion instead, because they are more social
animals. ``They told me a leopard is the most dangerous,
idiosyncratic and unmanageable of the great cats,'' she recalled.
But she dug in her heels. ``I thought only a leopard, so
individualistic an animal, would be weird enough to take up with a
human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Her refusal to compromise had its price. The final script
morphed again and again to accommodate the demands of the leopard.
After initially battling heavy rains and sleet in the Jordanian
desert, the cast and crew returned in a drier season only to find
problematically high temperatures. The leopard didn't like the heat
and plainly didn't want to work. And the leopard trainer, who had
carefully advised Ms. Currier during the writing of the script as
to what the leopard could and could not be expected to do, had to
reassess the situation as the leopard turned moody.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Currier confessed, the battle scenes and the
part of the film that deals with the artist ``got bigger and
bigger, and the part with the leopard got somewhat smaller.'' And
it became necessary to pack off to the more manageable desert in
Utah to complete many of the scenes with the leopard.
</P>
<P>
   During filming, Ms. Currier and the camera crew were in a
duvetyn-covered cage, for their protection and so the leopard
wrangler could have the animal's full attention. It was, of course,
Daniels who was at the greatest risk. ``The leopard was
terrifying,'' recalled the actor, who has just starred on the
London stage in the Pirandello play ``Naked'' with Juliette
Binoche. ``I got chewed and scratched and bitten. When the cat
would go along with the scene as scripted, I knew she wasn't
concentrating on her role. She was thinking, `So, how can I eat
this person I'm playing with?'''
</P>
<P>
   Why did he accept the role? ``It was one of the most
extraordinary things I had ever read, and I couldn't resist it,''
he said. ``Also, when do you ever get a buzz like that from doing
an acting job? My fear threshold is about 100 times higher than it
was when I began.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Balzac called Bette ``une vraie sauvage'' (a true
savage), neither she nor her rich and ridiculous relations provided
anything like the filmmaking challenge that the leopard did. But
wrestling ``Cousin Bette'' into a screenplay was traumatic in it
own way.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Seifert and Ms. Tarr decided to write a script together in
1991, and Ms. Siefert eventually hit upon ``Cousin Bette.'' Ms.
Tarr said they were both impressed by ``its accessibility and
wit,'' and because it was originally written to be published in
serial form, it had a ``sense of moving quickly,'' she said. The
two women studied Balzac, outlined the novel and finished the
script on July 14 _ Bastille Day _ in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   By that fall, Fox Searchlight had decided to support the film,
but the troubles were just beginning. ``We had been very faithful
to the novel in the first draft,'' Ms. Siefert recalled, ``but when
we started working with directors, it started to take another
twist. We were being asked to hack away at the characters or to
create composite characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tarr added: ``The richness of detail and digressions are so
amazing, and much of this had to be eliminated. Our script
decisions involved sacrificing delightful characters and
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Menaul, who was expected to be the director, made the
strong suggestion that Adeline Hulot, a main character in the
novel, be dropped. The writers were mortified, but the studio
agreed. Although thrilled when a new director, McAnuff, was brought
in, there was no chance to resuscitate Adeline fully. McAnuff did,
however, see fit to give Adeline a deathbed scene at the start of
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ms. Tarr sounds like a remorseful murderer when she
describes what happened. ``We literally killed Adeline,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the reduced number of characters, it was tricky to
maintain control of the story. ``A normal film follows four or five
characters,'' said McAnuff. ``We're really following eight. That
required lots of structural shenanigans.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is, by turns, a comedic and dramatic romp that has
narrative and visual richness and an immediacy not often seen in
period films. And it feels very much in the spirit of Balzac.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties, the women are working on adapting
another Balzac novel, which they decline to name. And McAnuff said,
``Even with all the struggle, I would eagerly do Balzac again.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Currier is leaving Balzac behind, teaming up
with her friend Maura Moynihan to write the script of a ``caper
comedy'' that Ms. Currier will direct. Not that she plans to keep
it simple: the story takes place in Katmandu, Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   Will the two films opening Friday have Balzac spinning in his
grave?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think that he would expect us to adapt because he
was a very practical writer, and a real professional,'' said
McAnuff. ``I like to think he would have expected us to refocus the
narrative structure to make it work cinematically. But happily,
I'll never get the phone call if he didn't like the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Balzac would probably be pleased to be back in the
spotlight. ``Fame,'' he once wrote, ``is the sun of the dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
