<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-AWARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY HONORS WOMEN WHO HAVE IMPROVED CHILD CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling child care the uppermost concern for
working mothers, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton honored eight
women Wednesday for their work to improve the quality of child
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to reinstill a sense of urgency in Americans,''
Clinton said. ``Commitment to child care is not only good for
children and family but good for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said more than half of the women in the work force are
mothers, and half of all mothers with children under the age of one
are working outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady warned against making child care a partisan
issue, mentioning the White House child-care initiative launched in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about taking care of Democratic or
Republican or independent children,'' Clinton said. ``We're talking
about taking care of American children.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady presented Redbook magazine's ``Mother and Shakers
of 1998'' awards to the women. Redbook is published by Hearst
Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Kate White, Redbook editor in chief, said the women were honored
in the magazine's June issue because they have ``fought
passionately for kids and families.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The emergence of child care as a national issue is a direct
result of efforts by women, such as the ones we have recognized,''
White said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those honored were Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., and talk
show host Rosie O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was honored for sponsoring every major child-care bill
since being elected to the Senate six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell was recognized for her New York-based fund-raising
organization, For All Kids Foundation, which has distributed more
than $1.5 million to 105 child-related charities. The foundation
was founded in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The other award recipients were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary Beth Phillips, a San Francisco mother whose infant
daughter was blinded after being shaken by her baby sitter, was
honored for launching Trustline, a state-certifying service that
checks for possible criminal or child-abuse background of
caregivers. Since the program's inception in 1989, Trustline has
reviewed nearly 33,000 potential caregivers, weeding about 2,500
potential caregivers who had criminal records, some including
murder and sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   _ Harriet Transgucci, of Summit, N.J, was awarded for
jump-starting an emergency child-care fund at the Summer Child Care
Centers in her hometown.
</P>
<P>
   _ Elaine Fersh, a Boston mother, was honored for the work her
group, Parents United for Child Care, has done in her city. Parents
United has helped school boards implement all-day kindergarten and
has developed after-school programs for children whose parents work
full-time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Elissa Bassler, a public policy director at the Day Care
Action Council of Illinois in Chicago, was awarded for persuading
the Illinois Legislature to allocate $100 million for child care.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yvonne Edwards, a child-care coordinator for Monterey County,
Calif., was honored for leading the effort to create a child care
and women's health care center for county workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Linda Mason of Cambridge, Mass., was honored for creating
Bright Horizon Child Centers, on-site centers for corporations such
as Mattel, IBM, Apple Computer, Motorola and AT&AMP;T. There are about
160 Bright Horizon centers around the country serving more than
14,000 children.
</P>
</TEXT>
