<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS BOUNCES WILLIAMS FROM THE FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Venus Williams, the Williams sister favored to give
top-seeded Martina Hingis true trouble in her attempt to monopolize
a fourth consecutive Grand Slam, instead submitted, 6-3, 6-4, on
Tuesday in the quarterfinals of the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Williams gave her least impressive performance in five meetings
with her fellow 17-year-old this year. She was so jittery in the
center-court spotlight that her beaded headdress shivered and
quivered even when she wasn't in perpetual motion trying to chase
down the backhands Hingis used to leverage their match in her own
favor.
</P>
<P>
   The rain clouds came and went, but the plot definitely thickened
in Paris, where the swirling clay got in everybody's eyes and tears
got in the eyes of several losers, none of whom could quite believe
their French Open experience was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Chilean firebrand Marcelo Rios, the favorite to make his
Grand Slam breakthrough at Roland Garros, wore an angry grimace on
his unshaven mug after letting himself be tripped up, 6-1, 2-6,
6-2, 6-4 by Spain's Carlos Moya. It was a misstep that cost the
third-seeded Rios his chance to pocket Pete Sampras' No. 1 ranking
for a second time this year.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams walked forlornly from the court, she appeared on
the verge of bawling like a baby; but, remembering her
self-proclaimed status as the lady-in-waiting most likely to
dethrone the deservedly smug No. 1, she kept her cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dude,'' was the odd and only word the chastened Williams chose
to mouth in the direction of her stonefaced mother-coach, Brandi,
as she passed by the friends' box. According to Williams, she and
her mother huddled for an unforgiving post-mortem on the
1-hour-22-minute match right after she soared a final backhand
blooper out of bounds on the second match point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too old for petting; I just need the truth,'' said
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made too many errors, definitely; that has to do with
mechanics, and I assure you those things will be corrected,'' vowed
the teen-ager, who had just two aces, plopped out two double faults
to trail 3-4 in the second set, and made a sorry total of 38
unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I was struggling too much to hold serve, and generally
that's a sign that you're going to break down,'' said Williams, who
was so tight from the service line that she once spewed both her
racquet and the ball into the net in the course of being broken in
the second game of the opening set.
</P>
<P>
   But the day provoked a relieved smile, not a mechanical or
emotional breakdown, from the three-time champion Monica Seles, the
sentimental favorite, who wore the wedding ring of her recently
deceased father-coach, Karolj, on a chain around her neck like a
talisman when she flew into Paris just a week after he succumbed to
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertain whether she would have the intestinal fortitude to
smash a single practice ball, much less pulverize an actual
opponent, Seles has been on automatic pilot at this Slam, her focus
unwavering, her grunt going full throttle, her mind on her business
and not her grieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of him every day, but for me, it's a tennis match,
it's a tennis tournament, and I'm here because I want to win it,
that's kind of my take on it,'' Seles said after pounding her way
past third-seeded Jana Novotna with a 4-6, 6-3, 6-3 comeback that
even the wet-eyed loser found ennobling. When the two met at the
net after Novotna drifted a backhand wide of the sideline on the
second match point, Novotna told Seles she hoped she would carry on
and win this event.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that, the sixth-seeded Seles first has to get past
a semifinal match with the ultra-confident Hingis. The Swiss
teen-ager leads their rivalry by 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martina is the No. 1 player, so you know what she's going to
give you,'' said Seles. ``You have to play the best tennis at the
moment that you can, and that's what I'll have to do on Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other women's semifinal, second-seeded Lindsay Davenport,
who dethroned last year's French Open champion, Iva Majoli, 6-1,
5-7, 6-3, will take a 2-6 record against fourth-seeded Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario. The Spaniard, twice a champion here, reached the
semifinals with a 6-2, 6-7 (5-7), 6-0 dismissal of Switzerland's
other teen-age wonder-girl, Patty Schnyder.
</P>
<P>
   The upset of Rios by the 12th-seeded Moya, who cut his Grand
Slam teeth the same way Rios did, by a reaching an Australian Open
final, deprived the men's draw of the only representative from the
top 10 to survive until the quarterfinal round.
</P>
<P>
   It also ended the 14-match clay-court winning streak Rios
assembled this spring by claiming titles at Rome and Austria,
distinguishing himself as the only man to win two clay titles in
1998 and the clear man to beat at Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rios was disturbed by a call that led to his dropping
serve to trail 4-5 in the final set _ he thought a ball bounced
twice on Moya's side of the net and so missed a play on an easy
volley _ he admitted that he didn't play with vintage Rios
aggression Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing the first set, 6-1, that killed me a little bit,'' said
Rios. ``I started recovering a little bit, but he played a great
match and deserved to win today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other men's quarterfinal, Austria's Thomas Muster, who
won his only Slam title here in 1995, was ousted, 6-4, 6-2, 4-6,
6-3 by a fake blond with a fine forehand, Spain's 15th-seeded Felix
Mantilla.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Last year's French Open men's champion, Gustavo Kuerten, who
made an affable enough exit in the second round of singles, where
he fell to Russia's 18-year-old Marat Sade, was thrown out of his
doubles quarterfinal Tuesday evening after he got into a squabble
with head umpire Bruno Rebeuh and hurled his racquet toward the
official.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gilbert Ysern, the tournament referee, the
infraction took place just after Kuerten and his Brazilian
teammate, Fernando Meligeni, had dropped the first set tie breaker
to Patrick Rafter and Jonas Bjorkman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kuerten was just unhappy with one call and lost his mind a
little bit,'' said Ysern. ``He threw his racquet very hard and very
fast and unfortunately it nearly hit the umpire and landed in the
crowd. It was a clear default situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebeuh is the same umpire who disqualified Jeff Tarango from
Wimbledon three years ago, an affront that caused the player's
wife, Benedicte, to direct a pair of slaps to the umpire's face,
but Ysern said there was no bad blood between Kuerten and the
official.
</P>
<P>
   Rebeuh was in the chair here last year when Kuerten won his
first and only Slam. Bjorkman said that Kuerten, one of the more
congenial players on the tour, was in tears and inconsolable in the
locker room after the incident. Besides being disqualified, Kuerten
will forfeit his French Open earnings, approximately $40,000, but
Ysern did not indicate that any further action would be taken
against the Brazilian. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
