<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-TV-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT KENNEDY: THE PRIVATE SIDE OF A POLITICAL STORY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last Washington to New York shuttle of the day was
two-thirds empty. Near the back sat Robert F. Kennedy, tears
welling up in his eyes, as the folk musician Phil Ochs, a fellow
passenger, sang ``Crucifixion.'' (``Who would want to hurt such a
hero of the game?/ But you know, I predicted it. I knew he had to
fall/ ... Do you have a picture of the pain?'') It had just dawned
on Kennedy, says the former aide who is telling the story, that the
song was about his brother.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel's three-hour special ``Robert F. Kennedy:
A Memoir'' (beginning Sunday night at 8), based on Jack Newfield's
1969 book, is about politics, of course. It's about the Senate
racket hearings, the civil rights movement, presidential campaigns,
power plays and the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But the personal side of Kennedy, who was assassinated in Los
Angeles 30 years ago (June 5, 1968), comes across with just as much
impact.
</P>
<P>
   William Haddad, who was on that plane beside Kennedy, tells the
Phil Ochs story. Robert Morgenthau describes having clam chowder
and tuna sandwiches with Kennedy by the pool at Hickory Hill,
Kennedy's McLean, Va., home, on Nov. 22, 1963, when the telephone
call came from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   William Vanden Heuvel tells of Kennedy, after late work nights,
stopping by Arlington National Cemetery and climbing the fence to
kneel at President Kennedy's grave and pray. George McGovern starts
out smiling as he recounts reactions to Kennedy's taking his dog
along on a campaign trip to South Dakota, but ends up moved to
tears, because that was the last time he ever saw Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's daughters tell of spending time at their father's
office when they were small. They read letters from him, one
written on the day the first black students were enrolled at the
University of Alabama, another written shortly after John F.
Kennedy's death.
</P>
<P>
   Challenged by a Columbia University student about his motives in
running for the Senate, Kennedy explains his desire to serve. ``I
don't need the money, and I don't need the office space,'' he
begins, winning his audience over.
</P>
<P>
   To young voters demanding his position on penalties for draft
evasion, he quotes Camus. And before an Indianapolis crowd to whom
he has just announced the news of Martin Luther King's death, he
speaks of ``pain which cannot forget'' and ``wisdom through the
awful grace of God.'' It has been a long time since a politician
quoted Aeschylus to us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
