<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGULL-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 `THE SEAGULL': A CHEKHOV ROMANCE TO STYMIE WOMEN OF THE '90s  
 (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ True to the content of ``The Sea Gull,'' which begins
with the presentation of an amateurish backyard play, the Blue
Light Theater Company's production of Chekhov's tragicomedy of
thwarted ambition has the feel of something slapped together for a
few supportive friends.
</P>
<P>
   The scenery, a stand of birch trees with shiny plastic leaves,
flanked on one side by an incongruous series of paneled walls,
offers a country house with such an incoherent layout it's a wonder
the owners didn't sack the architects. The desultory props and
furnishings fuel suspicions, not aroused by the script, that the
whole lot has been unloaded on Madame Arkadina and her brother by
their wily caretakers.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences will overlook a production's physical decrepitude if
it is merely a shabby overcoat that envelops an array of
immaculately turned out performances.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Austin Pendleton's entirely sub-par production exposes
none of the exquisite pathos in the clashes of ego and crushing of
hopes in Chekhov's sad tale. Pendleton's version, which lumbers
along for two and a half intermissionless hours, also labors under
some misguided casting and directorial choices, like the moment
when the aging Arkadina (Maria Tucci) decides the only way she'll
keep Trigorin (Mark Blum) is by mounting him.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Sea Gull'' is not always so crude. Most of the time, in
fact, it's as mild (and about as Russian) as American cheese. Jeff
Cohen, in retrospect, had an interesting concept last winter with
his modern adaptation of the play, set in the Hamptons. At least
there the actors, encouraged to find clarity in more familiar
surroundings, made sense of Chekhov's characters, set in their
unhappy ways.
</P>
<P>
   Pendleton, however, finds nothing in ``The Sea Gull'' to give
the play emotional depth or a coherent wholeness, and the staging
consists mostly of actors lined up or milling about.
</P>
<P>
   Angie Phillips' Nina conveys little of the tragic bearing of the
girl who leaves town as a starry-eyed naief and returns a shattered
outcast; Blum, as the self-infatuated pulp writer who uses and
discards her, plays Trigorin as a rumpled schlep who would have a
hard time getting to class, let alone the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Naughton's male model of a Konstantin _ why Nina would
reject him in favor of Trigorin is the sort of imponderable that
would give Ally McBeal nightmares _ comes across as sincere but
utterly dull. Joe Ponazecki's ineffectual Dorn practically
evaporates before our eyes, and Ms. Tucci, as Chekhov's horror show
of a mother, gets the character's self-absorption but none of her
grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   The director mutes the play's symbolism to the point of
irrelevance. When Naughton arrives onstage with the dead sea gull,
he tosses it matter-of-factly at the feet of Ms. Phillips, who
reacts as if he's taken off a pair of smelly old shoes. Naughton
says he shot the bird, but it wouldn't be surprising to learn the
poor thing had committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE SEA GULL
</P>
<P>
   By Anton Chekhov; translated by Tom Stoppard; directed by Austin
Pendleton; sets by Michael Schweikardt; costumes by Laurie Churba;
lighting by John Lasiter; sound by Jerry M. Yager; production stage
manager, Christina Massie; technical director, Peter Barbieri.
Presented by the Blue Light Theater Company, Greg Naughton,
actor-manager; William S. Doble, general manager. At Theater Four,
424 W. 55th St., Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Mark Blum (Trigorin), Tom Brennan (Shamraev), Francesca Di
Mauro (Masha), Alex Draper (Medvedenko), Greg Naughton
(Konstantin), Angie Phillips (Nina), Joe Ponazecki (Dorn), Molly
Regan (Polina), Bill Striglos (Sorin), and Maria Tucci (Arkadina).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
