<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TALLEY-THEATER-REVIEW     06-02 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALLEY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TALLEY &AMP; SON': DESPERATELY SEEKING ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It takes Timmy Talley a few minutes to realize he's
dead. It is July 4, 1944, and he is standing alone, wearing
fatigues and a helmet, in an old-fashioned Midwestern living room.
He has just been killed, thousands of miles away in the Pacific,
and only his spirit has come home.
</P>
<P>
   As Timmy (Tim Deak), who is invisible to his family, observes
them over the two acts of ``Talley &AMP; Son,'' he also realizes that
this is no bittersweet ``Our Town'' flashback to the joys of being
alive. Just about everybody in the Talley family is in desperate
need of attention, and almost nobody is getting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talley &AMP; Son,'' the last in the trilogy of Lanford Wilson's
dramas about the family, was not particularly well received when it
opened in 1985. Critics compared it with its predecessors ``The
Fifth of July'' (1978) and ``Talley's Folly'' (1979) and found it
wanting. But regarded alone, it stands as an intelligent reflection
on unhappiness and waning morality, and in the Jean Cocteau
Repertory production at the Bouwerie Lane Theater through June 14,
the audience is in the hands of pros.
</P>
<P>
   The family patriarch (Craig Smith), who is expected to die at
any moment, alternates between likable senility and periods of
coherence when he is completely in charge. His son, Eldon (Harris
Berlinsky), is undecided about selling the family manufacturing
business (which is making a wartime bundle manufacturing fatigues)
to a big corporation. And he's further troubled by a young woman
(Christine Hall) who turns up in shorts and a halter top claiming
that he is her father.
</P>
<P>
   Eldon's wife, Netta (Tracey Atkins), is a vision of period
domesticity in a polka-dot dress and apron, like an ad from a 1940s
copy of House and Garden come to life. Ms. Atkins exudes a ladylike
repression which helps make her seem authentically of her time.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Act I, when the Talleys' friend, Harley Campbell
(Charles Parnell), delivers the telegram announcing Timmy's death,
Netta faints. At the beginning of Act II, she insists that she
didn't, that she had thought there was a chair behind her. ``He's
taking this very hard,'' she says of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Eldon seems worthy of sympathy when he responds: ``How are we
supposed to take this? How do people take it?'' But then he
mentions that what really matters is whether Timmy killed his share
of ``Japs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Timmy's brother, Buddy (Patrick Hall), and his
annoyingly self-possessed wife, Olive (Mary Ellen Taylor), can't
keep their hands off each other. And Aunt Lottie (Elise Stone) sits
quietly in the corner, playing solitaire and dying of radium
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   The men in ``Talley &AMP; Son'' spend a lot of time apologizing for
cursing in front of the women, but it never occurs to them to stop
cursing instead. And as the drama plays out, it's clear that the
patriarch's rant about ``moral corruption'' applies to much more
than an affair with a woman from the wrong side of the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the play, Netta insists that Eldon lock up the
house before going to bed. He argues, because nobody in this town
locks his doors. ``Talley &AMP; Son'' is a heartbreaking portrait of
the moment in recent history when that changed.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TALLEY &AMP; SON'
</P>
<P>
   By Lanford Wilson; directed by Scott Shattuck; sets by Robert
Joel Schwartz; lighting by Brian Aldous; costumes by Susan
Soetaert. Presented by the Jean Cocteau Repertory, Shattuck,
producing artistic director; Robert Hupp, artistic director. At the
Bouwerie Lane Theater, 330 Bowery, at Bond Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Tim Deak (Timmy), Harris Berlinsky (Eldon), Elise Stone
(Lottie), Craig Smith (Talley), Tracey Atkins (Netta), Mary Ellen
Taylor (Olive), Christine Hall (Viola Platt), Patrick Hall (Buddy),
and Charles Parnell (Harley Campbell).
</P>
</TEXT>
