<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION FEARS TURMOIL IN MEXICO'S CHIAPAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ As firefighters inched toward controlling forest
fires in Chiapas, opposition politicians said Tuesday that
political strife continues to rage in the southeastern state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political-military crisis in Chiapas is becoming more
profound every day,'' said Camilo Valenzuela, state delegate to the
national executive committee of the left-leaning Party of the
Democratic Revolution, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   Despite three visits in the past month by President Ernesto
Zedillo, social and political factionalism, sharpened by the
intervention of the Mexican army, make Chiapas a tinderbox,
Valenzuela said in an interview at the party's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   He brought a group of Chiapan PRD leaders to Mexico City to air
what they described as political and physical harassment by state
officials loyal to the long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   After years of organizing and surviving the murder of scores of
party activists, the PRD has won political control of 18 of the
state's 111 municipalities since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot has been a slew of PRD officials indicted, Valenzuela
said, on trumped-up charges to remove them from office, endless
audits of municipalities governed by the PRD, and a devastating
round of budget cuts for municipalities proposed by the
PRI-controlled state government.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of PRD activists continues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1994, the Zapatista National Liberation Army led a
brief rebellion against the government and the impoverished
conditions of the state's Mayan Indians. More than 150 people were
killed in 10 days of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Since peace talks broke off nearly two years ago, villages have
divided along political, religious and economic lines. Armed
militias loyal either to the Zapatistas or to the PRI have clashed
repeatedly, killing hundreds and driving thousands more from their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   In December, 45 unarmed civilians _ many of them women and
children _ were slaughtered in the village of Acteal by a group of
pro-PRI gunmen allegedly trained by off-duty members of the Mexican
army.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of foreign supporters of the Zapatistas have been
expelled from the country for alleged political activities in
Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve people, including three Canadians and three Americans,
were expelled after a heavily armed force of state police and army
troops raided the autonomous municipality of Flores Magon on April
12.
</P>
<P>
   The interim governor of Chiapas, Roberto Albores Guillen, has
called the Zapatistas' unilateral creation of autonomous
municipalities unconstitutional and has broken up several in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   But in a surprise move three days ago, Valenzuela said, Albores
announced a plan to create 33 new municipalities within the areas
of the state's worst violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave interested parties just one week to register their
input,'' Valenzuela said.
</P>
<P>
   While the PRD is studying the plan, observers in Chiapas say it
remains to be seen if the Zapatistas will accept Albores' political
districting.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, firefighters are battling wildfires that have swept
across drought-stricken Mexico this year, spreading smoky haze
across the country and into the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0880 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-LOBBY-ART-700&AMP;ADD     06-02 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-LOBBY-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYISTS CHARGE THE FIELD IN MANAGED CARE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill., Ohio, Fla., Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(JT) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not long after Sen. Edward M. Kennedy introduced a
bill to overhaul managed care this spring, his staff put out a
feeler to the unwitting heroine of the movement, Helen Hunt, the
actress who portrayed the exhausted, angst-ridden, HMO-bashing
mother of an asthma sufferer in the movie ``As Good as It Gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Would she be interested in promoting the bill?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hunt is mulling it over, but countless others have jumped at
the chance, offering Democrats and lobbyists a public relations
coup in the explosive battle on Capitol Hill to revamp managed
health care: victims and their horror stories.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful insurance and small-business lobbies, meanwhile,
are fighting back. Last week, they began running advertisements
featuring ``Fat Cat Trial Lawyers'' who are ``laughing all the way
to the bank'' at the prospect of an expanded lawsuit provision in
proposed legislation. The radio spots were broadcast in Ohio,
Florida and Missouri, where some of the 12 House members on a
Republican managed-care study group _ and their constituents _
would be certain to hear them.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress considers wrestling with managed care in the next
two months, lobbyists are busy making sure their viewpoints are
heard too. Each side has spent at least $1 million in advertising
and close to $2 million in campaign contributions, mostly to
Republicans. They have hired astute lobbyists and barraged members
with faxes and telephone calls. And they have delivered
not-so-subtle reminders of party and corporate loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are lobbying like heck and spending money like crazy,''
said Rep. John Dingell of Michigan, the senior Democrat on the
Commerce Committee. Dingell has introduced one of the major pieces
of legislation on managed care along with Kennedy, D-Mass., and
senator Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   In just a few months, the managed-care conundrum has become one
of the issues of the year on Capitol Hill, with Democrats comparing
it to the minimum wage in its populist appeal. Originally, only a
few quixotic Republicans agreed with Democrats on the issue, but
slowly, with the polls showing its resonance, it has spread to the
rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, who for months shied away from the issue
despite broad bipartisan support for one of the bills, have
relented. Doing something about managed care, say lobbyists and
members of Congress, has become practically unavoidable. Now the
question is what.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are in a box and the industry is probably not
much more popular than tobacco right now,'' said Charles N. Kahn
III, the chief operating officer and president-designate of the
Health Insurance Association of America, which represents
commercial insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Any day now a House study group appointed by Speaker Newt
Gingrich of Georgia is expected to complete a bill to counter the
existing proposals that many Republicans consider too radical, too
regulatory and too likely to stoke frivolous lawsuits. So far,
though, the effort has drawn the ire of Gingrich, a reaction that
shows how contentious an issue it is for Republicans, and members
are busy retooling the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``In politics, you never know which way the football will
bounce,'' said Rep. Harris Fawell, an Illinois Republican in the
study group who said the public's concerns about managed care would
be addressed in the group's bill. ``The Democrats have jumped on it
and they seem to think it will be a nice vehicle for retaking
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the overhaul effort say they simply want to give
patients access to more doctors, the right to appeal a managed care
organization's decision to an impartial panel and the freedom to
sue the organizations for malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton revved up the issue in his January State of
the Union Message when he called for a patient's bill of rights,
without offering specifics. Lobbyists, sensing change, got to work.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until April, when Democrats in Congress
introduced their bill, that the political warfare broke out and the
``anecdote'' faced off against the advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats got an immediate, significant boost when the American
Medical Association decided to endorse the bill, despite
traditional reservations about lawsuits. Groups representing
nurses, pediatricians, anesthesiologists and many others came on
board, and all have been lobbying on behalf of the bill. Labor
unions have also made it a priority.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, the effort was bolstered again when a Republican
pollster conducted a survey that made some Republicans cringe. It
showed that 67 percent of those surveyed were willing to pay $17
more a month in premiums to change the system.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Senate Democrats started their ``victim a
day'' campaign, which brought one Democrat or another to the Senate
floor each day to let fly a poignant anecdote about an ordinary
American who had been victimized by a managed care company.
</P>
<P>
   One day recently, Sen. Barbara Boxer of California told of Harry
Christie, whose 9-year-old daughter was found to have a rare kidney
tumor and needed the expert skills that only two doctors in America
could provide. The insurance company directed them to a general
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my only child,'' Ms. Boxer quoted Christie as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're out of luck,'' came the reply from the company, Ms.
Boxer said. The family paid for the surgery themselves.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, President Clinton took up the mantle and comforted
Regina Powers, a breast cancer patient who recounted her
gut-wrenching confrontation with a health maintenance organization
when she wanted to see an oncologist and a breast surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is urgent _ I mean how many more stories do we have to
hear like Regina's before we actually act?'' Clinton asked at a
news conference with Ms. Powers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
