<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0881 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-LOBBY-ART-2NDTAKE     06-02 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-LOBBY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: Ms. Powers.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senate Democrats have threatened to attach their bill to other
pieces of legislation in June and July, a pressure tactic that is
not permitted in the House. But House members supportive of the
overhaul efforts have raised the specter of a ``discharge
petition,'' the procedural maneuver that revived the moribund
campaign finance debate, if Republican leaders fail to act.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, groups on both sides of the issue have contributed
generously to Congress. The managed care industry has given more
than $1.5 million in contributions to federal candidates and
parties so far this election season, paying particular attention to
Republican leaders, according to the nonpartisan Center for
Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Health specialists who are not doctors have doled out more than
$1.8 million, with 53 percent of it going to Democrats. The
American Medical Association has weighed in with more than
$646,000, 71 percent going to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The groups opposing the overhaul effort see their biggest
challenge as muffling the swell of violins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the debate and discussion is very objective,''
Kahn said in frustration. ``It's a disease-of-the-month club
approach, and then it's also a Chinese menu of solutions, some of
which are thought out and others of which the cost implications are
not even analyzed or thought through.''
</P>
<P>
   To get their message out, lobbyists have run a series of
newspaper and radio advertisements since January. They have stuck
closely to one theme of warning: Pass this legislation, and expect
to see premiums jump, the number of the uninsured to rise and
frivolous lawsuits to multiply.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyists have focused on certain Republican members, first
on the 88 who co-sponsored a bill by Rep. Charlie Norwood, the
Republican dentist from Georgia who spearheaded the first overhaul
effort. Six of those members backed off. When nine Republicans
supported the Democratic proposal, they were snowed under with
faxes, letters and telephone calls. Two of the lawmakers dropped
their support within 24 hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
