<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MILWAUKEE-COX     06-02 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MILWAUKEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feelings about Braves defection still run deep 33 years later
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE, Wisc. _ The historic first pitch still was nearly
three hours away, yet father and son had their game bratwursts on.
The car trunk was open. The brats were sizzling on the little
portable grill. The beer was frosty. And the Dischlers of Plain,
Wisc., were ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting 33 years for this night,'' Pat Dischler Jr.
said. ``I mean that seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for Monday, when the Braves opened a three-game series
with the Milwaukee Brewers, now in the National League, and finally
returned to their old homeland after a 33-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game I picked when I bought my season tickets was
June 1, 1998,'' Dischler said. ``I wanted to be here when the
Braves came back. To boo 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   He was here the night of Sept. 22, 1965, when Sandy Koufax and
the Dodgers beat the Braves in 12 innings, prolonging the civic
agony a bit more. It was the night the Milwaukee Braves played
their final game in Milwaukee County Stadium before moving to
Atlanta for the 1966 season.
</P>
<P>
   Dischler recalls the banner on the facade in the right-field
bleachers that evening: Goodbye, Milwaukee Braves. ``One of the
saddest signs I ever saw'' he said. ``There were a lot of sad
people, a lot of mad people.'' Few sadder, or madder, than
Dischler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so mad when the Braves left town I didn't drink Coke
again 'til I was 38,'' he said. A dry spell lasting 23 years,
prompted by a $15 million TV deal between the Braves and Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'd protest Coca-Cola the rest of my life,'' said
Dischler, now 48. ``Put it this way: I kicked a can around for a
long time. That was my team. Back then, you felt like they were
playing for you. Hank Aaron, Warren Spahn, Eddie Mathews, Lew
Burdette. There was no free-agency then. You knew they were going
to be on the team every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Until one year when the whole team was gone, after 13 memorable
seasons in Milwaukee. The Braves never had a losing season here
after moving from Boston in 1953. They set major-league attendance
records in the '50s, won two National League pennants and the 1957
World Series. They had power personified in Aaron and Mathews,
unparalleled pitching from Spahn and Burdette and a city's genuine
adoration, which included all the beer the Braves could drink.
Which they did.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the good old days. And then they were gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milwaukee always had this feeling,'' Dischler said, ``that
this community was not raped but ripped off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people here hate the Braves. They hate 'em,'' said Pat
Grainger, 35, an engineer and Braves fan, who lived in Atlanta
1976-86. ``People who've been around since the '50s, some of 'em
have never been to a game since. Some old men I know, they'll never
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Some didn't return when the debt-ridden Seattle Pilots moved
here in 1970 after one dismal expansion season. They became the
Milwaukee Brewers of, alas, the American League. The Brewers made
the postseason twice, won the AL pennant in 1982 and lost that
World Series in seven games to the Cardinals. Yet this has always
been a National League town, and now it is once again.
</P>
<P>
   When Bud Selig, the Brewers CEO, baseball's acting commissioner
and a native Milwaukeean, got a faxed letter last November from the
major leagues' realignment committee, he was overcome emotionally
and began to weep. After so much wrangling over realignment, and
Kansas City's refusal to switch leagues, the owners wanted Selig's
Brewers to move to the NL. He had resisted, to avoid any appearance
of conflict of interest. But perhaps more than anyone, Selig knows
Milwaukee is back where it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great night, a wonderful night,'' Selig said Monday.
``I guess there's a lot of fulfillment. I remember the last game
here 33 years ago. Now, the Braves are back, and all's well that
ends well.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig grieved that last, awful night of Sept. 22, 1965. By then,
he headed Teams Inc., the group that was in charge of running the
Braves' day-to-day operation, while the club's ownership, headed by
chairman of the board Bill Bartholomay, was, literally, safely
ensconced in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the saddest nights I've ever seen,'' Selig said.
``There was a standing ovation for Aaron and Mathews. The weeping,
the sadness. It was very, very, very emotional. I guess that night
if you would've asked me, or anybody, if the Braves would ever play
again here, well, it didn't look very good. But this is one of
those times in life we've come full circle, and it doesn't come
very often. I've looked forward to this game for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was Turn Back the Clock Night. Ticket and concession
prices were rolled back to the heyday '50s. Hot dogs, sodas and
bleacher seats cost a buck, general admission $3, upper-grandstand
tickets $4. Both teams wore replica Milwaukee uniforms from 1958,
the Braves in road gray, the Brewers in the old cream home jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron threw out the first pitch, just as he did on April 7
for the Brewers' home opener and NL debut. This one was caught by
Logan, the old battling shortstop who is now a Brewers scout and
the only original Milwaukee Braves player still living here.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Guthrie watched it all. Now 50 and a history teacher,
Guthrie grew up just a few miles from County Stadium in West Allis.
Logan lived in the neighborhood. ``I was out here virtually every
night as a kid. I lived out here,'' said Guthrie, who'd pedal his
bike to the ballpark, sometimes buy a 50-cent ticket but often sat
outside on a grassy knoll beyond right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was baseball crazy back then,'' said Guthrie,
wearing a Milwaukee Braves 1957 champs sweatshirt. ``They were like
the Packers are now. Even during the off-season, they'd be talking
about the Braves on the news. It was nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   It was troublesome one day in '64, when Guthrie was sitting near
the visitors' dugout and a Cincinnati Red yelled out to Mathews
during batting practice, ``I hear you guys are moving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' replied Mathews, saying what Guthrie was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were rumors,'' Guthrie said, ``but when it happened it
was very depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie was working as a hot-dog vendor the night of Sept. 22,
1965. ``I remember we ran out on the field after the game, ran
around the bases. People were picking up stuff: grass, dirt, even
the bases. I never thought I'd get to see the Braves again.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did. Most older fans here this week rooted for the
Brewers, although some wore old block-M Milwaukee Braves caps and a
few No. 44 Aaron Milwaukee jerseys. The Atlanta fans here? Those
were the younger ones, kids who have watched the Braves dominate
the 1990s. Some spent $20 on commemorative T-shirts that featured
two ticket stubs, one stamped the Braves' return to Milwaukee, the
other Milwaukee's return to the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milwaukee Baseball,'' the T-shirt reads. ``Past, Present &AMP;
Future.'' The future is rising beyond center field, where Miller
Park, the $200 million retractable-roof domed stadium opening in
2000, is being built. The past, and present, converges again
tonight. To a city's delight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
