</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-FLIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breakdown of Atlanta-Tokyo route
 &HT;    (Sidebar to DELTA-JAPAN)
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta's Atlanta-Tokyo nonstop flights will travel
6,850 miles _ nearly 1,600 miles more than Delta's next-longest
route.
</P>
<P>
   The airline will use 222-seat MD-11 widebody jets with optional
center fuel tanks. The planes will take off with more than 40,000
gallons of fuel, or about 8,000 more than needed, the airline says.
Passengers will fly a little less than 14 hours westbound and about
12 1/2 hours eastbound, with the difference due to wind patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Airlines, the incumbent on the route, uses 324-passenger
747-400 jumbo jets.
</P>
<P>
   Four pilots will work each Delta flight with two working while
the others rest in bunks at the rear of the cockpit. Federal rules
require the extra staffing for any flight over 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers will get three meals on either Delta's or JAL's
flights, with a choice of Western or Asian menus. Both carriers
staff the flights with bilingual flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's jets will have three classes: economy, business and
first. JAL's flights offer economy and business. While Asian
carriers are known generally for higher-quality service than
western airlines, the biggest single difference may boil down to
smoking. JAL still allows it; Delta has gone cold turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
