<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKERS CALL MORALES A LIAR IN TOBACCO DISPUTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorney General Dan Morales has repeatedly lied
and tried to ``bully'' the governor and other state officials in
the dispute over tobacco legal fees, seven legislators told a
federal judge Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Angry over Morales' effort to slap them with multimillion-dollar
penalties, the lawmakers responded with some of the strongest
language yet in the 4-month-old controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general is the one who is holding repeated press
conferences filled with lies and evasions,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments were made in a formal response filed by their
attorney, Pete Schenkkan of Austin, to Morales' motion seeking $25
million in sanctions against the legislators and Gov. George W.
Bush. The governor has not yet filed his response.
</P>
<P>
   Morales last week told U.S. District Judge David Folsom of
Texarkana that the governor and legislators should be fined for
allegedly acting in ``bad faith'' in their efforts to reduce $2.3
billion awarded five private lawyers who helped the state settle
the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said their opposition is politically motivated and
places the $15.3 billion settlement in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   He has said the private lawyers recently were willing to
consider a ``substantial'' reduction in their fees but that Bush
refused to negotiate with them. The governor's office said there
was still no guarantee that part of the fees wouldn't come from the
state's share of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers reportedly offered to reduce their fees to between
$800 million and $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislators said if anyone is jeopardizing the
settlement, it is Morales, because he has refused their attempts to
separate the dispute over lawyers fees from final approval of the
tobacco settlement. They also blame him for escalating the fight by
calling a press conference the same day he filed the sanctions
motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general's press release trumpeting the motion for
sanctions makes it clear that that motion was filed for purposes of
bullying and intimidating, in an effort to force legislators and
the governor'' to withdraw their opposition, the lawmakers' brief
said.
</P>
<P>
   They accused Morales of ``making false public statements for
emotional and political spin ... without proper attention to the
legal principles that control in this court.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales spokesman Ward Tisdale said the lawmakers'
characterizations of Morales are ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general has been nothing but truthful regarding
all the actions that have taken place throughout this litigation,''
Tisdale said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers also oppose Morales' efforts to prohibit them and
the governor from contacting tobacco industry representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the seven legislators argue that the $2.3 billion in
legal fees, which were based on a 15 percent contingency agreement
the outside lawyers had with the state, are excessive. They also
say the state may have to pay part of the fees from its share of
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In their brief, the lawmakers said cigarette companies
apparently have offered Morales and the private lawyers a
restructured fee agreement, similar to what the industry recently
agreed to pay lawyers in Minnesota's tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Minnesota deal, outside lawyers will be paid less than
in Texas but will receive all their money in less than three years,
rather than over 25 years, as in Texas. And the tobacco industry
agreed to pay all the lawyers' fees in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Industry spokesman Scott Williams said tobacco companies haven't
made such an offer to Texas. Tisdale said a payment plan similar to
Minnesota's has been discussed, but he wouldn't say who proposed
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been discussions about paying the lawyers less
money but in a shorter time frame,'' Tisdale said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators, in their latest federal court filing, again
urged the judge to let them question Houston attorney Joe Jamail
about allegations that Morales solicited millions of dollars from
lawyers he considered hiring for the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Morales was out of state Tuesday for meetings with tobacco
representatives. He is attempting to increase Texas' tobacco deal
by at least $2 billion to match, proportionately, the more-recent
Minnesota agreement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
