<HEADER>
A0888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-JAPAN-COX     06-02 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-JAPAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta's nonstop Atlanta-Tokyo begins today
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The number of airline seats flying nonstop between
Atlanta and Tokyo climbs sharply today.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines begins daily nonstop service between Hartsfield
and Narita airports, joining Japan Airlines on the route.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the airlines will fly 2,526 seats round-trip every
week, up from the 972 weekly seats now offered by JAL on Monday,
Wednesday and Saturday flights.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Atlanta market support such a dramatic increase,
especially amid an economic slump in Asia? It doesn't have to,
although the timing could be better, said Vince Caminiti, Delta's
senior vice president marketing-international.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an Atlanta issue, it's a Southeast issue,'' he
said. Caminiti said Delta will rely on passengers from across the
East connecting through the airline's Hartsfield hub.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's existing Tokyo flights from Atlanta stop in Portland,
Ore. That second stop for passengers who've already connected once
at Hartsfield means two more hours total travel time, compared with
more streamlined routings on rivals such as United or Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going after the connecting passenger who has been flying
through Chicago or Detroit or New York and offering them the same
or better service through Atlanta,'' Caminiti said. Delta expects
about 65 percent of its Atlanta-Tokyo passengers to be connecting.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the local market is unimportant. The additional flights
will boost Japan's business connections with Georgia, already ``the
center of Japanese industry in the Southeast'' with 370
Japan-affiliated businesses, according to Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, which plans to continue its Portland-Tokyo flights, has
long wanted a nonstop route from Atlanta but had to wait for a
breakthrough this winter in U.S.-Japan air treaty talks.
</P>
<P>
   Continental and American, which like Delta are bit players in
the U.S.-Japan market, also plan new nonstops from their hubs under
the treaty revision. And United and Northwest plan to fortify their
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question for Atlanta is whether JAL will continue
its service, begun in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Evilsizor, JAL's Southeast sales chief, said its flights
run 78 percent full on average but expects to lose 10 to 15 percent
as some fliers defect to Delta because of its daily service and
frequent flier program. He added JAL could face a decision later
this year whether to leave the route.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
