<HEADER>
A0890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-MALONE-COX     06-02 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-MALONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Malone and Jazz ``just want one''
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salt Lake City, Utah _ Just once in his life, Karl Malone wants
to ride off into the sunset on that Harley of his with an NBA
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be greedy,'' he said. ``I just want one. I
don't want three, four, five, or even two. I just want one.
Hopefully, we can take care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearing his 35th birthday, Malone has a resume that lacks only
an NBA championship ring. He has done all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Malone came into the NBA a raw-boned kid from a small community
in rural Louisiana and learned to play basketball the right way. He
honed his body, mind and skills to become the pre-eminent power
forward in the game. He ended Michael Jordan's reign as the NBA's
most valuable player a year ago and is the acknowledged driving
force for the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 6-foot-9, 255-pound Malone has a second chance to get
the one prize in sports that has eluded his grasp and escaped his
partner John Stockton and their phlegmatic, driven coach, Jerry
Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   He enters Game I of the NBA finals tonight against Chicago with
a reputation as a sometimes brutal competitor, a person who will do
anything to win. It's part fact, part fiction. Malone has been part
of a couple of ugly NBA moments. But those images must be balanced
by others:
</P>
<P>
   _ Two years ago during the West finals, a teary-eyed Malone
brought joy to a dying child, pushing his wheelchair into a
postgame press conference and introducing him as ``my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Malone, as Everyman, has spent several summers delivering
freight in his own 18-wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the offseason, Malone loves to hide in a sweat box in
Alaska, the bayous of Louisiana or the Arkansas Ozarks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Malone is not too proud to advertise Rogaine, a solution he
rubs into his ever-growing bald spot in an effort to grow hair.
</P>
<P>
   Malone is, in fact, an NBA enigma. His NBA success has given him
the wherewithal to comfortably escape the limelight. That's what
Malone does best.
</P>
<P>
   He often is content to hop on his Harley-Davidson, chromed and
pearl with painted western motif, and ride across valleys and
mountains. Sometimes in company, often alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go down to Vegas and get out in the limo with the big
Rolex on and 20 people around me,'' Malone says. ``I do have a
posse sometimes, when I ride my Harley, because we ride to Jackson
Hole every summer, and I got six or eight guys that I ride with.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone says he catches grief for not being like most NBA
players. But he doesn't own a double-breasted suit and a closet of
gold chains and bracelets. In fact, he's a blue jeans and T-shirt
kind of guy who recently enjoyed the birth of his fourth child.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, I was fishing and hunting all the time,'' Malone
said. ``But now I'm criticized for that. I love to hunt, and I love
guns. Now, when I go hunting, it's documented. I get my license at
the fish and game (department), and I have people upset with me
because I'm going bear hunting or I'm going cougar hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is how I grew up, hunting and fishing. I got a place
in Alaska, and (people say) I'm a hick for that. I go to Alaska to
fish, or I spend three or four days out in the tundra with friends
hunting caribou. But they say I'm a redneck for that. Things that I
do are not the norm for professional athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Take his commitment to winning, for example. Few equal Malone's
drive for excellence, although he says he gives into temptation
once in a while. A cheeseburger, for example, doesn't add to his
33-inch waist. He doesn't think he jeopardizes his health with a
cigar ``every now and then. I love a cigar.'' He doesn't mind a
visit to the Nevada border town of Wendover or a Shreveport
riverboat casino for a little gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know what I got to do the next morning,'' he said. ``If
you want to hang out and do things at night, you got to be able to
stay on your same schedule the next day. That's part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   His workout regimen, including daily weight-lifting and situps,
is stuff of legend, and he doesn't mind letting people know how
hard he works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about me bringing my lunch pail every night to help
you win,'' he says. ``I come to play for an organization every
single night. I'm going to play through injuries and give you what
I got to win. Now take a poll. And if you want to win, or have a
shot at winning, let's take a poll if you want to play with me or
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget getting to know me as a person. I really don't ever
care if a teammate really, legitimately gets to know Karl Malone as
a person. I don't mind if that happens. But that's not my job, and
that's not your job. If we hit it off, we hit it off. But competing
and playing hard and trying to pick up for my teammates, and win or
trying to win and be competitive every night, take a poll.''
</P>
<P>
   Mention his reputation as a roughneck on the court -- Isiah
Thomas had 40 stitches after catching a Malone elbow, and David
Robinson was knocked out earlier this year -- and you touch a
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get tired of hearing it,'' Malone said. ``But let me say
this: I played with a lot of guys who didn't like Karl Malone
because he played the way he played. When I play, I play to win.
But I don't ever play the game to win at all costs. I think there's
a way to win. And that's the way I like to win. I don't like to win
by doing something dirty. Things happen. It's unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not going to let anybody run over me on the court. If
you get me, and I know you were trying to, yeah, I'm going to try
to get you back. I'm not going to be passive on it. That's human
nature. That's defending myself. If you hit me, and I know you
tried to do that, at some point in time, I'm going try to get you
back. That's the competitor. That's Karl Malone. That's the
athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his unyielding spirit and remarkable body, Malone has
missed only one game because of injury in the past six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the long grind of a season, I think my work on the
weights has delayed the aging process, without a doubt,'' Malone
says. ``Those little nagging injuries that keep you out of games
aren't so bad. Yeah, I get bruised and all that. But there's never
a doubt in my mind that I'm going to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He plays it the way his mother told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom always told me, 'Never quit, never make excuses and
always, at some point in life, outwork your opponent,' `` he said.
``At some point, have it in your mind that you outworked your
opponent. Maybe you didn't. But in your mind, you thought you did.
And that's a big edge.''
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, Malone has never changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still the same little snotty-nosed boy from Louisiana who
happens to play professional basketball for a living,'' he said.
``I'm still the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Still wanting the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
