<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINT-COX     06-02 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBy Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sprint Corp. set the telecommunications industry abuzz
Tuesday, as it promised to fashion a new network that will let a
single telephone line handle voice, video and an extremely fast
Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, phone calls travel over a single circuit, and while
the circuit is open, it can't handle any other communication.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sprint network, someone will be able to log onto the
Internet, send a fax, play a video game and conduct a telephone
conversation simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City-based company, which made its name in
long-distance, raised hopes that it can help provide customers with
speedier data services and cheaper phone calls starting next year.
By early 1999, Sprint will offer the service to small and
home-based businesses, and by late 1999, to residential customers.
The company has not yet released any information on rollout dates
for specific cities, including Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile announcement also spurred questions about how
the service will be delivered and at which customers it will be
aimed. And it also shoved Sprint into the spotlight as a potential
partner or takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   But what made the first big splash was the promise that Sprint's
''Integrated On-Demand Network'' will rely on an entirely different
model of service than the one that has prevailed for more than a
century. All communication will be treated as data and handled by
equipment meant for data, not voice. Even the most basic customer
function _ billing _ would change, if Sprint has its way.
</P>
<P>
   The company wants to put meters in homes and offices to keep
track of how much data is passing through the wires. Instead of
paying by the minute, customers will pay by the bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint has brought to a head the need for networks to
evolve,'' said telecommunications analyst Brian Adamik of the
Yankee Group. ``Sprint is making the appropriate move.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the network possible, voice must be digitized as it
travels through thousands of copper phone lines. Rewiring millions
of homes with fiber optics seems impossibly exensive. Regional
phone companies like BellSouth plan to offer ADSL _ asymmetric
digital subscriber lines _ that would permit voice and data to
share those lines at high speeds. Sprint is expected to use a
similar kind of technology _ or lease it from the likes of
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Since creation of the Internet, data has been carried on
networks constructed to handle voice traffic. But that must change
_ partly because data transmission are expected to soon outpace
voice, and partly because the demand for speed is hard to satisfy
on a network built to carry conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, data hitched a ride on voice,'' said John
Callahan, spokesman for Lucent Technologies, which makes equipment
for handling both. ``Starting today, voice will have to accomodate
itself to the data world.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the surge toward the Net and to a digital system has been
the talk of the industry for some time. Sprint's approach may not
be radically different than that of other phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving in that direction _ I think everybody is,'' said
spokeswoman Leslie Aun of MCI, the nation's second-largest
long-distance company . ``We want to marry networks so that video,
data and voice are treated seamlessly.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokeswoman Julie Spechler said the company, which handles
about half the nation's long-distance calls, in January announced
efforts to ``future proof'' its network by expanding high-speed
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   But more than either of the two larger companies, Sprint is
concentrating on changing the way the data is transmitted and
managed, said Atlanta-based telecommunications analyst Jeff Kagan.
``This is Sprint's path to the future, but all the telephone
companies see the same finish line. It's just a question of which
vehicle you use to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint officials and analysts said consumers may not pay less
than if they purchased all the services individually. But they will
get more for their money, said Kagan. For instance, an Internet
connection would operate up to 100 times faster than with a
conventional modem on a traditional phone line.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Group President William Redderson said the Sprint
announcement ``reinforces'' what BellSouth has done to install
high-speed connections for local customers in its nine-state
region. ``We have been taking local networks down that path since
1994.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Sprint said the technology would let them provide
local service, the company might prefer to partner with Bells. That
would allow them to share the cost of installing equipment in
thousands of phone offices and piggyback on each other's marketing.
Even more likely would be Sprint's simply buying access to the
local service equipment, as it has already, said C. Sidney Boren,
BellSouth executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprint and BellSouth may also be odds, since long-distance
companies have hoped that use of Internet technology would let them
avoid payment of the access charges they now pay for connecting to
local networks. Federal regulators have said they think Internet
long-distance should include those fees, but have not taken action
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big old dead fish they didn't put in the middle of
the table,'' Boren said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
