<SLUG> BC-POPE-SWISS-GUARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN APPOINTS OUTSIDER TO COMMAND SWISS GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Hoping to clean house after the most shocking killings in
its modern history, the Holy See chose an outsider with broad
non-Vatican experience on Tuesday to replace the commander of the
Swiss Guards, who was killed last month by a disgruntled
subordinate.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican announced that Pope John Paul II had approved the
selection of Pius Segmueller, 42, a colonel in the Swiss army, to
replace Lt. Col. Alois Estermann.
</P>
<P>
   Estermann was found dead in his Vatican apartment on May 4,
beside the body of his wife and a 23-year-old Swiss Guard, only 10
hours after he had been appointed commander of the papal guards.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican, which conducted its own investigation of the crime,
said Estermann and his wife had been shot by the disgruntled young
guard, who suffered ``a moment of madness'' and then killed
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss Guards, who have protected the pope since the 16th
century, now play a largely ceremonial role in their medieval red,
yellow, and blue costumes and plumed helmets. The tragedy brought
the 100-man unit to the world's attention, and subjected it to
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I am a Christian and a believer,'' Segmueller
said, explaining why he had agreed to be considered for the post a
few days after Estermann was slain. ``I also have experience in
police work and security.''
</P>
<P>
   Segmueller, who has led relief teams in Switzerland and Africa,
added: ``And I also have experience in catastrophes.''
</P>
<P>
   The killings _ and the sensation they created _ were devastating
to the Swiss Guards, who are made up of young Swiss Catholics who
live an insular life even by Vatican standards, restricted by the
rules of both the army and the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``This news will lift the men's spirits, but there is still a
long way to go,'' said the Rev. Roland-Bernhard Trauffer,
secretary-general of the Swiss Bishops' Conference, which nominates
Swiss Guard commanders for Vatican approval. ``It would be naive to
think the drama didn't leave scars. There are still open wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Trauffer praised Segmueller, a German-speaker who was born in
Lucerne and is married with two children, as a leader whose contact
with the real world would help him in his new assignment.
</P>
<P>
   He studied and taught history and literature at the University
of Geneva and, as an army officer, served on a U.N. mission in
Namibia. A new deputy commander, Capt. Elmar Theodor Maeder, 35,
who is in the Swiss army and also has no previous Vatican or Swiss
Guard experience, was also appointed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Estermann was killed, the church was seeking to
bring new people into the corps. Estermann, who spent 18 years as a
Swiss Guard and was deputy commander when the top job became
vacant, did not get promoted right away. Instead, the Vatican spent
seven months searching for another candidate, preferably an
outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders discovered that many of the most promising
candidates among the Swiss nobility, diplomatic corps or military
were not eager to move to Rome for a job that pays little and whose
prestige has dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   After the killings, however, that changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened is that the tragedy in Switzerland was a
little like the death of Princess Diana in England _ there was a
terrible week of consternation and confusion,'' Trauffer said.
``After that a lot of qualified people realized the importance of
the Swiss Guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Segmueller, who said he had visited Rome a few times as a
tourist, said he knew only what he read in the newspapers about the
pope's army and did not want to prejudge what his task would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to study the situation and take measures,'' he said.
``But I cannot yet say what I must do or not do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
