<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-SIMPLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SIMPLE LIFE' IS SIMPLY ANNOYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to turn over a new gold leaf, Sara Campbell, nee Sara
Lipschitz, has moved her multimillion-dollar business empire to a
farm in upstate New York to experience the domestic ``simplicity''
she espouses on her television show.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``The Simple Life'' life isn't simple. Simply
annoying is more like it, with characters as one-dimensional as
white-on-white stationery, punch lines as obvious as antique ducks
amid statice and chintz.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second of two Martha Stewart spoofs on CBS. The
first, Jean Smart's ``Style &AMP; Substance,'' came and went quickly
this winter before the Olympic avalanche. ``The Simple Life'' also
will disappear long before the fall season begins _ a summertime
sacrifice, if you will, and the network's delicate way of saying,
``This turkey is sliced so thin it'll never make a sandwich, let
alone the fall schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Portraying the doyenne of domesticity this time is Judith Light,
best known for eight seasons of ``Who's the Boss?'' with Tony
Danza. Surrounded by domestically challenged daughter Freddi
(Ashlee Levitch), demanding mother Muriel (Florence Stanley),
insufferable producer Greg (James Patrick Stuart) and studly farm
foreman Luke (Brett Cullen), Light's character tries to bring order
and simplicity into a rural homestead that looks like one person's
interpretation of what might happen if Laura Ashley exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of explosions, it's not enough that the bombastic
``Nanny'' precedes ``The Simple Life'' on the CBS schedule.
``Nanny'' star and whine connoisseur Fran Drescher helps out in the
pilot episode Wednesday night, playing Fran Fine, former high
school classmate of Ms. Campbell/Lipschitz, in her customary getup
of high heels, high hemline and high volume.
</P>
<P>
   Parallels to ``The Nanny'' are everywhere in ``The Simple
Life,'' in fact. There's the stuffy British guy, played desperately
by Stuart but still this week's best trivia question. (He's the son
of Chad Stuart of Chad &AMP; Jeremy fame, and the guy who was Elaine's
boyfriend who had a thing for the Eagles song ``Desperado'' on an
episode of ``Seinfeld''). There's the smarter-than-the-rest-of-them
hired hand, played painfully by Cullen with an accent that's more a
hybrid of Albany, Ga., and New Albany, Ind. _ and about a day's
drive from upstate New York. And there are three kids: Campbell's
flunkout-prone daughter, Freddi, played smartly by Levitch, and the
precocious nephew and niece of Luke Barton, played precociously by
Ross Malinger and Eliza Dean.
</P>
<P>
   The best of this wilted bouquet is the thorny Stanley, who
re-creates the same Selma Diamond-sound-alike kvetch viewers have
come to know over the years. Stanley has a refined sense of comedy
and the ability to get a laugh without uttering a word; most of her
castmates, including Light, are reciting lines that aren't nearly
as amusing as the show's artificially enhanced laughter suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, a roasted turkey, a horny bull and a docile sheep
were not harmed during filming of the pilot episode. They were not
funny, either, but writers of ``The Simple Life'' apparently were
working with one of the old sitcom manuals, which states: ``When in
doubt, try putting a bull in the kitchen.'' As we all know, more
recent editions have removed that passage and replaced it with:
``When in doubt, go with cleavage.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it's Luke who finally has to inform Sara, ``Life ain't
simple, no matter where you live it.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have added: ``Make-believe ain't nearly as funny as the
real Martha Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Simple Life. Half-hour comedy about a Martha Stewart-style
self-conglomerate who moves family and firm to the country to find
domestic tranquillity. Premieres Wednesday night, CBS. Check local
listings. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send e-mail to:
tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
