A0898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-COX &UR;  &UR; OP     06-02 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-COX </SLUG>
     OPPONENTS CALL PRAYER AMENDMENT AN
ASSAULT ON LIBERTIES
 &HT;     By EUNICE MOSCOSO 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the House prepares to vote this week on a
constitutional amendment guaranteeing the right to school prayer,
opponents of the measure Tuesday called it an affront to civil
liberties.
</P>
<P>
   The ``so-called Religious Freedom Amendment is the most radical
assault on our liberties I have ever seen in Congress,'' said Barry
Lynn, executive director of Americans United for Separation of
Church and State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives a credible constitutional weapon to those who wish to
turn our schools into mission fields, whether they are members of
the Nation of Islam, the Church of Scientology, the next Heaven's
Gate or the local Baptist Church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, introduced by Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla., is
scheduled for a House vote on Thursday. It's the first vote of its
kind in 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendment states that ``the people's right to pray
and to recognize their religious beliefs, heritage or traditions on
public property, including schools, shall not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, is leading opposition to the measure
in the House. He said it is unnecessary and could force a wide
variety of beliefs on children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely do not want my two young sons some day exposed to
witchcraft, or satanic, or Branch Davidian prayer in the public
schools of Waco, Texas,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards found out Tuesday that the Christian Coalition has sent
out mailers in his district stating that he is opposed to prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian Coalition should be ashamed for sending out such
a hateful mailer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some religious groups are expressing opposition to the
proposed amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give the Christian Coalition a chance to paint their
opponents as ``voting against God,'' said David Saperstein, a rabbi
and director of the Religious Action Center of Reform Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   The vote will be featured on the Coalition's voting scorecard,
which will be distributed to its members later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Elenora Giddings Ivory, a reverend in the Presbyterian church,
said that the amendment is dangerous because schools could not
possibly satisfy all the religious diversity in their classrooms
and would therefore have to choose one religion over others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just among the Christian community there are different forms
of prayer. Pentecostals stand to pray. Catholics and Episcopalians
kneel to pray. Presbyterians bow their heads. In other religious
traditions prayer is done by chanting or lying prostrate on the
ground,'' she said. ``How is a public school to coordinate such
diverse activity?''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has also weighed in on the issue of school
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   In his radio address last week, Clinton said the amendment is
unnecessary because public schools already support voluntary
practice of religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than 200 years, the First Amendment has protected our
religious freedom and allowed many faiths to flourish, in our
homes, in our work places and in our schools. Clearly understood
and sensibly applied, it works. It does not need to be rewritten,''
the President said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents to the amendment say students can, at their own
volition, have Bible clubs in high schools, wear religious
clothing, read holy scriptures on the bus and in the lunchroom and
say grace over cookies and milk in the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   They also say that government funding of religious activity is
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   It would guarantee ``an ugly battle between religious groups
fighting for government funds, wreaking havoc on the American
tradition of religious liberty for all,'' said Terri Schroeder,
with the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is not expected to gain the two-thirds congressional
majority needed to send a constitutional amendment to the states
for ratification, but opponents say they expect its backers to
continue to push for school-sponsored prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, this fight will be re-fought in the near future, and
once again religious minorities will be forced to fight for their
survival,'' said Ira Forman, executive director of the National
Jewish Democratic Council.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
