<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AH, SO IT'S THE HOUSING MARKET HE'S SORE ABOUT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GODZILLA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Broderick, Jean Reno, Maria Pitillo, Michael Lerner,
Hank Azaria, Kevin Dunn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Roland Emmerich &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 139 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The news just gets better and better for the apoplectic Mayor
Ebert of New York (Lerner). First this big lizard (returning in a
remake of the 1954 ``Godzilla, King of the Monsters'') goes
bounding around town like a runaway Flatiron Building, stepping on
taxicabs, leveling neighborhoods, starting fires, defying fleets of
rocket-spewing helicopters and scattering the population in mad
panic.
</P>
<P>
   Then a young scientist named Niko Tatopoulos (Broderick), who
studies the outlandish growth of creatures affected by atomic
radiation, posits the theory that Godzilla is really just rooting
about for a cozy spot to have 200 babies. So how about Madison
Square Garden? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE. In smashing up the city, Godzilla is undoubtedly doing
bodily harm to a fair number of people, but in the manner of other
recent major disaster films like ``Deep Impact,'' ``Independence
Day'' and ``Twister,'' little graphic gore gets on screen.
Furthermore, much of the destruction is more spectacle than
disaster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX. None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY. Much. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR WHICH CHILDREN? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5. The film is too big and loud. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-10. Parents should be careful with sensitive children,
but unless they are bothered by movies with a lot of smashing
about, there isn't much harm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP. They shouldn't have a problem. (And try to stop
them.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Peter M. Nichols &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE TRUMAN SHOW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey, Laura Linney, Ed Harris, Noah Emmerich, and Natascha
McElhone &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Peter Weir &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 102 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a nice seaside town lives a sweet insurance agent, Truman
Burbank ( Carrey). But what Truman doesn't realize is that his life
is the brainchild of Christof, a television wizard (Harris) who has
created a live, real-time drama about Truman that is broadcast
around the world 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Within that lovely stage-set of a town are 5,000 cameras
capturing Truman's every move, thousands of extras, product
placements everywhere and actors playing his wife (Ms. Linney) and
best friend (Emmerich). But after meeting a woman (Ms. McElhone)
who appears oddly uneasy around him, Truman begins to suspect
something is not right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE. A mildly threatening gesture with a sharp kitchen
gadget and several dire scenes of storms at sea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX. None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY. Three or four expletives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR WHICH CHILDREN? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10. With no Ace Ventura-type slapstick yuks, this Jim
Carrey movie may well bore and confuse the very young. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-14. Savvier children may enjoy entering Truman's
alternative reality, although subtle satiric content may be over
the heads of most children this age. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP. Older teen-agers should find this satire of our
media-obsessed society amusing and thought-provoking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Suzanne O'Connor &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALMOST HEROES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Farley, Matthew Perry &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Christopher Guest &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 87 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's 1804 and Lewis and Clark are trekking west. Right behind
them, intent on getting to the Pacific Ocean first and cleaning up
on product endorsements, is the team of Edwards (Perry of
``Friends'' fame) and Hunt (Farley, who died last year).
</P>
<P>
   Edwards is the patrician leader with the high-flown rhetoric
about adventure and destiny. Hunt is the odoriferous rough-hewn
type who tries to eat pine cones. Much of their party takes off for
New Orleans, but those who stick it out with Edwards and Hunt get
to be terrorized by a Hollywood bear, go over a 200-foot waterfall
in canoes and be assaulted by stereotypically murderous
conquistadors. But dead ahead out there _ it looks like Malibu. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE. Some scuffles and assaults of the slapstick variety,
none of which would be taken the least bit seriously by even small
children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX. An Indian maiden with an eye for Edwards bathes partly nude
in a woodland stream. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY. Less than one would expect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR WHICH CHILDREN? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6. The profanity rules it out, but they'd be bored
anyway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-12. This is the right age, although more sophisticated
older children may turn off at the silliness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP. Farley and Perry have appeal, but the film is
miles beneath most teen-agers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Peter M. Nichols &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I GOT THE HOOK-UP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Master P, A.J. Johnson, Gretchen Palmer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Martin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 93 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two fast-talking hustlers who operate a so-called shopping
center in an urban slum lot manage to lie their way into possession
of a shipment of cellular phones. Within a short time they are
rolling in unaccustomed wealth, and their customers are talking up
a storm.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the hustlers, the phones are illegally hooked
into a legitimate network, and when the technology falters a
gangster's conversation about $70,000 in cash in an unguarded
locker is broadcast on the radio. The upshot is a neighborhood gold
rush and a contract on the lives of the hustlers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE. Beatings and gunplay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX. Partial nudity, simulated coupling, transvestite
prostitution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY. Incessant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR WHICH CHILDREN? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER 13. Under no circumstances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP. Keeping in mind that this is an R-rated movie
(and a poor one), there is no compelling reason for them to see it,
but they have probably experienced similar characters, language and
situations in other films they've seen.
</P>
<P>
   --Lawrence Van Gelder &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
