</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-THEATER-$ADV07-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO: SECOND TO NONE AS A THEATER TOWN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ This is a town where theater companies compete for
advertising space on supermarket bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   There, after the checkout counters, in the foyer of the Treasure
Island or the Jewel Osco, among the offers of free puppies, the
booklets on how to meditate and the offers of housecleaning
services, are the fliers for one-man and one-woman shows, new works
by young playwrights, adaptations of classic novels, even musicals,
being performed in second-floor loft spaces, garages converted to
black boxes and, yes, real theaters with seats that are nailed to
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mundane thing, theater in Chicago, pervasive as Polish
sausage. Unlike New York, where, nonprofit companies
notwithstanding, the theater seems part and parcel of a vast
commercial enterprise known as the entertainment business; or Los
Angeles, where, in spite of a sea of local talent, the theater is a
crippled sister to the movies; or a handful of cities like Seattle,
San Francisco, Philadelphia, Boston, Atlanta, Washington,
Minneapolis and Houston, where there are accomplished theater
companies but not the critical mass that can commandeer the local
Zeitgeist _ here in Chicago, the theater is a vivid,
attention-getting strand in the culture.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago is a theater town; so, of course, is New York. It's
really not true about anywhere else in the country.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Chicagoans will grudgingly admit that, theatrically
speaking, their city is still second, they are quick to point out
that factors like a more modest living standard and a general lack
of cynicism contribute to an atmosphere that is conducive to both
enthusiasm for putting on a show and the percolation of artistic
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Even though second-largest, Chicago's theater community is
probably the nation's most tightly knit, arguably its most
adventurous and almost certainly its most important incubator of
young talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theaters are possible here,'' said Martha Lavey, the artistic
director of Steppenwolf, the company founded in 1974 that is
probably more responsible than any other for putting Chicago
theater on the map. ``The real estate issue is a factor in New
York. In L.A., the artist issue is a factor. But here, there's a
critical mass of artists. You can get a space. And there's a
funding community that's responsive.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an atmosphere that breeds loyalty among those who were
weaned on it. ``I've been to a lot of theater in New York and L.A.
and all I can say is it's more about the people in Chicago, more
ingrained in the community,'' said the actor David Schwimmer, who
helped found the Lookingglass Theater Company here nine years ago
with several classmates from Northwestern University but who is
best known as Ross on the television series ``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwimmer is currently playing the title role in a decidedly
low-budget Look-ingglass adaptation of Dostoyevsky's novel ``The
Idiot,'' in which his familiar, hangdog demeanor, minus the glib
irony, is remarkably effective. ``The audience here really loves
and nurtures theater,'' he said. ``There's no sense of protocol, no
sense of a special occasion, like there is in New York. For most
people, going to the theater here is as casual a thing as going to
a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sentiment that is echoed all over town. And so are its
corollaries: that theater here is about art, not commerce. That
Chicago actors are more concerned with serving the material at hand
than their careers. That elsewhere critics are an enemy, but here
the small corps of reviewers is diligent and generally supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``An inferiority complex? I don't have it,'' said the director
Mary Zimmerman, 37, who came here from Lincoln, Neb., to attend
Northwestern. Now a Northwestern professor, an artistic associate
at the Goodman Theater, the city's largest nonprofit theater, and a
founding member of Lookingglass, Ms. Zimmerman, a recent recipient
of a MacArthur grant, has a formidable Chicago pedigree. But she
has also brought her athletic, visually vivid adaptations (``The
Notebooks of Leonardo Da Vinci,'' ``The Arabian Nights'') to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fabulous place to do theater, and particularly to
start doing theater,'' she said. ``For one thing, you can get an
audience. And if you are even remotely organized, you can get
critics to come to see your work at your 35-seat hole-in-the-wall
theater. That just doesn't happen in New York. I'm being
deliberately arrogant. But in my experience, we're not standing
like refugees at the border with hollowed-out eyes, yearning toward
the Hudson.''
</P>
<P>
   It is merely 25 years since the initial stirrings of the
so-called Off Loop theater movement, an explosion of experimental
stage activity in the mid-1970s that established Chicago as an
alternative to New York as a place for actors and directors to
work, that spawned a blunt and brawny style of acting and writing,
that revived the practice of ensemble work, and that propelled the
careers of, among others, the playwright David Mamet, the director
Frank Galati, the producer Gregory Mosher and actors like Joe
Mantegna, Dennis Franz, Meshach Taylor, William Petersen and those
now-familiar stars who were original members of the Steppenwolf
Theater Company: Laurie Metcalf, John Malkovich, Gary Sinise, Joan
Allen and Glenne Headly.
</P>
<P>
   Now, by some estimates, there are as many as 200 different
theater companies in Chicago at any one time, many of them
evanescent but a large majority viable, persistent and, as distinct
from New York, where the commercial theater is king, nonprofit. Of
the 120 theaters, producers and ensemble groups belonging to the
League of Chicago Theaters, the local trade association, only 20
are commercial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly perhaps, Chicago has not been a consistently
profitable stop for Broadway road shows. Nonetheless, a study of
the local theater market commissioned by the city government last
summer concluded that with a metro area population of nearly 8
million, Chicago is being underserved by commercial theater
producers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
