<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0905 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-THEATER-$ADV0     06-02 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-THEATER-$ADV07-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICAGO: theater producers.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The findings must have been a relief to officials; the city is
optimistically helping outside entertainment companies rebuild two
theaters as part of its massive effort to reinvigorate the
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Through a plan known as tax-increment financing _ by which the
city provides incentive money to developers in anticipation of
being repaid in the form of increased real estate taxes _ the city
contributed $17.6 million to a renovation, by Fox Theatricals of
St. Louis, of the 2,300-seat Palace Theater and $13.5 million to a
renovation of the Oriental Theater by Livent, the Toronto-based
company, which is to present ``Ragtime'' there in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   That would give the city six commercial theaters downtown
(including the Civic Opera House, home of the Lyric Opera between
September and April, but currently housing ``The Phantom of the
Opera''), a total of more than 16,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city has contributed $18.8 million to the
construction of a new downtown home for the venerable Goodman
Theater, which has been housed at the Art Institute of Chicago
since 1925, and in conjunction with the State of Illinois, $14.5
million for a new lakefront home for the 10-year-old Shakespeare
Repertory Company, the only all-Shakespeare-all-the-time company in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   How the new theater district will affect the life of the theater
here is unclear. This is a place where ``Beauty and the Beast,''
Disney's extravaganza, had a disappointing run this winter, but
where ``Co-Ed Prison Sluts,'' the signature gross-out comedy of the
tiny Annoyance Theater Company, has been a late-night hit for
years.
</P>
<P>
   It is also where the Court Theater, a 20-year-old Equity company
affiliated with the University of Chicago that has aspirations to
become a national center for classic theater, had to extend four of
five productions this season, including Euripides' ``Iphigenia''
plays and Chekhov's ``Cherry Orchard.'' It is where Frank Galati,
as a director at Steppenwolf and the Goodman and as a teacher at
Northwestern, created a local tradition of adapting classic novels
to the stage (remember his Tony-winning version of ``The Grapes of
Wrath'' in 1990).
</P>
<P>
   And it is where there are a handful of black theater companies
(including Chicago Theater and Onyx), at least two Hispanic
companies (Teatro Vista and Latino Chicago), at least one Asian
company (Angel Island) and one devoted to gay- and lesbian-themed
plays (About Face).
</P>
<P>
   This is a place where Schwimmer, Petersen and John Mahoney, all
local actors who made it big in Hollywood, are now on stage at the
theaters that gave them their starts. (Mahoney is starring in ``The
Man Who Came to Dinner'' at Steppenwolf; Petersen is in
``Flyovers,'' a new play by a Chicago playwright, Jeffrey Sweet, at
Victory Gardens Theater.)
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a place where unproven talents are taken
seriously, as they rarely are anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's a place where only one television series
(``Early Edition'') is filmed, and where movie companies come to
shoot only sporadically, resulting in a loss of talent to both
coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some 1,400 members of Actors' Equity, the stage
actors' union, live here, 25 percent of whom, said Kathryn Lamkey,
the director of the union's central region, make their entire
living onstage. And if that doesn't sound like a great number, it
does constitute a community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and I always felt that the whole Chicago acting pool was
our company,'' said Michael Maggio, an associate artistic director
of the Goodman, referring to Robert Falls, the artistic director of
the theater.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1959 that Bernard Sahlins, Paul Sills and Howard Alk
started the Second City, a revue theater with a company that
included Barbara Harris and Alan Arkin and that would go on to
produce the likes of John Belushi, Dan Ayckroyd and Bill Murray.
(The name was taken in defiance of A.J. Liebling, who used the
phrase sneeringly about the city in The New Yorker.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, William Sickinger established what would be the city's
first conventional theater company on the North Side, away from the
downtown business district known as the Loop. But it wasn't until a
decade or so later that a theatrical community began to take root,
when several new companies _ including Victory Gardens, St.
Nicholas and Body Politic _ came into being.
</P>
<P>
   David Mamet's play ``Sexual Perversity in Chicago'' had its
premiere at the Organic Theater in 1974; Steppenwolf began life the
same year, putting on its first shows in a church basement in
suburban Highland Park. They shared a softball league, several bars
as hangouts and a predilection for ensemble work and long rehearsal
periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just found it valuable to go about the business of
creating something without knowing if you'd actually be able to
produce it,'' Petersen recalled of the early days at Victory
Gardens, where he earned his Equity card in 1979, and whose current
artistic director, Dennis Zacek, has been there from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure why all this started,'' Zacek said. ``I guess it
was because the Goodman was so influenced by New York. Everyone who
performed there came from New York. Victory Gardens' purpose was to
develop theater in Chicago. And 25 years later, we've done some
developing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Flyovers'' is typical of its work: its cast of four _
Petersen, Amy Morton, Mark Vann and Linda Reiter _ are all Chicago
actors. The playwright, Sweet, is from here. The play, set in an
Ohio town, is about the aftermath of a high school reunion attended
by a man who is a television film critic not unlike the Chicagoan
Gene Siskel.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gardens has grown a bit; it has become a midsize
theater, one of a vanishing breed, putting on five shows a year
with an annual budget of about $1.5 million and controlling two
200-seat theaters and two small studio spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we're the Shuberts of Lincoln Avenue,'' Zacek said with
a laugh, adding more seriously: ``We're one of the few survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked in interviews about the apparent theater boom here,
many theater executives ticked off a number of companies that have
folded in the last few years: Wisdom Bridge, Body Politic, the
National Jewish Theater and the Candlelight Dinner Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-THEATER-$ADV0     06-02 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-THEATER-$ADV07-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICAGO: Dinner Playhouse.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the other hand, there is Steppenwolf, now ending its 23rd
full season, which has gone from being a subversive cultural force
to an established institution, with a budget of $5.3 million and a
subscriber base of more than 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who will look at what we do now and say
`Sellout,' '' Ms. Lavey acknowledged. ``But one can't forever
maintain the outsider renegade position. After 23 years of life,
it's attendant upon one to take the adult position. After all, the
institution is just recapitulating where the individuals are in
their lives. They are 40-year-olds with children and mortgages.''
</P>
<P>
   Steppenwolf has become an icon in the city and, because of its
reputation both as theater and star-making ensemble, the model for
emerging companies, from Lookingglass to the six-year old Roadworks
to even younger groups like Streetsigns and Shattered Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what Steppenwolf was able to do and seeing its growth
in the 80s was a motivation for us,'' said David Kersnar, the
artistic director of Lookingglass, which still does not have its
own theater despite an increased annual budget of $800,000. ``And
it was a motivation to stay in Chicago, knowing the city does
nurture ensembles.''
</P>
<P>
   Roadworks' tough, edgy productions of Mike Leigh's ``Ecstasy''
and Patrick Marber's ``Dealer's Choice,'' two British writers, have
led many theater professionals here to anoint it as the next hot
ensemble. It may be the prototype Chicago ensemble _ talented,
fortunate and ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   Roadworks was started by a handful of Northwestern theater
students who graduated without the promise of jobs when they
recreated their campus production of ``Road'' by Jim Cartwright,
another British writer, in a rented garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had bake sales, washed cars, wrote letters to everyone we
knew for money,'' said Debbie Bisno, the artistic director. ``And
we raised 5,000 bucks. We were playing for maybe four people a
night, but we got reviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the company's annual budget has reached $110,000, and it
produces at least two shows a year, concentrating on appealing to
the jittery sensibility of the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do `Long Day's Journey,' you know?'' said Ms. Bisno,
27, whose plans for the company include film production and a
branch in Los Angeles. ``We've always stuck to productions
appropriate to our age, signature pieces for 20-somethings. And
we've always envisioned ourselves as bigger than we are. I totally
admire what Steppenwolf has done. If we could emulate that ...''
Her words trailed off, the thought complete.
</P>
<P>
   Emulation of the larger and better known is also what the city
is attempting downtown, where the idea is to recreate an
entertainment district _ it has been in decline since the 1960s _
by constructing the nation's most prominent theater district west
of Broadway. Ostensibly, the theaters will attract restaurants,
retailers, even residences; the city expects the new theaters to
create 5,000 permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Broadway can send enough product to interest Chicagoans
is a question. A second is whether a raft of Broadway-style shows
will draw patrons away from Chicago's homegrown theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nonprofit executives shrug and say they suspect that
their audiences don't overlap too much with those that would flock
to see ``The Lion King'' or ``Jekyll and Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one, Barbara Gaines, the artistic director of the
Shakespeare Rep, which is getting its own new theater on Navy Pier
right on Lake Michigan, sounds as gleeful and optimistic as a kid
putting up a flier in a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fantastic what's happening,'' she said. ``I feel
absolutely no paranoia about these theaters coming in. I think the
suburbs, for them, are an untapped audience. And I think if our
work continues to be good, there will be funding for it and
audiences too. You want a New York versus Chicago? I'll give you a
versus. There's more hope here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
