<SLUG> BC-GRAMM-TOBACCO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
FRIENDS GRAMM, McCAIN BUTT HEADS OVER TOBACCO BILL 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Sen. Phil Gramm ran for president a few years
ago, one of his earliest backers was John McCain, an Arizona
Republican who broke ranks with many Senate colleagues supporting
GOP front-runner Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, Gramm, R-Texas, isn't lending a helping hand as
McCain tries to marshal support for the ambitious and controversial
anti-tobacco bill being considered by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm has been one of the most vocal critics of McCain's bill,
arguing that its $1.10-a-pack price increase for cigarettes would
impose an unfair burden on lower-income smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm has further complicated McCain's attempts to win approval
of the bill by offering an amendment that would return in tax
breaks almost all the revenue generated by the tobacco price
increase. Gramm has proposed eliminating the marriage penalty,
which gives some couples a smaller standard deduction than singles,
for spouses earning less than $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cut proposal has the potential of alienating what is
already a fragile coalition of Democrats and moderate GOP lawmakers
supporting the anti-smoking measure.
</P>
<P>
   The measure calls for the tobacco revenue to be used to help
states defray Medicaid costs related to smoking and fund other
health and anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Gramm have denied that their differences over the
tobacco bill have hurt their longtime relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been friends before this and they will be friends
after this,'' said Gramm spokesman Larry Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm recently said that if McCain were to run for president he
couldn't imagine supporting anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said that he is not angry at Gramm and some other
conservatives who have opposed his legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they have strongly held views. I treat them with
respect and they treat me with respect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Gramm, McCain and two other lawmakers huddled for an
hour to try to work out a compromise on the tax issue, with McCain
saying he could support more modest tax breaks. Neal said the
senators did not reach an agreement but will continue the
negotiations later this week.
</P>
<P>
   As currently conceived, Gramm's amendment could cost as much as
$50 billion over five years, which critics contend would make
impossible to fund any other programs with the tobacco money.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said that the
inclusion of a tax break could improve the prospects for the bill
because it might draw more support from conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   However, Neal said that even the Senate's adoption of the
marriage penalty provision would not necessarily guarantee that
Gramm would vote for the entire tobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   McCain indicated that he hopes to move to end debate on the
measure sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Senate can afford to have extended debate
forever. We have other pressing issues,'' he said. It requires 60
votes to end debate in the 100-member Senate. McCain said he was
optimistic but not sure that he had the votes to bring his bill to
a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, the Senate will likely consider a number of
amendments. McCain has proposed that $3 billion be allocated over
five years to help veterans with smoking-related illnesses, an
amendment that is not expected to generate much opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers will also consider a move to toughen penalties on
the tobacco companies if youth smoking is not reduced and a
proposal to remove federal price supports for tobacco farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear when the Senate will take up the issues. On
Wednesday many lawmakers are flying to Arizona to attend the
funeral of former Sen. Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Senate interrupted debate on the tobacco issue
to take up another measure regarding storage of nuclear waste. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
