<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN URGES BUSINESSMEN TO USE THEIR MONEY TO STEADY MARKETS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin gathered the nation's most
powerful businessmen at the Kremlin on Tuesday and urged them to
use their money to help steady Russia's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our own investors do not put their money in, foreigners
leave,'' Yeltsin warned the businessmen. ``If you want foreign
investors to put their money in, you must put in yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's central bank will hold an important treasury bill
auction on Wednesday. The sale has emerged as an important
bellwether for the government, which worries that the failure to
sell all of the bills will further unnerve jittery investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin went out of its way Tuesday to underscore Yeltsin's
appeal, which was made in a closed-door session. The presidential
request was made public by a Russian news service reporter who was
allowed into part of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Yeltsin listened to the businessmen's pleas for
lower rail and energy tariffs. Some bankers at the sessions also
urged the Kremlin to threaten bankruptcy proceedings against
deadbeat creditors.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's financial crisis comes to a head, Yeltsin is
striving to assure foreign investors and skeptical voters that
Russia's economic situation is under control.
</P>
<P>
   Enlisting the support of Russia's hard-hit but still powerful
businessmen is the key. Dispelling the impression that Russia is
run by a part-time president is also an important part of the
Kremlin's public relations campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's meeting began with bit of political theater.
</P>
<P>
   As the financiers assembled before a cordon of television
cameras, Yeltsin turned to Anatoly Chubais, the former Kremlin aide
he sent to Washington last week to appeal for additional
international financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did my telephone calls help?'' Yeltsin asked, referring to an
earlier appeal to President Clinton. Chubais dutifully agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting the mantle of a strong leader, Yeltsin also promised to
present an ``anti-crisis program'' by the end of the month. The
plan will be disclosed at a rare meeting in the Kremlin's Marble
Hall. Yeltsin summoned deputies from the upper and lower houses of
Parliament to the session.
</P>
<P>
   Still, obtaining Western aid is still vital to restoring the
confidence of investors, Russian officials say. And weeks of
deliberations and negotiations still appear to lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and other Western officials are trying to hammer out an
aid plan, but they are moving at a deliberate pace.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals under consideration include an $8-billion to
$10-billion reserve fund administered by the International Monetary
Fund to help Russia's central bank buttress the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials are also discussing other financial
arrangements, including one that would help compensate the Russians
for the toll that declining oil prices have taken on Russian
exports. As part of the aid effort, future World Bank disbursement
could be also be advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Just as critical are the economic reforms the Russian will be
asked to undertake in return. American officials have made it clear
that the additional financing will be ``conditional,'' a
stipulation that appears intended to insulate the Clinton
administration from criticism that it is giving the Russians
something for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the clouds were dark on Tuesday. The Yeltsin government
received a rare bit of good news when shares on the volatile Moscow
stock exchange rose 12 percent. But brokers played down the
significance, noting that trading was very light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going down on zero volume and going up on zero volume,''
said Tom Ashead, the co-director of research for United Financial
Group. ``The significance of this is that the market does not know
what to do and where to go.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yeltsin's meeting with the businessmen lasted for an hour and 40
minutes. It brought together 10 power brokers, including oil
company executives, bankers and the heads of major financial
industrial groups. The heads of some of the financial consortiums
included Vladimir Potanin of Interros, Mikhail Fridman of Alfa
Group, and Mikhail Khodorkovsky of Rosprom.
</P>
<P>
   The business barons have often fought among themselves, as they
jockeyed to control the spoils of the former Soviet state.
</P>
<P>
   Fridman said in an interview that his bank was doing its share
to invest in Russia: it bought $100 million in treasury bills last
week just before the IMF disclosed that it planned to disburse the
next $670-million installment of its $10-billion loan.
</P>
<P>
   Potanin said in an interview that Yeltsin underscored the need
to work together to cope with financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the point that we are in the same boat and that we
have to coordinate because of the very serious situation in the
economy,'' Potanin said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
