<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-CONSERVATION     06-02 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CONSERVATIONIST-805&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOLOGIST APPLYING HIS SCIENCE ON CAPITOL HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J., Ariz.)   (ART ADV: Photo of Dr. Gary K. Meffe at his home near Micanopy,
Fla., is available in the Wieck photo database in the NYTRNG
5/16-31 folder. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (bl)  
 By CARL HULSE   New York Times Regional Newspaper Group   c.1998
N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Biologist Gary K. Meffe is undertaking one of his
most ambitious experiments yet _ moving the science of conservation
out of the field and off the pages of obscure technical journals
into the corridors of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Meffe, an adjunct professor at the University of Florida who
edits the bimonthly periodical ``Conservation Biology,'' is in the
forefront of a move to inject more hard scientific research and
analysis into the usually politically and economically driven
debates over endangered species and public land use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservation biology _ as a science, a society, and a journal
_ needs to do a better job of informing environmental policy and
policy makers,'' Meffe wrote in the February issue. ``We cannot
simply wait and hope that the knowledge we generate will be adopted
by decision makers.''
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old expert in aquatic biology is certainly heeding
his own advice. At two high-profile Washington events earlier this
year, he bolstered national conservation organizations as they
first criticized a key federal policy on species preservation and
then promoted legislation to limit logging in national forests.
</P>
<P>
   Meffe doesn't see himself as an advocate, but more as the holder
of knowledge that it would be irresponsible to keep from those
shaping federal policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand we are scientists and need to remain
objective, dispassionate,'' he said in an interview. ``On the other
hand, the information we have and produce, the things we see and
know about are very relevant to how society gets along in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything wrong with taking scientific knowledge
and arguing a particular point to legislation if that knowledge has
bearing on it,'' he said. ``You get into trouble as a scientist if
you go beyond that and are arguing from personal feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of science as a tool in advancing legislation and
policy is related to the increasing complexity of the issues
confronting Congress, issues that can't always be addressed in
simple political terms. Decisions on subjects like global warming,
ecosystem preservation, ozone depletion, pesticide regulation call
out for some scientific rationale.
</P>
<P>
   True policy advocates say the support of respected scientists
such as Meffe can enhance the credibility of their cause with
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tremendously helpful,'' said Carl Ross, executive
director of Save America's Forests and a force behind the logging
proposal. ``It lets members of Congress know that there are
solutions to these many confusing problems. They get so many
different messages from different interests groups and this shows
the scientific community is backing this approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The forest coalition, which wants to halt timbering on millions
of acres of national forests and limit it on millions more,
marshaled an impressive list of more than 600 scientists to back
its bill. They included renowned primate expert Jane Goodall and
Harvard entomologist E.O. Wilson, a Pulitzer Prize winner, as well
as Meffe.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists argued that extensive clear-cutting of forests is
shattering ecosystems, putting thousands of species at risk and
permanently degrading natural resources in the immediate rush for
goods and materials.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was impressed with the credentials of the
scientific support for the bill introduced by Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., thus illustrating a problem with citing science
in such policy fights: all sides are typically able to muster
scientific justification for their position.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the forest bill suggested its backers simply
assembled an all-star cast of scientists who embrace the
conventional views of the environmental establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `scientists' involved in Sen. Torricelli's photo op are
not qualified based upon their research and expertise to evaluate
the proper management of the national forests,'' complained Sen.
Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Other forestry experts said the timbering the group is trying to
halt is essential to the health of the forests and the nation at
large.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of science within the forest service
that contends harvesting is an appropriate and sustainable
activity,'' said Bill Banzaff, executive director of the Society of
American Foresters. ``A broad brush approach to management policies
in our national forest doesn't make a lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Meffe understands there are competing views but he is
comfortable with his. And his view is a sought after one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Meffe is considered one of the leaders in the field of
conservation biology,'' said Laura Hood, director of science at
Defenders of Wildlife, a group that enlisted Meffe's help in
pointing up flaws in a federal endangered species policy. ``There
is a powerful voice there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Born in New Jersey, Meffe received undergraduate and graduate
degrees in zoology from Rutgers College and his doctorate from
Arizona State University. He said he wasn't ``a birdwatcher or a
frog chaser'' as a youth but was steered into conservation biology
by his college studies.
</P>
<P>
   From 1985-97, he was an ecologist at the Savannah River Ecology
Laboratory associated with the University of Georgia. But when he
was named editor of the journal of the Society of Conservation
Biology in 1997, he chose to relocate the publication to the
University of Florida, where he had done post-doctoral work as the
Archie Carr Fellow in the mid-1980s. He said he sacrificed salary
and a full professorship to return to an area he and his wife,
Nancy, love. They live near Micanopy on 10 acres they share with
rare gopher tortoises.
</P>
<P>
   While not the type of reading material found at supermarket
check-out lines, Conservation Biology is highly regarded among
those in the field, sort of a New England Journal of Medicine for
conservationists. With an international circulation of about 6,000,
the magazine is packed with academic papers and essays on a subject
of increasing scientific and popular interest.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the journal, Meffe is known as the author of the premier
textbook on conservation biology. And in addition to his new
profile in Washington, Meffe has another federal connection _ he is
one of the instructors for a week-long training course on ecosystem
management for U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service employees. The heads
of the agency will take it later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Meffe sees conservation biology becoming of critical importance
in the years ahead as mankind grapples with its interaction with
and impact upon nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost a very selfish applied science,'' he said. ``It
is not opposed to humans and what we do. In fact, it is a long term
vision of how humans can get along on the planet without
substantially degrading the very resources that support us.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Carl Hulse is a staff writer for the Washington bureau of The
New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This story was distributed
by The N.Y. Times News Service.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
