<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY FLING WITH SPRING WELL DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Ow! Ooh, eeh, ah, ooh, eeh, ah!
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? If you walk out barefoot to the carport to
retrieve your paper in the morning, it should.
</P>
<P>
   Those noises are the sounds of pain, the burning sensation one
suffers whenever . . .
</P>
<P>
   This is beginning to sound like a commercial for some kind of
intimate-hygiene product. You know, one of those crucial but
humiliating creams or salves you have to wear a disguise to the
drugstore to buy? And then you buy another item _ usually yet
another gross of dental floss _ that you don't even need, as a
diversion for the checkout person?
</P>
<P>
   Nah. The burning sensation is the pain in your toes and feet
from the blistering concrete, a sure sign that summer heat is
finally here.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, this year it took its t ime. It's a shame that El Nino
caused all the problems it did in California and that certain
vegetables are now so expensive they have to be appraised by a
jeweler before they can be displayed in the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   But I sure loved the spring.
</P>
<P>
   That all ended Tuesday, when Phoenix had its first 100-degree
day.
</P>
<P>
   Spring here this year was like a weather wonderland. If you grew
up back East, you remember the joy of a snow day. But do you also
recall the futile hope that the shor t-term vacation might be
extended for another day or two beyond the original snowfall? (This
usually ran parallel to the realization that you had a 10-page book
report due the next day and hadn't started the book.)
</P>
<P>
   It almost never happened. But
</P>
<P>
   this spring, all those childhood wishes came true, only in a
slightly different form. Maybe the sub-100-degree weather will last
a little longer, we told ourselves all of April and May, knowing
that it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   But it did. We had, for one bright, shining moment, actually
interesting weather.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it's over. Break out the car shades, folks, we're back in
the oven.
</P>
<P>
   One group that should be happy is the gaggle of television
meteorologists. I never noticed this before I wrote a column about
El Nino and its soothing effects on our weather, but several
readers pointed out that the forecasting folks really seem to love
the heat.
</P>
<P>
   (Frankly, I never much noticed the weather forecast at all.
Seems to me it's the k ind of thing they could wrap up in about 10
seconds: ``It's going to be 106 degrees tomorrow. Wear cool
clothing. Now, on to our expanded sports coverage. . . .'' Who
cares what the weather is like in Tulsa?)
</P>
<P>
   The readers were right. Several times I saw meteorologists
prognosticate a cool, wet day with the same frown normally reserved
for an anchorperson reporting on a missing dog. Don't worry, they
would say. Chin up. In just a few weeks, we'll be back up around
normal.
</P>
<P>
   Norma l? Burning blisters on your hands from the steering wheel
of your car is normal. Who wants that?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a knock we all get,'' Sean McLaughlin, meteorologist for
Channel 12 (KPNX), said, laughing and quoting Lincoln (the ``you
can fool all of th e people some of the time'' bit, fitting for a
forecaster).
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin was a good sport. He assumed I was calling to take
meteorologists to task for not being able to correctly predict the
first 100-degree day. Not at all. Although I was rem inded of the
old saw about a stopped clock being right twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   He claims to have enjoyed the lower temperatures as much as
anyone, even if he can't crow about them. ``El Nino for us has been
absolutely fabulous,'' he said, ``but the min ute I say that, I
hear from a thousand allergy sufferers.''
</P>
<P>
   And he says he's not exactly pining for hotter weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't hit (100 degrees), I'm glad I'm wrong,'' he said.
``I'm glad. It has been a fabulous spring.''
</P>
<P>
   An d now, summer heat. For McLaughlin, endless days of sunshine
mean an additional challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I keep things entertaining when I'm saying the same
thing every day?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of us, it means something else: Ow! &QL; 
Bil l Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0923 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEADLINE-OPERA-$ADV07     06-02 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADLINE-OPERA-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HARVEY MILK': ALMOST RISES TO REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.))   (For release Sunday, June 7.) 
(ja)  
 By DAVID SCHIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fad for headline opera, a genre that began so promisingly in
1987 with John Adams' ``Nixon in China'' and fizzled last year with
Michael Daugherty's ``Jackie O,'' seems to have passed. Breathe a
sigh of relief, knowing that we have been spared operas based on
O.J., Tonya, and Paula.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a new recording of ``Harvey Milk'' (Teldec 0630-15856-2; two
CDs), with music by Stewart Wallace and libretto by Michael Korie,
shows that the attempt to link the opera house to the nightly news
may have been a missed opportunity rather than a cynical marketing
strategy. Sensationalism did not kill headline opera; opera has
always thrived on shock. It was the dead hand of operatic tradition
that undermined the attempt to give opera a contemporary relevance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvey Milk,'' which was performed first at the Houston Grand
Opera, in 1995, and soon thereafter at the New York City Opera, is
a good test for headline opera. The story it tells, of the events
leading up to the 1978 assassination of the San Francisco
supervisor who created the first successful gay political movement
in the United States, presents all the elements needed to inspire
pity and terror. In its interplay of personal tragedy with broader
political forces, it recalls ``Boris Godunov'' or ``Don Carlos,''
yet its characters _ drag queens, militant lesbians and emerging
ethnic politicians _ and American locales are utterly contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   The story has also been told in other media. ``The Mayor of
Castro Street,'' a 1982 book by Randy Shilts and an important
source for Korie's libretto, is a masterpiece of print journalism.
``The Times of Harvey Milk,'' an Oscar-winning documentary by
Robert Epstein and Richard Schmeichen, offers images and voices of
the real characters, and captures the political turbulence of the
era. ``Execution of Justice,'' an intensely focused play by Emily
Mann, re-enacts the grotesquely mismanaged trial of Dan White,
Milk's political nemesis and killer.
</P>
<P>
   The opera, unfortunately, is the one version of the story that
seems unworthy of its subject. But the fault may lie as much with
the nature of opera today as with the shortcomings of the actual
words and music. A libretto may place contemporary characters on
the stage, but it seems nearly impossible to find an operatic idiom
that will sustain them. As soon as they start to sing, the
characters lose their connection to the present day.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteenth-century opera moved easily between the mythic and the
real in subject matter, and the refined and the popular in music.
Censorship imbued costume dramas with political relevance by
forcing audiences to read them as allegories. Today, realism is the
province of film and television. Opera seems an increasingly remote
artificial paradise, remote in both subject matter and musical
style.
</P>
<P>
   Headline opera and minimalist music promised to rebridge this
gap, but even in ``Nixon in China,'' artifice prevails over the
real. The Chinese characters, who for Western audiences are merely
icons to begin with, are entirely convincing, but where is Tricky
Dick? Adams' music gains its power by a relentless consistency, but
its sleek surfaces and symphonic proportions smooth out the rough
edges of its protagonist, who is a mere shadow of the terrifying
figure portrayed by Anthony Hopkins in Oliver Stone's ``Nixon.''
Movies can do close-ups. In opera, characters are dwarfed by the
stage, unless they are given music that transcends physical
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and Korie pursue a riskier, more epic path in ``Harvey
Milk.'' Instead of constructing the opera as a tight drama, like
Ms. Mann's play, they present it as a civic pageant, part
martyrology, part history lesson. They lead the audience
didactically from the age of the closet, through the Stonewall
riots of 1969 to Milk's political rise, triumph, and tragic demise.
The libretto is full of incidents from Shilts' book; indeed, many
of them go by so fast that listeners should read the book first, at
least if they want to know the identity of Medora Payne, an
11-year-old political supporter of Milk's, or the significance of
matzoh brei to Milk's love life. But in this approach, the whole is
more important than the parts. Milk and White are less characters
than emblems. So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Milk's life immediately became a legend, Shilts notes at the end
of his book, because ``it already existed in the lives and minds of
millions of gays.'' The operatic Harvey, despite the heavy use of
details from the real story, is a legendary figure far removed from
the person Shilts writes about, and it is hard to tell to what
extent the change was driven by political agendas and to what
extent by operatic habits.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Milk is a born activist, athletic, theatrical,
extravagant: a soul brother to his contemporaries Abby Hoffman and
Jerry Rubin. He became sexually active at 14 and easily filled his
life with a succession of thin young men who were flattered by his
romantic attention, intelligence, and energy.
</P>
<P>
   His promiscuity reveals more about his political drives than
about his sexual proclivities. The mostly unworthy objects of his
affection _ newly arrived in the big city, after having been thrown
out by their families, and often addicted to alcohol or drugs _
kindled Milk's compassion. His militancy grew less from any
suffering of his own than from his sensitivity to the suffering of
others. His compassion was also a political weapon, allowing him to
forge alliances beyond the homosexual constituency. His smile,
which made him sexually and politically attractive, was that of
someone surprised and empowered by his own happiness.
</P>
<P>
   The operatic Milk is an altogether different being, a whining
Jewish mama's boy. The opera begins and ends with the wailing of
the Kaddish, the mourner's prayer, and Harvey's mother floats into
the action periodically to remind him of the Holocaust; no wonder
he moved from Long Island to San Francisco. As a young man, Harvey
seems sexually insecure and ridden with guilt (an image belied by
beefcake photos of Milk and his boyfriends in Shilts' book). The
emphasis on the Holocaust serves the political legend. Dan White
and the cops are Nazis; the singer who plays White first appears as
a policeman who entraps the young Harvey in New York's Central
Park.
</P>
<P>
   The libretto also tidies up Milk's domestic arrangements for
political purposes. His hollow promiscuity is connected to his
years as a closeted, clean-cut Wall Street investor. On the night
of Stonewall he meets Scott Smith, a radical hippie, who converts
him to political activism, then becomes his self-styled wife. In
fact, though Smith remained Milk's business partner, they were
lovers only for a short time, but political legends, gay or
straight, seem to require puritanical whitewashing.
</P>
<P>
   More disturbing is the opera's continued, almost comic
insistence on Milk's sexual insecurity. As if desperate for
affection, Harvey asks Smith why he sticks around; since the
opera's Harvey was portrayed in the San Francisco opera production
recorded here by the handsome Robert Orth, it is hard to believe
that those lines did not elicit catcalls. The opera relentlessly
reduces Milk from an activist to a victim, the creation of a
political movement rather than its creator, either because its
political ideology demands that he be a martyr from start to finish
or because his musical voice is a whimper when it should be a bang.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Dan White, meanwhile, emerges as a cartoon devil. There is no
room here for Shilts' or Ms. Mann's nuanced portrait of the
all-American boy gone terribly wrong. Instead, the opera turns to a
caricature that too often smacks of reverse racism and snobbery.
White seems to be condemned simply because he is an Irish Catholic,
watches television from his Barcalounger and eats Twinkies.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that simple. White was the negative image of
Milk's identity politics, representing his constituents as
partisanly as Milk represented the Castro district. If Milk's
people were victims, White would claim, so were his people, driven
out of their neighborhoods by real-estate speculators. More
sinister, White was the tragic pawn of a political struggle between
old and new San Francisco that he barely understood. His rage may
have been fueled by Milk's greater political acumen, but his script
was being written by the fat cats downtown. According to Shilts,
White was their weapon against an emerging liberal consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's score has powerful moments, especially at the end,
when it sounds the perfect mournful tone. But it is plagued by an a
tin ear for vernacular speech and a chronic shortness of breath.
Korie's libretto provides many opportunities for strong musical
numbers, two love duets for Harvey and Scott, a mad scene for
White, two political rallies and a surrealistic vision of closeted
life in the '50s. But although Wallace often uses Adamsian
ostinatos in the orchestra, his vocal lines are twisted in an older
expressionist manner strangely at odds with pungently vernacular
lines like: ``Mama, I've slept with over a thousand men. If you
don't know by now, I'm gay, queer, feigelah _ different.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Wallace should have delivered one great love
song and a memorable gay anthem, but they just don't happen. Worse,
none of the lead characters is given a distinctive musical profile.
Harvey, sung here by Robert Orth; Scott, sung by Bradley Williams;
and Dan, sung by Raymond Very, for all their differences in
personality, age, and background, just sound like opera singers,
painfully trying to enunciate the street language and negotiate
their fussy musical lines without sacrificing a technique of bel
canto that comes from another world.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, and without conviction, the opera aims for greater
musical contrast through quotation. The opening chords of ``Tosca''
appear whenever Harvey goes to the opera house. ``The Rite of
Spring'' rumbles under the Stonewall riot, and White's speeches
dredge up memories of ``Nixon in China,'' but these are all
hit-and-run devices that mainly expose the lameness of Wallace's
own material. And when, at the end of the opera, we hear the taped
voice of Milk reading his political will, the dramatic power of the
moment painfully reveals Wallace's failure to give the opera's lead
character a voice with any similar power and pathos.
</P>
<P>
   Musical success for this opera would have required a more daring
eclecticism than Wallace was evidently willing to try: an
eclecticism that does not have to be imagined, because it is
already there in works like ``Trouble in Tahiti'' and ``Mass.'' If
only Leonard Bernstein had lived to set this libretto rather than
wasting his efforts on the narcissistic psychodrama of ``A Quiet
Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein might well have known how to bring down the walls of
the opera closet, the walls that trap the genre in singing styles
and musical forms from a distant past. The story demands the tragic
scale of opera, the intimate sophistication of cabaret, the
insouciance of pop, the utopian political drive of '60s rock. And
more than anything else, it demands the kind of melodic warmth and
memorability that brings the constituency it is celebrating into
the opera house to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite its flaws, ``Harvey Milk'' contains moments that
are touching and zany and contemporary in ways that we are used to
on the stage but hardly ever encounter in the opera house. And as
it reaches its tragic conclusion, the opera suddenly feels both
wrenching in its pain and heroic in its politics: the equivalent of
the message of hope that Milk so skillfully repeated at the end of
his campaign speeches. At these moments ``Harvey Milk'' seems to
open possibilities for a vital, risk-taking musical theater, free
from the oppressions of tradition, good taste and ``Masterpiece
Theater'' restorationism.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps headline opera just needs a few more years and a few
more honorable failures to realize its initial promise to
revitalize a 400-year-old art form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
