u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOTERROR-COX &UR;  &UR; HEALTH     06-02 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTERROR-COX </SLUG>
     HEALTH OFFICIALS SAY U.S. ILL-PREPARED FOR
BIO-TERRORISM
 &HT;     By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Experts now regard the threat of a terror attack
against U.S. civilians involving chemical or biological weapons as
``no longer a matter of if, but of when,'' a top health official
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that in addition to bombs, today's terrorists can
choose among highly dangerous agents, including chemical and
biological agents,'' James Hughes, director of the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention's Center for Infectious Diseases,
told a Senate subcommittee. ``An attack with a biological or
chemical weapon used to be considered very unlikely, but now seems
entirely possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes added that in recent years, CDC investigators attempting
to explain the causes of mystery outbreaks have been forced to
consider whether sickness was the work of terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This possibility arose during the investigations of the 1993
outbreak of hantavirus pulmonary syndrome in the United States, the
1994 outbreak of plague in India and even the 1995 outbreak of
Ebola hemorrhagic fever'' in Zaire, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He and others added that an infectious disease, deliberately
released by terrorists in the United States, might spread
throughout the country before it is recognized. By then, waves of
``second generation'' illness could already have begun among health
workers and others exposed to the initial victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is simply nothing that scares the hell out of me like
this issue,'' said Michael T. Osterholm, an Iowa public health
official who testified as a representative of the American Society
for Microbiology.
</P>
<P>
   In a commencement speech at the U.S. Naval Academy last month,
President Clinton announced that he was ordering government
agencies to prepare for ``nontraditional'' threats, such as
bioterrorism and computer sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's hearing was conducted by the Senate Appropriations
subcommittee on labor, health and human services. However, the only
member of the subcommittee to attend the two-hour affair was Sen.
Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C. He explained that Sen. Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., chairman of the subcommittee, was recovering from heart
surgery and other members were attending the Arizona funeral of
former Sen. Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   CDC officials, as well as state and local health officials, told
Faircloth that the best defense against a bioterrorist attack would
be a strengthened and upgraded national public health system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be like a battle tank that we need to win a war but has
the ability to be a very efficient school bus,'' said Ed Thompson,
state health officer of Mississippi and a member of the Association
of State and Territorial Health Officials.
</P>
<P>
   CDC's Hughes said that in addition to laboratory facilities and
training to quickly identify a deliberately released infectious
disease, health officials may need secure telephone lines. Some
experts have warned that widespread panic growing out of a
terrorist attack could jam conventional communication systems.
</P>
<P>
   Although deadly pathogens such as anthrax and biological toxins
such as botulinim are traditionally pictured as the weapons of a
bioterrorist attack, those diseases do not spread beyond the
initial victims, several witnesses told Faircloth.
</P>
<P>
   But deliberately released smallpox virus, plague bacteria or
some other pathogen might spread widely before it is ever detected,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have thought something like this would be some
sweeping, instant panic, but you're saying it will be a creeping
attack among our citizens, aren't you?'' Faircloth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are very fortunate and we are someday attacked by a
naive terrorist ... if we are lucky enough to get dumb terrorists,
they might detonate an anthrax bomb over a packed sports stadium or
release botulinim in an airport,'' said Thompson. ``But a
sophisticated terrorist could release smallpox virus in Jackson,
Miss., or Omaha, Neb., and we would see an ill-defined pattern of
disease that could be spread over our entire population before we
even recognize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth asked Hughes how many scientists CDC has working on
plague.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, when the outbreak occurred in India ... '' Hughes
started to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about 1994,'' Faircloth drawled. ``I want to know
about nineteen-ninety-now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes then repeated that the CDC had only one plague laboratory
specialist in 1994 when an epidemic of pneumonic plague, which is
spread from person to person like a common cold, appeared in the
Indian city of Surat. Today, he said, the center has 10 or 11
people working in its Fort Collins, Colo., laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
