<HEADER>
A0927 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-HABIBIE-410     06-02 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-HABIBIE-410-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S NEW LEADER, SELF-STYLED REFORMER, HOPES TO STAY
AWHILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Presenting himself as the reformer that
Indonesians have been calling for, President B.J. Habibie laid out
an intricate election timetable Tuesday that would keep him in
office at least through the end of next year, despite widespread
calls for a quick handover of power.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately effusive, assertive, defensive and a touch
melancholy, his eyes flashing and his hands chopping the air,
Habibie spoke in his first newspaper interview about his hopes to
lead Indonesia out of its political and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks after his elevation from vice president after the
sudden resignation of his friend and mentor, President Suharto, he
still seems amazed to be where he is.
</P>
<P>
   Gesturing across his broad desk and clapping his hands in
seeming astonishment, he said: ``You know, I was always sitting on
that side. The president was always here. Now I am here!''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he had to be reminded by an aide not to refer to
Suharto as president. ``You are the president,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Habibie outlined a confident program that challenged both
his critics and his former boss.
</P>
<P>
   Monday the attorney general announced an investigation of
Suharto's accumulated riches, but Habibie said he personally did
not favor digging into the sources of his predecessor's billions,
and he warned against ``Wild West'' justice.
</P>
<P>
   He defended the Suharto family's self-enrichment as part of a
feudal culture, and described his predecessor as frugal and never a
part of the jet set.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing Suharto's accumulation of billions of dollars, he
said: ``If you dig into the past, then the past is unlimited, and I
have limited resources. I'd better concentrate on the future. Many
of the things that are said are right and many things are also
exaggerated. And so it is not worthwhile for the future of my
country to dig into the past.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his own wealth and that of his family members, Habibie
said they are all highly educated and talented people who had
earned their riches fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Saying ``this is not a jungle,'' he also dismissed opponents who
are urging a quick transfer of power and insisted that the only
constitutional route to a transition involves a rather tortured
procedure that would lead to a parliamentary election next year,
followed by an electoral assembly at the end of the year that would
select a new president.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to rule out his own candidacy for a new term.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Habibie also gave a vivid account of the transition of power May
21, when he received the news that he would become president only
at the last moment and only from a presidential aide. Suharto, he
said, refused to speak to him.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie, who for 20 years was Suharto's minister of research and
technology, has little administrative experience and little base of
power, and had never been seen _ even by Suharto _ as a potential
president. Most Indonesians view him as a transitional figure, and
powerful forces are pressing him to step out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke with a mixture of deep affection and veiled criticism
for Suharto, a man he said he had known since childhood and
considers to be one of his best friends, but who now appears to
have turned his back on the new president.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed that Suharto, 76, had grown too old to sense
the mood of the people. As a younger man of 62, Habibie said, he
has a better feel for the aspirations of the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural process, aging, you know,'' he said. ``I don't
want to insult because he has done a lot for the country. But he's
not a young man. The students are my children and the students are
his grandsons. The gap between father and son is less than the gap
between grandfather and grandson. It is a generation gap, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with his patron, Habibie presents himself as a
champion of democracy and human rights, and of the kind of economic
openness that he said he hoped would quickly restore public
confidence in the economy and attract foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have another person _ you have another president,'' he
said. ``You have another economic team. You have transparency. You
could never talk to President Suharto the way you can talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I am not the king.''
</P>
<P>
   In a melancholy tale of the hand-over, he described his sudden
abandonment by Suharto, who he said had not communicated with him
since stepping down. When told of a newspaper report that Suharto
was passing the time playing golf and jogging, Habibie said,
``Golf? That's good.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time they met, he said, between 8 and 9 on the evening
before Suharto resigned on May 21, Suharto was still discussing his
plans to announce a new cabinet the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then at 11 o'clock I was informed by the secretary of the
president that he had changed his mind,'' Habibie said. ``He was
going to step down the next morning and leave it to the vice
president to take over the leadership of the country. The next
morning I applied to see him at home but they said, `No, he is on
his way. He will not receive you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie said he hurriedly asked various officials whether the
hand-over was constitutional, and was assured that it was. ``Then
they told me the president had arrived, and I immediately sent the
protocol officer to see whether I could see him, and he said no,''
he continued.
</P>
<P>
   After Suharto had read his brief resignation statement and
Habibie had taken the oath of office, he said: ``He looked at me,
he shook hands _ not a single word, just a smile. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Habibie said, as powerful politicians and
military men milled around him and his mentor disappeared in his
chauffeured car, he did the only thing left to him to do. He
prayed, ``God, give me strength.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing President Suharto has always told me _ because for
me he is like an older brother, and sometimes like a father, but
for sure a good friend; he's a good guy _ he told me: `My dear
Rudi, one day a lot of people will be looking at you. A lot of
people will know you. You will be the most lonesome man in the
world, because you have to face your own decisions.' And I faced
that. I had to face that and make decisions so fast.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of meetings with economic ministers, military
leaders and several opposition figures whom he has invited to join
him in regular consultations, Habibie said, he embarked on a
program that in many ways repudiated both the style and the
substance of his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Habibie is not more or less than the puppet of
his former master,''' he said. ``If that is the case, why on my
first day do I touch on human rights? Within 25 hours and 30
minutes after I took over, I announced a cabinet. Two hours later I
was negotiating about human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   He has begun what officials say will be the releases of hundreds
of political prisoners. But he said Tuesday there would be no
change in policy toward the separatist movement in the island
province of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, ``I was facing the military problem
between Prabowo and the others.'' Lt. Gen. Prabowo, Suharto's
son-in-law, had been removed from his command in a quick move by
the armed forces commander and defense secretary, Gen. Wiranto, to
consolidate his military command.
</P>
<P>
   In an angry show of force, Prabowo mobilized some of the troops
he commanded and stormed into Habibie's residence to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me what to do, and I told him to obey his
commander,'' Habibie said. But as a precaution, he said, the new
president and his family were moved for several hours that night to
a safe house and his grandchildren were flown by helicopter to join
him.
</P>
<P>
   Prabowo has accepted his demotion to head a military college
away from the capital, but he remains an unpredictable power.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, after that, I had to receive the Bank of Indonesia
and listen to the economic situation and make my decision what to
do or not,'' Habibie said. ``You see? I was alone. And then, you
know, it was already 11 o'clock, 12 o'clock. I had to read a lot of
things to make my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I tell you, that first week, I slept at most two
hours. But I was very calm, correct? I was not nervous, just calm.
Correct?''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was his two decades ``in the cockpit'' at Suharto's
side that prepared him for leadership. ``I'm not deaf and blind. I
can read. I can see. I can put a lot of questions, OK? I learned at
the hands of the master.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Suharto's team, he said, he could discuss
policies with him, but in the end it was his job to support the
president. That did not mean he did not have his own ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a puppet,'' he said. ``I was his former member of the
cabinet for 20 years and I know him personally for 48 years, and I
consider myself one of his best friends. You have also a best
friend, but that does not mean that you do everything your best
friend wants you to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie said some colleagues were urging him to act more
``presidential,'' to imitate Suharto's taciturn and measured style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say, `Hey, Dr. Habibie, you should look like
Suharto and talk like Suharto,''' he said, lowering his voice an
octave. ``But my children said to me, `No, I want to see you as you
are. Be yourself.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
