<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTT-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT SEEKS CHINESE SATELLITE DATA FROM WHITE HOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., asked
the White House on Tuesday to turn over all documents related to
President Clinton's decision to allow the export of U.S. satellites
to China for launch into space.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Clinton, Lott wrote that he and other Republicans
are concerned that recent satellite transfers may have compromised
national security. He asked for Clinton's cooperation in an
investigation of the matter begun this week by a special task force
of GOP chairmen formed by the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are deeply troubled about the national security
implications of satellite exports and related technology transfer
to the Peoples' Republic of China,'' Lott wrote in the letter
released by his office.
</P>
<P>
   The request came as Clinton prepared to visit China later this
month and as lawmakers on Capitol Hill readied themselves for their
annual debate on whether to grant most-favored-nation trading
status to China for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to notify Congress on Wednesday that he
plans to renew MFN for China unless the House and Senate votes to
block it within the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the MFN debate has often been heated, with
Republicans and Democrats split over whether to back it. But in
recent years, Lott, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and other
GOP leaders have been strong advocates of the special trade status.
</P>
<P>
   China is expected to win MFN again this year. But supporters
will have a tougher time getting it approved by Congress because of
the controversy over the satellite transfers and whether Beijing
sought to influence the 1996 elections with campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley told a group of exporters
Tuesday that he believes MFN will be granted to China. But he
acknowledged that the task of winning approval this year will be
far ``more difficult'' than in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Lott said his task force was particularly
concerned about the possible transfer of U.S. technology, which may
have allowed the Chinese to improve the accuracy of the missile
guidance systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that Chinese ballistic missile capabilities
may have been enhanced, either directly or indirectly, by these
exchanges,'' he said in the letter that also went to the State,
Defense and Commerce departments, as well as to the Arms Control
and Disarmament Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has also formed a select committee to conduct a House
investigation of the Clinton waivers, which were granted following
a 1996 decision to move the licensing authority for technology
transfers from the State Department to the Commerce Department. The
Republicans are interested specifically in a Clinton decision last
February to allow Loral Space and Communications Co. to launch a
commercial satellite from China while the company was under
investigation by the Justice Department for possibly providing
sensitive information to the Chinese in violation of federal law.
</P>
<P>
   In his broad request for information, Lott also asked for
records, including memos and computer e-mail related to all
technology transfer waivers to China granted by Clinton and any
military and national security concerns that may have been raised
about them. He also requested documents related to U.S. export and
licensing policies for U.S. commercial satellite technology.
</P>
<P>
   An official at the White House said the administration would
cooperate with the request. But he noted that much of the
information has already been made available ``in one form or
another'' to various Senate and House committees that are
responsible for overseeing decisions regarding ``the transfer of
technology abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to keep a check on the Republican investigations of
the waivers, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told
reporters Tuesday that he plans to set up his own task force of
Democrats to help ensure that the GOP inquiries are carried out in
a non-partisan manner. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
