<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONRAIL-HEARINGS-NYT &LR;      06-02 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONRAIL-HEARINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS TAKE MORE TIME OVER CONRAIL ACQUISITION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Fla. Pa.)  (ja)  
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, federal railroad regulators approved, with hardly
a blink, Union Pacific's acquisition of Southern Pacific to form
the nation's largest railroad. The result was one of the nation's
worst rail tie-ups, costing businesses billions of dollars
throughout the West.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday and Thursday, the Surface Transportation Board is
holding hearings on plans by two other railroads, Norfolk Southern
and CSX, to take over Conrail, the only major freight carrier
serving the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   While approval of those plans is expected, the board, striving
to make amends for the Union Pacific debacle, has already attached
tougher conditions and oversight to Conrail's acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The railroads said that the takeover of Conrail presented far
fewer threats to competition, reliability, and safety than Union
Pacific's $5.4-billion acquisition of Southern Pacific, and that
their preparations have been far more thorough. Businesses
throughout the Northeast will enjoy much smoother, faster shipments
from other regions, they said, and motorists on the interstates
will enjoy reduced traffic as 1.1-million truckloads of freight
each year are diverted to the rails.
</P>
<P>
   While shippers and labor unions generally supported the
acquisition, some said that it would present them with higher
shipping costs and unacceptable risks. The railroads, they said,
cannot reliably or safely handle the extra freight they expect the
merger to generate.
</P>
<P>
   Conrail is a monopoly by design, created by the government in
1976 from the failed Penn Central, itself a combination of the New
York Central and Pennsylvania railroads, and several other roads.
To assure its success, Conrail was given exclusive rights over much
of the region.
</P>
<P>
   CSX and Norfolk Southern, which dominate rail freight east of
the Mississippi, bought Conrail for $10.2 billion last year. They
have operated it independently pending government approval for
dividing it up and integrating its operations with theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Board's own existence is up for
congressional reconsideration this year. Members of Congress, labor
leaders and many shippers accuse the agency, the successor to the
Interstate Commerce Commission, of serving only to protect the
railroads.
</P>
<P>
   `It's the worst case of an agency that has been captured by the
industry it regulates,'' said Edward Wytkind, executive director of
the AFL-CIO's Transportation Trades Department. His union, citing
safety and job loss fears, opposes the Conrail acquisition, while
other unions, having negotiated job security provisions, support
it.
</P>
<P>
   The government, however, has not turned down a railroad merger
since rejecting a deal between Santa Fe and Southern Pacific in
1987. Customers and investors consider approval of the latest deal
a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most businesses believe the merger is a fait accompli,'' said
Douglas Rockel, an analyst with Furman Selz. ``The STB never saw a
merger they didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Linda Morgan, the board's chairman, said she would
have no comment because the case was pending. The board's only
other member is Gus Owen, with a third, nominated member, William
Clyburn Jr., awaiting Senate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   The board did not consider safety issues in the Union Pacific
deal. A series of crashes that left nine railroad crew members dead
followed the acquisition of Southern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the board has demanded that the railroads
submit thorough safety plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Union Pacific merger left too few locomotives and overworked
crews, supervisors often unprepared for their new duties, and
clashing computer systems that lost track of trains. Railyards
overflowed and delays mounted, as customers filed suits to recover
their losses and Union Pacific stock plunged.
</P>
<P>
   CSX and Norfolk Southern have therefore assured investors that,
instead of trying to capture immediate savings, they are buying
hundreds of extra locomotives and adding hundreds of conductors and
engineers to make certain the acquisition goes smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be chaos and confusion in this one,'' said Michael
Ward in an interview. As CSX's chief financial officer, he has
assumed prime responsibility for the Conrail acquisition. ``We've
had plenty of time to look at what we've learned from other
people's mergers.''
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk Southern, the smaller of the acquirers, would assume 58
percent of Contrail's operations, CSX 42 percent. Both would serve
New York and Washington, although only CSX would serve Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Shippers generally agree that, by splitting Conrail, this
railroad deal, unlike most others, would increase competition. `A
lot of our members thought they had died and gone to heaven,'' said
Ed Rastatter, policy director for the National Industrial
Transportation League, the leading association of shippers. But,
fearing that CSX and Norfolk Southern overpaid for Conrail,
Rastatter's association negotiated an agreement with the railroads
to control rates and see that Union Pacific's problems are not
repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Where Conrail and its acquirers overlapped, however, shippers
were wary of reduced competition. The Justice Department had
supported a complaint by Indianapolis Power &AMP; Light that CSX could
raise the utility's costs for hauling coal if competition from
Conrail is eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The Chemical Manufacturers Association, in fact, planned to tell
the board it opposed the deal. ``It doesn't take a rocket scientist
to figure out that when you take three railroads and make two out
of them you're going to reduce competition,'' said James Pasierb,
an association spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The railroads said that improved service, without the delays
caused by switching from their systems to Conrail's, would capture
so much freight now moving by truck that motorists traveling
between cities along Interstates 95 and 81 in particular ought to
notice the difference within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   The railroads have struck an agreement to use Amtrak's
high-speed rails, saying that Amtrak's safety and reliability would
not be compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Conrail, however, has seldom carried freight on Amtrak rails
since a 1987 collision between passenger and freight trains killed
16. Within cities, the railroads will continue to rely on trucks to
carry many shipments to their final destinations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
