<SLUG> BC-BARR-COX </SLUG>
     BARR SPEAKING AT IOWA GOP EVENT _ BUT WHY?
 &HT;     By REBECCA CARR 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The list of those invited to speak at an upcoming
Iowa Republican Party forum includes nearly every GOP hopeful for
the Oval Office in 2000. Former presidential candidates Lamar
Alexander and Steve Forbes will be there, as will Sen. John
Ashcroft of Missouri and House Budget Chairman John Kasich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Now add one more: Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Barr has accepted an invitation to return to his native state to
speak at the ``First in the Nation Gala,'' a political forum
scheduled for June 12 in Cedar Rapids. The event has featured every
Republican presidential nominee for the past decade, said Steve
Grubbs, chairman of the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Barr, a two-term congressman, insisted that the speaking
engagement is not a bid for the Republican presidential nomination.
Rather, it is an attempt to ``make sure public officials at all
levels of government, including the president, are held accountable
for their actions.''
</P>
<P>
   That means Barr will mostly likely discuss the current scandals
at the White House ranging from Monica Lewinsky to allegations of
illegal fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   Since Iowa is historically the stomping ground for presidential
aspirants, Barr's decision to speak with the rest of the pack has
some politicos wondering whether the conservative congressman is
just being coy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Iowa and everyone knows what Iowa stands for,'' said Aric
Kahle, spokesperson for the Iowa Republican Party. ``We're first in
the nation and everyone knows that Iowa is the testing waters for
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barr, not known for mincing his words, said his Iowa speech
is truly an attempt to get the nation focused on the issues he
thinks are important. ``I remain concerned about the direction the
Republican Party is taking and will remain actively involved in
helping shape our party's national agenda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is not exactly what Barr told the Iowa Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came away from a conversation with him thinking he was very
sincere about entering the national political scene,'' Grubbs said.
``Barr said he wanted to test a national message.''
</P>
<P>
   What this most likely boils down to is an attempt to do what
Ross Perot and others have done: capture the national spotlight to
push a personal agenda, said William Connelly, professor of
politics at Washington &AMP; Lee University and author of a book about
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly does not think that Barr is a viable candidate for the
presidency. He sees Barr's speech as a sign of atrophy in the
national political parties and a confirmation that the presidential
election process is increasingly dominated by the media.
</P>
<P>
   In such a culture, Connelly said, ``all sorts of people are
running who have no business doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Alexander, Forbes, Ashcroft and Kasich, Iowa voters
will hear from Rep. Steve Largent, R-Okla.; Gary Bauer, president
of Campaign for Working Families; Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma;
Alan Keyes; former vice-presidential nominee Jack Kemp; radio talk
host Oliver North; Gov. Marc Racicot of Montana, Sen. Bob Smith of
New Hampshire, and Marilyn Quayle, the wife of former Vice
President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably absent from the list are House Speaker Newt Gingrich
and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, widely considered prime
contenders for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
