<HEADLINE>
TRAINER PLEASED WITH REAL QUIET'S FINAL WORKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., see RAC-BELMONT) 
(ja)  
 By JAY PRIVMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his final workout before his bid for the Triple Crown in
Saturday's 130th Belmont Stakes, Real Quiet covered five furlongs
on Tuesday at Churchill Downs in 1 minute 1 second, a drill that
encouraged his trainer, Bob Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Preakness, he was a bit dehydrated, but now he's
hitting on all cylinders,'' Baffert said. ``He looks great. He's
training great. I'm amazed at the way he's come around. He's put on
weight. He looks fresh. He looks like he could run two weeks after
the Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet has trained primarily at Churchill Downs throughout
the Triple Crown. He was there for three weeks before the May 2
Kentucky Derby, then was in Maryland for just five days _ long
enough to win the May 16 Preakness Stakes _ before returning to
Kentucky. Real Quiet was to be flown Wednesday morning from
Louisville to New York and to receive a police escort for his van
ride to Belmont Park from John F. Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The jockey Dana Barnes was on Real Quiet for his workout.
According to Baffert, the colt started off too quickly in his
workout, so he told Barnes _ via walkie-talkie _ to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty anxious,'' Baffert said. ``He really wanted to
do a lot.'' By the end of the work, Baffert said, ``He was just
galloping, just cruising, doing it effortlessly. I want a strong
horse when the gate opens.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Real Quiet captures the mile and one-half Belmont, he will
become the sport's 12th Triple Crown winner and his owner, Mike
Pegram, will receive a $5-million bonus from Visa, the Triple
Crown's sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER MEANINGFUL WORKOUTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Four of the horses expected to challenge Real Quiet also had
important workouts on Tuesday. At Belmont Park, Classic Cat _ who
finished third in the Preakness _ breezed five furlongs in 1:01
2/5, Raffie's Majesty cruised through an easy half-mile in :49 3/5,
and Thomas Jo was timed in 1:28 1/5 for seven furlongs. And at
Churchill Downs, the long shot Hot Wells covered a half-mile in :48
3/5.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jo has won four straight races and six of his last seven,
but has yet to defeat horses of this caliber. He will be the first
Belmont Stakes starter for the trainer Jimmy Jerkens, who was a
long-time assistant to his father, Allen Jerkens, before going out
on his own in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would I feel if I win? Forget about it,'' he said,
smiling. ``This is one of those races everyone remembers.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raffie's Majesty finished fourth in the Illinois Derby in his
last start, but trainer James Bond said the extra distance of the
Belmont will suit his colt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can gallop for three miles and wouldn't even blow out a
candle,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINISH LINES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Both Grand Slam and Yarrow Brae are expected to be entered in
the Belmont Stakes by the trainer D. Wayne Lukas. Jerry Bailey had
committed to ride Yarrow Brae, but that was before Grand Slam's
victory in the Peter Pan Stakes, so Bailey could end up on Grand
Slam. Mike Smith is the other jockey who will be employed by Lukas.
... Hanuman Highway, who missed the Preakness Stakes and Peter Pan
because of a sore right front hoof, has switched to shoes that are
glued on, rather than affixed with nails. He will have a workout on
Wednesday. ... Entries will be taken and post positions drawn for
the Belmont Thursday morning. Unlike this year's Kentucky Derby and
Preakness Stakes, trainers will not select their post positions;
they will be determined in a blind draw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
