<HEADER>
A0941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOTECH-ARTHRITIS-ART     06-02 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-ARTHRITIS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRUGS BEING DEVELOPED FOR RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Penn., Mass., Ore., Neb.)  (ART ADV: A graphic concerning rheumatoid arthritis is being sent
to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 20 years she has had rheumatoid arthritis, Veronica
Lewandowski has undergone replacements of both hips, both knees and
the knuckles of her right hand. She has tried virtually all the
drugs available but nothing has really worked.
</P>
<P>
   But in the eight months since Ms. Lewandowski, a 39-year-old
resident of Worcester, Pa., began taking an experimental drug known
as Enbrel, she is less fatigued and no longer has to descend stairs
backward to spare her knees. And when her son fell off his bicycle
recently, she astonished her two children, and herself, by running
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had never seen me run before,'' said Ms. Lewandowski, who
had to give up her job in a chemical company laboratory because she
could no longer operate the instruments. ``Life is fun now.''
</P>
<P>
   Enbrel is the first drug produced by the two-decades-old
biotechnology industry that is aimed at rheumatoid arthritis, which
afflicts 2.5 million Americans and is the most severe of the
diseases of the joints. What is more, other promising new drugs for
rheumatoid arthritis are right behind it, a stark change for a
disease for which there have been almost no new therapies for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen this degree of activity in this field,'' said
Dr. Michael Weinblatt, a professor at the Harvard Medical School.
``I'm much more optimistic about controlling this disease than I
was five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The new drugs are causing excitement on Wall Street as well as
in the clinic because the potential market for them is estimated to
be in the billions of dollars each year. The stock of Immunex
Corp., the Seattle biotechnology company that makes Enbrel, nearly
tripled in the last year, though it has recently fallen back to a
level twice its 12-month low.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the coming new drugs are involved in the big merger
announced on Monday between American Home Products Corp. and
Monsanto Co., promising to make the combined company a powerhouse
in arthritis treatment. Immunex is 54 percent owned by American
Home Products, which will help promote Enbrel in the United States
and sell it overseas. Monsanto's pharmaceutical subsidiary, G.D.
Searle &AMP; Co., is leading the way to develop a new type of
painkiller for people with arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   The new drugs appear to be as good or better than existing
therapies but with fewer side effects. But they are not cures and
just how much optimism is warranted won't be clear for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Existing drugs can already control rheumatoid arthritis in 60 to
75 percent of the cases, especially if treatment is started early,
said Dr. Doyt Conn, senior vice president for medical affairs at
the Arthritis Foundation. He said the new drugs are likely to add
to existing therapies, not replace them.
</P>
<P>
   Immunex applied in May to the Food and Drug Administration for
permission to market Enbrel. The company hopes for approval as
early as the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Centocor Inc. of Malvern, Pa., hopes to file for approval of a
somewhat similar arthritis drug called Avakine within a year from
now. But an FDA advisory panel has just recommended approving
Avakine for treatment of Crohn's disease, an intestinal
inflammation. Once it is approved for that, doctors will also be
able to legally use it for arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected in 1999 are a new class of ``super aspirins'' that
treat pain and inflammation but without stomach bleeding and
ulcers, which are estimated to cause several thousand deaths a year
among patients who take existing painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   Searle expects to file for FDA approval in the third quarter of
this year for use of such a drug to treat rheumatoid arthritis,
osteoarthritis and pain. Merck &AMP; Co. is close behind, though it is
first concentrating on osteoarthritis and pain.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst Marion Roussel Inc., an American unit of Hoechst AG,
meanwhile, recently applied for approval to market still another
new arthritis drug, called Arava.
</P>
<P>
   Meirav Chovav, biotechnology analyst at Salomon Smith Barney,
said that Enbrel ``could be a billion-dollar drug five years out.''
Sales projections from various analysts are even greater _ $2
billion or more _ for the super aspirins.
</P>
<P>
   The new drugs have their limitations. The super aspirins, known
as COX-2 inhibitors, do not even claim to halt the progress of the
disease; instead, they are meant to relieve just the symptoms.
Enbrel, Avakine and Arava probably will slow the destruction of
joints but might not halt it completely, and they will not be able
to heal already damaged bone and cartilage. Moreover, patients will
probably have to take these drugs for life, possibly along with
existing medications. But the new drugs, if started early enough,
may allow sufferers to lead nearly normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make it as controllable and tolerable as
insulin-dependent diabetes or hypertension, where you have to take
your medication but life goes on,'' said Elizabeth Tindall,
clinical associate professor of medicine at the Oregon Health
Sciences University in Portland. ``That's a lot better than `Buy
your wheelchair now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous types of arthritis, the most widespread being
osteoarthritis, a wearing away of the cartilage that is associated
with aging that affects about 20.7 million Americans, according to
the Arthritis Foundation. But rheumatoid arthritis is the most
debilitating. Half the victims _ many are women aged 25 to 50 _
must quit work because of disability within a decade, Weinblatt of
Harvard said.
</P>
<P>
   Rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune disease, one in which the
body's immune system, designed to fight bacteria and viruses,
mistakenly attacks the body's own tissues, in this case the lining
of the joints.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, drugs for rheumatoid arthritis have been borrowed
from other diseases like cancer or malaria. They either suppress
the immune system in general or work in other ways not fully
understood. And they can have serious side effects. The most
commonly used is methotrexate, a generic cancer drug, which can
cause liver and lung problems in a small number of patients.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   There are also two dozen or so nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory
drugs, which range from over-the-counter aspirin and ibuprofen to
more potent formulations sold by prescription.
</P>
<P>
   The newer drugs take advantage of the explosion of knowledge
about the immune system. They are designed to be more specific in
their activities, hopefully producing better results with fewer
side effects. ``We are on the threshold of targeted approaches,''
said Conn of the Arthritis Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the COX-2 inhibitors. COX, which stands for
cyclo-oxygenase, is an enzyme involved in causing pain and swelling
at injury sites. But one type of COX is also involved in protecting
the stomach lining and in helping the kidneys function.
</P>
<P>
   Existing nonsteroidal painkillers like ibuprofen inhibit both
types of COX. COX-2 drugs block the action of the enzyme involved
in inflammation but leave the type that protects the stomach
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michelle Petri, who heads the FDA's arthritis advisory
committee, said that Searle's data show its COX-2 inhibitor to be
as effective as existing painkillers yet ``the toxicity profile was
the same as for people taking the placebo.'' But she said the
committee still asked for more data, in part to make sure there are
no effects on fertility, as an animal study suggested there might
be.
</P>
<P>
   The existing market for prescription nonsteroidal
anti-inflammatory drugs for arthritis is $2 billion in the United
States and as much as $5 billion worldwide, said Dr. Philip
Needleman, president of Searle. ``We think COX-2 inhibitors will
take over that entire market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Immunex's Enbrel works by stopping the activity of tumor
necrosis factor, or TNF, one of the major substances involved in
mounting an immune attack. TNF attaches to certain immune system
cells at docking stations known as receptors. Enbrel consists of
versions of this receptor that float in the bloodstream and act as
decoys, getting the TNF to bind with them rather than with the
immune cells.
</P>
<P>
   Immunex at first is aiming at patients for whom existing drugs
have failed. In clinical trials, about 60 percent of such patients
responded to Enbrel and 40 percent saw their condition improve
substantially. Immunex has also shown that Enbrel together with
methotrexate is better than methotrexate alone, said Peggy
Phillips, senior vice president for pharmaceutical development.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Enbrel will displace methotrexate is not clear
because a direct comparison of the two drugs has not been
completed. Moreover, a year's supply of Enbrel will cost between
$5,000 and $10,000, Ms. Phillips said, and patients must inject
themselves twice a week. Methotrexate is available in pills and a
year's supply costs only about $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Competition could also come from Hoechst's new Arava, which will
also be in pill form. Analysts consider it a conventional medicine
rather than a biotechnology marvel, but it does work by a mechanism
different from the existing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Another unknown is how effective and safe Enbrel will be over
the long run, said Dr. James O'Dell, chief of rheumatology at the
University of Nebraska Medical Center. Immunex's data extend only
to 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Johnson of Lake Oswego, Ore., began taking Enbrel in
December 1996. ``In the first year, I was literally cured, and it
was astonishing,'' she said. But in the last few months, she said,
some symptoms returned, though still nearly nowhere as bad as they
were before.
</P>
<P>
   Centocor's Avakine targets TNF not with a receptor but with a
monoclonal antibody, a specially engineered version of the body's
infection fighters.
</P>
<P>
   For the most seriously ill patients who are not helped by any
drugs, Cypress Bioscience of San Diego is applying this year for
approval to market a device that filters antibodies from a person's
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies _ including Amgen, Autoimmune Inc., Immune
Response Co. and Isis Pharmaceuticals _ are in clinical trials of
drugs that work in various other ways. Some companies hope to stop
the body from attacking itself to begin with. Anergen Inc., for
instance, has reported some effectiveness in early clinical trials
of an arthritis ``vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   But the immune system is complex and efforts to control it have
met with mixed results. Also, weakening the immune system can leave
a patient more susceptible to infections. Idec Pharmaceuticals
Corp. and SmithKline Beecham PLC last year suspended late-stage
clinical trials on an Idec arthritis drug after some patients
experienced declines in a key immune system cell. The companies
have now started new trials with a reformulated drug.
</P>
<P>
   Progress made in treating arthritis might also help in treating
other diseases, particularly autoimmune ailments like lupus and
Type 1 diabetes. Immunex is testing Enbrel for congestive heart
failure and COX-2 inhibitors show promise in colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, scientists hope to find the cause of the
self-immune attack. The Arthritis Foundation is searching for the
genes that make people susceptible to the disease. Because not all
genetically predisposed people get the disease, scientists suspect
there is some trigger, like a bacterium or virus, that sets it off.
But that trigger, if it exists, has not been found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
