<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-COX &UR;  &UR; TOBACCOB     06-02 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
     TOBACCO BILL SURVIVES CHALLENGE
 &HT;     By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The embattled comprehensive tobacco bill survived
an effort Tuesday in the Senate to move on to other legislation, a
move its supporters said would virtually kill the bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   The key vote came on an procedural effort to invoke cloture _
thus requiring consideration _ on a bill backed by the nuclear
power industry to proceed with plans to store industrial nuclear
waste at Yucca Mountain in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The motion failed, 56-39, to obtain the necessary three-fifths
vote in the 100-member Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said invoking cloture would
have put the tobacco bill back on the Senate calendar where any
senator could object to its further consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would put us at the mercy of every single opponent of the
tobacco bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., said Republicans were attempting to
``reward two very powerful industries: big tobacco and the nuclear
power industry,'' by voting for cloture.
</P>
<P>
   But Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he was simply
trying to provide time for the Senate to take up an array of other
pressing business.
</P>
<P>
   As senators continued to huddle privately, the tobacco bill
faced difficulties on several fronts, but primarily from Republican
lawmakers who argue the bill would impose a huge tax increase on
lower-income Americans who smoke cigarettes at a far higher rate
than more affluent citizens.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, would offset the bill's
$1.10-a-pack tax increase on cigarettes by eliminating the
so-called marriage penalty _ which imposes higher taxes for a
couple with relatively equal earnings than if they were single _
for couples with incomes under $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although Democrats have opposed tinkering with the marriage
penalty as part of the tobacco bill, Daschle said he could support
some proposal if it would increase chances of passing the
half-trillion-dollar tobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, a leading opponent of the tobacco bill, said
he would welcome changing the marriage penalty, but would still
oppose the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bill is still a fatally flawed bill,'' Nickles
said. ``This is a big tax increase. ... This is a big new spending
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., argued that the public pays $80
billion a year _ $1,370 per family _ to cover the cost of
smoking-related illnesses. Kerry argued the bill was not a tax
increase because the people who would pay higher cigarette prices
would do so voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, the Senate unanimously adopted an amendment by
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., to provide $660 million a year for five
years _ a total of $3 billion _ to reimburse the Department of
Veterans Affairs for the cost of treating veterans with
smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
