<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-FEST-$ADV07-530     06-02 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-FEST-$ADV07-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING BLACK CONTRIBUTIONS TO MODERN DANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 7.) 
(js) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most significant accomplishments of the American
Dance Festival in its 65-year history has been its shedding light
on the rich but often little-known contributions of black
choreographers to American modern dance. In 1987, the festival
began a long-term program to reconstruct lost classics and present
new work, to encourage black dance companies and to build wider
national audiences for repertories and dancers. An unparalleled
collection of archival and scholarly material on American black
dance was also begun.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, in Durham, N.C., will continue the programming
this Thursday through Sunday with ``Masterpieces of the Black
Tradition.'' Classics by Talley Beatty, Asadata Dafora, Katherine
Dunham, Donald McKayle and Eleo Pomare will be performed by the
Dayton Contemporary Dance Company and the Cleo Parker Robinson
Dance Ensemble of Denver. The dances will also be filmed for a
series produced by the festival and the Public Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, on June 23 and 24, Jawole Willa Jo Zollar and her
Urban Bush Women company will perform recent pieces as well as her
new ``Hands Singing Song,'' a work commissioned by the festival
through its Doris Duke Awards for New Work program. (The company
will also perform at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in
Massachusetts in August.)
</P>
<P>
   And on June 29, Fayard and Harold Nicholas, the tap stars known
as the Nicholas Brothers, will receive the 1998 Samuel H. Scripps
American Dance Festival Award for lifetime achievement in dance.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Scripps award in the festival's bare-bones early
years, and certainly there was very little black concert dance to
tap into. What the festival did have going for it was the visionary
practicality of early American modern dance. Martha Hill, a former
Martha Graham dancer who had become a dance educator, saw that what
the fragile yet determined young art of modern dance needed most
was a place to grow, away from the distractions of the city.
</P>
<P>
   What better place than a workshop, at Bennington College in
Vermont, that would offer six weeks of classes in dance technique,
composition, music, history and critical theory? And who better to
teach those dance classes than Martha Graham, Doris Humphrey,
Charles Weidman and Hanya Holm, by then stars of American modern
dance, who could also create and present work at Bennington? The
first students were 103 women, many of them physical education
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the festival, which moved to Durham in 1978, offers 65
classes a day, taught by 55 teachers, for some 500 professionals
and preprofessional students from around the world in studios,
classrooms and theaters spread out over the campus of Duke
University. This year, there will be 43 performances by 14 groups,
including an ice-dancing company, along with a film and video
festival, tributes to American dance legends, and lectures and
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its growth, however, the festival has remained at its
core a much-needed, prestigious summer home for established
modern-dance artists, and a place for the artists of the future to
develop in the company of those who have come before.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is not hard to chart the lineage from Graham, that festival
pioneer, to David Grenke, whose new company will perform this
season in Durham. Grenke danced with Paul Taylor, who danced with
Graham. Ms. Zollar's earliest dance training was with Joseph
Stevenson, who studied with Dunham, in her childhood home, Kansas
City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Zollar also talks of a heritage that includes Dianne
McIntyre, the black choreographer at whose New York studio Ms.
Zollar developed her own style in the 1980s. Ms. McIntyre was, in
turn, influenced by the improvisational work of the white
avant-gardists Judith Dunn and Bill Dixon. Even more, Ms. Zollar's
choreography has been informed by her memories of the sensuous
shake dancers she watched as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Graham created larger-than-life heroines. Ms. Zollar's pieces
are about everyday women. Her seven dancers will play themselves as
they are today in ``Self-Portrait'' and ``Transitions.'' In ``Hair
Stories,'' the dancers portray their younger selves. In the new
``Hands Singing Song,'' they are women whose hands push against
society's barriers, slap together in ebullient handshakes and
engage in what Ms. Zollar wryly refers to as what ``Jocelyn Elders
lost her career over.'' It is tempting to imagine that Graham might
have recognized Ms. Zollar's women as sisters to her characters, a
connection that seems entirely possible in the historical framework
of festival programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The African-American dance artist has at every turn been a
reflection of his/her social era, serving as a catalyst at one turn
and as a willing community barometer at others,'' Halifu Osumare, a
writer on black dance, observed in ``African-American Genius in
Modern Dance,'' published by the festival in 1993. In its
determined attention to that artistry, the festival has enlarged
and reinforced its founding traditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
