<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: ADVANCE BOARDING PASSES, HEATHROW TRAINS, HOTEL
UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
(bl) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three airlines _ American Airlines, Trans World Airlines and
United Airlines _ are eliminating all advance boarding passes this
month, which could mean longer check-in times for business
travelers at airports.
</P>
<P>
   With these moves, the three carriers are following in the
footsteps of America West, Continental Airlines and Northwest
Airlines, which stopped giving out advance boarding passes late
last year. American's and TWA's actions were effective Monday,
while United's new policy begins next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Delta Airlines eliminated advance boarding passes
only on its international flights. U S Airways still offers them on
all flights, though a spokesman said the carrier was ``taking a
very close look at its policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines say they are eliminating the passes because of the
ever-growing popularity of electronic tickets, which are currently
available on domestic flights but not most international service.
Another factor, the airlines say, is increased security procedures
mandated by the Federal Aviation Administration that require all
passengers to check in with an agent. Elimination of the passes
does not affect carriers' ability to offer travelers advance seat
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Before the FAA's procedures were instituted, in the wake of the
crash of TWA Flight 800, advance boarding passes had saved
travelers time upon arrival at the airport, since they could go
directly to the gate and use the pass to board their flight.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines that have eliminated the passes contend that this
change has not slowed their check-in or boarding procedures. Patty
McMenamin, a spokeswoman for Rosenbluth International, the
Philadelphia-based corporate travel company, said Rosenbluth's
clients ``do not seem to be unhappy'' about the changes, since many
fly with electronic tickets and are not affected.
</P>
<P>
   However, other officials predict the changes will make it
necessary for passengers to arrive at airports even earlier than
they do already. Sabina Terrades, vice president of marketing and
communications for Stevens Travel Management in New York, another
corporate travel company, warned that the changes ``would
definitely create a hassle.'' She added, ``Our travelers used to
get to the airport 20 or 30 minutes before their flight; now we
advise them to be there a minimum of one hour before departure.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Loucks, a spokesman for the American Society of Travel
Agents, predicted that ``lines at the gate are going to be
dramatically longer,'' noting that ``anyone who travels is going to
have to allow more time now at the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Train to Heathrow
</P>
<P>
   BAA PLC, which owns seven British airports, including London's
Heathrow Airport, will offer express train service between Heathrow
and Paddington Station in downtown London starting June 23. One-way
rates will be $17 for so-called express class and $33 for first
class; the journey will take 15 or 20 minutes, depending on the
terminal at Heathrow. Subway or taxi service between Heathrow and
downtown London normally takes at least one hour and the one-way
cost can run from $6 for the subway to $60 for a taxi, including
tip.
</P>
<P>
   Airline check-in at Paddington for British Airways, American
Airlines and British Midland passengers with hand luggage will be
offered. This service will be available next May for passengers who
want to check their luggage.
</P>
<P>
   The express service will operate every 15 minutes from 5:10 a.m.
to 11:40 p.m. daily. BAA will offer frequent bus service from
Paddington to West End hotels for $3.30.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Update
</P>
<P>
   The five London hotels owned by Millennium Hotels and Resorts, a
subsidiary of CDL Hotels of Singapore, are cutting their rates by
30 percent to 40 percent from July 6 through Sept. 6. The reduced
rates, which include value-added tax and breakfast, will run from
$199 a night at the Copthorne Tara to $250 a night at the
Millennium Britannia Mayfair.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Inter-Continental in New York is upgrading guests to a
suite for an additional $75 a night above their booked rate,
through Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The 24 Swiss hotels that belong to Leading Hotels of the World
set a single-occupancy room rate of $250, including value-added tax
and Continental breakfast, through March 31, 1999. A two-night stay
is required. Rates at these hotels normally range from $175 to $520
a night without breakfast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
