</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-OIL-DUMPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYAL CARIBBEAN ADMITS IT DUMPED OIL AT SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd., the world's
second-largest cruise line, announced on Tuesday that it had agreed
to plead guilty to federal charges of dumping oil at sea, lying to
the Coast Guard about the discharges and tampering with witnesses
and evidence, and as a result would pay $9 million in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The illegal activity involved at least five of Royal Caribbean's
12 ships. The company acknowledged that they had routinely dumped
waste oil into the sea instead of sending it through purifying
equipment for storage. In some cases the oil was pumped out of the
ships through illegal pipes that were then removed by the crews
just before Coast Guard inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The practice saved tens of thousands of dollars a year per ship,
the company said. In court, prosecutors said some officers had
received bonuses for cutting operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   The company is entering its guilty pleas, to eight felonies, in
San Juan, Puerto Rico, and Miami this week and will pay an $8
million fine and an additional $1 million for environmental
projects. The Justice Department said the $8 million was the
largest environmental fine ever levied against a cruise line.
</P>
<P>
   The offenses covered by the agreement occurred from 1990 to
1994, a period when Royal Caribbean's stewards and deckhands wore
buttons that said ``Save the Waves'' and urged passengers not to
bring on deck any paper goods or other objects that might blow
overboard.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Royal Caribbean, second in size only to Carnival
among all cruise lines, had argued vigorously that it was immune
from prosecution in the United States, since none of its ships are
registered here. For instance, the company, whose main offices are
in Miami, hired former Attorney General Benjamin Civiletti as its
lawyer and brought in former Attorney General Elliot Richardson as
a witness, to contend that under international treaties, discharges
from one ship, the Nordic Empress, could be prosecuted only by
Liberia, because the ship is registered there.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Tuesday, Royal Caribbean said its decision to
plead guilty was ``based on a review of the available evidence,
including evidence recently submitted by the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor may have been a decision on May 12 by Donald
Middlebrooks, a federal district judge in Miami, that Liberia did
not have sole jurisdiction in the Nordic Empress case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
