<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESCUE-AWARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST GUARD TO HONOR SUPPLY CREW WHO SAVED 42 RIG WORKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was after midnight when an offshore rig's distress
call reached the supply ship Trinity Seal. A natural gas well on
the Gulf of Mexico had blown, and spewing gas and debris threatened
the lives of 42 rig workers.
</P>
<P>
   A closer ship already had refused to approach when the Trinity
Seal plowed through high winds and 10-foot waves. As the captain
maneuvered the 175-foot vessel, steadying it as best he could, four
crew members guided rig workers on board. Then they sailed away,
counted heads and realized that someone was left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Defying danger a second time, the crew returned to the
thundering rig. They searched the rig with spotlights until they
found and rescued the missing worker.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the rig exploded in a fireball that could
have been deadly to workers and rescuers alike. Instead, the events
of April 1, 1997, are being remembered Wednesday as examples of
heroism at sea.
</P>
<P>
   The crew from the Trinity Seal, led by Capt. Randall ``Randy''
Treon, will receive the Coast Guard's meritorious public service
award from Adm. Paul Pluta in 11 a.m., CDT., ceremonies Wednesday
at the downtown Hyatt Regency in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred about 100 miles southeast of Cameron, La.,
on a platform known as East Cameron 328. It burned for three days
after the explosion, officials said, and it took a year to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disregarding their own safety, the crew of Trinity Seal
responded without hesitation knowing that the 42 workers aboard the
platform were in imminent and mortal peril from the uncontrolled
high pressure release of gas that could explode and consume the
platform and their vessel at any instant,'' a Coast Guard
announcement said.
</P>
<P>
   Other honored crew members are chief engineer Arthur Briggs,
mate Sidney Skinner and able seamen Anthony Bush and Jason Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were as humble as can be, but they are real heroes,''
said Mark Andrews, vice chairman of Louis Dreyfuss Natural Gas Co.,
which owns the platform.
</P>
<P>
   Treon, 38, with 17 years experience at sea, was within a few
miles of the rig when the crisis was reported about 12:30 a.m.
Another vessel was closer but refused to get involved, he said.
Panicky rig workers were preparing to jump into the rough seas
about 100 feet below.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they called me, they said the rig was `kicking,' it was
blowing, and they had to abandon the platform,'' Treon said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I was coming over there and not to get into the
water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 20-knot winds, Treon eased his ship into position to
accept fleeing rig workers, some of whom dove onto the deck of the
Trinity Seal from escape ladders and ropes.
</P>
<P>
   The vessel pulled away from the rig, but Treon did a U-turn
rather than leave someone behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had everybody,'' Treon said. ``And they did a
head count and found out there was some guy missing, so we had to
go back to try to find him. After we found him, we pulled away and
about 30 minutes later is when it blew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a massive explosion _ a huge fireball.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire melted the platform to the water level, causing $10
million in damages but no casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Treon said he'd never been so close to catastrophe, but ``it's
one of those things you don't think about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just do it, and then usually after a couple of days later,
you kind of think about it a lot,'' the captain said. ``When we saw
it blow, I think that's when reality finally hit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the evacuation, the other four crew members worked
together to assist the rig workers and trained a spotlight onto the
rig to help locate the missing worker. All the while, dangerous
gases roared from the blown-out well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what made everybody nervous, because we knew it was
fixing to explode,'' Treon recalled. ``We just didn't know when,
and we were trying to get out before it did.''
</P>
<P>
   A small spark could have ignited the fireball during the rescue,
but Treon said he was just ``lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very proud of Randy and his crew,'' said Ed Schreiber,
co-owner and vice president of Southern States Offshore, Inc.,
operator of the Trinity Seal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never thought about the situation in terms of it being
life-threatening to themselves,'' Schreiber said. ``They knew they
had to get these people off that platform before it exploded. They
never thought about any danger to themselves until it was all over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the stuff movies are made of.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said the rescued rig workers are ``extremely grateful''
to the Trinity Seal crew. They paid tribute to them a year ago with
a dinner in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They technically didn't have to respond to the call,'' Andrews
said. ``They could have turned a deaf ear to it. Somebody already
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept their heads and they got every one on board and gave
them blankets and literally some of the clothes off their backs _
and they did it in all the confusion and chaos,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been a real disaster, and thanks to these fine
men, it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
