<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-WORLDBANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BANK RESUMES LENDING TO INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INDONESIA-HABIBIE, INDONESIA-HABIBIE-MONEY) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The World Bank said Tuesday that it had approved a
$225 million loan to Indonesia, which is expected to use the money
to build roads, improve water supplies and rebuild schools.
</P>
<P>
   The loan, approved by the Bank's board Tuesday, is the first
World Bank credit to be approved for Indonesia since lending was
suspended May 18 amid the unrest that toppled President Suharto and
ushered in his successor, B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the bank's strategy to strengthen local planning and
avoid entanglement with the central government in Jakarta, the loan
will go directly to accounts set up by community leaders in rural
areas, the bank said in a statement Tuesday. The money is part of
some $43 billion in aid from the World Bank, the Asian Development
Bank, the International Monetary Fund and individual nations.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said the $225 million could benefit 7 million to 10
million rural Indonesians, especially those in the eastern regions
hardest hit by recent droughts. Villages contribute labor, cash or
materials to supplement loan money, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Guggenheim, the World Bank's loan project manager, said
the money was intended for ``people who really need the help the
most'' in a poor country that is the world's fourth most populous.
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheim, who has spent considerable time in Indonesia, said
villages in remote regions can be virtually cut off for months at a
time during rainy periods. Building a simple road, typically a
gravel path 10 feet wide, would, for instance, enable a pregnant
woman to get medical assistance or or allow farmers to get their
crops to market.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Fischer, the first deputy managing director of the IMF,
said in Tokyo Tuesday that the IMF may be able to resume
disbursement of its funds to aid the battered Indonesian economy
``reasonably soon,'' Reuters reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
