u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-P&AMP;G-AD-COLUMN-470&AMP;ADD     06-02 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-P&AMP;G-AD-COLUMN-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARING TO RISK BEING HIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ohio, N.Y.) (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's largest and perhaps most staid advertiser, the
Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., is unexpectedly kicking up its corporate
heels with an unconventional marketing ploy.
</P>
<P>
   The usually downright upright P&AMP;G is uncharacteristically making
a foray into so-called nontraditional media in an effort to
stimulate sales of Noxzema skin cream among women ages 21 and over.
The company is sponsoring a project centered on placing small
advertising signs, which pitch Noxzema with edgy messages, in the
women's restrooms of about 115 trendy restaurants, bars and clubs
in chic Manhattan neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, which are going up this week, are being hung in frames
affixed to the walls across from mirrors in the restrooms. The
signs are printed in reverse and are meant to be read in the
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   The ads offer such pithy, somewhat confrontational statements
as: ``It's not the lighting,'' ``Look as good as the woman your
date is hitting on,'' ``He must really love you for your inner
beauty'' and ``Did someone miss her beauty sleep?'' At the bottom
of each ad is a photograph of a jar of Noxzema and a slogan, ``Next
time Noxzema,'' being introduced solely for this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The project is indicative of the growing interest among
mainstream marketers in unusual media vehicles meant to reach
small, niche segments of the shopping public, particularly in urban
centers where trends are often incubated.
</P>
<P>
   Other such new media ventures include trucks that drive through
city streets, displaying billboards; ads beamed on the sides of
buildings; racks filled with postcard ads, which are placed in
restaurants, bars and nightspots; ads printed on coffee cups and
posted on coffee carts; and even small signs affixed to the backs
of messengers' bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new campaign is a break from traditional Noxzema
advertising, reaching young women in places they wouldn't expect
with a big dose of in-your-face humor,'' Mark Schar, vice president
and general manager for the skin cleansing and conditioning
business at P&AMP;G in Cincinnati, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noxzema in the blue jar has long been the leading facial
cleanser for teen-age girls,'' he added. ``The campaign drives home
the message to young women that Noxzema isn't just for teens; it's
for them.'' In addition to Noxzema, Schar oversees important P&AMP;G
brands like Coast, Clearasil, Ivory, Oil of Olay, Safeguard, and
Zest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Noxzema brand has been around forever, so there's a desire
to make it feel fresh, unexpected and new,'' said Gerry Miller,
executive vice president and managing creative director at the Leo
Burnett USA unit of the Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago, the Noxzema
agency. ``Media becomes a way, a means, for delivering a message
that's a little up the contemporary, hip scale.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you notice and ask `Who has the nerve to do that?' ''
he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The campaign, Miller said, is aimed ``at women who are thinking
about their face, about their skin, but not in the traditional
bathroom time and place _ in a bathroom that's eight feet from a
dance floor with people crowded around.''
</P>
<P>
   In the evolving alternative-media universe, bathrooms have
become a popular locale for advertising. Some ads appear on walls,
others on the doors of stalls and still others above urinals in
men's restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we sell to advertisers is a captive audience with a prime
demographic of 21 to 35,'' said David Dorfman, co-owner with Marc
Miller of Insite Advertising, a New York company that sells ad
space in restrooms in 250 locations in Manhattan to marketers like
P&AMP;G, the Joe Boxer Corp. and the RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's sex-specific,'' he added, ``so you can get either men
or women and eliminate the waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller of Burnett called the Noxzema campaign ``a bit risky,''
but added: ``Risk these days is living in the middle of the road
where most of the cars can pass over you. Instead, you take an
attitude, you take a point of view, which is cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The creative credits for the campaign are: Sarah Rose,
copywriter; Darryl Vasilinda, art director; and Chris Laubach,
creative director.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett has extensive experience in producing risk-taking,
rule-breaking campaigns for products meant for younger consumers
that are sold by marketing behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   For the Altoids brand of mints sold by Callard &AMP; Bowser-Suchard,
a unit of the Philip Morris Companies, Burnett has produced ads
with odd, offbeat imagery to promote the product as ``the curiously
strong mints.'' One shows a cheerful woman wielding a whip above
the headline ``Pleasure in Pain.'' Burnett won two awards last
month for the Altoids campaign _ including the $100,000 grand prize
for general excellence _ from the Magazine Publishers of America.
And for the Dewar's brand of Scotch whisky sold by Diageo PLC,
Burnett has created a trailblazing series of ads using wry humor to
make Scotch more palatable to drinkers ages 21 to 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree, the environment is inspirational,'' Miller
said of the influence of those campaigns on Noxzema's, ``but I'm
not sure it was all that literal and direct.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Moore, a spokeswoman at P&AMP;G for the product lines
supervised by Schar, declined to discuss the budget for the
campaign. The ads ``at this point are in New York City only,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get into future plans,'' Ms. Moore added.
</P>
<P>
   Among the bars, restaurants and clubs that will display the
signs are Pageant, Trilogy, the Tunnel, the Turtle Bay Tavern and
Union Bar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
