<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOCRACY-INDIA-IMPER     06-02 1638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRACY-INDIA-IMPERFECT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY: IS IT FOR EVERYONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (The prestigious Council on Foreign Relations is offering this
important commentary on late 20th-century democracy as part of our
monthly World Leaders Forum. To publish as a ``separate buy''
article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. )
 &HT;    
 By SAMUEL P. HUNTINGTON  
 c.1998 Council on Foreign Relations  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   EDITORS: The following identification line must be printed with
the column. Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This commentary is adapted from a panel discussion entitled
``Democracy: Is It for Everyone,'' held at the Council on Foreign
Relations, in New York, on May 19, 1998.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Is democracy for everyone? I think the answer is no, not yet,
but it certainly is for more people now than it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, the single-most important political phenomenon of
the late 20th century has been the expansion of democracy in
country after country around the world.
</P>
<P>
   And by democracy I refer to electoral democracies _ which I
define as a political system whose most powerful decision makers
are selected through relatively fair, honest, periodic elections,
in which candidates can freely compete and in which virtually all
the adult population is eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   By that definition, the number of democracies in the world has
gone up very substantially in the past few decades, from about 40
back in 1970, to 66, according to Freedom House, in 1988, to 117
now. This expansion has, in considerable measure, been worldwide;
it has affected every part of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   There is a heavy concentration of democracies, obviously, among
wealthy countries and among those who were part of, shall we say,
Western civilization. But at least one democratic regime exists in
every major civilization or culture in the world.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening to democracy as it spreads around the world? I
think it is becoming more variegated; it is taking on different
forms and acquiring different characteristics in different
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Second, democracy, as I've defined it, is simply a way of
constituting, limiting and changing governments. There is often a
tendency, however, to see it as something much more _ as, for
example, to suppose that the introduction of democracy will bring
about peace, equality, prosperity, harmony among nations and
classes and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think that is the case. For governments produced by
elections can be inefficient, corrupt, shortsighted or
discriminatory. They can pursue aggressive nationalistic policies
and pursue ruinous economic policy. Democracy is no guarantee that
other good things will happen, although they may.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tendency among people to assume that democracy won't
have unhappy consequences. However, I think we have to confront the
fact that, in this world, elections will produce results which
don't necessarily make us happy; they may produce anti-Western
governments, illiberal governments, ones that we find very
difficult to deal with _ including, when they are weak and resting
on fragile coalitions, even governments which will go off, as India
just has, and explode nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   To underline this point, I think this sort of caution,
concerning democracy, is desirable because of the widespread
assumption that, if other countries will simply democratize _ if we
can encourage them to move in that direction _ they will be
friendly and cooperate with us.
</P>
<P>
   For example, this assumption underlies the thinking of virtually
everybody on every side of the China debate. If only we could make
China democratic, the thinking goes, it would be so much more easy
to deal with. Well, perhaps it would be, but, on the other hand, it
is not difficult to conceive of a democratic China simultaneously
being a China which is highly nationalistic, in which politicians
competing for office appeal to Chinese nationalism and find it
worth their while, in terms of votes, to denounce the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   So while I am all in favor of promoting more democracies, I
think we ought to do it in a realistic way, with our eyes open.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think instituting a democratic system of government is
necessarily going to guarantee greater prosperity, greater
equality, elimination of ethnic conflict or the solution of a lot
of other social problems and ills. I do not mean that it will be
impossible for democratic governments to do that; only that there
is no guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   I think democracy is desirable for two reasons: One, it provides
order and a mechanism for incremental change, and it provides a way
of removing from office political leaders who have turned out to be
total flops.
</P>
<P>
   Two, it is also one way _ not the only way _ of protecting
liberty in a society. And I agree that violations of liberty are
less likely if you have a democratic system of elected officials
who are going to have to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   It is timely, of course, to consider that India is a democracy.
Yet one of the reasons why the recent nuclear explosions took
place, it seems to me, was the existence of a weak coalition
government and a minority party that obviously wants to build
popular support. Indeed, apparently _ so far, at least _ it has
been extraordinarily successful in building popular support.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, I think it is necessary, even though India is a
democracy, to recognize that lots of things make the relations
between the United States and India very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent conference at Harvard University, where people
attended from the major countries and regions of the world, and
discussed the attitudes of their political intellectual elites
toward the international system, the use of force, and so forth,
one of the points that came through loud and clear was the seething
resentment under the surface, in large part, in many areas of the
world about the United States. We are the superpower and people
don't like that.
</P>
<P>
   This came through particularly clear in a paper prepared by a
scholar from India. He wrote of the divisions among the Indian
elites, including the Gandhians, yet concluded: ``For all Indian
elites, the United States represents the major diplomatic and
political threat. On virtually every issue of concern to India, the
U.S. has veto or mobilizational power, whether it is nuclear,
technological, economic, governmental or political matters. That
is, the United States can deny India its objectives and can rally
others to join it in punishing India.''
</P>
<P>
   Who, if any, on the globe will remain in the authoritarian camp?
Today 55 percent of the people in the world live under democratic
government, according to Dr. Gideon Rose, at the Council on Foreign
Relations. I believe that 50 years from now a larger percentage of
the world will be democratic. I would not guess exactly what
percentage or who will and won't be. But I will say there will be
some non-democratic regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically perhaps, given such a pivotal role on the world
stage, the situation of democracy in the United States, I believe,
is not as good as it should be. It certainly seems to have been
more vigorous in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The major problem is the extent to which political competition
now has become increasingly competition among candidates, or
between candidates, rather than between parties, and the parties
have tended to become service organizations for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, there is the tremendous impact of television, not
just in terms of the influence on voters. Rather, the big influence
of television is the tremendous demand for money, and that's what
has made fund-raising such a central preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
   To glance through the daily newspapers, it seems that our
president now probably spends more time fund-raising for his party
than any other single activity. I don't know that any of the bills
in Congress are going to remedy that. Very probably there may have
to be some drastic action, such as provision of public funds for
campaigns, or at least for advertising on television.
</P>
<P>
   But then, democracies are not necessarily going to introduce
lots of good things. One can even think of democratic governments
that have been aggressive and that, in one way or another, have
terrorized parts of their population.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the young people of the country are inclined to wait for
the ideal world, or not wait, will depend upon, in large part, what
governments do and how governments act.
</P>
<P>
   And I don't think youth, or students in particular, are
necessarily going to be the central force for change in the coming
years _ and not necessarily a force for positive change. They may
be, but like so many other parts of the equation, that isn't at all
certain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 Council on Foreign Relations &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Professor Samuel P. Huntington is the Albert J. Weatherhead
III university professor at Harvard University, the director of the
John M. Olin Institute for Strategic Studies, chairman of the
Harvard Academy for International and Area Studies and chairman of
the Harvard Center for International Affairs. He is the author of
numerous books and articles, most recently, ``The Clash of
Civilizations and the Remaking of World Order.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
