<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHORER-DANCE-ART-$AD     06-02 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHORER-DANCE-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSPIRED BY BALANCHINE, NOW AN INSPIRATION HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo showing Suki Schorer, teaching ballet at Juilliard,
will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7)  
 (af)  
 By HILARY OSTLERE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Suki Schorer perches precariously on a ballet barre,
giving her the maximum overview of her students in Studio 3 at the
School of American Ballet at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 2 inches tall, she needs the extra height to conduct a
rehearsal of Balanchine's challenging ``Donizetti Variations,'' one
of three ballets presented this weekend at the school's Workshop
Performance at the Juilliard Theater. Her eyes dart everywhere.
Cajoling, joking, demonstrating, she demands perfection, just as
Balanchine, her mentor, did when she danced for the New York City
Ballet from 1959 to 1971. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schorer is famous for staging Balanchine ballets for the
workshop every year. ``I've been doing it for 24 years,'' she says.
``Twelve different ballets. I've recycled `Serenade,' one of my
favorites, four times.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schorer's students, who range in age from 16 to 18, treat
her with affectionate familiarity. ``If she wanted, I'm sure she
could still dance her part in `Donizetti,' '' says Ryan Kelly, 17,
one of three corps members who will be performing in the workshop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Megan Pepin, long-limbed and coltish and one of two students who
will dance the ballerina part, adds: ``She has so much energy. We
work hard, but we also tell stories and laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Before curtain time they know Peter Martins, City Ballet's
artistic director and ballet master in chief, will stop in to offer
suggestions and give a final stamp of approval.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schorer, 59, whose given name is Suzanne though she's never
called that, was born in Boston and is the daughter of the literary
critic Mark Schorer. She has won her reputation as a visionary
teacher with attention to detail and the ability to inspire people
to dance with naturalness, grace and a feeling of spontaneity and
not just perform the steps.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine spotted her ability to analyze and correct when she
was in the corps de ballet. ``He would ask me to explain what
someone in class was doing wrong and to suggest a correction,'' she
recalls. ``He would ask, `What do you think of this person _ not
what you're looking at now, but the talent underneath, the
potential that's there?' One day, because he had a meeting, he
said, `Suki, you start company class.' Sometimes he didn't turn up
at all, and I'd be there teaching as well as taking class.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Balanchine went out to scout new talent, Ms. Schorer would
occasionally go along. She taught a children's class, then an
intermediate men's class, then a class for new people in the
company. ``I tried to help dancers with their roles,'' she says.
``A dancer, perhaps in the corps of the `Waltz of the Flowers,'
would say: `Come and look at me. How could I do better?' We'd talk
about how each step should move, how we should put the feet to the
floor, how to bend the body. I tried to get them to dance the way
Mr. B. liked to see dancing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schorer acknowledges that she's not one of nature's Swan
Queens, but she excelled in the soubrette roles that Balanchine
created for her, like Pierrette in ``Harlequinade'' and the First
Butterfly in ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacques d'Amboise, the former City Ballet principal dancer,
says: ``I noticed her from the beginning. She was like a little
cosmic particle flitting around the stage. When she was our
children's baby sitter, I don't think she actually ever
(italics)sat.(end italics) But just because she's not outwardly
serious doesn't mean she not a great brain. She's the best teacher
I know.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schorer is enjoying a particularly good year. This spring
she received the Dance Magazine Award for lifetime service to dance
and was named to the senior faculty chair at the School of American
Ballet, previously held by the legendary teacher Stanley Williams,
who died last year.
</P>
<P>
   Her teaching continues to encompass lecture demonstrations and
the dissemination of the Balanchine ethos to teachers abroad. And
she's working on instructional dance videos and writing a book on
Balanchine technique, to be published next year by Knopf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, it's still more dance. ``I love to
tango,'' Ms. Schorer says. She and a friend, Russell Lee, go out to
spin around a ballroom in vintage dances or try to solve tango's
sexy complexities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could master the Argentine style in three
months,'' she says. ``Three years later I'm still taking lessons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
