<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0983 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDWATER-IN-STATE-AZ     06-02 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWATER-IN-STATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS PAY RESPECTS TO BARRY GOLDWATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Mike Thomas was the first one at the chu rch door
Tuesday morning. And before the sun set, he and 1,000 others had
said their good-byes to Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in ROTC at Camelback High School from 1955 to 1959, and
we won a lot of awards,'' Thomas recalled. ``Barry pinned a lo t of
them on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The former senator died Friday at the age of 89. More than 100
people were in line outside Trinity Cathedral when the bells rang
exactly at 11 a.m., and the doors opened.
</P>
<P>
   They came in wheelchairs, old station wagon s and big red BMWs.
Many were silver-haired, wearing Western hats and turquoise
jewelry. They were all native Arizonans, or at least Goldwater made
them feel that way.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater's wife Susan spent the day greeting every one with a
handshak e or a hug, except for a moment when retired Episcopal
Bishop Joseph Harte prayed with the family over the coffin at
noontime.
</P>
<P>
   The line of people passed smoothly, pausing at the coffin and
the baptismal font that displayed Goldwater's 1911 chu rch
registration.
</P>
<P>
   A few people left mementos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an eagle feather,'' said Debra Nez of Needles, Calif.
``I want to give it to him because he had respect for the Indians -
every tribe.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, an aging veteran wo uld imitate a posture of youth
and throw a salute.
</P>
<P>
   Past commanders of American Legion Post 41 showed respect for
Goldwater as a 49-year member gave an ``order-arms'' salute as the
visitation began. ``He helped get the deed for the property the
post is on,'' said former state lawmaker Earl Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   A uniformed honor guard from Luke Air Force Base flanked the
coffin without moving except to change personnel as the cathedral
bell chimed every 45 minutes. Joanne Goldwater, the sen ator's
eldest daughter, took a break from greeting guests at one point to
ring the bell.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong stream of visitors included some dignitaries -
former Maricopa County Supervisor Hawley Atkinson, former Arizona
House Speaker Don Aldridg e, former state Sen. Jim Buster of Yuma,
former Gov. Jack Williams. They all praised Goldwater's candor and
commitment to conservative principles.
</P>
<P>
   Most had a story to share, like Aldridge's helicopter trip with
Goldwater into Havasupai Villa ge at the bottom of the Grand
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were checking on a big hydroponic vegetable operation the
federal government had put in,'' Aldridge said. ``Before we got
there, they had thrown out all the hydroponic stuff and built horse
barns for
trail rides - something that made sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Attorney General Grant Woods had some regrets after
passing by the bier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have spent more time with him,'' Woods said. ``I
wanted to have lunch with him at least once a mon th. But things
come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Irma Chriseman, 90, of Sun City, got up early to ride to
downtown Phoenix with her daughter, Emilie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admired that man for many years,'' Chriseman said from her
wheelchair. ``I wanted to meet him so badly.' '
</P>
<P>
   The visitation helped with the family's sadness as well, Joanne
Goldwater said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me when I saw the casket draped with the flag,'' she
said. ``Just knowing he's in a better place is keeping our spirits
up. And having a lot o f my friends come down - a lot of my old
high school buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Kim Hudson of Phoenix, who needed a tissue when
asked about Goldwater. ``I'm sure he's better off,'' she said.
``But a lot of people are going to miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   Several visitors said they were disappointed in the turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought there would be many, many people here,'' Barbara
Shine of Glendale said. ``He was so big. There should have been
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a line outside the
</P>
<P>
   church on a hot day is what attracted Teeter Francies of
Phoenix, who was passing by on the way to an errand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they talked on the news was, we wouldn't be able to
get in,'' she said. ``But when we saw it wasn't crowded . . . .'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
