r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-AZR &LR;      06-02 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MACHO' AMENDMENTS IMPERIL TOBACCO BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain's massive anti-smoking bill is
</P>
<P>
   in peril because of ``macho'' amendments senators are pushing to
punish the tobacco industry and score political points, McCain said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in danger of knocking this thing way out of balance, if
we haven't already,'' the Arizona
</P>
<P>
   Republican said in an emotional speech on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   In a later interview, McCain placed the stalled bill's prospects
for passage at ``still better than 50-50. But you know me, I'm an
eternal optimist.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, McCain s aid, is that some senators want to toughen
the bill _ apparently for political posturing _ to penalize
cigarettemakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see going on here _ interestingly from both ends of the
political spectrum _ is such punitive amendments that we
</P>
<P>
   will drive the tobacco companies out of business,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers must decide whether to pass his legislation, McCain
said, or whether to simply to ``vote for amendments to show how
macho and tough we are on the tobacco companies.' '
</P>
<P>
   His remarks cast McCain, if only fleetingly, in the unlikely
role of a tobacco industry defender. The tobacco companies have
accused him of trying to orchestrate their demise. While conceding
he is no fan of the cigarettemakers, McCain has
</P>
<P>
   denied that his goal is to tax the industry out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's bill is designed to reduce youth smoking through stiff
cigarette price increases and sales and marketing curbs. The
measure would cost the industry at least $516 billion
</P>
<P>
   in tobacco-related health costs and anti-smoking programs. It
also proposes a ban on outdoor advertising by tobacco firms that
may violate free speech, says the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's backers hope to shut off debate and proceed to a vote
on the measure by early next week.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the Senate must consdider amendments that are
worrisome to McCain and the bill's other sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment, by Richard Durbin, D-Ill., would toughen the
penalties on
</P>
<P>
   tobacco companies if youth smoking reduction targets are not
met.
</P>
<P>
   The Durbin amendment _ combined with an earlier, passed
amendment eliminating a cap on the industry's legal liability _
``could be the death knell of the whole bill'' because
</P>
<P>
   it exacts such a great toll, said Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said if cigarette companies started going under, the
nation would be deprived of billions of dollars of tobacco revenues
that could go towards trying to con vince teens not to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   If the companies began closing, McCain said, 40 million adult
Americans would still find ways to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'd be a Marlboro, or a Camel or another operating out of
Mexico, El Salvador or whatever, and they
</P>
<P>
   would be exporting cigarettes into the United States which we
would not have nearly as much control over,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   There was some good news on the tobacco bill for McCain on
Tuesday. The Senate approved his amendment to add $3 billion
</P>
<P>
   in funding for veterans' tobacco-related health-care costs.
Veterans' groups have been angered at Congress for recently taking
away a $17 billion benefit program for former service members who
contracted smoking-related ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Debate o n the tobacco bill is scheduled to resume Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders said they feared the Republican majority was
losing interest in the bill; as evidence, they cited the Senate's
willingness to move on to other Senate business Tuesday while
</P>
<P>
   the tobacco measure was still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said the message seemed to
be, ``If Democrats behave, we'll probably be able to come back to
tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is out of session Wednesday so that membe rs may
attend the late Arizona Sen. Barry Goldwater's funeral in Tempe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at 202-662-7264 or via e-mail at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
