<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLANKENHORN-PROFILE-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF THE MORAL BASIS OF SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Miss., Mass.)   (mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From time to time in years past, David Blankenhorn's
grandmother would call him from Birmingham, Ala., to ask whether he
had found a job yet. He would patiently explain that he was in New
York running a group that promoted the importance of the family and
of fatherhood, but she never really got it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could always tell that she was thinking, `He gets paid to do
this?' '' he said last week. ``It was just so obvious to her that
it never occurred to her that it was necessary. So she always said,
`Good boy, you'll do fine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, 10 years after Blankenhorn willed the group into
existence, the Institute for American Values seems an improbable
venture, calmly searching for the moral truths of society from a
small office suite on the furious gyre of Columbus Circle. Its
name, which Blankenhorn concedes is both corny and grandiose,
sounds more like the academic offshoot of the Christian Coalition
than the brainchild of a 43-year-old former Vista volunteer and
liberal organizer.
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, the institute has achieved considerable mainstream
success in the last few years, taking pro-family arguments once
made only by the religious right and making them palatable for the
center and even a few academic leftists.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after two years of effort, 24 prominent professors,
politicians, and community activists from across the spectrum
signed a new report issued by the institute that is likely to
stimulate debate. The report, entitled ``A Call to Civil Society:
Why Democracy Needs Moral Truths,'' is the group's most ambitious
effort to date, making 41 recommendations to various segments of
society to reverse what it calls the nation's growing inequality
and moral depletion.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations are for the most part centered around the
idea of strengthening the married couple as the basic unit of child
rearing. To that end, the report calls on government to make
divorce more difficult to achieve and tax codes more supportive of
marriage. It supports giving a preference on welfare benefits to
married couples, making work places more flexible for parents and
reducing violence and sexual content on television during the
first, ``family hour'' of prime time. It also advocates more
emphasis on arts education, incentives to give more charitable
donations to anti-poverty groups and an end to state lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these ideas come from conservative groups like Focus on
the Family, while others are supported by liberal advocates. Few of
those who worked on and signed the report are known as flaming
ideologues; most are centrists, grappling like Blankenhorn for the
kind of ideological synthesis he began to develop years ago while
pondering why most Americans believe their country is in moral
decline.
</P>
<P>
   The chairwoman of the group that prepared the report was Jean
Bethke Elshtain, the University of Chicago ethics professor. Other
members included Cornel West, professor of religion and
Afro-American studies at Harvard; Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind.; and John
Atlas, executive director of the Passaic County, N.J., Legal Aid
Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great majorities of Americans feel we are on the wrong track,
that the institutions of civil society are getting weaker,'' said
Blankenhorn, who lives with his wife and three children on the
Upper West Side of Manhattan. ``At one time, only religious zealots
would talk about this, and it's still kind of countercultural to
assert that it's possible to have some shared moral understandings.
But we believe that it's not only possible, but necessary.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Blankenhorn, as one of his friends put it, tends to amble
through a sentence, a residue of his upbringing in Jackson, Miss.,
more prominent than any remaining accent. Friends say his courtly
willingness to listen to a person's argument and find a common
ground with others has helped him hold together disparate groups
like the most recent panel. His institute gets its $600,000 budget
from a variety of donors.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he has also deliberately avoided the most
rupturing flash points: There is no mention in the report of
abortion or gay rights. (He says he is personally wary of
legislation that extends benefits to same-sex partners, believing
that the mother-father relationship is the best way to raise
children.)
</P>
<P>
   His quest for the moral basis of society came after graduating
from Harvard and working several years as a community volunteer in
the Boston area, railing against high utility rates and organizing
low-income residents to fight City Hall. After seeing firsthand the
effect on children of single-mother families, he began writing
articles on the importance of traditional fatherhood, and spent
three years fruitlessly knocking on doors, trying to get centrist
and liberal academics interested in families.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1989, he put together the first of several
conferences on the subject, beginning to popularize the notion of a
more civil society that was not necessarily based on divine
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Blankenhorn's critics often say that he is too rigid in his
conception of the ideal family, but they acknowledge that his
advocacy of fatherhood has pushed the debate beyond the usual
polarizing arguments. He says he will be satisfied if he can get a
few citizens thinking about the obligations of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it doesn't come across as finger-pointing, like some
kind of national catechism,'' he said. ``We don't think anyone has
perfect access to the truth, or a complete understanding of it, but
we do believe that moral truths really exist. And it shouldn't be
taboo to think so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
