u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-AUCTION-320&AMP;AD     06-02 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-AUCTION-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S WEEKLY DEBT-AUCTION FACES AN ESPECIALLY TOUGH SELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-ECON) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Raising the money it needs each week to pay off
debt that is coming due and fund its persistent budget deficit has
always been a tricky proposition for Russia, given the nation's
tumultuous political and economic climate.
</P>
<P>
   But the job will be particularly difficult on Wednesday, when
the government needs to raise about $1.2 billion from the financial
markets in the face of near-panic among domestic and foreign
investors about Russia's ability to maintain the value of its
currency and honor all its debts.
</P>
<P>
   The government has failed in its three previous weekly debt
auctions to raise all the cash it needs, and economists said it
remained unclear whether Wednesday's auction would go any better.
Although sky-high interest rates and the possibility of additional
aid for Russia from the International Monetary Fund have somewhat
reassured investors, economists and market analysts said Russia
might once again be able to sell only a portion of bonds it is
offering. That would force the government to dip into its skimpy
financial reserves to pay off its creditors, deepening the sense of
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has been pressing domestic banks and
investors to buy the bonds as a sign of confidence in Russia's
prospects. There were some reports on Tuesday that domestic
investors, who are required to place money in escrow with the
government the day before an auction if they want a chance to bid,
had made bigger-than-expected deposits on Tuesday, suggesting that
demand for the bonds could be better than expected. But analysts
said that with the situation so unsettled it was difficult to
predict any quick end to the financial turbulence, especially if
foreign investors remain wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be another volatile day,'' said Dmitry Chernyak,
a Russia specialist at Merrill Lynch in London. ``I don't see a lot
of foreign investors returning to the market at this point.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russia's main vehicle for raising money on its domestic
financial markets is a type of bond, known as a GKO, that matures
in less than a year. The country has about $60 billion in GKOs
outstanding, and because of the bonds' relatively short durations
the government is forced into a weekly scramble to redeem them and
refinance the debt. Investors demand short maturities to minimize
the risks of the ruble's being sharply devalued, eroding the return
on the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   By most estimates, as much as a third of the GKOs are held by
foreign investors, with Russian banks holding most of the rest. The
crisis in Asia had made foreign investors skittish about investing
in developing economies even before Russia's latest woes erupted.
And since the Russian stock market began falling and the currency
started coming under pressure, foreign investors have been pulling
their money out of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   To make ruble-denominated investments more attractive and prop
up the currency's value, the Russian central bank has pushed up the
short-term interest rates it controls to 150 percent. The tactic
has succeeded in maintaining the ruble's value so far.
</P>
<P>
   But between the government-controlled interest rates and the
rates set by the market _ including those on the GKO bonds, which
are currently around 65 percent _ Russia's interest costs threaten
to soar out of control. Nearly a third of the government's
expenditures this year are projected to go to making interest
payments (the comparable figure in the United States is about 14
percent), and that projection is based on an assumption that GKO
rates will decline to around 35 percent, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If interest rates remain high it exacerbates the budget
problem and puts them in effect in a debt trap,'' said Desmond
Lachman, the head of emerging market economic research at Salomon
Smith Barney, the investment firm in New York. ``It's imperative
that they get interest rates down quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   If rates remained at their current levels for the rest of the
year, the budget deficit would be around 8 percent of gross
domestic product, compared with the 5 percent target agreed to last
week by the IMF and Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, according to
Erik Nielsen, an economist at Goldman Sachs in London.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, who met with Kiriyenko on Monday in Moscow as part of a
delegation of Western bankers, said Russia plans to try to lessen
its dependence on the domestic GKO market by issuing more bonds
denominated in dollars and other currencies through financial
markets in Europe. He said Russia now hopes to raise as much as $6
billion this year on the European markets, up from $3.5 billion
under a previous plan.
</P>
<P>
   Russia will need to finance the redemption of around $50 billion
in debt this year, Nielsen said. But if there is good news for the
government, it is that the redemptions are fairly evenly spaced out
through the rest of the year, giving the Finance Ministry and the
central bank an opportunity to work out a solution on the run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
