<SLUG> BC-BBO-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS GAMBLE ON DREW, SLUGGER PHILLIES COULDN'T SIGN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the fifth pick in the first round of baseball's annual
draft, the St. Louis Cardinals gambled on Tuesday by selecting J.D.
Drew, the college outfielder whom the Philadelphia Phillies were
unable to sign in the past year. Unfortunately for the Cardinals,
they did not hear from Drew the sentiment expressed by the Mets'
first-round choice, Jason Tyner. Asked if he might be represented
by Scott Boras, Drew's agent and the No. 1 scourge of major league
clubs, Tyner said: ``Scott Boras doesn't fit my personality at all.
I don't fit that. I feel honored the Mets drafted me and I don't
want to hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyner is a 21-year-old center fielder from Texas A&AMP;M by way of
Beaumont, Texas. The Mets made him the 21st player drafted, and he
was followed three picks later by Andy Brown, an 18-year-old
Richmond, Ind., high school outfielder whom the Yankees selected.
The Phillies, who made Drew the No. 2 pick last year, drafted first
this time and took Pat Burrell, a third baseman from the University
of Miami, whom they projected as a first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited the Yankees picked me,'' Brown, who batted
.466, said by telephone from his home. ``They were my first choice.
I knew they were showing a lot of interest. I was really hoping
they would pick me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyner, a .384 hitter with 37 stolen bases, was equally excited.
``It's a dream come true for me,'' he said from his home. ``New
York is an unbelievable place for baseball. They love their
baseball there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his plan was to sign as quickly as possible. He had
someone who has been advising him, he said, and wasn't sure he
would hire an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs in recent years have found Boras so difficult to negotiate
with that many shun his clients. Five players who had been
projected as first-round picks Tuesday were not because of the
perception that Boras will represent them.
</P>
<P>
   Representing Drew, who has started his second season as a
professional with the Saint Paul Saints of the independent Northern
League, Boras demanded a $10-million signing bonus in negotiations
with the Phillies until the last day they were eligible to sign the
outfielder. The agent finally reduced the asking price to $7
million, but the Phillies rejected the proposal, raising their
overall offer but sticking to their $2.6-million signing bonus that
was in line with the going rate for high first-round choices last
year. Matt Anderson, a college pitcher who was the No. 1 pick,
signed with Detroit for a $2,505,000 bonus, a record for a drafted
player. Walt Jocketty, the St. Louis general manager, said the
Cardinals drafted Drew with their eyes open, having spoken with
Boras as recently as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were probably three guys for sure, maybe four, we keyed
on in the draft,'' Jocketty said by telephone from St. Louis.
``When we saw they were going to be selected ahead of us, we
decided to go with Drew. We just felt J.D. Drew is one of the best
players in the draft. He has the ability to play in the big leagues
soon. We decided we'd draft him and do the very best to sign him.
The ceiling is high on this guy and sometimes you have to take some
risks to succeed.'' His exploratory chat with Boras, Jocketty
added, went as expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of restated his position,'' Jocketty said. ``We look
at it this way. He has a chance to play in a good organization, one
of the most storied organizations in baseball, one with a lot of
Hall of Famers and one of the most prolific home run hitters of all
time. There are a lot of things we think we can use to sell him on
playing here.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Jocketty said, he knew of two other teams he
wouldn't identify that were prepared to draft Drew, who in his
first four games with St. Paul this season hit .583 with a .917
slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The general manager, who last year pulled off an unexpected coup
by signing Mark McGwire to a multiyear contract, said the Cardinals
had internally discussed at length the cost of signing Drew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'd rather not divulge what we've discussed,'' he
said. ``It's something we have to talk to them about first. But
we're well aware of what the situation is.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the Cardinals fare no better than the Phillies? The club
had three other picks in the first 55 selections, Jocketty said,
seeing that as a consolation.
</P>
<P>
   Among other first-round picks, the San Diego Padres took Sean
Burroughs, a high school third baseman, whose father, Jeff, was the
American League most valuable player in 1974, and the Minnesota
Twins selected Ryan Mills, an Arizona State pitcher, whose father,
Dick, pitched in two games for the Boston Red Sox in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had wanted to draft Mark Teixeira, a high school
third baseman from Maryland, but in their talks with him on Monday
night, they could not induce him to commit to signing for a bonus
in the $1.5-million range. He wanted about $500,000 more. Teixeira,
who had been projected to go higher than Brown, is believed to be
one of those players whom Boras will advise.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Yankees failed to sign their No. 1 pick, Tyrel
Godwin, an outfielder, who opted to go to the University of North
Carolina. The Yankees offered Godwin $1.9 million; he sought $2.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
