u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBIN-ECON-450&AMP;ADD-NY     06-02 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-ECON-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN CRISIS COULD SPREAD TO OTHER COUNTRIES, U.S. OFFICIAL
WARNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin warned on Tuesday
that unless Russia's financial crisis is resolved, its economic
troubles ``could spread to Central Europe,'' placing two major
regions _ Asia and Europe _ in simultaneous downturns.
</P>
<P>
   In his first statement since President Clinton said on Sunday
that the United States would support an international bailout of
Russia, Rubin chose his comments carefully to avoid worsening the
flight from Russian and Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be fair to say that the situation facing the
world today with respect to financial stability is unprecedented,''
Rubin told a group of executives on a presidential export council.
``Russia's a difficult situation. We have an obvious national
security interest. There is also the risk, once again, of contagion
that could spread to Central Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin has a clear political agenda: He has been trying for
months to convince a skeptical Congress to increase Washington's
contributions to the International Monetary Fund by $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He has met enormous resistance, with conservatives saying the
fund interferes in free markets and liberals contending that it is
saving wealthy investors by imposing austerity programs that make
ordinary workers suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Both Rubin and his deputy, Lawrence Summers, argue that Russia's
latest crisis underscores the urgency of adding to the fund's war
chest. U.S. officials have said that if an aid package is put
together for Russia, it would have to come from the IMF and the
World Bank, not directly from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rubin's warning on Tuesday seems in stark
contrast to his recent predictions that another major outbreak of
trouble was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks ago Rubin told the Foreign Policy Association in New
York, ``The probability of the crisis worsening or spreading, or of
a major new crisis developing, is low.'' He said essentially the
same thing to Congress several weeks earlier, though some top aides
winced at the time and declined to make the same prediction
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, in a brief telephone conversation, Rubin said his
earlier statements referred to ``a systemic crisis that could have
a material impact on our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In his public comments Tuesday, he reiterated his belief that
while the U.S. trade deficit would rise ``substantially'' this
year, the overall impact on the economy ``has been relatively
minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a world right now where the only healthy economy,
growing on a sustained basis, is the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration's concern, however, is that if economic
contagion spreads beyond Asia, it will become harder and harder to
insulate the United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the heart of that issue _ and of Rubin's comments on Tuesday
_ is the question of how economic troubles in one part of the world
worsen troubles elsewhere, a little-studied subject that has
suddenly become a top challenge in U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Some links are clear-cut. Southeast Asia's troubles, which began
last summer, are being reignited by Japan's worsening recession,
and in particular by the steady fall of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is a major purchaser of Asian goods, so its downturn is an
enormous weight on the region. The yen's fall only aggravates the
problem, because it puts competitive pressure on other nations to
let their currencies fall so the goods they make retain a price
advantage over Japanese goods in other markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question,'' one senior administration official
said recently, ``that if Japan turned around, the picture would
look very different throughout Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   More tenuous is the connection between Asia's troubles and
Russia's. Many view the link as primarily psychological: Investors
are fleeing all emerging markets, regardless of their differences.
In recent days, investors have not only fled Russia; they have
gotten out of Brazil, Turkey and other, smaller markets. Each
country has its own problems, but they are worsened whenever
investors get skittish and flee to the relative safety of the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia's case, the alarm bells are ringing in Washington, but
not with enormous urgency. Deputy finance ministers from the
world's largest industrial countries meet in Paris next week to
discuss their next moves. Officials say it will probably take
several weeks to put together a package of loans or emergency
credits through the IMF, the World Bank and other international
institutions. And the aid they are considering _ about $10 billion
_ is about a quarter of what was promised to Indonesia, and a fifth
of what was promised to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the plan for now. In both South Korea and
Indonesia, the size of the problem increased dramatically while the
fund and its member states negotiated over what to do. The same
could easily happen with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are talking weeks, you are talking the vast
unknown,'' one senior official in an international institution
dealing with Russia said on Tuesday. ``Several weeks is a very,
very long time in the markets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
