<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DONKING-COX     06-02 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONKING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Promotor has more pressing matters than Holyfield-Akinwande
fight
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Midway through a news conference, a member of the
promotional team let out a sarcastic snore while the stand-in for
Don King delivered a string of words with unparalleled dryness.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. The promotion for the Evander Holyfield-Henry
Akinwande heavyweight-title fight Saturday lacks so much zip,
people Tuesday actually found themselves missing Don King.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is, at least that news conference was a lot
shorter,'' Madison Square Garden executive Paul Munick, the
surrogate King, said later. ``If Don was here, he'd still be
talking.''
</P>
<P>
   King wasn't at the Garden, which is at least part of the reason
ticket sales have been slow and the pay-per-view telecast is
shaping up as another splash of red ink for Showtime. The promoter
was four miles away, sitting in a Manhattan federal courtroom, for
a re-trial on insurance fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   King's attorneys want him focused on the trial, not the fight
card, and they certainly don't want him in a room filled with media
members. It follows that when fight officials asked attorneys about
King's availability for the news conference, the answer was, ``No.
We want him in a controlled environment.''
</P>
<P>
   King has been reduced to mute by legal advisers recently, and it
could not come at a worse time. He is 66 years old and has been
worn down by a number of lawsuits and defections, including, but
not limited to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Tyson lost his boxing license after his infamous
ear-biting incident, stripping King of his greatest source of
income. King earned a significant percentage of Tyson's $140
million in six fights after his release from prison, and also cut
deals with the MGM and Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tyson is suing King for $100 million deals and is trying to
get out of his deal with the promoter, which has four fights
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   _ Holyfield, King's second-biggest income source, figures to
retire after two or three more fights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Welterweight champion Felix Trinidad is reported to be near
the end of his deal with King and might defect to rival Bob Arum,
who also promotes Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   _ King's partnership with British promoter Frank Warren ended in
a blur of lawsuits. When Warren left, King lost his financial ties
to rising featherweight ``Prince'' Naseem Hamed, one of boxing's
few draws.
</P>
<P>
   _ MGM ended its affiliation with King after the Holyfield-Tyson
II post-fight riot.
</P>
<P>
   And this week is not going well. Carl King, Don's son, showed up
late for Tuesday's news conference and left in a huff after
Akinwande's manager, J.C. Courreges, complained about the lack of a
private car.
</P>
<P>
   Carl King then took a shot at Munick's toastmaster abilities. He
said his father is ``frustrated he can't be here, but he can leave
the promotion in the hands of some very capable people. They're
just not up there, he said, pointing to the dais. Asked why he
didn't run the news conference, Carl King said, ``I don't know,''
then left the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Munick said, ``I don't know why he came late, and I don't know
why he's upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Munick concedes that Don King's absence hurts the show and added
that he would have thought twice about the Garden guaranteeing a
significant site fee _ reported to be more than $2.5 million _ if
he knew King's trial would last this long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have Don King here, doing what he does best,
promoting an event,'' he said. ``Say what you want about Don, with
the fraud trial and everything, but there's nobody better at what
he does. He's out there. He's pitching. By the end of the week,
he's kissing rabbis and priests and sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   Munick said King might drop by the Garden on Friday, an off day
for the trial. In the mean time, there are plans today to bring
Holyfield to the Broadway set of ``Lion King,'' to Belmont on
Thursday to pose with Triple Crown candidate Real Quiet and to the
Letterman show Friday.
</P>
<P>
   King, who has survived a manslaughter conviction and other legal
entanglements, figures to be in court for another two weeks. The
end of his promotional reign has been forecast before, particularly
when Tyson was in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But then millions of dollars flowed into his pocket when Tyson
re-signed, and King bellowed, ``I have risen from the media pallet
of death.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, he is only comatose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
