<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home values in U.S. increasing, as reported in different surveys
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Depending on whose figures you read, home values in
the United States were up either 5.7 percent or 9.1 percent in the
first quarter, compared with the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   A report issued by Experian RES, an Anaheim, Calif.-based real
estate data collector, said values were up 9.1 percent, a peak for
the decade. However, a quarterly report issued Tuesday by Freddie
Mac said the nation's annualized rate of home-value appreciation
was 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difference is how appreciation is calculated.
Experian uses sales prices of the same houses in metro areas, while
Freddie Mac tracks both sales and appraisals by region.
</P>
<P>
   During most of the 1990s, the average, year-to-year increase has
been 2.5 percent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Experian has Northern California cities leading the pack with
double-digit appreciation, and cities like Baltimore and Hartford,
Conn., actually losing value.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta houses appreciated at a 2.2 percent year-to-year rate,
ranking 31st among 38 cities on Experian's list.
</P>
<P>
   In the Freddie Mac report, South Atlantic states were the
leaders at 7.6 percent annualized appreciation, with the Pacific
states _ including California _ second at 6.8 percent. Data on
individual metropolitan areas were not given.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Levent, president of Metro Brokers/Better Homes and
Gardens, tends to believe the Freddie Mac figures, based on what is
going on in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen 5 percent to 6 percent increases in sales prices,
and our business stays pretty constant in the 15-county metro
area,'' said Levent, though he acknowledged that Experian's method
of tracking appreciation is valid.
</P>
<P>
   So why does Atlanta's rate look low compared with Oakland,
Calif., on the Experian report?
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is a good housing market, said Nima Nattaugh, Experian's
research director, but some of its statistical oomph comes from new
houses that do not have a resale track record.
</P>
<P>
   Northern California, on the other hand, has a resale housing
market whose valuation is driven by short supply and long demand
caused by jobs in the high-technology industry. In Southern
California, where houses lost value earlier in the 1990s, ``the
growth rates are high, but the recovery we are seeing is regaining
lost ground,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
