</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-FINAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulls try underdog tactic
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salt Lake City, Utah _ In pursuit of their sixth championship in
eight years, the Chicago Bulls have decided to redefine themselves
as underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure's not on us,'' Chicago's Scottie Pippen said
Tuesday. ``No one's expecting us to win. Everybody's expecting the
Jazz to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls are listed as a 6-5 pick to win another NBA
championship, even though the Utah Jazz has homecourt advantage and
is a slight favorite in Game I tonight at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year (the pressure) was on us, and this year it's not,''
Pippen said. ``There's no pressure on us. It's a different feeling.
We've never (before) been in a situation where we were written
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls' motivation this year is ``to prove everybody wrong,''
Pippen said. ``Everybody's predicting that the Jazz, having the
home court, will win the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah forward Karl Malone isn't buying the Bulls' message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a little bit of their Game 7 against Indiana (on
Sunday), and I heard Judd Buechler say they were underdogs,''
Malone said in a cynical tone of voice. ``Yeah, right.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said that, no matter what the Bulls say, Chicago's
Michael Jordan summed it for him: ``After everybody said everything
they said, Michael said, 'But we have heart.' That's all I needed
to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They find a way to win, so I don't listen to that stuff,''
Utah guard John Stockton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have relied on home-court advantage during four of the
six championship runs. In 1993, they beat Phoenix in six games
after the Suns compiled the best record in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has never played in an NBA Finals in which he did not
emerge as the series' most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   So, even though the Bulls are trying to play the underdog role,
they still have many of the same players who won the 1997 title by
defeating Utah in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still consider us to be the champions,'' Jordan said. ``They
still have to take that away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jordan, there are new challenges for his team.
``We've got to prove we can win on the road,'' Jordan said. ``They
beat us twice in the season, here, in our building. Their hunger
may be stronger than ours. People say maybe it's Utah's year. We
battle age, experiencing this so many times in terms of losing
focus in pressure moments. So, we look at it as though the
pressure's not really on us. . . . But we like our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
