<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-COX     06-02 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA Finals Notebook
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY , Utah _ The Utah Jazz know how close they came
to beating the Bulls in the Finals a year go, losing the first game
84-82 at the end when Karl Malone threw up bricks at the foul line,
losing the fifth game when Michael Jordan, weakened by an attack of
food poisoning, scored 38 points, including the game winner in a
90-88 war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there. The door was open,'' Chris Morris said Monday,
``but we closed the door in our own faces.''
</P>
<P>
   One to grow on means a lot, Malone said. ``In life you rarely
have an opportunity to correct something. The chance never comes
back or maybe it's two, three, four years down the road. But to
have an opportunity the next year to correct something you didn't
finish last time, I'm excited. It's not supposed to work out like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dennis Rodman was a fraud in last season's Finals, insulting
the Mormon religion, spending off days in Las Vegas during the week
the Bulls resided at a Park City ski resort and commuted 45 minutes
into town for games and practices.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan says he only hopes Rodman will temper his love of the
good life this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure Dennis is thinking about how he didn't perform
as he wanted to last year (2.7 ppg., 7.7 rebounds, 5 of 20
shooting). Hopefully, that's motivation within itself. Vegas being
so close, I don't think he can really control his appetite. I just
want to make sure his appetite doesn't impede our objectives in
winning a title. I can't tell Dennis not to be Dennis, but all we
can ask Dennis is to be Dennis on the basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Bulls are not staying in Park City this time around, but
in a local hotel where Jordan says he will spend most of
non-basketball time, living off room service. ``I won't eat pizza,
though.'' It was pizza that allegedly made him ill last June.
</P>
<P>
   _ Once again Monday, Jordan distanced himself from coach Phil
Jackson's future with the Bulls. Nor will winning or losing in this
series influence his decision. ``If my hunger and my excitement for
the game continues at the end of the season, win, lose or draw,
I'll continue to play,'' he said. ``You can't win every time at the
end of the season. You lose a game, does that stick with me? Does
that drive me crazy? No. I can deal with that. That's part of the
game. I just don't want to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The way to beat Chicago entails more than simply stopping
Jordan, Jazz coach Jerry Sloan said. ``The big thing is stay
between him and the basket and that's a more difficult assignment
than it sounds. You have 50 percent chance he's gonna miss it.
Don't increase that by fouls, second shots. Those things are the
big difference. You become so concerned with everything going on
that you fail to rebound, block out, and then you turn over the
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your concentration can't be to the point where you only try to
stop Michael Jordan. You also have to defend the four other guys
and that's fundamental basketball. He's gonna score 40, 50.
Everybody knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
