</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERMOSILLO DEAL MAKES SENSE FOR MLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlos Hermosillo's allocation last week to the Los Angeles
Galaxy makes sense on so many levels that it's difficult to
envision the griping that has accompanied the move as anything more
than sour grapes.
</P>
<P>
   That would be in error, of course: How are supporters, or
executives, or even players of the Dallas Burn, the Tampa Bay
Mutiny or the San Jose Clash supposed to react when the most
talented team in Major League Soccer pulls off such a coup? The
rich get richer, and the poor wail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to June 27 when Carlos Hermosillo plays
here in Spartan Stadium,'' San Jose Clash president Peter
Bridgwater said when the news got out. ``I want to kick his ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridgwater, a fiery Englishman, has good reasons for that. He
pursued Hermosillo for more than a year, and the Mexican striker
nearly signed a deal last fall that would have sent him to the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   That fell through, and MLS officials had no hope of luring the
33-year-old star north of the border until a deal that would have
sent him to Guadalajara broke down during last week's Mexican
League ``draft'' in Acapulco. That left an opening that Deputy
Commissioner Sunil Gulati quickly filled, engineering a complicated
agreement among MLS, Hermosillo, the Mexican player's former club
(Cruz Azul) and Necaxa, for whom he will play once the Galaxy's
season is over.
</P>
<P>
   That he ended up in Los Angeles was the work of his wife, who
insisted that if the Hermosillo family was heading to America, it
would make its home in Southern California, where some of her
family resides.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else seemed to fit, too: The Galaxy was owed an
allocation from the Jorge Campos trade in January; it needed a
Mexican to boost sagging attendance; and it had been pursuing
Mexican strikers since before the season kicked off two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dallas Burn remains a team without stars, Tampa
Bay a team without wins, and San Jose has to endure the loss of
Hermosillo to its chief rival, the announcement of which upstaged
its signing of Mexican veteran Francisco Uribe, also last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   All three of those sides
</P>
<P>
   teams are league-owned, and they have too often been overlooked
as teams with big-moneyed ``investor-operators'' reap the lion's
share of talent. Dallas has built one of the best teams in MLS with
little help from the league; Tampa Bay is still reeling from the
league's decision to move star playmaker Carlos Valderrama to
Miami; and the Clash learned long ago it must take a back seat to
its southern neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The whole affair raises questions about MLS's single-entity
structure, designed in part to create parity or at least a level
playing field among the 12 teams. Is it fair that a team as strong
as the Galaxy, which was 10-1 when Hermosillo agreed to the deal,
is given one of the most significant allocations in league history?
</P>
<P>
   It's not as easy a question to answer as it may appear. MLS
officials understand their teams in Los Angeles and New York must
be successful, on the field and at the gate. The Galaxy's on-field
record has not led to increased attention at the Rose Bowl they
averaged 17,057 in the four home games sandwiched between the
opener and Hermosillo's signing and what was missing, General
Manager Danny Villanueva says, were Mexican fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've definitely seen, especially through the Mexican (League)
playoffs, a turning of attention in Los Angeles,'' Villanueva
noted. ``The Latin crowd (at the Rose Bowl) is largely Central
American. ... I don't think there's a player able to attract
Southern California soccer fans the way Carlos Hermosillo can. We
expect a jump (in attendance).''
</P>
<P>
   How much, he won't say, but 33 percent sounds fair. The Galaxy
should, once Hermosillo arrives, get crowds in the 28,000-30,000
range, maybe more. Hermosillo is the third-leading active
goalscorer in world soccer, with 275 goals in 457 games. That he
was overlooked for Mexico's World Cup team has been heavily
criticized on both sides of the border, making him somewhat of a
martyr. That will compute here in ways it couldn't elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Is that favoritism for the Galaxy or smart business?
</P>
<P>
   The rich do get richer, but whose fault is that? The Galaxy
traded away two of its biggest stars Campos and Eduardo Hurtado and
still won. Of what's left of L.A.'s stars, only Cobi Jones and
Mauricio Cienfuegos likely were coveted by many other teams, and
while they are enjoying their best MLS seasons, so are several
others: Brazilian speedster Welton, the league scoring leader;
Clint Mathis, the clear rookie of the year choice
</P>
<P>
   Martin Machon, who quietly does as he pleases on the left flank;
and Ezra Hendrickson, who has emerged as a solid attacking
defender.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Jones, Cienfuegos and maybe Welton, these are role
players; why should the Galaxy be penalized because they're all
doing well?
</P>
<P>
   There's another view on all this, one that sounds reasonable
even if it a bit far-fetched. MLS wants a strong Galaxy because it
wants the Galaxy in the MLS Cup final, which will be played at the
Rose Bowl. If the Galaxy's there, they figure 100,000 show up. If
someone else, say Dallas or San Jose, represents the West, maybe
40,000 show. A full house might sway Disney, which reportedly has
backed off from its desire to bring a team to Anaheim, to invest in
the league and purchase a team. And that, you have to figure, would
help everyone involved in MLS.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX
</P>
<P>
   Now that Hermosillo is headed for L.A., what happens with German
star Juergen Klinsmann, who appeared likely to be Rose Bowl-bound
when the World Cup ends.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has no foreign slot open, and Hermosillo's contract
no terms announced, but he's got to be making the $236,000 max
slices heavily into L.A.'s salary-cap space. And why would the
Galaxy need another
</P>
<P>
   aging forward?
</P>
<P>
   Odds are, MLS will try to sway Klinsmann if he decides to come
to MLS to Chicago, where he'd be embraced by Chicagoland's German
community. But Klinsmann owns property in Orange County, and his
wife is from San Diego; what if he tells the league that he'll play
only if he can stay in Southern California?
</P>
<P>
   In that event, the Galaxy would have to jettison one of ther
foreigners, Cienfuegos, Machon, Hermosillo, Welton or Wellington
Sanchez. Sanchez, who hasn't made an impact yet, seems the
likeliest, but if he turns out to be the player he's been rumored
to be, that decision won't be so simple.
</P>
<P>
   Cien is L.A.'s most popular player, a Salvadoran legend whose
influence on the Galaxy is incalculable. Machon, a Guatemalan,
would be tough to replace on the field and at the gate. Hermosillo
stands to be the Galaxy's biggest attraction. And Welton has become
one of MLS's premier forwards, and he's only 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
