<HEADLINE>
CENTENARIANS DON'T FUSS ABOUT 100 DEGREES 
</HEADLINE>
 DEGREES-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA HELSER   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - So what's all this fuss about hitting 100?
</P>
<P>
   For days, experts have been predicting the triple-digit event,
but until Tuesday the century mark had been an elusive no-show for
Phoenix. The temperature finally hit 100 at 2:34 p.m. _ and peaked
at 101 three minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as Atta Reynolds and Paul M. Pair are concerned,
hitting 100 was a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds turned 100 more than a year ago and Pair reached the
century mark in March. And together they awaited the 100-degree
breakthrough together Tuesday, as th ey licked ice cream cones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to turning 100 (years old) and it didn't make
any difference to me,'' said Reynolds, sporting a knitted sweater
vest. ``So what? I'm a 100!''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't care about the rising temperature, ei ther.
</P>
<P>
   But Phoenix was a little more excited about hitting the century
mark. Rarely had it taken so long to accomplish that feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only was this the 8th coolest spring since we've been
keeping records for the last 102 years, but the re have only been
11 other times when it's been this late to reach 100,'' said Craig
Ellis, meteorologist for the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   On an average, the temperature reaches 100 on May 14.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who turned 100 more than a year
</P>
<P>
   ago, said she refuses to fret over age or heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the buildings are refrigerated, all the homes are
refrigerated and so are all the cars,'' said the Phoenix resident,
who arrived here in 1936 and whose son is a meteorologist in
Colorado . ``You shouldn't worry about the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Now living at Beatitudes Campus of Care, Reynolds remembers a
time when the Valley wasn't quite so cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to sleep out in the yard, it was so hot. But I
never worried about it,''
</P>
<P>
   she said. ``I loved to work out in the yard all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the prospect of a long, hot summer trouble Pair, who
has lived in Phoenix since 1977, and also resides at Beatitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat doesn't bother me and the older I get th e less it
bothers me,'' Pair said. ``I don't understand it. I can't explain
it, but I'm just real happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Hamilton, medical director for Beatitudes may have an
explanation. As the body ages, the mechanisms that keep it in
</P>
<P>
   balance aren't as finely tuned as they once were.
</P>
<P>
   ``So although your body doesn't tolerate extreme heat that well,
the heat doesn't bother you that much because you don't feel it
like you used to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherwise, Ellis is hap py to predict cooler days ahead, at
least for the next few.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have another 100-degree day,'' he said, ``until at
least into next week at the earliest.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's no getting off the weather hook.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Craig sai d, the Valley can expect approximately 90
days of 100-degree temperatures or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least that's the average,'' he said. ``But nobody knows how
many we'll have this year for sure.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Linda Helser can be reached at 444-8243 or at
Linda.Helser(at)PNI.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
