</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORANGE-COUNTY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH AGREES TO $400 MILLION SETTLEMENT WITH ORANGE
COUNTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ORANGE-COUNTY-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(JT) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   with LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. agreed Tuesday to pay $400
million to Orange County, Calif., to settle claims that the leading
Wall Street brokerage firm helped push the affluent county into
bankruptcy four years ago with reckless investment advice.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement will largely close the book on the largest
municipal bankruptcy in the nation's history, which shook the
foundations of the municipal bond market, a basic way that towns
and cities across the country finance services such public schools
and roads.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement by Merrill is one of the largest for any
securities-related litigation and is by far the largest stemming
from the 1994 Orange County bankruptcy, which set off a storm of
litigation as the county sought to recover some of the more than
$1.6 billion it suffered in losses from risky investments.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill, which has consistently maintained it did nothing wrong,
said it decided to settle because the costs and distraction of the
litigation did not justify the battle. But the magnitude of the
settlement was still considered surprisingly huge and goes a long
way to restoring much of what Orange County lost.
</P>
<P>
   The county still has lawsuits pending against more than a dozen
Wall Street securities houses and a variety of other companies. But
Merrill Lynch was clearly the county's main target, since it was
much more heavily involved than other companies in selling risky
securities to the county-run investment pool.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Merrill Lynch has settled, attorneys predicted, others
will follow suit. ''We're very pleased with the result,'' said
Bruce Bennett, a Los Angeles attorney who has represented Orange
County. ``We think it represents a very substantial recovery for
Orange County.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement with Merrill Lynch brings the county's total
recovery from legal settlements to more than $621 million. Analysts
and other attorneys said that based on Tuesday's settlement with
Merrill Lynch, they expect the county could end up recovering
nearly $1 billion overall out of a total of more than $1.6 billion
lost.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not a disaster for the county, an affluent area
south of Los Angeles, which has a thriving technology industry,
tourist attractions including Disneyland and an unemployment rate
below 3 percent. A boom in California's economy has largely
restored the social services that were cut immediately after the
bankruptcy. Municipal officials said the money recovered will
probably go mainly toward restoring capital spending plans that had
been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more part of Orange County's history than its
future,'' said James Doti, president of Chapman University, which
is in the county. ``The economy of Orange County is doing great.
But this cloud of bankruptcy has been hanging over our head. This
is the last page of an ugly story.''
</P>
<P>
   The losses were suffered by 200 school districts, municipalities
and other public agencies that invested in the pool that was run by
Robert Citron, Orange County's treasurer at the time, who was
released last October after serving two thirds of a one-year term
in jail. His deputy, Matthew Raabe, was sentenced to three years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Because the money recovered from litigation goes preferentially
to schools and then the other public agencies and municipalities,
school districts have already recovered 98 percent of their losses,
said Paul Brady, city manager of Irvine and chairman of the Orange
County Investment Pool Committee. Municipalities and other agencies
will be able to recover more than 90 percent of their losses after
getting the proceeds from the settlement with Merrill, But the
county itself is only now starting to share in the recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, one of the largest firms on Wall Street, has
argued that it had not done anything wrong and that the risky
investments that went sour were the decisions of Citron.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that we acted properly and professionally in
our relationship with Orange County,'' Merrill Lynch said in a
statement issued Tuesday. ``However, after weighing the substantial
costs and distraction of continuing to litigate, we determined that
it would be in the best interests of Merrill Lynch and all our
constituents to definitively bring this matter to a close and end
the uncertainty inherent in any judicial proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch said it already had set aside money for the
settlement, which would not affect its earnings for the second
quarter, which ends this month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to paying $400 million to Orange County, Merrill
Lynch agreed to pay an additional $17.1 million to the Irvine Ranch
Water District, which also had sued Merrill Lynch over the
bankruptcy. Last year the company paid $30 million in a settlement
with the county district attorney to assure that the county would
not bring criminal charges against it. It also agreed last year to
pay $1.9 million to settle a class action suit brought by holders
of Orange County bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But Merrill Lynch is still not completely free of the legal
consequences of Orange County's bankruptcy. The Securities and
Exchange Commission is investigating whether the company violated
securities laws in another role it performed for Orange County _
underwriting bond offerings. The SEC is looking at whether Merrill
adequately informed bond buyers of the risks involved. The
Securities and Exchange Commission Tuesday declined to comment but
some attorneys involved in the bankruptcy predict Merrill and the
federal agency might also now move toward a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
