<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: RACE TO BUY THE BROWNS HAS NEW YORK FLAVOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (ja)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Howard Milstein, the real estate developer, and Chuck
Dolan, the cable television magnate, have three things in common:
lots of money, businesses that are located in the New York
metropolitan area and a desire to own the soon-to-be-revived
Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   The race to buy the expansion Browns is accelerating, with
Milstein's and Dolan's groups among six to have applied to the
National Football League. No price has been set _ estimates range
from $400 million to the moon _ but it will most likely be the
costliest sports franchise ever for several reasons: a lucrative
lease at a new stadium where the team will start play in 1999;
immediate access to $70 million a year from new TV deals, and a
rabid fan base that seems certain to support the new Browns as it
did the old ones before Art Modell shipped them to Baltimore in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here because this is a fundamentally great
investment,'' Dolan, the chairman of Woodbury, N.Y.-based
Cablevision Systems, said Tuesday from Cleveland, his hometown.
``We love Cleveland and we want to own the Browns.''
</P>
<P>
   Milstein, who is a co-owner of the New York Islanders, said
Monday from Cleveland: ``This will be a very good business. We
expect to realize significant value from the team as a business.
You have to look at the whole issues of winning football and
restoring tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns' move to Baltimore, where they were renamed the
Ravens, was the most wrenching team shift since the Dodgers moved
to Los Angeles. As part of the NFL's approval of the move, the
Browns' name, colors, and logos remained in trust for the new
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of the Browns as the team for the next century,''
Milstein said. ``We're going to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the other potential applicants, the Dolan and Milstein
groups paid $150,000 to enter the process, and are being
investigated by the NFL for their financial worthiness before they
receive economic data upon which to base their bids. An owner is
expected to be chosen in September.
</P>
<P>
   Milstein was persuaded to join the bidding five weeks ago by
Calvin Hill, the former Browns and Dallas Cowboy running back, and
Paul Warfield, the Hall of Fame receiver for the Browns and Miami
Dolphins. Robert Lewis, a lawyer for Milstein, is also part of the
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the job is to re-establish a winning reputation _ one that
goes back in Cleveland to the 1940s _ we can do it,'' said Hill, a
consultant to the Cowboys. ``We know both sides of the ball. We had
wonderful careers as players, but since I retired, I've been a
consultant and administrator.'' Warfield is in private business.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan returned to his hometown on Tuesday, with his brother
Lawrence, a lawyer in suburban Cleveland, to announce that the
entertainer Bill Cosby had taken a 5 percent stake in their
ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby was not an investor in the Dolans' group when they
declared their interest several weeks ago. Cosby said he was not
added as a token, to be a prominent symbol for a league without
black ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it,'' Cosby added, but he said that the
potential size of his investment, $25 million if the team costs
$500 million, placed him in a different category.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Dolan said, ``I don't see the appropriateness of
tokenism when we're discussing Bill Cosby.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he did not want to speculate about whether the Dolans
added Cosby because they felt their group needed a prominent
African-American. But, he said: ``The fact that Paul and I are
black and Howard and Robert are white is wonderful. We're not just
people who fit categories. It was about getting the best team.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chuck Dolan, the Browns would be a personal investment,
separate from Cablevision's acquisition of Madison Square Garden,
which owns the Knicks and the Rangers. He would provide the bulk of
the money to buy the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure anyone who is seeking wealth to get a good
education and have a brother like I have,'' Lawrence Dolan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolans and the Milstein group appear sanguine that the
league will not price the team into the stratosphere; Malcolm
Glazer, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers' owner, reportedly said the price
should be $1.5 billion. In the NFL's last expansion, Carolina and
Jacksonville paid $140-million entry fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to bid the value,'' Lawrence Dolan said. ``But
it's important the winning bid not necessarily be the biggest
bid.''
</P>
<P>
   Milstein echoed the sentiment. ``If all they want is maximum
dollars,'' he said, ``maybe it's not a good business deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
