<HEADER>
A1024 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARIANNA-OPERA-$ADV07-     06-02 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIANNA-OPERA-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING MONTEVERDI IN THE NOW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Arianna,'' which will be given its first American performance
Sunday by the Opera Theater of St. Louis, is not exactly a new work
and not exactly an old one. Quite who wrote it is also in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   According to the title page of the score, it is a ``lost opera
by Claudio Monteverdi ... composed again by Alexander Goehr,'' the
English composer who, now 65, has steadily been gaining a
reputation for music at once serious and playful, beautiful and
quirky, as this is.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the story goes back to 1608, when Monteverdi wrote
``Arianna'' for a wedding at the court of the Gonzagas in Mantua.
The subject was, as usual in early opera, a classical myth. Theseus
and Ariadne have left Crete, after she, for love of him, turned
from her family and helped him defeat the Minotaur.
</P>
<P>
   Their destination is Athens, where Theseus is king, but they
have stopped on the island of Naxos. Theseus is persuaded that the
Athenians will not accept Ariadne, who comes of enemy stock, so he
sails away alone, under the protection of night. When Ariadne wakes
to find him gone, she is distraught. Then, out of the blue, a new
consort arrives in the shape of the god Bacchus, who takes her up
to join him in the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arianna'' was much appreciated in its time, especially for its
lament, which Monteverdi published as a solo piece and a madrigal.
In those early days of Baroque emotionalism, the lamenting heroine
was already an established type: composers had quickly learned how
music could, by slow stepwise falls, by sudden lifts of the voice
and by obsessive repetition, model hopelessness, shrieks of anguish
and the monomania of despair.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody did all this better than Monteverdi, but though he
revised the opera for later productions, the rest of its score
somehow got abandoned, like Ariadne, as time moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Goehr, as Bacchus. In 1994 he decided to set the libretto
by Ottavio Rinuccini a second time. The libretto is a remarkable
piece of work, Renaissance in sentiment but true to the ancient
Greek stage in its use of chorus and messengers to narrate much of
the action.
</P>
<P>
   The task was not to embed the surviving lament in pastiche: that
would have been to create a fake opera, not a lost one, and for
Goehr it was a preliminary stage. Having set the Rinuccini text,
slightly cut, in Monteverdian style, as a sequence of melodious
dialogues, madrigalian choruses and instrumental sinfonias, he went
on to vary, elaborate and play with what he had fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   And, for that matter, with what Monteverdi had fashioned in
1608, since the authentic lament is also transformed, and also
honored, by Goehr's attentions: the melody ranges more widely
(magically so, after the familiar opening phrases), the harmony is
enriched, and the accompaniment is laid out, as throughout the
opera, for an ensemble of 17th-century scale but 20th-century
countenance, featuring flutes and saxophones, high string trio,
percussion, harp and electric guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Goehr was well equipped to take on the challenge of imagining
Monteverdi _ indeed, of imagining himself as Monteverdi. For one
thing, he is a composer with a profound sense of being heir to the
Western musical tradition, and thus of housing, inside his own
creative personality, the ghosts of the greats.
</P>
<P>
   He is an artist with the rare selflessness that could allow his
internal Monteverdi, in this case, to pretty much take over. He
also has the technical adroitness, taste and intelligence necessary
to give that internal Monteverdi the tools, together with enough
charm and lightness of touch to make the cooperation a delight.
</P>
<P>
   Besides all that, Monteverdi had a special place in making Goehr
a composer. His father, Walter Goehr, was a conductor and a member
of Schoenberg's circle: hence, in part, the junior Goehr's
reverence for the central tradition, often to the extent of
emulating its characteristic forms, textures and techniques.
</P>
<P>
   But Walter Goehr was also a leader in the mid-20th-century
Monteverdi revival, and in Monteverdi his composer son found an
alternative to the harmonic richness and inwardness of Schoenberg.
Monteverdi held out an ideal of music as pure melody and
spontaneity, and Goehr as a young man was captivated.
</P>
<P>
   He was not prepared, though, to ditch the artistic morality that
Schoenberg had defended, and his works of the last 40 years can be
seen as a sequence of sites in which the battle between Central
European Romantic or modern weight and Italian Baroque lightness is
fought again and again, occasionally with intensity but more often
with exuberant good humor.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   So it is in ``Arianna.'' Sometimes, whether in the lament or in
what surrounds it, the musical language of 1608 sounds through
freshly; more often it is patinated or observed through layers of
pearl. Harmony and texture haze the image, and there are passing
references to what has been happening in the interim between
Monteverdi's Baroque dormition and his modern awakening.
</P>
<P>
   Goehr invites us to hear a little of Debussy's Melisande in
Arianna, and there are teasing touches of Puccini occasionally at
the ends of phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Harder to know is whether the echoes of Richard Strauss'
``Ariadne auf Naxos'' come from the composer or from us, as we
watch similar events, especially the arrival of Bacchus, unfold in
music. After all, the question of the author's authority is being
posed gently and gracefully throughout this entertainment, by an
author _ Monteverdi _ whose death could hardly be more certain (for
we can visit his grave in the Venetian church of I Frari) or now
more unsettlingly insecure.
</P>
<P>
   However this music arrived, it is riddled with Monteverdianisms:
in the vocal decoration, in the dancing character and brightness of
the sinfonias, in the keen expressiveness and tonal lucidity of the
melody, in the repeated notes to finish clauses, in the brushing of
the accompaniment into and under the vocal line.
</P>
<P>
   (For those who cannot hear the opera in St. Louis during the
next couple of weeks, there is a newly released recording of it on
NMC, distributed by Allegro, of Portland, Ore. The singing is
variable, but the wonderful countertenor Lawrence Zazzo, as
Bacchus, is spellbinding in the final song.)
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the harmony and the instrumentation are almost
constantly telling us that this is not Monteverdi at all, and thus
reinforcing our knowledge of the case (if we can hold on to that
amid all the pleasure and opalescence). The Monteverdi we hear is
an absent Monteverdi. This is still a lost opera.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the view of the central character that was tolerable
in 1608, and even unsurprising, is so no longer. That Ariadne
should be ``rescued'' by a male figure she has never met is not, in
Goehr's treatment, a happy ending. Her lament, as he adapts it, is
a great journey of self-learning. This is where she rescues
herself.
</P>
<P>
   By the end her persona is one of dignity raised to a point where
it becomes challenging, and her final words (``Rejoice in my
rejoicing'') are set in a way that indicates she accepts Bacchus as
she accepts the inevitable: with dismay, with foreboding and with
the heightened awareness her self-knowledge has brought.
</P>
<P>
   Another key moment in Goehr's setting comes when a messenger
tells of Ariadne's hopeless striding into the ocean after the
departing Theseus. Nothing in this marvelous passage was written by
Monteverdi, yet what drives through it is everything we have always
thought Monteverdi to be about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arianna'' is a triumph of musical resuscitation, and because
it presents us with Monteverdi composed now _ with a Monteverdi who
can write for electronic sampler, and who knows about Schoenberg,
Debussy and Puccini _ we rejoin the audience of 1608, confronting
something that did not exist before and that is therefore
uncategorized and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the ``Arianna'' that was performed at the Gonzaga
court, but it might be how it felt.
</P>
</TEXT>
