u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TEXAS-1STLD-W     06-02 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEXAS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS CENSUS `AMERICAN ISSUE' IN BACKING NEW COUNTING
METHOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to move up Bentsen item and to delete graf from bottom) 
 
By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ President Clinton, meeting Tuesday with Houstonians
affected by low census tallies, embraced a new counting method
vigorously opposed by Republicans and set the stage for a critical
showdown with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton toured the Womens, Infant and Childrens Program, which
receives federal funds based on the decennial census. At the
Magnolia Multi-Service Center near downtown, he also heard from
minority leaders and academics who urged a more accurate census for
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The president, making his third trip to Houston this year, also
helped Texas Democrats raise $800,000 at a $5,000-per-plate
luncheon at the posh River Oaks home of attorney Richard Mithoff.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also paid an unscheduled visit to former U.S. Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, who recently suffered a mild stroke. Clinton stayed at the
Texan's townhome for about an hour. Bentsen served as Clinton's
first treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton flew to Dallas where he raised $1 million for the
national Democratic Party before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hispanic enclave of Magnolia Park, Clinton sought to put
a human face on the census problems, which have enormous political
and financial ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the count is, wherever the people are, this is not a
political issue, this is an American issue,'' Clinton told the
eight panel members and 150 other officials in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The census issue has raged in Congress for more than a year.
Clinton offered his support for a Census Bureau plan, developed by
the National Academy of Sciences, to use statistical sampling to
estimate the 10 percent of the population that enumerators are
unable to contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has got an ax to grind for any method; we should all
want the most accurate method. And when it's all said and done, all
we should want is to have everyone of us properly, accurately,
fairly and constitutionally counted,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington, Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, chairman of the
House Republican Conference retorted: ``Sampling corrupts a basic
sense of fairness by treating people as numbers that can be
estimated rather than individuals who have a right to be counted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau has estimated that it failed to count 8
million people in the 1990 census, most of them children and
minorities, and double-counted more than 4 million for its most
inaccurate count ever.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Houston had the largest undercount of any urban
city as the census missed 66,748 people, again most of them
children and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means some of our most vulnerable populations routinely
are omitted when it comes time to provide federal funds for
critical services. An inaccurate census distorts our understanding
of the needs of our people, and in many respects, therefore, it
diminishes the quality of life not only for them, but for all the
rest of us as well,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton addressed a crowd that included members of Congress and
Houston Mayor Lee Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president couldn't have picked a better place to pinpoint
the inaccuracies with the 1990 census,'' said Rep. Gene Green,
D-Texas. ``It's estimated that Texas lost about $1 billion in
federal funds because of the inaccuracies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mary desVignes-Kendrick, director of the City of Houston
Health Department, said accurate census data ``is critical to
public health.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted census data on child poverty rates helps determine
nutrition programs and child health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Moreno, chairman of the Association for the Advancement
of Mexican-Americans, said the census must accurately chart the
growth of Hispanics in the United States. ``Over the next 50 years,
Hispanics and Asians will provide almost half of the country's
population growth. Those statistics are going to be very
critical,'' Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Joe, owner of Great Wall Enterprises, a marketing firm
aimed at the Asian community, called the census ``the bible for
corporations looking to plan their business allocations for
marketing and advertising.'' An inaccurate count means she has
trouble selling corporations on the idea of Asian outreach because
Asians are undercounted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton complained the issue will be difficult to explain to the
American people. Chiding Republicans, Clinton said it was ``quite
unfortunate that some in Congress have so vociferously opposed
sampling, because improving the census shouldn't be a partisan
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Republicans accuse Clinton and the Democrats of
pressing the statistical sampling method as a way to gain more
seats in Congress and state legislatures across the nation.
Electoral office districts are based on census figures.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans fear they could lose 24 seats in Congress, which
would cost them control of the House, and more than 400 seats in
state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president doesn't get it. He continues to advocate the use
of an unproven methodology that didn't work during the 1990 census
and won't work in the 2000 census. We've heard enough of his
`political' science. Where is the `empirical' science,'' said Rep.
Dan Miller, R-Fla., chairman of the House subcommittee on the
census.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have filed suit to block the Census Bureau's
sampling method, and the case will be heard in late summer.
Legislation also has put the case on the fast track for a Supreme
Court hearing this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mallett, deputy secretary of commerce and a Houston
native, said that despite the lawsuit the Census Bureau is bracing
for a fight in Congress before the issue is finally settled. He
said the bureau must have the dispute resolved by February in order
to perform the census.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle staffers T.J. Milling and Jamie Stockwell contributed to
this story. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
