<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR RAISES POSSIBILITY OF SENDING IMPEACHMENT REFERRAL TO
CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-LEWINSKY) 
(sw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, on Tuesday
raised the prospect for the first time publicly that he may send to
Congress an impeachment referral against President Clinton in the
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came in papers he filed with the Supreme Court
urging it to quickly resolve efforts by the Clinton administration
to block the testimony of several officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be blunt,'' Starr wrote in replying to the White House
contention, raised again on Monday, that some of the testimony
being sought by investigators is protected by the attorney-client
privilege. ``The Nation has a compelling interest that this
criminal investigation of the President of the United States
conclude as quickly as possible _ that indictments be brought,
possible reports for impeachment proceedings issued, and
non-prosecution decisions announced. This Court's immediate review
would powerfully serve that vital goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The President's response,'' Starr added, ``treats this as a
matter-of-fact investigation. But the unhappy fact is that, at the
determination of the Attorney General herself, a President is under
serious criminal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and lawyers, following Starr's investigation of
whether the president had a sexual relationship with Monica
Lewinsky and urged her to lie about it, have speculated for months
about the possibility of an impeachment report. However, the filing
on Tuesday marked the first time that Starr has publicly signaled
that he is moving in that direction. Such a report would inform
Congress that the independent counsel had found evidence of an
impeachable offense, compelling Congress to consider whether to
exercise its authority under the Constitution to remove the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it may be months before such a report is completed. Starr
and his staff must first face a crucial decision about whether to
prosecute Ms. Lewinsky, a former intern at the White House, for
perjury and other charges. And they remain embroiled in a series of
legal disputes with the administration _ over the testimony of a
top White House aide, Bruce Lindsey, as well as several Secret
Service agents _ that may take months to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the White House on Tuesday called Starr's brief
``an act of public relations, not a work of law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Starr's filing today serves as a vehicle for rhetoric in
the place of legal substance,'' said the statement, which was
issued by Jim Kennedy, a special adviser to the White House
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, who on Tuesday jettisoned her flamboyant
California lawyer, William Ginsburg, in favor of two seasoned
criminal defense lawyers from Washington, is under investigation
for perjury, obstruction of justice and witness tampering. In the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, she and Clinton denied under
oath that they had a sexual relationship, although she is said to
have contradicted her sworn testimony in secretly recorded
conversations with a former colleague, Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the new legal team by Ms. Lewinsky raised the
prospect that negotiations over a possible plea agreement or
immunity deal, which had stalled in recent months, could be
renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing to short-circuit the normal appeals process, Starr on
Tuesday asked the Supreme Court for the second time in two weeks to
bypass the Court of Appeals on the administration's challenge to
grand jury testimony by top aides and Secret Service officials.
Starr asked the justices to expedite the administration's appeal of
a Federal District judge's order compelling three employees of the
Secret Service to answer questions about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The employees, two uniformed officers and the agency's chief
counsel, had declined to answer the questions citing a new kind of
privilege that the Secret Service maintains is essential to ensure
the safety of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Starr asked the Supreme Court to quickly consider
Clinton's appeal from the same judge's order compelling the
testimony of two senior presidential aides, Lindsey and Sidney
Blumenthal. On Monday, Clinton abruptly dropped the executive
privilege claim that had blocked Blumenthal's testimony, but he
continued to assert the attorney-client privilege claim to limit
the testimony of Lindsey, a deputy White House counsel and one of
the president's closest confidantes.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers have urged the Supreme Court to let the
appeals process run its normal course, prompting Starr to reply on
Tuesday that it was in the national interest to quickly resolve the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the President himself (among others) is under criminal
investigation, the grand jury, this Office, the President, the
Congress, and the Nation have a compelling interest that the matter
be resolved quickly and definitively,'' Starr told the justices.
``More months of protracted litigation are inimical to the Nation's
well-being. The facts are needed, and they are needed now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
