<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-PLAYS     06-02 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-PLAYS-ART-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTER 90S ANXIETIES, STAGE RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo showing John Cameron Mitchell in ``Hedwig and the
Angry Inch''; Alfred Molina, Alan Alda and Victor Garber in ``Art''
will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7)  
 (af)  
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gasp!
</P>
<P>
   This is not a sound often heard anymore among Broadway
audiences. Gasping these days is generally reserved for the arrival
of large, eye-catching pieces of scenery, especially scenery that
moves, and such spectacle tends to be accompanied by heavily
amplified, gasp-drowning music.
</P>
<P>
   But what about that sudden, collective catching of breath that
whooshes through a hushed theater, a noise that seems as
involuntary and inevitable as that of someone who has been punched?
</P>
<P>
   There were occasions during the recent New York theater season,
which is celebrated by the presentation of Sunday night's Tony
Awards, when that sound flew out of audiences who had achieved a
rapt, respectful communion with what was happening on the stages
before them.
</P>
<P>
   The inspirations for these abrupt responses, which are surely
more gratifying to actors than even standing ovations, are wildly
varied and, taken out of context, unremarkable. A bedraggled,
middle-aged Irishwoman puts on a pair of rubber gloves, the kind
used for washing dishes. A priggish Parisian draws a childlike
sketch of a man skiing. A Brooklyn dockworker plants a kiss on the
mouth of another man.
</P>
<P>
   What's the big deal? Even men kissing men is not unheard of on
television. But each of these prosaic actions _ from, respectively,
the current Broadway productions of ``The Beauty Queen of
Leenane,'' ``Art'' and ``A View From the Bridge'' _ registers like
a clap of thunder.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that the emotional weather in these works started
out stormy doesn't take away from the gestures' power to shock. The
crisis at which you have vicariously arrived makes perfect,
illuminating sense.
</P>
<P>
   The plays described here all figure prominently in Sunday
night's broadcast of the 52nd annual Antoinette Perry Awards at
Radio City Music Hall from 9 to 11 p.m. on CBS. (From 8 to 9 p.m.,
PBS will broadcast some presentations at the music hall on
``Broadway '98: Launching the Tony Awards.'') ``Beauty Queen,'' by
the young Anglo-Irish dramatist Martin McDonagh, and ``Art,'' by
the Iranian-born French playwright Yasmina Reza, are nominated for
best new play; Arthur Miller's ``View From the Bridge,'' produced
by the Roundabout Theater Company, for best revival.
</P>
<P>
   None of them represents the kind of breakthrough in form or
content that ``Angels in America,'' Tony Kushner's fantasia on life
in the age of AIDS, did five years ago. And it would be overly
optimistic to see them as harbingers of an era in which the
straight play can flourish again on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, this was a season that confirmed the worst as
well as the best of the current directions in theater, with a
mediocrity like the revival of ``Wait Until Dark' selling entirely
on the basis of Quentin Tarantino's presence and a musical like
``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' yawning its way through a storybook
formula.
</P>
<P>
   But the vivid presence of ``Beauty Queen'' and company in the
Times Square area, and their ability to stir emotional currents far
beyond the reach of your average musical blockbuster, is
heartening, a testimony to the enduring appetite for theater at its
most elemental. They speak to the child in everyone who begs,
``Tell me a story,'' and then finds he can't sleep afterward.
</P>
<P>
   For none of these works is unconditionally the stuff of what you
would call a feel-good night at the theater. ``Beauty Queen,'' set
in a bleak provincial Ireland, and ``View,'' which takes place in a
blue-collar Brooklyn neighborhood of the 1950s, are crackling
studies in self-delusion and self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``Art,'' the shortest and slightest of the three, is
described by its author as being as much a tragedy as a comedy,
turning a silly quarrel among three friends over a painting into a
glimpse of fathomless isolation.
</P>
<P>
   The greater surprise is that the tone of these plays isn't out
of keeping with what has been an exceptionally busy year in the New
York theater. From the visual bedazzlement of such megamusicals as
``The Lion King'' and ``Ragtime'' to the gritty naturalism of such
Off Broadway hits as Jez Butterworth's ``Mojo'' and Mike Leigh's
``Goose-Pimples''; from the absurdist wasteland of the first-class
revival of Eugene Ionesco's ``Chairs'' to the memory-haunted
Poconos of Neil Simon's ``Proposals,'' there has been a distinct,
sober awareness of the darker threads of life: of mortality,
cruelty, injustice and existential loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   This was the season, lest you forget, in which Nazi uniforms
became a wardrobe staple. The Weimar-era sybarites of ``Cabaret,''
the 1966 musical by John Kander and Fred Ebb, re-emerged with
startling clarity, elucidated by the English director Sam Mendes,
as the victims and executioners of the Holocaust to come; while
that carefree party girl Sally Bowles, brilliantly reinterpreted by
Natasha Richardson, became an aimless woman on the edge of an
abyss.
</P>
<P>
   A heavily revised version of ``The Diary of Anne Frank,''
directed by James Lapine from Wendy Kesselman's adaptation of
Frances Goodrich and Albert Hackett's 1955 script, brought the
Gestapo onto the stage toward the play's end and chose not to
conclude with Anne's hopeful declaration of her belief in human
goodness.
</P>
<P>
   The standard-issue revival of ``The Sound of Music,'' which
largely remained as sugary as ever, scaled up the menacing
political context, and ``Edelweiss'' was sung by the wholesome Von
Trapps before an oversized Nazi flag.
</P>
<P>
   Even the corporate show-business machines, Walt Disney and
Livent, found the serious side in their eye-popping spectacles.
Disney's second adaptation of one of its popular musical cartoon
movies, ``The Lion King,'' was far more adventurous and, for all
its festive atmosphere, more somber than its earlier ``Beauty and
the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Taymor, an avant-garde director who specializes in folk
and ritual theatrical techniques, introduced a raw sense of death
and predation that sometimes seemed at odds with the cozy fable at
the show's center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragtime,'' the producer Garth Drabinsky's epic adaptation of
E.L. Doctorow's novel, heard America singing in the early part of
this century, and what it heard, in the songs by Stephen Flaherty
and Lynn Ahrens, were cries of oppression, frustration and social
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   The composer Paul Simon's misbegotten $11-million musical ``The
Capeman,'' the season's most flamboyant flop, turned the real-life
story of a street-gang murder into a salsa-driven rock opera of
crime, punishment, and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   All of these shows had ambition and innovation to spare. Yet
none really advanced the evolution of the organic American musical;
they registered more as novelty toys, lacking the exhilarating
humanity and the electric bond with their audiences of the
breakthrough productions that opened two years ago, ``Rent'' and
``Bring In da Noise, Bring In da Funk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lion King'' is undeniably inspired in its use of a global
visual vocabulary, but its story, dance, music and individual
performances are all secondary. It is perhaps best viewed as a
series of breathtaking tableaux, a sort of latter-day Ziegfeld
Follies by way of National Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capeman'' was never able to find the basic stagecraft simply
to tell its story or to match the spark of its revolutionary score.
``Ragtime'' suffers from a sense of having been produced by
corporate committee; it's a good-looking, liberal-minded historical
pageant with little feeling of spontaneous life.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted a new Broadway musical with a human heart, you
would have had to have seen the short-lived ``Side Show.'' With a
book and lyrics by Bill Russell and a rich, compelling score by
Henry Krieger, ``Side Show'' dared to ask its audiences to identify
with a set of performing Siamese twins, stunningly portrayed by
Alice Ripley and Emily Skinner, and in the process created one of
the fuller, warmer character portraits of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream theatergoers recoiled, however, clearly feeling safer
with the icy sensationalism of the long-running ``Titanic'' across
the street.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown audiences have had no such reservations about another
portrait of an anomaly, the Off Broadway sleeper ``Hedwig and the
Angry Inch,'' in which John Cameron Mitchell, the work's author,
plays a transsexual rock star in search of a completed self.
</P>
<P>
   With an eclectic rock-pop score by Stephen Trask, ``Hedwig,''
like ``Side Show'' (and like ``Rent,'' for that matter),
demonstrates how contemporary musical idioms can revitalize a
classic genre without sacrificing its essential sentiment. Both
shows are reminders that once upon a time, people went to musicals
to (italics)feel,(end italics) not just to look at pretty pictures.
</P>
<P>
   They also reflect the spirit of an age in which cultural and
sexual identity is in flux. The same point of view is embodied in
two current, galvanic one-man shows: John Leguizamo's
autobiographical ``Freak'' on Broadway and Danny Hoch's ``Jails,
Hospitals and Hip Hop'' at Performance Space 122, works in which
two young master chameleons repeatedly transform themselves to show
how race is as much a matter of mind-set as skin color.
</P>
<P>
   A questing spirit was equally evident in David Mamet's eloquent,
troubling ``Old Neighborhood,'' which considered the pain and
rudderlessness of living in a world without faith. Mamet's most
deeply personal play to date, it also featured extraordinary
ensemble work from Peter Riegert, Patti LuPone, Vincent Guastaferro
and Jack Willis, none of whom, shamefully, were nominated for
Tonys. Nor was the play itself, which is easily the best new drama
by an American this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks were well represented by intriguing but uneven
offerings from such stalwarts as Sam Shepard (``Eyes for
Consuela''), Tina Howe (``Pride's Crossing'') and Jon Robin Baitz
(the witty ``Mizlansky/Zilinsky, or `Schmucks' ''). But it was a
clutch of young playwrights from England and Ireland who shone
brightest, combining old-fashioned narrative verve with a bold,
atmospheric use of language.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to McDonagh, represented by both the excellent
``Beauty Queen'' and a less certain production at the Joseph Papp
Public Theater of ``The Cripple of Inishmaan,'' there were
Butterworth, whose ``Mojo'' at the Atlantic Theater Company was a
high-adrenaline romp through London murder and mayhem in 1950s
Soho, and Conor McPherson, who provided a deliciously sly exercise
in Gothic storytelling, ``St. Nicholas,'' beautifully delivered by
the Scottish actor Brian Cox at Primary Stages.
</P>
<P>
   For evidence that the British are less than perfect as theater
artists, look to Peter Whelan's ``Herbal Bed'' or David Hare's
disappointing ``Judas Kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall level of acting this season was, in fact,
exceptional, starting with the symbiotic quartet of Irish
performers who, under Garry Hines' direction, make ``Beauty Queen''
such a potent brew: Marie Mullen, Anna Manahan, Brian F. O'Byrne
and Tom Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   The magnificent Cherry Jones shimmered through the many ages of
one woman in ``Pride's Crossing,'' while Nathan Lane drew a satiric
sketch worthy of Daumier as a sleazy Hollywood producer in
``Mizlansky/Zilinsky.'' Anthony LaPaglia and Allison Janney, under
Michael Mayer's direction, expertly conjured a fiery, tragic muse
out of the kitchen-sink ``A View From the Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon Russell Beale dazzled and chilled as a bland everyman of
an Iago in the Royal National Theater's excellent visiting
production of ``Othello,'' directed by Mendes, at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music; Vanessa L. Williams confirmed her sensual star
presence and high-sheen skills in the concert version of ``St.
Louis Woman,'' from the invaluable Encores series at City Center;
Ms. Richardson and Alan Cumming, as a demonic nightclub M.C.,
hauntingly located the desperate, vulnerable center of ``Cabaret'';
the stand-up comic Lea DeLaria emerged as a meteoric musical star
in the Public Theater's ``On the Town'' and the Encores production
of ``Li'l Abner,'' and Geraldine McEwan and Richard Briers breathed
endlessly entertaining life into the moribund couple of ``The
Chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   This last production, a London import directed by Simon
McBurney, showed how a seemingly quaint period piece can be
resurrected with a freshness that makes it feel newly minted. All
art, of course, is to some degree a dialogue with the past as well
as the present, and revivals and pastiche plays and musicals don't
have to be museum pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how the inventive Off Off Broadway deconstructions both
of ``Uncle Tom's Cabin,'' by that fine young troupe the Drama
Dept., and of Eugene O'Neill's ``Emperor Jones,'' by the great
experimental veterans of the Wooster Group, used a medley of
century-spanning performance styles to create a shifting landscape
of perceptions of complicated works that can never again be seen
with virgin eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And in Millburn, N.J., the Paper Mill Playhouse presented a
revelatory revival of ``Follies,'' Stephen Sondheim's profoundly
ambivalent hommage from 1971 to a more innocent era of musical
theater.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Robert Johanson, with affectingly honest
performances from stars ranging from Ann Miller to Donna McKechnie,
the production (which, if heaven allows, is Broadway bound) made it
clear that this great, multi-layered musical isn't about making fun
of a theatrical heritage but about learning to live with it and to
take it into the future. It turned out, oddly enough, to be the
most modern-seeming show of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
