<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MILESTONE IN ATTEMPT TO CLEAN UP MUNICIPAL FINANCE
MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BC-ORANGE-COUNTY) 
(JT) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The $400 million settlement between Merrill Lynch and Orange
County, Calif., is another significant milestone in efforts, now
years in the making, to clean up questionable practices in the $1.3
trillion municipal finance market.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the municipal marketplace, where cities and
towns across America raise money to provide services to their
citizens, has been rocked by a series of scandals often involving
cozy political arrangements between local officials and some Wall
Street bankers. But the bankruptcy of Orange County, one of the
richest in the country, was striking in the sheer scale of the loss
_ $1.6 billion _ and now for the magnitude of the payments from
Wall Street firms and others to settle the legal charges.
</P>
<P>
   For years, municipal finance has been considered a backwater of
Wall Street. And because it operated at a lower profile, with less
celebrated deal makers and less glamorous assignments, many of the
same standards considered appropriate in the raising of capital by
corporations never seemed to apply. Wall Street firms wanting
lucrative municipal bond deals, for example, eagerly wrote big
checks to politicians able to hand out those deals. And poorly
informed local financial officers were easy prey for Wall Street
firms often peddling risky and wildly inappropriate securities to
be bought with taxpayer dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But in late 1994, just when Orange County became the largest
municipal bankruptcy in American history, government regulators
began a serious effort to clean up the municipal finance market
that is only now beginning to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Orange County bankruptcy drew national attention to the
municipal debt markets at a time when the Securities and Exchange
Commission had just undertaken efforts to improve the municipal
market overall,'' said Paul Maco, head of the SEC's office of
municipal securities. ``We've made great progress. We've improved
disclosure in the markets, we've eliminated many conflicts of
interest between bond issuers and Wall Street firms, and we are
putting into place a better system for providing prices of
municipal bonds to the retail investor.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been just a coincidence that the SEC's chairman,
Arthur Levitt, declared cleaning up the municipal markets his ``No.
1'' priority close to the Orange County bankruptcy filing. But the
publicity surrounding the debacle certainly served to focus a
spotlight on those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The following has been accomplished in the intervening years:
</P>
<P>
   _Efforts have succeeded to eliminate ``pay to play'' practices.
Wall Street firms are now prohibited from making campaign
contributions to local politicians that hand out bond underwriting
business.
</P>
<P>
   _More disclosure has been required of municipalities when they
issue bonds to investors.
</P>
<P>
   _Fraud charges have been leveled by the federal government
against a number of firms, bankers and municipal officials. At
least one major banker, Mark Ferber, a former partner at Lazard
Freres &AMP; Co., was sentenced to a 33-month jail term for failing to
disclose a secret kickback arrangement he had with another Wall
Street firm.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Orange County settlement with Merrill Lynch _ the
largest piece of nearly $600 million the county has collected so
far _ is a signal of how much remains to be done. The settlement
shows there is plenty of blame to spread around, including everyone
from the county officials who were loath to raise taxes and instead
devised a get-rich-quick scheme with public money to the Wall
Street advisers, deal makers and lawyers who enabled that scheme to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   In almost fitting justice, the amounts that the county is
expected to collect _ around $800 million or so when all the
lawsuits against Wall Street professionals are settled _ and the
amount the county will lose itself will ultimately be about equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This episode shows there are a lot of people in municipal
governments at the decision-making level without the training to
make financial decisions,'' said one Wall Street investment banker,
who was involved with Orange County and spoke only on condition he
not be named. ``Situations can arise when you have the confluence
of so many dollars. You've got profits to be made by Wall Street
professionals and people in municipalities who aren't always at top
capability.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bennett, the attorney for Orange County who led the
bankruptcy case, added: ``The message of this settlement is that
public money is fairly well protected by the statutes, and when
they are violated it will result in liability by those who do
business with municipal officials. This was the largest settlement
ever in municipal finance and maybe the sheer size of it will lead
people to be more careful and not treat public money as a hedge
fund.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
