<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-TREATIES-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BLASTS HURT EFFORTS TO LIMIT NUCLEAR ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: India, Pakistan)   (Eds: See also PAKISTAN-GOALS) 
(mk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nuclear tests by India and Pakistan have undermined the
agreements and assumptions on which efforts to stop the spread of
nuclear weapons have been based for the last 30 years, a range of
officials, analysts and diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   They say the tests have also helped to all but doom prospects
this year for Senate approval of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,
which prohibits nuclear testing and which the Clinton
administration has made a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   The tests have also revived a fierce debate about how to get
countries to keep their commitments not to develop nuclear weapons
and how to stop India and Pakistan from plunging headlong into a
nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nuclear tests are the most significant and damaging
proliferation event in years,'' said Lawrence Scheinman, who until
August was assistant director of the U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency and is now director of the Washington office of
the Monterey Institute of International Affairs, an arms control
research center.
</P>
<P>
   But arms control advocates disagree about how much the tests
have changed the prospects for halting the spread of the weapons
and how the United States and other nations should respond.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the amount of damage to efforts to stop the
spread of nuclear weapons will depend on whether India and Pakistan
are forced to pay a high price for their tests. They say that would
mean getting other countries to join the United States in imposing
tough sanctions to discourage similar tests.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts warn that while the tests have undermined American
efforts, the administration should acknowledge that neither India
nor Pakistan is as potentially dangerous as countries like Iraq or
Iran. Isolating India and Pakistan with tough sanctions, they say,
may only complicate efforts to keep them from putting nuclear
warheads atop missiles and from sharing their nuclear know-how with
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``American policy has always placed India, Pakistan and Israel
in an unstated, special category _ the de facto weapons state,''
said Richard Haass, director of foreign policy studies at the
Brookings Institution. ``So we need to continue distinguishing, in
fact, if not in arms control theory, between them and rogue
states.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An all-out isolation campaign is a mistake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some arms control advocates say the administration has not put
sufficient emphasis on nuclear disarmament in general. Paul
Leventhal, president of the Nuclear Control Institute, a
Washington-based nonprofit group that lobbies for arms control,
said the administration had inadvertently encouraged the tests by
making trade a higher priority.
</P>
<P>
   Others cite the relative lack of progress in disarmament by the
two countries with the most nuclear weapons _ the United States and
Russia _ noting that treaties and agreements between them permit
each side to have 3,500 long-range nuclear missiles and unlimited
tactical nuclear weapons. But most analysts give the administration
relatively high marks for its efforts to stop the spread of the
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the administration claimed a major arms control
achievement _ helping to draft the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,
which bans all test explosions, and persuading reluctant
governments in China and France to sign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an effort to counter opposition in the United States, the
administration agreed to spend $45 billion over the next 10 years
to enable weapons laboratories here to develop ways to check the
reliability of bombs without detonating them, by using computer
simulation, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the Indian and Pakistani tests, the treaty was
already on life support in the Senate. Conservative Republicans,
including Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the influential chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said adherence to the treaty
could not be verified and vowed to block Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Helms wrote President Clinton that he would not
consider the test ban treaty until the Senate voted on the
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty and the global warming treaty reached
in Kyoto, Japan. In practical terms, that meant the test ban treaty
had virtually no chance of coming to a vote in the Senate this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some arms control analysts say, the Indian and Pakistani
tests may have lessened the chances even further.
</P>
<P>
   Ten prominent members of the Union of Concerned Scientists _
including Adm. William Crowe, former chairman of the joint chiefs
of staff; Hans Bethe, the Nobel Prize-winning physicist, and
Herbert York, a former founding director of the Livermore National
Laboratories _ sent letters to the Senate urging action on the
treaty now.
</P>
<P>
   Haass of the Brookings Institution, who worked in the Bush White
House, said: ``Even if India and Pakistan do sign the test ban,
which India has hinted it may do, the tests make the treaty
something of a mockery. To push for it now says: Get your testing
done and then sign. Why should we reinforce this cynical message
when the problem is not so much further testing as stopping the
deployment, use and transfer of nuclear technology.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the administration maintains that it has
``redoubled'' its commitment to the treaty. The Indian and
Pakistani tests, a senior White House official said, ``demonstrate
the urgent need for such a treaty now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't write the treaty's epitaph just yet,'' the official
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
