<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSI-BOTTLER-NYT &LR;      06-02 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-BOTTLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPSI DISMISSES BOTTLER IT SAYS THREATENED TO JOIN COCA-COLA SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ohio, Fla.) (js) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a highly unusual move, Pepsico broke off a 32-year franchise
agreement with one of its largest independent bottlers on Tuesday,
saying that the bottler had threatened to intervene in Pepsico's
lawsuit against Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pepsi officials, executives from the bottler,
Central Investment Co. of Cincinnati, met with Pepsico's chairman
and chief executive, Roger Enrico, on Monday and insisted that a
number of demands be met within 24 hours or that they would enter
into the suit as a counter-plaintiff on Coke's side. Central
Investment, which also bottles Pepsi products in Fort Lauderdale
and Palm Beach, Fla., demanded more territory in Florida and Ohio,
money for marketing expenses and a limit on prices of concentrate,
Pepsi officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests to us that their real aim was to force us to pay a
stupendous ransom to avoid our very legitimate initiatives against
Coke being compromised or blunted,'' Enrico said in a letter sent
to 200 of the company's bottlers. In a telephone interview on
Tuesday, he called the demands ``the utmost in disloyalty,''
adding, ``We don't need traitors in our family and we're not going
to have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico also sued Central Investment in U.S. district court in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone messages left for Dick Caudill, an executive of
Central Investment Co. named in Enrico's letter, were not returned
on Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   The dispute with the bottler comes amid intense negotiations
between Pepsico and several of its independent bottlers who have
not signed a new contract with the company. The new contract
removes the fountain business from bottlers for the first time, an
important element in Pepsico's reworked strategy to gain market
share from Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot more than Pepsi just acting tough,'' said John
Sicher, publisher of the Beverage Digest, a trade magazine, adding
that Central Investment is Pepsi's ninth-largest independent
bottler. ``A big franchise company does not terminate a major
bottler unless it feels the bottler has seriously breached its
fiduciary duty to the franchise company.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit Pepsico filed against Coca-Cola last month contends
that Coke unfairly pressed food-service distributors not to carry
Pepsi products. Lawyers for Coca-Cola moved last week to have the
suit dismissed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
