<SLUG> BC-NY-UNION-SQUARE-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: COMMERCIAL RENTS RISE NEAR UNION SQUARE IN MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 By MERVYN ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ In late 1996, W &AMP; M Properties spent more than $16
million to buy 58,000 square feet of retail space at the base of
the Zeckendorf Towers condominium on the east side of Union Square.
It was a time of continuing renewal for the once-seedy
neighborhood, and W &AMP; M expected that the rents from the tower's
dozen stores would make the deal profitable. But even W &AMP; M did not
reckon on the rents it is getting today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first year's income was considerably more than we
anticipated,'' said Fred Posniak, vice president of W &AMP; M, which is
owned by the Malkin real estate family. ``And this year's will be
even higher.''
</P>
<P>
   The Union Square area, whose resurgence can be traced to the
1980s, is seeing a spurt of development that includes new housing,
a 14-screen multiplex cinema, a mammoth Virgin music and
entertainment store and two New York University residence halls.
And with the neighborhood's increasing desirability, brokers say, W
&AMP; M and some other retail landlords have been able to charge rents
much higher than they might have imagined a year and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   Posniak said that Marine Midland Bank had just signed a renewal
lease for its 4,556-square-foot branch at the towers at an average
annual rent in excess of $120 a square foot; the rent under its old
lease was less than $90 a square foot. In April, he said, Federal
Express renewed the lease on its 1,495-square-foot space for more
than $140 a square foot. ``Its old lease was less than $90, and
when we bought the space we projected a rent of about $90 a square
foot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, Starbucks leased a 3,500-square-foot store near
15th Street for more than $100 a square foot annually, Posniak
said. The previous tenant, a Woolworth's store, had paid $80 a
square foot. And A &AMP; P, whose original rent for its
30,000-square-foot store was less than $20 a square foot, took an
additional 2,100 square feet for more than $100 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Posniak's tale is being repeated around Union Square. Faith Hope
Consolo of Garrick-Aug Associates Store Leasing said she is
representing a food-service tenant in a lease that is out for
signing at $100 a square foot for 1,800 square feet at 42 Union
Square East, between 16th and 17th Streets. The previous tenant, a
delicatessen, had paid $25 a square foot, Ms. Consolo said.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for space has also increased. Jonathan Switzer
of Winoker Realty said that an 800-square-foot retail space at
24-32 Union Square East had recently been leased to California
Burrito for an annual rent of about $100 a square foot. ``There
were about 10 offers, from businesses like greeting-card dealers
and newspaper stands,'' said Switzer, who represented the building
in the deal. ``Some were as high as $130, but the owner decided to
go with a name, creditworthy tenant,'' he said. The previous
tenant, a food store, had paid about $75 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Consolo said that there is a food shop in a
1,500-square-foot retail space at 3 East 14th Street, not far from
the square, that pays an annual rent of $50 a square foot. The
owner of the building is seeking a new tenant and asking $90 a
square foot, she said, ``and they've already received offers of $90
or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the 1980s, The city's Parks Department began a
series of major improvements to Union Square Park, which, although
home to a celebrated Greenmarket several days a week, had long been
plagued with an image as a haven for drug dealers and the homeless.
A $3.4-million program included turning the park into a large open
space and eliminating its thick undergrowth, hidden paths and
screen of bushes around the perimeter, which the police said
provided cover for drug sales. Also in the '80s, William Zeckendorf
Jr. developed the 670-unit Zeckendorf Towers condominium.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Related Companies began construction on a $130
million, 240-apartment development on the full block south of Union
Square between Broadway and Fourth Avenue. The building will
include a new 75,000-square-foot Virgin music and entertainment
store, a 14-screen United Artists movie theater and a
48,000-square-foot Circuit City electronics store.
</P>
<P>
   Residential tenants began to move in this week, and the retail
sites are expected to begin opening after Labor Day. They will join
the many chains already in the neighborhood, among them Nobody
Beats the Wiz, Barnes &AMP; Noble, Toys `R' Us, Bradlees and P.C.
Richard.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-story, 650-bed New York University residence hall is to
open in September on 14th Street between Fourth and Third avenues,
where Luchow's restaurant stood. Work has begun on a 16-story,
1,000-bed university residence hall and recreation center just two
doors down, on the site of the Palladium. With these two halls, as
well as the existing 700-bed Carlyle Court residence hall, the
university will house about 2,350 university students in and around
Union Square by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a seven-day-a-week, 24-hour-a-day location,''
Posniak said. ``There are already several Off Broadway theaters in
the area, and the old American Savings Bank building on 15th Street
is going to become an Off Broadway theater. The neighborhood is
full of upscale restaurants. The Union Square subway stop has an
entrance in the towers building, and the station is one of the
busiest in the city, with about 250,000 people a day. That's a lot
of bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at Union Square now, Posniak said he had only one
regret. ``All I can tell you,'' he said, ``is that I wish we had
more space there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
