<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRUCK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE GUYS TRYING TO SEE TRUCK TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Stacy Compton looks up, he sees Jeff Gordon, Dale Earnhardt
and Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Compton is fifth in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series heading
into the Pronto Auto Parts 400k Friday night at Texas Motor
Speedway. Ahead of him are some of the biggest names in auto
racing.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not exactly Gordon, Earnhardt and Burton behind the
wheel of the trucks. They're sort of busy on the Winston Cup
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   But they are, directly or indirectly, behind the men who are
behind the wheels of the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The truck that Jack Sprague has driven to the top of the truck
series points standings is owned by Hendrick Motorsports, which
also owns Gordon's Cup car. Gordon himself is listed as a co-owner
of the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hornaday, second in the truck standings, has the backing of
Dale Earnhardt Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ruttman, third in the points, drives for Jack Roush. Roush
owns five Cup cars, including the No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford
driven by Burton. Ruttman drives the No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford in
the truck series.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sauter, fourth in the points, drives for Richard Childress.
Childress also owns Earnhardt's Cup car.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes Compton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got Hendrick and Earnhardt ahead of us, we've got Roush
and Childress up there,'' he said. ``We're an independent right in
the midst of a lot of Winston Cup influence.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes Compton, and fellow independents like Tony Raines,
Bryan Reffner, Randy Tolsma, Rick Carelli and Rick Crawford,
decided underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   An independent team can be competitive in the truck series.
Compton, Raines Reffner, Tolsma, Carelli and Crawford are in the
top 10 in points.
</P>
<P>
   An independent team can win in the series. Compton has won a
race this season, as has Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   But it's difficult for an independent to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner won the inaugural title in 1995 in a truck owned by
Childress. Hornaday won in '96, and Sprague won last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those teams that have Winston Cup backgrounds, as we get past
midseason and start heading down the stretch, I think you'll see
the points race spread out a little bit,'' said Don Hawk, president
of DEI. ``We don't spend all of our money the first six weeks. We
don't spend all Ron's energy the first six weeks. We've got a lot
of staying power.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cup-affiliated teams not only tend to have deeper pockets,
but they have a deeper pool of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's right there at their fingertips,'' said Buddy Morrison,
co-owner of the Arlington-based Reher-Morrison engine shop that is
running a limited schedule in the truck series. ``When you've got a
Winston Cup team that's doing a lot of testing, they're out there
in highly instrumented cars working on little picky things that are
real hard to learn. They make a bunch of tiny improvements. A truck
team that's affiliated gets that automatically. When you get that
kind of expertise, it's a big advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers like Compton and Reffner don't have that edge. Both
drive for teams that started from ground zero last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our own,'' Reffner said. ``We started from scratch,
and that hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   It hurts, but Compton said it doesn't have to be crushing. He
doesn't know Gordon or Burton. Earnhardt has never given him any
advice. But he still is aiming for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a really solid team,'' Compton said. ``We've proven
that. We don't have the Winston Cup influence, but we've got a lot
of things in our favor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
