<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-COX     06-02 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shuttle launched for last rendezvous with Mir
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON, Texas _ The space shuttle Discovery made a flawless
blastoff Tuesday for the ninth and last shuttle docking with
Russia's space station Mir.
</P>
<P>
   But problems on Mir that threatened to delay the flight might be
well taken as a warning that building the International Space
Station, scheduled to start in November, will likely face
unexpected complications and dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery lifted off precisely on schedule a few minutes after 6
p.m. Eastern Daylight Time from Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
Once the 4.5-million pound rocket cleared the launch tower, control
of its nearly 10-day mission shifted to NASA's Johnson Space Center
here.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes of the countdown, the temperature still was
registering 95 degrees, prompting launch controllers to keep close
watch on the hydraulic systems at the pad, especially the movable
walkway. The limit for launching is 99 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 miles above Earth, Mir's automatic thrusters were
firing on cue, keeping the station on an unswerving course. The
cosmonauts fixed the steering system Monday, three days after it
shut down. Without automatic steering, Mir would have been too
shaky for a shuttle docking.
</P>
<P>
   The space center opened an auditorium to the public, where more
than 800 people watched the launch on three giant screens and
veteran shuttle commander Kevin Kregel gave a running commentary.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle and its six crew members are to dock with Mir on
Thursday. It's the last planned shuttle visit to the aging space
station before Russia abandons it next year, then drives it back
into earth's atmosphere for a fiery destruction. It's also the last
scheduled flight for Discovery before U.S. Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio,
rides it back into orbit in October.
</P>
<P>
   The next era in human space dwellings is scheduled to begin Nov.
20 with Russia's launch of the first element of the International
Space Station, the control module. It's to be followed Dec. 3 by
space shuttle Endeavor's launch with the space station's docking
node, which will connect the control module and several others to
be launched in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Former Troy resident Nancy Currie will play a key role on that
mission, using the shuttle's remote manipulator arm to help connect
the U.S. And Russian modules.
</P>
<P>
   A last-minute problem on Mir threatened to delay Discovery's
launch. On Sunday, a motion-control computer failed, leaving the
sprawling station to tumble slowly in its orbit. Mir's Russian crew
replaced the computer with a new one but continued to wrestle with
the control problem until declaring it fixed Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest of many problems that have bedeviled and
sometimes imperiled Mir's crews, including U.S. astronauts. It
prompted Andy Thomas, who has spent the last 4 months on Mir, to
ask Discovery's mission controllers whether the problem would delay
his return to earth. He said last week he was ``very keen'' for
Discovery to pick him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to a certain extent, but, hey, maybe it's our
signature. It certainly adds some drama,'' said Frank Culbertson,
director of NASA's shuttle-Mir program.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, problems _ sometimes fatal or life-threatening _ have
accompanied all space station programs since the Soviet Union's
Salyut 1 became the world's first space station in 1971:
</P>
<P>
   E The first three cosmonauts launched to Salyut 1 could not
board the station because of docking problems. The next crew
occupied it for 23 days, but all three died during their return to
earth when their capsule depressurized.
</P>
<P>
   E America's first station, Skylab, lost one of its two
electricity-generating solar panels and an insulating shield when
it was orbited in May 1973. After the last crew left Skylab in
1974, it fell out of orbit in 1979, sooner than expected.
</P>
<P>
   E Mir has been in service for more than a decade, but it has
experienced a series of mishaps, especially within the last two
years. Fire broke out in February 1997, forcing the crew to don
oxygen masks. An oxygen generator failed the next month, leaving
the crew with a two-month air supply. Last June, a seven-ton cargo
rocket collided with the station, poking a hole in one of its
pressurized modules and damaging a solar panel. The computers that
manage control and power have had problems ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-nation International Space Station will be far bigger and
more complex than any of its predecessors. It will have far more
capabilities, but it has already had more than its share of
problems. The upcoming launches originally were scheduled for 1997,
then pushed back to this summer because of Russian delays in
delivering the all-important service module. Continuing delays
prompted the latest schedule slips.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, space station cost estimates continue to soar above
$20 billion, not counting launch costs.
</P>
<P>
   The nine shuttle dockings with Mir and seven long-duration
flights on the station by U.S. astronauts are what NASA calls Phase
One of the International Space Station program. It began in 1995
and ends with this flight. Culbertson said the problems encountered
during Phase One have been a benefit because they gave lessons in
how to detail with unexpected problems.
</P>
<P>
   If the International Space Station follows the historical trend,
it will give plenty of lessons of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
