<HEADER>
A1064 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIGHT-TRUCK-SAFETY-30     06-02 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHT-TRUCK-SAFETY-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD EXPLORER HAS HIGHER CHANCE OF CAUSING INJURY, TESTS FIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mich., Canada)   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ The first round of American crash tests
analyzing what happens when light trucks hit cars has found that a
Ford Explorer, a mid-size sport utility vehicle, was twice as
likely as a mid-size car, mini-van or pickup truck to inflict a
critical or severe injury to a car driver's chest and somewhat more
likely to hurt a car driver's head and neck, according to test
results released at an international conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ricardo Martinez, the administrator of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration, which conducted the tests this
spring in Ohio, said that the results reflected a real-world
problem in which sport utility vehicles inflict more damage on
cars. But auto industry officials were deeply divided on the value
of the tests, with some saying that the tests provided little if
any new information while others said that the tests were only the
first steps in what could be a long research program.
</P>
<P>
   With help from a private contractor, the government slammed four
different vehicles traveling at 33 miles an hour into the driver's
side of four stationary Honda Accords. The four striking vehicles
were a two-wheel-drive Ford Explorer, a Chevrolet Lumina mid-size
sedan, a Chevrolet S-10 pickup and a Dodge Grand Caravan mini-van.
After checking the dummies in the driver's seat of each Accord,
regulators determined that the mid-size car, the mini-van and
pickup would each have had an 18 to 20 percent chance of inflicting
a severe injury to the chest of a real person and a 2 percent
chance or less of inflicting a critical injury. The Explorer would
have had a 40 percent chance of inflicting a severe injury and a 5
percent chance of inflicting a critical injury, according to the
test results.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Explorer is one of the smaller American-made sport utility
vehicles, and the two-wheel-drive version, which was used in the
test, rides lower and is more likely to override a car in a
collision than the four-wheel-drive version. Its score for damage
to the Accord dummy's head and neck was 395, on a scale for which
1,000 is likely to be fatal. By comparison, the pickup's score was
314, the car's score was 242 and the Caravan's score was 193.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the striking vehicles also had dummies in their front
seats. The car provided the most head and neck protection for the
dummy in its own driver's seat, while the Explorer scored second
best. But the car also provided the worst head and neck protection
for a dummy in its front passenger seat, while the Explorer did
second-worst. The Explorer fared best on chest protection for both
dummies.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said that the tests showed that light trucks _ a
category including pickups and mini-vans as well as sport utility
vehicles _ were clearly incompatible with cars during collisions.
``It's not a question of whether or not the compatibility issue
exists,'' said Martinez, a former emergency room physician. ``It
does, everyone knows it does, the question is why does it exist and
what can we do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said his agency would conduct four front-to-front crash
tests this summer and develop computer simulations for further
research. The goal is to determine how vehicles can be redesigned
to make car occupants safer without making light truck occupants
less safe.
</P>
<P>
   Light trucks account for only one-third of the vehicles on the
road, but now kill more people in cars than other cars do. Martinez
said the mismatches in collisions appeared to reflect the greater
height, greater weight and stiffer frames of light trucks. But he
said further research was needed to determine the relative
importance of these issues and whether any new regulations might be
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and auto industry officials spoke at an international
traffic safety conference in this factory town across the Detroit
River from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The auto lobbyists and executives here acknowledged that some
safety problem existed on the nation's roads but questioned whether
the test results provided any new information.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Felrice, a former top regulator who is now the director
for regulatory affairs at the American Automobile Manufacturers
Association, a Washington lobbying group for Detroit's Big Three
automakers, said that it was unclear why the pickup and mini-van
inflicted virtually the same damage as the mid-sized car.
</P>
<P>
   While mini-vans are built much like cars, pickups are built like
sport utility vehicles. Regulators said they had expected the car
to inflict less damage.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have crashed hundreds of cars into each other over
the years and can usually predict what will happen. But only now
are regulators beginning to examine light truck collisions with
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's test results also held several small surprises for
which regulators had no immediate explanation. While the Explorer
inflicted the most damage to the head, neck and chest of the dummy
in the Accord driver's seat, the mini-van did the most damage to
the dummy's pelvis. While pelvis injuries receive less attention
from regulators because they are less likely to be fatal, such
injuries can still be debilitating.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Petrauskas, Ford's vice president for safety and
environmental affairs, said that the damage done by the mini-van,
which has a low front end, showed that there were trade-offs
involved in developing lower-riding sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Ford manager said in a recent interview that, among
other safety features, the company was designing new suspensions
that would allow sport utilities to ride closer down to the wheels,
reducing the risk that they would override cars' bumpers. Mrs.
Petrauskas refused to discuss Ford's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Petrauskas said that Ford had crashed an Explorer into the
side of a Taurus and found less damage than regulators found in
their test into the side of the Accord. She also questioned
Mercedes' claim to have produced a safer sport utility vehicle,
saying that Ford had crashed a Mercedes sport utility into the side
of a Taurus and done the same damage as with the Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said that his goal was to persuade the industry to
conduct research and eventually make design changes, rather than
pursue a lengthy regulatory process. ``I want to focus on corporate
responsibility,'' he said. ``Anybody can fight the industry _
changing the industry, that's a little more work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
