 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; STOP AND SMELL THE FL ... &LR;
</P>
<P>
   J &UR; ohn Gipson &LR;  of NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center has informed
members of the American Geophysical Union that wind and ocean
current changes caused by El Nino have resulted in the Earth
rotating in an uncommonly leisurely fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy is going from the Earth into the atmosphere,'' he
said at a meeting last week. ``The Earth is slowing down.'' This
has caused an increase (that peaked in February) in the average
length of a day, by about half of a thousandth of a second. ``El
Nino's given us this extra time,'' said Gipson.
</P>
<P>
   Wincing at the possibility of millions of people sitting around
twiddling their thumbs, Personals passes along this time-spending
idea from Self magazine: ``Keep a hair journal of a new cut or
color, adding Polaroids and jotting down observations about styling
time, reactions to weather and how long color lasts.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Other optimistic notes:  &UR; Darryl Forman &LR;  noticed a small
wooden sign in a newly planted San Francisco flower garden: ``Grow,
Damn It.'' Meanwhile, the woman in the voting booth next to
 &UR; M.T. &LR; 's at the John Muir school in Berkeley was punching her card
so forcefully that he could hear the staccato rhythm, punctuated by
her equally audible rap: ``Why do we have to vote for these
jerks?''
</P>
