<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BYSTANDER-KILLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK WOMAN KILLED BY STRAY BULLET
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A kind of murder that has become increasingly rare in
recent years returned to New York City on Monday night when a
19-year-old woman was shot and killed on a Brooklyn street corner
by a stray bullet that was apparently intended for someone else,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Sheamba John King, 19, had just used a pay phone
around the corner from her apartment in East Flatbush and was
talking to some friends around 9:30 p.m. when a burst of gunfire
crackled and a single shot struck her in the back and killed her,
the police said. Detectives believe that the fatal bullet was one
of about 10 shots fired by a group of young men having a fight, but
said that they were not sure who the intended target was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that she was not the intended target,'' said Betsy
Herzog, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Such random shootings have become rare in recent years. As the
murder rate has plummeted _ there were 770 homicides reported in
the city last year, down from 2,245 in 1990 _ the number of people
killed by strangers has fallen the fastest. In the last two years,
roughly 20 percent of murder victims were killed by strangers, down
from 37 percent in 1993, police statistics show. And the number of
innocent bystanders shot has fallen each year since 1991, when a
spate of random shootings led the police to keep a tally of such
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The killing devastated Ms. King's family. ``She was a very loved
child,'' sobbed her grandmother, Emily John Ocsi, 65.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Ms. King got married. It was also the year that she
became an American citizen, after having immigrated with her family
from Guyana seven years ago. And it was the year she was to
graduate from Erasmus High School. She had already had her portrait
drawn in pencil, wearing her cap and gown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were planning to have a big party July 9,'' Mrs. Ocsi said,
clutching the graduation portrait to her chest. ``It was for her
graduation, and for her 20th birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ocsi was the first member of the family to come to the
United States from Guyana, back in 1976. In 1991 she sponsored her
daughter, Barbara, and her four grandchildren, Marcy, Carl,
Samantha, and Sheamba _who was the youngest _ for citizenship. They
all moved to Brooklyn, eventually all settling in the same
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so happy,'' Mrs. Ocsi recalled. ``I didn't know her
then. She was born while I was over here. Now we were all
together.''
</P>
<P>
   As she sat in the apartment that Ms. King shared with her mother
and siblings at 1354 New York Ave., in the Vanderveer Estates in
East Flatbush, Mrs. Ocsi broke down and wept for her granddaughter,
crying, ``Sheamba gone, Sheamba gone.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Ms. King's friends, Sheba Williams, 17, tried to comfort
her. ``Don't cry now,'' she said softly, rubbing the wailing
woman's shoulders. ``Don't cry now.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends remembered Ms. King as a jokester who was full of life,
who loved to dance to the latest reggae hits at parties and who had
hoped to become a hairdresser after graduating from high school.
She already worked after school giving shampoos at True Skill, a
hair salon on Nostrand Avenue. And she often did the hair of
friends and woman in the neighborhood, giving them braids, weaves
and curls.
</P>
<P>
   She was supposed to do a friend's hair the night she was killed.
``I had just left her on the corner,'' recalled Doretta Williams,
22. ``It must have been two minutes after I left her she was shot.
I said, `Come fix my hair.' She said she'd come later.''
</P>
<P>
   Detectives at the 67th Precinct were questioning several men
Tuesday about the shooting. An investigator who spoke on the
condition of anonymity said that the police believe that one of the
men Ms. King was standing with may have been in a dispute earlier
that night and may have been the target of the fusillade. It
appeared no one besides Ms. King was hit, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard the shots,'' said a friend, Afana Johnson, 20, who
was in her apartment at the time. ``We were like, `They're always
shooting, those gangs.' Then we heard someone yelling, `Sheamba
shot, Sheamba shot.' We went down. She was lying on the floor. We
were praying she'd pull through. Her eyes were open. You hear about
things like this every day, but you don't think it will come so
close to home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't deserve this, she didn't deserve a bullet like
that, she didn't have to die like that,'' Ms. Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
