<HEADER>
A1081 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTCHALET-LADN     06-02 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTCHALET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORT CHALET CHAIR HANDS OUT $1.8 MILLION IN SHARES TO EMPLOYEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a gesture so generous that it elicited two
standing ovations from the company's managers and longtime
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Norbert Olberz, Sport Chalet chairman and interim chief
executive officer, told 109 workers Tuesday that he was giving them
300,000 shares, collectively, of his own company stock as a reward
for a year of record earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I salute the 109 new owners,'' said the 73-year-old former
pastry chef, who moved from a small town near Bonn, Germany, and
bought the first Sport Chalet store in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a country, where a poor immigrant can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the company were handed out based on seniority.
Ten-year employees received 2,000 shares, plus 100 shares for every
year thereafter. Thus, at Tuesday's close of $6, a 15-year veteran
of the company would get about $15,000 worth of shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company will benefit from employees who will have more
pride in their work,'' said Tom Ishkanian, an 18-year company
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Olberz, whose ownership will be reduced to 65 percent after the
$1.8 million gift, agreed. ``Everybody will work like an owner.''
</P>
<P>
   The shares represent about 4.6 percent of Sport Chalet, which
has 6.5 million shares outstanding. About 8 percent of the
company's work force received a share of the gift.
</P>
<P>
   But recipients, who cheered and whistled as the announcement was
made at company headquarters in La Canada, a Los Angeles-area
suburb, early Tuesday, can't sell the stock for two years in
accordance with Securities and Exchange Commission regulations.
They also will lose the stock if they're fired or go to work for a
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't faze Barbara Gagne, an employee for the last 17
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally unexpected,'' she said, all smiles. ``I'll just
keep it and let it grow. Maybe I'll pass it on to my children and
grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though workers can't sell the stock yet, the law requires
they pay taxes on it immediately. Sport Chalet said it will lend
money to workers at market rates to meet those obligations.
Employees can pay it back through payroll deductions lasting up to
four years.
</P>
<P>
   The stock gift couldn't have come at a better time for the
company, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   It should motivate workers at a time when Sport Chalet faces
increased competition in the marketplace, said Bob McGee, an editor
at Sporting Goods Intelligence, a trade publication in Glen Mills,
Penn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this offer will breed goodwill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Authority, the nation's largest sporting goods chain,
will be entering California this year, with four stores opening in
the Los Angeles area by fall, McGee said. Oshman's is expanding in
Southern California this fall as well.
</P>
<P>
   And Sportmart, which was purchased by sporting goods retailer
Gart and already competes with Sport Chalet in Southern California,
has gained clout thanks to the merger.
</P>
<P>
   After losing money in 1996, Sport Chalet lured Craig Levra _
former vice president of store operations at Sports Authority _ to
become president and chief operating officer. He's led the effort
to improve operations.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year 1998, the 19-store Sport Chalet reported a
39 percent increase in profit to $3.2 million (49 cents a diluted
share) from $2.3 million (35 cents) a year ago. Sales rose 3.9
percent to $143 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, earnings dropped to $281,000 (4 cents)
from $347,000 (5 cents) a year ago on sales of $37.1 million vs.
$34.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sport Chalet also is drawing plans to build a new corporate
office at the same La Canada location, to be completed by the
summer of 1999. The 70,000-square-foot project will encompass a
50,000-square-foot store and the rest for corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of more than $7 million, the project will be part of a
$31 million shopping center complex to be built on 11 acres on
Foothill Boulevard east of Angeles Crest Highway. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
