<SLUG> BC-NY-TWAFLIGHT800-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAMAGE-LIMIT LAW DOES NOT APPLY TO FLIGHT 800 LAWSUITS  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A law that limits damages in high seas accidents will
not apply to lawsuits filed on behalf of the passengers killed in
the crash of TWA Flight 800 two years ago, a U.S. District Court
judge ruled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision could have a significant impact on the 145 cases
filed on behalf of passengers' families and estates. The Death on
the High Seas Act, enacted in 1920, says that plaintiffs can only
recover damages in proportion to monetary losses caused by a
person's death. Such losses typically include lost income or
financial support provided to a spouse or children.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, by Judge Robert Sweet of U.S. district court in
Manhattan, comes in response to a motion filed by defendants in the
lawsuits, including TWA and Boeing. The defendants had asked the
judge to limit possible damages under the law.
</P>
<P>
   TWA Flight 800, which took off from Kennedy International
Airport en route to Paris on July 17, 1996, exploded in the air and
crashed into the ocean off Long Island, New York. All 230 people on
board were killed. Investigators have said the Boeing 747's center
wing fuel tank exploded, but the reason for the explosion is still
undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   Had Sweet applied the Death on the High Seas Act to the TWA
Flight 800 cases, the plaintiffs would have been forbidden to sue
for emotional pain on behalf of the families of those killed in the
crash. But Tuesday's ruling means that plaintiffs will be able to
seek higher damages, particularly in the cases of children and
other people who did not earn large amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a child's case, where the child is not contributing any
money to the parent, there is little pecuniary loss,'' said Lee
Kreindler, the lead lawyer for the plaintiffs. ``All the
non-monetary losses can now be essentially recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 25-page decision, Sweet said the act did not apply
because the TWA Flight 800 crash occurred within U.S. territorial
waters. Referring to a 1988 proclamation by President Ronald
Reagan, Sweet said territorial waters extended 12 nautical miles
from the shore at the time of the TWA Flight 800 disaster.
According to the National Transportation Safety Board, TWA Flight
800 crashed 8 nautical miles from the southern shore of Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet's decision, the first to consider the law's application in
such circumstances, turns on his legal interpretation of the words
``high seas'' within the law. Although the term is not clearly
spelled out, Sweet interpreted it to mean waters outside the
country's territorial jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, spokesmen for TWA and Boeing declined to say whether
the companies would appeal. Doug Webb, a Boeing spokesman, said the
company was ``reviewing our legal options.''
</P>
<P>
   TWA's damages in any lawsuits are already limited by the Warsaw
Convention, which limits legal damages in airline disasters to
$75,000 per passenger. The only way the damages could be increased
is if the plaintiffs could prove that the airline acted with
willful misconduct. In a statement issued on Tuesday, the airline
said, ``There has been no finding in any of the extensive
investigations of any deficiencies in TWA's operations that caused
this tragedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
