r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-02 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS VICTIMIZE SCHOOLKIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - The courtroom filled up 20 minutes befo re gavel
time, starched collars all around, fine silk ties. The players
entered amid much hand-shaking and many hiyas. Everyone knew
everyone. The room buzzed with good cheer.
</P>
<P>
   You could sit through a thousand court proceedings and never
hear
</P>
<P>
   such a noise.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was special, though, a reunion. The politicians and
their lawyers have been gathering at the Arizona Supreme Court
building every few years, all decade long.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion: Fixing Arizona's public schools. The r esult:
Always more shame.
</P>
<P>
   This sad past went ignored as the room filled up _ same as 1993,
same as 1996, same as 1997. The same as every other time the
Arizona Supreme Court shot down a school-funding fix.
</P>
<P>
   The people we elect have ne ver been much for history,
understand. Not much for observing it, not much for making it. And
surely not much for teaching it.
</P>
<P>
   The gavel slapped twice. In filed the justices, five black
robes. The gavel slapped again, beginning Round Four.
</P>
<P>
   One lawyer argued for Students FIRST, Gov. Jane Hull's $371
million plan to build schools. Next stood three lawyers opposed,
there for poor school districts and rich, and for the state
superintendent of schools. They hate the plan's ``opt-o ut''
provision and its limits on bonding.
</P>
<P>
   For an hour, the five on the bench asked questions. The lawyers
talked and banked a few hundred bucks more. We'll have a winner in
a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The loser I can name right now.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona 's schoolkids.
</P>
<P>
   They lost because it's been seven years and still this lawsuit
stands unresolved. They've lost thanks to seven years of
legislative ignorance, legislative gutlessness and legislative
delusion.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years of subpar schoo ls. Seven years of dragged wingtips.
Seven years of press conference lies.
</P>
<P>
   The astonishing thing wasn't the debate, or the thought that
Students FIRST might die and leave an entire school system again at
Square One. It was that politicians l ike House Speaker Jeff
Grocost and Senate President Brenda Burns had the nerve to show
face. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Said Burns, a legislator since 1987: ``I don't feel like there's
any failure at all. ... It is very difficult to change so
drastically the wa y we do things. There's a comfort level there.
The court clearly wanted a major change. We have provided that, and
it takes a lot to get that done.''
</P>
<P>
   So true, so true. It takes a lot of kids flushed like waste, a
lot of hopes snuffed. Seven years' worth, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of that wasted time can be found on Durango Street,
in another kind of courtroom. The juvenile kind.
</P>
<P>
   There, wheat fabric covers the walls and the sound of sobbing
dominates. I've heard it often, an d did again Tuesday, with Burns'
boast fresh in my ears.
</P>
<P>
   Day in, day out, eight courtrooms brim with delinquents and
parents, losers current and losers future. Every day, Arizona fails
some more.
</P>
<P>
   Lousy schools _ thanks mostly to lous y legislators _ deserve
much of the blame. Figure lame education ranks in the top three on
the causing-criminals scale, beside garbage parents and poverty.
Figure better schools would save kid after kid. Not all, not most,
but some.
</P>
<P>
   I watche d kids in need of saving for hours. Every minute felt
like, oh, seven years.
</P>
<P>
   One boy, 12 years old, sat hands and ankles cuffed, his mother
to his left. He was slender and flame-eyed. The charge: He'd drawn
a picture of himself gunning down students and staffers. He'd spent
three weeks in county detention, awaiting a shrink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to go home,'' he begged.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said no, not yet. That answer made sense given the
charge, but it would've been better to have no ne ed of the
question. For seven years, our politicians could've helped make
sure. They couldn't be bothered.
</P>
<P>
   They patted backs, instead, and had reunions. Always, and again
Tuesday, they stood in the wrong courtroom. &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be r eached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
