<SLUG> BC-SPY-PLEA-BARGAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN PLEADS GUILTY TO SPYING FOR EAST GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of three former campus radicals arrested in
October in an espionage sting has agreed to plead guilty to spying
for East Germany, lawyers in the case said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   James Clark, who worked as a private investigator and an Army
paralegal, would plead guilty in exchange for a reduced sentence.
He and his co-defendants, Terry Squillacote, a former Pentagon
lawyer, and her husband, Kurt Stand, who was a representative of an
international workers' union, face life sentences on charges of
spying for Communist intelligence services since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said all three were spies for East Germany.
Stand, enlisted by his father, recruited Clark and then his wife,
the indictment said. Clark was charged with espionage and
conspiracy to commit espionage by delivering top secret defense
documents to East Germany between 1979 and 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI obtained old files from the East German spy service in
1995 and decoded them; the FBI says it found the three defendants'
names in those files. The agency then devised a sting operation to
trap the three into admissions of espionage, setting up a ``false
flag'' operation designed to make them believe that the South
African government wanted them to work as intelligence agents.
</P>
<P>
   Clark succeeded Stand as chairman of the Communist Party's youth
wing at the University of Wisconsin's Milwaukee campus in 1974,
where Stand met Ms. Squillacote. All three were dedicated lifelong
Marxists, but their lawyers and defenders said after their arrest
that they were guilty of nothing more than loyalty to that
ideology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
