<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1097 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-TEXT-NY     06-02 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCERPTS OF COURT PAPERS FILED BY INDEPENDENT COUNSEL
</HEADLINE>
  (With CLINTON-STARR) 
 (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following are excerpts from court papers filed with
the Supreme Court on Tuesday by Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, in response to President Clinton's court motions against
Starr's appeal for an expedited review of privilege claims by the
Supreme Court in the Monica Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The critical fact justifying this Court's review _ and review
before judgment in the Court of Appeals _ still remains: by
asserting a purported privilege for governmental attorney-client
communications, the President of the United States has directly
challenged the ability of the Federal grand jury to obtain evidence
of possible criminal acts by the President and others. This is,
save for Nixon, without parallel in the history of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Because the President himself (among others) is under criminal
investigation, the grand jury, this office, the President, the
Congress, and the nation have a compelling interest that the matter
be resolved quickly and definitively. More months of protracted
litigation are inimical to the nation's well-being. The facts are
needed, and they are needed now.
</P>
<P>
   This is not our view alone. To the contrary, the President
himself stated in January of this year that the American people are
entitled to more rather than less, sooner rather than later. That
is still true. We will be blunt: the nation has a compelling
interest that this criminal investigation of the President of the
United States conclude as quickly as possible _ that indictments be
brought, possible reports for impeachment proceedings issued, and
nonprosecution decisions announced. This Court's immediate review
would powerfully serve that vital goal.
</P>
<P>
   The President's response treats this as a matter-of-fact
investigation. But the unhappy fact is that, at the determination
of the Attorney General herself, a President is under serious
criminal investigation. That unfortunate circumstance is a rare
occurrence in our nation's history. A President who invokes
governmental privileges that have the effect of thwarting such an
investigation is even rarer. (Only 2 of 42 Presidents have seen fit
to do so.) And issues involving the President that arise during the
course of such an investigation are necessarily vital to the
functioning of the executive branch and to the people as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, few issues more directly implicate the rule of
law than a President using, or appearing to use, newly asserted
governmental privileges that serve, at least in part, to protect
the personal interests of the President himself (and his close
associates.) . . . The President argues that, unlike in Nixon,
there are no impeachment proceedings under way. The leadership of
the House of Representatives has indicated that it awaits a report
from this office before it will consider whether to hold
impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the White House has stated that the specter of
such proceedings substantially impacts the orderly administration
of the executive branch. In this regard, the Court may wish to
consider the need submissions presented to the District Court. The
evidence contained therein demonstrates the importance of Mr.
Lindsey's testimony to the investigation and to the weighty
statutory responsibility imposed on this office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB-COX     06-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three students charged after pop-bottle bombs explode at Ohio
school
 &HT;    By Lou Grieco and Joanne Huist Smith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Three students were charged with a total of 13
delinquency felony counts after they built and detonated three
pop-bottle bombs at the Trotwood-Madison High School in suburban
Dayton, Ohio Monday, police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The students, two aged 15 and one 16, remain in Montgomery
County Juvenile Detention Center. Trotwood-Madison School District
Superintendent Samuel C. Brewer said the students have been
suspended and may be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   With school shootings across the country since October _
including those in Springfield, Ore., West Paducah, Ky., Pearl,
Miss., Jonesboro, Ark., and Edinboro, Pa. _ school officials can't
afford to take chances with students and weapons, Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very unfortunate incident,'' Brewer said. ``It was
certainly disturbing. Youngsters need to learn that decisions that
they make can be harmful to themselves or to others.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second such case in a southwest Ohio school since
Friday, when police discovered a crude explosive device in a
student's bookbag at Little Miami High School in Morrow, Ohio,
between Dayton and Cincinnati. Police said the teen who made it
showed off his handiwork to friends.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, police said the students had no intent to harm
others. It was more of a ``look what I can do'' scenario, Trotwood
Police Lt. Fred Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Morrow incident,''we and the police believe the
student had no intent to use the device to harm himself, other
students or staff,'' Little Miami School Superintendent Michael
Verelli II said. ``It appears to be a case of when you create
something you want to show it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Miami school staff heard about the homemade bomb after
three students told them the student held a private ``show and
tell'' for a group of students.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured and no property damage was reported in either
case. In Trotwood, the students made the devices by combining
household cleaning products into three plastic soda bottles, then
went outside and threw them. One landed on school grounds, two
others on a nearby lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Police Capt. Jim Borland said the chemicals become unstable
after they are mixed and could have exploded in the students'
hands. The acid formed would have burned them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials heard loud ``pops,'' investigated, then sent
the students to the principal's office.
</P>
<P>
   The three students were shocked when police arrived, Borland
said. ``They didn't realize it was going to be such a big deal,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The students were charged with delinquency by reason of
possessing a dangerous ordnance on school grounds and manufacturing
a dangerous ordnance, Borland said.
</P>
<P>
   The three appeared Tuesday in Montgomery County Juvenile Court,
where Judge Nick Kuntz entered denials of responsibility for each
boy. The Montgomery County Prosector's Office has not decided
whether to ask Kuntz to transfer the boys to adult court, said
spokesman Jim Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Two are in the temporary custody of foster parents through
Montgomery County Children Services, Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley Crime Lab is testing the device found at Little
Miami to determine how dangerous it is, Warren County Prosecutor
Tim Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old Morrow student made the device after a friend
called him on a boast that he could make a bomb, Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow police took the student into custody Friday. He remains
in the Warren County Juvenile Detention Center, where he will
undergo psychological testing. He was suspended from school and
could be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   In Trotwood, Brewer said he is waiting for a report from the
school principal before deciding whether to expel them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes kids just don't think. You see the apologetic look
on their faces after the fact, but by then it's too late,'' said
Verelli, the Little Miami school superintendant.
</P>
<P>
   Educators across the Miami Valley look forward to the end of a
school year marred by violence and threats of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to pull out all the stops to show kids it's still
safe to go to school,'' said Robert Bixler, principal of Little
Miami High School. ``Our parents know what's going on. When they
call, we invite them to come in walk down the halls and see that
everything is okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer break for Trotwood and Little Miami begins Thursday
afternoon, but school officials are preparing for September
</P>
<P>
   After many school violence incidents around the country, people
later said there were warning signs. Trotwood-Madison
Superintendent Brewer said the district plans to develop a list of
warning signs to help staff determine if a student is headed toward
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``These incidents are like a cry for help and attention,''
Brewer said. ``We as a society have to decide if we value our
children more than guns or weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Grieco and Joanne Huist Smith write for the Dayton Daily
News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JAZZ-BULLS-NYT &LR;      06-02 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN A KEY TO BULLS' CHANCES AGAINST JAZZ  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Dennis Rodman sauntered into the Delta Center
and stood before everyone like a neon sign. No wonder Las Vegas is
such a lure for him. He can hear the dice rolling from the shadows
of the Wasatch Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Vegas being so close, you can't control his appetite for
it,'' Michael Jordan said on Tuesday before the Bulls practiced for
Game 1 of the NBA finals on Wednesday against the Jazz. ``I can't
tell Dennis not to be Dennis. You just have to ask him to be Dennis
on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been Rodman's problem when the court is occupied by
Karl Malone. Rodman has been unable to slip around Malone's shadow
for rebounds, incapable of nudging him outside his range and
hard-pressed to stay out of foul trouble. His ineffectiveness was
obvious during the National Basketball Association's championship
series last year. So Rodman created drama off the court by darting
off to Nevada and by throwing darts at the Mormons. ``I feel like
I'm home,'' Rodman said. ``It's good to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is not like last year, when the Bulls had a safety net
for the unfocused Rodman: Brian Williams. He is not there to save
the Bulls this year. He's with the Pistons. It's up to Rodman to
make Malone work for his shots in what has always been a difficult
matchup for the Bulls' jumpy forward. It seems Rodman's usual blend
of elbows and mind blows ricochet off Malone's steel vault-like
frame. It is tough to get under the skin of a man who appears
stuffed with boulders, and harder to sneak inside the head of
player wise enough to ignore you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch some of the things Dennis does to other players,''
Malone said after the Jazz's practice. ``And it seems like a lot of
the young players want to show him how tough they are. I just take
this approach: play the game. I've seen it all. I've heard it all.
I've done half of it. I also realize for us to win a championship,
I can't allow someone to take me out of my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman failed in this attempt to divert Malone's game during
last year's final. Malone simply walked away from Rodman's act,
leaving the spring-filled forward crestfallen with a frustrating
2.3 points and 7.7 rebounds a game. In turn, Malone puffed out his
Popeye chest for 23.8 points and 10.3 rebounds a game.
</P>
<P>
   As little as Rodman accomplished, his disappearance was not
catastrophic. Williams was there in the low post, shadowing Malone
on the fast break and keeping him occupied underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rodman will be asked to do the same. The Bulls need him to
limit Malone just enough to keep them from having to send two men
to him, which only opens up the 3-point opportunities for Bryon
Russell and Jeff Hornacek. It is Rodman's chore to protect the
Bulls from an impact that could turn the series in the Jazz's
favor. Malone certainly altered the regular-season outcome for the
Jazz as Utah won both games this season against the Bulls. He
averaged 32.5 points and 9.5 rebounds in two games. Rodman came up
with 2 points and 9 rebounds for the series.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodman is not ready to spew credit Malone's way. Instead, he
continued his tirade on officials Tuesday. ``It's hard to guard
Malone,'' Rodman said. ``Just the slightest touch, and you get
called for a foul.''
</P>
<P>
   This was referee bashing, Part II. In the Bulls' series with the
Pacers, Rodman attributed the rebounding success of Antonio Davis
and Dale Davis to the officials, too. After averaging 16 rebounds a
game in the first two rounds of the playoffs, his output fell to an
average of 9.9 against the Pacers in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The more Rodman struggled, the more he pouted. Part of his angst
was over his in-and-out role in the starting lineup. Toni Kukoc was
Coach Phil Jackson's choice to start with a favorable matchup
against the Pacers. This time, with Malone posing such a menacing
presence, Jackson is leaning toward making Rodman his starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Dennis is ready,'' Scottie Pippen said. ``We have to
have him playing at the level that we're used to seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   In case he is not, Jackson could opt to bring Dickey Simpkins
off the bench or slide Pippen over on occasion to face Malone.
Kukoc has little chance of defending Malone. And there is no
Williams to save them. Rodman knows all of this, of course. He
realizes what kind of pressure is on him. Whatever he does in his
spare time, the Bulls will need his full-time attention on Malone
whose ability to block Rodman out with his body and mind has so
often turned the Bulls' neon star into a wallflower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to stop Malone,'' Rodman said. ``I have to limit him to
18 or 20 points a game, and not give him 35. It's time to roll. And
not make excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
