<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BREEDER, SMALL HORSE AND LARGE SHOT AT HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The breeder of Real Quiet doesn't think the colt was
an ``ugly duckling,'' as racing people say. And he doesn't agree
that his mother was ``a blue-collar mare.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't deny that Real Quiet was born with crooked legs and
had operations on both knees as a yearling, or that he grew so thin
from lack of exercise that he was nicknamed ``The Fish.'' Or that
he was sold for the giveaway price of $17,000 because it looked as
though he might break down. And he certainly doesn't think his colt
is a ``freak'' who has outraced his pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   So, the breeder, Eduardo Gaviria of Bogota, Colombia, will fly
to New York to join the crowd on Saturday at Belmont Park when his
underprivileged horse tries to win the 130th Belmont Stakes and
sweep the Triple Crown. It is a feat accomplished only 11 times,
the last by Affirmed 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If he does it, Real Quiet will top off his journey from rags to
riches. He has already banked $1.9 million, and he would earn
$600,000 more for a victory in the Belmont plus a $5 million bonus
offered by the Visa corporation for sweeping the Triple Crown,
which comprises the Kentucky Derby, the Preakness and the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Breeding shares in Real Quiet are already being offered for
$525,000 each, with an ultimate syndication value of $21 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I kick myself for selling him so cheaply?'' Gaviria asked
on the telephone the other day from his office in Bogota.
``Absolutely not. I have no regrets. I am so proud of Real Quiet
and what he's achieved. If I had kept him, he wouldn't be where he
is today. The money aspect is not very important at this time. I've
been rewarded far beyond my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody close to Real Quiet has been rewarded beyond their
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, who was training quarter horses until he switched
to thoroughbreds 11 years ago, thought his big horse this year was
Indian Charlie, who won the Santa Anita Derby. But Real Quiet ran
second there, then outran Indian Charlie in the Kentucky Derby and
took over the barn.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pegram, the owner of Real Quiet, said: ``My reaction to the
criticisms of Real Quiet? Give me the cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in buying horses with the best pedigrees.
I don't have the money. I get nervous when the price gets over
$100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram had no reason to get nervous when Baffert went to the
huge Keeneland auction in Kentucky in September two years ago.
Other successful race horses have come from humble beginnings:
Cigar and Holy Bull, in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But Real Quiet walked into the sales ring on crooked legs. His
sire was Quiet American, who won the NYRA Mile in 1990 at Aqueduct,
and his mare was Really Blue, who raced for two years and earned
just $31,290.
</P>
<P>
   The mare was one of five kept by Gaviria and his wife, Ann, at
Little Hill Farm, their 20-acre farm in Ocala, Fla. They send the
mares to Kentucky to be mated, and usually keep the mare and her
foal in Florida until the foal is old enough to be raced or sold.
</P>
<P>
   They met at the University of Michigan, where Gaviria studied
mechanical engineering. They also own an 85-acre farm outside
Bogota, where Gaviria runs his business in chemicals and industrial
paints.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last quarter-century he has been studying pedigrees
and breeding race horses, and now keeps the official stud book in
Colombia. ``In a way,'' he said, ``I'm a little guy in the
states.''
</P>
<P>
   But he bought Really Blue at Keeneland in 1991 after noticing
that ``she was young and came from an outstanding family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This pedigree,'' he said, ``has produced the winners of the
French and English Derbies, and Majestic Prince, who won the
Kentucky Derby, and Real Quiet, who won this year's Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a mating to produce a stakes horse. I wasn't
thinking of the Kentucky Derby. But there were limitations of
money. I couldn't send her to high-quality stallions in Kentucky. I
didn't even know if they would accept her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consulted John Werk in Kentucky, and he gave me 15 or 20
names of stallions to choose from. I chose Quiet American, who is
from the Prospector line. On the bottom line, the mare goes back to
Raise a Native, which I wanted. And that's how she was sent to
Quiet American.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet was foaled at Susan Forrester's Glen Ridge Farm, and
a month or so later was sent home to the Gavirias at Little Hill
Farm, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have great conformation,'' Gaviria remembered, ``and
he was thin. So, we sent him to the veterinary center at the
University of Florida, where they implanted screws into both knees
and attached wires in both knees to force them to grow in the right
direction. The operations took place in April two years ago, and he
stayed thin because he was confined to his stall for two months or
more until they took the wires out and he didn't get the chance to
develop his muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, he wasn't in his best flesh when he went to the auction
that September. My best friends in Ocala advised me to get rid of
him. He might break down. We didn't even set a reserve price, the
price we had to get or we take him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping to get $30,000 or $40,000 for him. But Bob
Baffert showed up and took him for $17,000. It was the cheapest
price I ever got for a horse. But I was kind of happy that he went.
I was almost sure he was going to break down. I thought: I'm glad I
didn't keep him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram, who has made a fortune in fast-food franchises, doesn't
know how the story will end. But he shares Gaviria's feeling of
great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will tell us how great he is,'' Pegram said. ``And his
history won't be written for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
