A1109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-NELSON-COX     06-02 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-NELSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia golfer returns home with game in top form
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Larry Nelson's comfort zone probably hasn't been this
wide since the 1980s, when he won three major championships and
made his third Ryder Cup team. Three days ago in Pittsburgh, Pa.,
the affable man from Marietta, Ga. captured his second wire-to-wire
win on the Senior PGA Tour this year, taking the tournament by five
shots. A day earlier, Nelson built a record-tying 36-hole lead of
eight strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson ran his 1998 winnings to $713,670, for a total of
$1,0267,127 since turning 50 in September. If that's not a wake-up
call to Hale Irwin and Gil Morgan, who thought they had the
copyright on Senior Tour domination, then what is?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really not my thinking,'' a typically modest Nelson
said Tuesday. ``I'm just excited to be playing well. My iron game
seems to be getting better, and that's kind of what's held me back
the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be just the beginning. On Friday at the Golf Club of
Georgia, Nelson plays as a senior in the Atlanta area for the first
time, at the $1.35 million Nationwide Championship. Next week's
BellSouth Senior Classic at Opryland in Nashville, Tenn. is played
on the Springhouse Golf Club course that Nelson designed.
</P>
<P>
   Playing golf courses for the first time, which is the routine
for Nelson in his first full season as a senior, he estimates a
disadvantage of two or three shots. Playing last week on a course
new to everyone, Sewickley Heights Golf Club in Pittsburgh, Nelson
separated himself from the field. To those who have watched Nelson
firsthand the last nine months, his rise is no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a (multiple) major winner,'' South African John Bland
said. ``He knows what it's all about. He's got all the shots. He's
a very complete player. You don't have a record like his without
knowing what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's familiarity with the Golf Club of Georgia is limited to
a few corporate outings. He remembers demanding par 3s and
undulating greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite TPC-style, but it's not quite Atlanta Country
Club, either,'' Nelson said. ``I could go out there without a
practice round and pretty much know which way the holes go.''
</P>
<P>
   With 30 percent of his PGA Tour victories in the majors _ two
PGAs and a U.S. Open _ Nelson is using such background material as
handy reference. Last week, Nelson geared back his aggressiveness
and found an immediate reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been kind of an aggressive player,'' he said,
``and it's kind of been feast or famine. On a golf course where you
have to be a little more conservative, like last week, I've played
more like it's a U.S. Open or a PGA.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the approach is working.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
