<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR URGES SUPREME COURT TO INTERVENE IN SECRET SERVICE DISPUTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to speed up what he calls a ``serious
criminal investigation'' of President Clinton, independent counsel
Kenneth Starr asked the Supreme Court on Tuesday to intervene in
his dispute with the administration over testimony from Secret
Service employees.
</P>
<P>
   Starr wants the high court to take the case on an emergency
basis and decide it along with his request to force Bruce Lindsey,
the president's most trusted White House adviser, to cooperate in a
federal grand jury investigation into whether Clinton obstructed
justice by urging a cover-up of his sexual misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   The request by Starr sets the stage for a constitutional
showdown _ possibly this summer _ over creation of a so-called
``protective function'' privilege to shield the Secret Service from
having to disclose what they see or hear while protecting the
president.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr continued his efforts to accelerate the investigation,
Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern at the center of the
sex-and-perjury probe, dumped California lawyer William Ginsburg
and hired two Washington lawyers who have experience with special
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg, whose tactics had stirred controversy from the
earliest days of the investigation, is turning the case over to
Jacob Stein and Plato Cacheris, a move that renews Lewinsky's
chances of securing a deal to avoid prosecution in exchange for
testifying before Starr's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to claim a special exemption against testifying for
Secret Service agents is uncharted legal territory
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service Director Lewis C. Merletti has asserted that
forcing agents to testify about what they observe of the
president's private life would severely damage the agency's ability
to provide close protection. Clinton and former President Bush
endorse Merletti's position.
</P>
<P>
   In documents filed with the Supreme Court, Starr said he ``has
reason to believe that the `privileged' observations that Secret
Service is currently withholding from the grand jury would
constitute important evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson last month
issued two rulings ordering Lindsey, two Secret Service officers
and a Secret Service attorney to testify before Starr's grand jury.
The Clinton administration moved to appeal both decisions, which
prompted Starr to seek expedited review by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In his pleadings seeking to bypass the U.S. Court of Appeals and
have the Supreme Court review the case late this month, Starr
argued that this is no ordinary investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unhappy fact is that ... a president is under serious
criminal investigation,'' the prosecutor said. ``That unfortunate
circumstance is a rare occurrence in our nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be blunt: The nation has a compelling interest that
this criminal investigation of the president ... conclude as
quickly as possible _ that indictments be brought, possible reports
for impeachment proceedings issued, and non-prosecution decisions
announced,'' Starr wrote. ``This court's immediate review would
powerfully serve that vital goal.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jim Kennedy accused Starr of ``trying to
end-run the rules and leap-frog the legal process.'' He
characterized the briefs filed by Starr as ``an act of public
relations, not a work of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's decision to seek new counsel comes just days after
Ginsburg issued his latest blast at Starr, in an open letter to a
legal journal that implied that his client and the president has a
sexual relationship. Both Clinton and Lewinsky have denied such
allegations under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Stein is a former special prosecutor who investigated but did
not file charges against President Reagan's attorney general, Ed
Meese, during a corruption investigation. He also represented
former Sen. Robert Packwood, a Republican who resigned amid charges
of sexual harassment. He worked closely with Starr on that case.
</P>
<P>
   Cacheris's clients have included CIA turncoat Aldrich Ames,
President Nixon's attorney general, John Mitchell and Fawn Hall, a
secretary who was accused of removing documents related to the
Iran-Contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is one of two former White House employees who
allegedly had sexual encounters with Clinton. Despite her denials,
Lewinsky reportedly has admitted having sex with the president in
conversations secretly tape recorded by former colleague Linda
Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is investigating whether Lewinsky and Clinton lied. Also
being examined by Starr is whether Clinton, Lindsey or Vernon
Jordan were involved in efforts to convince Tripp to help cover up
an encounter between the president and Kathleen Willey, who alleges
that Clinton kissed and groped her outside the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to keep Lindsey from having to answer Starr's questions
before a federal grand jury, the White House is arguing that
attorney-client privilege protected him from having to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey, an attorney and close personal friend of Clinton's for
the past 30 years, has interviewed witnesses who appeared before
Starr's grand jury and also met with Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
