<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RFK-BUILDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BID TO RENAME JUSTICE DEPT. BUILDING DERAILED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite indications that there would be no
opposition, a drive to name the Justice Department headquarters
after Robert F. Kennedy to mark the 30th anniversary of his death
Saturday has been derailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look likely,'' Michele Davis, a spokeswoman for
House Majority Leader Richard Armey of Texas, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of House members, including 40 Republicans and nearly
every Democrat, have signed letters that support naming the
building. But House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia decided not to
bring the measure up for consideration this week because of
opposition from some House GOP leaders, said lawmakers who back the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich did not tell the supporters who opposes the measure,
but the lawmakers said the speaker is reluctant to anger
conservative members.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said Tuesday that the prospects are
dim for quick House passage of the bill memorializing his brother,
a former attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own sense is I don't think it is going to pass at this
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he was unaware of a specific opponent to the bill,
but said the partisan atmosphere in the House makes it difficult to
honor his late brother. The Senate is waiting for a House vote
before acting on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Elmendorf, the chief of staff to House Democratic leader
Richard Gephardt of Missouri, said Gephardt is committed to getting
the measure passed this year and will continue trying to get the
bill to the floor this week.
</P>
<P>
   If the measure is not brought up this week, Gephardt would
consider filing a so-called discharge petition to circumvent House
leaders and force a vote, said Elmendorf.
</P>
<P>
   The bill to name the Justice Department building could be
considered by the House at any time this year, but supporters were
pushing to get it approved by the anniversary of Robert Kennedy's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and Armey had assured supporters of the bill months ago
that they would not block it if a majority of House members
supported the measure. Two other House leaders _ Majority Whip Tom
DeLay of Texas and Republican Conference Chairman John Boehner of
Ohio _ signed the letter of support last month.
</P>
<P>
   President John F. Kennedy named his brother and campaign
manager, Robert Francis Kennedy, attorney general in 1961. RFK held
the position until 1964, when he resigned to make a successful run
for the Senate from New York. He was a candidate for the Democratic
nomination for president in 1968 when he was shot by Sirhan Sirhan
on June 5, the night he won the California primary. He died the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department building at 10th Street and Constitution
Avenue has never been named. The FBI building across the street is
named for longtime FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover, who was Kennedy's
nemesis for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Congress renamed Washington National Airport
after former President Reagan. And when the House returns to work
today after the Memorial Day recess, it will consider six
noncontroversial bills, including four to name post offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
