<HEADLINE>
SEN. MCCAIN'S ANTI-SMOKING BILL IMPERILED BY ``MACHO'' AMENDMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Resending to change slug from MCCAIN to TOBACCO)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Repu blic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republic Washington Bureau &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain's anti-smoking bill is in peril
because of ``macho'' amendments senators are pushing to punish the
tobacco industry and score political points, McCain said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   `` We are in danger of knocking this thing way out of balance,
if we haven't already,'' the Arizona Republican said in an
emotional speech on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   In a later interview, McCain placed the stalled bill's prospects
for passage at ``st ill better than 50-50. But you know me, I'm an
eternal optimist.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, McCain said, is that some senators want to toughen
the bill, apparently for political posturing, to penalize
cigarettemakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see going on here _ interestingly from both ends of the
political spectrum _ is such punitive amendments that we will drive
the tobacco companies out of business,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers must decide whether to pass his legislation, McCain
said, or whether simp ly to ``vote for amendments to show how macho
and tough we are on the tobacco companies.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks cast McCain, if only fleetingly, in the unlikely
role of a tobacco industry defender. The tobacco companies have
accused him of trying to
orchestrate their demise.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that he is no fan of the cigarettemakers, McCain
has denied that his goal is to tax the industry out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's bill is designed to reduce youth smoking through stiff
cigarette pri ce increases and sales and marketing curbs. The
measure would cost the industry at least $516 billion in
tobacco-related health costs and anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also proposes a ban on outdoor advertising by tobacco
firms, and that may violate free speech, says the American Civil
Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's backers hope to shut off debate and proceed to a vote
on the measure by early next week.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the Senate must consider amendments that are
worrisome to Mc Cain and the bill's other sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment, by Richard Durbin, D-Ill., would toughen the
penalties on tobacco companies if youth smoking-reduction targets
were not met.
</P>
<P>
   The Durbin amendment _ combined with an earlier, passed ame
ndment eliminating a limit on the industry's legal liability _
``could be the death knell of the whole bill'' because it exacts
such a great toll, said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that if cigarette companies starte d going under,
the nation would be deprived of billions of dollars of tobacco
revenues that could go toward trying to persuade teens not to
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   If the companies began closing, McCain said, 40 million adult
Americans would still find ways to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'd be a Marlboro, or a Camel or another operating out of
Mexico, El Salvador or whatever, and they would be exporting
cigarettes into the United States, which we would not have nearly
as much control over,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   There was some good news Tuesday on the tobacco bill for McCain.
The Senate approved his amendment to add $3 billion in funding for
veterans tobacco-related health-care costs. Veterans groups have
been angered at Congress for recently taking away a $17 billion
benefit program for former service members who contracted
smoking-related ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Debate on the tobacco bill is scheduled to resume Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders said they feared the Republican majority was
losing intere st in the bill; as evidence, they cited the Senate's
willingness to move on to other business Tuesday while the tobacco
measure was still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said the message seemed to
be, ``If Democrats behave, we'll
</P>
<P>
   probably be able to come back to tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is out of session today (Wednesday) so that members
may attend the funeral in Tempe of the late Arizona Sen. Barry
Goldwater.  &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at 202-662-7264 or via e-mail
atjeff.barker(at)pni.com on the Internet.  &QL;
</P>
