<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-COLLAPSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY WITH HEART CONDITION DIES AFTER CLIMBING STAIRS
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Bronx teen-ager with a heart condition died in the
hallway of his school on Tuesday morning after running up five
flights of stairs to a class, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The student, Matthew Bandoo, 15, climbed the stairs at Harry S.
Truman High School in Co-op City after attempting to console a girl
who said she was worried that some students were going to beat up a
friend of hers, school officials and family members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the child did not go to his third-period
class, which was physical education,'' said Karen Crowe, a
spokesman for the Board of Education. ``Instead, he went into an
unoccupied office on the second floor, then went up the stairs
after helping his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew's mother, Pamela Bandoo, added that her son was hoping
to warn the friend of the girl he had been consoling of approaching
danger. ``He was on his way to tell her to be careful, that someone
was going to jump her,'' she said. ``But he didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bandoo was running up the stairs with another student while on
his way to a 10:30 a.m. class and began to complain of chest pain
after reaching the seventh-floor hallway, Ms. Crowe said. He
collapsed after a few steps. A teacher who was nearby ran over and
performed cardiopulmonary resuscitation on the youth while another
teacher dialed 911, Ms. Crowe said. Bandoo was pronounced dead 45
minutes later at Jacobi Medical Center, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bandoo said that her son had heart surgery to repair a
congenital defect when he was 5, but officials said that he had no
restrictions on his record indicating that he could not participate
in physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crowe said because of this Bandoo was not eligible to
receive a pass to ride on the school's four elevators.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bandoo said that while her son knew that he had to monitor
his condition, he had maintained an active life since his surgery,
playing basketball with his school friends and nursing a dream of
someday being a Knick. ``He loved basketball and wanted to be like
them, to play on the team.'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bandoo said her husband died of cancer five years ago and
that Matthew was the rock that had settled her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't talk about his father's death, kept it all inside,
but I used to tell him all my problems,'' she said, describing how
her son was lining up summer jobs to help out with the family's
finances. ``I always looked forward to coming home, sitting and
talking together. But that part is gone now, a part of me is
gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
