<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SEMANTIC ANTICS, TRANSLATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Gore recently offered me a chance to
repent. He sent me a Forgiveness Coupon. (He really did.)
</P>
<P>
   The postcard-sized coupon reads: ``The Vice President of the
United States Hereby Issues this Forgiveness Coupon to Maureen
Dowd. We learn from Our Mistakes. It is easier to get forgiveness
than permission.'' It was signed ``Al Gore.'' (Really.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore introduced Forgiveness Coupons into government to encourage
employees to take risks. If they make a mistake, they can submit a
coupon to their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Now he was offering me the chance to win absolution, should I
write a column that irritates him.
</P>
<P>
   While I was delighted to see a flash of Gore's old
mischievousness, I did begin to fret that he was Reinventing
Government in some flaky, huggy New Age way.
</P>
<P>
   But my faith in him was restored on Monday when he announced
that the White House had sent out a directive urging bureaucrats to
drop their long-winded, jargon-ridden humbug and use ``plain
language'' when writing forms, letters, memos and rules. Or, as
Orwell wrote, use English to reveal rather than conceal.
</P>
<P>
   But why stop at federal agencies? Why not apply this new
common-sense standard to the semantic dodges of the White House
itself?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Controlling Legal Authority, that is where the government
really needs to speak to the American people in unvarnished
English. So let us, as Gore asks, translate some scandalese into
plain talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will undoubtedly be folks out there who will suggest,
`Oh, oh, this must be some great scheme to delay.' ... That's just
nonsense.'' _ White House Counsel Charles Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Delay rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Lindsey told the grand jury ``that he had no information
that anyone had committed perjury or obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Bug off. I'm never telling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service asserted a new ``protective function
privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``We've seen some truly amazing stuff. And we need
to stay in close. Wouldn't you like to know how the president
really got that cut on his forehead?''
</P>
<P>
   William Ginsburg justified writing that Kenneth Starr ``may have
succeeded in unmasking a sexual relationship between two consenting
adults'' by saying he was just being sarcastic.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Sure they did it. Sure I'm an incompetent nitwit.
That's why Monica dumped me.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official said that the decision to drop
executive-privilege claims for Bruce Lindsey and Sidney Blumenthal,
while asserting attorney-client privilege for Lindsey, was ``based
on the law and based on principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``We'll sacrifice Sidney. He doesn't know much. And
he doesn't know when to stop. Anyway, he's Hillary's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the concern I've heard the president and Ruff raise
with respect to this matter is an institutional concern that
relates to this president and future presidents,'' said Mike
McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``We'll do anything to save our own skins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is of high moment,'' said Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``I'm a crazy, obsessed person who messed up this
whole case by not getting Lewinsky's testimony when I had the
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the advantages of this project outweigh this
risk, and that we can effectively rebut criticism of the waiver,''
Sandy Berger wrote to the president in a memo urging Clinton to
give the go-ahead to Loral, headed by the Democrats' top donor,
despite the fact that the company was under Justice Department
investigation for giving the Chinese militarily useful information.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Don't worry. We've got cover. Take the money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As with Nixon. ... This litigation involves fundamental
constitutional issues arising out of the doctrine of separation of
powers.'' _ Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: (A frothing sound.)
</P>
<P>
   McCurry told reporters their questions on executive privilege
were a distraction as the president was ``focusing on a very real
question of the balance of forces on the Indian subcontinent.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Hallelujah! Maybe the prospect of thermonuclear
war will get their minds off Monica!''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made repeated promises to cooperate with the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Kiss my grits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
