<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1126 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      06-02 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S SEN. JOHN MCCAIN EMULATED GOLDWATER'S QUALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ People wonder a lot who Sen. Joh n McCain is these
days.
</P>
<P>
   His musings about running for the presidency have created a
virtual cottage industry of journalists atempting to look into the
Arizona Republican's soul.
</P>
<P>
   The pundits might be advised to look at McCain's desk. I t once
belonged to the late Barry Goldwater. The desk, like Goldwater, is
in the old style.
</P>
<P>
   It was bequeathed to McCain, and when he sits at it, he says,
it's hard not to think of its former owner.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is to address
</P>
<P>
   mourners at Goldwater's funeral today, says he often recalls the
Arizona icon's candor and adherence to principles. And McCain, who
is not ashamed of adopting heroes and role models, said he tries to
emulate those qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a
</P>
<P>
   rare combination of one who adhered to his ideology, but yet
also achieved legislative results,'' McCain said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater, who died Friday, is credited as a champion of
national conservatism. But he also created a prototyp e for future
Arizona Republican senators such as McCain.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy for his successors might be to be outspoken, adopt
national concerns, but above all never forget who elected you.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who says he will consider running f or president in
2000, learned the lesson. He has adopted the Grand Canyon and
American Indians as primary issues _ in addition to loftier matters
such as telecommunications and national defense.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain said he can't credit Goldwater
</P>
<P>
   for one trait the two shared: a penchant for salty, off-the-cuff
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame Goldwater for that failing,'' McCain said,
laughing. ``I think part of that is my own homegrown intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends often said of Gol dwater, and later of McCain, that he
seemed genuine because he didn't adopt the politician's trick of
tailoring his message to suit a particular audience.
</P>
<P>
   But his candor sometimes got Goldwater in trouble. So, too, for
McCain, who once got criticized for jokingly referring to Leisure
World as ``Seizure World.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater really was a loose gun at times. Sen. Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz., who also will address mourners today, recalled how
Goldwater's former office had some some su spicious dents in it.
``Barry had an air pistol at his desk, and he took pot shots at the
brass plate and door knob,'' Kyl said. The partially patched holes
are visible today.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he actually has two other Arizona role models bes
ides Goldwater. They are former Rep. Mo Udall, D-Ariz., and John
Rhodes, the former U.S. House Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits have speculated that part of McCain's appeal is his
willingness to admit to imperfections, and to the need to seek
</P>
<P>
   out guides. McCain is happy to enunciate what he acquired from
each of his mentors.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Goldwater, obviously, it would be stand up for what you
believe in. From Rhodes, it's the importance of working together
with your colleagues on
</P>
<P>
   both sides of the aisle. From Udall: environmental, Native
Americans and humor,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Barker can be reached at 202-662-7264 or via e-mail at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
