<SLUG> BC-SATCHER-CHILDREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN GRILL SURGEON GENERAL ABOUT SMOKING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He's 14 years old, in the eighth grade, and he says
he smoked for two years. He quit recently, and now, he says, he
wants to help other teenagers do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia pupil, Omar Bugg-Bey, got right to the
point when he interviewed Surgeon General David Satcher Tuesday.
``Since cigarettes are still being sold illegally to children, what
needs to be done to stop this and help keep children from
smoking?'' Bugg-Bey asked.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher is used to being grilled about tobacco regulation, but
usually the questions come from reporters, politicians, or
lobbyists. However, Bugg-Bey and other students ages 9 to 14 had
Satcher in the hot seat to ask about tobacco concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 students from three local public schools were in the
American Cancer Society's smoking-prevention program. They asked
articulate questions, and like Bugg-Bey, they did not mince words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why has Congress not passed the tobacco-regulation bill, and
what are you going to do about it?'' asked Aaron Stroman, 13, a
sixth grader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you fight to have no tobacco, cigarettes, or cigars
so nobody dies from it or gets sick from it?'' Danielle Falardeau,
9, wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kids really ask tough questions,'' Satcher said.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon general assured Stroman that he wants the
tobacco-regulation bill passed, too. ``I'm doing my best to help
people understand that this bill is important, because it will let
the Food and Drug Administration have much more authority to
regulate the tobacco industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate continues to debate a tobacco bill, the sponsor,
Senator John McCain, Republican of Arizona, said he might try to
limit debate and bring the issue to a vote next week. The bill
would cost tobacco companies at least $516 billion over 25 years,
raise the price of cigarettes by $1.10 a pack over five years, and
allow the FDA to regulate nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   To answer Danielle's question, Satcher said wiping out tobacco
in this country is not a realistic option. ``The United States is
known for free enterprise and for letting people have the freedom
to make their own decisions about what they want to do with their
lives,'' he said. ``So we're pushing for regulating the tobacco
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to passing legislation, Satcher said the government
is trying to educate the public, especially children, that smoking
damages one's health and to prevent children from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important to reach the children with this message,''
he said. ``About 80 percent of people who smoke started when they
were younger than 18, and many of them will become addicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bugg-Bey said that helping young smokers quit is as
important as prevention. ``But some don't want to stop smoking
because they're addicted to it, or they think they don't have any
real reason to stop,'' he said. ``It's hard to quit for some
people, but it is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   He quit smoking, he said, after he was in the prevention
program, and after his mother told him he had a heart condition.
``I realized that my smoking could kill me,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
