<HEADLINE>
ABC CHIEF LEAVES DISNEY TO DIRECT COMCAST CABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ABC Broadcasting's chief has resigned Tuesday, the
latest in a string of top-level departures at The Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Burke, a 12-year Disney veteran, became president of
Philadelphia-based Comcast Cable Communications on Tuesday, and
senior vice president of Comcast Corp. He had overseen 10 ABC
stations, 27 radio stations, eight radio networks and Disney's
domestic syndication arm.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, son of former Capital Cities/ABC chief Daniel Burke,
joined Disney in 1986 and helped develop the Disney Stores chain.
He became president of Euro Disney in 1992 after the French theme
park had performed below expectations and took the ABC post after
Disney bought Cap Cities two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Recent departures from the Burbank-based entertainment giant
include Richard Nanula, chief financial officer, chief strategist
Lawrence Murphy and cable programming chief Geraldine Laybourne.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have cited Chairman Michael Eisner's tendency to
micro-manage as a reason but others contend such turnover is
typical for a large corporation.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC spokeswoman said a replacement for Burke probably will be
named this summer. Disney stock fell 11/16 to 110 1/8. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
