<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-LAUNCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE RACES TOWARD FINAL RENDEZVOUS WITH MIR SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The shuttle Discovery rocketed into space
Tuesday and raced toward a final U.S. link-up with Russia's Mir
space station.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery roared from the Kennedy Space Center launch pad at
6:06 p.m., EDT.
</P>
<P>
   On course to reach Mir on Thursday, the shuttle's five Americans
and a Russian trailed the orbital outpost by nearly 5,500 miles as
they began their pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting Discovery's arrival are Andy Thomas, the seventh and
final U.S. astronauts assigned to live on the aging station, and
his two cosmonaut hosts. Thomas, 46, is in the homestretch of a
nearly five-month journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we head uphill into space, we're going to make you proud
and bring our good friend Andy back home,'' said Discovery
commander Charles Precourt.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas asked NASA personnel to prepare a meal of lasagne and
Oreo cookie ice cream for his June 12 return to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing fine,'' Thomas assured NASA personnel in Russia's
mission control center as he awaited the liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle escaped sweltering Florida heat. By late afternoon,
the temperature flirted with a 99-degree limit that would have
forced a postponement. Shuttle engineers did not design their
machinery for a sustained exposure to such high temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the launch was in jeopardy when Mir's
computer-driven steering system faltered, setting the 120-ton
outpost adrift. By Tuesday, the network of electrically-driven
turbines that keep the station's power-generating solar arrays
bathed in sunlight were back in working order.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's mission is the last in a succession of nine dockings
with Mir inaugurated in mid-1995 to prepare the former Cold War
rivals for the upcoming assembly of a new international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's launch, however, was the first for the shuttle's new
fuel tank. The towering, orange, silo-shaped tank was fashioned
from a light weight alloy of aluminum and lithium, shaving 7,500
pounds. The savings will permit shuttles to lift the heaviest
components of the new station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you fly a new piece of equipment we give it a little
extra attention,'' said Don McMonagle, who chairs NASA's mission
management team. ``All of us breathed a little sigh of relief,
whether it was overtly or covertly.``
</P>
<P>
   Precourt's crew includes pilot Dominic Gorie, flight engineer
Wendy Lawrence and mission specialists Franklin Chang-Diaz and
Janet Kavandi. They were joined by Valery Ryumin, 58, a former
Russian cosmonaut and most recently the manager of his country's
cooperative human spaceflight program with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ryumin plans an engineering assessment of Mir, parts of which
have weathered more than twice their five-year design life.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement formally struck last weekend, the Russians
plan to drop the big station through the Earth's atmosphere and
into the ocean by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   With shuttle visits drawing to a close, the Russians will lose a
crucial supply line that has enabled them to keep Mir operable
despite their faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   On their final visit, U.S. astronauts will deliver more than a 1
1/2 tons of food, clothing, water and other supplies to cosmonauts
Talgat Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin. They will leave with more
than a ton of equipment, including frozen medical specimens that
offer a record of physical changes in the space travelers as they
became accustomed to the weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's visit to Mir will draw to a close Monday, with a
final novel exercise.
</P>
<P>
   With Gorie at the controls, Discovery's crew plans to separate
to a point 240 feet from Mir and hold its position. At the same
time, Mir's cosmonauts will inject a tracer gas into the station's
sealed off Spektr module.
</P>
<P>
   Spektr bore the brunt of a near-disastrous, June 25, 1997,
collision with an out-of-control Progress cargo capsule. The module
decompressed from a breach in its hull. Though suspected to reside
at the base of a solar array, the source of the seepage has never
been precisely pinpointed.
</P>
<P>
   The escaping gases should glow a greenish-blue shade when they
encounter sunlight, potentially revealing the site of the leak to
the shuttle's cameras.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
