<HEADLINE>
2 HEAVYWEIGHTS AND A BOXER 
MAXIMUM TROUBLE 
CELEBRITIES FOR CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By GLENN COLLINS with KIM STEVENS and BENJAMIN WEISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it a marriage made in courtroom heaven or an unholy legal
alliance? Raoul Lionel Felder, the New York divorce lawyer, and
Johnnie Cochrane Jr., who is living in New York these days to tape
his daily show on Court TV, have teamed up to defend Riddick Bowe,
the former heavyweight champion. Bowe, once famous for wearing the
pictures of his wife, Judy, and their five children on his warm-up
T-shirt, is now being sued for divorce in Baltimore. Enter Felder.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bowe was indicted by a federal grand jury in
Charlotte, N.C., and charged with abducting Mrs. Bowe and the
children from their home in Cornelius, N.C., where they had moved,
and attempting to drive them to his home in Fort Washington, Md.
Bowe, who faces a maximum sentence of 10 years, denies the charge.
Enter Cochrane.
</P>
<P>
   The two lawyers, who have never teamed up before, have been
coordinating their efforts this week during hours of discussion.
``It's the best duet I've ever danced with anybody,'' Felder said.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON TERM FOR POP-ART KING
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Max, whose psychedelic pop art of the 1960s
made him an icon of the art world, was sentenced in federal court
on Tuesday to two months in prison for concealing more than $1.1
million in income from the IRS in connection with sales of his
works.
</P>
<P>
   Max was also fined $30,000, ordered to pay his back taxes, and
to perform 800 hours of community service by teaching art to
disadvantaged children in four public schools in the Washington
Heights section of New York under supervision of the court and the
Children's Aid Society.
</P>
<P>
   In court, one of Max's lawyers, Roy Black, told Judge Kimba Wood
that his client had been extraordinarily generous, donating
millions of dollars of artwork to charitable causes. At one time
his distinctive, surrealistic swirling figures seemed to be
everywhere, adorning coffee mugs, T-shirts, and posters.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor, Robert Cramer, did not dispute his charitable
efforts, but argued that his contributions were a ``powerful
marketing device'' for his commercial endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   In pleading guilty to conspiracy and tax evasion, Max, 60, could
have received up to 14 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very very sorry for what I have done,'' he told Wood. ``I
know in my heart that nothing like this will ever happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   HALE, HALE, GANG'S ALL HERE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I'm not the celebrity, the children are,'' said Dr.
Lorraine Hale, a founder of Hale House, the Harlem agency that
cares for infants who are born to mothers addicted to drugs or
alcohol, or who have the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   She said it with a wink, since a few other guests turned up for
the recent Hale House benefit at the Plaza. There was Spike Lee,
who discovered Hale House while shooting ``Do the Right Thing.''
And Rosie O'Donnell, who spoke about the value of teaching children
social consciousness. And Evander Holyfield, who recalled growing
up the youngest of nine children in a single-parent home.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was paparazzi time, and the Hale House children watched
the celebrities become children. Ms. O'Donnell stood next to
Holyfield, waited until the camera barrage, then pretended to take
a bite out of his ear. The Tyson ear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
