<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HITCHCOCK-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL WAR `FASCINATES' HITCHCOCK INTO TAKING UP ARMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the ice he's the head coach, but when he pulls on his navy
tunic, blue pants, and shoulder bars and insignia, Stars boss Ken
Hitchcock is just another officer in the Union Army.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian-born-and-raised Hitchcock is an avid student of the
Civil War. He has taken part in several summer re-enactments since
his first introduction to it when he toured the Gettysburg
battlefield in 1992 during the NHL All-Star break while he was an
assistant coach with the Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This old guy in his 70s spent five hours in a golf cart taking
me around the whole Gettysburg battlefield,'' Hitchcock said.
``From that day I couldn't get enough information about it. I
became involved in round-table discussions about the Civil War, and
from '92 to '95 I'd go to a re-enactment every summer as a
participant.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his first re-enactment, Pvt. Hitchcock has climbed in the
ranks to his present post as second lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became involved with the conflict and the struggle between
the Confederacy and the Union and how strong each other's beliefs
were,'' Hitchcock said. ``It fascinated me, not the political
aspects but the military and psychological strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to understand how people could get people to do the
things they did unconditionally. I couldn't believe the commitment
that people made toward their leaders, their states, their
countries. I became fascinated by the actual military process.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock has used what he has learned about the Civil War as
motivation techniques when he coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've shown video, I've shown clips of movies,'' Hitchcock
said. ``After we didn't make the playoffs here my first year, I
showed a movie clip from ``Gettysburg,'' about seven or eight
minutes long. There were some features in there that I thought were
terrific. I showed them to the players, just to emphasize the
points of being part of a group and on values.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has empathy for both sides in the war, there was no
question that he and his reproduction rifle would fight for the
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fascinated by state's rights and the belief in the
Confederacy,'' Hitchcock said, ``but I feel strongly about the
Union side in a lot of areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to get a clear understanding of what people were
thinking, what their thought processes were. I really try to
understand both sides, but I'm still a Union person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
