<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COMMENCEMENT-NYT &LR;      06-02 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMENCEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 NEW YORK SCHOOLS CHANCELLOR EXHORTS GRADUATES TO PUBLIC SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew exhorted City College
graduates Tuesday to pursue ``the beauty'' of public service, but
he did not remark on the issue dominating talk on campus: the
decision by the Board of Trustees of the City University of New
York to phase out remedial courses at its four-year colleges.
</P>
<P>
   In a commencement address at the college that is the top
supplier of teachers for the school system, Crew found a receptive
audience among the 2,550 graduates for his call to public service.
The college says that about 90 percent of the 800 recipients of
bachelor's and master's degrees in education either already work in
New York City public schools or are going on to jobs in them.
</P>
<P>
   With the rousing cadence of a preacher, he salted his remarks
with references to hope and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world that we shape must be filled by people who
ultimately understand the quality, the beauty and the dignity of
public service,'' Crew said, urging the graduates to ``suspend
their disbelief'' when confronted with the array of seemingly
insurmountable challenges that accompany public jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Crew's remarks received vigorous applause, though not as much as
that garnered by the valedictorian, Anita Dhawan, whose speech was
a rallying defense of City College and remediation.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees voted last week to adopt a plan pushed by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki to phase out remedial
education at the 11 senior colleges by 2002 as a way to raise
standards in a system they believe should focus its mission solely
on students prepared for college work.
</P>
<P>
   The move is expected to increase pressure on the public schools
to improve the academic caliber of its graduates, many of whom go
on to CUNY. Several City College graduates afterward said they were
surprised Crew did not take up the subject, but a spokeswoman for
the chancellor said he was complying with a request from college
officials _ made months before CUNY's vote _ to speak on his
personal views of public service in keeping with the theme of the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the chancellor, who has long had a good rapport with
Guiliani, said he regretted the trustees' decision but promised
that the school system would improve enough to insure graduates are
ready for college work.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ms. Dhawan did not shy away from the topic. She,
too, knew her audience and whipped them into hearty cheers with her
criticisms of Giuliani and Pataki, who she believes have tarnished
the name of a college that has turned out Nobel laureates and civic
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the ability to live up to the City College name and
the City College tradition and give those who graduate 20 years
from now a name to be proud of,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Brooklyn College &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If public colleges continue to lose the support of voters and
legislators at the present rate, they could become like ``dead
spacecraft, with no new missions to fly,'' Vernon Lattin, the
president of Brooklyn College, told 3,000 graduates seated in the
leafy quadrangle of the Flatbush campus.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the booming economy, he said, the 50 United States ``are
now spending $23.1 billion less for higher education than they were
20 years ago.'' New York state, he added, ranks 49th in the funding
of higher education for every $1,000 of personal income.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, he said, is that public institutions will become
``smaller, more-expensive, semiprivate colleges and universities
for those who can afford the higher cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Lattin concluded by urging the graduates to ``do what you can to
make sure that others may have the opportunity that you have
enjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   An honorary doctorate of humane letters was also awarded Tuesday
to Harry Belafonte, who brought the audience to its feet with a
resounding rendition of ``Daaay-O! Daylight come and you
graduate!'' It was an adaptation of the song that became his
signature calypso piece in the 1950s. --WILLIAM H. HONAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bernard M. Baruch College &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Protests over its new remedial policies have been a recurrent
theme at CUNY graduation ceremonies this year, but Baruch College's
commencement Tuesday at Madison Square Garden was upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Although two faculty members stood and turned their backs when a
CUNY trustee spoke, and many faculty wore yellow stickers saying
``Stop the War on CUNY,'' there was little sense of embattlement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there were repeated accolades for Baruch's president,
Matthew Goldstein, who is leaving this month to take the helm at
Adelphi University and who helped turn Baruch into one of the
most-respected colleges at CUNY during his seven years as
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even CUNY's critics have taken unmitigated pride in Baruch,''
said Richard Stone, a CUNY trustee, who called the college ``the
ornamental jewel in the City University system.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Baruch alumni, Bernie West, a writer who worked on the
sitcoms ``All in the Family,'' ``The Jeffersons'' and ``Three's
Company,'' and Miguel Fuentes Jr., the president of Bronx-Lebanon
Hospital Center, were given honorary doctorates.
</P>
<P>
   West kept the audience chuckling with an address that borrowed
from his days as a comic in the Catskills. While many commencement
speakers ask the graduates to look ahead, West had them looking
ahead to retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a man of leisure,'' he told the 2,000 graduates and their
guests. ``I do nothing all day and sometimes I don't finish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so difficult to wax nostalgic,'' he added, ``if you can't
remember anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he mentioned that he had turned 80 last weekend, the
graduates rose and sang ``Happy Birthday'' to him. --KAREN W.
ARENSON
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Princeton University &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Princeton University's class of 1998 made its ceremonial exit
through the hallowed FitzRandolph Gate Tuesday, capping Princeton's
251st commencement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 1,110 undergraduate degree recipients, who
followed tradition by filing out of the university through the
ornate gate onto Nassau Street, 620 graduates received advanced
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The honorary degree recipients were Howard Gardner, a professor
of education at Harvard University; Robert Kahn, president of the
Corporation for National Research Initiatives, who is considered a
founder of the Internet; Matthew Perry Jr., the only black federal
district court judge in South Carolina's history, and John Wilder
Turkey, a Princeton professor and a leading statistician.
Princeton's president, Harold Sharpiro, delivered brief remarks to
conclude the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Neitzke, the valedictorian, said, ``For 21 years we have
basically been living with the training wheels on; everything we've
done we've done with other people looking out for us, carefully
nurturing our potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've brought us to this critical juncture, and now we are
finally ready to put all that preparation to work. Just like the
kid on the bike, I'm sure we'll find that life without the training
wheels is more exhilarating than we ever expected, and I'm sure
we'll do our benefactors proud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
