<SLUG> BC-NY-REPUBS-CONVENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASSAU COUNTY LEGISLATOR TO RUN AGAINST MCCALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bruce Blakeman, presiding officer of the Nassau
County Legislature, was selected by Republican leaders Tuesday to
challenge state Comptroller H. Carl McCall in the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   Blakeman's selection was made during a conference call among New
York Republican leaders, led by U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, also of
Long Island; Gov. George Pataki, and William Powers, chairman of
the state Republican Party. The selection completes the Republican
ticket and came two days before state Republicans start a two-day
convention in New York City, where they are expected to ratify the
slate.
</P>
<P>
   Blakeman, in an interview, described his selection in a way that
also provided a glimpse into the tight operating style of the
state's Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was called to a meeting today with my county chairman, Joe
Mondello,'' Blakeman said Tuesday. ``Mondello informed me he had a
conference call with Bill Powers, Gov. Pataki, Mike Long, the
chairman of the Conservative Party, and Sen. D'Amato, and during
the telephone conference call he recommended me for the state
comptroller's nomination. They agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republican leaders, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, confirmed Blakeman's account.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two and a half years, Blakeman has been the head of
the Nassau County Legislature. Before that he was a member of the
Hempstead Town Board and he previously worked as a private attorney
in Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   Blakeman's selection was instantly seized on by Democrats as
evidence of bossism in the Republican Party. When the state
Democrats held their convention last week in Rye Brook, they made
no effort to agree on a single candidate, realizing that they could
not, and instead set up primaries for governor, lieutenant governor
and U.S. senator. As of now, it appears there will be no Republican
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al D'Amato's absolute control of the Republican Party is
perfectly evident in his convincing Bruce Blakeman to accept the
role of sacrificial lamb against the unbeatable Carl McCall,'' said
Matthew Hiltzik, press secretary for the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Blakeman said Hiltzik's attack showed that Democrats were
worried about his strength as a candidate. ``Their panic is
encouraging,'' he said. ``It sounds to me like a pretty hysterical
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little evidence of concern Tuesday among Democrats and
McCall's advisers to the prospect of a Blakeman candidacy. He is
barely known outside of Nassau County, and party leaders said they
would not be providing him with money to finance a campaign, though
they said he has some family wealth that could help him pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   And even some Republicans acknowledged privately that Blakeman,
who is 42 years old and has been in public life for only five
years, had little chance against McCall. From that perspective, his
selection seemed to underscore the cordial relations between the
Republican governor and the Democratic comptroller. Pataki and
McCall traveled together to Israel last month, for example, leading
some members of both parties to suggest that the two men had
something of a nonaggression pact, which would not be unusual
between comptrollers and governors of opposite parties during
election years.
</P>
<P>
   And on a more pragmatic level, several Republicans have said
they were wary of running an aggressive campaign against McCall,
the highest-level black elected official in the state, that could
serve to draw McCall's supporters to the polls, and perhaps then
help other Democrats running on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But Blakeman insisted his candidacy was serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running to win and I expect to win,' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
