</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR URGES SUPREME COURT TO TAKE UP CLINTON CASE QUICKLY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, focusing on
yet another pressure point in his investigation of President
Clinton, asked the Supreme Court Tuesday to quickly affirm whether
a federal judge ruled correctly that Secret Service agents must
testify before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In that request, and a parallel plea to have the court rule on
Clinton's attempt to use attorney-client privilege to shield deputy
White House counsel Bruce Lindsey from grand jury testimony, Starr
summoned the specter of Watergate and compared Clinton's legal
tactics to those of former President Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are needed, and they are needed now,'' Starr
declared in a court filing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We will be blunt: The nation has a compelling
interest that this criminal investigation of the president of the
United States conclude as quickly as possible _ that indictments be
brought, possible reports for impeachment proceedings issued, and
nonprosecution decisions announced.''
</P>
<P>
   In another development Tuesday,  &UR;  &LR; Monica S. Lewinsky dismissed
her outspoken attorney, William H. Ginsburg, replacing him with
Plato Cacheris and Jacob Stein, two well-known criminal defense
lawyers schooled in the ways of Washington and the high-profile
legal battles that dominate much of the capital's culture. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's decision to sever legal ties with Ginsburg, a
longtime family friend from Los Angeles who specializes in medical
malpractice lawsuits, removes one of the most ubiquitous figures
from the case and ends one of the more curious pairings in
Washington's recent collective memory.
</P>
<P>
   With a mix of paternal concern, roguish charm, and an outsider's
naivete, Ginsburg stormed through the capital in late January,
sending constantly changing signals on the nature of Lewinsky's
relationship with Clinton and his own relationship with Starr.
</P>
<P>
   On one particular Sunday, Ginsburg achieved the public relations
feat of appearing on all five network public affairs shows. More
recently, he gave Lewinsky permission to pose on a Southern
California beach for a glossy magazine photo spread, and he wrote a
highly critical column on Starr for a California journal. All the
while, he has been sharply criticized for his nuts-and-bolts
representation of Lewinsky _ primarily his inability to win her
immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was getting to the point where his representation was like
watching a car crash over and over and over again,'' said Jonathan
Turley, a Washington lawyer and law professor at George Washington
University. ``Mr. Ginsburg succumbed to largely self-inflicted
wounds. His performance has come as close to self-immolation as an
attorney can reach.''
</P>
<P>
   By bringing in two well-known defense lawyers, Lewinsky either
is actively preparing for her own indictment in the case or
possibly trying to repair her tattered relationship with Starr in
hopes of reopening immunity talks and winning a new deal, analysts
said. Lewinsky could be facing charges including perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Cacheris has represented such high-profile figures as
Iran-Contra figure Fawn Hall and convicted spy Aldrich Ames. Stein
comes equipped with a reservoir of knowledge of how such
investigations work, having served as an independent counsel
investigating former Attorney General Edwin Meese in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most obvious opportunity created by change of counsel is
to reopen immunity negotiations,'' said Turley.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Brand, a Washington defense lawyer, said, ``Plato is a
real trial guy. He knows how to go to trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal maneuvering continued across the spectrum of the
Lewinsky case Tuesday, as Starr submitted another filing to the
Supreme Court asking for an expedited ruling on the issue of
whether Secret Service agents should testify before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Starr won a crucial decision on the question from US District
Judge Norma Holloway Johnson last month, a ruling that the Clinton
administration said Monday it would appeal. By asking the Supreme
Court to consider the case later this month, Starr is attempting to
prevent Clinton from delaying the investigation with legal appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service has argued that by allowing agents to
testify, future presidents and others who receive protection may be
endangered by trying to distance themselves from agents and
inadvertently putting themselves in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Starr last week asked the Supreme Court to expedite a hearing
into the issue of executive privilege, after also winning a federal
judge's ruling on the matter. The White House on Monday decided not
to appeal the denial of executive privilege to Lindsey, who is
perhaps Clinton's closest confidant, and to communications aide
Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Clinton decided to appeal the decision on Lindsey's
testimony on the issue of attorney-client privilege. Because
attorney-client privilege involves no constitutional issues,
Clinton hopes the justices will decide not to hear the case,
instead letting the matter wind through the routine appeals
process.
</P>
<P>
   In arguably his sharpest language on the case yet, Starr wrote
in Tuesday's filing, ``By asserting a purported privilege for
government attorney-client communications, the president of the
United States has directly challenged the ability of the federal
grand jury to obtain evidence of possible criminal acts by the
president and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is, save for Nixon, without parallel in the history of
the republic,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House fired back that Starr, in Tuesday's court
filings and a speech on Monday, was offering up rhetoric in the
place of legal substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Starr himself has said, `In court there are a lot of rules
and you'd better play by them.' That's exactly what we're doing in
going to the court of appeals,'' said White House spokesman Jim
Kennedy. ``Mr. Starr's trying to end-run the rules and leapfrog the
legal process.''
</P>
<P>
   On Lewinsky's decision, Ginsburg had taken to virtual open
warfare with Starr, even in the face of growing indications that
the independent counsel might seek her indictment. Last week, in an
article he wrote for a California legal journal, he asked Clinton
to use his presidential powers to fire Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the case in January, Ginsburg's tack was far different.
Then, he teased the news media, and thus the public, with hints of
Lewinsky's potentially lurid story of Oval Office sex.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 25, he said in a television interview, ``She wants to
talk to the independent counsel and unload everything she has.
Everything.'' That day, amid widespread reports that Lewinsky kept
clothing with a semen stain from Clinton, Ginsburg talked of the
existence of a ``dress that might be forensically important in
terms of DNA evidence.'' No such evidence is known to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Many news outlets have reported that Ginsburg offered Starr a
proffer, saying Lewinsky would testify to the existence of a sexual
relationship with Clinton, but denying accusations that Clinton
tried to influence her testimony in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment suit.
</P>
<P>
   By Feb. 1, Ginsburg publicly changed his story, saying, ``It'll
pass. The president will remain in office, he'll do a good job,
we'll all, hopefully, have a sound economy, keep our jobs, and I
think everything's going to be fine.'' On March 4, he said
pointedly, ``There was no sexual relationship with the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
