<SLUG> BC-CHINA-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL TO QUIZ AIDES TO 3 PRESIDENTS OVER SATELLITE EXPORTS TO
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's chief investigator looking into
whether China gleaned from American satellites secret information
that may have jeopardized U.S. national security said on Tuesday
that he would summon top officials from the Reagan, Bush, and
Clinton administrations to testify in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., who heads the Senate Intelligence
Committee, said that the panel would examine the practice of
issuing presidential waivers to allow the export of American
satellites for launching on Chinese missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, the waivers have been required as a result of
sanctions imposed after the killings in Tiananmen Square. President
Bush issued waivers for the export of nine satellites. President
Clinton has issued waivers for 11 satellites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look at the historical perspective, from Reagan and Bush
to Clinton,'' Shelby told reporters. ``We'll look at what the
policy was then and how it changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said the panel would seek testimony from former Bush
officials including James Baker, the secretary of state, and Brent
Scowcroft, Bush's national security adviser. He said the panel
would also seek testimony from past and present aides to Clinton
such as William Perry, the former defense secretary; and John
Deutch, the former director of central intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said he might also summon Gen. Colin Powell, the former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, who served as the national
security adviser to Reagan from late 1987 until early 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1988, Reagan approved the first plan to allow the
export of American communication satellites to China for launching
on Chinese rockets. Clinton administration officials said they only
followed a waiver practice started by Bush and insisted that no
sensitive information has been transferred.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican critics say that officials in the Clinton
administration adopted a more freewheeling approach to exporting
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence committee on Tuesday listed some of the
questions it would try to answer: Which specific Chinese launches
of U.S. manufactured satellites, if any, facilitated the
transmittal of technical knowledge to the Chinese launch industry?
Did such information enable China to develop more effective
missiles?
</P>
<P>
   The panel will also look into allegations that the Chinese
government sought to influence elections in the United States in
1996 through political donations. A Democratic fund-raiser, Johnny
Chung, has told investigators that he received much of the nearly
$100,000 he gave to Democratic causes from a lieutenant colonel in
the Chinese military, according to officials familiar with the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's committee action, endorsed by an advisory group of
Republican senators led by Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority
leader, marked the latest step in a multi-pronged congressional
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The House plans to create a select committee, headed by Rep.
Christopher Cox, R-Calif., to investigate the accusations. But
Democrats and Republicans are still wrangling over the makeup of
the panel and its procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate intelligence panel is to hold closed hearings on
Thursday and Friday with George Tenet, the director of central
intelligence; Attorney General Janet Reno, and Louis Freeh, the
director of the FBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
