<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRILL LYNCH SETTLES SUIT BROUGHT BY ORANGE COUNTY
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has agreed to pay $400 million to Orange County,
Calif., to settle the largest municipal bankruptcy in the nation's
history. The settlement means that the county has recovered more
than $621 million so far, and analysts expect it could end up
recovering more than $800 million over all out of a total of more
than $1.6 billion lost.
</P>
<P>
   SINGLE-FAMILY HOME SALES SOAR
</P>
<P>
   Low interest rates and strong consumer confidence helped push
sales of new single-family homes up 5.2 percent in April, to an
annual rate of 888,000 units. In another report, the index of
leading economic indicators increased one-tenth of 1 percent in
April. Both are signs that the economy is expected to keep growing
in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER SALES JUMPED 27 PERCENT IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Chrysler cars and trucks soared 27 percent in May,
making it the best month ever for the No.3 United States automaker.
</P>
<P>
   REGULATORS PONDER CONRAIL TAKEOVER
</P>
<P>
   Federal railroad regulators are holding hearings Wednesday and
Thursday on plans by Norfolk Southern and CSX to take over Conrail.
Although they are expected to approve the takeover, analysts say
they will move cautiously because of the rail tie-ups that resulted
from the merger two years ago of Southern Pacific with Union
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED AS NASDAQ REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks slipped, but technology issues rebounded from
steep losses Monday. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 31.13
points, to 8,891.24. The Nasdaq composite index, heavily weighted
with technology issues, rose 14.97 points, to 1,761.79.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices slipped. The 30-year yield rose to 5.79 percent
from 5.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN WARNS OF RUSSIA'S IMPACT
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Rubin called for a resolution to Russia's
financial crisis before its economic troubles spread to Central
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY OFFICIAL LEAVES FOR COMCAST
</P>
<P>
   Steven Burke, 39, was named as head of Comcast's cable
television unit as it moves toward selling digital TV service and
Internet access through cable lines. Burke had been president of
Walt Disney's ABC Broadcasting division. He helped found the chain
of Disney Stores, led the revamping of Euro Disney and was
considered by some as a possible successor to Michael Eisner as
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   LITIGATOR SAID TO SEEK INTEL SUIT
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission's top litigator is said to have
recommended that the commission sue Intel on charges of antitrust
violations. The commissioners are likely to vote on the
recommendation next week.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT-TRUCK CRASH TESTS RELEASED
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration released
crash-test results that it said showed sport utility vehicles could
inflict more damage on cars. Automotive industry officials said the
results provided little if any new information.
</P>
<P>
   SARA LEE TO GIVE AWAY PAINTINGS
</P>
<P>
   Some 40 Impressionist paintings and sculptures worth about $100
million will be donated by Sara Lee Corporation to 20 museums
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI ENDS BOTTLER'S FRANCHISE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico broke off a 32-year franchise agreement with one of its
largest independent bottlers, contending that the bottler insisted
on a number of demands or else it would enter into Pepsico's
lawsuit against Coca-Cola on Coke's side.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH AIRWAYS' NO-FRILLS UPSTART
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation of the European airline industry has created
competition among low-cost, no-frills companies, but the rivals are
complaining about British Airways' Go subsidiary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
