<HEADER>
A1171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COL-COLLEGE-NYT &LR;      06-02 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-COLLEGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESERVING COLLEGE PRIDE IN A TEMPEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Fanfare for the Common Man'' heralded the City
College class of 1998 as they filed past cheering friends and
relatives and into Lewisohn Plaza. The music was as fitting as the
smiles and high-fives they shared with friends and relatives. Even
the school's custodial crew was clapping. For the sons and
daughters of working people who never dared go to college, there
was nothing common about graduation day.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolism abounded, down to the chief marshal who preceded the
college president carrying a mace. In medieval times, a bodyguard
wielded it to protect officials. It might still come in handy,
considering how the City University of New York has endured
withering criticism for lax standards, lazy students, and devalued
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The best defense against those attacks was in the crowd and on
the VIP stand, like Angela Goan. She started at City as an Irish
immigrant who took remedial math to bolster her confidence and
ended up six years later with a perfect average and the honor of
being named salutatorian.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion that her degree is worth less than those bestowed
in a storied past angered her. She worked as a nursery school
teacher's aide full time by day and studied by night. Her financial
aid was a modest reimbursement from her job and her credit card,
which helped her defer tuition payments. She earned a bachelor's
degree in education, summa cum laude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good professors, we work hard and it's not like you
come here and are guaranteed an A,'' said Ms. Goan, who will study
for her master's degree at City. ``It's demeaning for somebody to
think you could work so hard and put in so much effort and then
they say it's not worth what it was before. That it's not special.
This is special.''
</P>
<P>
   At 35, she is the first in her family to go to college. Her
mother, who still lives in County Donegal, Ireland, does not grasp
the full impact of her accomplishments, although she is proud. She
was the one who suggested to Ms. Goan that she visit New York,
hoping that the girl would get her wanderlust out of her system and
come home.
</P>
<P>
   But home had its limits for someone like Ms. Goan, who went from
high school to factory work. ``College is not expected of you,''
she said. ``You could very well go into a dead-end job.''
</P>
<P>
   Eager for change, she had come to the states as a live-in nanny
13 years ago. In the early 1990s, she was caring for children and
decided she wanted to become a teacher. She took a job as an aide
at a nursery school and enrolled in college. Worried that she had
been out of school for a decade, she took a remedial math class,
although she had passed the placement test.
</P>
<P>
   Her remedial work was voluntary, yet she saw it as a necessary
morale booster. Unlike the City University of New York board that
voted to eliminate it at the senior colleges, she defended its
place in the four-year schools. Shunting remedial courses to the
community colleges would add one more step to discourage people
from pursuing an education, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everybody goes to college at a young age, and not all of
them took high school seriously,'' she said. ``When you're older,
you realize the value of an education. But maybe you don't have the
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   She developed a slew of time- and money-saving skills to get
through college _ most of which involved having no social life, no
spare income and no time to read or do much else for fun with her
husband, Aliou Coulibaly. But she considered that easy, compared
with the cooking, cleaning and child-raising that classmates had to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, they're going to be productive and contributing to our
society,'' she said. ``And that's the part I don't understand when
people and politicians criticize us. It all comes back into the
pot. If you give something out, it all comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it public college karma. That theme echoed in the ephebic
oath that Ms. Goan and her classmates intoned at the end of
commencement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We men and women graduating from the City College of New
York,'' they began, as they pledged to be dutiful and diligent,
respectful and reverent. ``We will never bring disgrace to our city
by any act of dishonesty or cowardice nor ever desert our suffering
comrades in the ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time that vow was uttered by the many was not at City
College but during Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's inauguration in
January. The mayor led the crowd in what he called the Athenian
Oath of Fealty. The words were the same, except for the part about
City College.
</P>
</TEXT>
