<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-D'AMATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SENATOR QUID PRO QUO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following editorial will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday, June 3:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who glories in the nickname ``senator
Pothole,'' appears to be planning another re-election campaign in
which New Yorkers will be regaled with populist yarns from
constituents who have had their roads repaired, immigration
problems resolved, their insurance carriers whipped into line.
</P>
<P>
   Being of service is the core of D'Amato's sales pitch, and as he
himself said when announcing his candidacy for a fourth term, ``the
little people have needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But as an article in Tuesday's Times points out, D'Amato, the
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, is too modest about his
attempts to deliver and too vague about for whom. For every
beleaguered widow and irritated homeowner who has marveled at the
senator's willingness to be of aid, there appears to be a long line
of Wall Street executives, investment brokers and credit card
companies that have asked D'Amato for assistance and sealed the
request with a contribution. Corporations, it seems, have needs too
_ very expensive ones.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokeswoman, D'Amato has denied that his eagerness to
help out a multibillion-dollar business with a merger problem or
limited partnerships in need of a tax break has anything to do with
the fact that the beneficiaries of his legislative zeal were also
big campaign contributors. The real connection, she said, is that
``Senator D'Amato is always fighting for New Yorkers and New York
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   (When the needs of local businesses are completely fulfilled,
the senator appears to occasionally have enough spare time to
devote to fighting for the needs of campaign contributors in
Delaware or Puerto Rico as well. So many big guys to help, so
little time!)
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of accuracy, D'Amato's re-election ads should
feature a more realistic mix of beneficiaries. For every man on the
street who got a hand from senator Pothole, we would like to see a
$100,000 donor from the financial services industry describing, in
moving detail, how D'Amato was there when he was needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
