<SLUG> BC-NY-READING-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAIN, NEW YORK CITY READING SCORES ARE UP  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the second year in a row, scores by elementary
and middle-school students on citywide reading tests improved
slightly, just shy of the national average, according to Board of
Education figures released on Tuesday. Scores went up in each of
the city's 32 community school districts, though the gains across
the board were smaller than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more than 418,000 students in the third through eighth
grades who took the California Testing Battery Reading exam in
April, 49.6 percent scored at or above grade level; the national
norm is 50 percent. Last year, 47.3 percent scored at or above
grade level.
</P>
<P>
   But, as was the case last year, not all students were required
to take the test, a practice that had raised questions about the
reliability of the figures. Students who demonstrate on a separate
language proficiency test that their knowledge of English is
limited are exempt from the citywide reading examination, in
keeping with state Education Department regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first time that policy was applied. The
exclusion, critics had said, artificially raised scores, although
the board adjusted 1996 scores in order to make valid comparisons.
This year, no such adjustments are necessary, since limited English
speakers were exempt again.
</P>
<P>
   This time, 4,300 fewer students with limited English skills were
exempted from the reading test, and 1,300 fewer students were
absent on the days the tests were administered _ offering some
reassurance to testing experts, since scores can be inflated by
exempting more limited English speakers or urging low-performing
students to stay home on the day of the test.
</P>
<P>
   A new form of the test was administered this year, reducing the
chance that scores rose simply because students grew accustomed to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got fewer kids who are being eliminated and the
scores are going up, that's a good sign,'' said Dr. Thomas Fisher,
an expert on evaluating test scores who is assessment administrator
for the Florida education department. ``That means you are being
more inclusive and achievement is going up. That's good, especially
if you're giving a new form of the test.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news briefing at Board of Education headquarters on Tuesday
afternoon, Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, who has far greater
control over each district now than he had in the past, was
jubilant. The two-year gain of nearly 6 percent was the largest in
16 years. ``This system cannot only perform but it has done this
two consecutive years,'' he said. ``This is not a fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   He was accompanied by nearly all his district superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   Crew expressed unequivocal support on Tuesday for the district
superintendents; under state legislation passed last year, he can
end their contracts if he finds persistent educational failure in
their districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have said all along was this is about incremental,
sustained progress,'' he said. ``I am not worried that gains in any
particular district are not as high as we wanted them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Berne, a New York University vice president who
specializes in studying the city school system, said on Tuesday
that the chancellor's new power over school boards meant that city
and state officials would be looking closely at what action he
takes with low-performing districts whose scores have not risen as
much as the rest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2204EDT &QL; 
