<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-NUKE-REACTOR-503&AMP;A     06-02 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-NUKE-REACTOR-503&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS DECLARE CONN. REACTOR READY TO RESTART 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN RABINOVITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKVILLE, Md. _ After completing one of the most intensive
safety reviews in the history of the nuclear power industry,
federal regulators said Tuesday that one of the three Millstone
nuclear reactors in Connecticut was ready to restart and brushed
aside criticism that they had failed to investigate a number of
problems at the plant sufficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Unit 3 has been idle for more than two years, and while the
proposal to allow it to begin operating again is not final _ the
recommendation comes from the staff of the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission and still must be approved by the four commissioners _
it was seen as a pivotal moment. Shirley Ann Jackson, the NRC
chairwoman, called it a ``watershed point.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to restart Unit 3 has been closely watched by
operators of nuclear plants nationwide. Not since Three Mile Island
has there been such an ambitious effort to turn around a troubled
nuclear plant, many industry experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said it had used the equivalent of 70 full-time staff
people working on Millstone for more than two years. And a team of
outside consultants spent more than 160,000 engineering-hours
conducting the most thorough review of a reactor's design that
regulators said had ever been done.
</P>
<P>
   With the report issued Tuesday by a special projects office,
formed two years ago to address a host of safety problems at
Millstone, Hugh Thompson, a deputy executive director at the NRC,
said, ``The staff is confident that Unit 3's licensing and design
bases have been established, the staff is confident that an
adequate corrective action program has been established, and Unit 3
is ready to transition into an operational mode and begin restart
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the eight-hour hearing Tuesday at NRC headquarters
included testimony from many who did not want it to start. Critics
cited a host of problems as evidence that the Unit 3 reactor should
not be authorized to restart. They noted that a recent leak in one
safety valve had not been repaired, that the consultants' review
had discovered more than 100 calculating errors in the plant's
design and that federal regulators and the outside team of
consultants had not looked at enough of the plant's safety systems.
</P>
<P>
   And David Lochbaum, a nuclear engineer with the Union of
Concerned Scientists, a watchdog group, said that while Northeast
Utilities, the operator of Unit 3, had made substantial
improvements, he was not convinced that the NRC would be poised to
shut the unit down again if problems arose.
</P>
<P>
   The NRC asked the commissioners to file their votes by Tuesday,
though there is no set deadline for the ballots. Three votes are
needed to approve the restart of Unit 3. If Jackson and the three
other commissioners give their approval, it would still take some
time _ perhaps four to six weeks _ before the reactor was running
and producing electricity. Northeast Utilities desperately needs
the additional power for the hottest days of summer, when
electricity usage is at its yearly high.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even then, regulators noted, the unit's final go-ahead would
still turn on the resolution of some outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear when Unit 2 would be restarted, as it is at
least several months behind Unit 3 in repairs. All work on Unit 1,
the oldest and smallest Millstone reactor, has been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle to get the reactors back on line is critical to the
survival of Northeast Utilities, which has spent almost $1 billion
to fix the Waterford, Conn., plant and has seen its revenues
plummet as a result of the reactors' shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the Connecticut Department of Utility
Control has ruled that Northeast must cut the rate it charges
consumers by $14 million a month if Unit 3 is not producing power
soon. Such a rate reduction could throw Northeast Utilities into
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort to improve Millstone has repercussions beyond
Northeast Utilities and may be a telling sign of the NRC's ability
to deal with its own problems.
</P>
<P>
   Only one year ago, the General Accounting Office issued a report
that found that the agency had been too lax in enforcing
regulations and had been too cozy with the nuclear power industry.
</P>
<P>
   Millstone became the poster child of all that had gone wrong at
the NRC, and the agency acknowledged that it had made mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   For at least a decade, the agency had allowed the plant to
operate out of compliance with its licensed design, and regulators
did not heed a host of safety complaints that were raised by
employees. Instead, the NRC actually handed over the names of
employees who raised complaints to Northeast Utilities and took no
action to protect them when the company harassed and even fired
those whistle-blowers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, two years after the NRC recognized these problems and
then levied the largest fine ever against a nuclear plant _ $2.1
million last December _ there are still questions about the
agency's ability to avoid another Millstone.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as if to underscore the difficulties the agency faces,
Jackson held a news conference after Tuesday's hearing in which she
disclosed that a Senate Appropriations subcommittee, the Energy and
Water Development Subcommittee, had proposed eliminating 500 of the
1,400 positions in the agency that dealt with regulating nuclear
reactor safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be devastating to the agency,'' Jackson said, noting
that the proposal was very much ``in flux.''
</P>
<P>
   But aside from that potential setback, Jackson insisted that the
the agency had made substantial progress in the last two years,
bringing in a new management team, ratcheting up safety standards,
requiring more oversight of inspectors in the region and beginning
considerations on a new system to evaluate reactor safety.
</P>
<P>
   Lochbaum remained skeptical. In the review of the reactor's
design, he noted that the outside team of consultants that the NRC
had brought in only looked at 15 of the 88 safety-related systems,
and that it discovered that Northeast had made 158 calculation
errors in its evaluation of how its design would work.
</P>
<P>
   While regulators dismissed such mistakes as minor, Lochbaum
maintained that these problems could suggest a more widespread
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Jackson said that if Millstone were authorized to restart,
the agency would be ready to shut it down again quickly if the old
problems returned, saying ``Many, many things have changed at the
NRC.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
