<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WALL STREET TURNS HOSTILE TO CHAINSAW AL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chainsaw Al is getting cut up by Wall Street, which is beginning
to suspect that there is more to corporate success than a
willingness to fire people.
</P>
<P>
   Chainsaw Al is the nickname given some time ago to Al Dunlap,
who became a corporate legend after he was hired as chief executive
officer of Scott Paper Company and dismissed thousands in the
course of turning around the company, which eventually was sold to
Kimberly-Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most CEOs are ridiculously overpaid,'' he wrote in his memoir,
``Mean Business,'' which became a best seller, ``but I deserved the
$100 million I took away when Scott merged with Kimberly-Clark.''
Modesty and understatement have never been among his prime virtues.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1996, when a struggling Sunbeam Corp. turned to him as a
savior, there was cheering on Wall Street. One analyst compared the
move to the Los Angeles Lakers signing Shaquille O'Neal. Sunbeam's
stock price leaped 49 percent the day the move was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, whose memoir proudly notes that his nicknames, in
addition to Chainsaw Al, have included The Shredder and Rambo in
Pinstripes, set about dismissing bosses and workers. And it seemed
to work.
</P>
<P>
   For 1997 the company reported sharply increased sales and
profits, and in February its board rewarded Dunlap with a 100
percent pay increase, guaranteeing him an annual salary of $2
million. He also got a grant of 300,000 shares and such management
perks as financial planning advice and country club dues. The
company's stock price, at $18.63 after the leap following Dunlap's
hiring, soared to $53 in early March.
</P>
<P>
   Then the bad news arrived. It turned out that the profits for
the final three months of 1997 had gotten a big boost from the sale
of barbecue grills _ not normally a big winter item. Sunbeam had
offered phenomenal terms to customers such as Kmart and Wal-Mart to
buy grills early. That had the effect of making 1997 profits look
better, and of taking sales away from the first half of 1998.
Results this year are dreadful.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap met with analysts last month to explain what had
happened. ``I take full responsibility,'' he said, before making
clear it was everyone's fault but his. He blamed the weather. He
blamed a retail chain for messing up grills that had to be
recalled. He explained that because he had been working on a series
of acquisitions, ``I left a marketing guy in charge of operations.
Mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the grills being sold in December, he denied it was an
effort to ``artificially pump up'' 1997 profits. It was, he
explained, ``a well-intentioned market-driven strategy that simply
didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam is now integrating those acquisitions _ First Alert,
Coleman and Signature Brand _ and promises to make big savings
through plant closings and the dismissals of 5,100 workers. Dunlap
has fired some of his top aides and brought in replacements from
the outside.
</P>
<P>
   But burned investors no longer seem to trust him. The stock
price has dropped 58 percent, and Wall Street analysts who once
lionized Dunlap now seem unimpressed. ``We would like,'' wrote one
analyst who no longer is recommending Sunbeam, ``to have heard a
more tension-easing tone of humility from top management.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Dunlap, who declined to be interviewed, is
that he appears to be in no danger of losing his job. The new
contract he signed before the bad news hit guarantees him $2
million a year for at least three years. Chainsaw Al is doing just
fine, even if his shareholders aren't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
