</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SEATTLE -- June 2, 1998 -- AUTHOR-BLUME-SPI, 6-2 -- Judy
Blume, who became a household name after selling an astounding 65
million books for children and young adults. ``I'm very insecure
about my writing,'' says Ms. Blume, in Seattle recently promoting
her new adults-only novel ``Summer Sisters.'' (Grant M.
Haller/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CORDOVA, Alaska -- June 2, 1998 -- COPPER-RIVER-SALMON-2,
6-02 -- Jeff Bailey, a fisherman in Cordova, Alaska, hoists aboard
a Copper River king salmon. Spring's first run of these highly
prized fish is avidly watched and awaited by chefs nationwide. Most
of the Copper River's bounty will be available until August. But
the best-tasting of these fish, connoisseurs say, are the
early-running ones, which are available until mid-June. (Al
Grillo*/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CORDOVA, Alaska -- June 2, 1998 -- COPPER-RIVER-SALMON-1,
6-02 -- Fishing boats gather near the mouth of the Copper River,
where salmon start their 300-mile run upstream to spawn in the icy
headwaters of the Wrangell Mountains. A string of restaurants and
fish vendors from Puget Sound to Long Island Sound, from Miami to
Los Angeles, swear that there is no other fish that gets people
quite like this first wild salmon of the season. (Al Grillo*/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   *MANDATORY PHOTO CREDIT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1998 --
UPSCALE-RESTAURANT-TRINKETS-2, 6-2 -- Rhonda Muziani, the ``teddy
bear girl'', holds her tray of full of teddy bears at The Rainbow
Room. ``We substituted bears for cigarettes when the no-smoking
laws went into effect,'' explains Robyn Massey, the director of
public relations for the Rainbow Room. (Barbara Alper/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1998 --
UPSCALE-RESTAURANT-TRINKETS-1, 6-2 -- Upscale restaurants that have
entered the merchandise arena include Jean George with this silver
wine coaster and Evian holder, left, and The ``21'' Club with this
umbrella bearing their name. Because some of these items are
available at restaurants and nowhere else, selling them to
customers makes a lot of sense. (Barbara Alper/New York Times
Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1998 -- GREEN-ZEBRA-TOMATOS, 6-2 --
Zebra tomatoes, a striking heirloom variety that can be tawny and
green or green on green, are now in specialty shops. These tomatoes
make delicious preserves and pickle nicely. In exotic recipes, like
Vietnamese chicken salad, thinly sliced strips of zebra pulp can
take the place of green papaya. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1998 -- FOOD-NOTES, 6-2 -- The
produce department at Zabar's has expanded from a few items to this
new all-organic display. The Upper West Side deli, which opened in
1936, has made significant changes to keep up with demands of its
clients. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SALT LAKE CITY -- June 2, 1998 -- BKN-JAZZ-SLOAN, 6-2 --
Bobbye and Jerry Sloan walking by their home in Wasatch Mountains.
Bobbye was diagnosed with breast cancer shortly after Jerry, the
coach of the Utah Jazz, faced his biggest challenge, the Chicago
Bulls. ``The situation she's gone through had made us more aware of
each other, a lot more,'' Jerry says. (George Frey/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
