<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TAXIS-NYT &LR;      06-02 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND THOUGHTS EMERGE ABOUT NEW RULES FOR NEW YORK TAXIS
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than half the members of the city's Taxi and
Limousine Commission say they are having second thoughts about at
least one of the measures they approved last week in cracking down
on taxi drivers, and they criticized the Giuliani administration
for pressuring them to vote so quickly on sweeping new rules to
overhaul the industry's safety practices.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the eight commissioners said in interviews that they
would like to reconsider one crucial rule that makes it much easier
to suspend cabbies over safety violations and other infractions.
And even though Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said he would not back down
on any of his proposals, several commissioners said their concerns
were growing about two other major safety measures that were tabled
last week in the face of industry opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash at the commission is potentially significant
because five votes are needed to pass _ or reconsider _ any rules,
and some of the commissioners are clearly upset by the
bare-knuckled nature of the mayor's recent attack on the taxi
industry.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the commissioners _ who have often been
criticized as being too protective of the industry _ were venting
frustration at being caught in this battle. But the mayor's aides
are still lobbying them hard, and even some industry lobbyists say
they doubt the commissioners have the gumption to reverse
themselves or stand in the way of the mayor's determination to
shake up the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the commissioners also disclosed Tuesday that in
addition to a closed-door meeting of the board just prior to
Thursday's vote, the commission held an unpublicized meeting two
weeks earlier to discuss the mayor's proposals. Legal experts have
said that Thursday's meeting probably violated the state
open-meetings law, and spokesmen for industry groups said on
Tuesday that they planned to cite the meetings in suits seeking to
overturn the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   While leveling the criticism, the commissioners agreed there was
a need to improve taxi safety and said they stood behind most of
the 15 new rules, which would increase fines on drivers and require
higher insurance coverage for accident victims. Some also
acknowledged that in many ways, they were simply painting
themselves as reluctant rubber stamps for the mayor and that they
should have had a better understanding of the rules before they
voted.
</P>
<P>
   But several commissioners accused the agency's staff of leaving
them largely in the dark as the new rules were developed and then
failing to fully explain them, especially one that authorizes the
suspension of any cab driver for as little as one moving violation
and one administrative infraction within 18 months. Several
commissioners said that they had no idea that the regulation could
be just as strict as one they had tabled on Thursday because some
felt it was too harsh and could penalize average drivers as well as
bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the commissioners who expressed serious qualms, Sandra
Silverman and Marvin Greenberg, were the crucial swing votes in
favor of the mayor's proposals last week.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Silverman said the way the administration had pushed the
commission for a quick vote ``really deeply offended me.'' She said
she agreed to vote for the rules only because she did not want to
see another month of antagonism between the mayor and the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been dismayed from the beginning by the mayor's
rhetoric,'' said Ms. Silverman. She added that she thought the
commission needed to revisit the issues involving driver
suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, who also was worried about suspending drivers too
quickly, said he was especially concerned about the other tabled
proposal, which would require every person or company that owned a
yellow cab to post a $100,000 bond for accident victims. Many
independent drivers have said it would be impossible for them to
come up with the money for the bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that I've learned in my years with the commission is
that you don't promulgate rules you can't enforce,'' he said. ``So
if people can't come up with the equity that the bonding companies
claim they do require, then we're beating a dead horse and I don't
want to get involved in that.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission's internal politics are volatile because only
three of the commissioners were appointed by Giuliani. The other
five, including Ms. Silverman and Greenberg, were appointed either
by former Mayor David Dinkins or by City Council members. Another
complication is that only six of the eight commissioners were
present for last Thursday's vote, where the measures were approved
by five of them with one member, Alberto Torres, abstaining in
protest.
</P>
<P>
   While the mayor's aides predicted confidently that the bond
proposal and the tabled measure involving driver sanctions were
sure to pass when the absent commissioners, Ramona Whaley and Elias
Arout, returned, neither commissioner seemed supportive of the
mayor's package.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just thrown upon us too fast, this reform,'' said
Arout, who called the bond proposal ``out of whack.''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized the proposal on sanctions for traffic
violations, which which would lower the threshold for suspensions
to six Department of Motor Vehicle points from the current 11. ``I
personally feel that six points is very low and 10 points is
sufficient,'' he said. ``You get six points, the man gets suspended
for 30 days, he can't buy food _ that's just not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver penalty rule that did pass last week sets up a
separate point system for violations of TLC rules and calls for
suspension after five penalty those points within 18 months. A
driver could accrue five points by getting one ticket for following
too closely _ a summons that several commissioners said could
justifiably be issued against just about any car in midtown traffic
_ and another for failing to give a passenger a receipt.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whaley, who left Thursday's meeting before the vote, saying
she had just returned from Africa the night before and was tired,
said on her way out the door that she opposed stiffer penalties for
cabbies. ``Things are already hard enough on the taxi drivers,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
