   (NYT11) ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast -- June 2, 1998 -- AFRICA-ABORTION,
6-02 -- Fernande Aka, 19, sits by the window at her home in Abidjan
last month. After two illegal abortions, she suspects she is
sterile. ``The doctor took new patients, three of us at a time,
into his clinic, and we were all treated very quickly,'' says Miss
Aka. ``There was no anesthetic, he just kept talking to me the
whole while. Within 15 minutes we were on our way.'' (Robert
Grossman/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WORCESTER, Pa. -- June 2, 1998 -- BIOTECH-ARTHRITIS,
6-02 -- In the 20 years Veronica Lewandowski has had rheumatoid
arthritis, she has taken myriad ineffective drugs and has undergone
replacements of both hips, both knees and the knuckles of her right
hand. But in the eight months since Ms. Lewandowski, 39, began
taking an experimental drug known as Enbrel, she is less fatigued
and no longer has to descend stairs backward to spare her knees.
``Life is fun now,'' she says. (Tim Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1998 -- FANTASTIQUE-THEATER-REVIEW,
6-02 -- Fabric, aided by unseen puppeteers, dancing underwater in
``Symphonie Fastastique.'' The production is a gratifying reminder
that there are still things undreamt of in theater producer's
philosophies. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SEATTLE -- June 2, 1998 -- AUTHOR-BLUME-SPI, 6-2 -- Judy
Blume, who became a household name after selling an astounding 65
million books for children and young adults. ``I'm very insecure
about my writing,'' says Ms. Blume, in Seattle recently promoting
her new adults-only novel ``Summer Sisters.'' (Grant M.
Haller/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CORDOVA, Alaska -- June 2, 1998 -- COPPER-RIVER-SALMON-2,
6-02 -- Jeff Bailey, a fisherman in Cordova, Alaska, hoists aboard
a Copper River king salmon. Spring's first run of these highly
prized fish is avidly watched and awaited by chefs nationwide. Most
of the Copper River's bounty will be available until August. But
the best-tasting of these fish, connoisseurs say, are the
early-running ones, which are available until mid-June. (Al
Grillo*/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CORDOVA, Alaska -- June 2, 1998 -- COPPER-RIVER-SALMON-1,
6-02 -- Fishing boats gather near the mouth of the Copper River,
where salmon start their 300-mile run upstream to spawn in the icy
headwaters of the Wrangell Mountains. A string of restaurants and
fish vendors from Puget Sound to Long Island Sound, from Miami to
Los Angeles, swear that there is no other fish that gets people
quite like this first wild salmon of the season. (Al Grillo*/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   *MANDATORY PHOTO CREDIT
</P>
