<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ST.JOHN'S-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED STORM AND JARVIS TALK, BUT COACH'S SALARY IS ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis boarded a train Tuesday morning bound for Washington
from New York. He was headed back to his office at George
Washington University and possibly out of the running for the St.
John's basketball coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   According to a person close to the negotiations, Jarvis wants a
salary of at least $800,000 a year. He currently earns $600,000
coaching George Washington. That figure includes work with
basketball camps, radio and television jobs, as well as a contract
with Nike.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they offer $700,000, he won't leave GW,'' the person said.
``Mike has got a great job. He doesn't need this job. If he doesn't
take this job, he's ultimately looking to move to the NBA. If the
money is right, he will go to St. John's.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis met with St. John's athletic director, Ed Manetta, and
St. John's executive vice president in charge of finance, Bob
Crimmins, on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He then met with St. John's president Donald Harrington. While
the meetings went well, the two sides are at an impasse. St. John's
does not want to tender an offer to Jarvis unless certain that he
would accept the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. John's is a wonderful institution, one of the premier
college basketball coaching jobs in the country,'' said Rob Ades,
Jarvis' agent. ``Any coach would be happy to work there under the
right circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis is the highest-profile candidate of the four coaches who
have met with Manetta; he has reached the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament four times in his eight seasons at
George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's believes that it can bring in one of the other three
candidates, Davidson's Bob McKillop, St. Bonaventure's Jim Baron,
or Siena's Paul Hewitt for about half of what it would cost to hire
Jarvis.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have an NCAA tournament victory among them, but all
three coaches are well regarded and would love to have the job,
even at the discount price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
