<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SALSA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS SAY SALSA IS NOT A VEGETABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHY GEORGE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Salsa: ``a hot sauce made with chilies, tomatoes,
etc.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Webster's defines it. But the federal government has
other ideas. Listen up, students. Salsa is now officially a
vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agriculture Department recently decreed that salsa may
be counted as a vegetable in school lunches under certain
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be loaded with spices, stabilizers or other
non-vegetable ingredients. Also, a mere spoonful splashed atop a
taco won't do _ it has to be at least one-eighth of a cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good for me because I love salsa,'' said Gaia Fisher, a
senior at Bothell High School, north of Seattle, where the drippy
red stuff was offered along with taco salads Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the usual offerings of carrots and corn, salsa is a
great vegetable, added junior Micael Bogar.
</P>
<P>
   Bothell High, like many other schools in the area, has long
offered salsa as a seasoning. But will they now start offering it
as a vegetable?
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue, Renton and Federal Way schools are likely to do so,
but Seattle and Northshore schools probably will not, according to
nutrition directors in those districts.
</P>
<P>
   For Linda Hoel, food supervisor for Bothell's Northshore School
District, calling salsa a vegetable doesn't quite ring true. ``It's
always been just kind of a side condiment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a high honor for a condiment to make the USDA's list of
school vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Consider ketchup, salsa's more established sister in the tomato
sauce family. It never reached that height.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Reagan administration's 1981 proposal to count
ketchup as a vegetable in school lunches was so widely scorned that
it was quickly dropped _ like a rotten tomato.
</P>
<P>
   But salsa is ``not at all'' like ketchup, says Carla Kaser,
Renton's school nutrition director.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can actually see the big chunks of tomato in it,'' said
Kaser, who confessed to being a salsa aficionado.
</P>
<P>
   Ketchup, on the other hand, oozes with sugar and vinegar and is
much more highly processed, nutrition experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Local school districts started hearing about salsa's ascendancy
two weeks ago, when the state superintendent of public instruction
issued a bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salsa may now be credited as part of the fruit/vegetable meal
component for child nutrition programs,'' says the bulletin, which
is posted on the Internet on SPI's homepage,
http://www.ospi.wednet.edu
</P>
<P>
   ``When USDA first disallowed salsa from receiving credit in the
school meals program, it was because salsa was used as a condiment
or garnish and served in amounts smaller than one-eighth cup,'' the
bulletin says. ``As salsa has become more widely accepted by
children, it is used more as a vegetable side dish in amounts
greater than one-eighth cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The bulletin explains that only the vegetable content of salsa,
not starches or stabilizers, may be counted as part of the
one-eighth cup.
</P>
<P>
   And that portion alone won't satisfy all nutritional
requirements. Each meal still has to include a total of at least
three-fourths of a cup of fruits and vegetables, said Skip Skinner,
the state's food distribution manager.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner said the USDA ruling on salsa was requested by schools
around the country. For years they were frustrated that the USDA
distributed salsa to schools, but wouldn't let them count it as a
vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Another driving factor, Skinner said, is salsa's growing appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overtaken ketchup as the most popular tomato product,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
