<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-FUTURE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING FUTURE FOR PHARMACEUTICALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the future, pharmaceutical drugs as we know them
will be changed forever by the merging of two exploding scientific
fields _ genomics, or the study of the human genetic blueprint, and
information sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs will be safer, and more tailored to treat specific
diseases with fewer side effects, scientists said Tuesday at the
Nasdaq International Science and Technology Summit in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, patients will be able to tell before they take a
drug if it will work for them, given their particular genetic
makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Such advances, which are only 10 to 30 years away, are being
made possible by applying the vastly increasing computational power
of computers to unraveling how genes interact in the human body.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fundamental paradigm change has occurred,'' said Leroy Hood,
chairman of the department of molecular biotechnology at the
University of Washington, and a leading figure in the emergence of
this new hybrid field. ``It is the simple idea that biotechnology
is an informational science.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently biologists have concentrated on understanding
single genes by studying them in isolation.
</P>
<P>
   But genomics is the study of hundreds or thousands of genes at a
time, Hood said. ``What we really want to know about genes is not
how they act in isolation, but how they operate in networks.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this ``systems biology,'' or informational sciences
approach that yields the most promise for applications in the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   But to reap the full benefit of that approach, researchers from
universities, companies, non-profit institutes and government labs
are going to have to find innovative ways to work together.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hood is in the final stages of organizing a new
biotechnology institute that will assemble computer scientists,
engineers and molecular biologists to work together on these
complex problems. The institute would bring together academicians
with large and small industrial partners to work in collaboration,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The private and public sectors are interdependent, said Edward
Lazowska, chairman of Computer Science and Engineering at the
University of Washington. ``The complex interplay among government,
academic and industrial labs has driven progress forward in both
information sciences and biotechnology.''
</P>
<P>
   Without that interaction, neither field will progress.
</P>
<P>
   The technology summit, which runs through Wednesday, attracted
biotechnology executives, academics and investors from around the
United States and Europe, all seeking to understand a complex field
that is morphing daily into something new.
</P>
<P>
   The same advances that enabled computers to double in speed
every year are now enabling molecular biologists to decode the
human genome at rates unimaginable even a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The human genome is ``the most incredible software program ever
developed,'' Hood said. Each gene is made up of nucleotides, or
basic building blocks denoted by the letters A, T, C and G. The
task of the Human Genome Project, a world-wide, multi-institutional
effort started in 1990, is to discover the sequence of the more
than 250 million letters in the code.
</P>
<P>
   That sequence ultimately governs the interactions of more than
100,000 human genes, and dictates how a single cell divides and
develops into the billions of cells that make up a human being.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, scientists had decoded about 2,000 genes, or only about
2 percent of the total genetic material contained in the human
genome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biologists haven't been playing with a full deck,'' said
Randall Scott, president of InCyte Pharmaceuticals, a genomic
database company in Palo Alto, Calif. Understanding how the genome
works to program the body with that information is like ``trying to
play a game of spades with three or four cards in the deck.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, scientists have nearly the full deck of cards,
he said. The next task is to decipher exactly what those genes do,
how they interact, and how they are regulated in the body.
</P>
<P>
   Doing that will require applying many of the tools used by
computer scientists to analyze, model and decipher information.
</P>
<P>
   As scientists figure out what certain genes do and how those
genes differ from person to person, they will have a better
understanding of why people are predisposed to certain diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they will be able to look for drugs that work
specifically on the actions of those genes, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ultimate goals of genomics is preventive medicine,
Hood said. ``By identifying genes that predispose to disease and
using preventive therapy, we can keep people well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
