<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS PITCHES YANKEES TO 6-3 VICTORY OVER WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Wells' perfect game and near-perfect record
have been tough to overshadow. But Tuesday night, when Wells took
the mound against the White Sox, he was not exactly the center of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, practically Ruthian in his presence since his perfect
outing on May 17 against the Minnesota Twins, was reduced to a
supporting role when it seemed that a twinge in his pitching
shoulder could open the way for the major league debut of the Cuban
defector Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque, as Cuba's one-time national team great is known,
arrived from Columbus on Tuesday with a $6.6 million, four-year
contract, a 7-1 minor league record and many great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot of attention to overcome. But Wells managed in his
own inimitable way. He proved healthy enough to start, as Hernandez
was relegated to a seat in the general manager's box in the upper
environs of Yankee Stadium. Then Wells showed he was also more than
good enough to win an eighth straight decision as the Yanks cruised
by Chicago 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Wells (8-1) and the Yankees thus resumed their normal routine,
confounding yet another luckless American League opponent and along
the way sweeping the two-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, now 39-13, erased the minor concerns raised when
the team lost the final two games of a four-game set with
second-place Boston this past weekend. The Yankees have now won
eight of their last 11.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wells has been a major part of the Yankees' dominance. Unlike
the perfect game against the Twins, Wells did not prove to be
unfathomable Tuesday night, just unbeatable as he pitched eight
innings and allowed just three runs on seven hits. Mariano Rivera
got his 11th save.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox left fielder Albert Belle did manage to homer of the
left-hander twice in his first three at-bats, bringing his season
total to 13 and his series total to three. And Chicago first
baseman Wil Cordero also found the seats.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees and Wells were saved because the Yankees
hitters, quiet in the homer department early in the season, are
also finding the proper range of late.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill hit a two-out solo homer off Sox starter Mike
Sirotka in the first inning. After Belle tied the score in the
second and Cordero homered to put the Sox up in the third, the
Yankees regained the lead with a four-run fifth.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Yankees tied the score, bunching singles off the bats
of the ageless Tim Raines, Chad Curtis and Scott Brosius. Then the
team that entered the game ranked ninth in the league in homers
unleashed more power, in the form of a three-run homer off the bat
of Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   The homer, hit with two outs, was the Yankees' fifth in the
series and sixth in three games. Jeter, now with eight, tied for
the Yankees' lead with the idle Darryl Strawberry. O'Neill improved
his total to five.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive support and Wells' ability to limit the White Sox
to solo home runs enabled the pitcher to remain in impressive
cruise control. Wells has not lost a game since his season debut on
April 2. He has not allowed more than three runs in any of his last
five starts.
</P>
<P>
   The last team to score more than three runs against Wells was
Texas, on May 6. That game proved a watershed of sorts, because
Wells brought unwanted attention by failing to convert a 9-0 lead
into an easy victory. Wells left that game leading only 9-7, then
took up residence briefly in Joe Torre's doghouse as the manager
openly speculated about Wells' physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   There are no such questions now. With his winning streak intact,
the shoulder in place, Wells cannot be overlooked for long. Even on
a day when there was an El Duque spotting. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
