look at the bloodlines of Real Quiet, poised for a run at the
Triple Crown, which would be quite a tantalizing possibility for a
colt of modest breeding. By Joseph Durso.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COPPER-RIVER-SALMON (Seattle) _ The Gulf of Alaska was tossing
up waves of 20 feet or more and the winds roared to 40 miles an
hour, but the storm did not deter the fleet in pursuit of what is
arguably the world's best-tasting fish _ Copper River salmon _ on
their first run of the season. Why all the fuss? A string of
restaurants and fish vendors from Puget Sound to Long Island Sound,
from Miami to Los Angeles, swear that there is no other fish that
gets people quite like this first wild salmon of the season. By Tim
Egan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT6,7) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   UPSCALE-RESTAURANT-TRINKETS (New York) _ The prix fixe dinner at
Lutece includes three courses of the restaurant's specialties. It's
$65, wine, tax and tip not included. The Limoges plates aren't
included either, but they are, in fact, for sale ($185 for a
five-piece setting). So are the wine glasses and the linen
tablecloth. Of course there are already plenty of theme-park
restaurants like the Hard Rock Cafe and Planet Hollywood where you
can order a burger with a T-shirt on the side. But in the last
couple of years, more sophisticated establishments have been
following suit, taking their own kind of refined commercialism to
the top tier of Manhattan's restaurants. By Suzanne Hamlin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT4,5) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PASTRY-CHEF (Paris) _ Except for a few late-nighters
stumbling home, the Avenue des Champs-Elysees was eerily still. But
inside Laduree, a tea room, pastry shop and restaurant, everything
was astir. It was 6 in the morning, and Pierre Herme, the premier
pastry chef in Paris, was taking the first of many rounds through
the place. To the French, Herme has achieved the stature of the
legendary pastry chef Gaston Lenotre. And since last September he
has taken charge of one of Paris's most beloved tea salons and
pastry shops. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PALE-ALE (New York) _ India Pale Ale from the Heartland
Brewery. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-ZEBRA-TOMATOES (Undated) _ On green zebra tomatoes. By
Molly O'Neill.
</P>
