<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RACIAL-KILLINF-NYT </SLUG>
  
 VICTIM'S FATHER CRITICIZES RELEASE IN RACIAL KILLING  (js) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The father of Yusuf Hawkins, the black teen-ager who
was murdered nine years ago during a racially motivated attack by a
large crowd of white youths on a Brooklyn street, harshly
criticized state officials on Tuesday for the release of Keith
Mondello, one of the men convicted in the case, from prison.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Moses Stewart, spoke at a news conference in Harlem
on Tuesday at which he echoed a call by the Rev. Al Sharpton for a
march this Saturday at noon on Bensonhurst, the neighborhood where
Hawkins, 16, was fatally shot twice in the chest on Aug. 23, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be sure he doesn't have a happy homecoming,''
Stewart said of Mondello, who served eight years of a 12-year
sentence in the Attica state prison after being convicted of
rioting, unlawful imprisonment, menacing and possession of a
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Grant, a spokesman for the New York State Division of
Parole, said Mondello was released because state law requires
prisoners with records of good behavior to be freed after serving
two-thirds of their sentences. Mondello was denied parole in 1994,
1995 and 1997, Grant said. Though not considered to be on parole,
Mondello will remain under the parole board's supervision until the
rest of his term is completed in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In their decisions to refuse parole, board members called
Mondello the ``organizer and leader of a bat-wielding mob'' that
attacked Hawkins, who had gone to Bensonhurst to look at a used
car. Parole board members said Mondello had never expressed remorse
about the attack and would probably commit more crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bensonhurst killed my son and spit in my face,'' Stewart said
at a news conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, who in the months after the murder of Hawkins acted as
a spokesman for the victim's family and organized emotionally
charged marches through Bensonhurst, vowed on Tuesday to stage
rallies again in the largely white neighborhood. ``We still have a
sense of outrage as some welcome him home,'' Sharpton said of
Mondello.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
