<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHILD-WELFARE-NYT &LR;      06-02 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-WELFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI REVAMPS CHILD WELFARE SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the most dramatic revamping of New York City's
child welfare system in over a generation, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
announced Tuesday that he would put hundreds of millions of dollars
in foster care contracts up for competitive bidding in an effort to
care for abused and neglected children in their own neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, New York City will allow churches, child
care providers and other nonprofit groups to bid for slices of the
city's $614 million child welfare contracts. The organizations will
be required to create networks of neighborhood-based services _
foster homes, health care, counseling, drug rehabilitation _
instead of sending the vast majority of children for foster care
and counseling services outside their communities and boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   The city also plans to adopt new measures to judge the
performance of the neighborhood-based contractors, focusing on
assessing the experiences of the children in their care. Those
agencies that fail to reduce complaints of abuse and neglect _ both
in foster care _ who fail to ensure that children receive timely
medical care and who fail to carefully monitor children returned to
abusive or neglectful parents may ultimately lose their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The changes had long been sought by city officials, advocates
for children and foster care agency workers as a way to provide
easy access to children and troubled families. They reflect a
national movement toward neighborhood-based programs as increasing
numbers of cities and states seek to stabilize the lives of
children in foster care and to extend that assistance to their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, city officials had repeatedly renewed contracts with
virtually the same group of child welfare agencies that have
dominated the foster care business for decades. And child welfare
officials often criticized the system that routinely sent battered
children to foster homes far from their neighborhoods, schools and
biological parents, even though about 75 percent of abused and
neglected children ultimately return to parents or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the sheer scale of change stunned officials in the child
welfare field, who had expected Giuliani to roll out the
initiatives gradually, neighborhood by neighborhood, over a period
of three or four years, as he made good on his promises to overhaul
the city's child welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the city will release applications for contracts in the
Bronx Wednesday and for the rest of the city in the fall. City
officials say children expected to enter foster care in the Bronx,
which has a high concentration of the city's abused and neglected
children, will be placed in their neighborhoods starting in January
of next year. Newcomers to foster care in the rest of city will be
placed in their own communities by July 1999; children currently in
foster care will not be disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a radical and dramatic transformation of how child
welfare services are delivered in New York City,'' said Nicholas
Scoppetta, the commissioner of the Administration for Children's
Services, who was hired by Giuliani to improve the city's long
troubled child welfare agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to strengthen neighborhoods and reduce the abuse
and neglect that is now all too pervasive and make life safer and
better for kids,'' said Scoppetta, who stood alongside Guiliani
during a news conference at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The city released few details Tuesday of the changes to come.
And while many child welfare specialists cheered the long-awaited
initiatives, they worried about many questions left unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Will the city, the child welfare specialists wondered, provide
enough dollars for agencies to put the new plan in place? Will
children in foster homes in their neighborhoods be endangered by
aggressively abusive parents? Will parents in poor neighborhoods _
which have historically lacked desperately needed services like
drug rehabilitation programs _ end up with fewer options than they
had when agencies sent them to programs across the city?
</P>
<P>
   Scoppetta tried to allay those fears Tuesday, saying the city
had no plans to reduce child welfare spending. In fact, he said,
the city has already added an additional $13 million to finance
more counseling and drug treatment programs. He added that the
contracts would allow children at risk from further abuse from
aggressive parents to be sent to foster homes outside their
neighborhoods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
