<SLUG> BC-RFK-30YEARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCILMAN WANTS PART OF BOULEVARD NAMED FOR RFK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``a'' national news file.) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In marking the 30th anniversary of Robert F.
Kennedy's assassination in Los Angeles, Councilman Nate Holden said
he wants to rename a stretch of Wilshire Boulevard after the
senator.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony in front of the Ambassador Hotel, where Kennedy
was shot June 5, 1968, Holden said Tuesday he will ask the City
Council to designate a one-block strip of Wilshire as Robert F.
Kennedy Memorial Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   The council is scheduled to vote on the motion Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be assured that at this site, where we lost one of our great
leaders, we are going to have a sign that says he stood here and he
died here,'' Holden said.
</P>
<P>
   If the motion passes, the parkway would consist of a 100-yard
stretch along the 3400 block of Wilshire, between Kenmore and
Alexandria streets. The hotel is on one side of the street, and
Koreatown businesses are on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Former Los Angeles Rams football star Rosey Grier, who was with
Kennedy the night of his death, led a prayer in front of the hotel
Tuesday but refused to go inside for a tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there, and I don't want to go through it again,''
Grier said. ``It's painful enough just standing out front.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden stumped for his motion as he walked through the
Ambassador Hotel ballroom and the kitchen pantry where Kennedy was
shot by Sirhan Sirhan. The hotel has been closed for nine years,
but is still rented out for location filming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always there when America needed him,'' the councilman
said. ``We should have honored him here a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the local business community also came out to show
support for Holden's motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This streetscape site should stand as a tribute to Robert F.
Kennedy for years to come,'' said Richard McDermott, past president
of the Wilshire Chamber of Commerce. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0449 </DOCNO>
