<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHILD-WELFARE-ADVO     06-02 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-WELFARE-ADVOCATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORHOOD CARE WORKS, ADVOCATES SAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (See NY-CHILD-WELFARE)  
 (ATTN.: Calif., Ohio, Mo., Pa., Ore.)  By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, most government agencies around the
country placed children in foster care homes on a first-come,
first-serve basis _ even if it meant moving children from their
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, though, a growing number of cities,
counties and states _ hoping to improve the quality of care for
foster children _ have been moving toward using neighborhood groups
to provide basic services such as foster homes, health care and
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, children's advocates said Tuesday, the
approach has worked. And now, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Tuesday,
New York City will try the new approach.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 500,000 children around the country are in foster
care, according to Michael Petit, deputy director of the Child
Welfare League in Washington, which represents the nation's child
welfare commissioners. But of that number, perhaps half are in
homes located at least an hour or so away from the child's family _
a logistical nightmare that children's advocates say is disruptive
to the child, to the family and to social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, the Youth Law Center, a public interest law firm
in San Francisco, sued Los Angeles County for supervising foster
children inadequately, in part because the children were spread all
over the area and social workers were not seeing the children.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the two sides settled, with one of the provisos
being that the county establish neighborhood-based programs, said
Carol Schauffer, director of the Youth Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of foster parents being happier, and kids having much
less disruption, it has worked,'' said Ms. Schauffer, about the
county's pilot programs.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, a nonprofit organization in Baltimore, the
Annie E. Casey Foundation, began organizing neighborhood-based
programs in Ohio, Philadelphia and other places, quickly attracting
attention across the country, Ms. Schauffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, for instance, has been moving toward
neighborhood-based programs for about three years, and now St.
Louis, Kansas City and about two-thirds of the state have such a
policy, said Carmen Schulze, director of the Missouri Division of
Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   This has entailed opening up the foster care process to
competitive bidding _ similar to what New York is proposing _ and
enlisting help from groups like the Salvation Army, Ms. Schulze
said.
</P>
<P>
   And in Oregon, the State Office of Services to Children and
Families has just launched two pilot programs in the Portland area
designed to keep foster children not only in the same neighborhood,
but in the same school, said Kevin George, the program's
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this idea will work in New York, though, will depend not
so much on the principle _ which children's advocates say is
generally unassailable _ but on the implementation by the city's
beleaguered Administration for Children's Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it good or bad?'' said Petit. ``Well, it really depends. If
it's executed well, and done properly with sufficient resources,
and it's monitored, then it can work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2246EDT &QL; 
