<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GREEN-D'AMATO-574&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN ACCUSES D'AMATO OF ACTING IN RETALIATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Green, who is seeking the Democratic nomination
for the Senate, accused Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, the man he wants to
unseat, Tuesday of trying to dismantle a federal board that
regulates a system of mortgage banks, in retaliation for the firing
of one of his political allies by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Green, New York City's public advocate, also charged that
D'Amato was pushing federal legislation that would allow mortgage
banking policies that would benefit large banking corporations and
wealthy investors, groups that have been major contributors to the
Republican senator's campaign account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. D'Amato is more interested in expanding corporate welfare
for banks and his lobbying friends than in increasing housing for
working families,'' Green said in a news conference at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for D'Amato denied that the senator was
retalilating against the Clinton administration for removing
Lawrence Costiglio as a director of the Federal Housing Finance
Board in March. Costiglio, who was appointed to the board by
President Bush, is a longtime D'Amato supporter who, along with his
wife, has contributed $6,600 to the senator's campaigns since 1992,
according to Green.
</P>
<P>
   Lisette McSoud Mondello, D'Amato's spokeswoman, said his bill
was intended to update an archaic and ineffective regulatory
system, and she described Green as ``still bitter'' about losing
decisively to D'Amato in the 1986 Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This once again demonstrates that Mark Green is a desperate
candidate,'' Ms. Mondello said. ``It's sad that he has to resort to
such negative tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's latest attack on D'Amato underscores one of the
fundamental differences between him and the other two Democratic
candidates for the Senate, Geraldine Ferraro and Rep. Charles
Schumer. While the other two candidates have sought to portray
D'Amato as out of touch with New York's political mainstream, Green
has vowed to make an issue of D'Amato's ethics and voracious
campaign finance machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Green's news conferece also demonstrated the Democratic
candidate's efforts to turn one of D'Amato's political strengths,
his chairmanship of the powerful Senate Banking Committee, into a
weakness. Green contends that D'Amato has consistently used his
position to attract campaign contributions from wealthy
special-interest groups, and do favors for them in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been his entire career,'' said Joseph DePlasco, Green's
campaign spokesman. ``He's always been more inclined to work for
large contributors and special interests than for potential
homeowners and constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a fight in Washington over the future of the Housing
Finance Board, which regulates the Federal Home Loan Bank system.
The 12-bank system was created by Congress during the Depression to
provide low-cost funds to retail banks to help them underwrite
long-term mortgages for home buyers. The system helped create the
30-year, fixed-rate mortgage that has made home-ownership possible
for a broader spectrum of people.
</P>
<P>
   In April, D'Amato proposed legislation that would abolish the
Housing Finance Board and transfer its regulatory duties to the
Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, which also oversees
two other federally chartered corporations that underwrite home
mortgages, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has said that he introduced the legislation to abolish
duplicative federal offices.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Green and Bruce Morrison, chairman of the Housing Finance
Board, contend that D'Amato's bill includes language that would
require the 12 Federal Home Loan Banks to pay dividends to their
shareholders high enough to make their stock ``a competitive
investment.'' The Home Loan Banks are cooperatives that are owned
entirely by retail banks that make mortgage loans.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Morrison said that language would allow the
Federal Home Loan Banks to make investments that might be more
profitable than home mortgages, but that would divert the system
from its central mission of making home ownership available to more
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefits would be likely to end up in the pockets of
shareholders, not borrowers,'' said Morrison, a former Democratic
congressman from Connecticut who was appointed to the Housing
Finance Board by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Green's campaign also contends that D'Amato's bill could fatten
the profits of the retail banks that own shares in the Federal Home
Loan Banks. And many of those retail banks are contributors to
D'Amato, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
