<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980602.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1237 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSONCOMMENT-     06-02 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSONCOMMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hingis still worlds better than Venus
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ The latest issue of GQ magazine features on its cover
Martina Hingis wearing a short, stunning white dress that's tighter
than, if possible, her groundstrokes. Hingis doesn't look like a
17-year-old in the photograph. No, sir.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she hardly looks 17 in a tennis dress, either.
</P>
<P>
   In a tennis dress, she is the oldest teen-ager in the history of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Other girls, even some practically as young as her, have won
big. Hingis' pending hurdle in the French Open semifinals, Monica
Seles, once held the record for Grand Slam precociousness that
Martina broke. But none of them, Seles included, did it as she does
it, with a game evolved far beyond her linear years.
</P>
<P>
   Martina's tennis instincts defy logical explanation because such
sophisticated shot-making is presumably learned, not genetically
programmed at birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has never played teen-age tennis,'' says Heinz Gunthardt,
who coaches Steffi Graf, a former teen queen of some note. ``The
first time I saw her, she played adult tennis. When you see a
teen-ager, you see incredible shots. When I saw Martina, I did not
see her make incredible shots. She made it look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   And she did it again Tuesday, putting her ``rivalry'' with Venus
Williams on hold until another day. It becomes a rivalry when
Williams spanks Hingis in a tournament that matters. That's when,
and only when, this thing between them turns into something.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Martina rules. Unequivocally. She's 6-2 against Venus
and leads 4-0 in Grand Slam tournaments won.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on appearances alone, Venus appears to be at the very least
Hingis' equal. After all, she is taller, faster, stronger and more
athletic, besides being 105 days older.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the match starts. The woman and the girl quickly
identify themselves. There's no absolutely no confusion as to which
is which.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Williams swatted a whole slew of more incredible
shots, hitting balls hard enough on occasion to make you wonder if
she belonged in the men's draw instead. But when they totaled up
the score of a much-anticipated Roland Garros quarterfinal, Hingis
was again an easy winner 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, she remains comfortably on track to complete a career
Grand Slam before she obtains her driver's license. Mon dieu!
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always leading,'' she said. ``I never thought if (Venus)
can beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   L'equipe, the French sports daily, tagged Williams ``La Menace''
to Hingis in its headline on a story previewing the match. As it
turned out, Venus proved a menace just to herself, committing
frequent double faults and 38 unforced errors. She was among the
first to concede she never stood a chance.
</P>
<P>
   A tough concession, by the way, given her plan to take over the
No. 1 ranking from Martina by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to have to get a little more serious,''
Williams said. ``It's probably good for me to lose, so I can really
see what I'm doing wrong, to really look at myself and say, `Venus,
you're not there.' That's what I have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I have the opportunity. What is it, three weeks before
Wimbledon? I have all the time in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Three weeks is hardly long enough for her to learn how to
paint like Monet, which is basically how Hingis plays tennis.
</P>
<P>
   As is usually the case, Williams hit some of the best shots you
will ever see Tuesday _ and also some of the worst. On one serve,
she lost her grip on the racket and tossed it almost into the net.
She whacked several balls 20 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I got a little too excited,'' she admitted, ``really
wanting to hit a winner, maybe sometimes prematurely, also. Of
course, I have to do away with that. I have to take steps to make
sure it doesn't happen anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive points early in the match, as early as the second
game, summed up the difference between Hingis and Williams. Serving
after Hingis held, Venus had belted a ferocious, I mean truly
awesome, forehand down the line for a 40-15 lead, only to have
Martina counter with a delicately placed inside-out crosscourt
backhand that barely clipped the chalk.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis got to deuce and wound up breaking as Williams chased
another ``my God!'' forehand winner with a pair of ``good God!''
net errors before swatting a backhand several feet long.
</P>
<P>
   The die was cast. You sort of sensed Venus was already dead.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to give Seles decent odds, either, despite a history
of French Open triumphs in her first tennis-playing life. Monica's
game, post-stabbing, never has rounded out to the extent Hingis'
already has. Seles remains a two-fisted slam-bammer and therefore
vulnerable to receiving a lopsided lesson in court geometry from
the kid.
</P>
<P>
   The kid, that is, who isn't one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2252EDT &QL; 
