u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAKE-ASTRONAUT-HNS &LR;      06-02 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAKE-ASTRONAUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI GROUNDS FAKE ASTRONAUT WHO GAINED ACCESS TO SECURE NASA AREAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Texas, Ala., Fla.) 
 
By R.A. DYER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ By falsely claiming to be an astronaut, a 48-year-old
Texas man gained access to NASA's most secure area, federal
investigators said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Alan Whittredge, who was arrested Sunday morning in his
Galveston County, Texas, home, faces charges of impersonating a
federal employee and of lying to federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   According to an affidavit by NASA special agent Joseph Gutheinz,
Whittredge used false credentials to gain access to Mission Control
at Marshall Space Center in Alabama during a November shuttle
mission, was given training on a flight simulator and attempted to
gain access to a fighter jet in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Besides claiming to be an astronaut, Whittredge also told
investigators and personnel from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration that he was a Medal of Honor winner and a CIA
official, the affidavit states.
</P>
<P>
   The biographical claims are repeated on an official looking
Internet Web page, beneath the title ``National Aeronautics and
Space Administration/Lyndon B. Johnson Space Center,'' in which
Whittredge is identified as a NASA astronaut and CIA agent.
</P>
<P>
   Gutheinz stated that NASA personnel records establish the
suspect was never an astronaut, military records show he never
received the Medal of Honor and a CIA official said that Whittredge
was never an employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``When told it is a crime to lie to federal agents conducting a
criminal investigation and when presented information refuting his
story, Whittredge said that he understood the nature of the crime,
but that all his claims are true,'' Gutheinz wrote. ``He
subsequently repeated those assertions in his written statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Such claims led to a security breach in November at NASA's
facility in Huntsville, Ala., according to the affidavit by
Gutheinz. According to Gutheinz, who works for NASA's office of
Inspector General, Whittredge used his home computer to identify
himself as a CIA regent and astronaut on Nov. 7, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whittredge requested a tour of the facility based on the false
credentials,'' Gutheinz wrote. ``Whittredge claimed he would be
flying on a shuttle mission and was interested in payload
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, Whittredge was, on November 21-22, 1997, granted
a tour of Marshall Space Center and access to Mission Control. Mr.
Whittredge was permitted to sit at the console of NASA Mission
Control (NASA's most secure area) at Marshall Space Flight Center
during a shuttle mission.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 16, 1998, the affidavit continues, Whittredge gained
access to technical data on a space shuttle thrust propulsion
system that is not available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the affidavit states, Whittredge lied his way into a
meeting with senior pilots and the executive officer of the
Kingsville Naval Air Station in Texas. As a result, he was given
training on a T-45 Aircraft Flight Simulator, Gutheinz wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Also in May, Whittredge attempted to obtain permission to fly a
T-45 aircraft at the Naval Air Station in Pensacola, Fla. The
affidavit does not state whether he was successful or not.
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Moss, FBI special agent in Houston, could provide few
details on the case. ``We don't know what prompted him to do what
he's done _ it'll take a while to sort things out,'' Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, spokespersons for NASA released no details about the
case, referring inquiries to the U.S. Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Gutheinz's affidavit, released by that office, states that the
suspect has a plane, but no friends or job in the community. It
also states that he lives in a recreational vehicle, with a
permanent address in Florida, and has moved twice in the last eight
months, living in both League City and Galveston in southeast
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Web page that features the apparently fake biography of
Whittredge states that the suspect operated as an undercover agent
for the CIA for more than 20 years, including assignments in Japan,
Russia, Southeast Asia and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   It also states that Whittredge is a Top Gun trophy winner for
his flights for the Navy, and has flown UH-1 Huey helicopters in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   It states that he continued to work for the CIA but was assigned
to NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Under the heading ``NASA Experience,'' the Web page states:
``Jerry was selected as an astronaut by NASA in March 1998 and will
report to NASA when his contract is issued. He will then complete
his training as a pilot/commander.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutheinz, in the affidavit, stated that Whittredge stuck by his
story _ even when confronted with facts to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   James Oberg, a 22-year veteran of the Johnson Space Center and
now a private space consultant, said that there have been numerous
astronaut imposters in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been about a dozen over the last 30 years,'' Oberg
said. ``They usually show up in fake flight suits and give speeches
and sign autographs. They do it for wanting to indirectly bask in
that glory. Sometimes they use their own names, and sometimes these
people use the names of real astronauts.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors say that if convicted on the most serious
charge _ impersonating a federal officer _ Whittredge could receive
five years imprisonment and a $250,000 fine. He made an initial
federal court appearance Tuesday and will have a bond hearing
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2253EDT &QL; 
