A1239 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-TEX     06-02 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ NOT BUYING BULLS' `UNDERDOG' CLAIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The Utah Jazz appears to be the right team in
the right place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests, however, the Chicago Bulls are the wrong
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   While the rested, ready and rolling Jazz talked up its genuine
chance to dethrone a dynasty in the NBA Finals, Michael Jordan
added fuel to his perpetual fire by pronouncing his five-time
champions as underdogs entering tonight's crucial Game 1 at the
Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're underdogs, sure,'' Jordan said. ``Utah has its house in
order. They've got what we've had over the years while we're
battling a lot of differences like age and losing focus because
we've been here so many times. To me, it's an added incentive
because this role is unfamiliar for us. Winning this one would be a
lot more gratifying, because it's going to be the toughest to
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Added teammate Scottie Pippen: ``The pressure's not on us
because no one expects us to win. It's a different feeling for us
in that we've been sort of written off, but I like our position.''
</P>
<P>
   While the weary defending champs limp into the Finals after
surviving a seven-game series with the Indiana Pacers, the Jazz has
been patiently waiting 10 days since sweeping the Los Angeles
Lakers. Utah, which lost a close six-game series to the Bulls last
season, admits to having the talent, the game plan, the motivation
and the encouragement to beat Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, Jazz forward Karl Malone isn't buying into
Chicago's mind games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all keep saying they're vulnerable, but I'm not falling for
it,'' Malone said. ``Underdogs? Yeah, right. I heard Michael say he
may be tired, but he's still got heart. Coming from him, that's all
I needed to hear. They're still the champs until we beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   If not enthusiastically accepting the role of favorite, the Jazz
admits that this is the ideal situation for Utah to win the first
championship in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could I imagine a better scenario to win a title?'' Jazz guard
Jeff Hornacek said. ``No. Well, yes, only if Michael had retired
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   While logic, statistics, trends and momentum point to a Jazz
triumph, Jordan emerges as The Great Equalizer. Almost every Jazz
advantage can be countered, if not erased, with ``Yeah, but the
Bulls have Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid to say it,'' Utah's Shandon Anderson said. ``We
wanted the Bulls. Not only to win a championship, but to beat the
best team and the best player.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jordan _ considering retirement after the season _ is to lose
a Finals series, this seems to be the best chance. A look at Utah's
top five apparent edges over a Bulls team that appears more
desperate and ripe than at any time during their run through the
'90s:
</P>
<P>
   Rust over fatigue. One of those two excuses will be used after
tonight's Game 1. Only once has a team headed into the Finals after
a longer layoff than Utah's 10 days. The '82 Lakers defeated the
76ers, 4-2, after sitting for 12. The Bulls, meanwhile, admit to
being physically drained after outlasting the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully they'll be nice and tender for us,'' Malone said.
``I know Game 1 is the one they want. It's huge to the series. If
we can get it, our rest may kick in and so will their fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Mailman on the loose. With Brian Williams's speed and Jason
Caffey's bulk no longer in Chicago, the Bulls must try to guard
Malone with a combination of Dennis Rodman, Dickey Simpkins and
even Pippen. It was a disaster during the regular season, with
Malone averaging 33 points on 62 percent shooting after getting the
lighter Rodman in early foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to win this series with our big guys, so I'm putting
the pressure on them and myself,'' Malone said. ``I played like a
C-plus last year. This year I've got to bring my A game against
Dennis or whoever. I've seen it all, heard it all and done about
half of it myself. I respect Dennis, but I'm not amused or bothered
by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sucking air. The Jazz has three defenders _ Hornacek, Anderson
and Bryon Russell _ to run at Jordan. The Jazz, hoping Malone and
Jordan cancel each other out, plans on winning the series with its
deeper bench.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, however, is yet to have one of his trademark defining
games in these playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the ace in the hole,'' said Jordan, who will attack Utah's
smaller defenders with post-ups. ``I can't say I'm not tired
physically, but my mind and my heart are refreshed.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jazz coach Jerry Sloan: ``We've got to keep a body between
him and the basket and make him shoot the jumper. Even then, you've
only got a 50 percent chance he'll miss. The real trouble comes
when you start letting him drive and then fouling him.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeat offender. This will be the first time Chicago faced the
same opponent twice in the Finals. The Jazz shouldn't be
intimidated by the Bulls anymore, having beaten them twice in the
regular season, including a rally from 24 points down Feb. 5 at the
Delta Center. Last seasons, Utah lost three Finals games by two,
two and four points. And the past five Finals rematches have been
won by the team who lost the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   Home sweet home. The Bulls might be the best team ever on the
road in the Finals, but the Jazz is 43-6 at the Delta Center this
season and have won 10 of their past 11 playoff games. Chicago,
which failed to win in Indiana during the Eastern Conference
finals, will have to win at least once in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Home teams have won 206 of the 259 seven-game series since 1984.
Of the seven teams to sweep conference finals like the Jazz since
1977, six went on to win the title. And of the eight teams that
needed seven games to win the conference finals, only two won the
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an uphill battle and we know it,'' Jordan said. ``Some of
our swagger is probably gone, but nobody has taken anything away
from us yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
