u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT &LR;      06-02 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRATES TOP METS 5-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Brian Bohanon escaped a bases-loaded jam with a 3-0
count on the batter Tuesday night. Doing it twice was too much to
ask.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon, who had been nicked for the tying run on back-to-back
bloop hits with two outs in the fourth, struck out Turner Ward with
one out and the bases loaded in the fifth after falling behind 3-0
in the count.
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Young golfed a low and inside 3-0 pitch inside the
third-base bag into the left field corner for a three-run triple as
the Pittsburgh Pirates rallied for a 5-2 victory, their second in
as many nights over the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Not even John Olerud's first stolen base in over two years could
prevent the Mets (31-22) from losing their second straight game. It
was the first time the Mets had lost two straight games since May
14-15.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon _ the self-described ``short/middle/long reliever'' _
has been one of the team's most valuable pitchers. He entered the
game after a 58-minute rain delay with a 2-1 third-inning lead and
a 1.58 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates tied the game on Jose Guillen's two-out, inside-out
bloop double to right and Doug Strange's cracked-bat bloop single
to center. But Bohanon had no one to blame but himself for the
Pirates' winning rally.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran left-hander walked the pinch-hitter Jermaine
Allensworth with one out in the fifth. Tony Womack followed with a
single to left just inside the line. And then Bohanon hit Al Martin
with a 1-2 pitch to load up the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Up came Ward, the No. 3 hitter in the Pittsburgh lineup, who
quickly took three balls. Bohanon fought back with a called strike.
Ward fouled three consecutive pitches off, before taking a called
third strike on the outside corner, the pitch registering just 78
mph on the Three Rivers Stadium radar gun.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon needed another out to escape the jam, but he quickly
fell behind Young, 3-0, too. Young responded by drilling what
probably would have been ball four down the line and into the
corner. And Bohanon (2-2) was headed for his second defeat of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Bohanon was pitching for the second time in
three days was because of the rain delay. Before the game, a
torrential thunderstorm with ping-pong-ball sized hail had pelted
the artificial turf. But it subsided, and the Mets held a 2-1 lead
on the strength of a Mike Piazza first-inning run-scoring single
and a Butch Huskey second-inning home run when it began to rain
again in the top of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Once the storm passed, it had taken Mets starter Masato Yoshii
with it. Yoshii, who had allowed an unearned run in the first,
thanks to a two-base error in left by Bernard Gilkey, had thrown
only 24 pitches over the first two innings. But Manager Bobby
Valentine figured the almost hourlong wait was too much.
</P>
<P>
   So on came Bohanon, who either ran out of gas or out of luck
Tuesday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
