<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET WORKOUT IMPRESSES BAFFERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ A relieved Bob Baffert said he was pleased with
Real Quiet's final workout before Saturday's Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The California-based colt, who has been training at Churchill
Downs in Louisville, Ky., went 5 furlongs in 1:00 4/5 under
exercise rider Dana Barnes on Tuesday morning. Real Quiet is
scheduled to arrive at Belmont Park today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous this morning, but we're ready to party now,''
said Baffert, Real Quiet's trainer. ``He wanted to go too fast, so
(Barnes) had to take hold of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet's recent strong workouts suggest he has recovered
from his post-Preakness fatigue. He'll try Saturday to become the
first horse to sweep the Triple Crown race since Affirmed 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The number of confirmed opponents grew to nine Tuesday when
Hanuman Highway was upgraded from ``possible'' by Kathy Walsh, the
gelding's California-based trainer. Decisions haven't been
announced on two other ``possibles,'' Grand Slam and Limit Out.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer D. Wayne Lukas indicated that if Grand Slam runs, Jerry
Bailey might ride him, leaving stablemate Yarrow Brae to Mike
Smith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
