A1394 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--BULLS-HNS &LR;      06-02 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--BULLS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's drop curtain &QL; 
on spoiled dynasty
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ Like anything that is left to hang around too long
_ milk, cheese, old shoes _ even the greatest sports dynasties will
go bad.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where, after all these years, we are with the mighty
NBA franchise from Chicago, a sour, spoiled bunch that this spring
has begun to take on the odor of Limburger and last week's fish.
</P>
<P>
   The great Michael Jordan slips and falls and complains the refs
won't give him an obvious call in the closing seconds of Game 6 at
Indiana in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The almost-great Scottie Pippen whines about an official holding
a grudge for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The tattooed, dress-wearing freak show of Dennis Rodman cries
out to be noticed and then pouts that for some reason he is treated
differently than any other lunatic in the asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson, the Zen phony, rants and raves about
injustice and paints complex pictures of conspiracies hiding behind
every backboard and never gives his opponents credit.
</P>
<P>
   Never has a team more closely lived up to its nickname than the
Bulls, who in the waning days of their reign over our sports in the
'90s are dropping so many cow patties on their legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Is anybody else sick and tired of the Bulls and the bull?
</P>
<P>
   Not of Jordan and the magical way he can elevate his body and
his game at the most critical of times. But of Nike and Gatorade
and agent David Falk and all of the rest of the corporate carnival
sideshow that follows basketball's version of Elvis on and off the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Talented but troubled
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to admire the way the Bulls reach down into
their vast well of playoff experience to extricate themselves from
the tightest of situations. But it is something else to be forced
to follow along with the soap-opera travails of a dozen
rich-beyond-imagination young men and their manipulative,
condescending coach constantly whining about a lack of respect.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Cindy Crawford complaining about the mole on her cheek,
and you are on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   We are supposed to stay up nights fretting for Pippen, who
insisted on getting a long-term contract extension and now
considers himself grossly underpaid at $2.8 million per year and
might have to flee Chicago to find justice in a cold world.
</P>
<P>
   We are supposed to be sympathetic that Jordan _ who earns $33
million for a single season of playing basketball _ might be be
asked to play next year for a different coach. One who might not
simply sit on the bench clipping his fingernails while turning over
the de facto running of the team to His Airness.
</P>
<P>
   We are supposed to be outraged that the coach _ Jackson _ has
spent the past half-dozen years publicly and personally ridiculing
the general manager who hired him and now might be told to look
elsewhere for employment. Before the season, Jackson said wild
horses could not drag him back to the Bulls after this season. Now,
he sniffs and moans and does a weepy little tap dance to say he's
being reluctantly pushed out the door.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, what happens when we turn great athletes
into off-the-court idols who are bigger than Godzilla. Eventually,
the cold-blooded lizard will turn and bite you.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is a burden these days for the Bulls _ management,
the media, the referees, their opponents. It is tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls exude arrogance
</P>
<P>
   When the Bulls win a game, the worshipful Chicago media usually
genuflect in the direction of Jordan and call it divinely inspired.
When the other team wins _ as Indiana did three times in the last
series _ it is written off in satanic verses as some kind of
hellish conspiracy concocted by the NBA and NBC, who we are told
would inexplicably like to kill off their golden goose.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have come to believe they've been cast in the
permanent role of the good guys, preordained to always win. It is
an arrogance that emanates from Jackson, the luckiest man this side
of Ringo Starr, who by happenstance fell into greatness.
</P>
<P>
   They have bosses they don't love. How original. They have jobs
that force them to get up by the crack of noon. How terrible. They
have agents who make them get by on six figures a month. How
intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they must face the Utah Jazz in the NBA Finals for the
second straight year, and we'll listen to complaints about the
dearth of entertainment options from Rodman. Just call it Mormons
vs. moron.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone and John Stockton await. Never has all that Jazz
seemed such an appealing alternative to so much Bull.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
