<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-CAPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK DOMINATES, AND SABRES ARE ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Buffalo Sabres, sixth-place finishers in their
conference and 23 years removed from their only appearance in the
Stanley Cup finals, averted another elimination from the playoffs
Tuesday night and kept their championship hopes flickering.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres defeated the Washington Capitals, 2-1, at the MCI
Center in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference finals. By winning, the
Sabres cut the Capitals' lead to three games to two, forcing the
four-of-seven-game series back to Buffalo for a sixth game on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Woolley, a former draft pick of the Capitals, kept the
Sabres' season going with a brilliant unassisted goal that broke a
1-1 tie with 4 minutes 26 seconds to play in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Two more victories and the Sabres will have provided another
stunning notch to their season by reaching the final round for the
first time since the 1974-75 season, which is the season the
Capitals began play in the National Hockey League. Two more
victories, and Buffalo will be looking to add either the Dallas
Stars or the defending champion Detroit Red Wings to its list of
playoff victims this season.
</P>
<P>
   After both teams scored in first period Tuesday night, neither
team was able to score in the second period and for most of the
third. Dominik Hasek would not allow the Capitals to, and the
Sabres just couldn't. Until Woolley split the Capitals' defense,
skated in alone on Olaf Kolzig and put the puck between the
goalie's pads.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason the Sabres were even in a position to win the
game so late in the third period was the heroics of their
goaltender, Hasek, who made 34 saves in what was his best game of
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, who poked fun at himself at practice on Sunday, taping a
sign to his back that read ``Swiss cheese,'' was stellar Tuesday
night. After allowing two soft goals in Game 4, one from 70 feet
out, Hasek was spectacular in doing what he does best _ steal a
game with timely saves. His heroics in the second and third periods
kept a lifeless Sabres team in the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, with the score tied, 1-1, Hasek stopped the
Capitals sniper Peter Bondra on a clean breakaway for the second
time in the game. Then he stuffed Adam Oates' wraparound attempt,
the second time Hasek stuffed Oates from point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   When the momentum in this series shifted to Washington last
Saturday in Buffalo, so did the pressure to win _ for both teams.
The Sabres' Game 4 loss at home put them down by 3-1; it meant they
were no longer expected to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the onus fell on the Capitals. Now they had to close
the deal. But the Capitals had been in this position many times.
And yes, there was a large bone stuck in Washington's throat in
those past series.
</P>
<P>
   Five times they had taken a two-game lead in a playoff series.
Three of those times they led by three games to one but choked,
failing to win the series. Tuesday night's game was their first
chance, and maybe their best, to put away the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the ice was a team that had already
accomplished more than expected. After qualifying as the
sixth-seeded team in the Eastern Conference, the Sabres beat a very
talented Philadelphia Flyers team in the first round. They followed
that upset with a sweep of the Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams looked uneasy during the first few minutes Tuesday
night. Missed passes and misfired shots led to many blown
opportunities. The score was tied, 1-1, after 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres got the game's first break. Darryl Shannon scored on
a weak shot from the top of the left circle that somehow got behind
Kolzig. It gave the Sabres a 1-0 lead 6:33 into the game. Kolzig
never saw the puck as it went through a maze of sticks and skates
before sneaking through his pads.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Nikolishin's power-play goal at 16:29 tied the score at
1-1. Nikolishin intercepted an errant pass as he skated hard to the
net. With the puck on his stick, and no one between him and Hasek,
Nikolishin put the puck through on the short side. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
