<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-LONGBCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS SURVIVE AND ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Imagine if Dave Snow ever decided to market his
Dirtbag playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Why, there'd be teams all over the country with patches on their
knees, their ace pitcher going out for the biggest game of his life
with his finger glued
</P>
<P>
   together, and then knocking off some bigtime spit-and-polish
outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Long Beach State did on Tuesday, adding high and
mighty Miami to the growing list of giants to fall victim to the
49ers, who continue to dance merrily along in the College World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we are - Dirtbags,'' right fielder Chuck Lopez
said, proudly, just after delivering the key hit in the 49ers'
improbable three-run, ninth-inning rally that beat, Miami, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't know what Dirtbag baseball is all about by
now, they never will,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In just the past week and a half, at the West Regional at
Stanford and here at the CWS, the 49ers have eliminated Stanford,
Alabama, Florida State and Miami - every one one of them, at one
time or another this year, ranked among the top five college teams
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange sight indeed at the post-game press conference
- a quartet of high Miami draft picks, including the No. 1 player
taken Tuesday, Pat Burrell, trying to explain what went wrong, then
the 49ers showing up with, among others, Mike Hota, who had more
hits Tuesday (three) than he did his first two years
</P>
<P>
   at Long Beach State (two).
</P>
<P>
   How long can the 49ers (43-22-1) keep it going?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to keep it together one more day,'' said Snow, the
49ers' coach, ``and the day after that ... ''
</P>
<P>
   The next test will come this evening: Arizona State, one of two
undefeated teams remaining in the CWS (Louisiana State is the
other). The 49ers have to beat ASU twice, tonight and Friday, for a
crack at Saturday's championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Impossible?
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to thrive on beating better teams,'' Lopez said,
anxious for the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   It was another staggering season-ender for Miami relief ace
Robbie Morrison, the victim of the 49ers' flurry of ... well, stuff
</P>
<P>
   , in the ninth inning. It was nowhere near as dramatic as when
he was tagged for a two-run, two-out homer in the bottom of the
ninth by LSU's Warren Morris that cost Miami the CWS crown, but,
from the sound of it, no less painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Morrison said of the '96 Series, ``was a big moment in
my life ... and my goal, all of our goals, was to win the national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Morrison who blew away the 49ers in the ninth inning of
Game 2, striking out three of the four batters he faced. And it was
Morrison again on Tuesday, who entered the game in the eighth and
promptly erased a 49er threat with a pickoff and a strikeout, then
started the ninth with the score tied, 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Hall, who earlier in the game slugged his seventh homer -
but also committed two errors - started the ninth with a single.
Then, Sam Monroy, a pinch hitter, and one of the 49ers' better
bunters, first showed bunt, then pulled back and slapped a bounder
toward second. The second baseman, Manny Crespo, fielded the ball,
but shortstop Bobby Hill was on the right field side of second
base, and Hall slid under his tag. Two on, nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Terrmel Sledge bunted to first baseman Rick Saggese, who,
unwisely, tried to force Hall at third. His throw wasn't close.
Bases loaded, nobody out, and Lopez the batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get some pitch that was up,'' Lopez said
later. ``I was trying to hit a fastball, that didn't work, so I hit
a good curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   A 0-2 curve, bouncing it over the Hurricanes' drawn-in infield,
scoring two runs and sending Sledge to third. Sledge then scored on
a wild pitch for a 6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did the little things, we didn't,'' said Miami coach Jim
Morris. ``The little things got us . . . the hit-and-run, putting
guys in motion, their defense on the bunt plays . . . they got it
done when it counted.''
</P>
<P>
   Just not right away. The 49ers, despite 11 hits over the first
six innings, managed just two runs while stranding seven runners,
four of them in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``One inning I thought our offense was pressing a little,'' said
left-hander Mike Gallo, the 49ers' starter, ``so I was going around
the dugout trying to pump up everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo needed some pumping himself; the index finger on his
pitching hand had two painful blisters. The 49ers put in a call to
Bill Buhler, the former longtime Dodger trainer, who prescribed . .
. super glue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called Nu Skin but, I swear, it smells like super glue,''
said Gallo, who had a new layer applied each inning and said it
didn't bother him at all on the mound. Gallo worked six innings,
striking out eight, and making just one slip: the 2-2 pitch he
threw to Aubrey Huff in the second inning he hit for a two-run
homer to tie the score. Dennis Kordich, the third 49er pitcher, got
the win, and Jason Marr pitched the ninth for his ninth save and
second in the CWS.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes broke the tie with a run in the fifth, then the
49ers got even again in the sixth, and in typical Dirtbag style.
Hota led off with an infield single. Scott Redfox, whose three-run
homer beat Florida State earlier, bunted Hota to second. Then Jason
Yount, who little by little is emerging from his late-season slump
- he's 4-for-9 in the CWS - singled Hota home.
</P>
<P>
   Said Miami's Morris: ``They made all the plays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
