u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAFT-AMATEUR-COX     06-02 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAFT-AMATEUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four Georgians go in first round
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Corey Patterson's youthful devotion to the hometown
Braves ended Tuesday when the suburban Atlanta's Harrison High
School baseball star was drafted by the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, the third player selected in the amateur draft,
became the highest Atlanta-area draft pick since 1970, and was one
of four Georgians selected in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder J.D. Drew of Hahira, Ga., who would not sign with the
Phillies after being selected No. 2 last year, was chosen fifth by
St. Louis. Shortstop Adam Everett, another Harrison High product
who played college ball at South Carolina, was taken by Boston with
the 12th pick. And outfielder Rick Elder of suburban Sprayberry
High was taken 26th by Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the big reasons for the upgrade in talent in
this state is the coaches have gotten much better, and that
reflects on the players,'' said Paul Snyder, the Braves' director
of scouting and player development.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Philadelphia selected University of Miami third
baseman Pat Burrell with the top pick, and Michigan State pitcher
Mark Mulder was selected second by Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, without a first-round choice, took right-hander Matt
Belisle of Austin, Texas (McCallum High), with their first pick,
52nd overall.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson hit .560 for the Class AAAA state champion Hoyas with
22 home runs, 61 RBIs and 36 stolen bases. The last area high
school player to be selected that high was Decatur's Mike Ivie, who
was picked No. 1 by the Padres in 1970. In 1967, Ron Blomberg of
Druid Hills was taken No. 1 by the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson knows he's stepping into a pressure-cooker.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family and I have talked about (the pressure), and the only
thing I can do is go out and experience everything and act like a
professional,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, who had signed a letter of intent to play at Georgia
Tech, is expected to get a signing bonus of about $2 million. He
got the call from Cubs general manager Ed Lynch just after 1 p.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been waiting to play professional baseball since I was
a little kid,'' Patterson said. ``I'm just glad the Cubs showed
interest. Now I have to go out and help them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies are expected to convert Burrell into a first
baseman, because they already have last year's rookie of the year,
Scott Rolen, at third. ``I've had experience with that position
before,'' Burrell said, ``and it's something I'm comfortable
with.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis may have taken a chance on Drew. He turned down a
potential $6 million deal _ $3 million was guaranteed _ from the
Phillies last year. Drew wants a signing bonus of $10 million. The
Cardinals may be willing to give Drew more than the Phillies
offered, but it's unlikely they'd agree to his current demands.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Burroughs, son of former Braves player Jeff Burroughs, was
taken ninth by San Diego. Burroughs, from Long Beach (Calif.) High,
is a power-hitting third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
