<SLUG> BC-NHS-GRIEVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student drops grievance against school after NHS entry denied
 &HT;    By Margo Rutledge Kissell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Amanda Lemon has decided against pursuing a
formal grievance with Xenia High School about its decision to
exclude her from National Honor Society because she has a baby.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 18-year-old said Tuesday she still plans to fill
out forms she received from the Office of Civil Rights for the U.S.
Department of Education in Cleveland to see whether discrimination
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon said she hopes that may help future students. But as for
herself, she said she is ready to move on with her life.
</P>
<P>
   She'll participate in Xenia High School's commencement at
University of Dayton Arena tonight and plans to attend Sinclair
Community College in the fall with the goal of becoming an
occupational therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I made my point. I got so much support, it was
amazing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon, who had a 3.8 grade point average, was accepted into the
National Honor Society earlier this spring but was later told the
five-member faculty council reversed its decision after learning
she has a 11-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon, who spent her days at the Greene County Career Center,
initially wrote a letter filing a grievance with the principal
because she believes the faculty council's decision violated a
federal law (Title IX of Educational Amendments of 1972), which
prohibits schools from keeping pregnant or parenting students from
membership in organizations like the National Honor
</P>
<P>
   Society.
</P>
<P>
   The principal upheld the faculty council's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Superintendent Judy Hennessey said Lemon hasn't filed
the grievance form. ``We haven't heard anything from her,''
Hennessey said.
</P>
<P>
   Margo Rutledge Kissell writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
