<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-ARENA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES TO BUILD ARENA?  
 NEW FACILITY POSSI BLE IF AWA STAYS AS IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes are pursuing the possibility of building
an arena in the Valley if efforts to renovate America West Arena
fail, according to team president Shawn Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter emphasized the team's first option is to stay at America
West Arena, where it ju st completed the second year of a five-year
lease. The Coyotes, the city of Phoenix and arena management are
considering a plan to renovate the facility to eliminate the 4,300
obstructed view seats for hockey.
</P>
<P>
   That plan could cost around $20
</P>
<P>
   million and possibly shut down the arena for at least a portion
of two summers. The exact cost of the plan, and who would pay for
it, have not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Coyotes ``are not putting their eggs in one
basket,'' said Hunter , who declined to reveal specifics of the
Coyotes' pursuit of a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to do is find a situation that allows us to be
successful in the long term,'' Hunter said. ``We continue to
explore all of our options, some of which are exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving out of Arizona is not one of those options, Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our options are in the Valley of the Sun,'' he said.
``I think the fans have proven that this is going to be one of the
premier markets in the lea gue.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Richard Burke said last fall that if the team did decide
to build an arena, it would be done with little or no burden to
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be very creative,'' Hunter said. ``I'm not saying
we would eliminate this a s an option, but we would prefer not to
go to the public and say, `Vote on building us an arena.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But arenas today cannot be built 100 percent on private
dollars. The key is, how can you get to a model that is good for a
city and good for a team?''
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, the Coyotes are expected to announce they will
not raise ticket prices for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Although the average ticket price in the NHL increased 6 percent
last year, it's not ``terribly unusual'' for a team to hold the
line on prices for a year, said Sean Brenner, editor of ``Team
Marketing'' Report''.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of teams budget ticket prices in two- or three-year
increments,'' he said. A team that doesn't raise prices one year
might hike them s ubstantially in following years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ticket price announcement, Hunter and Burke
are expected to discuss arena issues at an open house later this
week at their Scottsdale facility, the Cellular One Ice Den.
</P>
<P>
   They
</P>
<P>
   maintain the Coyotes cannot be financially successful if they
stay in America West Arena under present conditions. The obstructed
view seats and a lease that limits their revenue from advertising
and sponsorships are issues that need to be addresse d, Hunter
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes would like to have a renovation plan in place before
next summer, when construction would have to start. If the plan
falls through, the team probably would increase its efforts to
build its own facility.
</P>
<P>
   T here are inherent problems with that, however. Burke has
expressed reluctance to enter the arena business. Financing such a
structure is always complicated, and it's questionable if the
Valley could support another arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are no longer considering becoming a part of the
Cardinals plans to build a new complex in the East Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The city wants to keep the Coyotes at America West Arena,
provided it makes economic sense, said Dave Krietor, the city's
director of communi ty and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coyotes bring about 700,000 people into downtown Phoenix
each year and are a significant generator of both people and
excitement,'' Krietor said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
