<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL RODMAN'S ACT HURT BULLS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salt Lake City - He has a glimmering chance to show his worth ,
rescue his teammates, prove he isn't just a self-obsessed moron
fading into pop culture oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   And Dennis Rodman is going to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't relax in Utah,'` Rodman said. ``It's not my scene
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Idiot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK, it's OK,'` Bulls Coach Phil Jackson said. ``If it
helps him get to bed and to sleep at night, then fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. Everyone goes to Vegas to catch up on his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Just once, it would be nice to see Rodman pour all his focus
into basketball , recognize the ``scene'' he abhors happens to be
the quest for an NBA championship. But more than anything, it would
be nice if Jackson dropped the peace pipe and put down his foot.
Just once.
</P>
<P>
   So it is somewhat ominous that the Bulls need Rodma n more than
ever. They are porous in the post and need someone to stop Karl
Malone. They are a tired bunch that needs an infusion of energy,
which happens to be a Rodman specialty. At least it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very exhausting,'' Rodman sa id. ``We're not 25,
26-year-old antelopes anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   So it makes perfect sense to fly to Vegas after Game 1. Or
during the off-day. Or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just for a couple of hours,'' Rodman said.
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   Last year during the Finals, Rod man was allowed to leave his
teammates and bolt to Las Vegas. It was a move that infuriated both
Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen, and why not?
</P>
<P>
   After all, when Rodman wasn't calling the natives a bunch of
bleeping Mormons and throwing colored
</P>
<P>
   chips around a casino, he was getting absolutely flattened by
Malone. And if it wasn't for Jordan crawling out of a sickbed to
steal Game 5, it's likely the Jazz would be the defending champions
in this series.
</P>
<P>
   So what'll make this any differ ent?
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this year is going to be a little less talk, a lot
more action,'' Rodman said. ``It's very difficult to play Karl
Malone. The slightest touch, and they call the foul. But this year,
I'll be more aggressive, more useful. Karl Mal one is no different
than anyone else. He just has less hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Rodman has not been paying attention to Rogaine. As
for his plan to stop the semi-trailer in shorts?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, brother,'' Rodman said. ``I'm going to have to t
ell his wife to go somewhere else and let me sleep with him for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Malone will hear Rodman's comments, and he will shrug
them off. If there's one person immune to Rodman's antics, it's
Malone. He remembers Rodman long before the hair dye and nose
rings, before he became the most celebrated Madonna wannabe in
history.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Malone knew Rodman when he was a lanky, introverted kid
only a few years removed from his job as an airport janitor.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Jazz d on't need any added incentive to end
Chicago's reign. Their coach, Jerry Sloan, is a hard-nosed leader
who recently cleansed himself of any loyalty to the Bulls. They are
2-0 against Chicago this season, and have won 10 of 11 games. They
will not su ffer from stage fright; they are the first opponent to
get a second crack at Chicago in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Logic will tell you that the Jazz will win the series. Except
nothing logical has ever applied to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   For all the analysis over U tah's prolonged layoff, this much is
true: Whether it helps or not, the Jazz are under tremendous
pressure to win the first two games at the Delta Center. Because of
the rest. Because they are facing the least potent Bulls' team to
grace the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no Brian Williams, no Jason Caffey, no time for
the champions to catch their breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need to do is win Game 1 or Game 2 here,'' Rodman said.
``And the series is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, Rodman will have much to do with the outcome. He
might surprise us. Or he might leave his game at the craps table,
fiddling like a fool while Rome is burning. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
