<SLUG> BC-BBC-ASU-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU'S MILLS DRAFTED IN FIRST ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ It was an odd place to learn about the rest of
</P>
<P>
   your life, on a practice field in the heart of Nebraska with
cars and freight trains rattling nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But tuning out distractions has been Ryan Mills' forte, and the
Arizona State pitcher seemed at peace Tuesday after learning he was
sele cted sixth overall by the Minnesota Twins in Major League
Baseball's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad it's over,'' Mills said. ``It's an exciting time
for me, but it's also a little weird because I didn't expect to be
in a College World Series when I found out. My mind's been on other
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now I know where I'm going. I'm a Minnesota Twin, and I'm
ready to roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills is the highest Sun Devil to be drafted since Antone
Williamson went with the fourth pick to the Milwaukee
</P>
<P>
   Brewers in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Five other ASU players were selected Tuesday. Pitcher Phill
Lowery was taken by the Florida Marlins in the sixth round. The
remaining four went to National League West teams: infielder Andrew
Beinbrink, Colorado Rockies (10th
</P>
<P>
   round); infielder Dan Meier, Diamondbacks (14th); pitcher Aaron
Kramer, San Diego Padres (18th); and infielder Richy Leon, Rockies
(23rd).
</P>
<P>
   Mills is close to agreeing to a contract that includes a $2
million signing bonus. The left-hander turn ed down $575,000 from
the New York Yankees in high school, a decision many criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will show the nature of things is rapid-fire or slow
as molasses,'' said Jeff Moorad, Mills' adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been afraid to step up a nd set a market. Our
preference is for a quick process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins' top pick last season (No. 9 overall), Michael
Cuddyer, signed a $1.85 million deal. The No. 6 pick overall last
year, Geoff Goetz, received $1.75 million from the New York M ets.
</P>
<P>
   Mills feels confident a deal will be reached soon.
</P>
<P>
   He was not surprised by the news. He had been on the phone
Monday night with Moorad, who suggested this was the scenario that
was likely to unfold, despite an indication by the Chicag o Cubs
that they might select him with the third pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the deal is pretty close to being done,'' Mills said.
``This whole thing just hasn't sunk in yet. I probably don't
realize what it means because there are so many other things I' m
thinking about right now. I'm excited and just glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins have had odd relationships with their top draft picks.
They lost Travis Lee to the Diamondbacks after Moorad, also Lee's
agent, took advantage of a loophole that allo wed Lee to become a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Mills will start with the Twins in Class A ball, with either
their upper-level club in Fort Myers, Fla., or their lower-division
A team in Fort Wayne, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Mills learned the news Tuesday during practice for today's
College World Series game against Long Beach State.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately called his parents and was later approached by
many of his teammates, who offered their congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's well-deserved,'' outfielder Mikel Moreno sai d.
``He's been through a lot. He's a great pick and will be an impact
player pretty soon. He's worthy of that high pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery knew little about the Marlins but enough to be pleased
with the selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're world champions ,'' he said. ``I'm really
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Meier watched two of his teammates get selected by Colorado, his
home state, while he will stay close to his new home since the
Diamondbacks picked him in the 14th round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little surprised,'' he sa id. ``I was told by three or
four scouts that I'd go between 10 and 15, but until you hear it. .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Pat Murphy was pleased how the day went for his
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very satisfying for any coach,'' he said. ``You love to
see th e players get a great opportunity after coming to college. I
think this program, because of the schedule it plays and how it's
upheld its expectations, that's helped the players along.''
</P>
<P>
   More ASU players, including Moreno, Greg Halvorson and Jer emy
Jones, likely will be selected as the draft continues today and
Thursday.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
