r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-DRAFT-CASSTEVENS-     06-02 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-DRAFT-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT STEALS SPOTLIGHT FROM SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Omaha, Neb. - This is what Major League Baseball should have
done: Hold the amateur draft next Tuesday. Invite the top players
and their parents. Televise the first round live, with Bud Selig at
the podium introducing each pick, one by one.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the sixth pick, the Minnesota Twins select
</P>
<P>
   left-handed pitcher Ryan Mills, from Arizona State . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Mills ascends the stage, like a graduating senior. He puts on a
Twins cap. Flashes his youthful smile. Baseball promotes the fresh
faces of the future to millions of TV viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how baseball does it.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:45 p.m. Tuesday, a reporter told Pat Murphy the news. The
ASU coach, seated in the dugout, asked, ``Who should we have tell
Mills?''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy turned to the kid seated next to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go tell him, Chip.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Gosewisch, an ASU player on the injured list, knows Mills
well. They were teammates at Horizon High School.
</P>
<P>
   Gosewisch left the dugout and began the long walk around the
University of Nebraska-Omaha ballpark , where he found his friend
sitting alone in a patch of shade in right field, his back against
the chain-link fence.
</P>
<P>
   The two spoke, shook hands.
</P>
<P>
   Mills found a pay phone and called his parents. &QL; 
At least it's over &QL; 
Moments later, the Sun Devils ace was looking into TV cameras,
fielding questions. How about the Twins? How much is your bonus?
How soon will you sign? Who is your agent?
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Mills doesn't have an agent. He has an adviser,
which is what an agent is ca lled until Ryan completes his college
eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   All this happened as ASU was practicing for today's College
World Series game. If the Sun Devils beat Long Beach State, they
will play for the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved it's over,'' Ryan
</P>
<P>
   said of the draft watch.
</P>
<P>
   But how about his teammates? The draft may influence some of
their lives, too. ``Half our team is affected by it,'' Murphy said.
Players who were passed over in the first round had to wait and
wonder. Would their na mes be called? The full list of drafted
players won't be released until next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have the draft during the College World Series,''
Murphy said. He knows, of course, that Major League Baseball can _
and will _ do whatever it wan ts.
</P>
<P>
   Why hold the draft during college baseball's showcase event?
It's not fair to the participating players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The draft can disrupt teams and affect players negatively.
Disappointed over being overlooked or chosen later than
</P>
<P>
   projected, some kids brood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't affect my pitching,'' Mills assured all. Hopefully
not. But you wonder how any bonus baby even can see home plate with
dollar signs in his eyes?
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to start managing his after-life toda y,'' ASU Athletic
Director Kevin White said of first-round picks. ``I think the draft
is very disruptive. (ASU's) players already are dealing with pretty
substantial challenges. They don't need more to think about this
week.'' &QL; 
Dealing with it &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being 20 years old and learning you just became a
multimillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Heady stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like learning that your interview for an entry-level
job with Allstate was successful,'' White said. No offense to
Allstate.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours before Miami was ousted from the Series, Hurricanes
All-American Pat Burrell learned the Phillies had selected him with
the top pick. The news was expected. Burrell said he would stay
focused on the Series. Still, how does a kid wipe the g rin off his
face?
</P>
<P>
   ``My only consolation,'' Murphy said, with Burrell in mind, ``is
that every other (World Series) team has to deal with it too.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, Major League Baseball has waited five years and nine
months and still hasn' t named a commissioner. Yet it won't
postpone the draft for a week?
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-98 2344EDT &QL; 
