<HEADLINE>
OREGON WELCOMES NEWMAN TO BASKETBALL STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Don Newman believes he proved beyond any d oubt last
season he deserves to be a head coach, and that one day he again
will be a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   But for the time being, Newman is an assistant coach, at Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, who as Bill Frieder's interim replacement last season
led Ariz ona State to an 18-14 record that surpassed most
expectations, was officially named an assistant to Ducks Coach
Ernie Kent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After unsuccessfully pursuing some head coaching vacancies,
Newman decided this would be his best opportunit y. He would have
been allowed to remain at ASU another year, but with new Coach Rob
Evans and his staff firmly in place, that wasn't appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was very important to stay in the loop,'' Newman
said. ``And staying in the Pac-10 wa s very important to me. If I
had to leave, this will be very good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best part for Newman is he can resume his search for
a head coaching job as early as next season. Kent said he wouldn't
stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If th at were to happen, I'll do everything I can to help him
get that job, and wish him the best,'' Kent said. ``He's smart
enough to know what to look for in his career. If the opportunity
comes for him, if he feels it's the right job, the University of
Oregon will still have been a lot better off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent, himself a rookie coach in the Pac-10 last year, said he
first thought about hiring Newman when he replaced Jerry Green at
Oregon after the 1996-97 season. But by that time, Newman, forme
rly the head coach at Cal State-Sacramento, had been hired by
Frieder.
</P>
<P>
   When Oregon assistant Jay John recently left to take a similar
job at Arizona, Kent called again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don's an outstanding guy,'' said Kent, whose team went 13-14
and
</P>
<P>
   tied ASU for fifth place with an 8-10 record. ``I talked to some
outstanding people who inquired about the job, but Don fits in so
well. He has a passion for the game and a passion for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent said he knows how ASU's players rallie d around Newman,
describing Newman as ``somebody that kids can trust and believe in
and count on.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as having a former head coach next to him on the bench,
Kent said, ``I don't fear hiring good people.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman, whose family i s moving for the second time in two
years, will tie up loose ends in the Valley and report to his new
job within a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just from going there, I can tell everybody's excited about
their Ducks,'' he said. ``They're the only game
</P>
<P>
   in town, and they want to be good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
