A1413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-02 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jazz favored; let gamesmanship begin
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ With the inferiority complex the Chicago Bulls are
hauling around, you almost wonder if they stand a chance against
the Utah Jazz in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is expecting us to win,'' the Bulls' Scottie Pippen
said Tuesday. ``Everybody is expecting the Jazz to walk away with
this series. It's a great feeling, being the underdog. You want to
go out there and prove everybody wrong. The pressure is not on
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Since when did George Costanza, the Seinfeld character with the
defeatist attitude, sign a 10-day with the Bulls?
</P>
<P>
   This small and insignificant feeling isn't what we've come to
expect from the two-time defending NBA champions, the formerly
untoucha-Bull dynasty that is 5-for-5 in the NBA Finals this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, the Bulls have gone from the 800-pound gorilla
to road kill in the short span of one shaky playoff series. Even
Michael Jordan, the confident one, believes it is fair and just to
declare the Bulls long shots to win the NBA Finals that begin
tonight at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just went seven games, and they're rested,'' Jordan said.
``They have the home-court advantage. What we've had over the
years, when we won our championships, people look at that as an
opportunity to succeed. So I consider us an underdog (because Utah
now enjoys those advantages).''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the gamesmanship started before the games in the
Finals. The Bulls had been in Utah only an hour when Jordan, Pippen
and friends started talking about how the Jazz has the advantages
entering the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago had to go seven difficult games to beat Indiana in the
Eastern Conference finals. Utah swept the Los Angeles Lakers in
four games in the West. Chicago has had only one practice to get
ready for the Jazz. Utah has waited on its next opponent since May
24. Karl Malone, John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek are rested. Jordan
and Pippen are not.
</P>
<P>
   Boil it down, and what do you get? One skeptical Utah team.
Malone laughed at the notion the Jazz is the clear favorite to win
this series.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls? Underdogs? Not as long as the greatest player in the
universe tugs on those baggy britches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't buy any of that, absolutely none of it,'' Malone
said. ``I did watch some of the game when they played Indiana in
the seventh game, and I saw an interview with Jud Buechler who said
they're the underdog. Yeah, right. I don't buy any of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael summed it up. After everybody said what they said, he
said, `But we have heart.' And coming from him, that's all I needed
to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan admitted Tuesday that the Bulls aren't coming into the
Finals with their hats in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also consider us champions to be beaten,'' he said. ``So
they have to take it away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Jazz is confident this rematch of last season's Finals
is the perfect time when the Bulls can be had.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put their sneakers on like us,'' Malone said. ``We're
athletes, and they are, too. You think I'm just back in the Finals
just to be here? I'm back to win a championship. It's going to be
tough. But I'm looking forward to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game is important. We understand how important it
is. That's the game they want. Of course, they want both of them.
But I think they realize that the first game is important. And I
think if we can take care of business in the first game, I think
our rest will kick in the longer the series goes.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Malone added, the Jazz won't be short on motivation as it
seeks the first NBA title in franchise history while the Bulls try
to make it six rings in eight seasons. Only the two Rockets
championships during Jordan's try at baseball interrupted the
Bulls' run of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``In life, sometimes you never have an opportunity to try to
correct something,'' Malone said. ``Sometimes, these opportunities
never come back. Or it's two or three or four years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have an opportunity the next year to try to correct
something that you didn't finish last time, I'm glad. In sports or
life, it's not supposed to work out that way. And I'm looking
forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Utah is cocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I happy to have the Bulls? I don't know if anybody would
be happy having to play the Bulls,'' Stockton said. ``On the other
hand, they are the best team in basketball, and that certainly
presents a challenge that, hopefully, everybody will rise up for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to have the opportunity to play here again in this
situation. It was a great situation last year for this franchise to
get there for the first time. I'm equally excited this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the world champs, and they didn't get there by having
stuff given to them. You can downplay how they're playing all you
want, but they're the world champs and they fought through a tough
series (against Indiana). I think people thought they were down and
out there. And they just find a way to win. That's what makes them
great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz players believe they have one key advantage going into
the series, and it is neither the home court nor the extra rest.
It's the experience gained by going against Chicago last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came off a big series against Houston last year and stepped
right into a pretty unique situation for all of us,'' Stockton
said. ``And this year, it's probably the opposite end of the
spectrum. We've had a lot of time to stop, think about it and get
ready for it. Whether we gain anything from last year's deal, I
can't say.''
</P>
<P>
   But coach Jerry Sloan can.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more experiences you get, good or bad, they are going to
make you better,'' Sloan said. ``If you're willing to try to become
better, those experiences will help anybody. It helps everybody to
have a little better idea of what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls have something working in their favor. Even though
they lost twice to the Jazz in the regular season, the Bulls are
battle-hardened. Even though they lost all three road games in the
Indiana series, they are road-tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is predicting that the Jazz will win because they
have the rest and the home-court advantage,'' Jordan said. ``But we
feel like we're going to come in here and win some games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prove we can win on the road against a team that
had the best record in the league. Their hunger may be stronger
than ours. There's a lot of things that might make people say,
`Well, maybe this is Utah's year.' But we look at the pressure as
not really being on us. But I like our chances either way.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as Pippen said, the desire to prove the Bulls again can
beat the odds is something that stokes their desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very good about this team,'' he said. ``Even though
they beat us in the season series, we feel like right now, it's our
time to go out and prove that we can win a series without having
the home-court advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that passion to disprove doubters that keeps anybody from
believing the Bulls rate as true underdogs in this series. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
