<SLUG> BC-FBO-RATTLERS-OBIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATTLERS CRUSHED BY DEATH OF EX-PLAYER VAUGHN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Milton Vaughn, who battled heart d isease for two
years while hoping to return to the Rattlers, died Monday in his
Phoenix home.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death has not been determined. An autopsy is
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, 27, was discovered in the evening by his roommate and
former t eammate, Richard Ashe.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive catalyst of the Rattlers' 1994 championship
season, Vaughn left the team's annual charity golf tournament in
Ahwatukee on Monday morning, complaining of nausea after playing
four or five holes, Coach Danny
</P>
<P>
   White said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, after his second Rattlers season, Vaughn was
diagnosed with cardio myopathy, which causes swelling of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Vaughn was on a heart transplant list at the
University of Arizona's Medical Cen ter, said Gene Nudo, Rattlers
vice president of administration.
</P>
<P>
   White said Vaughn, who played for Arizona State in 1993, chose
an alternative method of treatment and seemed to be doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, he had lost 70 to 80 pound s,'' White said.
``But he gained it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was a receiver and defensive back whose interception
helped beat Albany in the Arena Football League semifinals in '94.
In two seasons, he had 117 tackles and six interceptions, which
rank s second on the team's all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who worked as a season ticket account executive for
Phoenix Arena Sports, never gave up hope of playing again. He
recently received clearance to begin light workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn attended every Rattlers home game and most of the
practices, remaining close to the players and coaches. A younger
brother, Brian, a Scottsdale Community College student, videotapes
the practices for the Rattlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really tough for me,'' quarterbac k Sherdrick Bonner
said. ``He was the first person I was really close with on the
team. I'm just stunned right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's practice was canceled, but the players met to console
one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew Milt was ill, but everyt hing was encouraging that
he was getting better,'' Nudo said. ``I saw him (Monday) at the
golf tournament. That morning, I've got my arm around the guy. That
evening, he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find a better person than Milton Vaughn. He was a
lways there to help a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Nudo said the team will honor Vaughn by wearing his number (7)
on their jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is a precious treasure, and today is a great tragedy,''
Rattlers receiver/linebacker Hunkie Cooper said. ``Milton will
always be missed dearly physically, but spiritually, he will be
with us every day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
