<HEADER>
A1416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MARTINEZ-COX     06-02 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MARTINEZ-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Martinez like clockwork in win No. 243
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Stinson
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE, Wisc. _ Twenty-three years, 3,955 innings and one
interrupted retirement into the chase, Dennis Martinez finally
caught up to Juan Marichal late Tuesday night. On Turn Back The
Clock Night at County Stadium, El Presidente was never more a part
of the present.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves pole-axed Milwaukee 9-0 behind Andres Galarraga (a
pair of homers and five RBI) and Andruw Jones (a pair of triples
and a homer) but the night really belonged to Martinez, who won his
second game as a Brave but his 243 as a major leaguer, tying the
sky-kicking Marichal for most victories by a Latin American
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   How do you throw a curve with your fingers crossed?
</P>
<P>
   Having endured two winning chances last month which were torched
late by the bullpen, Martinez left little to chance in this one,
working nine innings while allowing 10 singles, a double, striking
out three and walking one. Every play he needed, he received, from
three double plays to Dave Nilsson retiring the side early on with
a liner directly into Jeromy Burnitz's leg as he tried to advance
to second.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga became the first Brave to reach 20 homers with
a two-run, 435-foot blast to center field in the fifth, giving
Atlanta a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The homer was his second in three games, his fifth in 12 games
and all but guaranteed it would take more that 24 to lead the club
by season's end, as Ryan Klesko did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who opened the night with four career triples _ two this
season _ hit his second triple of the night in the third, sending
Marquis Grissom vainly into the center field wall for a ball that
missed going out by three feet. That gave the Braves and Martinez a
second chance to complete a play they flubbed in the second inning,
when Martinez missed a sign and swung through a squeeze play with
Jones half-way down the line.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez fouled that pitch. In the fourth, he was perfect,
laying down a bunt to the right side to bring in Jones for a 3-0
lead. That run gave the Braves pitching staff 11 RBIs and 15
sacrifices this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves broke out to a 2-0 lead in the second on an extremely
rare play _ a Grissom misplay.
</P>
<P>
   After Javy Lopez and Michael Tucker strung together consecutive
singles, Andruw Jones sent a hard liner into center field that
initially brought Grissom in a couple steps.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The ball was hit deep enough to reach the warning track
and Grissom never made it back in time, jumping fruitlessly as the
ball sailed over his head to the wall. As County Stadium broke into
a round of boos, both Lopez and Tucker scored and Jones ran until
he reached third base. The error was Grissom's second of the season
and only added to his early season frustration. He has missed 19
starts this year, most recently limited by a strained buttock.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
