r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DRAFT-DBACKS-AZR &LR;      06-02 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DRAFT-DBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS USE 1ST PICK ON UA FOOTBALL RECRUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Diamondbacks have cultivated a sincere
</P>
<P>
   and positive relationship with their neighbors to the south in
Tucson, establishing spring training headquarters and a Triple-A
affiliate there.
</P>
<P>
   But their latest move might not play so well in some parts of
the Old Pueblo.
</P>
<P>
   With thei r first pick in Major League Baseball's amateur draft
on Tuesday, No. 103 overall, the Diamondbacks took Darryl Conyer,
an 18-year-old outfielder from Mission Bay High School in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous athlete,'' scouting director Don M itchell
said. ``An outstanding runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell was referring to Conyer's ability on the basepaths and
roaming center field. But Conyer runs well on the football field,
too. So well, in fact, that he signed a letter of intent to attend
the
</P>
<P>
   University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he believes the 5-foot-10, 195-pound Conyer will
pick the Diamondbacks over the Wildcats and not attempt to play
both sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to him, and he expressed a 100 percent interest in
base ball,'' Mitchell said. ``He knows if he devotes all his time
to baseball, he's going to be a very good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Rich Tomey, the son of Arizona football Coach
Dick Tomey, works for the Diamondbacks in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Conyer, wh o was not available for comment, was picked in the
third round, where the going rate is a signing bonus in the
$200,000-$300,000 range. Plus, the Diamondbacks would pay for his
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be fun to watch,'' General Manager Joe Garagiola
Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he hasn't really concentrated on baseball. If we can get
him to be a 12-month a year baseball player, this is going to be a
guy who brings things with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Conyer's high school coach, Dennis Pugh, said
</P>
<P>
   Conyer ``is the best prospect I've had in 24 years of coaching.
He runs, hits for power. He's got potential written all over him.''
</P>
<P>
   Relegated to waiting until the third round because of the
free-agent signings of Jay Bell and Willie Blair, the Diamondbacks
nevertheless made some interesting picks. Conyer wasn't the only
one. They also took right-handed pitcher Brian Sager, a high
schooler from Branford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Sager has signed with national power Stanford, where pitchers
thri ve. That explains why he was available for the Diamondbacks in
the 13th round. But he could end up being a steal. One publication
had the Diamondbacks taking him with their first pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of surprising he slid as far as he did,'' M
itchell said. ``We're glad, and we have interest in him. We've
already talked to him, and he's anxious to see where the
Diamondbacks are coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Sager and his family ``are taking some time to reflect on this
experience,'' Mitchell s aid. ``They're disappointed, like anyone
would be. But we told them specifically we're not going to come in
and talk about 13th-round money.''
</P>
<P>
   With their fourth-round pick, the Diamondbacks took left-handed
pitcher Javier Lopez from the Univ ersity of Virginia. Mitchell
said Lopez has good control, an effective change-up and the
potential to throw harder than he does (88 to 90 mph).
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks dipped into the local pool by taking infielder
Dan Meier (14th round) from Arizo na State, left-handed pitcher
Christopher Cervantes from Pima Community College in Tucson (15th
round) and right-handed pitcher Bret Prinz (18th round) from
Phoenix College.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Meier, Mitchell said, ``He's been on and off as far
as
production, but we really like the way he swings the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the limitations, Mitchell said he was pleased with how the
draft progressed on the first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a challenging spring for us,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
