<HEADLINE>
EAGER TO PLAY TOUGH-GUY ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ It is not simply a mound to Richy Leon, but a
stage , where he can shed his placid exterior and play the bad guy
for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a different person when I pitch. It's kind of neat,'' he
said. ``I kind of like that I can play the role of the rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   This rebel has a cause today when h e starts for Arizona State
against Long Beach State in the College World Series. A victory
advances the Sun Devils to Saturday's championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was an emotional one for Leon. He learned about the
start and also that he had been dra fted by the Colorado Rockies in
the 23rd round.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't quite sure how scouts perceived him. During the
regular season, he started 24 games as a second baseman, 10 as a
shortstop, two as a designated hitter and 10 as a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   He also
</P>
<P>
   can play third base _ which he did in the Cape Cod League last
summer _ and the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the only guy who felt his job was safe this season was
catcher Jeremy Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the consummate team player,'' ASU Coach Pat Murphy
</P>
<P>
   said. ``He's done everything we ask as the program has grown.''
</P>
<P>
   Said outfielder Mikel Moreno, ``He's invaluable. He can play
second, third, shortstop. He's a big-time pitcher. Whatever Coach
has asked him, he's always done it, and he does it real well.''
</P>
<P>
   But would his versatility work for or against him? Would scouts
like his ability to fill a variety of roles? Or would they feel
that he failed to specialize and perfect one position?
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, apparently, perceived it as a positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really hesitated whenever (Murphy) would tell me do
something,'' Leon said. ``Sometimes I would think, `Am I ever going
to get a shot at this or that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now when I look at it, I think it helped me. If I'm versatile,
it
</P>
<P>
   means I can help them in many different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno believes ``it's been tough on him at times. Any time
you're on a team, you always want to get playing time every single
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon, a right-hander, doesn't have the overpowering fast ball of
Ryan Mills or Phill Lowery, but he finds ways to win, even if he
has to work a little harder to do it. He is 3-0 in 10 starts this
season with a team-high (among starters) ERA of 6.67.
</P>
<P>
   He went seven innings in ASU's Midwest Regional vi ctory over
Oklahoma State, allowing five runs (two earned) and 10 hits while
striking out 10.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy would be comfortable with only four or five good innings
from Leon today because the Sun Devils' relievers _ particularly
Chad Pennington _ have been so effective in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a great experience,'' Leon said. ``Not many
people get to pitch in the College World Series, so I'll have
something to tell my grandkids.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he gets to be tough-guy Richy Leon f or a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit more take-charge, aggressive on the mound,''
he said. ``It's a different mentality. On second base, you have to
be a little more controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon is a semester away from graduating. He hopes to pursue a
mas ter's degree and coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, his mind is on Long Beach State, which eliminated
Miami, 6-3, from the College World Series on Tuesday, avenging a
first-round loss to the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are considered the surprise tea m of the tournament.
Third baseman Paul Day was the Big West Player of the Year with a
conference-high .438 batting average and 96 hits. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
