<HEADLINE>
UA THROWER SET FOR CHAM PIONSHIP  
 KNOWS DISCUS FIELD'S VERY TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best college disc us thrower in the country isn't taking
anything for granted in the NCAA Track and Field Championships this
week in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Doug Reynolds has lost only twice, but despite having
the nation's top collegiate throw of 206 feet, 1 1 inches, there
are four others _ all from the Pac-10 and including a teammate _
who aren't too far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Waltz of Washington State has a throw of 206 feet, with Ben
Lindsey of Washington (202-7), Arizona's Chima Ugwu (202-5) and
Luke
Sullivan of UCLA (197). Waltz and Ugwu have gotten the better of
Reynolds, but the former Greenway High star likes his chances at
the meet, which begins today and runs through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas has won six straight men's titles and is favor ed to
make it seven, but ``Track and Field News'' predicts their toughest
challenge to come from Arizona. In the women's competition,
Louisiana State is going after its 12th consecutive women's title,
but its reign is expected to come to a close, with Texas and UCLA
battling for team honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a good chance,'' said Reynolds, who also
qualified in the shot put after placing sixth in the Pac-10 meet
with a throw of 57-10 \.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that two of them have beate n me, none of that
matters. I'm really confident with the training we've put in, and
I'm ready to go. I think we can beat anybody out there, the team
and myself. We're really well prepared. If I lose, it won't be
because I wasn't prepared. It will
</P>
<P>
   be because someone out there is a better thrower.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the fact that he competes daily against the 6-foot-4,
304-pound Ugwu has helped him progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good of a competitor as anyone out there,'' Reynolds
said. ``You can't
</P>
<P>
   count him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, a 6-foot-4, 275-pound senior, has aspirations that go
beyond a collegiate championship. He hopes to be a member of the
U.S. Olympic team in 2000, and he'll get a better handle on things
when he competes in the U.S . Championships in New Orleans (June
19-21).
</P>
<P>
   He says he's not sure how long he will compete, but he's
planning his future. With a major in community health education,
Reynolds hopes someday to design health care strategies for clinics
and corp orations.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds is one of 11 Wildcats who have qualified for the men's
meet. Ugwu is ranked second in the shot put and fifth in the
discus, Abdi Abdirahman is second in the 10,000 meters and fifth in
the 5,000, Esko Mikkola is third in th e javelin, Dominic Johnson
is third in the decathlon and fourth in the pole vault, and Patrick
Nduwimana is sixth in the 800.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona women qualified four athletes. Amy Skieresz is the
defending champion and favorite in the 5,000 and 10, 000 meters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
